<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-RAIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE NO LONGER SEALING OFF PARKS IN DRUG RAIDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Police Department has stopped the
practice of sealing parks during drug raids and keeping law-abiding
citizens from leaving them. The change in policy came to light
Thursday, as the city settled a lawsuit brought by a professor who
was briefly detained and handcuffed during a sweep in Washington
Square Park last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The man who filed the lawsuit, Lloyd McNeill, 62, an associate
professor at Rutgers University, had tried to leave the park, where
he had been sitting on a bench with a group of senior citizens when
police began a raid on June 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was 5:20 p.m., McNeill said Thursday, and he had a 5:30
appointment a few blocks away with a graduate student who was
scheduled to defend her thesis.
</P>
<P>
   But McNeill found that he could not leave the park because all
the exits were blocked by police barricades set up to help police
officers and federal agents carry out a drug sweep that led to 58
arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking, `Why would they inconvenience all these people
who are not part of the drug world?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he tried to leave, McNeill said, a police officer told him,
``If you come around that barrier, I'll handcuff you and arrest
you.'' But McNeill said that he went around the barrier anyway, and
was quickly handcuffed and briefly detained in a patrol car before
a higher-ranking officer freed him.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later the New York Civil Liberties Union filed a
lawsuit on behalf of McNeill in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the civil liberties
union, said that McNeill agreed to settle the case after the Police
Department issued new guidelines that keep officers from sealing
parks.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines were put forward on May 8 in a memo which
stated that when police close off portions of parks, at least one
exit is maintained for those who wish to leave.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement announced Thursday, McNeill received a
$10,000 award and payment of his legal fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
