<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-GRASSROOTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEADS SCHOOYARD DISCUSSION GROUP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With CHINA-CLINTON)   (sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ President Clinton led a schoolyard discussion on
Friday in Xiahe, about 30 miles east of Xian and adjacent to the
famed archeological site of the terra cotta warriors buried in the
tomb of Emperor Qin Shihuang.
</P>
<P>
   The president heard from a carefully selected group of citizens
of Xiahe and nearby towns: a schoolteacher, a clinic worker, a
restaurant owner and the manager of a factory that produces
souvenir replicas of the terra cotta warriors.
</P>
<P>
   The president listened intently, asking whether government
policies had led to growing prosperity in the village and
elsewhere, the level of education in the area and the challenges of
running a small business in the booming Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
   He also took questions. A restaurant owner asked the president
why he was holding such a discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two reasons,'' the president answered. ``First of all, I
think it's important for people in positions like mine, in the
United States and China, understand how people live at what we call
the grass-roots level and understand how the policies we make
affect the way people live and the lives of ordinary citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``And secondly, because the American people are
very interested in learning more about the Chinese people as a
result of my trip. So when we do this there will be pictures and
reports of this meeting in America so people just like you in
America will have a feeling for what it's like to be a teacher or
run a restaurant or work with old people.''
</P>
<P>
   Next on the itinerary for the Clintons is a tour of Emperor
Qin's tomb. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
