u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-METS-ORIOLES-NYT &LR;      06-26 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS TOP ORIOLES, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With derogatory Yankee chants in the air and 35,156
fans on hand, there was a festive mood at Shea Stadium on Thursday
night as a prelude of sorts to this weekend's bragging-rights
showdown with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets did not disappoint as, in the ninth, Carlos Baerga
blooped a two-out single to give them a 3-2 victory over the
Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo did not disappoint, either, as he turned in perhaps
his strongest outing since the Mets acquired him from Los Angeles
on June 4. The Japanese right-hander allowed two runs and four hits
in seven strong innings, while walking two and striking out eight.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo was even more dominant than he had been in Florida two
starts before, when he held the Marlins to four hits over six
scoreless innings. And still, Nomo _ who has not won since May 25
and has yet to win as a Met _ departed on Thursday night with the
Mets trailing by a run.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Piazza, who was booed by some in the fifth when he left
a runner on third base, drove home Wayne Kirby, who had tripled as
a pinch-hitter for Nomo, with a sacrifice fly in the seventh to tie
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Edgardo Alfonzo drew a leadoff walk off the
Baltimore closer, Armando Benitez (2-2). After Luis Lopez and
Piazza both struck out, Baerga came through with his single to
center field, the Mets' ninth hit of the game, one in each inning,
and their first in 10 at-bats with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   It brought home the winning run. Now it's bring on the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the fourth in the last five games for the Mets
(42-32) and their third in a row over the struggling Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback made a winner of Dennis Cook (3-2), who pitched two
scoreless innings in relief of Nomo, who entered Thursday night's
game with 50 walks in 802/3 innings, the fourth-highest total in
the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe his lack of control this year might be attributable
to a multidirectional instability _ or looseness _ that was
detected in the Japanese right-hander's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But General Manager Steve Phillips has said that Nomo's right
shoulder is sound and Manager Bobby Valentine said that it has long
been known that Nomo had the instability in both shoulders, dating
back to arm trouble he had in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same doctors who examined him when he first came here and
every year since have proclaimed it to be the same,'' Valentine
said. ``Laxity will give you impingement, which manifests itself in
pain. I don't know how it deals with control.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, Valentine said, has not felt any pain. And the only
control problems that Nomo had on Thursday night _ when he threw 69
of his 103 pitches for strikes _ came when the Baltimore starter
Scott Erickson was at the plate. Erickson drew both of Nomo's
walks.
</P>
<P>
   One came back to haunt Nomo.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the fifth, Erickson walked on a full-count
pitch, after Nomo had inexplicably fallen behind 3-0 on a pitcher
who has rarely batted in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were trailing by 1-0 because of a line-drive
inning-opening home run in the fourth by Roberto Alomar that
ricocheted off the foul pole in right.
</P>
<P>
   After Nomo struck Brady Anderson out on three pitches following
Erickson's second walk of the game, it looked as if Nomo would be
able to extricate himself from the jam.
</P>
<P>
   But Nomo's third pitch to Joe Carter went about 10 feet over
Piazza's head for a wild pitch, as Erickson took second.
</P>
<P>
   Carter then blasted a 3-0 offering over Brian McRae's head in
center field.
</P>
<P>
   McRae appeared to get a bad jump on the ball, which one-hopped
over the fence for a ground-rule double. Erickson scored from
second and the Orioles led, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets battled back for a run in their fifth after Erickson
walked Alfonzo with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Franco's triple to right center made it 2-1, which was
where it stood when the Mets batted in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine sent Kirby up to pinch-hit for Nomo. Kirby responded
by tripling over Carter's head in right.
</P>
<P>
   One out and one hit batsman later, Piazza drove Kirby home with
a sacrifice fly. And even though the Mets could not finish off the
rally and perhaps give Nomo the victory, they at least spared him
the indignity of another defeat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
