<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-VOLLEYBALL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. VOLLEYBALL TEAM SHOWS POSITIVE SIGNS IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Don't get Mick Haley wrong. Winning is always nice. It
just isn't always the objective.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Haley, the coach of the United States women's
national volleyball team, didn't get the win, falling three games
to one to Canada at the Dallas Convention Center, but he got what
he wanted most _ a good look at a group of young players hoping to
win a chance to try out for the 2000 Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our starters aren't here,'' said Haley, who coaches the Texas
Longhorns in the fall. ``This team is a bunch of young kids who
haven't played together before. We don't expect them to be smooth.
But you get a chance to see how they play under pressure and get a
feel for who can do it and who can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was a sloppy and disorganized performance from the
opening serve, as the Americans fell behind 11-2 en route to
dropping the first game 15-5. They followed with their only surge
of the night, blasting out to an 11-1 lead in game two only to
watch the Canadians reel off 12 consecutive points to tie the game
at 14 before the U.S. finally put it away.
</P>
<P>
   From then on it was all Canada, with undersized-but-powerful
outside hitter Bridget Soucy leading the charge as the Canadians
closed out the match with 15-13 and 15-12 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we lost, I think the second game was the important
one for us,'' said Canada coach Doug Reimer, whose team lost, 3-0,
to the U.S. on Wednesday in Tulsa, Okla., and played the Americans
again Saturday in Sacramento, Calif. ``When we came back from so
far behind, it reminded us we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point we said, `Look, this is it,''' said Soucy, a
1996 Olympian who joined the Canadian team last week after her
professional team in Italy ended its season. ```This is our match,
and we're going to take it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Haley got a chance to see some of his players react to
adversity. Several made good impressions, notably former Penn State
star Terri Zemaitis, who finished with 11 kills and team highs in
blocks (six) and attack percentage (.400).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all new to this, so it's kind of fun,'' Zemaitis said.
``We're all getting a chance to play and we know some of us are
going to get a chance to do bigger things.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was as much confusion as there was stellar play for
the Americans. Haley started a different lineup last night than he
played in Tulsa, and tried various combinations of players all
night in an attempt to find chemistry and to see as many players as
he could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone did something pretty good at times, but we had our
problems,'' Haley said. ``Basically, we want to give these kids a
chance to show us what they can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
