<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONIC DRAFTEE WILL, IN TIME, RISE AND SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The local angle on the NBA draft shaped up as such a
non-event that when he was announced as the Sonics' first-round
draft selection, Vladimir Stepania was half a world away, dead
asleep.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Sonics didn't even know until almost the last
moment Wednesday that they were taking him, so the Vladster could
hardly be faulted.
</P>
<P>
   If both parties were mutually bewildered, you should have seen
the knot of reporters gathered around a speakerphone in the press
room of KeyArena preparing to interview the European star.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a sketchy NBA biography and a scratchy international
connection, an early question was mandatory: Where are you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Where?'' he said, struggling with the nuances of English. ``In
bed.''
</P>
<P>
   After the laughter faded, and the Sonics made a couple of more
selections, the ennui began to dissipate, too.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania, 21, was in Treviso, Italy, at a basketball camp, and
the Sonics were in the middle of changing a non-event to an event
to a happening.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing a sniffling Texas teenager as well as a UCLA reject
allegedly booted for smoking dope, Sonic risk-taking hadn't
inspired as much draft intrigue since 1989. That's when then-club
president Bob Whitsitt took Dana Barros, a too-short shooting
guard, and Shawn Kemp, a too-wild teenager who couldn't stick at a
college.
</P>
<P>
   But the guy who can make the 1998 draft a turning point in club
history is Stepania. A 7-footer ``highly skilled'' in the sport,
according to club personnel hound Billy McKinney, who had seen him
play in person five times, Stepania needs only to bulk up before
stepping out in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Given his youth, the remaining year on his pro contract with a
team in Ljublijana, Slovenia, and the impending NBA lockout,
chances are he won't play until after next season.
</P>
<P>
   But if he eventually creates a Toni Kukoc-like impact with the
Sonics, fans can thank a friendship connection that might be among
the weirdest in draft history.
</P>
<P>
   As draft day approached, the Sonics were sufficiently smitten
with Stepania to consider trading up to get him. Then their
pre-draft projections indicated he could fall to Seattle at the
27th pick. But beyond his basketball skills, the Sonics knew so
little that team president Wally Walker fired off an urgent call
the morning of the draft to an old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a rush to get some information on the kid,'' said
Bob Walsh, the Seattle sports entrepreneur with extensive business
ventures in Russia and its breakaway republics. Walsh immediately
called an old friend in Washington, D.C.: Tedeo Djaparidze,
ambassador to the United States from the republic of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Not the Georgia of Scarlett O'Hara, Ted Turner, Ray Charles and
clueless Olympic bus drivers. This is the Georgia of Genghis Khan,
Eduard Shevardnadze, the Black Sea and Caucasus Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador called Tbilisi, the Georgian capital and the
Stepania family's hometown, where he sought an old friend: the
basketball coach who tutored Stepania since the age of 6.
</P>
<P>
   From Tbilisi to Washington to Seattle, Stepania's character
reference came back: smart, hard-working, solid citizen, eager for
a shot at the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ambassador is a huge fan of the NBA,'' Walsh said. ``I
went with him to the All-Star Game in Cleveland in '96 when they
had the 50th anniversary team, and he was thrilled to meet Bill
Russell and Lenny Wilkens. He recited all their stats and awards.
As a boy in the Soviet Union of the 1950s and '60s, he and his
friends used to get NBA games on illegal broadcasts on Voice of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd been telling me for two years about this kid, but I
hadn't followed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said it wasn't surprising that the ambassador was so
familiar with what would seem an obscure moment for an
international diplomat. Georgia has a population of about 5
million, nearly a third of which is in Tbilisi, ``so everybody
knows everybody, and most are related.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia became a sovereign state only in 1991, after nearly 200
years of Soviet and Russian rule, so anything or anyone who gains
some international notoriety for a young nation becomes known
quickly to all. In fact, the ambasssador's 14-year-old son has
played some low-key streetball with Stepania.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said Stepania's father is an architect of Georgian descent
and his mother is a native Russian involved in national sports
organizations. The kid speaks six languages, and by playing for the
past two years in the Yugoslavian league, he's well over
homesickness and well into worldliness.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics compared his skills to those of Alvan Adams, a 6-9
high-post center of the 1970s-era Phoenix Suns, when new Sonic
coach Paul Westphal was an All-Star guard. But in his media chat,
Stepania was as bluntly honest as George Karl.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this moment, I don't feel that I can help,'' he said. ``If
I improve in one or two more years, I feel I have the chance to be
a good NBA player.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no hurry. With such young draftees as Rashard Lewis and
Jelani McCoy, not to mention the NBA lockout, the Sonics can give
Stepania a year to get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
