<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEYSTONE MARINERS RESUME SWOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ So much for a prolonged Mariner winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   It's two and start over. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   After winning back-to-back games for the first time in almost a
month, the M's on Thursday resumed their June Swoon with a 6-0 loss
to the San Diego Padres before 32,626 fans at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On a day starter Ken Cloude pitched well enough to end a
personal two-month winless streak, Padres left-hander Mark Langston
teased the Mariners with breaking pitches and changeups, tricked
Cloude into an inning-ending double play on a bunt, and was bailed
out of his only predicament when reliever Donne Wall induced
Glenallen Hill to bounce into a first-pitch double play with the
bases loaded in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego led by three runs at the time and presented another
microcosm of things that have gone wrong this season.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, manager Lou Piniella said, ``I've seen things
this year that I've never seen before in baseball and we still have
July, August and September.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Piniella said, ``The senility of the manager is
in doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners saved their worst for last.
</P>
<P>
   Although a four-run deficit may not have been erased, it became
a six-run gap in the eighth inning during another defensive
collapse. Two catchable balls were flubbed so badly that the
batters were credited with hits.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff hitter Carlos Hernandez lofted a routine fly ball to
left-center. For some unexplainable reason, neither center fielder
Ken Griffey Jr., an eight-time Gold Glove winner, nor left fielder
Glenallen Hill, who doesn't have any _ for good reason _ called for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Hill ran to his left. Griffey sprinted to his right. Hill backed
off at the last second, and the ball fell to the grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of us called for it,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's close to the ball, I concede,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, and the Padres' lead larger, Hill
misplayed a ball Quilvio Veras hit, turning it into a two-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I catch the ball, it's a good play,'' Hill said. ``If I
miss it, I'm the goat. I guess I'm the goat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude, standing several feet away in front of his locker,
wondered what it's going to take to win a game. The right-hander's
record dipped to 3-7 and he hasn't won since April 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I pitched that poorly, but I keep pitching just
well enough to lose,'' he said. ``It is very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude found himself in a two-run deficit right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Steve Finley pulled a down-and-in fastball
past first base for a one-out double and Tony Gwynn doubled to
left-center. Ken Caminiti blooped a run-scoring single to right
field with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he got past the first inning, he did a nice job,'' said
Piniella of his starting pitcher. ``But Langston pitched better.''
</P>
<P>
   Langston, a hard-thrower earlier in his career, relied on soft
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw a lot of breaking pitches for strikes and changed
speeds,'' the former Mariner said. ``Everything worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Langston also used his savvy.
</P>
<P>
   With Russ Davis on first base and one out, Cloude popped a bunt
into the air. Langston, noticing that Cloude wasn't running,
allowed the ball to drop. First baseman Wally Joyner picked it up
and started an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been waiting my entire career to do that,'' Langston
said, smiling. ``Actually, I was going to pick it up and throw to
first, but Wally was there first and he made a great play.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude learned the hard way that you run everything out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as concerned about that (play) as much as I am about
my pitching,'' he said. ``It has been over two months since I won a
game and that's not fun. Losing gets old real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   But so does botching scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Langston wobbled in the sixth inning when Alex Rodriguez and
David Segui singled and Jay Buhner walked, loading the bases with
one out.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, batting a decent .286 this season with runners in scoring
position, smacked Wall's first pitch directly to the pitcher, who
snared the ball and started a home-to-first double play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
