<HEADLINE>
L.A. TRANSIT AGENCY'S NEW BUDGET PILES DEBT ON TOP OF DEBT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC MOSES  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The MTA's board of directors adopted a $2.5
billion budget that adds $378 million in debt the agency's chief
executive called necessary for it to recover financially.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MTA will have to borrow to meet the region's
transportation needs in this upcoming fiscal year and in my view in
the next, at least several fiscal years,'' said Julian Burke, CEO
of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not overburdened with debt,'' Burke told the board
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly an hour of discussion about the agency's debt,
board members voted 8-0 to adopt the budget. Absent were county
Supervisors Gloria Molina and Don Knabe and Mayor John Fasana of
suburban Duarte. Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich and Councilman
Larry Zarian of suburban Glendale left early.
</P>
<P>
   Also approved were county Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky's proposals
aimed at limiting how much the agency can borrow in the future. One
requested a ceiling on debt, and another asked that all future
budget documents indicate which projects are funded by borrowed
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with debt'' as long as there are
controls in place, Yaroslavsky said. ``We do it at the county
(level). We do it in our home mortgages.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the agency has no policy to guide its borrowing. Burke
said he is drafting a debt policy to rectify that situation.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the Daily News reported that the MTA would go broke
within a decade if it continued to build rail lines downtown and in
suburban Pasadena and to East and West Los Angeles. And even if the
MTA halted all new rail construction, it would face a serious
deficit for years to come, according to a comprehensive review of
the agency's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Burke called in January for a moratorium on construction of rail
lines to Pasadena, the Eastside and Mid-City.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday he told the board that the MTA still must borrow
$233 million for existing rail projects in the upcoming year,
including $60 million to fulfill a contract to buy train cars for
the shelved Pasadena Blue Line, $84 million for the Hollywood
subway and $33 million for the North Hollywood subway line.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 1998-99 year, Burke said, the debt will rise
to $4 billion. With the repayment of principal and interest spread
out over three decades, the total cost to the agency will be $6.8
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Burke defended the practice of borrowing as necessary to get the
agency through its current ``growth sequence'' and to finish the
Metro Red Line to North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 percent of the MTA's operating budget, or $349 million,
is earmarked for repayment of old debts in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, the MTA board's chairman,
said the agency was saddled with the debt by limitations the
federal government attached to federal money for subway projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was flawed policy where we've gotten way too little for way
too much,'' he said. ``Maybe accepting federal money was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The MTA still is waiting to hear whether the Federal Transit
Administration will approve Burke's financial recovery plan and how
much federal money it will receive next year. The agency has
requested $100 million for rail and $25 million to buy new buses.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, bus-rider advocates assailed the MTA board
for ignoring the demands of riders who claim the agency is not
complying with the terms of a federal court order requiring it to
alleviate bus overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   Bus Riders Union organizer Eric Mann blasted the new spending
blueprint as ``another rail budget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are talking about billions again in money they don't have
to continue building the rail system because the answer is, `We
have to finish what we started,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget provides funding for 83,000 more bus service hours,
the delivery of 111 new buses and money to buy 50 more.
</P>
<P>
   Mann contends the MTA must add 1,600 new buses at a cost of $1.1
billion in the next two years, and his group is considering asking
the judge to require that the agency find the money to accommodate
the more than 90 percent of its customers who ride buses.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, however, accused the MTA of violating a Civil Rights Act
provision that requires transit agencies to spend money on buses in
an amount proportional to the number of riders. This budget failed
to do that, he said, adding that no one on the MTA board seemed to
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't one minute today when somebody said, `How much do
we owe the Bus Riders Union?' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
