<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS READY TO MAKE SONICS BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ He held up a Sonic uniform in an atmosphere not unlike
the one Shawn Kemp found when he arrived in Seattle. But Texas prep
star Rashard Lewis' skills are mostly compared to the NBA's Scottie
Pippen and Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   And before deciding to skip college for the NBA, Lewis took a
little advice from Los Angeles Lakers phenom Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the leap from preps to the pros became reality,
Lewis revealed no regrets. Instead, the 6-foot-10, 18-year-old
displayed the confidence that one day he will become Pippen, Horry,
Kemp and Bryant sewed together _ an NBA megastar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hard worker and I'm going to bring a lot of excitement.
I think I can make Seattle a better team for years to come,'' said
Lewis, who arrived in Seattle on Thursday after becoming the
Sonics' 32nd pick in the second round of Wednesday's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was one of three high school athletes taken in the draft.
Indiana liked the NBA-caliber size of New Jersey prep star Al
Harrington, and chose him ahead of Lewis with the 25th pick. But
Lewis is considered the most skilled of the teenage bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' slender frame is compensated mostly by his scoring
ability, ballhandling, rebounding and athleticism. He needs to get
stronger to make a big impact in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Seattle really knows how good he can be. He's
very developed. I expect him to be in the NBA for a long time,''
said Carl Poston, Lewis' Houston-based agent, who also represents
Horry and Orlando's Anferenee Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis became a high school legend at Alief Elsik High School in
Alief, Texas, a Houston suburb. Not only did a plethora of college
scouts attend each of his games, but at least one NBA scout also
sat in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Juanita Goodman, Lewis' mother, recalled the family home turning
into a political campaign headquarters. Her phone rang constantly.
If it wasn't a college recruiter on the line, Lewis was being given
advice on what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman eventually allowed her son to make his own decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was on his heart. That's what he wanted to do,'' said
Goodman, who has three other children _ Ricky, Kiah and Kirsten.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're raising children, it's always go to school and get
an education,'' Goodman said. ``But I told him to do what was on
his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis knew he was turning pro the day he returned from Magic
Johnson's All-Star game in Detroit. The April event featured the
top prospects from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers were in town to play the Pistons, and Adidas
sponsored the game so Kobe Bryant (an Adidas client) came to the
banquet,'' Lewis said. ``He told me to follow my heart. That meant
a lot to me knowing that (Kobe) made the jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, like Bryant, easily could have gone to college with
freshman eligibility. He scored a 20 on his ACT _ 17 is the minimum
required _ but eventually turned down Florida State, Kansas and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was visibly disillusioned when the Houston Rockets passed
on him with three picks in the first round. Thursday, though, Lewis
was more than satisfied with his secret admirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised (when the Sonics made the pick). After
thinking about it, I'm happy I'm here in this situation,'' said
Lewis, who hopes to spell Detlef Schrempf and Vin Baker at times,
although he readily admits being a Rockets fan who idolizes Hakeem
Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in Houston is a Hakeem fan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   All Lewis knows about the Sonics is ``they're a team that's
always been hungry for a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Discounting her motherly bias, Goodman wanted to give Sonic fans
something to nibble on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait until they see him play,'' she said. ``Seattle is in for
a treat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
