<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHOUT OUT BRAVES, 6-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the hour after pitching his perfect game May 17,
David Wells insisted his newfound prominence in baseball history
wouldn't change him. He was wrong, it seems. He's become a better
pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   With the heat index well over 100 degrees here, Wells sweat
rivers and shut out the Braves on six hits here on Thursday night,
6-0, becoming the fourth American League pitcher with 10 wins this
season. Wells also hit a single in four at-bats, as the Yankees
(53-19) won for the third time in their four games with Atlanta,
which has the National League's best record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you can play with the best in the game,'' said
the Braves' Chipper Jones, ``and you've just been taken out behind
the woodshed and given a nice beating.''
</P>
<P>
   Having taken Atlanta, the Yankees now invade Shea Stadium for
three games with the New York Mets. Tino Martinez, the Yankees'
star first baseman, was hit by a pitch in the eighth inning on
Thursday night on almost the exact same spot where Baltimore's
Armando Benitez hit him May 19, and Martinez likely will be
replaced by Jorge Posada at first base.
</P>
<P>
   Wells struck out five, didn't walk a single batter for the third
straight start _ he's gone 29 innings since his last walk _ and
reduced his ERA to 3.92. ``I've never seen Boomer this confident,''
said David Cone, referring to Wells by his nickname. ``I don't know
whether that's because of his perfect game, but it seemed to have
an effect on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made his mark in history, in Yankee lore, and that means
a lot to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre used to be the pitching coach for the Mets, and
he's currently the pitching coach for the Yankees. ``No one was as
locked in as Dwight Gooden in 1985,'' said Stottlemyre, ``but David
is as locked in as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells pitched his second complete game, in spite of the brutal
conditions that forced him to retreat for the air-conditioned
clubhouse and guzzle water between innings. ``About a gallon,''
said Wells.
</P>
<P>
   His idol is Babe Ruth and dressed in a grand style the Bambino
might've appreciated on Thursday night. His back left pocket
flapped inside out from his pants, a square of white drumming
against the uniform gray as Wells walked. The top three buttons of
his jersey were undone, so that the NEW and YORK were turned down.
A hint of a goatee surrounded his mouth. He was a good ol'
fashioned ballplayer, a weekend warrior.
</P>
<P>
   Wells tugged at his jersey constantly, fidgeting throughout,
coming to bat for the first time in the third inning. Denny Neagle
had retired the first eight Yankee hitters, but Wells, with an
exaggerated pigeon-toed finish to his swing _ like the Babe _ lined
a single through the left side of the infield, only the second
regular-season hit by a Yankees' pitcher since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch worked Neagle to a full count, and with two out,
Wells broke from first. Knoblauch fouled off Neagle's pitch, and
Wells slowly trudged back to first. Wells broke from first again
with the pitch, again Knoblauch fouled the ball off. Wells was
wearing down quickly. Ozzie Guillen, Atlanta's shortstop, yelled to
Wells, ``If he hits about three of those, you're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch flied out to end the inning, and Wells returned to
the mound after being toweled off by the trainer Gene Monahan and
had his most efficient inning.
</P>
<P>
   Neagle allowed just one hit in the first four innings but lost
command in the sixth, walking Knoblauch, and with a full count, he
walked Derek Jeter. Nobody out, runners on first and second. Neagle
ran the count deep on Paul O'Neill, three balls and two strikes. As
Neagle began his motion, Knoblauch broke from second, Jeter
following from first.
</P>
<P>
   And O'Neill slammed a line drive into right-center field, the
ball rolling to the wall, the merry-go-round of Yankees'
baserunners spinning wildly, Knoblauch and Jeter scoring, O'Neill
sliding awkwardly into third base, his feet in the air like a funny
car. Tim Raines singled home O'Neill and Chad Curtis homered,
giving the Yankees a 5-0 lead and finishing Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre and Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, wondered if and
when Wells would finally wilt. Stottlemyre wanted to go to the
mound in the sixth, to give Wells a breather, and Wells waved him
back testily before he was two steps out of the dugout: Don't come
out here.
</P>
<P>
   Leading off the seventh, Wells turned on a fastball and drove it
to deep right field, the players on the Yankees' bench rising to
see if the Boomer had pulled a Babe. But Gerald Williams hauled in
the drive just short of the warning track, and Wells staggered off
the field, pausing at third base to say to Chipper Jones, ``I never
want to come back and pitch here.''
</P>
<P>
   He kept going, though, feeling somewhat faint. Ramiro Mendoza
warmed up and was ready to pitch the seventh, the eighth, the
ninth. But in the dugout, Wells said to Torre, ``Might as well go
out there for the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   His legs cramped up during the final inning, Wells said, and he
thought about calling Torre out, for relief.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept going and finished, with the same stuff that Joe
Girardi said made him fun to catch: Good fastball, great curveball
and change-up, terrific location, the same stuff that's made him
just about perfect for more than a month now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
