<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDOUGAL-1STLD-WRITET     06-26 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDOUGAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN MCDOUGAL FREED BY FEDERAL JUDGE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add response from Clinton in 8th graf; light rewriting
throughout first 10 grafs; deletes 3rd-to-last graf; different
hed.)   (mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Susan McDougal, the embattled Whitewater figure who
suffered incarceration rather than answer grand jury questions
about Bill and Hillary Clinton, was unexpectedly freed from prison
Thursday by a federal judge in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives wept as Mrs. McDougal offered a dazed smile at the
decision by Judge George Howard Jr. of U.S. District Court in
Little Rock, after she insisted that her 21 months of imprisonment
had severely aggravated a spinal condition. Saying he was motivated
by ``compassion and mercy,'' Howard reduced her sentence in a
Whitewater fraud case to time served.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still so stunned,'' Mrs. McDougal said when she emerged
from the courthouse 90 minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't know what to say,'' she exulted, still in her
two-piece bright-orange prison uniform, looking physically wan but
ebullient in spirit. ``I still don't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling eliminated the remainder of a two-year prison
sentence she began serving in March for her conviction in the first
Whitewater trial on charges of mail fraud, misapplication of funds
and making false statements. Mrs. McDougal must serve 90 days of
home detention, and still faces charges in Little Rock and
California.
</P>
<P>
   But taking into account the 18 months of separate jail time she
had served for resisting the grand jury investigation of the
Clintons, the judge ruled that she be freed from prison for the
fraud conviction. The judge gave Mrs. McDougal 10 days to settle
her affairs and report to her parents' home in Camden, Ark., where
she will be under electronic surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a much better person today than the one you sentenced,''
Mrs. McDougal told the judge. ``I promise you, you won't be
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, visiting the village of Xiahe in China, was
asked about Mrs. McDougal's impending release. ``I'm concerned
about her health, and I hope she gets better now,'' he said. ``I
hope the judge's decision puts her in a position where she can get
over her pain and her difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal's troubles with the courts and Kenneth Starr, the
Whitewater independent counsel, were hardly ended by the ruling,
because Mrs. McDougal was re-indicted by Starr last month for once
more refusing to answer grand jury questions about the Clintons and
Whitewater. That trial, on charges of criminal contempt and
obstruction of justice, is set for Sept. 28 in Little Rock. Howard
is also scheduled to preside over that case.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Mrs. McDougal faces an unrelated criminal trial on
July 13 in California on charges that she embezzled $150,000 from
the conductor Zubin Mehta when she worked as his bookkeeper from
1989 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Laura Henley, indicated that Mrs. McDougal might
spend the night in a Little Rock hotel but was soon expected home
under the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take her home so bad,'' Mrs. Henley said, beaming
and teary-eyed outside the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Through her travail, Mrs. McDougal has maintained a combative
resistance to Starr and his attempts to implicate the Clintons
criminally in the decade-old complex of real estate and political
events known as Whitewater. She stood firm in leg irons and high
heels as she was led off the first time for her silence, and her
supporters opened a Web site (www.stopstarr.org) that portrayed her
as a martyr to prosecutorial zeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Resign and I'll answer all their questions,'' she said
defiantly to prosecutors in her second contempt struggle with
Starr, insisting he had numerous conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Howard issued his decision after hearing testimony from Dr.
Ronald Fisk, a clinical neurologist at the University of California
at Los Angeles, that Mrs. McDougal was suffering seriously
progressive curvature of the spine and related disk problems that
may require surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's spokesman, Charles Bakaly, noted that criminal contempt
charges were still pending against Mrs. McDougal. ``The judge made
a compassioned decision based on medical testimony to release Mrs.
McDougal, and we respect the judge's decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal has repeatedly rebuffed the independent counsel
team, accusing Starr of bias in his investigation of Clinton's
affairs in his years as Arkansas's governor. In her re-indictment
last month, prosecutors charged that after Mrs. McDougal was
granted immunity and compelled to testify by a federal judge, she
failed to answer questions posed by prosecutors and grand jurors,
contending that the prosecutors were prejudiced.
</P>
<P>
   The questions covered whether Clinton had testified truthfully
at Mrs. McDougal's criminal trial, the nature of Mrs. Clinton's
legal work on behalf of a corrupt Little Rock savings association,
and the Clintons' knowledge of an improperly financed land deal
that was supposed to bail out Whitewater Development Co. in which
they had invested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to answer the grand jury's questions,'' Mrs.
McDougal declared, according to her jury testimony denouncing the
prosecutors. ``But they don't have anyone in here that will take
this investigation where it should go.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors maintain she had no legal basis for refusing to
answer questions central to the investigation. They sought to
cross-examine her about the version of Whitewater events and
denials offered by Clinton in his videotaped deposition at her
trial. Nor would she say whether she had a discussion with Clinton
about an improper loan issued to her in 1986 by David Hale, a
former municipal judge who ran an investment company backed by the
Small Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Hale has testified that Clinton, when he was governor, asked him
to issue the $300,000 loan, some of which paid for Whitewater
expenses. Clinton has denied under oath that he knew about the loan
or played any role in obtaining it.
</P>
<P>
   After her release, Mark Barrett, an associate independent
counsel, emphasized that the government had offered no opposition
to Mrs. McDougal's motion to be allowed her freedom on her own
recognizance, pending her next contempt trial.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all her remaining legal problems, Mrs. McDougal was in
high spirits on the Little Rock sidewalk as she tasted freedom for
the first time since September 1996. Her attorney, Mark Geragos,
said, ``Without a doubt it was more than I expected.'' He escorted
her away to ``get her some clothes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
