<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANETS (Undated) _ The discoveries of planets beyond
the solar system, stimulating renewed speculation of other possible
worlds throbbing with life, are now drawing closer in cosmic terms
to the world of their discoverers. The latest detection, made this
month by American astronomers, is of a planet about twice the mass
of Jupiter orbiting the star Gliese 876, one of the Sun's nearest
neighbors at a distance of only 15 light-years away. Previous
confirmed extrasolar planets have been observed at stars 40 to 80
light-years away. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Chart has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-SCHOOLS (Boston) _ ``Neighborhood schools'' is a fraught,
to some even frightening, phrase here. Nearly a quarter-century
ago, it was the rallying slogan of those who opposed forced busing
to achieve school integration; today, it can still conjure up
images of angry protesters and nightstick-swinging police officers
in the white enclaves of Charlestown and South Boston, of
saucer-eyed children watching adult violence from their school-bus
windows. For all that historical baggage, however, the Boston
School Committee on Wednesday night is scheduled to take up the
issue of whether to move back toward neighborhood schools,
reopening the old debate despite any trepidation because, backers
of the proposal say, it simply seems time. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT11) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GM-STRIKE (Flint, Mich.) _ Like a large stone thrown in a pond,
the strikes at two General Motors' parts factories are producing
economic effects that are slowly rippling out across North America.
The first effects were felt immediately in this town when the
strike began, because GM accounts for more than half the employment
and taxes here The next ripples came over the last two weeks as the
company has closed 26 of its 29 assembly plants in North America
and curtailed production at nearly 100 parts factories. Now the
effects are reaching across the country, into communities and
states where the auto industry has been less visible than here in
the industrial Midwest. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-60MINUTES-MEDIA (New York) _ CBS is likely to add a second
weekly installment of ``60 Minutes.'' By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   MERGERS (Undated) _ The growing conviction by corporations
worldwide that bigger is better in the global marketplace has
generated a merger wave that has dwarfed anything preceding it. By
Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   SUNBEAM-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Since last week's firing of
Albert Dunlap as chairman and chief executive officer, and a stock
sell-off caused by warnings of a bleak financial outlook for the
rest of the year, Sunbeam Corp. has revealed even more bad news. On
Thursday, the company said there were unanswered questions about
its 1997 financial results and confirmed that its accounting
practices were under informal investigation by the Securities and
Exchange Commission. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   MAGS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Two magazines are supplementing their
appeals to readers and advertisers with unconventional supplements
that are appearing in issues now coming out. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
