A7978 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT &LR;      06-26 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WASHINGTON LIVES IN TWO DIFFERENT WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At one end of Pennsylvania Avenue lies the U.S. Treasury
building. At the other is the Capitol. They are not that far apart
in miles, but they seem to inhabit different worlds. While the
Treasury deals with the threat of financial hurricanes, the
Congress legislates as if there were not a cloud in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials have moved from one crisis to another, all
stemming from the Asian woes. There have been alarms in Thailand,
Korea, Indonesia, Russia and Japan, and there are worries about
China, Hong Kong and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Disaster has been averted, but there are signs of a global
slowdown. Japan's recession is official, and Hong Kong's will be,
as soon as figures for the current quarter are compiled. A World
Bank official talks about regional depression.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least for now, is too harsh a view. But the pain for
many is great, and is spreading. With economic activity on the
decline in what had been the world's fastest-growing area,
commodity prices have been falling. On average, commodities have
lost about a quarter of their value since last fall, but some,
notably oil, have gone down much more rapidly. Oil-producing
countries this week agreed to cut production again in an effort to
prop up prices, but that is unlikely to work, even if producing
countries do not cheat on their production quotas, unless economic
activity in Asia begins to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Asia, bankers are wondering why they made loans to
borrowers who cannot repay. Crony capitalism and political pull
explain some of the bad loans, but many can be traced to the
exuberance and assurance that accompanies economic booms, which can
make credit cheap and easy to get. Now the cycle has turned.
Bankers are cautious and international investors are edging out.
``The virulent Asian virus, in the form of capital flight, now has
affected big developing countries like Russia, South Africa and
Brazil,'' says Barton Biggs, Morgan Stanley's chief investment
strategist.
</P>
<P>
   But on Capitol Hill the picture couldn't be prettier. The
American economy is booming and there is a budget surplus. Goodies
are being given to favored constituents, in such forms as a
pork-laden highway bill and cuts in capital gains taxes.
Congressional leaders have agreed that the current low 20 percent
rate should be made available to investors who sell after holding
on for a year, rather than waiting 18 months. But Speaker Newt
Gingrich thinks that is too modest, and wants to cut the rate to 15
percent. At the same time, the rules on retirement accounts are to
be liberalized to make it possible for better-off Americans to
escape taxation after retirement in return for paying some taxes
now.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Asian problems have had a relatively small, and
mixed, effect on this country. Our exports are falling, and our
trade deficit has soared to record levels because the Asians can't
afford to buy what they used to buy. The manufacturing sector is
starting to feel the pinch. But capital is fleeing to the relative
safety of this country, driving bond prices up and interest rates
down. Fortunately, European economies that had been sluggish when
Asia was booming are now improving. But Europe too is starting to
feel the impact of the Asian woes.
</P>
<P>
   The world's economies and financial systems, for better and for
worse, are more integrated than ever before and it is unlikely that
the American boom and the Asian virus can coexist for long. A wiser
Congress now would be devoting itself to two tasks. First, it would
be looking for policies to try to keep Asia from turning into a
total economic disaster area. Second, it would be trying to husband
resources so that our government will be able to withstand a
slowdown if one comes without having to either raise taxes or sink
into another huge budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Congressional leadership seems to be determined to
pursue the opposite course. The bill to provide badly needed funds
for the International Monetary Fund languishes while the tax
breaks, which will be at their most costly in a few years, take
center stage. It would appear that the Capitol is in a different
world from the one the Treasury is working so hard to keep afloat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
