<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PHILLIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX FEND OFF PHILLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The lawyers, guns, and money are never far away,
but for one night, anyway, Bret Saberhagen kept them all at arm's
length, which is about the same way he treated the Philadelphia
Phillies in a 7-5 win Thursday night at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, setting aside a domestic dispute that he says has
affected his performance of late, held the Phillies to five singles
and an unearned run in six innings, which went a long way toward
stopping the Red Sox' three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox weren't able to leave town without one last scare from
the pesky Phillies, who scored four runs off Tom Gordon in the
ninth and had the tying run at the plate before Ron Mahay struck
out Bobby Abreu for his first big league save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess this probably completes my everyday thing, from
hitting to the on-the-mound stuff,'' said Mahay, the converted
outfielder who gave up a two-run single to Mark Parent before
whiffing Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who stopped the Sox' six-game losing streak, their
longest of the season, nearly a month ago, had lost his last two
decisions but raised his record to 9-5 despite feeling under the
weather for the last couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't look healthy but he threw well,'' said Phillies
catcher Parent, who was referring more to Saberhagen's shoulder
than whatever else was ailing the righthander.
</P>
<P>
   At 36, Parent is old enough to have faced Saberhagen when he
dominated, before his right shoulder was recycled. ``Location is
the biggest difference,'' Parent said. ``He used to be able to dot
an ant's butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen may lack that kind of precision now, but he still has
enough to squash pests when needed. He was supported by solo home
runs by John Valentin (No. 10) and Damon Buford (No. 5 and third in
36 at-bats this month) and a two-run, two-out single by Darren
Lewis in a three-run seventh fueled by an error by Phillies second
baseman Mark Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   But with Gordon having his worst outing since he gave up four
runs in Atlanta June 8, the Red Sox wound up needing the two runs
they scored in the ninth on a double by Darren Bragg, singles by
Jason Varitek and Mike Benjamin, a wild pitch, and a double-play
grounder by Lou Merloni.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important that we turned it around tonight,'' said
Lewis, who lined his hit on a 3-and-2 pitch from lefty Matt Beech
after the Phillies starter had struck out Benjamin and pinch hitter
Billy Ashley with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like we were playing badly. They've been swinging
the bat well and taking advantage of their opportunities, but it
was crucial for us to get out of it as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   After being blown out for six runs in four innings by expansion
Tampa Bay in his last start, Saberhagen had admitted to being
affected by child and spousal support issues he is attempting to
resolve with his ex-wife. He said he shares custody of their three
children, but he is seeking a reduction in support payments that he
claims are $85,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about it, he said, was a help.
</P>
<P>
   ``It relieved a lot of the stress I had built up,'' he said.
``People on the team, guys were coming up to me saying, `What's the
matter with you? You're not acting like your usual self.' You don't
feel like telling people what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm trying to cut (the support) off. My three
kids will always be my No. 1 priority and are well taken care of.
Unfortunately, there are a lot of other circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen was cruising along with a four-hit shutout with two
out in the sixth until he unexpectedly encountered an adversary
almost as formidable as his ex-wife's divorce lawyer: the Red Sox
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Valentin and first baseman Mo Vaughn committed
errors on consecutive plays. Valentin's throw on Rico Brogna's
bouncer went right through Vaughn's glove, allowing Brogna to
reach. The next batter, Parent, also bounced one to Valentin, who
took his time to measure his throw, then bounced one in the dirt
past Vaughn, Phillies runners ending up on second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, working carefully, then hung a 3-and-2 offspeed
pitch that Abreu whacked into center field for an RBI single,
making it 2-1. Lewis flied to right to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started all that garbage that inning,'' said Vaughn, who
said he lost Valentin's throw in the crowd. ``If that didn't
happen, he's probably still pitching. I just lost it, and the ball
hit the top of my glove. But that play should have been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Red Sox, the Phillies' defense also turned
generous in the seventh, when Lewis's second error of the night
allowed Boston to build on its lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phillies played us real tough,'' Vaughn said. ``Guys like
(Scott) Rolen and the rest, they play hard. They're an
up-and-coming team. We needed a win to get back on track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
