<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANDARDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA SCHOOL STANDARDS CALLED TOPS IN NATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHRYN CRENO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona's new academic standards for children at public schools
are the best in the nation, according to a report released Thursday
by a Washington, D.C., organization that looked at academics
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``More states earned D's and F's than A's and B's,'' concluded
the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation, a private educational research
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet . . . at least a few states managed to write magnificent
standards: documents that expect much from students. And three
states _ Arizona, closely followed by California and Texas _ did a
good enough job across the board to earn an honors-level GPA (grade
point average).''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation gave Arizona a B+ composite grade. Its science
standards earned an A, while math and English standards earned B's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool!'' said Penny Kotterman, who will be sworn into office
next week as the president of the Arizona Education Association.
``It's quite an honor. Arizona is finally No. 1 in something
related to education.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood also was jubilant at the state Department of Education,
which developed the standards with panels of citizens and educators
before they were adopted by the state Board of Education in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thrilled,'' said Billie Orr, an associate
superintendent charged with spreading the word about the new
standards and a future high school graduation test based on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the top _ and not even sharing it with anyone. It's
truly incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Fordham's report called academic standards in many other states
``vague'' and ``hostile to knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Three states _ Iowa, Nevada and Wyoming _ were not included in
the study because they do not have a formal set of academic
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national picture is bleak,'' the report concluded.
``Scores of states have spent millions of dollars to create shabby
_ and in some cases utterly useless _ documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona spent about $1.7 million to develop the Arizona
Instrument to Measure Standards or AIMS test _ which is based on
the new standards and which fifth-, eighth-, 10th- and 12th-graders
will take starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's science standards were praised for their careful
definitions and specific requirements. For example, Sir Isaac
Newton's laws must be introduced by eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that the science standards have been criticized
by teachers and college professors for excluding the word
``evolution.'' A panel of citizens and educators is revising the
standards to include evolution, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
   Kotterman said she believes Arizona's standards work because
they were developed during a 2{-year process that included input
from panels of teachers, administrators, parents and even
schoolkids. &QL; 
 &UR; Cathryn Creno can be reached at 444-8056 or at
cathryn.creno &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
