<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-ALLEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S UNANIMOUS: ROSENBLATT BEATS ALLEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEDYARD, Conn. _ Dana Rosenblatt had to work a full shift
Thursday night, but not for want of trying to get off early.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 10 rounds, the Malden, Mass., middleweight pounded
the head and body of Arthur Allen as if he were an old throw rug in
need of a dusting. Then the tiring Rosen-blatt suddenly went wobbly
when Allen landed a short uppercut late in the final round that
seemed to momentarily stun him.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he was so far ahead that he needed only to stay upright
to win his fourth straight fight since a 14-month layoff caused by
a hand injury. When he did, judges Fred Ucci and George Smith had
him a 98-91 winner, while Robert Paolino saw it 96-93. The Globe
had Rosenblatt in a 99-92 romp.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt dominated the first four rounds, pounding Allen to
the body and then hooking him to the head until he had bloodied his
right eye and had his mouth hanging open from fatigue. But at the
end of the fourth, Allen got his head into Rosenblatt's face and
gave him a slight cut along the inside of his left brow that was
more of an irritant than a concern.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Rosenblatt's plan was to try to negate Allen's
81-inch reach by getting inside and staying there, ripping body
shots with the surgically repaired right hand that had caused that
long layoff.
</P>
<P>
   Allen finally began to take this one-sided beating personally
late in Round 5. When the bell sounded, he stood nose to nose with
Rosenblatt in a stare-down that carried considerably less
intimidation than the norm because it came after he had lost all of
the fight's first 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This pattern continued, with Rosenblatt scoring heavily to the
body and often to the head but spending too much time leaning in on
the inside. This caused him to lose his balance on occasion and
prevented him from landing a crisp hook to the head that might have
rendered Allen unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Allen (23-4) finally did go down late in the eighth from a
crushing left hand but was up at the count of four. Rosenblatt
attacked him wildly but was unable to land a finishing shot. Allen
gamely took his lumps and occasionally fired back to no avail as
the fight dragged on to its 10-round conclusion. The only question
by now concerned what had prompted Allen to stay upright for so
long while being peppered by 123 more punches (302-179) than he
managed to land despite throwing 45 more than Rosenblatt (625-580).
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had him out in the eighth round,'' said Rosenblatt
(32-1). ``The guy gave me a good fight, but it takes time to get
yourself back to 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt's victory was good news for his promoter, Bob Arum,
who was in need of some because the bad news for him had started
long before the fights did. Arum learned early in the day that
International Boxing Federation welterweight champion Felix
Trinidad had signed a new promotional deal with Dino Duva and
Friday will announce a six-bout deal to fight exclusively on HBO.
Worse for Arum, Trinidad and World Boxing Association champ Ike
Quartey had signed an agreement for a fall meeting. This came even
as Arum was increasing his $3.5 million offer by $1 million for
Quartey to fight World Boxing Council champ Oscar De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   In the ring, De La Hoya's next scheduled opponent, Julio Cesar
Chavez, suffered a deep cut over his right eye in the second round
of what was supposed to be a tuneup fight with Ken Sigurani.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a foul,'' said Chavez (101-2-2). ``I was really
(upset), so I went straight for the knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   It came one round later when Chavez nailed Sigurani with a
booming right hand that sent him spinning to the floor. He got up
at the count of four but immediately fell backward into the ropes,
and referee Arthur Mercante Sr. jumped in and stopped the bout at
2:09 of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught me with a heavy right hand, and that was it,''
Sigurani said. ``He's still one of the great punchers in the
division.''
</P>
<P>
   He may be, but he is also a worn-out one who seems to end up
bleeding after every fight these days, regardless of his opponent.
This time he was cut badly enough that he went immediately to a
local hospital for plastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about an inch and a half long,'' said cutman Miguel
Diaz. ``But he'll be fine for September.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure he will. Until the fight starts.
</P>
</TEXT>
