<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS INTRODUCE OLOWOKANDI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just a few hundred feet from the future home of
the franchise, the Los Angeles Clippers on Thursday introduced the
future of their franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Center Michael Olowokandi arrived at the Los Angeles Convention
Center, adjacent to the site where construction has begun on the
Staples Center, where the Clippers and Lakers will play basketball
in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi couldn't have sounded happier in his first day as a
Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's big time, coming to L.A.,'' Olowokandi said. ``That's
more or less like a dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever it takes to make the team better.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was accompanied by his parents, Ezekial and Agnes.
His father is a Nigerian diplomat stationed in England. Both
parents got their first glimpse of their son's basketball skills
when they watched a videotape Wednesday morning in the Clippers
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if they wanted their son to leave England to try and play
college basketball, Ezekial Olowokandi responded, ``Not at all. We
stress academics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Why can't you play basketball here?''' Michael
said.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi has hardly ignored academics, majoring in mechanical
engineering at Pacific. But that will wait, now that he is
guaranteed millions as the NBA's top draft pick, the first European
to claim such an honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``How significant an impact I make remains to be seen,'' a
humble Olowokandi said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was primarily a track star in England, Olowokandi
said he couldn't resist the lure of pro basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track got kind of old. I was more exposed to the American
game,'' Olowokandi said. ``We saw highlight films of Magic Johnson
and Michael Jordan. It was something I wanted to be part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi was welcomed at the press conference by Clippers
forward Maurice Taylor. The pair have a lot in common, since Taylor
didn't play basketball until he was 16, and Olowokandi did not play
organized basketball until he was 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make my life a lot easier,'' Taylor said. ``If
you asked management, they know who I wanted to pick. We both
started playing basketball fairly late. We both want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only question Olowokandi had trouble answering was how
he felt being on a team that does not have a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no feelings about that. That's not my job,'' Olowokandi
said. ``That's up to management.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it came as a mild surprise publicly that the Clippers
took Olowokandi over Arizona point guard Mike Bibby, Olowokandi's
agent, Bill Duffy, said the hype of Bibby going No.1 was overblown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was orchestrated. I think that was a media
campaign orchestrated,'' Duffy said, referring to Bibby's powerful
agent, David Falk.
</P>
<P>
   As for Falk, he was upset Thursday that the Clippers bypassed
his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Clippers made a mistake,'' Falk said. ``I think
the Clippers' loss is (Vancouver's) gain. I think Olowokandi will
be a terrific player, but I think that you need somebody directing
and running your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk acknowledged that he met Tuesday afternoon with Clippers
owner Donald Sterling, in a last-ditch attempt to get Bibby in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as we approach the 21st century for a team like the
Clippers _ and you're moving into a new building with the Lakers _
I think it's more than simply a business decision,'' Falk said.
``It's an entertainment decision. I think with Mike having won a
national championship, he's the best-known player in the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Although USC coach Henry Bibby is not a candidate for the
Clippers' coaching position, he had hoped to establish a
relationship with his son, with all the talk that Mike would become
a Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy that we might be able to get our relationship
where it should be between a father and son,'' Bibby said.
``Hopefully, his mother will let him grow up the way he should and
let him get on with his life and be himself. Hopefully, she will
stay out of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bibby's mother, Virginia, said she intended to move to
Vancouver to be with her son, and ``we won't have to deal with''
the problems that exist in the family.
</P>
</TEXT>
