<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DOUGLAS-SAVARESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVARESE DERAILS DOUGLAS'S BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEDYARD, Conn. _ The dream ended with both Buster Douglas and
Lou Savarese on the floor Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Savarese was on his knees in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Buster Douglas was on his back in a fog.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken only 2 minutes 42 seconds for Douglas to fall from
grace, triggering Savarese's celebration of his first-round
victory.
</P>
<P>
   All week, Douglas had looked like a man suddenly old and worn
out. His face seemed gaunt, his belly loose. Though only 38, which
these days seems young for a heavyweight boxer, he appeared to be a
fighter on his last legs.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the first bell sounded in the Bingo Hall at
Foxwoods Casino, he wasn't even able to stand on those legs, having
been knocked off them by a straight right hand that sent him
toppling to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   One second he was jabbing hard, the way he had the night he beat
Mike Tyson for the world championship eight years ago. The next, he
was drawing that left hand back a little too slowly and crumbling
from a straight right over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched a lot of film of him,'' said Savarese (37-2, 31
KOs). ``He was dropping his left hand when he jabbed, and I was
looking to come in over the top of his jab.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Douglas got up at the count of four, he was now in the
wrong place at the wrong time. His dream of cashing a
million-dollar check for a rematch with Tyson was turning into a
nightmare of punches he could not stop hitting him in places he
could no longer protect.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Savarese carefully circled at first, searching patiently for
another opening, his heart racing as he watched his clearly wounded
opponent move. Finally, he saw what he was looking for and sent
another right hand to the ear, and Douglas went down again, landing
hard.
</P>
<P>
   Although he got up again, Douglas was now standing in the
executioner's dock, waiting for the hangman. His fate was sealed
when an emboldened Savarese rushed in and fired a flurry of punches
over the former champion's lowered hands, and Douglas fell down a
third time, this time landing face first, as Savarese leaped into
the air.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no three-knockdown rule in an International Boxing
Association title fight, so as Douglas struggled to push himself up
off the canvas once again, referee Steve Smoger informed the
already celebrating Savarese that the party was over.
</P>
<P>
   Or rather, that it hadn't quite started yet.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for it to begin. Before Savarese could leave
the neutral corner to finish the demolition, Douglas righted
himself, only to topple backward in Savarese's corner without
another punch being thrown.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Steve Smoger took one look at Douglas's pile of flesh on
the canvas and didn't even bother to count. The dream was over for
Buster Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up big time,'' said Douglas (36-6-1), his eyes still
glassy as he spoke minutes after he'd lost what surely seems his
final fight.
</P>
<P>
   With his robe now back around his shoulders and a hood covering
his head, Douglas left the ring and headed back to his locker room.
As he walked, his trainer, John Russell, dealt forthrightly with
the aftermath: ``Maybe it's time for us to go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Buster Douglas wasn't heard quarreling with that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-DOUGLAS-SAVARESE-     06-26 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-DOUGLAS-SAVARESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVARESE MAKES QUICK WORK OF DOUGLAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANSHANTUCKET, Conn. _ James (Buster) Douglas and Lou Savarese
came here on Thursday night to reaffirm their standing in the
heavyweight division. It took just one round for Savarese to clear
things up for himself and muddle things for Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   With three blazing right hands Savarese sent Douglas sprawling
to the canvas three straight times in the first round, prompting
Referee Steve Smoger to stop the bout at 2 minutes 34 seconds after
Douglas had wobbled to his feet and had fallen into his corner
following the third knockdown.
</P>
<P>
   The knockout victory earned Savarese (37-2) the International
Boxing Association championship and left him in a sobbing heap on
the canvas. The stunning setback probably sent Douglas (36-6-1)
back into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell, Douglas' longtime trainer, said: ``He got popped
good. Maybe it's time for us to go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, 38, who knocked out Mike Tyson for the undisputed
heavyweight championship of the world in 1990, had ballooned to 400
pounds and was near death in a diabetic coma in 1994. He lost
weight and regained his desire to box while getting himself in
shape.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Savarese had not looked this impressive since
his 12-round loss to George Foreman in April 1997. He was knocked
out by David Izon last November and won on a second-round technical
knockout in his last fight, against Jeff Lally on April 23.
Savarese had gone into training with Tim Hallmark, Evander
Holyfield's Houston-base conditioning trainer.
</P>
<P>
   On the undercard, Julio Cesar Chavez took his stroll along the
garden path toward his Sept. 18 bout with Oscar De La Hoya in Las
Vegas, Nev., but it wasn't as smooth as he thought it would be.
Yes, he did beat Ken Sigurani, stopping him on a technical knockout
when Referee Arthur Mercante stopped the fight at 2 minutes 9
seconds of the third round. But it was not without some pain.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez (101-2-2) and Sigurani (22-2) clashed heads in the second
round and the butt opened a cut over Chavez's right eye. Chavez
ended the fight before it could become a bigger problem.
</P>
<P>
   De La Hoya stopped Chavez on a cut in the very same place in the
fourth round of their 1996 fight. The promoter Bob Arum said
Chavez's eye should heal within a month and that there was no
danger that the fight against De La Hoya would be postponed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
