<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8012 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN     06-26 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROJECT: JUMPSTART DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers' new coaches arrived
Thursday, saying all the right things and promising to bring energy
to the sagging club.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting instructor Mickey Hatcher, pitching coach Charlie Hough
and bullpen coach John Shelby were brought in by new general
manager Tom Lasorda for their blend of personality, championship
experience and teaching ability.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher and Shelby were key members of the Dodgers World Series
championship team in 1988. Hough, promoted from Class-A San
Bernardino, pitched on three Dodger pennant winners in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie is the most knowledgeable pitching coach in the
organization,'' said the outgoing Goose Gregson. ``The team is in
excellent hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, also brought in from San Bernardino, was one of the
most popular players in Dodgers history. But he also was a .280
hitter who became a respected batting instructor during three
seasons as a minor-league manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players responded to him and we know they will respond here,
too,'' said Dodgers manager Glenn Hoffman, who served the past two
years as minor-league field coordinator. ``Behind all the fun is a
guy who can teach and understands about patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher received a huge ovation during the game when one of
clips from his playing days appeared on the left-field video
screen. He greeted Lasorda with a hug in the Dodgers dugout before
the game. ``I'm going to make them all switch-hitters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby's new job is confusing, to him as well. He was a career
outfielder for Baltimore and the Dodgers but will spend most of his
time in the bullpen. But Shelby also will be responsible for
coordinating the Dodgers pregame batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be out there and I'll probably be in the dugout, too,''
Shelby said. ``I think it is a job that will develop as we go
along. It is great to be back here. Tommy said I'd make it back
someday.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Opening day: Adrian Beltre began his major-league career
Wednesday night with an RBI single on the first pitch he faced
against left-hander Chuck Finley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he said. ``I never played in front of a crowd
like that before. But I didn't really feel nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, was brought up Monday from Double-A San Antonio,
where he batted 321 with 13 homers, 56 RBI and 20 stolen bases
despite missing 20 games with sore ankles. Beltre also got a hit in
the 11th inning Wednesday but aggravated his left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still bother me, but I can play through it,'' he said. ``
Maybe they brought me up a little too early, but being here is what
every player lives for. I feel I am ready.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Martinez in Dominican: Ramon Martinez, who will undergo
season-ending shoulder surgery on Tuesday, has returned to his home
in the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very down right now,'' said Dodgers vice president Ralph
Avila, who will play a bigger role in the Lasorda regime. ``But
nobody worked harder last winter when he had the torn rotator cuff.
He will work that way again and I expect him to make a complete
recovery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
