<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LAD     06-26 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOOPER'S ROAD   MAP DIRECTS HIM EASTWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL SCHLOTTER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lance Hooper had accomplished all he could on West Coast race
tracks. So in 1997, with Winston West and Featherlite Southwest
Tour titles on his resume, he kissed wife Jennifer and daughter
Nicole goodbye and left Palmdale to seek his NASCAR fortune in
North Carolina, the heartland of stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was spent making contacts _ shaking hands and saying
yes sir and no sir to as many team owners as possible. Along the
way, he made occasional guest appearances driving on the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck and Busch Grand National series.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he caught a limited Busch Series ride with Richard
Jackson Motorsports.
</P>
<P>
   With his team making only seven of the 15 races so far, Hooper
isn't exactly tearing up the tour in points. He's not ranked in the
top 40. But he was the second-fastest qualifier at June 5's
Hardee's 250 at Richmond International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   And more important in Hooper's view _ he's getting a racing
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning a lot,'' Hooper said. ``This is all a stepping
stone to my goal to be in Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Hooper excelled on the short flat tracks of the West early in
his career. But he found his expertise of scant value on Eastern
circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to retrain myself,'' Hooper said. ``Their short
tracks back here are longer than our long tracks out west. And
their flat tracks have more banking than our banked tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition is fierce as well, Hooper said. At any given
race some 50 to 55 cars might show up to qualify for the 36
starting slots. And up to a dozen of the drivers might be Winston
Cup regulars looking to warm up for their race by whipping up on
the Busch drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Thus it was that Hooper was pretty proud of that No.2 start at
Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt pretty good about that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hooper sees nothing but good things ahead for himself and his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a brand new car,'' he said. ``And we're a young
team and we're growing together.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard part for Hooper is being away from his wife and
daughter. And he is hoping his team can scrape together the funds
to come out west for the Busch tour's July 19 stop at California
Speedway in Fontana.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get sponsorship for that,'' Hooper said. ``My
wife and daughter are still in Palmdale and I really want to come
out for that race. So if you know of anyone.....''
</P>
<P>
   __ Wedding-bell blues: North Hollywood racer Jeff Shafer and his
girl friend Jolene Wulff have planned for months to get married in
Escondido on July 5 and then spend the next week or so honeymooning
in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Then Shafer got this job driving a race car on the KOOL/Toyota
Atlantic series with Arciero-Wells Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent an invitation to one of the mechanics on my team and
he comes up to me and says, `Hey, you know we're testing in
(Wisconsin) the next day.''' Shafer said. ``I said, `Uh-oh, we're
going to have to resolve this.'''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the resolution was painless _ albeit inconvenient _ and
has Wulff's blessing. The couple's nuptials end at 9 p.m. July 5.
At 10 p.m. they board a plane for Milwaukee, arrive at about 5:15
a.m., then drive an hour and a half to the Road America track in
Elkhart Lake.
</P>
<P>
   After a day of testing Shafer's car, the couple will catch a
plane for Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Shafer said Jolene doesn't mind the detour.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's completely supportive of my career,'' the Grand High
School product said. ``All she said was that she wanted to go with
me to Wisconsin. She didn't want to get married, then stay behind
while I went off to test.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Herta close again: Valencia's Bryan Herta won his second pole
start of the season and finished third at last weekend's FedEx CART
Budweiser/G.I. Joe 200 in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   It was Herta's second pole of the season and the fifth of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Herta held the lead three times during the race. But he
encountered a bit of bad luck when his team gambled by taking an
unscheduled pit stop for fresh tires on lap 73 of the 98-lap race.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was to bring Herta in for fresh tires during a yellow
flag, giving him an advantage over eventual winner Alex Zanardi,
who chose to stay on the track. But when the green flag came out to
restart the race, Herta got stuck in traffic while Zanardi speed
off to an untouchable lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Herta's third-place finish moved him into fifth
place in season points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
