A8178 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DISSIDENTS-HN     06-26 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISSIDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND AIDES RESPOND SOFTLY TO CHINA'S ARREST OF DISSIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton responded cautiously Friday to the
Chinese government's ham-handed roundup of prominent dissidents in
the opening days of his historic visit and said the arrests
underlined the importance of his policy of engaging China.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese authorities' detention of at least three political
activists in the city of Xian where Clinton began his nine-day
visit played right into the hands of the president's critics back
home who insist that his policy of ``constructive engagement'' with
China is a one-way street.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called reports of the arrests ``disturbing'' and added:
``If true, they represent not China at its best and not China
looking forward but looking backward.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials tried to minimize the impact of
the seizures at the outset of 11 hours of U.S.-China summitry
following a controversial welcoming ceremony in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the first American president to visit China since the
murderous crackdown on pro-democracy activists in and around
Tinanamen Square in 1989. The suppression claimed the lives of up
to 800 unarmed demonstrators and bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said China's latest detentions merely underscore the
necessity of his mission to persuade Chinese authorities to expand
individuals' political freedoms to match the shift to a burgeoning
free enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests make ``it all the more important that we continue to
work with the Chinese and to engage them,'' Clinton said in Xian
before flying to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has insisted that privately conveying U.S. concerns
about Chinese human rights has paid off with prisoner releases and
expanded U.S.-Chinese trade.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said there was not a reliable count on the number
of dissidents detained or arrested. One U.S. official, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said White House officials regard the
crackdown merely as an effort by local governments to stem
potential protests by activists who might seek to use Clinton's
visit as protection for their activities.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger also
downplayed Clinton administration concerns, insisting that the
ill-timed detentions were ``not directed at'' Clinton because
``this happens generally in connection with these types of
visits.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger added that the detentions were ``not of the scale that
has happened before.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when pressed by reporters did Berger begin to express
indignation.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests are ``thoroughly unacceptable,'' Berger said. The
Chinese government's explanation in response to inquiries by
Ambassador James Sasser ``so far has not been terribly
satisfactory,'' Berger said, adding: ``They dispute the facts or
otherwise explain these incidents away.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger declared at one point: ``People are not debris to be
swept up for a visitor and we have expressed our concern about this
to the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who has visited China twice in recent months to set the
stage for Clinton's visit, said Chinese authorities approached the
visit with a ``combination of excitement, anticipation and fear''
that triggered ``the instinct of some...to let their desire for
order overwhelm their ability to permit expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton planned to privately press Chinese President
Jiang Zemin to release more than 2,000 imprisoned Chinese citizens
who are either in labor re-education camps or prison, including
about 150 residents of Beijing imprisoned for their roles in the
Tiananmen Square movement.
</P>
<P>
   Berger hinted that Chinese authorities would release additional
dissidents from prison after Clinton's departure, adding: ``I would
not anticipate that we would see the fruits of those discussions
while we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's arrival in the ancient Chinese capital of Xian late
Thursday appeared to trigger the detention of at least three
advocacy of democracy and the forced flight of a fourth activist.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his advisers have resisted appeals to meet privately
with Chinese dissidents _ claiming that the rendezvous could irk
the Beijing regime and provoke retaliatory arrests after he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY MAY END HERE - OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yang Hai, a resident of Xian and one of 70 Chinese who signed an
open letter appealing for Clinton to meet with dissidents during
his visit, was detained Thursday shortly after ABC News'
correspondent Sam Donaldson tried to interview him at an Xian
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities detained two other Xian-area activists, as
well, according to the Information Center of Human Rights and
Democratic Movement in China, based in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Yan Jun, a Xian resident who signed the letter, and Li Zhiying,
who lives near Xian, were detained Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese police also picked up Fu Sheng, a resident of Xian who
signed the appeal to Clinton, and sent him by train to Qingdao on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons that I came here was to discuss both
privately and publicly issues of personal freedom,'' Clinton told
reporters on Friday as he prepared to meet with residents of the
village of Xiahe, adjacent to the site of the buried 2,200-year-old
terra cotta warriors outside Xian. ``So I think it's very important
for me to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says his efforts have won the release of two prominent
Chinese dissidents in the past eight months. Wei Jingsheng was
freed from prison and sent into exile in the United States last
November shortly after Clinton raised his case during the state
visit to the United States by Chinese President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Dan was freed and sent into U.S. exile in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 0819EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PM-CHINA-CLINTON-0626     06-26 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PM-CHINA-CLINTON-0626-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON FLIES TO BEIJING FOR SUMMIT TALKS
 &HT;    EDs: Note that the time for broadcast of the Tiananmen ceremony
is one hour earlier than we originally thought.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Bill Clinton flew to smoggy Beijing Friday
in hopes of wrapping up a nuclear weapons ``detargeting'' agreement
by which both sides would pledge not to point their missiles at
each other.
</P>
<P>
   After a low-pressure day in Xi'an of sightseeing and talking
with peasants about their village-level elections, Air Force One
headed here for an intense weekend of negotiations and banquets
with leaders of China's ruling communist party politburo.
</P>
<P>
   The initial glow of Clinton's Day One in China was dimmed Friday
with the news that Chinese security officials had detained three
dissidents in Xi'an, reportedly after they delivered a letter to
the city police bureau protesting the arrest of several other
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called reports of the detentions ``disturbing.'' His
national security adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger added, ``People
are not debris to be swept up for a visitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Official talks with Chinese President Jiang Zemin are set to
begin immediately after the Chinese carry through their 21-gun
welcoming ceremony for the American president on the western edge
of Tiananmen Square. The 20-minute Tiananmen ceremony is expected
to be broadcast live on some American news networks at 9 p.m.
Friday EDT (9 a.m. Saturday Beijing time).
</P>
<P>
   If behind-the-scenes bargaining between U.S. and Chinese
security advisers goes well, a missile detargeting agreement is
likely to be unveiled in a signing ceremony in front of the Great
Hall of the People a few hours after the Tiananmen Square welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would certainly like such an agreement,'' Berger told a
news briefing in Xi'an. But Berger said he wasn't sure if details
could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's homefront critics have called a
``detargeting'' deal meaningless, arguing that a missile's
targeting coordinates can be secretly updated in less than 20
minutes. Clinton has replied that such an agreement could prevent
an accidental world war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you detarget, yes, you can always go retarget a missile, we
all know that,'' Clinton said in a Washington interview with Cox
News Service last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it takes some more time, and 20 minutes in a world of
instantaneous communications is an eternity. So the possibility of
avoiding a mistake, or even backing down from a conflict, is
dramatically increased with detargeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reached America's first ``detargeting'' agreement with
Russian President Boris Yeltsin in 1994. Then Russia signed a
similar ``detargeting'' agreement with China in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last year, China has resisted American entreaties to
join in a mutual ``detargeting'' pact. A Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman insisted again this month that the United States must
first sign a ``no first use'' pledge, under which no future
American president could threaten nuclear strikes to deter a
non-nuclear ground or sea attack.
</P>
<P>
   Western intelligence agencies have reported that China has an
aging thermonuclear strike force of 13 to 18 intercontinental
ballistic missiles (ICBM), including perhaps four with sufficient
range to hit New York City and Washington D.C. According to Chinese
sources, each Chinese ICBM is armed with one city-busting hydrogen
bomb warhead of three-to-five megatons.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading to Beijing and the controversial Tiananmen Square
welcome, Clinton spent the day around Xi'an Friday, visiting
villages and touring China's most important archeological dig, the
2nd Century B.C. vault containing than 7,000 ancient terra cotta
warriors, horses and chariots.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby village of Xiahe, Clinton heard Yang Dongye, 56,
the owner of a soy sauce and vinegar factory, enthuse about how his
life has improved in China since the wave of private-enterprise
reforms initiated by the late communist leader Deng Xiaoping in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, no matter what your abilities are, you are told
to do what you are supposed to do,'' Yang said. ``But after the
reform, everyone can have the space to show their own talent and to
work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   For clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
