<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCK-SWINDLE-NYT &LR;      06-26 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCK-SWINDLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONGANTHAU, AFTER ARREST, SEEKS REPEAL OF STOCK RULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Announcing arrests in an international stock swindle
Thursday, the Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau,
called on federal authorities to repeal a regulation that he said
leaves investors vulnerable to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said the defendants in his recent investigation used
a law that allows companies to avoid many financial reporting
requirements when issuing stock outside the United States. The
section of the federal securities law, called Regulation S, has
been the subject of controversy during the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan prosecutors said Thursday that the defendants had
taken advantage of the regulation to fraudulently inflate the stock
value of several small companies. They said that investors in
England and the United States were cheated out of more than $17
million in the last five years as a result of the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said that the suspects approached small companies in
need of cash and told them they could provide fast money by selling
stock to overseas investors. Because the stock sales fell under
Regulation S, the companies did not have to file financial
information with Federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the defendants set up phony corporations on the
Isle of Jersey, and used the corporations to buy the stock. The
phony companies traded the stocks back and forth, inflating their
value.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the stocks were sold to American and British
investors, who did not know that they were overvalued, prosecutors
said. A critical element of the fraud, Morgenthau said, was the
inability of legitimate investors to get accurate financial
information about the stgck offerings _ because of Regulation S.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men, Salvatore Mazzio, 40, of Long Island, a New York
stock promoter, has already pleaded guilty to attempted enterprise
corruption and faces up to 15 years in state prison, Morgenthau
said. Two other suspects have been arrested by the British police,
but have not yet been charged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, Regulation S is a big mistake,'' Morgenthau
said Thursday. ``There really is a single market now. It isn't as
though the markets in Europe, or anywhere else, are all that
different.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulation S has been debated in the financial community in the
last several years, in part because law enforcement officials
believe it was a tool that was increasingly used for fraud. John
Moscow, a prosecutor who has handled a number of complicated
financial cases for Morgenthau's office, said Thursday that
Regulation S ``has been known for years as a scoundrel's delight.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan King, a spokesman for the Securities and Exchange
Commission, said Thursday that the commission had tightened
Regulation S in the last several months. The commission has
increased the reporting requirements and has lengthened a holding
period during which Regulation S stock cannot be sold in United
States markets.
</P>
<P>
   The original purpose of the Regulation S exemption was to lessen
the expense of raising capital for American corporations by
eliminating the often high costs of reporting and registering
stocks with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes made this spring were stronger financial
record-keeping requirements for companies that do issue Regulation
S stock. Under the new regulations, companies must affix a marker
to the stock indicating it was issued under Regulation S.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also must keep records of who buys the Regulation
S stock, and must notify the buyers that the stock cannot legally
be sold in the United States until a year after its issue date.
Even then, King said, there are restrictions on how much stock can
be sold at one time.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgenthau said that the failure to require full disclosure
in stock issuance was an invitation for fraud, particularly when
overseas investors could hide behind bank secrecy laws that exist
in many foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is wrong,'' Morgenthau said. ``Whatever they do
overseas affects U.S. investors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
