A8297 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX     06-26 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: This concerns a cat and a religious experience
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ We moved across town finally, starting last
weekend and continuing through most of the week. By late Wednesday,
we were out of the old house, in the new one and had unpacked
everything.
</P>
<P>
   Some people greet this news with some disbelief. You moved,
unpacked and even hung the pictures in four days, they say
skeptically. It takes us months to unpack everything.
</P>
<P>
   This is largely a difference in perspective, I suspect. I am a
maniac about unpacking as quickly as possible. I will start early
and stay late. For example, the night that preceded the religious
experience and the cat, I hung pictures until 2:30 a.m. and was
back up at 7 finishing up.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, my running buddy has the same approach to moving. Get
it done, get the stuff put up and get things back to normal as
quickly as possible. Or as normal as they get in a house with a
teen rock musician, a precocious nine-year-old beauty-queen
fanatic, and my two weekend teen-agers. Not to mention the cats.
</P>
<P>
   Being a long_time cat tenant (nobody owns cats; you just rent
them for a while), I have learned to leave the cats in the old home
as long as possible. Cats are Republican in nature. They don't like
change. Dogs are Democrats. They have a lot of fun but make a lot
of messes. So when moving cats, I make it the absolutely last thing
that I do.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki came to the new house first. She's my running buddy's cat,
a pretty Siamese with a brain about the size of an acorn _ and only
about half of that actually works. Luckily she has a winning
personality. It took her about 30 seconds to adapt to the new
house. Her approach was simple: Hide under the bed and sleep during
the day, and get on top of the bed and sleep with us at night. Eat
a lot and meow a lot. Siamese cats have an annoying meow.
</P>
<P>
   Otto is a tougher nut. He was my cat pre-marriage, and he's had
a rough life. He weighs about 15 pounds, a gray tabby who's
probably five years old and though neutered will still fight
anything in sight. Cats, dogs, raccoons _ it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Otto and I are tight. He showed up at my house during the
bachelor days, and we hit it off well. During those days, he stayed
outside all the time, often disappearing for days at a time but
then showing up bedraggled, often bearing a few fresh scars. It's
rough having to uphold a reputation as a kick-bootie cat. I fed him
faithfully, got his shots, and spent many pleasant hours on the
deck with him lying beside me, his fat head on my lap.
</P>
<P>
   When we got married and moved yet again, Otto mellowed out. My
theory is the female influence of my running buddy. Soon Otto was
staying inside most of the time, sleeping on the couch and
generally turning sorry. He and Kiki made peace after about six
months of brief skirmishes. The turning point was when he and Kiki
were chasing each other around the swimming pool, and Kiki nudged
him on a hairpin curve. Otto went into the pool.
</P>
<P>
   He got right out, shook himself like a dog. It's the first time
I've seen a cat look embarrassed. Imagine the ignominy, a 15-pound
cat knocked into the drink by a five-pound weenie Siamese. After
that, Otto's reputation was shot. He was humbled.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on Wednesday, I brought Otto out to the new house. He
was not a happy camper. Cats don't like riding the road, especially
locked up in a small cage. I was careful not to let him outside all
day. He eventually settled down and slept on our bed. Everything
seemed fine.
</P>
<P>
   Late that night, while hanging pictures, he wanted outside. Otto
won't use a litter box, which is another reason we're tight. Cats
can be housebroken just like dogs if they've got a lick of sense.
Even Kiki, bless her heart, is housebroken. I hate litter boxes.
</P>
<P>
   So I let him out and waited. He took off like a rocket. I called
him for about 30 minutes. Finally I went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, no Otto. We searched, asked around. By the next night,
I was convinced he'd hit the road again. After all, that's how I
got him.
</P>
<P>
   I was depressed. I've never been this attached to an animal. So
I sat in the porch swing late Thursday night, occasionally calling
his name.
</P>
<P>
   Then I prayed. It was a brief prayer, just a sentence really.
What I said was, ``Please God, bring Otto back here.''
</P>
<P>
   He showed up not 15 seconds later, meowing loudly. He was worn
out from whupping the competition, came inside, ate loudly and
slept until late the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   The small hairs on the back of my neck stood up when he turned
the corner and walked up just as soon as I finished my prayer.
Maybe it was coincidence, or good luck, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor of The Lufkin Daily News. His e-mail
address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
