<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EDENROC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glamor and glitter: Desi and Lucy stayed here
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ Things happen at the Eden Roc Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Like the time recently when Bobby Brown arrived with his wife,
Whitney Houston, and caused a scene in the lobby, berating bellmen
and any service people within shouting distance.
</P>
<P>
   Or the time George Clooney was kicked off the hotel's basketball
court because he had sneaked in without paying the $35 fee for
nonguests. And it wasn't the first time, according to a hotel
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Eden Roc is never dull, and it has been that kind of place
since the doors opened in 1956, and Harry Belafonte, Milton Berle
and Nat King Cole played the resort's elegant Cafe Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   Desi and Lucy were frequent guests, and the hotel's intimate
Mona Lisa Room was the setting for private parties including one
for Elizabeth Taylor and Mike Todd for the premiere of the film
Around the World in 80 Days.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the pool deck was Harry's American Bar, the hottest
nightclub in town, where celebrities could mingle with other
celebrities including Katharine Hepburn, Groucho Marx, Jackie
Gleason, Esther Williams, Bogie and Bacall, and Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most glamorous hotels in glamorous Miami Beach, the
Eden Roc was designed by Morris Lapidus, who also created the
Fontainebleau Hotel next door.
</P>
<P>
   The fantastic decor was beyond description - not Art Deco, not
French and not Baroque, Lapidus claimed. It was just grand - an MGM
set with gleaming terrazzo and marble floors and an enormous
columned lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has undergone a $28 million restoration, and with the
help of the 96-year-old Lapidus, looks much the same as it did in
its heyday, with mint green Alice-in-Wonderland furniture in the
lobby, and purple and green Baroqueish furniture in the guest
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And while Ocean Drive's boutique hotels attract their share of
publicity, the 14-story Eden Roc, named after a resort in France,
still is one of the hottest addresses in town. From Boyz to Men to
Sean Connery, Shaquille O'Neal, Steven Spielberg and Debbie
Reynolds, the celebrities still stay at the Roc.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fontainebleau Hilton Hotel, built in 1954, is
about to undergo a $100 million renovation that will include a
41-story tower. The new building will require the bulldozing of the
100-foot-high trompe l'oeil mural, painted in 1985 by Richard Haas,
on the southern wall of the hotel at a bend in Collins Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The mural, which gives the illusion of driving between two grand
arches into the resort, is beloved in South Beach and the prospect
of it being torn down has caused an outcry.
</P>
<P>
   Fontainebleau spokesmen won't discuss renovation projects. But
Randall Robinson of the Miami Beach Community Development
Corporation, says the hotel's plans have been approved and the
mural will soon be history.
</P>
<P>
   Take pictures of it now.
</P>
<P>
   BE COOL AT THE POOL
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: You're not allowed to sweat here - just to exude
glamour. Bring your 4-inch heels and your designer Lycra. Men can
wear anything from Milan.
</P>
<P>
   How much? At the Eden Roc, summer rates range from $145 to $245.
Call (800) 327-8337. At the Fontainebleau, rates range from $169 to
$225. Call (800) 445-8667.
</P>
<P>
   What to do? Both hotels have spas. The Fontainebleau has a great
swimming pool with a waterfall. Kids love it.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: JENNIFER PODIS/Staff Photographer
</P>
<P>
   The Fontainebleau Hilton's famous 100-foot-high trompe l'oeil
mural,
</P>
<P>
   on Collins Avenue, will be history when a $100-million
renovation,
</P>
<P>
   including a 41-story tower, gets under way.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-24-98 1332E
</P>
