<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MERRITISLE27-C     06-26 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MERRITISLE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travelling Cape Canaveral's wild neighbors best done from car
 &HT;    By John Lopinot
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERRITT ISLAND, Fla. _ A space center and a scenic refuge live
next door here, co-existing as friendly neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Merritt Island National Wildlife Refuge began as a
buffer zone for Cape Canaveral, when the National Aeronautical and
Space Administration bought 88,000 acres of Merritt Island in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Now, people come here to see the birds, manatees, bobcats and
raccoons.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge is one of the nation's most unusual natural areas.
With a subtropical climate, the 140,000-acre refuge has been shaped
by millions of years of wind and waves. Its barrier island has
ridges, swales and marshes that support 18 endangered or threatened
wildlife species, more than any other wildlife refuge in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Natural salt marshes like this have all but disappeared from
Florida's east coast because of development. Artifacts found at
mounds and shell middens indicate Indians may have lived on the
island as early as 7000 B.C.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1950s NASA began operations at Cape Canaveral. They
expanded significantly in 1961 when President Kennedy expanded
NASA's space exploration. You can see the launch towers for the
space shuttle from some roads in the refuge.
</P>
<P>
   A prime area to view birds is along the 6-mile long Black Point
Wildlife Drive, considered one of the premier birding areas in
Florida. Watching animals and birds in their natural habitat is
exciting, but it takes patience - wildlife often blends in with the
surroundings. Here are some tips to make your trip more successful:
</P>
<P>
   Drive slowly (20 mph or less). Stop frequently and quietly look
and listen.
</P>
<P>
   Take binoculars, wildlife identification guides, cameras, film
and telephoto lenses.
</P>
<P>
   Visit in the early morning or late afternoon when wildlife is
most active. The best months are October through March, during the
seasons when birds migrate. But birds can be found on the refuge
year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for wildlife just in the open water areas. Search the
mud flats, the edge of dikes, the trees and grass, which provide
cover. Also look for raptors soaring overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife is accustomed to cars on the wildlife drive. Getting
out of your car to get a closer view or take a picture will
probably scare away your subject. You are encouraged to stop, but
pull over to the side of the road so others can pass.
</P>
<P>
   STOP, LOOK AND LISTEN
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: Easy going here. Enjoy the wildlife drive from the
air-conditioned comfort from your car. Three short trails will make
you break a sweat this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   How to get there: Take I-95 north to Titusville. Then take SR
406 east to the refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Address: Merritt Island National Wildlife Refuge, P.O. Box 6504,
Titusville, FL 32782. Call (407) 861-0667.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: Sunrise to sunset. The refuge is occasionally closed
during space shuttle launches; call before you go to see if it will
be open.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: Free; but donations are accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
