r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MIAMIBEACH27-C     06-26 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MIAMIBEACH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The quick tour: 6 beauties on the beach
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH, Fla. _ While you're eating roast pork at Gloria
Estefan's restaurant, Larios, on Ocean Drive, you can impress your
friends with your knowledge of Art Deco.
</P>
<P>
   All you really need to know is this: The Art Deco buildings in
Miami Beach had three influences - cruise ships, the French world
exposition in 1926 and the turn-of-the-century German philosophy of
no frills architecture.
</P>
<P>
   First, the maritime inspiration. The porthole windows, curved
metal rails, flags and smokestacks on buildings came from the big
ocean liners that docked here. One of the best examples is the
Welcome Center building on Ocean Drive at 10th Street. The back of
the building looks like the bow of a ship moving out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   The second influence was the ornate decorations from the French
Exposition of Modern Industrial and Decorative Arts in 1926. An
example is the ``frozen fountain'' low relief on many buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The German influence was the straight, severe lines of the
``machine age.'' .
</P>
<P>
   You could spend a week inspecting all the buildings in the
district. Or 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick tour - all the buildings are on Ocean Drive near
the Welcome Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Central Hotel (between Sixth and Seventh streets),
fabulously renovated in 1985, was the first hotel to be returned to
its original splendor. (Miami Beach was decaying in the '60s and
'70s.) Built in 1937, it was the hangout for such Hollywood stars
as Clark Gable and Rita Hayworth. Giorgio Armani stays here. So
does author Anne Rice (along with her fictional French vampire
Lestat).
</P>
<P>
   The Avalon Hotel, on the northwest corner of Seventh Street and
Ocean Drive, has its share of celebs - one of the Spice Girls
checked in two weeks ago. This streamlined Deco building has stark
square columns. The 1955 Olds 88 convertible out front has been the
hotel's mascot for nine years. (It still runs.)
</P>
<P>
   The Waldorf Towers, 860 Ocean Drive. Check out the round glass
tower that looks like a lighthouse or a bridge on a ship.
</P>
<P>
   Versace Villa, corner of Ocean Drive and 11th Street. A
Mediterranean Revival extravaganza in the center of the Deco
district. The owner, Gianni Versace, was gunned down last year in
front of the black gates. This is where the tour buses stop and
block traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The Tides hotel, between 12th and 13th streets. This was the
last big Ocean Drive hotel to be renovated. It opened May last
year, and is the hippest place to stay. It's a severe Art Deco
monolith. Notice the porthole windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardozo Hotel. Don't miss the coral balusters and terrazzo
floors. And look out for the Estefans, who eat at the restaurant
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   ALL DECO-ED OUT AND READY TO STROLL
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: Saturday morning at 10:30? You're going to sweat,
but not from walking the dozen short blocks on the tour. Most of
the time, you're standing in front of buildings listening to the
guide. Bring a hat and sunscreen. Better yet, go in January.
</P>
<P>
   Tours: Art Deco Walking Tours leave the Art Deco Welcome Center,
on Ocean Drive at 10th Street, every Thursday evening at 6:30 p.m.
and Saturday at 10:30 a.m. Buy tickets, which are $10, at the
Welcome Center. Tours are 90 minutes. Call (305) 672-2014.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
