<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTHRITIS-DRUGS26-COX     06-26 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHRITIS-DRUGS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rheumatoid arthritis drug working wonders
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ Rheumatoid arthritis began crippling Peter
Looram when he was 41. Slowly, insidiously, the disease _ which
causes the body's immune cells to attack the joints _ sapped his
strength and diminished his ability to use his hands.
</P>
<P>
   By 49, he was taking a regimen of potent drugs that seemed
ineffectual. He spent a lot of time just sitting or lying down _ a
far cry from the outdoor athlete he had been in his adopted home of
Aspen, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't mountain bike or ski. I couldn't do eight hours a
day of work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the drugs he was taking weren't working, Looram's doctor
recommended an experimental drug being tested in his area.
</P>
<P>
   He enrolled last year in one of several national trials for
Enbrel, a drug developed by the Immunex Corp., which offers a new
approach to fighting the pain and inflammation of rheumatoid
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   This drug targets specific proteins that cause inflammation.
Low-dose chemotherapy drugs, such as the methotrexate Looram was
taking, attempt to depress immune cells in a shotgun manner to
suppress the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The shotgun approach can result in side effects, including liver
and lung problems.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkably short time after he started Enbrel _ three weeks
_ he was feeling improvement. Pain decreased, and the ability to
move his joints increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tickled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He found he could do more walking and hiking.
</P>
<P>
   This amazing turnaround doesn't surprise Dr. Yvonne Sherrer, a
Pompano Beach, Fla., rheumatologist who is also conducting
experimental trials with Enbrel.
</P>
<P>
   Even though her study is ``double-blind,'' meaning neither
doctor nor patient knows whether the drug or a placebo is being
administered, Sherrer has seen incredible improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't absolutely know who's getting what until after the
`blind' is taken off, but . . . we've had people go into very quick
and complete remissions,'' she said. ``This is really exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherrer, who has studied the disease for 17 years, said the
improvement was much quicker than with conventional drug
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw effects within a few weeks. With methotrexate, you
usually don't begin to see (improvement) for six weeks. And it
really doesn't show a significant difference for about three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these people (in the clinical trials) were
dramatically improved by four to six weeks with fewer side
effects.''
</P>
<P>
   The only negative, she said, is that the drug is injected, much
the same way a diabetic uses insulin. Patients inject once or twice
a week. Occasionally, patients develop a rash at the injection
site, but that seems to be the most serious side effect noted in
studies. Minor colds were also reported.
</P>
<P>
   The improvement was so dramatic for one of Sherrer's patients
that the woman begged to be kept in the trial, even when she
developed high blood pressure unrelated to the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to take her off it, but she begged me to let her stay
on _ that was how much a difference it made in her quality of
life,'' Sherrer said.
</P>
<P>
   Another patient, a forest ranger, was at the point where she was
sure she would be fired or have to quit because of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your hands get swollen, stiff, you're in pain, you lose grip
strength. A typical pattern is that it affects the small joints of
the hands and feet, but it can affect really any joint, and if you
can't grip, or hold a pistol . . . well, she's gone from the point
when they were probably going to fire her to doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sherrer doesn't know for certain who is taking the Enbrel,
Looram knew he was testing the drug in the trial he joined. When
trials are completed, Enbrel will go to the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration for approval, before it is available to the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Enbrel, call Immunex at 1-800-IMMUNEX
(466-8639).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
