A8308 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GWTW-ART27-COX     06-26 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GWTW-ART27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Artist's descendants seek original ``GWTW'' works
 &HT;    By Gary Schwan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The paintings are gone with the wind, too.
</P>
<P>
   For years, artist Armand Seguso's descendants have been looking
for his art, which was used in the original poster and programs for
the movie ``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody in the family has been able to locate any of the
original work for the movie, or the original posters, for that
matter,'' said Armand's grandson Rick Seguso, a West Palm Beach
artist and actor.
</P>
<P>
   Seguso thinks MGM's art department may have simply discarded or
misplaced the oils. But Armand Seguso owned the rights to the
original works, his grandson said. It's possible he might have
painted over the canvases, or thrown them out himself.
</P>
<P>
   For Armand Seguso, ``Gone With the Wind'' was another commission
among many, and he had a reputation as one of the country's fastest
movie illustrators. And one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``An old advertising device has attained the stature of a new
art form on the American scene,'' wrote an MGM publication in the
'40s, bragging about Seguso's Old Masterly skill. ``The old
ballyhoo circus poster of the past has been superseded by the
finely executed, super-powered appeal of the modern motion picture
poster.''
</P>
<P>
   Seguso may have worked for Selznick, but his inspiration was
Titian.
</P>
<P>
   Seguso (1897-1984) was born in Italy. He arrived in Wilkes
Barre, Pa., with his family when he was 4 years old. A violinist,
he began a music career at 17 with his waltz composition, ``Dream
of Mother.'' He studied art at the noted National Academy of Design
in New York, paying his way by playing theaters and cabarets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me of one instance when a fight broke out at a cabaret
he was working,'' Rick Seguso recalled. ``His half-brother pulled
him off a piano bench, where he was playing the violin. Seconds
later, there was a gunshot, and a bullet hit right where he'd been
sitting.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, Armand Seguso was commissioned to create advertisements
for Buster Keaton's ``Steamboat Bill, Jr.'' His best work was with
MGM, however. Besides ``Gone With the Wind,'' he created art for
dozens of films, including ``Mrs. Miniver,'' ``For Whom The Bell
Tolls,'' ``Kismet'' and ``Thirty Seconds Over Tokyo.''
</P>
<P>
   Seguso spent most of his career in New York, where he created
oil paintings based on detailed instructions sent to him from
Hollywood. ``He worked mostly from publicity stills and
occasionally live models,'' said Rick Seguso. ``The studio's art
department was very specific about what it wanted, and he was in
demand because he could give it to them quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides creating the posters, Armand Seguso painted portraits of
the lead actors in ``Gone With the Wind,'' which appeared in a
program sold at theaters around the country. Price: 25 cents. Price
today: a lot higher.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Seguso doesn't recall hearing many anecdotes about the film
industry or ``Gone With the Wind.'' He simply remembers his
grandfather as a lively jokester, a ``wonderful ham'' who liked to
play the guitar and violin at home.
</P>
<P>
   He also inspired his grandson, who is a painter, musician and
actor. Rick Seguso, 49, once worked as road manager for Bruce
Springsteen, sharing a house with the rock star in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   His paintings of imaginary landscapes and moody musicians have
won awards. He began exhibiting his work in the '70s, and now shows
at West End Fine Art in West Palm Beach and the International Art
Center in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He's appeared in movies shot in South Florida, such as ``Hostile
Takeover,'' and is currently appearing on stage in the Hollywood
Boulevard Theater production of ``Jenny's Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he ever thought of creating posters for his plays? ``No, but
thanks for the idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
