<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8309 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARLEY-MINISTER27-COX     06-26 1635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLEY-MINISTER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can a guy who loves motorcycles teach you about God? He says he
can
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH GARDENS, Fla. _ The Rev. Ray Underwood insists he was
not kicked out of King's Academy in the 11th grade.
</P>
<P>
   He was simply practicing his Kung Fu for Christ routine when his
foot went through the girl's bathroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood, who was in a Kung Fu for Christ group at a local
church, was suspended for three days and chose to leave the popular
West Palm Beach Christian school in 1975. He graduated from Palm
Beach Gardens High School a year later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was truly an accident,'' Underwood said. ``But I was a
terror as a kid. People would never have thought I would go into
the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a minister _ but not much changed.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Underwood is a 6-foot-5, 200-pound, 39-year-old pastor
with a high energy style who rides a ``hog,'' a Harley-Davidson
motorcycle, to services at the church he founded 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like speed,'' he said. ``I like going fast. When it comes to
speed, I like being on the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, this wired pastor pours his daring and enthusiasm into his
work. The Palm Beach Community Church in Palm Beach Gardens that
frequently draws as many as 1,000 people on a Sunday is, not
surprisingly, a different kind of place.
</P>
<P>
   The church follows a ``seeker sensitive'' nondenominational
model pioneered by the Willow Creek Community Church in South
Barrington, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to reach Baby Boomers _ and their children _ who are
either spiritually illiterate or have been put off by the
institutional church.
</P>
<P>
   There are no religious symbols to be seen and precious little
religious language to be heard in the Eissey campus theater where
the church meets on the grounds of Palm Beach Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning worship is a wondrous mix of music, drama and
nonthreatening Christian teaching in a relaxed atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   A music and drama team of 80 people spend as many as eight weeks
planning each Sunday experience.
</P>
<P>
   Stand-up vocalists belt out Christian music with a heavy beat
accompanied by electric guitars and drums. The audience _ or
congregation _ watches a dramatic presentation about the theme of
the day or sees a video on a huge screen that hangs above the
stage.
</P>
<P>
   And then Underwood or a colleague preaches for 30 minutes or
more using cultural catchwords to communicate religious ideas.
</P>
<P>
   A recent sermon titled ``What Would Jesus say to Bill Gates''
concluded that, in their spiritual life, Gates and everyone else
was running the wrong software, needed to upgrade to God's
operating system and run compatible programs.
</P>
<P>
   The ``seeker'' concept plays down traditional church trappings
and tries to make the ancient Gospel relevant to a high-tech,
fast-track, educated, skeptical population.
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite word is contextualization,'' Underwood said. ``It
simply means to take the Christian message and make it meaningful
to the cultural context in which you find yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to work. Kristina Vera got a direct mail promotion from
the church at her home in Palm Beach Gardens earlier this year. The
flier was about dating and relationships; it pictured Underwood on
his ``hog'' and invited her to a Sunday service at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Vera, 38, never went to church as a child, she said, and didn't
know where to start when she felt the need as an adult. The mailing
was intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Wow, a reverend with a Harley,' '' Vera said. ``I
can relate to that.''
</P>
<P>
   She found a caring community that welcomed her as a single
woman, addressed issues important in her life and helped her better
understand herself and her world, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such a false, bad image of the church,'' Underwood
said. ``They look at it as an institution that judges people rather
than one that loves and accepts people.''
</P>
<P>
   His commitment to build a church for the unchurched _ those who
know essentially nothing about religion _ came late in his faith
journey.
</P>
<P>
   Underwood was raised as a Southern Baptist in the First Baptist
Church of Lake Park. His family moved to North Palm Beach from
Miami when he was 3.
</P>
<P>
   He was always rushing as a kid. He thinks he was hyperactive and
knows he was always in trouble, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a teenager, he raced anything that would move _ hot rods,
dragsters and bikes. He loved risking his life racing his father's
boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was such a rush for me because you keep pushing to go
faster and faster. If you go too far, you kill yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he went to King's Academy in the ninth grade, he
knew he wanted to be a clergyman. That conviction was grounded in
his experiences in a happy home, at church, at church camp, in
prayer and wrestling with God about his future. But, for a
teenager, there were other good reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls at Kings,'' he said. ``You told them (about being a
minister), they'd hug me and kiss me. I'd say, `Oh, this is pretty
good.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He left Kings after the Kung Fu for Christ incident, but not
before meeting Janet Cooley, the young woman who would become his
wife. Their three children, Raymond, 15, Janell, 14, and Phillip,
12, attend Kings now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty active,'' said Paul Tatham, dean of admissions
at Kings Academy who remembers teaching Underwood's wife. ``He
married a good girl and has great kids. But he was kind of wired in
high school. They often turn out to be your best youth pastor
types. They know all the tricks of the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood graduated in 1979 after three years at Crichton
College, a nondenominational Bible college in Memphis, married
Janet and entered the Mid American Baptist Seminary in Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   He was hungry for knowledge and eager to start a church. He took
some courses at Fuller Seminary in California and enrolled in the
Trinity Evangelical Divinity School near Chicago to study for a
doctorate in missions.
</P>
<P>
   There, he was introduced to the Willow Creek model of evangelism
and decided to start a church in a high-growth area filled with
unchurched people. Florida was one possibility. A trip to the Holy
Land sealed that decision, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a bus approaching Tel Aviv in 1983, Underwood was deep in
thought about starting a church in Florida but feared that a local
boy would not be respected as a minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and there it was in front of me,'' Underwood said.
``A huge sign said Palm Beach. We were staying at the Palm Beach
Hotel in Tel Aviv.''
</P>
<P>
   A dozen people met to start the church in 1985. A lifelong
friend and seminary classmate, Tom Kiedis, offered his mother's
home in Palm Beach Gardens as a meeting place. Kiedis is now the
teaching pastor of the church.
</P>
<P>
   The first public service in October drew more than 200 people to
a movie theater in Loehmann's Plaza in Palm Beach Gardens. They
quickly outgrew one theater and moved into another in the complex.
</P>
<P>
   The church moved to Dwyer High School in Palm Beach Gardens for
two years and then, four years ago, to Eissey Campus theater.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is a staff of nine and a budget of more than
$800,000. The church leases more than 9,000 square feet of space at
the NorthCorp Center in Palm Beach Gardens for offices and meeting
space to use through the week. A counseling center employs licensed
therapists who offer marital, family and group counseling.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 people meet regularly in small groups that target
men, women, singles, married couples and deal with relationships or
spiritual issues, Kiedis said.
</P>
<P>
   The church has had a role in starting six clones of itself from
Naples to Orlando, including the Treasure Coast Community Church in
Jensen Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision carrier in all this is Ray,'' said Mike Kelly, an
original church member from Palm Beach Gardens. ``I believe God and
Ray are in the same place in terms of trying to serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics complain that churches of this kind belittle the Gospel
and water down the power of faith in order to be relevant.
Supporters insist that's not true, and scholars grudgingly agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, I become more and more respectful of these
movements. The places are flooded with people,'' said the Rev.
Lesley Northrup, assistant professor of religion and culture at
Florida International University in Miami. ``At least, you've got
folks who are responding to people who are _ as we used to say in
the '60s _ where they're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Underwood's newest vision is to build a home for the church in a
community church/auditorium in the Abacoa development in Palm Beach
Gardens. Negotiations are under way, Underwood said. The building
would be available for all community groups to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think community gathering places play a vital role in
society,'' he said. ``The church used to be that place. It was a
focal point.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist youngster who became a motorcycle-riding
pastor wants the church to be a focal point for a new generation of
faith seekers. He offers advice he has followed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't see church the way you always see church,'' Underwood
said. ``Be willing to get out of the box. Do things in a new way.''
</P>
<P>
   RECENT SERMONS
</P>
<P>
   Titles of some recent sermon series at Palm Beach Community
Church:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``What Would Jesus say to . . . Bill Clinton, Princess Diana,
Bill Gates, Oprah, Donald Trump and Dennis Rodman.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Three Things God Loves: Leisure, Laughter and Love Making.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Has Your Dating Turned to Debating?'' The series addresses
issues such as getting your partner to listen and how to have a
good fight.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Getting a Grip on . . . Life, Time, Activities,
Opportunities, One's Self and Relationships.''
</P>
