<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pampering is the point at Ponte Vedra
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA, Fla. _ I arrived early at the Ponte Vedra Inn and
Club Spa for my 8 a.m. appointment. That was the only time slot
available. This spa is a very busy place.
</P>
<P>
   I wore flip-flops, shorts, a T-shirt and no makeup for my
facial, which seemed appropriate to me on this stormy Thursday
morning. But women ranging in age from 30 to 70 turned up for their
appointments in dresses and high-heels.
</P>
<P>
   These ladies took this spa business very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But we soon were all dressed the same - naked under our
terry-cloth spa-issue robes.
</P>
<P>
   I had signed up for a Swedish massage, which is gentle and
relaxing, and a glycolic facial. They put glycolic acid on your
face to help erase all those little wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   I was a little worried about that second part. Having acid
thrown on your face sounded painful, and those wrinkles really
weren't that bad ...
</P>
<P>
   But I forgot about that while Billie, the massage therapist,
literally rubbed my worries away. While she firmly stroked my
muscles, she told me about working in a spa on the Norway cruise
ship. When my 50 minutes were up, I was so relaxed I felt like I
had been on a ship for a week. Why pay $1,500 for a cruise when you
could just get Billie to massage you for $60?
</P>
<P>
   I was led to a waiting room in the spa - as modern and clinical
as a hospital - where I was soon summoned for my facial, which at
$80 should make me look like Heather Locklear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it hurt? My face isn't going to turn really red is it?
Will I be able to go to work tomorrow?'' I was panicking.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan was soothing as she put on so many masks I lost track
- the cleansing mask, the hydrating mask, the pineapple-papaya
mask. She massaged my neck, arms and feet, and by the time I got
the glycolic mask I didn't know what hit me.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it only stung a tiny bit. My face didn't turn red. My
wrinkles were still there, but my skin looked darn good.
</P>
<P>
   That's the main point at this spa. Clients want to look good.
The fitness center with all those machines is across the street,
but in this building, it's beauty that counts.
</P>
<P>
   You can get your hair colored, your nails done, and your body
waxed - lips, brows, chin, half leg, full leg, half arm, full arm,
underarm, you name it.
</P>
<P>
   And 10 minutes away, at the Mayo Clinic, the sky's the limit.
Dr. John Harris, the hospital's head of plastic surgery, often does
seminars at the club.
</P>
<P>
   You can have cosmetic surgery at the clinic and recuperate at
the Ponte Vedra Inn and Club. A lot of women, and men, do.
</P>
<P>
   The club has a health package called the Mayo Ponte Vedra
Seaside Program, where a guest can check into the club hotel, get
an in-depth checkup at the Mayo Clinic on Day 1, and an analysis
and recommendations on lifestyle changes on Day 2.
</P>
<P>
   Through the remainder of the visit, guests follow the doctor's
guidelines at the fitness center and spa, and they take home an
exercise and nutrition program.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
