<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PONTEVEDRA27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walk this way to a place with plenty of cache
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTE VEDRA, Fla. _ There wasn't exactly gold in them thar
hills. In fact, there weren't even any hills. Just a lot of sand
next to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   But there were rich veins of rutile, ilmenite and zirconium,
used in steel processing, and before you could say ``zirconium
rush'' a bustling settlement known as Mineral City sprang up in the
late 1800s in the northeast corner of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1928, the bottom had fallen out of the mining market, and
the land's owner, National Lead Co., noticed all the rich
industrialists heading to Henry Flagler's hotels in St. Augustine
and Palm Beach. The company decided to build its own resort.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, Mineral City became the more sophisticated-sounding
Ponte Vedra, named after a town in Spain. That same year, British
golf-course architect Herbert Strong was hired to design a links
course along the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A two-story log cabin and ocean-front cottages were built to
accommodate executives, clients and some of those Northeastern oil
tycoons. A private club opened in 1938, and an elite enclave was
born.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Ponte Vedra Inn and Club is still exclusive, though
today the members include Jacksonville Jaguar football players
instead of oil tycoons. And a regular Joe still can't stop in for a
Budweiser in the bar. If you aren't a hotel guest or a club member,
you will be told, politely, to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Ponte Vedra, an unincorporated town on the south edge of
Jacksonville, still has a cachet that is bringing the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   The town has two other resorts: the Lodge and Club at Ponte
Vedra (owned by Gate Petroleum Co., which owns the Ponte Vedra Inn
and Club) and the Marriott at Sawgrass.
</P>
<P>
   The Lodge and Club, built in 1989, is a beachfront inn with 66
rooms - the suites have fireplaces.
</P>
<P>
   The Ponte Vedra Inn and Club is a sprawling modern resort with a
fitness center, several pools and six restaurants. Recent guests at
the resort have included Lady Bird Johnson, Nancy Reagan, Tom
Petty, Hank Williams Jr., Steve Spurrier, Willard Scott and Marcus
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Guest rooms are in modern two-story buildings, but you can still
imagine the old days in the Great Room, the original clubhouse with
high wood beams and two massive fireplaces at either end.
</P>
<P>
   The Club Scene
</P>
<P>
   Sweat index: If you're sweating here, it's because your golf
ball landed in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Getting there: Take Interstate 95 north past St. Augustine to
Exit 101, which is Route 202 and Turner Butler Boulevard. Go to the
end. Turn north on A1A. At the second light, turn right. At the
second three-way stop sign, turn right. You'll see the driveway to
the reception office.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: You have three choices: the Ponte Vedra Inn and
Club (800-234-7842; summer rates, July and August, range from $170
to $290); the Lodge and Club at Ponte Vedra (800-243-4304; rates
range from $190-$250); and the Marriott at Sawgrass (800-228-9290;
rates range from $129 to $179).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
