A8316 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-BURNING27-COX     06-26 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-BURNING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hell is out there and it's coming
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW SMYRNA BEACH, Fla. _ The only thing standing between George
Johnson's house and the advancing monster is a barbed wire fence
and three firefighters. A sullen mass of yellow smoke rolls and
roils upward from deep in the woods and scrub behind Johnson's
home.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Johnson points. There, there it is, he says.
</P>
<P>
   And a lick of yellow flame leaps up a pine tree far off in the
woods, then another, then a line of yellow paints an ugly swath
that stretches away for hundreds of yards.
</P>
<P>
   The fire exhales a searing heat that billows invisibly across
Johnson's parched lawn. And the noise. A snapping and hissing
cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon sun overhead is as high as it ever gets at these
latitudes, but an ocher smudge is the only hint of its existence.
The sky is heavy, dour, the color of an undertaker's overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   All of Volusia County, Florida, is wrapped in a thick cowl of
smoke. It drifts among trees like a Carolina morning mist. It hangs
in the air, on clothes. It sears the eyes and throat. Horses in
paddocks shake their heads and stomp and pace skittishly in the
gritty gloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole county's burning,'' says one of the three
firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Chuck Lupo, a strike team task force leader with
Palm Beach County Fire and Rescue. He lives in Lake Worth. His
partners on a small red pumper truck are Jim Meyer and Jim Parent,
both from St. Lucie County Fire and Rescue. They've been working
the fires for three days and nights.
</P>
<P>
   The fires jump around the county like fleas on a dog. Lupo,
Meyer and Parent chase them. They've had little sleep. They're
black with soot made greasy by sweat. Their eyes are streaked red
and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen fires burned in the county Wednesday. Some
were a few acres in size, others a few square miles. One thousand
bulldozers and pumpers from as far away as New Mexico are arrayed
against the blazes. The firefighters don't so much battle the fires
as try to contain them with fire breaks bulldozed behind homes and
along the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   But the flaming yellow lines snap like whips, this direction one
minute, over there the next, across the road a moment later. A
shift in the wind and everything changes. And people like George
Johnson hope Lupo can hold the line because a barbed wire fence
isn't worth a damn against this trespasser.
</P>
<P>
   Lupo has used his radio to call for a bulldozer to enlarge the
fire break behind Johnson's house, but the dozer is somewhere else
on the line. Lupo knows that this side of the fire runs on for
about 600 yards, but he has no idea where the other side is or who
is on that line or what the conditions are. Or where the bulldozer
is. He goes off on foot in search of earth-moving equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and Parent slip cloth masks over their faces, pull on
their helmets and begin tugging hose off the pumper. They have
maybe 1,000 gallons of water on the truck, just enough to keep the
fire from consuming them and the truck if it leaps the fire break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't enough water in the county to put these fires
out,'' says Parent. ``We need rain, not just showers, but rain,
days of rain, buckets and sheets of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he and Meyer wade into the fire to douse an exploding
bramble patch that is spewing embers skyward in every direction.
</P>
<P>
   The smoke is so thick you lose your bearings in seconds. Only
the uncoiled hose points the way out. The fire truck becomes a red
smear in the smoke, then disappears. You know up is up and down is
down, but that's it.
</P>
<P>
   Flames on the left lick at palmetto palms, and on the right they
shoot up a stand of pine trees. A dried swamp has slowed the fire's
progress directly in front, but now it's curling around the sides
of the bog, flanking the firemen.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is closing in, and when you gulp the air for relief
you get no air. Just hot and aching lungs. Your head throbs in
minutes. There is only heat. Choking, crushing heat. And the noise,
sickening, steady. It's like listening to a diesel engine with a
stethoscope.
</P>
<P>
   It's so dry the dirt burns.
</P>
<P>
   Where the bulldozer has uprooted trees the root balls burn. The
soil is like talc and when you kick it up near the fire it puffs
into flame. The tops and sides of your feet feel the heat before
your soles, but when your soles start to cook it's past time to get
out. A spider flees its web a few seconds before the heat melts it.
You wonder where the deer went. You especially wonder where the
rattlesnakes and water moccasins went.
</P>
<P>
   Then you wonder where the firemen went. They're at the end of
the hose, maybe 15 feet away and almost invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer and Parent follow the hose out of the woods. They decide
to back the pumper down the fire break to allow the bulldozer
access. To the west the sky is black, but not from the fires.
</P>
<P>
   A massive thunderhead forms a strange backdrop to the burning
forest. Blue flashes of lightning backlight the scene, but the
sound of thunder is swallowed by the fury of the fire. The cloud
promises rain, but it's lying.
</P>
<P>
   As if to taunt the firemen, a single large drop of water splats
on the dirty windshield of the pumper. Another kicks up dust at
Parent's feet. Two drops. The firemen look upward, shake their
heads, get into the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Something else big and yellow is crashing through the
underbrush. But its 8-ton presence and growl are welcome. Brian
Forret is sitting at the controls of his Caterpillar. He's a lean
guy who is so covered with soot he looks like a mighty thin vein of
anthracite.
</P>
<P>
   He's come over from Port Richey to help. He's cut enough fire
breaks in the last two days to put a road building crew to shame.
</P>
<P>
   A fire break will work as long as the fire doesn't run right up
to it and jump over. Sometimes firefighters will start a fire along
the break to knock down vegetation the advancing fire could feed
on. Then, as the big fire approaches the break it finds no
nourishment. It slows and dies.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in the case of the fires near State Road 40 west of Daytona
Beach, the fires will race right over breaks, roads, swamps and
homes. It all depends on the wind, the undergrowth, the slope of
the land. Luck.
</P>
<P>
   George Johnson is lucky Wednesday. Lupo and his team keep the
fire caged in the woods. Forret widens the break with his bulldozer
and is last seen plowing the forest hundreds of yards to the north.
But the fire will try to outflank the break. It'll try to sneak
around and come at the houses from the other side of Western Road.
It won't quit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither will the firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
