<HEADER>
A8318 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NO-FIREWORKS27-COX     06-26 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NO-FIREWORKS27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No fireworks for Florida Fourth
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ fires rage on, so fireworks now are
illegal in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles recently signed an executive order making it
a crime to sell or use fireworks throughout the state, except for
permitted public displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so dangerous. Obviously, this is not something we want to
do. This is a little like taking away Christmas,'' Chiles said in
Miami. ``I don't know that Florida has had to do this before. These
fires are unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   The order came just 11 days before the Fourth of July, but after
a month in which 158,000 acres of woodland have been lost to fires
sparked by unusually hot, dry weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida has 2,472 men and women who have been fighting these
fires for the past four weeks,'' Chiles said. ``We've been blessed
we haven't lost any firefighters' lives, and we must do everything
we can to protect these courageous people.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiles, Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford and State Fire
Marshal Bill Nelson decided against prohibiting municipal fireworks
displays because some coastal cities could argue that their shows
would explode over the ocean and pose no fire threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be a Grinch, but you can be a reasonable Grinch,''
Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, most municipalities said their fireworks
celebrations would go as scheduled, though Greenacres rescheduled
its display for Aug. 23 to make it part of its Street Beat event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major concern is the area that lies west of Community
Park,'' said City Manager Rich Olson, noting the heavily wooded
areas adjacent to the park. ``It would be extremely hard, if those
areas caught fire, for us to fight them.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gabel, community events coordinator for West Palm Beach,
said the city planned to keep its $35,000 display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we do ours over the Intracoastal and we'll have the
fire marshal and a couple of trucks on site just to be safe,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon Thursday, retail fireworks outlets had already
stopped selling.
</P>
<P>
   At Phantom Fireworks on Forest Hill Boulevard, employees watched
a would-be customer being interviewed on TV, answered continual
phone calls and waited to get the official word from company
lawyers. But they knew what was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``What choice do we have?'' said manager Ira Schwartz. ``We're
not like Publix or Winn-Dixie, where they can just take stuff off
the shelves. We're out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   The store, normally open until 10 p.m., would have gone to its
pre-holiday schedule and begun staying open until midnight.
Instead, employees will either ship stock to stores out of Florida
or pack their bags and head for those stores to work. Ten part-time
workers are out of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Phantom is a national chain with five Florida stores. How much
will the ban cost the business?
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of this as the last 10 days before Christmas,'' Schwartz
said, ``and ask Burdine's how it would affect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy Fireworks of Boca Raton owner Ronald Hunnewell didn't
open for business in anticipation of the ban. The side panels of
his tent in a parking lot at Boca Rio Road and Glades Road were
lowered and the tables that had been full of sparklers and flying
rockets Wednesday were cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable why they have bans,'' Hunnewell said.
``But it certainly hurts financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunnewell said that although he'll store his merchandise and
hope the ban is lifted, he doesn't expect it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to be optimistic at this point,'' Hunnewell
said.
</P>
<P>
   As drafted, Chiles' order bans fireworks, including hand-held
sparklers, in each of the state's 15 ``fire'' districts in which
the drought index is over 400 on a scale from zero to 800. That
description currently describes the entire state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we are concerned about is thousands and
thousands of individuals, maybe most of them children, using
fireworks on top of the tinderbox that is Florida,'' Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   The executive order, which remains in effect for 60 days unless
it's lifted, makes selling or using fireworks a second-degree
misdemeanor that carries a punishment of 60 days in jail or $500
fine. But Chiles said he expects good citizens to help make it
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think that the people would be aware of the ban, and
if you see your neighbor setting off fireworks you would be telling
your neighbor you really shouldn't be doing that, you'll burn down
the neighborhood,'' the governor said. ``I would think that would
be the strongest enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Joe Brogan, Alexandra Navarro Clifton, Shirish
Date, Chuck McGinness, Mary McLachlin, Seth Mnookin, Africa Ragland
and The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
