<HEADER>
A8321 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-ELECTRICITY27-CO     06-26 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-ELECTRICITY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Debra Jasper and Jennifer Chorpening
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Consumers in the Miami Valley and across the
Midwest should conserve electricity to ward off widespread power
outages that could come as a result of hot weather and idled power
plants, Ohio's governor and utility officials said in response to
the recent heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hot and humid weather from Kansas City to Philadelphia is
a major problem and it could not have come at a worse time,'' said
Dick Kimmins, spokesman for the Public Utility Commission of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it unseasonably hot, but officials said several
major electric-generating plants in Ohio are now off-line. The
combination is causing power interruptions for some Ohio industrial
users and could cause temporary power outages for residential
customers, particularly in northern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the hot and humid weather conditions persist, the
Midwest as whole is going to have to conserve,'' said Neil
Costello, managing director of Dayton Power &AMP; Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures are expected to stay in the 90s into the weekend in
the Dayton area, and Costello said some major industrial users have
been asked to use their own generators in order to conserve power
needed by the Miami Valley region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Costello added, however, that even though power usage is now
more than 100 megawatts higher than last summer's peak of 2,840
megawatts, DP&AMP;L ``is not experiencing the types of problems being
experienced by other utilities.''
</P>
<P>
   All of DP&AMP;L's generating and distribution systems are on-line,
he said. ``We're going to continue to work around the clock to
deliver service.''
</P>
<P>
   Donna Valentine, area manager for Ohio Edison, which serves
customers from Ashland to Springfield, said the company is
considering using ``rolling outages'' as a last resort. The term
refers to shutting off the power to certain areas for two hours at
a time.
</P>
<P>
   That's necessary, in part, because a tornado Wednesday in the
area of the Davis-Besse plant in Ottawa County damaged a major
transmission line.
</P>
<P>
   If rolling outages are implemented, Valentine said the company
will give special consideration to hospitals and customers listed
as needing electricity for public health and safety reasons.
</P>
<P>
   She said Ohio Edison officials have told major car
manufacturers, steel customers and other manufacturers that their
power may be interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   They've also appealed to customers to shut off their air
conditioners if possible or at least turn the thermostat up to 78
degrees and take other conservation measurers.
</P>
<P>
   American Electric Power of Columbus and electric utilities
across Ohio have made similar appeals, as has Gov. George
Voinovich.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Marie Lewis, a spokeswoman for AEP, said its electrical
shortages have affected seven states, from Indiana to Tennessee.
She said the firm itself has shut down all unnecessary lights in
its buildings, turned off its elevators and unnecessary computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something we face every day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Voinovich also directed all government offices to conserve
electric power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several major electric generating plants in Ohio are off-line
and a major transmission line was disabled,'' Voinovich said.
``These events, coupled with the hot, humid conditions across the
state, require both residential and commercial electric customers
to conserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mike Dawson, spokesman for Voinovich, noted that the
problem could be worse. ``The governor can declare an energy
emergency. We're not at that point yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with electricity were predicted in May by the East
Central Area Reliability Council, which in its seasonal assessment
said a potential for record electrical demand might exceed
available generation. The report cautioned that transmission
outages during periods of heavy power flow could result in local
area power interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Kover, executive director of the Miami Valley Emergency
Management Agency, said the Red Cross normally opens up shelters if
power were to shut down here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing, if power goes out, is to cool people down as
much as possible,'' he said. ``(We) would seek out large areas that
different communities have ... that we could use (as) the community
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Kavita Kumar contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
