<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8322 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGS-CLEANING27-CO     06-26 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGS-CLEANING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dam may separate salamanders from swimmers
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As Austin officials drained water from Barton
Springs Pool recently, biologists with nets and plastic cups
scoured the exposed limestone and gravel pool bottom for stranded
salamanders, returning 10 of them to deep water.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kirk Watson, showing off the pool's first cleaning in five
weeks, outlined what he hoped would become a permanent solution to
the conflict over the endangered species and the preservation of a
spring-fed swimming pool that has taken on iconic proportions for
many Central Texans. Yet the mayor declined to predict that the
plan, including a dam separating the shallow end from the deep end,
will resolve the controversy of how mankind and beast should
inhabit the same waters. ``This is Barton Springs,'' Watson said.
``I wouldn't say it's the last chapter. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove his point, two swimmers at the press conference
challenged the proposed site of the dam, suggesting that at least
36 inches upstream would be better. The extra yard _ or about a
dozen adult salamanders laid end to end _ would put the dam just
beyond the one-eighth-mile marker, making it easier for swimmers to
measure their laps more precisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's nit-picking,'' said Marilyn Prengler, a year-round
swimmer in the constant 68-degree water.
</P>
<P>
   Austin, after all, already has made a federal case out of the
salamander, which has been on the Endangered Species list since
last year, and how its home is cleaned for the benefit of the
thousands of human swimmers and waders.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit, a federal judge this month refused to stop the
pool cleaning, saying it does not threaten the species. As an added
benefit, humans don't slip and fall on algae-coated rocks or become
hidden from the eyes of lifeguards when the normally clear water
turns murky after it rains.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, however, a tractor hose broke, spreading
a cup of hydraulic fluid razor-thin over 800 gallons of water. The
spill, contained by silt fences, did not affect the salamander
habitat, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the City of Austin will go to the U.S. Fish &AMP; Wildlife
Service for a permit to make permanent changes in the pool,
including the dam, to minimize the impact of the cleanings on this
particular salamander, which lives only in Barton Springs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal will be published, probably in July, and citizens
will be given 30 days to comment. Everything is negotiable,
including the 36 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the wildlife service approved seven additional
experimental cleanings, enough to get the city through the summer
season, until the federal agency acts on the final permit this
fall. It also will teach biologists more about the care of
salamanders.
</P>
<P>
   If the permit is granted, city officials expect to close Barton
Springs Pool, probably in the winter, to build the dam and make
other changes. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make the ``beach area'' of the pool's deep end about 61/2 feet
deep. While the gravel-bottomed beach is not a beach _ it is
usually covered with 3 or 4 feet of water _ it is salamander
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Deepening it will leave 6 inches of water over the bottom when
the deep end is drained for maintenance. Salamanders now get
stranded there when the water is lowered. Vegetation will be
planted on the new bottom for the salamanders.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establish a $45,000 yearly city fund for salamander research.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also are authorizing $10,000 this year to make up for
any damage to the species habitat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Close fissures _ the rocky outbreak where the springs flow
into the pool _ to swimmers and waders.
</P>
<P>
   City officials don't want people wading over the salamander
habitat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Install a pumping system to keep water over the fissures
whenever the water is lowered in the deep end. The system also will
be used during dry spells to pump water to other springs where
salamanders live.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious change to the pool will be the dam, which will
be about 3 feet high. By separating the shallow and deep ends,
officials say, they can drain the pool 40 times a year to clear the
algae, leaving the deep end where salamanders live undisturbed
except for four annual cleanings.
</P>
<P>
   In the deep end, officials said, sediment and flooding debris
must be removed. A vacuum _ with a screen to keep salamanders from
being sucked up _ may be developed.
</P>
<P>
   The dam will have gates in the bottom to allow water to flow
between the shallow and deep ends. Screens on the gates will keep
the salamanders from migrating into the shallow end. During the
cleanings, the gates will be closed and the water from the shallow
end will be flushed through drains on the limestone bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Austin lawyer Robert Kleeman, who represented clients who tried
to stop the cleanings with a federal lawsuit, reserved judgment on
most of the measures, but he endorsed the dam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like we're making progress,'' he said. ``We were
lowering the whole pool just to clean the shallow end.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
