<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-WATER27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falling aquifer forces conservation measures
 &HT;    By Harry Thomas
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Citing falling water levels in the Edwards Aquifer, the
City of San Marcos and the Edwards Aquifer Authority have imposed
mandatory water conservation measures for residents and some
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The Edwards Aquifer Authority began its stricter Stage II
conservation rules. They apply to Edwards Aquifer pumps in Bexar
County and parts of Comal, Hays, Caldwell and Guadalupe counties,
with more severe restrictions on San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   Under the authority's measures, residents in affected areas can
water yards two days a week. In cities, residents' watering days
will be set by local water utilities, while rural residents can
water on Wednesdays and Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos residents can water one day a week, either Tuesday or
Thursday, based on their home address.
</P>
<P>
   Aquifer authority officials called for the tougher measures
after water levels in the Edwards Aquifer _ the whale-shaped
underground limestone reservoir that stretches from Kyle to about
100 miles west of San Antonio _ dropped below 642 feet above mean
sea level. The Bexar County Index Well was at 641.9 feet Thursday
morning, said authority spokeswoman Jeanne Janes. The portion of
the Edwards Aquifer that feeds Barton Springs in Austin is
geologically separate.
</P>
<P>
   San Marcos City Manager Larry Gilley called for the stricter
steps when the level was at 642.2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As this hot, dry weather continues, San Marcos residents are
urged to redouble their efforts to conserve water,'' said Gilley.
``We could encounter some extremely severe conditions this summer,
and we want to do all we can to protect our water supply, the
springs and the river.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Marcos restrictions also affect local businesses.
Restaurant-goers will receive water only upon request, and
commercial nurseries will be allowed to water only from 6 to 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Other San Marcos and Edwards Aquifer restrictions include a
prohibition on the use of unrecycled water for fountains,
street-cleanings and private car washes.
</P>
<P>
   In San Marcos, commercial and residential violators can be fined
$50 to $200. Fines under the aquifer authority's plan were
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, the city's water conservation efforts remain
voluntary. Residents are being asked to water their lawns once
every five days, based on the last number in their address.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
