<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX     06-26 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When the Klan wants you
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I hate to miss it, but I'm going to skip this
weekend's Ku Klux Klan rally in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing like a Klan rally to get the old juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   The Klan knows this, of course, which is why two Texas Klan
groups decided to hold a joint rally Saturday in Jasper, the
8,000-population timber community in East Texas where three white
ex-cons have been accused of torturing and dragging to death a
49-year-old Jasper black man.
</P>
<P>
   People who say the Klan's timing couldn't be worse don't
understand the Klan. From the Klan's point of view, the timing is
perfect. From the point of view of any American with reasonable
mental health, there is no good time to hold a Klan rally.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the New Black Panther Party share with the Klan an
understanding of the ingredients needed to attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based group conducted an armed rally and march in
Jasper on the day murder victim James Byrd Jr. was buried. They
knew the nation's press would be crawling all over Jasper that day
eager to spread their tit-for-tat solution to racial violence.
</P>
<P>
   After witnessing the public-relations coup enjoyed by the New
Black Panther Party, the Klan groups announced they also would
rally in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered citizens of Jasper, both black and white, just
wish everyone would go away and leave them alone. If they weren't
at each other's throats before this tragedy, which they weren't, it
will be a miracle if they can stay that way. Actually, Jasper's
African-American mayor has led his citizens in prayer asking for
heavenly help to maintain racial harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Jesse Jackson was on the scene in front of TV cameras
before benumbed Jasper residents had time to absorb the tragedy.
Jackson was first in a legion of national figures and politicians
to descend on Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Texas NAACP leaders called a public meeting of the executive
board in a Jasper church when the Klan groups plan to rally.
</P>
<P>
   The new peace-and-harmony Klan would love to be seen preaching
white pride and nonviolence while their opponents are seen as
profane and
</P>
<P>
   violent. And they might get their wish.
</P>
<P>
   After my column advised readers to not believe the
peace-and-harmony message now being preached by Grand Dragon
Michael Lowe of the Texas Knights of the KKK, a leader of a rival
Klan called to say an armed New Black Panthers planned to return
for the Klan rally. He agreed that Lowe's peace-and-harmony message
was phony.
</P>
<P>
   Another person called me a racist for comparing Lowe's history
of racism with his new sheetless, politically correct message.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've covered a number of public Klan rallies. I
know how easily Klan speakers provoke crowds and stir the juices.
That's what they want to do.
</P>
<P>
   The press is there to report, but especially to see if things
get out of hand. We eagerly gather the most provocative quotes and
pass them along to our readers or viewers. We certainly don't look
for bland quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Hurled epithets are good. Hurled bricks are even better,
strictly from a professional reporting point of view, of course.
</P>
<P>
   If the confrontation erupts into a bloody free-for-all,
reporters and photographers on the scene have a chance to have
their words and pictures distributed nationwide. Something like
that could mean prizes, awards, raises and promotions. It's also
darn exciting and can be worked nicely into conversations for a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I nearly decided to go to the Jasper Klan rally. But
I know that's what the Klan wants me to do. It's a judgment call,
but this time my judgment tells me to stay home and not give the
Klan what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
