<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS WARN RUSSIA COULD SPLIT APART 
</HEADLINE>
   News Analysis  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In Russia, history never lies very far beneath the
surface of events.
</P>
<P>
   So President Boris Yeltsin's call this week for strong
anti-crisis measures and his warning of political unrest unless
they are enacted have evoked memories of the civil war that
followed the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yeltsin government caught in a deepening economic
morass as interest rates have risen to 150 percent, some analysts
expressed fear that the vast Russian Federation may be stretched to
the breaking point and could even split apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader did not specifically refer to last month's
overwhelming election of former Gen. Alexander Lebed, Yeltsin's
arch foe and rival, as the governor of the Siberian province of
Krasnovar. But some experts see that event as a disturbing sign of
tensions between the regime in Moscow and the distant hinterland,
which could produce an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conditions are bad for many Russians, but the further one
travels from the capital, the worse they get,'' according to Serge
Laplante, a Russian specialist at France's National Research
Council. ``And conditions are worst of all in Siberia even though
Russia's natural resources are in greatest supply there.''
</P>
<P>
   Laplante cited the millions of Siberian miners and other workers
who have gone unpaid for months, and in some cases, years. He added
that the general breakdown in public services, such as hospital
care, is more extensive in Siberia than anywhere else in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The analyst, who has traveled widely in Siberia, explained that
``the Siberians increasingly think of themselves as a separate and
neglected people. For them, Moscow is very distant and has little
interest in their well-being and might as well be the capital of
another nation.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that Siberia's disenchantment with the last Soviet
ruler, Mikhail Gorbachev, contributed to his downfall in 1991.
Siberians are now equally fed up with Yeltsin who, like Gorbachev,
hasn't fulfilled his promises to them, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tension between Siberia and European Russia has always existed
although the vast majority of Siberians are ethnic Russians and
many of their families have been settled there for centuries. The
resentment tends to be strongest when the national government is at
its weakest, according to Russian-born analyst Nicholas Chomsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Lenin and the Communists seized power in 1917, Siberia
became a stronghold of counter-revolutionary forces,'' he
explained. ``For a time, in 1919 and 1920, an anticommunist admiral
named Alexander Kolchak had almost all of Siberia under his control
and seemed likely to overthrow the Communists by marching on
European Russia from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolchak failed only because of his own military incompetence,
Chomsky said, adding that ``many Siberians haven't forgotten that
for a while they seemed to have their destiny in their own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Chomsky added that ``Siberia's abiding complaint is that it
hardly benefits from its own mineral wealth, that it should be rich
but instead is poor. There is little doubt many Siberians would
jump at the chance of independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
