<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE RIGHT FURNITURE FOR YOUR SUMMER PLACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Umbrella tables, while festive-looking, offer a
healthy alternative to the picnic table, which offers no protection
from the sun unless you have it placed under a shade tree.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of umbrella tables appears limited _ an umbrella
stuck through a hole in a table _ but some thought should go into
the materials before purchasing one.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture sets, including table, umbrella and four chairs, range
in price _ depending on material and craftsmanship _ from
approximately $199 to more than $1,000. With proper care, the
furniture should be able to withstand the summertime elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always keep the umbrella closed when not in use or
unattended,'' stressed Jennifer DiIanni, furniture manager for
A-Frame Pools in Latham, N.Y. ``They are the main reason for tables
tipping over in a high wind. If you are in a windy location, you
may want to get an umbrella with wind vents, so that a mild wind
can pass through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Umbrellas are made from vinyl mesh, which allows some light to
filter in but not rain, and acrylics, which last longer than canvas
and won't fade. An umbrella costs approximately $50 to $250 and up.
</P>
<P>
   Standard umbrella bases are filled with sand or stone and begin
at $30. More expensive bases, such as those made from steel,
wrought or cast iron, can cost up to about $200. The latter also
allows you to use the umbrella without the table, should you want
to place it by a chair for reading, or use it to shade plants.
</P>
<P>
   As for the furniture itself, wood is a natural choice for the
beauty in the grain and finish. But wood becomes dry when left out
in the sun and should be lubricated with linseed or other oils to
keep it from drying out and chipping, cracking, splitting or
warping.
</P>
<P>
   Real wicker and bamboo are attractive and practical for indoors.
But outdoors, they can warp, pull apart, peel or splinter.
</P>
<P>
   Tables with polyvinyl construction are relatively
maintenance-free, except for washing off any dirt or spills.
There's even polyvinyl-coated wicker and bamboo, or resinweave that
simulates wicker.
</P>
<P>
   Metal furniture is durable, but if left out it may eventually
start to rust and require a coat of primer and paint every few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Many tables come with a metal or polyvinyl frame or base and a
glass or stone top. The plus of a mesh metal top table is that
water goes through it rather than having to be sponged off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
