<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEWART'S-ICECREAM-$A     06-26 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART'S-ICECREAM-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY DISCOVERS THE DOS AND DONTS OF MAKING ICE CREAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENFIELD, N.Y. _ Two years ago, Gary Dake and Jim Derway, the
flavor gurus behind Stewart's Ice Cream, thought they had devised a
killer combination for a new taste sensation.
</P>
<P>
   From toddlers to grandparents, who doesn't love Rice Krispie
Treats? Put gobs of that sweet, gooey, marshmallow confection in
ice cream and you've got a runaway hit, Dake and Derway figured.
</P>
<P>
   So, they worked up a formula at the sprawling Stewart's
production plant here on the outskirts of Saratoga Springs, both
loved the results, and the cartons rolled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great flavor and customers loved it, but the Rice
Krispie Treats got so damn hard in the freezer that they were
damaging people's teeth,'' Dake said. After the company had to pay
some customers' dental bills, the flavor was yanked from the
Stewart's lineup.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the only flavor faux pas for the ice cream meisters
over the years. Some innovations never get off the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   In their business, it helps to think like kids. This led to an
experiment with Skittles, the chewable candy with bursts of intense
fruit flavor. Once frozen, the Skittles turned into molar-cracking
pebbles and the flavor never went into production.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are challenges, but running an ice cream factory is as
much fun as you'd imagine it is,'' said Dake, 37, vice president of
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Dake is the third generation of his family to run the dairy
product manufacturer founded in 1921 by Dake's grandfather and
great-uncle in Greenfield. It is still family-owned and privately
held. Dake's father, Bill Dake, is president and chief executive
and his father's wife, Susan Dake is an executive. About 20
relatives are involved with the board or as shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been any cows grazing the Stewart's acreage since
the '20s. The company buys milk in bulk from about 50 different
dairy farmers in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Percy and Charles V. Dake produced Dake's Delicious
Ice Cream, but the Dakes sold the business in the late 1920s and
lost the name. In 1945, the Dakes bought Stewart's Dairy and soon
began producing Stewart's Ice Cream.
</P>
<P>
   Derway, 40, production manager of the ice cream department,
worked his way up the chain of command after starting 17 years ago
as a fill-in on the ice cream line. He recalled his boyhood in
Hudson Falls, saving up money for a gorging at the ice cream
counter of Stewart's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd eat so many make-your-own sundaes we made ourselves
sick,'' Derway said.
</P>
<P>
   The company recently celebrated the 50th anniversary of
make-your-own sundaes, an innovation of Philly Dake in 1948. During
a two-day, make-your-own sundae promotion June 6-7, 233,000 sundaes
were sold in Stewart's Shops at 50 cents apiece.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the summer ice cream rush, when counter sales of
dip ice cream for cones and sundaes doubles at the 279 Stewart's
Shops, Duke and Derway recounted some of their hits and misses as
flavormeisters.
</P>
<P>
   They'll know soon enough whether flavors they formulated back in
February that will debut at stores this summer _ Pineapple
Upside-Down Cake, Berry Strawberry Sherbet, Adirondack Bear Claw,
Citrus Margarita, White Light and Black Raspberry Cheesecake _ will
get the thumbs up or thumbs down from customers.
</P>
<P>
   Dake and Derway won't take the also-rans personally. ``Jim and I
guess wrong sometimes,'' Dake said. ``A customer buying an ice
cream cone is a happy customer. It's a happy product. You can't eat
this stuff with a frown on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't remind them of the cappuccino candy disaster, though. The
duo were excited about the new flavor and worked up a batch. ``The
problem was that the candies absorbed water and turned into liquid
blobs,'' Dake said. ``You can't just throw any candy into the ice
cream and expect it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hidden legal landmines in names, too. A Stewart's
maintenance engineer tossed out a name for a new flavor at a staff
meeting. Everyone liked Java the Nut. That's what was printed on
the half-gallon cartons.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks of the cartons hitting the stores, Dake got a
letter from attorneys representing LucasFilms and director George
Lucas. They claimed trademark infringement because the flavor was
too close to the name of the ``Star Wars'' character, Java The Hut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged letters and I finally decided we would rename the
flavor,'' Dake said. Newly printed cartons reveal the flavor has
been changed to Java Nut.
</P>
<P>
   Derway is proud of one of his brainstorms that succeeded
brilliantly. A candy maker shipped Stewart's cases of Pop Rocks
trying to entice them to stock them in their shops. Derway had a
plan for those bright specks of candy that hit saliva inside the
mouth and explode with a soda water's fizz. But his first attempts
at Pop Rocks ice cream fizzled. The candies shot their loads once
they hit the ice cream mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Derway tinkered a bit and discovered that if he encased the Pop
Rocks in a thin chocolate-flavored coating, the fizz would be
preserved. He got the candy maker to ship blue and red Pop Rocks,
and later added a cherry swirl to the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Voila! Fireworks flavor was born. It was tested at the counter
last summer in time for the Fourth of July and it was such a hit in
dips that this month Fireworks is coming out in half-gallon
cartons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really looks like an explosion with the swirl and you get
that fizz, too. Kids love it,'' Derway said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ice cream plant operates around-the-clock (two shifts of
production and one shift of equipment-cleaning each day) and churns
out about 2 1/2 million gallons each year. A deep freeze storage
area (minus 40 degrees F.) holds three weeks worth of inventory.
That's 40,000 gallons of bulk ice cream and 200,000 half-gallon
cartons.
</P>
<P>
   Ice cream is a pretty basic product with these base ingredients:
milk powder, liquid sugar, liquid corn syrup, sweet whey, imported
Dutch cocoa (for chocolate flavors).
</P>
<P>
   Color and flavor are added to the base ingredients and are
pumped into a 500-gallon tank and heated to 170 F. and held for 30
minutes for pasteurization. The mixture is then cooled and pumped
through a freezer system as air is injected into the mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Air is key to ice cream. ``Our ice cream is about 50 percent
air,'' Dake said. More expensive premium brands like Ben &AMP; Jerry's
or Haagen-Dazs use less air; cheaper supermarket brands use more.
The difference is obvious when you compare the weights of a
half-gallon of different ice creams in your hand at the store.
Without the pliability provided by air, you'd be left trying to
hack away at ice cream as dense as a block of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Just before it flows into waiting cartons, candy bits and any
special effects such as a swirl topping are added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all that complicated,'' Dake said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's Ice Cream is sold exclusively in its ubiquitous brown,
shingle-roofed shops, which stretch from the Adirondacks to the
Catskills with 10 stores in southern Vermont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
