<HEADER>
A8499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CONNICK-BOS &LR;      06-26 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CONNICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAD ABOUT HARRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family comes first for Harry Connick Jr., the father of two
young girls and husband of former Victoria's Secrets model Jill
Goodacre. When Connick is home, he guards his privacy and hopes the
phone won't ring.
</P>
<P>
   Fat chance.
</P>
<P>
   The phone has been ringing off the hook for Connick, who has two
successful careers happening at the same time. He's an in-demand
musician whose love of traditional jazz and funk has struck a chord
with millions. He's an in-demand actor whose career took off in the
blockbuster sci-fi film ``Independence Day'' and led to a starring
role in the recent ``Hope Floats,'' a romantic comedy with Sandra
Bullock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't ask for anything more with the way things are
going. I really couldn't,'' says Connick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I've worked hard for it, but the fact that things have
materialized _ that's pretty much luck, you know,'' he adds. ``You
can work for it, but plenty of people work for what I have and
don't get it. So I think it's all about the luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but you also create your own luck, right?
</P>
<P>
   That's been true of Connick. He's been loved and maligned
because of his matinee-idol good looks, but he has not rested on
his laurels. Even now, he's taking violin lessons to improve his
skill at writing string arrangements for his mostly piano-based
songs. As for movies, he's ``constantly'' reading scripts, up to
three, four, and five of them per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family always comes first, but I like to work, too,'' says
Connick, now 30.
</P>
<P>
   And he's not afraid to be his own toughest critic. Looking back,
he says the funk phase of his last few years (capped by the cosmic,
New Orleans-steeped ``Star Turtle'' album) was fun, but ultimately
he became bored by ``the lack of challenge musically.'' He also
comments harshly on string arrangements he wrote for his Christmas
album a few years ago, saying, ``I wouldn't hire that guy today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the string stuff was just too obvious,'' says Connick,
who adds that even some of the arrangements on his recent jazz/pop
release, ``To See You,'' sound ``primitive to me now,'' though he
feels musically that ``they're the most complex thing I've done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning more and more _ and I'm getting better at it,''
says Connick, a child prodigy whose father was the New Orleans
district attorney and whose mother was a judge. Connick became a
star at age 21 via the soundtrack to ``When Harry Met Sally,'' but
his quest for self-improvement has never left him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mess around on a lot of instruments, but I'm not really good
on that many of them,'' he says. ``I played bass for a long time,
but I don't know anyone who would hire me as a bass player. The
same with guitar, the same with a lot of the brass instruments.
Like, I probably play trumpet better than I play saxophone or
trombone. But I've always wanted to have a working knowledge of
these instruments because, since I'm the arranger, it's nice to
know what the instruments are capable of. That's why I've been
taking violin lessons. The more knowledge you have, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of great composers who were instrumentalists,''
Connick continues. ``I would say they were all instrumentalists,
but you can sort of tell the ones that were piano players and the
ones that were string players. But I would rather that line be a
little bit blurred. The last thing you want to hear is strings that
sound like a piano player wrote them. So I just think it's
important to know how many instruments work, because they can do
things that the piano can't do, and vice versa. So over the years,
you just keep playing and playing and playing. And I play well
enough for what I need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's still not well enough for some critics, especially jazz
critics, who have taken Connick to task for not being a purist. But
Connick is not about to apologize. He loves traditional jazz and
big-band music (he expects that his next record will be big-band
oriented, though he's not saying for sure). But he also loves New
Orleans funk _ another medium that appealed to him as a youth and
found its way into his music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you spread out and do something else, especially with
jazz critics, they don't want you back,'' he says. ``But I'm very
fortunate that members of the listening public haven't been
affected by any of that stuff. I just perform and do what I like to
do. I'm very proud of my musical efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Connick, if truth be told, is not overly fazed by any negative
reviews. He credits his father (the district attorney) for
toughening him up on that score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess growing up with politicians in the family, I was
around critics my whole life. For my dad, it just was never an
issue. He did what he thought was right and moved on. And that's
had an impact on me.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that Connick is adamant about is that his involvement
with movies has not compromised his focus on music. He wrote the
songs for his latest album, ``To See You,'' while on the set of
``Hope Floats,'' and had plenty of time to do them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing but time on a movie set,'' says Connick.
``You'll do a scene for an hour and then you've got six hours to
kill. I mean literally kill. So there's nothing to do but read a
book or do what you have to do otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his next film plans, Connick says, ``I haven't made any
decisions yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And what are his criteria for choosing? ``It's really the story
and how the character fits into the story,'' he notes. ``I've never
had a problem doing characters that are evil or funny, as long as
they fit into the story. Whether they're an action hero or a drug
dealer doesn't make too much difference at this point. Maybe it
will sometime in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character in `Hope Floats' was a great character and
everything worked out,'' he says, referring to his role as a
self-made architect who goes to the big city but returns to his
Texas hometown to be a handyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so many factors involved'' in a film, Connick says.
``You have to think about who's directing it, who the other actors
are, which studio is doing it, when it's being filmed, and where
it's being filmed. If they sent me away to Siberia for four months,
I don't know if I could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And then come these expectant words:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if every other piece was in place, I just couldn't be
away from my family for that long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
