<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN FUNK IS A SLAM DUNK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are only 30-second blurs on ESPN, commercials to promote
professional women's basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was to blend ``something cool'' with the WNBA, and
as Tom Clendenin, ESPN's advertising director, explained, ``what is
cooler than a '70s funk band?''
</P>
<P>
   Never know with these advertising types. Not that there is much
discrepancy over what real funk is. George Clinton, the granddaddy
of funk, concluded a long time ago that the Doobie Brothers were
cool, but ``can you imagine Doobie in your funk?''
</P>
<P>
   But give credit to Weiden &AMP; Kennedy, the New York advertising
agency responsible for much of ESPN's spots. They produced the
back-in-the-day funk for the series of commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the agency did was call Niles Rogers. As many
recall, Rogers was part of the '70s band Chic, which pumped out
hits like ``Freak Out'' and ``Good Times.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter song was sampled by the Sugar Hill Gang and
transformed into the first commercial rap song, ``Rapper's
Delight.'' Rogers is the real deal, even doing the score to Eddie
Murphy's film ``Coming to America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and Tag Gross, his colleague at RTG Music Limited, a New
York music composition, production, and talent casting company, set
out to assemble a band to recreate the sound of the '70s with the
rhythms of the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't look far.
</P>
<P>
   They found their lead singer on the New York club scene. His
name is Justice X. That's his real name, as Gross tells the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I handed him the W-4 forms and asked him to spell his name and
he told me Justice X,'' Gross said. ``I asked him how he spelled
`X' and he told me `X.' I went `Wow. Is that your whole name?' He
told me no, that his full name is Justice De La X.''
</P>
<P>
   The lead guitarist is Gabriel Gordon. He has been around the
music scene for years, most recently touring with Natalie Merchant
on the Lilith Fair tour.
</P>
<P>
   On trumpet is Wayne du Maine, a classically trained musician who
performs in the orchestra pit for the Broadway play ``Titanic.'' Du
Maine graduated from Julliard and now conducts that school's
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Drummer Sterling Campbell also has been around for years, mostly
performing with rock bands, including recording with David Bowie on
his latest album.
</P>
<P>
   Bass player Jerry Barnes has recorded with Roberta Flack.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for these guys to come together as a band
and produce a sound that exceeded even the lofty expectations of
Weiden &AMP; Kennedy's creative director, Stacy Wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them really knew each other,'' Gross said. ``It was
one those deals where they either had heard about one another or
they had a friend who knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The group rehearsed for two weeks before the commercial shoot.
They produced 12 30-second spots in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians are a leery lot.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said they didn't really know how big the commercials were
until they saw the breakfast wagon in front of the studio before
the first day of the shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the costumes, those orange-and-white get-ups
that resemble the colors of the WNBA ball, with scarves wrapped
around their necks. And, of course, the naturals, or the Afros, as
'70s wannabes call the hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   The spots were shot a bit rough to give viewers the impression
that they are peering into a reherasal. But the sound is
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real honest funk,'' Gross said. ``They ran with it and
rocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Between camera changes, for instance, Gross said the band would
strike up some classic funk songs. ``I'm telling you, they were
getting off in rehearsals,'' Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   No telling what the future is for the WNB-Ays.
</P>
<P>
   Gross said the later spots have bass player Barnes doing a long
solo and storming off the set and Justice X screaming at him.
``Gimme back my scarf,'' Justice yells. The next spot shows Barnes
being replaced by a short Japanese guy, Kenji Hino.
</P>
<P>
   The plot line reunites the band with Barnes back on bass and
Hino on, of all things, congas.
</P>
<P>
   Gross wants the WNB-Ays to perform at halftime during the WNBA
playoffs. Maybe even cut an album.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
