<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8509 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACHILLE-TERRORIST-2ND     06-26 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACHILLE-TERRORIST-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 GAZA CITY: ... he says.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abbas surfaced for the first time in April 1996. He claimed to
have embraced the peace process and was allowed to enter Israel for
a meeting of the Palestinian National Council, where he voted in
favor of revoking those parts of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's charter that called for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's conditional on Israel recognizing my national rights,''
he cautions. ``My presence here shows we are interested in peace.
But now we have the feeling peace is getting farther and farther
away. The growing distance means violence is nearby. If peace
fails, all options are open.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, who promotes himself as a world expert on terrorism,
has stridently criticized PLO President Yasser Arafat and the
Palestinian Authority for failing to dismantle the ``infrastructure
of terrorism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Netanyahu administration permitted Abbas to reenter
Israel again last month. Netanyahu's senior adviser, David Bar
Illan, tries to evade criticism by pointing out that it was the
more liberal Labor government of Shimon Peres that approved Abbas's
initial entry in 1996 for the Palestinian National Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Abbas and a cadre of aging guerrillas were allowed into Gaza at
the time to bolster the peace process. According to the Oslo
Accords, any Palestinian whose entry is approved by Israel will not
be prosecuted for crimes committed prior to the signing of the
agreement in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Abbas returned shortly after the council meeting to Iraq to
collect his wife and children. It is not clear under the agreement
that Israel was obligated to let him back to Gaza. Yet he returned
on April 28, crossing through the Israeli checkpoint on the border
of Egypt before entering into Palestinian-controlled Gaza. After a
five-hour delay at the border, the Netanyahu administration
approved entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm as puzzled by it as anybody. It's very difficult to
rationalize,'' concedes Bar Illan. ``But we have to live by it. The
political process sometimes overrides the theory on terrorism. It
is quite difficult, admittedly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tarassian, who leads a right-wing group, Our Jerusalem,
fumes that Abbas is sitting in Gaza. ``It's despicable that the
Israeli government let him in,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Tarassian, Rabbi Avi Weiss, an American right-wing activist, and
Dov Hikind, a New York assemblyman, have petitioned the Israeli
High Court demanding Abbas's arrest and extradition. The court
referred the case to a panel of three judges, a move that indicates
the petition is being taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But efforts to bring Abbas to justice have gone nowhere. Italy
has made no efforts to extradite him, and the US Justice Department
claims it has no grounds to seek his extradition because there is
no outstanding warrant against him. The American warrants were
dropped after his conviction in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, the PLO settled a lawsuit with the Kling-hoffer
family and the tour operator of the hijacked luxury liner for an
undisclosed sum. Abbas says he would like to go to America to
apologize to the family _ an assertion that reflects the egotism
and need for approval that marble his comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, America saw my name and thought of terrorism.
Do you think America still sees me that way?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kling-hoffer family remains outraged that Abbas is free to
live in Gaza. Jay Fischer, a family lawyer, says: ``My clients are
deeply upset... Any force of law that can bring him to justice
should be carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Abbas's present role as a former militant who now supports
the peace process may be useful to Israel and to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In the current peacemaking terrain, his Palestinian Liberation
Front presents a secular and relatively moderate alternative to the
Islamic Resistance Movement Hamas whose military wing has carried
out a spate of suicide bombings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Abbas criticizes Hamas these days, distinguishing between
guerrilla actions like his in which civilians were ``accidentally
hurt'' and those by Hamas which target civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Merari, who served for 22 years as the Israel Defense
Force's chief hostage negotiator, often struggled to defuse Abbas's
plots. ``He was an innovative terrorist, unique in his
accomplishments,'' concedes Merari.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Israel can accept Abbas's present freedom,
Merari, who is now a professor of pyschology at Tel Aviv University
and a leading expert on terrorism, responds: ``You have to at some
point, in order to move forward, realize there are horrible
memories on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Palestinians, there is Deir Yassin and children killed in
the Intifadah,'' explains Merari, referring, respectively, to the
Arab village which was the site of the worst wartime attrocities by
Jewish forces during the 1948-1949 war and to the 1987 Palestinian
uprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``If both sides want to move on from their own painful memories,
at some point you have to draw a line ... But I should point out
that he is as close to that line as you can get.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
