<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUICE FIRM LOOKS TO STAY FRESH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several years on Madison Avenue, Doug Levin fled to Maine
in the late 1980s, vowing never again to have anything to do with
the advertising business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get away from the hype,'' says Levin, whose resume
includes stints in the New York offices of ad agencies Doyle Dane &AMP;
Bernbach and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, the 37-year-old Levin is chief executive of
Fresh Samantha Inc. of Saco, Maine, which since its founding in
1992 has looked to do for super premium fruit juice what Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Homemade Inc. has done for ice cream _ transform a
commodity into a cult product with a fanatical following.
</P>
<P>
   In its early days, Ben &AMP; Jerry's relied largely on guerrilla
marketing to make itself known _ guerrilla marketing often being a
euphemism for in-house advertising done on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Samantha has taken a similar approach.
</P>
<P>
   College kids in purple wigs hand out free samples with names
such as Raspberry Dream or Spirulina Fruit Blend or whatever
happens to be Fresh Samantha's oddball flavor of the month.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, delivery trucks in lurid hues serve as rolling
billboards for the brand.
</P>
<P>
   But now the privately owned company is at a crossroads. As it
moves into new markets such as New York, Baltimore, and Washington,
it is rethinking its promotional strategy.
</P>
<P>
   With 1998 revenues expected to reach $14.5 million, up from $7
million last year, Fresh Samantha recently hired a public relations
firm, Warner Public Relations of Manchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It's on the lookout for a design firm to create new labels and
packaging. It might also tap an ad agency to do some work on a
project basis.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fresh Samantha's 1998 marketing budget could hit the
``mid six figures,'' up from last year's $80,000, says Carin Warner
of Warner Public Relations.
</P>
<P>
   But Fresh Samantha faces a dilemma. In looking to reach new
customers, it could alienate its core audience of college kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Generation Xer who's been our early adopter,'' Levin
said. ``Kids between 17 and 28, they want to go against the
mainstream. They want the underdog alternative, the kookie unlikely
product that isn't slammed into their heads by mainstream
advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   In Levin's view, Fresh Samantha is truly an alternative from
most juices consumers buy at a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Those juices tend to be heavily processed and pasteurized. Some
contain preservatives and sweeteners. As a result, a juice made
today can be sold next month and consumed a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a downside to processing and preservatives. The same
living organisms that can spoil are the ones that give a juice much
of its taste and health benefits, Levin claims.
</P>
<P>
   So Fresh Samantha minimizes the processing that neutralizes
these organisms. The result is a healthful, tasty juice, Levin
says, but one with only a 10-day shelf life and a high price.
</P>
<P>
   A single serving of Fresh Samantha can cost $2.50, at least a
dollar more than most pasteurized juices of about the same size.
</P>
<P>
   Given this focus on freshness, rushing juices from Fresh
Samantha's Maine plant to the supermarkets and cafes that sell it
is critical. Bad weather that slows delivery _ like the recent
heavy rainstorms _ is ``a disaster,'' Levin says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like Federal Express,'' he says of Fresh Samantha. ``For
us, it's all about overnight delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Samantha's price has been almost as big a challenge as
getting juices to retail outlets in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   In rural Maine, most folks won't pay $2.50 for a juice, even if
it's fresh squeezed and has a funky name like Mango Mama.
</P>
<P>
   In focus groups of ``suburban moms,'' reaction to Fresh Samantha
was mixed, Warner says; health enthusiasts were wowed and willing
to pay Fresh Samantha's premium price, but some in the group said
they would ``just as soon buy Tropicana.''
</P>
<P>
   But in ``urban college markets,'' it's been a completely
different story, Levin says.
</P>
<P>
   It's been students from Tufts, Harvard, and Boston College who
have fueled Fresh Samantha's explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   As it prepares to move forward, Fresh Samantha must figure out
how to sustain its growth while retaining its cult status.
</P>
<P>
   It must figure out how to woo older consumers and consumers in
markets far removed from its Maine base without disenchanting its
core customer of college kids who seem to be leery of products
hyped by traditional advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, `How do you advertise in a very unadvertising
way?''' Warner says. ``We have to figure out how to walk a very
fine line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
