<SLUG> BC-SUN-BUMS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRATERNITY OF FRY FINDS A PLACE IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The shade and shape of a bronze Buddha, Choo is
probably the darkest, but the equally deep tans of Louie the
Handicapper, Joe the Cop, Mike the Plumber and I'm Just Bucky make
it tough to tell where noses end and stogies begin.
</P>
<P>
   With racehorse-sounding nicknames and sweaty hides to match, the
``Sun Bums'' of Constitution Beach have unfolded their lounge
chairs every March for decades. They bask and baste almost every
sunny day until November, when, like so many Thanksgiving turkeys,
they're roasted to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees and divorcees all, these Sunshine Boys readily admit
theirs is a dangerous pastime, with barely a thing between them and
the hazards of ultra violet rays but sagging swim trunks, a thick
coating of coconut oil (SPF-0), a few faded tattoos and an
``I'm-this-old-and-I'm-still-here'' hubris only grandfathers and
war veterans can get away with.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ``bums,'' a trim 71-year-old Louie Cataldo (dubbed
Louie the Handicapper from a lifetime spent betting at Suffolk
Downs) was diagnosed with skin cancer a couple of years ago, but he
swears that just before he was to begin treatment, it cleared up on
its own. His doctor, he says, is furious with him for refusing to
abandon his 1970s-issue Playboy bunny swim trunks, (George
Hamilton, look out) his baby oil or his days in the rays with his
pals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be up front: We are not good role models and we are not
proud of it,'' says Joe D'Tiga, aka Joe the Cop, a 59-year-old
retired Boston police officer, as he stood at the water's edge with
a half dozen of his lifelong beach buddies. ``I make sure these
young kids around here use sun protection. We don't want anybody to
be like us, except when it comes to having a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   And that they do. Carmen De Lucia, called Choo because he's
``waiting for my train to come in,'' says the loosely organized
group (``If there's sun, we come'') has had as many as 100
``members'' over the years -- mostly older men and women who soak
in the sun and each other's company from lunch until supper.
</P>
<P>
   Some come for exercise -- swimming and walking no matter the
temperature -- and some come to relive the romantic and adolescent
thrill of whiling the hours by the sea on a warm day, sun on their
faces, sand between their toes, wind and, well, jet fumes rippling
through their hair (the beach does face two of Logan's largest
runways).
</P>
<P>
   But they all come to &UR;  &LR; talk. As the tanned troupe settle onto
their beach blankets and lounge chairs, a sight conjuring spicy
Italian sausages nesting in buns, there is non-stop chit chat about
this and that.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, it starts with the President's pecadillos (``He's a
disgrace!''), diverts to local politics (``Ray Flynn lives in
Eastie now. Let's get him down here with us!''), touches briefly on
women (``We're no good with them. We're all divorced. That's why we
can spend so much time down here!'') and lands on the hottest topic
of all: the male potency pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``At our age, we talk about three things: Viagra, Viagra,
Viagra,'' deadpans Choo, 66, a gregarious retired construction
worker and self-appointed beach watchdog/master of ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Choo keeps tabs on the renovations under way on the
East Boston beach and bathhouse; makes sure little kids don't go
too far into the waves, and mingles among other beachgoers looking
for old friends and making new ones. In bikinis, preferably.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Bums vow to live their golden years literally. And they
look to the ``old timers'' as inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   They are the paling elders, many in their 80s, who also come to
the beach every day _ but sit under the awning at the bathhouse,
proving that old beach bums never die, they just sit in the shade
-- and fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Tony the Bee Man, Tony the Carpenter, Tony the
Mailman, Tommy the Fire Chief and Andy Gumballs,'' says Choo, his
voice tinged with reverence as he points to the sitting seniors.
``That will be us someday. Our tans might fade away, but we never
will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
