<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ROCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN FOGERTY KEEPS ON ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Fogerty is making up for lost time. Absent from the road
for too long because of disputes with his former record label,
Fogerty came back with a loud bang last year. He played hits from
his Creedence Clearwater Revival catalog that he had rarely done in
the last two decades. And he's back on the road this summer,
enjoying every minute of it once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing for the people, having a great time,''
Fogerty says from his tour bus as it winds through upstate New
York. ``The simplest way to say it is that I live for the time I
can be performing. I also have my family with me, so I get to be
more normal than a lot of rock 'n' roll guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty may still be a mystery man to some folks, but for
others, he's the architect of some of the greatest classic rock on
the planet. His compositions include ``Born on the Bayou,'' ``Bad
Moon Rising,'' ``Proud Mary,'' ``Lodi,'' ``Green River,''
``Fortunate Son,'' and ``Who'll Stop the Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever time I've got left, I'm going to do my darndest to
enjoy it and be reconnected with my own work,'' says Fogerty, after
playing Harborlights last year during a vaunted comeback tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that touring would be just a normal part of my
musical life from now on. Years ago, when I first planned to be in
music, I thought I'd do all the things that other people do _ tour,
make records, be on TV, whatever,'' says Fogerty. ``But a lot of
the interruptions in my career were not of my own design. I really
paid a pretty big penalty for doing all the work and making some
other people really rich and famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty is still fighting with Fantasy Records, which owns the
publishing of the CCR songs he wrote after he signed a publishing
contract that ``kids would sign just to get a deal.'' For years, an
embittered Fogerty wouldn't perform the songs because he didn't
want to line Fantasy's pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he says, ``If I sat around and worried about that stuff
all the time, I'd get really upset. But I've got a lot of positive
things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The positives paid off last year. Fogerty, who now records for
Warner Bros., made a return album, ``Blue Moon Swamp,'' which won a
Grammy for best rock album, beating out entries from Aerosmith, the
Rolling Stones, and U2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still pretty knocked out about the Grammy,'' he says. ``I
didn't dare hope to win the Grammy against all the people I was up
against. It's just a really nice validation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fogerty yearns for more respect from the general
audience. ``It's been tough to be away so long. A lot of people
either don't know about me or have forgotten,'' he says. ``And
also, because of the notoriety of having the band's name of
Creedence Clearwater Revival, you're somewhat seen as part of a
whole. I still have people walk up to me and go, `Well, are you on
a solo career now?' And I say, `That's a strange way to put it,
because I've been solo since the day I was born.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that whole confusion, but I have to prove myself.
That's kind of how I look at the tour. I'm quite happy to do that
because, frankly, I like the compeition. I feel I can hold my own
with anybody. It's fun for me to get up and show off.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogerty just released a live CD, ``Premonition,'' taken from a
performance at a Warner Brothers soundstage in Burbank, Calif.,
last winter. Much of it shows that he hasn't lost a step, though he
did just lose his drummer, Kenny Aronoff, to the Smashing Pumpkins.
Aronoff has been replaced by Michael Cartellone, who has worked
with the Damn Yankees and is a ``straightahead, edgy-type rock 'n'
roll drummer,'' says Fogerty.
</P>
<P>
   The song ``Premonition'' is also brand new and foreshadows an
album of original material Fogerty hopes to make in the next year.
``I just felt I really needed to write a new song for this project,
to show that I'm moving forward,'' he says of his current live
album. ``Otherwise, it's just going to feel like some old Vegas guy
trotting out his old trusty whatevers. And I don't feel that way at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rickie Lee at Nectarfest: Rickie Lee Jones is in an up mood
these days. The progressive Beat-pop/trip-hop-and-more singer just
signed to Mercury Records, which will rerelease her quietly
bewitching, trip-hoppy ``Ghostyhead'' album this fall. ``They've
been courting me, and taking me around here and there,'' she says
of label management, led by music-biz legend Danny Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   For the immediate future, however, Jones will perform solo at
the first annual Nectarfest Satrday at Nantucket's Tom Nevers Navy
Base with Bruce Cockburn, Jonatha Brooke, Patty Larkin, Livingston
Taylor, Ellis Paul, and others. She and most of these acts will
then island-hop on Sunday to play at Martha's Vineyard high school
athletic field. (Also part of the fest: Bob Weir, David Crosby &AMP;
CPR, Bo Diddley with Entrain, Jemima James, and others play
Saturday at the Vineyard site, then most of them switch to the
Nantucket site on Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done many festivals, but I'm looking forward to
this,'' says Jones, adding, ``We won't harm anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Festivals are really fun,'' she continues. ``It's not like a
concert with just my name on the marquee. I really enjoy walking up
and playing the music and knowing that I don't have to carry sound
and lights for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jones performed some West Coast dates of the
H.O.R.D.E. Festival, playing with a band she called Chain Austen (a
play on Jane Austen). ``I was doing some very alternative,
aggressive stuff,'' she says of that experience. ``People who
didn't know me liked it a lot. Kids came up to me and said, `What
was the name of your band again?'''
</P>
<P>
   For Nectarfest, though, Jones will do a retrospective of her
career, which started with the hit ``Chuck E.'s in Love'' in 1979.
And she'll also do some music that she hasn't recorded. ``I like
the idea that some songs are living songs, that you have to go
experience them rather than hear them on record.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will then play at the Gibson Guitar Festival in Newport,
R.I. July 26, backed by a band for that occasion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
