<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOAKLEY LAMENTS A HOUSE DIVIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's House is dysfunctional. The Congress doesn't work
because it is broken apart by factionalism. Instead of Democrats
and Republicans working in tandem to make the system work, we have
the ideological equivalent of Hatfields vs. McCoys, with
vengefulness displacing patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   To Joe Moakley, the weathered South Boston Irishman who ran away
at 15 to fight in World War II and for more than a quarter-century
has been on station in the US House, the poisoning of the
congressional well coincided with the retirement (1986) of his old
pal, Tip O'Neill, as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly half a century, O'Neill's beaming countenance helped
curb partisan prejudices and steered colleagues toward calmer
waters when war, recession, or race threatened to tear apart the
institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When O'Neill left, the fun went out of this business, and the
walls started to be built in that middle aisle,'' Moakley said this
week from his outpost in the Rules Committee he used to chair. Newt
Gingrich's reign as speaker has divided the House as never in his
experience, said Moakley. As proof he thumbed through a 51-page
report compiled by grumpy House Democrats: ``Politically motivated
Investigations by House Committees'' since 1995, Year One of Newt.
</P>
<P>
   It was Moakley who suggested to minority leader Dick Gephardt of
Missouri that staff assemble a list of all the taxpayer-financed
investigations launched by Gingrich's team in just 3 1/2 years. The
envelope, please:
</P>
<P>
   _Thirty-eight current ``politically motivated investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   _Seventeen more that have been shut down.
</P>
<P>
   _$17 million worth of legislative costs, and rising.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley fully endorses the report's claim of ``a clear pattern
of abuse'' by the GOP majority ``to harass political enemies,''
i.e. Democrats. Bear in mind, he insists, ``that this $17 million
doesn't count the $40-plus million spent so far by Kenneth Starr,''
the special counsel investigating Clinton. Starr's four-year probe
is approaching the $50 million price tag, with no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   That $17 million price tag is for Congress alone and does not
include what other branches of the federal government must spend to
conduct what amounts to more than 50 separate House investigations.
And when you toss in the other special prosecutors and separate
investigations launched by the Republican-controlled Senate, it
seems likely that the price tag to the taxpayer of
Republican-inspired probes will approach or perhaps even surpass
$100 million by the time Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly some of these investigations are legit. Maybe half,
maybe more. But, 55? And counting? ``This is why Congress is not
doing its work,'' said Moakley. ``It's so blatantly political.''
And the subpoenas showering down upon Democrats who work in the
White House or elsewhere in the government or in the unions,
nongovernmental groups or other organizations deemed hostile by
congressional Republicans are an expensive proposition to defend
against, said Moakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to bankrupt the opposition and drain the
coffers of groups who might oppose Republican candidates,'' he
claimed. The issuance of subpoenas has degenerated into bitter and
at times farcical debate, though the Reform and Oversight
Committee, after months of disarray and staff firings, agreed 40-0
Tuesday to agree on subpoenas for the probe of whether the Chinese
government influenced Clinton administration policy with concealed
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman, Representative Dan Burton of Indiana, had
denounced Clinton as ``a scumbag'' and became the poster boy for
bad manners and a symbol of mindless partisanship. ``I'm after
him,'' Burton has said. The sulfurous atmosphere of the House has
caused a virtual breakdown of communication among members.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt has called on Gingrich to remove himself from
congressional investigations for insulting Clinton and White House
staffers in a number of speeches. Gephardt pointed out that
Gingrich routinely challenges the patriotism and truthfulness of
his political enemies and has ``demeaned'' the office of speaker by
claiming that the Clinton administration operates, in Gingrich's
words, ``the most systematic, deliberate obstruction of justice,
coverup, and effort to avoid the truth we have ever seen in
America's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Gingrich himself was assessed a $300,000 penalty by his
own membership for his own ethical lapses, Democrats were less than
charitable in their response. But Gingrich doesn't need Democratic
votes on the House floor. He has an 11-seat margin of majority _ 12
after Tuesday's GOP victory in a New Mexico special election _ and
the Republicans' big superiority in fund-raising gives them a huge
advantage for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   So Newt keeps the scandal-pedal to the metal. ``No
administration in American history has lacked the moral authority
of Clinton-Gore,'' he told his rund-raising machine, GOPAC. ``We've
never seen this kind of complex, interlocking lawbreaking.'' Can
Newt have somehow missed the Nixon years?
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by $100 million worth of investigations and a news
industry that would rather sell salacious accusations than
patiently investigate the more sensational claims, the scandal
mills grind on, exceedingly fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
