<SLUG> BC-RENT-A-CHEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-THE-GO CHEFS DISH IT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DEBBY MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you pay a complete stranger to come into your
house to do the sweeping and scrubbing, how about paying a complete
stranger to come to your house to do the sauteing and simmering?
</P>
<P>
   As more and more busy people find themselves maxed out and
frazzled at the end of the working day, more and more personal
chefs are stepping up to the stove to get dinner on the table.
</P>
<P>
   For Jill Williams Gilmore, a financial adviser with three young
children, ``cooking is a necessary evil. It's too easy for a
working parent to open up a can.''
</P>
<P>
   So every couple of weeks, Rachel Stewart, owner of the Kitchen
Magician in San Anselmo, shows up with her ``pantry-in-a-car'' and
assembles five family-sized entrees and side dishes, leaves them
packaged and labeled in the refrigerator and provides an
instruction sheet.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you'd never know she'd been in the kitchen,'' Gilmore
says. ``It's nice to have restaurant-quality food in your home two
or three times a week, especially with kids as young as mine.''
</P>
<P>
   These aren't the live-in cooks of yesteryear. These are
entrepreneurial individuals with a passion for cooking and an urge
to be self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   The personal chefs of today visit the homes of their clients and
prepare either the meal of the day or as many as 10 meals at once.
They're usually out of the house before their clients get home.
</P>
<P>
   At dinner time, all the client has to do is choose an entree and
side dishes, follow the directions, and serve.
</P>
<P>
   This may involve simple reheating in the microwave oven, or
perhaps finishing a sauce by further reduction or popping frozen
garlic bread twists into the oven. Stewart tells of a fish dish she
seasoned and assembled and left uncooked for a client, who did the
job himself (and was thrilled with his new-found skills).
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore likes the fact that Stewart will suggest, but not
prepare, certain accompanying dishes. ``I do it myself,'' Gilmore
says. ``The kids have to realize I can actually do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has been running her personal chef business for about 18
months and cooks for nine clients. In a single day, she can prepare
18 to 20 portions of perhaps five to seven snazzy entrees, plus
side dishes, for $300, food costs included.
</P>
<P>
   In her vast repertoire are elegant soups, curries, pastas,
vegetables and some treasured recipes from her mother, like chicken
sausage with yams and apples and a maple glaze.
</P>
<P>
   A popular dish is a puff-pastry-topped casserole of salmon
fillets layered with rice, fresh spinach, mushrooms and tarragon.
Then there's another favorite of smoked ham, chickpeas and chard.
``It depends on what's in season, what's at the farmers market,''
Stewart says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of single clients,'' she says. ``They don't want
to go to restaurants, they want to eat at home. And they want to
eat better. People are very food-savvy in the (San Francisco) Bay
area, and there's an incredible wealth of ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   What was once a luxury only the privileged could afford
increasingly is becoming a phenomenon of the working professional
class.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the upper crust continues to delight in the services
of personal chefs. Lori Regis and Amaryll Schwertner are the owners
of Fork in the Road, a San Francisco-based outfit that provides
upscale customized meals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dare say that personal chef service at the level we provide
probably hasn't filtered a whole lot into the middle-class
market,'' Regis says.
</P>
<P>
   And what level might that be? For a recent meal for a wealthy
businessman, the menu consisted of caviar with puff pastry, a
chicken liver mousseline, fresh-picked arugula and home-made
croutons, Niman Schell rack of lamb with a sauce of lamb reduction
and grape must, creamy risotto, Romano beans with mint and cumin
garnish, cocoa and chocolate souffles, and cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and wine. The dinner guest was the owner of Chalk Hill
winery, and the client himself is on the board of Kendall-Jackson
winery, so both labels were poured.
</P>
<P>
   ``A percentage of what we do is cooking, and a larger percentage
of it is protocol,'' Schwertner says.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, this was not an unusual dinner for the client _ he
just happened to have company that night, so Schwertner and Regis
merely prepared more servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less opulent, but still elegant service might come from the
California Culinary Academy in San Francisco, where 10 percent to
15 percent of the alumni have worked as personal chefs, and
students frequently moonlight as personal chefs, according to Kim
Amatore, CCA marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for service vary, but $20 to $30 per hour, plus food, is
par. Most prefer to keep their client list to a minimum _ their
days are filled with tongs and toques, couscous and coriander at
school, after all.
</P>
<P>
   With the level of sophistication academy-trained chefs provide,
though, aren't finicky children likely to turn up their noses at
dinner time? Many personal chefs are more than happy to cater to
the delicate palates of kids by making a meal the whole family can
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart does an intensive food interview with prospective
clients to determine their tastes. ``I'll meet families with
children, and they say `the kids eat what we eat.' But the reality
is that they eat what the kids eat. So I'll make spaghetti, but
I'll make it more interesting for the adults with eggplant or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Five news and business magazines, among them U.S. News &AMP; World
Report and Your Money magazine, recently named the personal chef
business one of the hottest home-based businesses for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Riding that tiger is David MacKay, founder of the United States
Personal Chef Association in Albuquerque, N.M. The association,
established in 1991, boasts more than 1,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more than an agency,'' MacKay says. ``We are a
professional organization. We provide cooking and business training
for our chefs, and we put chefs together with folks in the
community who want to hire them. We have audiotapes, videotapes,
correspondence courses.''
</P>
<P>
   And recipes. USPCA provides its members, half of whom are not
academy-trained, with 500 recipes designed to survive freezing and
reheating. Membership is $49 a year. The cost for the training,
plus the investment in kitchen equipment, runs between $1,000 and
$1,500, and MacKay says his personal chefs can make $40,000 to
$50,000 per year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Information on the United States Personal Chef Association can
be obtained by calling 800-995-2138.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
