<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THREADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOK SCANTS PERSONAL TO FOCUS ON ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THREADS OF TIME 
Recollections 
By Peter Brook 
Counterpoint, 212 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British director Peter Brook is one of the great visionaries
of contemporary theater, a man who breathes life and passion into a
form that all too often seems deadened by crass commercialism and
utter banality. In his stage (and subsequent film) adaptation of
the Indian epic ``The Mahabharata,'' he created a sweeping canvas
for all the great human motivations _ loyalty and jealousy, love
and hate, constancy and revenge. But for all its epic scope, the
production drove home a simple truth: Life, at its richest and
fullest, is a mix of the sacred and the ordinary, a poor man's
communion shared in a bare yet blessed space.
</P>
<P>
   Brook's long career has dramatized this truth, and he has
written eloquently about his theatrical vision in such classics as
``The Shifting Point'' and ``The Empty Space.'' His new memoir,
``Threads of Time: Recollections,'' begins as a sort of
quasi-autobiography about how a young man who started in
conventional theater managed to tear down the fourth wall and
reinvent the form. But while the book offers fleeting glimpses of
theatrical luminaries including Glenda Jackson and Sir Laurence
Olivier, this is not your typical backstage tell-all. On the first
page, Brook admits an aversion to such gossipy tomes: ``I do not
feel a compulsion to tell the whole truth,'' he writes. ``I have no
respect at all for the school of biography that believes if every
social, historical, and psychological detail is added together, a
true portrait of a life appears.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, you have to respect this stance, but as a result
of his reticence, Brook ends up with two distinct stories rather
than an organic whole. His memories _ the titular threads of time _
form an incomplete autobiography that is frustrating at best, dull
at worst. But when he finally gets around to the creation of his
International Center for Theater Research, a one-of-a-kind dramatic
laboratory in Paris, another story unfolds; the writing sings with
exemplary passion.
</P>
<P>
   The child of Russian immigrants, Brook was born in England in
1925 and enjoyed a safe childhood behind the gates of a cozy
household. He fed his imagination as a youth, lapping up film and
theater, and went off to Oxford as a dutiful son. Through a
combination of determination and luck, he gained a quick entree
into the theater world, directing productions in the West End and
at Stratford-on-Avon as a young man. While he was emerging as the
enfant terrible of the British stage, he also began a spiritual
search that is never quite clearly illuminated.
</P>
<P>
   Brook also has a maddening habit of casting out throwaway lines,
casually referring to a childhood illness or an experience with
hallucinogenic drugs but then letting them hang, forgotten and
unexplained. He briefly mentions his romance with his wife,
Natasha, but never even identifies her surname, or much else about
her.
</P>
<P>
   But when he focuses on the International Center, Brook writes
with breathtaking honesty and passion. He describes an epiphany he
had one day when a pony mysteriously leaped out of a patch of
quicksand: He, too, was compelled to escape the traps of
traditional theater. He makes the dreary yet necessary task of
fund-raising sound like a mystical quest. He leads the reader,
along with his multicultural troupe of actors, on a journey that
takes them to villages in Africa and to urban sprawls in
California. ``It is how you enter a village that counts,'' he
writes, then goes on to describe simple yet sacred encounters in
his search to find a universal means of communication.Brook is at
his best here, as both a writer and director.
</P>
<P>
   ``Threads of Time'' is inspiring when Brook lets us glimpse the
place where the fabric of his personal values and his theatrical
vision come together. He doesn't entirely weave the two threads
together in this memoir, though, and that's just plain perplexing,
since his passion for theater as a healing force is a welcome tonic
in this age of numbingly antiseptic art. At the very least, he
offers a sliver of hope for anyone still willing to believe that
art matters. ``Theater,'' he writes, ``can penetrate into the
darkest zones of terror and despair for one reason only: to be able
to affirm, neither before nor after but at the very same moment,
that light is present in darkness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
