<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMBAT-COMPUTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS _ THEY'RE IN THE ARMY NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LEWIS _ Harnessing the power of computers to the American
soldier, the Army is preparing to formally unveil the first combat
division in history built from the ground up around the microchip
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of planning and experimentation with
state-of-the art computer technology embedded in communications and
weapons systems, the 4th Infantry Division at Fort Hood, Texas,
will be certified as ready for deployment in 18 months, said Gen.
William Hartzog.
</P>
<P>
   As commander of the Training and Doctrine Command, Hartzog has
led the Army-wide program to field the new systems.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Force XXI, for the 21st century campaigns in which it
will fight, the new Army structure aims at increasing combat
effectiveness, maneuverability and decision making through computer
applications throughout the combat and support forces, Hartzog said
in an interview at Fort Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Units will use state-of-the-art M1A2 Abrams tanks and M3 Bradley
infantry vehicles, but will require fewer per brigade. The division
will require only 15,000 troops, instead of the 18,000 now on its
roster.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the division will be an array of computer networks
that provide commanders and soldiers with unparalleled knowledge of
the battlefield before and during combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Force XXI concept emerged after the end of the Cold War as
Army leaders realized that future threats facing the United States
would likely bear little resemblance to the massive entrenched
Soviet Army in Europe, which the U.S. Army had designed itself to
fight, Hartzog said.
</P>
<P>
   Severe pressure to shrink the size of the Army, combined with
new threats from terrorists and spreading weapons of mass
destruction, impelled the service to embrace the technology
revolution, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th Infantry Division, which consists of three heavy
brigades that rely on tanks and armored infantry carriers, will be
smaller but much more lethal due to new information systems used by
the commanding general and front-line riflemen, he said. While
retaining its combat punch for fighting in a conventional war, the
division can also be tailored for emergencies requiring a smaller
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In a major field test last year at the Army's National Training
Center in Southern California, a brigade from the Texas-based
division demonstrated how its digital computer power translated
into battlefield success, Hartzog said. Examples included:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Surveillance: When an enemy force began invading the
unit's operational area, surveillance aircraft and, later, unmanned
aerial vehicles, tracked the formation and transmitted data showing
the location and route of advance, allowing the brigade to
immediately prepare for battle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Air strikes: Helicopters attached to the brigade capitalized
on the same sensors to conduct an attack on the enemy, destroying
its air defenses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground and air defense: Mobile systems such as Avenger
air-to-air missiles and the Javelin anti-tank weapon were found to
be increasingly lethal against the simulated enemy because their
units were able to deploy rapidly and accurately.
</P>
<P>
   _ Battle space dominance: Even though outnumbered, new
command-and-control systems enabled the digital brigade to
outmaneuver the enemy on an extended battlefield, particularly
because the unit's artillery had the technology to immediately
track and fire on targets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Logistics: In addition to maneuvering and fighting faster than
the enemy, computer technology also enabled the brigade to resupply
its combat units faster and more efficiently, allowing them to
return to the fight sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The current schedule is to equip and train the two heavy
divisions and the III Corps headquarters based at Fort Hood. The
1st Cavalry Division will be completed in the year 2003 and the
corps headquarters by 2005, Hartzog said.
</P>
<P>
   A parallel effort to add digital combat systems to the Army's
light divisions, particularly the 82nd Airborne and 101st Air
Assault Divisions, will proceed during the next decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that the Army has historically been a very
conservative organization when it comes to radical restructuring or
introducing new technologies, Hartzog said the Force XXI program
has also aimed to accelerate the service's decision-making process,
particularly in terms of designing and procuring new weapons
systems.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line to the computer revolution is that the soldier
in combat will have the answer to three fundamental questions,
Hartzog said: ``Where am I? Where are my subordinates? Where is the
enemy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have that (information), you have something that has
never existed in the history of warfare,'' Hartzog said. ``We
intend to have the entire force ready by 2010,'' he said, referring
to the Army's mechanized and armor divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hartzog, 56, has led the Army Training and Doctrine Command
since October 1994. He previously served as deputy commander of the
U.S. Atlantic Command and also commanded the 1st Infantry Division.
He is a combat veteran of Vietnam, where he served two tours.
</P>
<P>
   Hartzog was interviewed during a visit to the advanced ROTC
summer camp at Fort Lewis, where 4,000 cadets are undergoing field
training and leadership development this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1320EDT &QL; 
