<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-PICNIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIR'S `PICNIC' RETAINS ITS POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contrary to popular belief, Peter Weir's stunning ``Picnic at
Hanging Rock,'' was not based on a true story. There was no
Appleyard College, no unexplained disappearance of three Australian
schoolgirls and their teacher in 1900. But this film is no less
potent for being fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the Joan Lindsay novel, Weir's 1975 adaptation is as
genteel as it is unsettling. Both surreal and terrifyingly
realistic, ``Picnic at Hanging Rock,'' is the story of a school
excursion gone horribly wrong. The girls of Appleyard College, an
``educational establishment for young ladies'' run by the severe
Mrs. Appleyard (Rachel Roberts), are allowed to spend Valentine's
Day at Hanging Rock, a series of ominous-looking cliffs in
Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   All of the girls, chaperoned by Miss MacCraw (Vivean Gray) and
Dianne de Poitiers (Helen Morse) are allowed on the trip, except
for Sara (Margaret Nelson). She is not only regularly chastised by
Mrs. Appleyard, but harbors a deep love for her fellow classmate,
Miranda (Anne-Louise Lambert).
</P>
<P>
   Once the girls reach Hanging Rock, four of them, led by Miranda,
set off to climb and explore the cliffs. They seem held in the
mountain's thrall, all except Edith (Christine Schuler), who senses
something awry. When her classmates continue their ascent, Edith
runs away, screaming. Soon, local authorities are notified of the
disappearance of the girls, as well as Miss MacCraw whom Edith
passed as she ran down Hanging Rock.
</P>
<P>
   What Edith witnesses at Hanging Rock is never articulated, and
therein lies the film's appeal. Unlike most films today which leave
nothing to the imagination, neither Weir nor screenwriter Cliff
Green were compelled to answer every question and solve every
riddle. Even when one of the girls is found, it only deepens the
mystery surrounding her still-lost classmates and teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say the tension is anything less than palpable.
The film is infused with such dread and foreboding, each moment, no
matter how seemingly insignificant, becomes laden with meaning,
from birds in flights to a once-reliable watch which suddenly
stops.
</P>
<P>
   Weir would go onto direct such mainstream hits as ``The Truman
Show,'' ``Dead Poets Society,'' ``Witness'' and ``The Year of
Living Dangerously.'' ``Picnic at Hanging Rock'' still stands as
one of his best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
