<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8530 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ASSASSINS-BOS &LR;      06-26 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ASSASSINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FATHER ROY' TAKES ON THE PENTAGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
``Father Roy: Inside the the School of Assassins'' 
On: Sunday at 8 p.m. on PBS 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   First things first: during the last few decades, the militaries
of El Salvador, Argentina, Chile, and several other Latin American
countries murdered, tortured and ``disappeared'' thousands of
innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   Far from denouncing these crimes, Washington too often condoned
them. When visiting soldiers trained at the US Army's School of the
Americas in the 1960s, 70s and 80s, human rights lessons seemed an
afterthought. The main goal was hunting down
(itals)comunistas.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Roy Bourgeois, a US naval officer in Vietnam who became
a Maryknoll priest, has seen Latin American armies trample on the
poor and powerless. Bourgeois gave up a quiet life of reflection to
work in a slum in Bolivia and, more recently, to set himself up as
a watchdog at the entrance to the School of the Americas, in Fort
Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   He's a dedicated, engaging activist, and Susan Sarandon's
low-key narration of ``Father Roy: Inside the School of Assassins''
makes a persuasive case for getting the Pentagon out of the
business of training Latin Americans. The hour-long film, directed
by Robert Richter, notes that the school's graduates have included
reprehensible characters such as Panama's Manuel Antonio Noriega
and a Bolivian dictator.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois has a personal stake in this: two friends of his,
American nuns, were among those raped and killed by Salvadoran
officers in 1989. Several of the officers accused of the crime had
attended the School of the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Bourgeois, who is now in jail for trespassing on Army property,
wants the school closed. He has been joined by several
Massachusetts politicians, including Representatives Joseph P.
Kennedy II, Joe Moakley and Martin T. Meehan.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to argue with someone like Bourgeois as he recounts
horrifying anecdotes with his Lousiana drawl. And yet there's
another side to the story, and it gets short shrift because of
Richter's understandable but unyielding point of view. There is an
argument, advanced by several officials in the Clinton
administration, that the school has finally been forced to reform.
These days, ironically, it is the only place that some cadets and
officers from south of the border learn that it is not permissable
to torture people simply because they are suspected of
collaborating with guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father Roy'' lets a Pentagon official make such points, but
his comments are dropped in like pebbles against the current of a
stream. The film relies heavily on interviews with and sermons by
Bourgeois as well as clips of the 1989 massacre by the Salvadoran
officers.
</P>
<P>
   If the School of the Americas cannot shed its terrible
reputation, much of the fault lies with the US Army. Most
commanders still refuse to admit that the school tolerated human
rights abuses in the name of snuffing out Marxism. They insisit on
maintaining a ``wall of fame'' featuring photos of high-ranking
graduates (never mind that several have been tied to abuses and
drug corruption). And instead of reveling in the right of critics
to speak out, the army insists on belittling Bourgeois and calling
him _ of course _ a Communist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-DOLITTLE-BOS &LR;      06-26 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-DOLITTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DOLITTLE' A PRESCRIPTION FOR PREACHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DR. DOLITTLE 
Directed by: Betty Thomas 
Screenplay by: Nat Mauldin, Larry Levin 
Starring: Eddie Murphy, Ossie Davis, Oliver Platt, Kristen Wilson,
Kyla Pratt, Raven-Symone, Richard Schiff, Peter Doyle, Jeffrey
Tambor 
Running time: 91 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (crude humor and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Dr. Dolittle'' has lots of animals, but not enough script. It
isn't Eddie Murphy's updated doc, talking to the animals, that
causes the sense of shortfall here, but a lame screenplay that
smothers high spirits under a pall of uplift. The movie spends a
lot of time knocking itself out doing the ``Babe'' and ``Mr. Ed''
thing, making dogs, rats, guinea pigs, owls, monkeys, pigeons, and
even a handsome tiger (that melts your heart with the dignity it
brings to the otherwise undistinguished proceedings) appear to be
talking. It spends the rest of the time sending a heavy-handed
message of self-empowerment, starting with Murphy's doc, whose
ability to communicate with animals was squelched when he was a boy
and must be reignited if he to become whole.
</P>
<P>
   He's got to learn that it's OK to be himself and open himself to
the joys of interspecies dialogue. It's the first step in
encouraging his younger daughter to stop thinking she's weird and
learn to love herself. And the self-empowerment theme extends to
the clinic he runs with two other docs. There he must find the
courage to stand up to a takeover by a big medical conglomerate
that would make him and his partners rich, but result in staff
firings and cutbacks in patient care. He's got to resume talking to
the animals, in other words, to keep the clinic people-oriented.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a few points worth making about symbiosis and
community, as he cures the animals and they cure him, but it does
so in such pedestrian fashion that we're simply not entertained
much. Part of this has to do with the fact that most of the time
Murphy was acting against nothing, or perhaps a pie-plate or tennis
ball on a string, with the animals computerized in later. The lack
of spontaneity is inescapably apparent. So are Murphy's limited
acting range and director Betty Thomas' tendency to fall back on
stock gestures, the most annoying of which is the one I think of as
the ``Home Alone'' meets Edvard Munch scream, a lazy and hackneyed
device that's plugged in whenever generic fright is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's rubbery smile of untrustworthiness is employed rather
too often not to fall prey to the law of diminishing returns, too.
The San Francisco locales retain a freshness that largely eludes
the film, although not for lack of effort from Ossie Davis' father
figure, Kristen Wilson's warmly appealing embodiment of the
thankless neglected wife role, Richard Schiff's sidestepping of
cliche as Dolittle's sympathetic medical partner and Kyla Platt and
Raven-Simone as his daughters. But I thought we nailed the film's
big insight a long time ago with the parrot that sang ``I Gotta Be
Me'' in ``Broadway Danny Rose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8534 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SEASON-LOOKINGBACK     06-26 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SEASON-LOOKINGBACK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE TV SEASON JUST PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every four years, World Cup soccer brings us some of the worst
acting this side of Cinemax in the wee hours. If they wanted to,
many of the world's elite booters could moonlight as guest
lecturers at the John Stockton Academy of Dramatic Flops in Short
Pants.
</P>
<P>
   Stockton plays professional basketball when he's not falling to
the floor in a heap. He could learn plenty by watching
international soccer players. Upon the most incidental contact,
these strapping, durable athletes fall faster than the fortunes of
the U.S. side. They take dives even when the nearest opponent is in
the next time zone. They writhe and grimace on the grass until the
guy with the magic water _ from Lourdes, we presume _ administers a
splash, and then they're ready for Act II.
</P>
<P>
   It's all so they can induce a referee to make a ruling in their
favor and simultaneously catch a breather in a game that knows no
timeouts. Often, the referees take the bait. Either way, the viewer
gets a steady dose of overacting that makes one look at ``Meego''
in a more favorable light.
</P>
<P>
   OK. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   But it does make one appreciate the good stuff on TV. And even
fake wrestling looks good alongside the melodramatic flops and
drops of World Cup soccer.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, we take our annual look at the best of the TV
season just past, hoping that the the occasional kick in the pants
won't send the network executives sprawling.
</P>
<P>
   Best new fall series to be renewed:
</P>
<P>
   This one is a no-brainer, even though ``Ally McBeal,''
September's most inventive new star vehicle, was leaking a little
oil by May. It's an affliction common to shows produced by the
supremely gifted David E. Kelley, whose creative juices sometimes
boil over and gum up the works.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kelley's clever treatment of the old love-triangle
scenario made Calista Flockhart a legitimate star and gave Fox the
most talked-about new show of the season. Perhaps the best thing
about ``Ally McBeal'' is how it evolved into a fine ensemble piece
that showcased not just Flockhart's remarkable acting ability _ her
expressive face alone deserves an Emmy _ but also the talents of
Peter MacNicol, Greg Germann, Lisa Nicole Carson and Courtney
Thorne-Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Best new midseason
</P>
<P>
   series to be renewed:
</P>
<P>
   The frighteningly articulate teenagers of The WB's ``Dawson's
Creek'' can be a little hard to take at times, but Kevin
Williamson's bittersweet memoir of growing up in North Carolina
wins points for style and presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that, in the telling, North Carolina, where the show
is filmed, becomes Massachusetts for some inexplicable reason. The
four principal cast members _ James Van Der Beek, Katie Holmes,
Joshua Jackson and Michelle Williams _ are appealing and convincing
as teens awakening to new realities. Sure it's soapy, but it's not
Aaron Spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Best new series to be canceled:
</P>
<P>
   If anyone needs proof that network executives don't really mean
it when they say, ``We have great faith in this year's lineup,''
consider ``Nothing Sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   On the theory that they have to fill 22 hours of programming
each week with something other than a test pattern, the networks do
a fair amount of guessing despite all their demographic research
and hocus-pocus-focus groups. ABC deserves some credit for taking a
flier on ``Nothing Sacred,'' a series about a Catholic priest
trying to reconcile his own beliefs with the dogma of his religion,
but it also deserves to do penance for failing to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing Sacred'' started out in a difficult time slot on
Thursday nights, and then was assigned Saturdays, where shows go to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that Saturday episodes draw smaller audiences, ABC owed
it to the producers to give ``Nothing Sacred'' sufficient time to
build a following. Instead, it pre-empted the show countless times
and then pulled it from the schedule with five shows still to air.
Hardly a vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   The official network explanation is that low ratings caused the
demise of ``Nothing Sacred.'' But to expect overnight success in
today's multichannel universe is just plain stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Best example of
</P>
<P>
   bottom-line programming:
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a Top 20 show, but ``Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman''
regularly won its Saturday night time slot and had a loyal
following of fans after six seasons. The problem for CBS was that
most of those fans fell into the over-50 demographic that
advertisers loathe.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional Madison Avenue wisdom _ we use the term loosely
_ is that people over 50 are not nearly as susceptible to an
advertiser's blandishments as, say, a 25-year-old. Thus, CBS
couldn't charge as much for commercials on ``Dr. Quinn'' as it
could on lower-rated shows that appeal to younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   I was never a fan of ``Dr. Quinn,'' but I still find CBS's
decision to dump it monumentally offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Best first impression
</P>
<P>
   that didn't last:
</P>
<P>
   Among comedies, ``Veronica's Closet'' had the best-made pilot
episode of the fall. Crisply directed and well acted, it appeared
to be more than just a half-hour of filler in the cushy hammock
between ``Seinfeld'' and ``ER.'' But, while delivering huge ratings
to NBC, it never delivered the quality entertainment its pilot
promised. Instead, it played like so many other interchangeable TV
comedies: shrill, forced and only occasionally funny.
</P>
<P>
   Kirstie Alley's neurotic romance expert, Veronica Chase, is
especially annoying, proving that the vein mined for several
seasons by ``Caroline in the City'' has not been exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Best miniseries:
</P>
<P>
   NBC pulled out all the stops with ``Merlin,'' a new take on the
Arthurian legend, and USA Network can rightly be proud of ``Moby
Dick,'' featuring Patrick Stewart as the troubled Capt. Ahab, but
scenes from A&AMP;E's bubbly and beguiling remake of ``Tom Jones'' are
as fresh in the mind today as they were on the screen in April.
</P>
<P>
   It was sheer pleasure to watch Max Beesley and Samantha Morton
take Tom Jones and Sophie Western through the English countryside
in Henry Fielding's comedy of errors and missteps. Every aspect of
the six-hour project _ acting, photography, costumes, script,
direction _ was at the top of its craft.
</P>
<P>
   Best midseason stink bomb:
</P>
<P>
   This one's a tie between ``Ask Harriet'' and ``The Closer.'' And
tying them together even further is this curiosity: Ed Asner had a
supporting role in both, and it's hard to tell which one made him
more uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's ``Ask Harriet'' debuted first, with the premise of a
sexist-pig sports columnist getting canned and returning to the
same newspaper as a female advice columnist. Anthony Tyler Quinn
was the guy in drag, and Asner was the newspaper's clueless owner
who found him/her attractive. On the wince scale, it was easily a
10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Closer'' marked Tom Selleck's return to a regular series
since his days on ``Magnum, P.I.,'' but it was more a reminder that
staying away is sometimes the wiser course of action. Selleck
played an advertising executive who started up his own small agency
after being fired by a big one. Asner was the agency's seasoned,
all-knowing creative director.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the show didn't have one.
</P>
<P>
   Best-promoted series finale
</P>
<P>
   If there's someone in this country who didn't know ``Seinfeld''
was ending its nine-season run in May, he may have a future as a
universal juror, untainted by exposure to the media. He also could
do well as a continuing guest on the talk-show circuit: ``Tomorrow,
on the next `Oprah,' the guy who was blissfully unaware of the
`Seinfeld' finale.''
</P>
<P>
   The obsessive way the media covered the event was really quite
embarrassing, and the runup to the series-ending episode probably
made it impossible for Jerry Seinfeld and Larry David to satisfy
such inflated expectations.
</P>
<P>
   NBC also deserves some blame for greedily stretching the thing
over two hours. ``Seinfeld'' was always at its sarcastic best in a
tightly produced half-hour. Its finale suffered from a serious case
of bloat.
</P>
<P>
   Best series finale:
</P>
<P>
   At one hour, the finale of ``The Larry Sanders Show'' was also a
tad too long, but it was everything the ``Seinfeld'' swan song
wasn't: sharp, satirical and scorching.
</P>
<P>
   Garry Shandling never won an Emmy for ``Larry Sanders,''
probably because its subject matter _ a behind-the-scenes look at a
not-so-fictitious talk show _ cut too close to Hollywood's version
of reality. But fans of the show will always remember it as a
comedy that knew what it was trying to say about human frailty and
insecurity.
</P>
<P>
   The finale was especially touching and funny at the same time.
Pretty much what you'd want when you're saying goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   John Levesque is the P-I's television critic. Call him at
206-448-8330 or send e-mail to: tvguy(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
