<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-COUSIN-BOS &LR;      06-26 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-COUSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGE HAS WILY REVENGE IN `COUSIN BETTE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
COUSIN BETTE 
Directed by: Des McAnuff 
Screenplay by: Lynn Siefert &AMP; Susan Tarr (novel: Honore de Balzac) 
Starring: Jessica Lange, Elisabeth Shue, Bob Hoskins, Hugh Laurie,
Kelly Macdonald, Aden Young 
Running time: 108 minutes 
Rated: R (sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cousin Bette'' is the film debut of stage director Des
McAnuff, and his inexperience behind the camera shows in his
tendency to overitalicize the excesses that Honore de Balzac wasn't
exactly loath to portray in red-blooded terms in his novel. In
short, McAnuff seems too eager to punch the material up, much in
the manner of many a so-called contemporary staging of this or that
classic. It undercuts a sly, steely, otherwise absorbingly
authoritative performance by Jessica Lange in the title role of an
embittered spinster, looking pasty but wiry under a startling black
hairdo. She is the classic poor relation who gets back at the
Parisian relatives who have callously and thoughtlessly demeaned
her for years.
</P>
<P>
   The film begins on a promisingly malicious note as Lange stands
alongside the deathbed of her rich sister (Geraldine Chaplin). When
the dying woman asks Bette to take care of her family, our
appetites are whetted by Lange's way of compressing her lips before
saying, in frighteningly controlled tones, ``I'll take care of them
all.'' When her brother-in-law offers her a job as housemaid
instead of proposing marriage, as she thought he would, she thinks
she might have found love anyway when she meets and aids an
impoverished Polish sculptor who lives in the garret adjoining hers
in the theater district. There, talented seamstress that she is,
she makes her living as a costumier.
</P>
<P>
   It's when Bette's last chance for love is whisked out from under
her by her spoiled niece that revenge enters the picture. It's fun
to watch her get even, although it must be said that the family
members, with their various weaknesses, make it easy for her.
Although quite capable of acting alone, Bette enlists the aid of
the star of the burlesque house that employs them both. Elisabeth
Shue provides a sense of fun with the unbridled vulgarity in which
she revels. Bob Hoskins is another plus as the rich mayor and
leading lecher. Although Adan Young has his moments as the sculptor
ruined by the soft life, talking more and more about art and
practicing it less and less, he turns too blubbery and nondescript
too soon.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, McAnuff seems not to have trusted Balzac's lusty
potboiler to simmer along on its own gleefully malicious energies.
He's good at playing the atmosphere of the theater against the
upheavals caused by the aristocrats' selfishness, but rather less
convincing at making them seem a portent of the revolution of 1848.
In his rush to register with contemporary audiences, McAnuff
abandons subtleties _ as Lange never does _ for crude captions.
``Cousin Bette'' is worth seeing for Lange's passion curdled into
malice, administered with a silken expertise that is nowhere to be
encountered in anything surrounding her. Against her, the others
seem vastly overmatched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8538 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-OUT-OF-SIGHT-BO     06-26 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-OUT-OF-SIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD'S TWISTING PLOT MAKES A `SIGHT' TO BE SEEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
OUT OF SIGHT 
Directed by: Steven Soderbergh 
Screenplay by: Scott Frank (novel: Elmore Leonard) 
Starring: George Clooney, Jennifer Lopez, Ving Rhames, Dennis
Farina, Steve Zahn, Don Cheadle, Isaiah Washington, Albert Brooks,
Catherine Keener, Nancy Allen, Keith Loneker 
Running time: 129 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some strong violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Hollywood gets Elmore Leonard's novels right, they offer
pleasures no other crime movies do. ``Out of Sight'' gets Elmore
Leonard right. It's ``Get Shorty'' without the film biz satire,
``Jackie Brown'' with more snap and a few more curveballs. It's
also the first movie in which George Clooney looks like a real
movie star, relaxed, on top of his game, having fun. It's easy to
believe that this is the movie that made him feel secure enough to
leave TV's ``ER,'' convinced that his roguish charm could indeed
translate onto the big screen. Unlike the scripts for his previous
movies, this one gives him a good character to play.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is Jack Foley, a career bank robber who has spent half
his life in prison, is determined never to go back, and is equally
determined to score one more big heist and retire. The other half
of the equation is Jennifer Lopez's smart cop, much tougher than he
is. They meet under unusual circumstances. She happens to be
present during a prison break and winds up confined in the trunk of
a getaway car with Clooney. This is the scene that could make or
break the movie. Steven Soderbergh's deft direction turns it into a
successful launch and reminds us that the great thing about
Leonard's capers is their quirky unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's movies go places other movies wish they were clever
enough to have thought of, and ``Out of Sight'' is no exception as
Clooney's felon and Lopez's cop find themselves growing interested
in one another. They talk, are pleasantly surprised to find
themselves on the same wavelength, make us feel the presence of
sexual chemistry that's allowed to simmer through several plot
twists and finally moves forward in a hotel room in Detroit. There,
he returns to her the gun he used to make her surrender, and both
openly confront the risks they're taking by acting on their
attraction _ freedom in his case, career in hers.
</P>
<P>
   During the bedroom scene, they convince us they're sharing not
only sex, but intimacy. It's hot and it's sweet, and the fullest
realization of glamorous and slightly edgy screen romance out of
Hollywood this year. One reason their attraction works is that it's
given breathing space by the funny, surprising antics of the
surrounding lowlifes and the wary father of Lopez's character,
Dennis Farina's retired cop, who tenderly gives his daughter a
revolver for her birthday and chases off her married suitor
(Michael Keaton, in a funny unbilled cameo that makes him seem to
have drifted in from ``Jackie Brown''). Another ``Jackie Brown''
alum, Samuel L. Jackson, comes through in an unbilled grace note at
the end, giving the film that final lift of surprise you feared it
had run out of.
</P>
<P>
   The others comprise a terrific ensemble cast. Ving Rhames is
oak-solid as Clooney's prison buddy, Steve Zahn is a comic plus as
the stoned surfer who leads everybody to the last big caper, Don
Cheadle and Isaiah Washington more than hold up their end when it
comes to juggling violence and humor as a pair of prison
acquaintances who want in on the big score, and Albert Brooks is a
plus as a crooked broker who stupidly bragged about having $5
million in diamonds when he was doing time for insider trading. In
his stone-faced way, Brooks makes the white-collar criminal seem
more reprehensible than the professionals, not only Clooney's
gentleman thief, but the killers, including ex-NFL linebacker Keith
Loneker, who momentarily forgets the diamonds and starts emptying
the fridge of steaks.
</P>
<P>
   Watching how all the characters slide together, bounce off one
another, and carom back onto the same collision course is part of
the fun. Leonard claims he doesn't know how his novels are going to
turn out when he begins them, that he starts with characters and
lets them show him the way. ``Out of Sight'' certainly plays that
way, even during its intricate interplay of flashbacks that show us
how things converged. ``Out of Sight'' is a heads-up action
romance, filled with sassy wit, a beautifully gauged undertow of
poignance, brightly and playfully alive. It never goes awry,
although it's certainly aware of the many ways in which life does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SAMPSON-BOS &LR;      06-26 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SAMPSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSICIAN REACHES THE POINT OF NO RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the outside, Caleb Sampson's life looked fine. The
45-year-old keyboardist-composer was continuing his work with the
Alloy Orchestra, the Boston trio whose specialty was scoring modern
soundtracks to silent films. He'd won accolades for his soundtrack
to Errol Morris's film ``Fast, Cheap and Out of Control'' and had
composed music for an upcoming 30-minute film by Morris, ``Stairway
to Heaven,'' for the BBC. Classically trained, Sampson had composed
music for MTV, VH1, HBO, PBS, Showtime, and ``Sesame Street.'' The
demand for his musical talents was so heavy, says Terry Donahue, a
partner in the Alloys, that the main problem was deciding which
offers not to accept. He had a happy marriage to Kathleen Hickey
and a 19-month-old son, Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   But Sampson, who grew up in Lewiston, Maine, and often sought
refuge in the great outdoors, had been suffering from a severe
sleep disorder. It started a couple of years ago and worsened last
month when the family bought and moved into an Inman Square
condominium. At best, he was getting four hours of sleep a night,
usually just one or two, sometimes none at all. It took its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was great in reality,'' says Donahue, ``but his
reality had changed so much. Every little fear became blown up to
the point of no return. All the fleeting negative thoughts just
stayed there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson hanged himself June 8 in the Cambridge, Mass. studio he
shared with Ken Winokur, his other partner in the Alloy Orchestra.
He had just come from a meeting with his psychiatrist, who had
suggested hospitalization for his deep depression. Sampson and his
wife had the same psychiatrist. Hickey says the doctor talked to
Sampson about suicide and Sampson said, ```No, I'm safe. I would
never do that to Kathy.' Those were his final words.'' Legally, the
doctor couldn't commit Samspon without his approval. Says Hickey:
``I talked to the doctor and he said: `Caleb knew what to say to
get out of the office.'''
</P>
<P>
   Winokur found the body. He recalls a feeling of ``shock, sadness
and a strong degree of disppointment how he left his wife and
child.'' There was no note.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an absolutely atrocious sleep disorder and general
depression,'' says Winokur. In Boston, there are ``the best doctors
in the best medical centers of the Western universe, and they
weren't able to pull him out of it. Nothing in his life merited any
kind of despair. His career and life were going well. We've tried
to rationalize this over and over again. But he just got sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickey first met Sampson eight years ago. Then, they lost touch
and had a chance meeting outside Boston's Tower Records a year and
ahalf later. ``It was magic,'' says Hickey. ``We thought it was
fate. He was the most vulnerable, fragile, but strong, gentle,
loving soul that I ever met. I'll never meet someone as unique,
gifted, and emotionally vulnerable. We were a tremendous gift to
each other. He brought the most joy and love to my life and I know
I brought the most joy and love to his life. We were
extraordinarily happy together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were together almost five years,'' she adds. ``Part of him
always had this yearning and despair, this ache for something.
There were times where he was capable of having a darker experience
of the world. When we got together, we thought a wonderful
relationship and marriage would fix it; we thought `Fast, Cheap and
Out of Control' would fix it; we thought buying a house would fix
it. But Caleb had huge anxieties about having adult
responsibilities, and they competed with the feelings he had about
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a creative person with a risky career, who gave up some
of what he had saved (to buy the condo). He'd say, `How can I be a
musician and support a family?' I'd say, `Honey, you're one of the
most successful muscicians we know.' But the money was a symbol, it
represented stability. He was terrified of taking those risks and
having those responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickey says Sampson had been on a variety of anti-depressants
and sleep-aid medications. Nothing worked. ``That exacerbated it
and tortured him,'' she says. ``He couldn't get any relief. He felt
like an utter and complete failure. Everything except for me _ it
never was us _ became a source of deep anxiety and strees and the
sleep problem didn't help.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter irony, of course, is that Hickey was right about
Sampson's career growth. The Alloy Orchestra, just one slice of his
creative life, had scored new music to ``Metropolis,'' ``The
Wind,'' ``Nosferatu,'' ``The Lost World, ``Sylvester,'' and
``Lonesome.'' They played at the Telluride Film Festival. Last
summer, they played Radio City Music Hall as ``Metropolis'' was
showed. Last autumn, they played at the Louvre, accompanying
``Lonesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Winokur: ``We traveled the world together and shared a lot
of weird food.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in a Globe interview, Sampson explained their
immersion in the silent world. Initially, he said, ``none of us
were interested in silent films. Like us, hardly anyone has had an
exciting experience watching silent films until we came along.
People go, `Silent film? I don't know, sounds like going to
school.' It turns out to be this intensely engaging thing. We have
become ambassadors of spreading the faith, but not through any
great design.'' The idea was suggested by former Coolidge Corner
programmer David Kleiler.
</P>
<P>
   Employing Sampson's syntheziers and the other two's massive
percussion rigs (using everything from metal ducts, pipes, and
bedpans to conventional drum kits), the Alloys created a
topsy-turvy world of sound _ sometimes whimsical, sometimes
frightening, sometimes warm. For all their clamor and clatter, they
were not a dissonant outfit. They played a couple of First Nights
in Boston to excited crowds. Their audience spanned ``infants to
geriatrics,'' as Donahue puts it.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson ``had an absolute uncanny knack for spontaneously
creating melody,'' says Winokur. ``We could sit down and he could
roll 'em off his fingertips, one after another. He could do a
hundred projects a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought in a classic romantic sensibility,'' adds Donahue,
``that sentimentalist thing that really translated. It helped make
our audience as broad as it was. He was very easy to work with, his
palette was so broad. If we were working on a piece (Ken and I)
didn't think was working, he could throw it away and start fresh,
where most people would go `Hey, that's my song.' The chemistry was
kind of amazing, and we used each other's strengths really well,
covering up our weaknesses at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Alloys' next project was _ and remains _ scoring the 1923
Eisenstein film ``Strike,'' about a failed workers' revolt. ``It's
very shadowy and gray,'' says Donahue. The group will announce a
new synthesizer player and composer in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   With Sampson's death, guitarist, composer, and arranger John
Kusiak also lost his partner. The two, who collaborated on ``Fast,
Cheap and Out of Control,'' had worked together over seven years
and done approximately 50 soundtracks. ``He was so naturally suited
to creating music for visual media,'' says Kusiak. ``It was
something that seemed to flow out him intuitively. I remember we
were doing a PBS documentary and he sat down and looked at a cue, a
minute long. We played it back once and he played along with the
picture. It was perfect. No changes. I was floored.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a great human being,'' Kusiak adds, ``someone who liked
to have a lot of fun. We'd work on projects and he'd find a putter,
a golf ball, and cup and set up a whole course in the studio. He
was the traditional Mainer _ frugal, quirky. He ate the same
breakfast every morning, a couple big bowls of Maypo. He would ride
his bike everywhere. He never seemed to need much in terms of
possessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Their score for Morris's ``Fast, Cheap and Out of Control'' was
praised by Roger Ebert as creating a ``haunting, otherworldly,
elegiac mood that makes all of the characters seem noble and a
little sad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He channeled everything, a lot of his emotional life, into his
music,'' says Hickey.
</P>
<P>
   But, of late, Donahue says, his sleep deprivation ``was the only
thing on his mind, the only thing he'd talk about. He was getting a
little sleep, but since they moved he hadn't gotten more than four
hours, at the most. He'd be getting up, surrounded by responsiblity
and pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson loved Maine, says Hickey, and would have lived there had
his career permitted. She called him ``a loner for much of his
life, with a huge network of friends.'' She says he felt bad about
having to take medication, and was vehement about not being
hospitalized. He'd been on a new anti-depressant for six weeks
before his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had talked about suicide,'' says Hickey, ``and he promised
he wouldn't do it. He felt hopeless. Everything was amplified to
such a degree. He was lucid enough to know it was happening. He'd
say `What is happening to me?' ... It frightened him that it was
getting out of control. It was new to him, that he had something
that couldn't be treated, that couldn't be fixed from love,
compassion, and patience, the things in life that usually givve one
hope or joy. He'd put his hand over his heart and say `I'm in so
much pain.' I'd say, `We'll try to get you through this and trust
in time it'll get better.' I think his mind was so completely
ravaged. He chose an option that brought him peace. ... The reality
was so different from how he perceived it. He was denying the
greatness of his life. As hard as it is to accept, he made a choice
that left him with the dignity he could handle. In some ways, I can
hold on to an image that he had found peace, that living with a
mind that was ravaged and out of control, he just wanted his mind
to be at rest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (A fund has been set up for Sampson and Hickey's son, Oliver.
Contributions can be made to: Oliver Sampson, c/o the Alloy
Orchestra, 613 Cambridge St., Cambridge, MA 02141.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
