<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-DOLITTLE-     06-26 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DOLITTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DR. DOLITTLE' IS A GOOD PRESCRIPTION FOR THE 90S FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WALTER ADDIEGO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buried somewhere deep inside Eddie Murphy's ``Dr. Dolittle'' is
a nice little family movie about a successful, driven dad who
finally gets in touch with the warm and fuzzy things in life.
</P>
<P>
   He does, indeed, talk to the animals, which helps him become
human again and revives his strained relationship with his
wonderful wife and smart, charming kids.
</P>
<P>
   The talented Murphy is appealing here, performing with sincerity
and restraint _ a wise choice, since his co-stars are a menagerie
of wisecracking animals with voices provided by a whooping crop of
his comedian friends (Chris Rock, Norm Macdonald and Albert Brooks
among them). Forget about bleating and barking: These critters
sound like they've paid their dues on the nightclub circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Set in contemporary San Francisco in a world of corporate
takeovers and fancy utility vehicles, the picture bears almost no
relationship to Hugh Lofting's children's stories nor to the
charmless 1967 musical, ``Doctor Dolittle,'' with Rex Harrison.
Murphy, the producers, and director Betty Thomas (``Private
Parts'') clearly set out to make a movie appealing to today's
audiences, and that's where the problems begin.
</P>
<P>
   Families raised on in-your-face TV like ``Married ...With
Children'' and ``South Park'' may have a low tolerance for
cuteness. OK, I suppose you could name some movies, too, that fail
the good-taste test. So the filmmakers decided to add a little
mustard in the form of butt-sniffing, flatulence and poop jokes
that begin with the opening scene and never really let up.
</P>
<P>
   The movie definitely stresses the ``animal'' side of animals.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy plays Dr. John Dolittle, a physician who has it all: an
adorable family, a plush Pacific Heights condominium and a thriving
practice that he and his partners are preparing to sell to
corporate interests for big money.
</P>
<P>
   But the strain is showing: He's abrupt, a bit testy and always
in a rush. As a boy, John was able to talk to the family dog, but
his no-nonsense father (Ossie Davis) wouldn't allow him to nurture
the gift, so John's forgotten all about it.
</P>
<P>
   But after a minor car accident, John hears a tongue-lashing from
a stray dog. Word spreads through the animal underground about his
rediscovered powers, and soon he's being consulted by owls with
injured wings and horses with dimming vision. Also on hand are a
couple of smart-aleck rats and a suicidal tiger from a circus in
town.
</P>
<P>
   The animal effects _ combining real creatures with puppets and
computer enhancement _ are accomplished, and the zingers, insults
and riffs delivered by the furry cast wouldn't be out of place at
your local comedy pub.
</P>
<P>
   By treating animals, John rediscovers his zest for medicine, and
becomes a better dad and husband. Presumably, he also gets to sleep
with his wife (Kristen Wilson) again _ a running gag has animals
interrupting their sex life.
</P>
<P>
   There are subplots involving John's incarceration in a mental
hospital (not too funny), and various machinations by a greedy
medical partner (Oliver Platt).
</P>
<P>
   That's about it. The animals tear off some funny one-liners, and
there's a nice little money-isn't-everything lesson. On the other
hand, the bathroom humor and general air of testing the envelope
are persistent, and, with the salty language, likely to turn off
some parents. But let's accentuate the positive (and I wish other
filmmakers would take note): ``Dr. Dolittle'' clocks in at a cool,
crisp and blessed 85 minutes. This is movie bliss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-26 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUDY YORK'S MYSTERY RUN AT A HOME RUN RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rudy York was a pretty good ballplayer, but no one has ever
offered a satisfactory explanation of why he up and swatted 18 home
runs in August 1937, or why he almost broke his own record when he
hit 17 in August 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Will they someday be saying the same thing about Sammy Sosa?
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. Sammy is getting a better reward at the
pay window for his month of June than the affable York did when he
took apart the American League for a month nearly 61 years ago.
Sammy checks in at $10 million per. Rudy probably wasn't even
making five figures in those innocent days of yore.
</P>
<P>
   The man Sosa is about to elbow aside for one of those quirky
baseball records occupies a niche in baseball history that makes
him a familiar name for the advanced fan and a who's-he? for the
casual observer. He knocked in 100 runs on six occasions and he had
30-plus homers four times, but it is reasonably safe to say that
the thing he is most remembered for is that blistering month of
August in 1937, when he had 18 home runs and 51 runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did I mention he was the first baseman on the 1946 Red
Sox?
</P>
<P>
   ``A hell of a player,'' recalls Johnny Pesky, who played against
York in 1942 before becoming his teammate in '46 following a trade
with the Tigers. ``We all respected his judgment. He never squawked
on a pitch. And if one of us had a question _ was the pitch too
high, too low, or whatever? _ we'd go to Rudy for an opinion.
`John,' he'd say, `I think it was all right.'''
</P>
<P>
   York played a season and change for the Sox. He had 17 homers
and 119 RBIs for the '46 pennant winners and he won Game 1 of the
World Series with a towering 10th-inning homer off Howie Pollett.
By that time, he was 33, and he must have been one of those guys
who got old fast. (Part of the York folklore is that he was a
fairly serious drinker.) The Sox shipped him to the White Sox early
in '47. ``We all felt bad when he left,'' Pesky says. ``He was a
good guy to have on the team. He used to accuse me of hitting with
a tennis racket. You miss guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he had a great deal of Indian blood, people often looked
at the Alabama native and assumed facts not in evidence, as Perry
Mason might say. Foremost among those assumptions: that he was an
``instinctive,'' as opposed to a cerebral, player.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Doerr laid that idea to rest on the occasion of York's
death from cancer in 1970. ``At first,'' Doerr explained, ``I
regarded Rudy as a man with a great bat _ power and strength. Later
I found it was a lot more than that. He studied pitchers, spotted
giveaways, was uncanny in outguessing the opposing batteries.''
</P>
<P>
   York moved on to the Philadelphia A's in '48, retiring after
playing in just 31 games with a .275 career average, 277 homers,
and 1,152 RBIs. He could tell the grandchildren that among his
other acomplishments, he led the American League in home runs (34),
RBIs (118), and slugging percentage (.527) in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   In 1937, Rudy York was a 23-year-old rookie utilityman for the
Tigers, a good team whose main problem in life was that the New
York Yankees existed. He played some third and he caught, and he
would later becopme a full-time first baseman, but the truth is he
was a born DH. When August began, he wasn't even in the lineup,
even though the Tigers were casting about for a catcher following
what would turn out to be the career-ending beaning of
player-manager Mickey Cochrane by New York's Bump Hadley. Hank
Greenberg would eventually move to left so York could play first,
but that was three years down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that when August arrived in 1937, York had been a
Tiger contributor (12 homers), but nothing more. There was a
doubleheader here in Fenway Aug. 1, and York's only appearance was
a pinch-hit role in the first game. He didn't play the following
day, either.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't even hit his first home run of the month until Aug. 6.
He hit another the next day, and he was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   These were different times, in every way. Though York was on a
major roll, there was little national attention until the last week
of the month. On Aug. 27, distinguished Globe baseball writer Mel
Webb doffed the old journalistic fedora in Rudy's direction: ``That
boy York of the Tigers is hitting in sensational fashion ... it is
doubtful whether the old `Babe' ever put in a more effective
stretch than has Mickey Cochrane's recalled catcher.''
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of The Babe, Mr. Ruth himself weighed in the
following day. ``That DiMaggio boy sure looks like a natural to
become the No. 1 hitter in the game, but you can't overlook that
young Tigers catcher, Rudy York,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   York had some good company on that Detroit team. Serious
baseball fans would easily recognize every member of the starting
team, as well as starting pitchers Tommy Bridges and Eldon Auker.
The No. 3 hitter was Hall of Famer Charley Gehringer, who was on
his way to leading the league with a .371 average. The cleanup man
was another Hall of Famer, Greenberg, en route to driving in _ hope
you're sitting down _ 183 runs. York was batting fifth during the
streak.
</P>
<P>
   He had four two-homer games, the third of which, on Aug. 30,
gave him 16 homers for the month. Only then did anyone mention that
he had a chance to eclipse Ruth's total of 17 in September 1927. No
one knew from ``SportsCenter'' in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers finished the month at home with a game against the
Washington Senators. Talk about a dramatic finish. York blasted a
pair of three-run homers in a 4-for-4 performance. He drove in
seven runs.
</P>
<P>
   Those 18 homers withstood subsequent challenges from, in
addition to himself, Greenberg, Ralph Kiner, and Mickey Mantle, who
all had 16-homer months; and from Willie Mays and Albert Belle, who
pounded out 17 in a month. Now he has been caught by Sammy Sosa,
and he is no longer a man apart.
</P>
<P>
   What got into Rudy York? Who knows? His only explanation: ``It
was sort of warm, like it is down in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy York wasn't a Hall of Famer, and it's reasonably safe to
say that Sammy Sosa isn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball. It is a source of endless mystery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
