<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREMENT INVESTOR IS ON TRACK WITH 401(K) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 44 and would like to retire at age 62 with an income of
about $50,000 a year. We now have $157,000 in a 401(k) plan, with
$17,000 of it in a 5.95 percent guaranteed income fund, $56,000 in
Fidelity Magellan fund, $59,000 in a Standard and Poor's index 500
fund, and $25,000 in Warburg Pincus Emerging Growth fund. Annual
contributions, including my employer's match, will be $11,000 a
year. Other investment options within the 401(k) are Warburg Pincus
International Equities and Fidelity Advisor Balanced funds. Our
only debt is a $148,000 mortgage, on which we have been making $400
monthly prepayments and expect to pay it off in about 10 years. Are
we better off continuing with that, or should we be investing the
extra money? We have two children who will be going to college in
the next few years. Some of the money needed will come from my
wife, who will return to work. Should we contribute less to the
401(k), or make lower prepayments of the mortgage to help fund the
college expenses?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; K.G. &LR; ,  &UR; Vancouver, Wash &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My suggestion is to keep plugging away at the 401(k)
contributions at the current rate.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, your employer's contributions may come in the
form of a match of your own, so that every dollar you divert may
cost you more than a dollar in eventual savings.
</P>
<P>
   More important, you seem to be pretty well on track to reach
your retirement goal, but a reduction of payments might leave you
falling short.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the math: If you achieve average annual total returns of
10 percent form the retirement portfolio, with contributions at the
current level, after 18 years the pool would be $1,397,608. You
might expect such a sum, invested in retirement to produce an
income stream of 6.5 percent, to bring you $90,844. This sounds
great, until you begin thinking of inflation. If inflation runs at
a 3 percent average over the next 18 years, that $90,84 would have
the buying power of $53,361 in today's dollars; if inflation is 4
percent, the value in today's dollars would be $44,843. In other
words, you're in the ballpark, but achieving your goal is far from
certain, and reduction of contributions would probably make it
fairly likely you would fall short.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, my suggestion would be to stop prepayments of the
mortgage right now, putting the money instead into college savings,
hoping that with this head start you can meet the college expenses
that come up during the next six or eight years and then, upon the
final graduation, turn once again to the mortgage prepayments --
this would still give you a decade before retirement, which would
be plenty of time to retire the mortgage at least by the time
you're 62.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I'm not enthusiastic about the current market, I'm
even less enthusiastic about that $17,000, or a little less than 11
percent of the 401(k) portfolio, that's in the fixed-income fund. I
suggest you grit your teeth and move it into the Warburg
International Equities fund, which will broaden the diversification
of the portfolio, and which over the course of some 18 years should
give you a great deal better performance than the fixed- income
fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 70 years old and my wife is 60. Between us we draw
$1,728 from Social Security. We have $65,000 in a savings account
and IRAs totaling $320,000, of which $210,000 is in Pegasus Growth
and Value fund and $110,000 is in Pegasus Mid Cap Opportunity fund.
Our condo here is worth $140,000 and is owned free end clear, as is
a $40,000 home we own in Florida. To live in comfort, we need an
income of $3,500 to $3,800 a month. Do you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; C.M. &LR; ,  &UR; Waterford, Mich. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes _ I think you should shift a great deal of the IRA money
into fixed-income holdings, designing the portfolio so that the
yields on your investments provide you with your desired income
stream, rather than relying on the vagaries of the stock market to
support you.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose you decide you can live on a median figure of
$3,650 a month. After Social Security, this would leave you with a
requirement of $1,922 a month from your investments. If the $65,000
that's now in savings were diverted to a CD or a money market fund
(or a combination of the two, so designed as to give you the best
rates plus whatever liquidity you feel you needs) this would bring
in about $300 of the required monthly money. I suggest you then
move $300,000 of the IRA money into a fixed-income portfolio. Since
Pegasus has a limited menu of fixed-income funds, you might look to
another fund family for this.
</P>
<P>
   My choice, based on low expenses and a disciplined approach to
investment policies, would be Vanguard, where I would suggest a
portfolio evenly divided between its Short-Term Corporate Bond, its
GNMA, and its High-Yield Corporate Bond funds. You might expect
such a portfolio to produce an average yield of 6.5 percent, which
would meet the remainder of your ongoing cash needs. The upshot of
these changes would be that you would have sharply reduced
stock-market risk, and still retain a token $20,000 in the two
Pegasus stock funds untouched, slowly building a fund which should
give you a little protection against the effects of future
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   I think that reduction of risk the most critical thing here --
more important than building a fund to hedge you against inflation.
Counting on stock-market gains to fund living expenses can be a
dangerous business. Suppose that you began withdrawing $1,622 a
month from the Pegasus funds, and that at the time you began the
market went into a tailspin, losing value at a rate of 10 percent
annually for two years.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of that two- year period your $320,000 in principal
would have declined to $223,875 -- a level at which you would have
to stretch hard to meet your needs. The more conservative path
should fill your financial needs, afford you less worry, and over
the long haul should generate an accumulation, rather than
invasion, of your principal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 1 55-year-old woman who plans to work full-time for
another seven years, and perhaps thereafter as necessary. With the
current market instability I sold all my blue chip stocks, placing
the $90,000 proceeds in a money market fund. I also own $30,000 in
mutual funds, invested in Fidelity Puritan and Oakmark funds.
Finally, I am contributing $300 a month to an all-stock 401(k)
investment. Where do you think the cash in the money market fund
should be placed with my somewhat short time horizon?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; J.L. &LR; ,  &UR; Vista, Calif. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the classical suggestion for an intermediate-time
investment such as this is a balanced fund, such as Fidelity
Puritan which you already own. But I suspect that since you have
just bailed out of equities, so you're not likely to be
enthusiastic about that. So why not build a portfolio such as I
have suggested for C.M., in the letter above. You might reasonably
expect this to produce a yield in the neighborhood of 1 percentage
point to one and a half percentage points better than the money
markets, and while bond funds are far from isolated from market
sways, over the course of time good fixed-income funds tend to
balance whatever losses they sustain with similar gains, ultimately
leaving the owner with the yield. One advantage of such an
investment is that you would already have a substantial income
stream in place by the time you retire. At a 6.5 percent average
annual growth rate, that pool would grow to $139,858 in seven
years, and at that point might be counted on to produce a $9,090
annual income stream.
</P>
<P>
   To give you a fuller view of your likely financial picture in
retirement, if your 401(k) is funded at the current level, and if
both that account and your mutual funds grew at an average annual
rate of 8 percent during the next seven years (no, I am not
optimistic about stocks for the intermediate term) that pool would
be worth $84,712 by the time of your expected retirement date.
(This would, however, require that you used other funds to pay any
tax liabilities which the mutual funds generated during that
accumulation phase.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
