<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS PARTNERSHIP INVESTORS HEAD DOWN TO THE BUZZER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Pitino would call a timeout to regroup if his Boston
Celtics were under this much pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the team's publicly traded partnership units that are
under the gun, falling sharply on relatively heavy volume over the
past two weeks. The issue: a plan that would split the Celtics
master limited partnership into two new entities.
</P>
<P>
   Unit holders can swap for an interest in either of the new
partnerships and their level of ownership will remain unchanged,
though each of the investment vehicles has distinct advantages and
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But confusion over the complicated reorganization plan and
questions about the way it has been advanced are prompting some
investors to simply sell instead of choosing between one of the two
new ownership vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Selling pressure has been building as the June 30 deadline to
choose one of the two partnerships approaches. Celtics units,
priced at 16 3/4 Thursday, have slumped nearly 20 percent in the
last four weeks, and trading volume is running at about 10 times
normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that there is the aura of impropriety, although that
may not be the actual case,'' said Sheryl Marshall, a broker at
Donaldson, Lufkin, Jenrette who has bought Celtics units for her
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and other brokers complain that the reorganization is
taking place without any independent appraisal or ``fairness''
opinion from outside experts, despite potential conflicts of
interest between public unit holders and the Celtics general
partner, among others. The potential conflict is cited in public
documents describing the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics officials said they did not obtain a fairness opinion
because the reorganization will have no impact on the ownership
interest of unit holders. Officials also said professional
assurances could have cost several million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was structured to make it as equitable as possible, so
everyone maintained their portion of the business,'' said chief
financial officer Richard Pond. ``Proportionately, no one is going
to be in any different position on July 1 than they were on June
30.''
</P>
<P>
   An earlier reorganization plan created by Celtics chairman Paul
Gaston, which never made it to the board for a vote, probably would
have caused more controversy. That plan, detailed in securities
documents, would have substantially reduced team ownership by
Gaston and his affiliates in exchange for other investments. The
initial plan was scrapped after financial advisers estimated the
team's value at $140 million to $160 million.
</P>
<P>
   The idea: Make sure everyone ended up with the same value,
dollar for dollar, but rearrange the actual assets. Besides the
basketball team, the Celtics partnership holds nearly $100 million
in cash and securities.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston and his affiliates currently own about 50.1 percent of
the Celtics partnership. The initial plan would have reduced the
investment in the team to about 20 percent through the use of two
new, related partnerships. In return for the reduced team
ownership, the Gaston group would have gotten other investments of
comparable value.
</P>
<P>
   The catch: placing a value on the team. An investment advisory
firm, Houlihan Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, was hired to assess the entire
deal and, among other duties, come up with the preliminary estimate
of the team's value.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics said the investment firm's ``draft presentation''
was not a factor in the decision to drop Gaston's plan. But the
partnership later held ``informal consultations'' with what was
then known as Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co., the large investment firm once
associated with former Celtics president Stephen Schram.
</P>
<P>
   Celtics executives said in documents that they decided it was
too hard to obtain a reliable appraisal of the team's value for the
plan to work.
</P>
<P>
   But the documents also said Houlihan Lokey balked when the
Celtics asked the investment firm to back up their public summary
of events in writing with the US Securities and Exchange
Commission. Executives at Houlihan Lokey did not return calls
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are being forced to change their ownership structure
because a special tax status extended to a small group of master
limited partnerships is expiring. The Celtics partnership earns
money free of federal income taxes and passes most of it on to
investors, much like a real estate investment trust.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current plan, unit holders can choose to swap their
investment for units of a new public partnership, Boston Celtics
Limited Partnership II, or a private vehicle, Castle Creek
Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Castle Creek investors will continue to enjoy the tax advantages
of today's Celtics partnership. But they will be stuck with an
illiquid investment, unable to sell their units on a public market
at any time as they can today.
</P>
<P>
   Another catch: Castle Creek is open only to investors who own at
least 100 Celtics units. About 78 percent of registered Celtics
investors own fewer than 10 units, often bought as souvenirs rather
than securities.
</P>
<P>
   The new Celtics partnership owns a chunk of the business that
will earn less because it will be subjected to income taxes. But
the partnership units will trade publicly, just as they do today,
and investors who choose the option get other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Unit holders of the new public partnership also will receive $1
cash per unit and an unsecured, 40-year note with a face value of
$20 and a coupon of 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That package is hard to value, but some investors estimate the
new Celtics partership unit might be worth $6 and the publicly
traded note will be heavily discounted, perhaps down to $12. Add
the cash and the total package could be worth about $19.
</P>
<P>
   But the handicappers also warn that thin trading could skew the
actual price when the unit and the note begin trading next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
