<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-SMITH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE ARE GOING TO THE DOGS _ TO RELIEVE OFFICE STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your boss getting on your nerves? Work driving you up a wall?
</P>
<P>
   Try petting a puppy.
</P>
<P>
   On several occasions, a Seattle Post-Intelligencer employee has
brought a batch of English cocker spaniel pups to work, and the
reaction has been both swift and amusing. It is a sight to see
normally hard-nosed reporters down on the floor making kissy-poo
and talking baby-talk to little dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really see people's personalities come out,'' said Katy
Khakpour, P-I receptionist and occasional puppy-minder. ``Everyone
goes crazy when they see a dog in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Using animals to help with work place stress is an idea that is
catching on. The Oregon Humane Society in Portland, for example, is
mounting a pilot ``Animals in the Workplace'' program with five
small companies.
</P>
<P>
   The response so far has been enthusiastic, said program manager
Virginia Dagg, whose first client was Cascade Direct, a small
Portland direct-mail business. ``Employees just went crazy _ they
loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is one of only a handful of humane societies that
appear to be doing it, Dagg has had calls from interested
organizations all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care where you work, I don't care if it's the most
wonderful job in the world, there's still a stress factor.''
</P>
<P>
   But studies have shown that being around animals can lower
people's blood pressure and otherwise reduce stress.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for pets in the workplace grew out of the success of
similar programs to bring animals to nursing homes, hospitals and
other settings for animal-assisted therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The animals in Dagg's program are not from the shelter, but are
already trained for animal-assisted therapy. They and their
handlers will typically have had about 25 hours of hands-on
coursework to make sure the animals are comfortable around people,
loving and interactive. Once the program is fully under way, Dagg
anticipates the animals will go to each workplace about once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies are letting animals come to work on a more
informal basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gaining in popularity here and there,'' said Maureen
Fredrickson, vice president of the Renton-based Delta Society, a
national organization that trains service animals for people with
disabilities, as well as handlers and animals for animal-assisted
therapy programs. ``As more information gets out about how animals
reduce stress, and more companies are trying to alleviate stress,
more companies are considering it.''
</P>
<P>
   But companies that try it have to be careful to respect the
needs of employees who don't like or are allergic to animals, she
said. The animals should always be kept away from people who don't
want to be near them.
</P>
<P>
   But many people enjoy seeing other's pets, she said. ``We see
people taking little stress breaks to play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some will ``borrow'' an animal to go for a walk. ``It's real
interesting to watch the office dynamics. It makes people much more
approachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, any pet who comes to work must have ``appropriate
business skills,'' she said. They must be controllable and under
control at all times. They can't interrupt people, and must be
clean and well-groomed. The animals also have to behave
appropriately around other office pets.
</P>
<P>
   Delta, for example, has between five and 10 dogs, three or four
birds, two or three rabbits and assorted cats reporting to work
every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't go hunting'' each other, she said. ``We've had one
or two swallowing incidents, luckily they were non-fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   The regular on-the-job pets tend to form their own office
families, she said. The dogs know not to bother the cats, and
vice-versa. Some of them even pal around together.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Americans With Disabilities Act, passed in 1994,
also has been a driving force in introducing more animals to the
workplace, Fredrickson said. ``Public places are experiencing
well-trained animals for the first time. People are seeing that the
animals don't bring in 4 million fleas or knock over the
merchandise, that animals can be well-behaved.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Richmond, of Richmond Public Relations Inc. in downtown
Seattle, brings 18-month-old Molly, a chocolate standard poodle, to
work on days the dog doesn't go with his wife, Betty Ann Richmond.
Betty Ann uses Molly as part of her therapy practice in Fremont.
</P>
<P>
   ``She humanizes the workplace,'' said Louis Richmond, who
renegotiated his lease to accommodate the dog and even has her sit
in on the occasional board meeting. ``People pet her in the
elevator all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And she draws attention on her walks through Seattle's city
streets, he said. ``What people do, more than anything, is they
smile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Smith is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. Her e-mail
address is carolsmith(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
