   SCOTUS-SEX _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ An explainer of the case
involving the Boca Raton lifeguards whom the Supreme Court ruled in
favor of in a sexual harassment case today. (Kleinberg, Palm Beach
Post)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HEAT _ Tracking statewide energy crisis and local impact of heat
wave; unstable hot air could gives us relief in the form of rain
this afternoon. Among checks, will see how the weather is affecting
farmers who may be the only ones truly happy with how things are
working out.(Chorpening/Kumar, Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   AMISH _ NEW HOLLAND, Pa. _ Eli's grandfather reckons that the
Amish are like other folks. ``We believe the best environment for
the Plain People is the farm,'' he explained, standing in a
well-ordered woodshop near fertile fields that his family has
cultivated for six generations. ``So just like you will save and
bend over backwards to send your children to college, we will save
and bend over backwards to help our sons and daughters buy a
farm.'' The problem for Eli's grandfather _ who does not want to be
identified further because of church strictures _ and the 36,000
other Plain Sect disciples in picturesque Lancaster County is that
developers are encroaching on farmland they have tended since
William Penn welcomed their persecuted forebears nearly three
centuries ago. (Dart, Cox News Service). A 1STLEDE MOVED Wednesday
in advance.
</P>
<P>
   FIRES _ Following developments in Ormond Beach, where fire still
threatens homes. (Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-BURNING _ All of Volusia County, Florida, is wrapped in
a thick cowl of smoke. It drifts among trees like a Carolina
morning mist. It hangs in the air, on clothes. It sears the eyes
and throat. Horses in paddocks shake their heads and stomp and pace
skittishly in the gritty gloom. ``The whole county's burning,''
says one of the three firefighters. (Reid, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-MAIN _ Update on numbers, what investigators know, any
developments. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-RULES _ Has the cluster of E. coli cases generated a push
to fast-track those pool regulations to get them on the books by
summer's end, do other states have such regulations, are there
other pool-related health problems (other than drowning) that
someone tracks? Can people check on a specific pool by calling
their county health department? (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ECOLI-SOLUTION _ An Atlanta-based company claims it has the
solution to E. coli outbreaks in the pool. It's a ``natural,''
copper-based solution that is non-toxic, EPA and FDA approved, and
can go into drinking water _and it kills bad bacteria, including E.
coli. (Lee, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-CONTROVERSY _ ATLANTA _ Allegations by a former Atlanta
policedeputy chief that top brass may have manipulated the city's
crime statistics is dividing the Atlanta Police department into
opposing camps. (Longa, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
