<HEADER>
A8573 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-WIND-HNS &LR;      06-26 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-WIND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GONE WITH THE WIND,' BUT NOT FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gone with the Wind'': It's immune from criticism.
</P>
<P>
   It is. Fifty-nine years after it was first released, this grand
old dame of American film is too plump with its own significance to
be judged by modern eyes. Too much time has passed since its
premiere _ too much history, too much celluloid, too many
thunderous shifts in pop culture and society. Acting has changed.
Movies have changed. Acceptance of racist and sexist stereotypes
has changed.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Gone with the Wind'' were a few years older, it would be
eligible for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost six decades after Rhett and Scarlett first swapped
insults in the Twelve Oaks library, the two of them are back at it
up on the big screen. And despite the yawning gaps between movies
then and movies now, producer David O. Selznick's vast, sumptuous
saga of love and loss in the Civil War is still an entertaining and
blisteringly sexy film.
</P>
<P>
   There's no nudity to speak of (except for a couple of swaddled
infants), and what kisses there are remain inflexibly
close-mouthed. But big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He smiles as though he knows what I look like without my
shimmy!'' gasps Scarlett (Vivien Leigh), voicing the subtext to
Clark Gable's famously crinkling leer. With Gable in a movie, no
one had to disrobe; his glance did it for them, with humor and
economy.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Gone with the Wind'' is, despite its nearly four-hour
running time (with intermission), an economical film. It wastes no
time in its fated pairings, its portrait of an Old South felled by
war or its tear-jerking obeisances to melodrama. The thing zooms.
Victor Fleming was a no-nonsense director, so we probably have him
to thank for the movie's fleet narrative although he was just one
of several people (Selznick and George Cukor included) who had a
hand in the film's direction. Production was infamously unwieldy
and cluttered with egos.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is, as ever, based on Margaret Mitchell's best-selling
novel about Scarlett O'Hara, the scrappy young daughter of an Irish
plantation owner (Thomas Mitchell) in pre-bellum Georgia. The film
opens on Scarlett's bickering with Mammy (Hattie McDaniel), her
flirtations with beaus and her undignified pleas to Ashley Wilkes
(Leslie Howard), a weak-spirited, whippet-thin dreamer who's about
to marry his cousin Melanie (Olivia De Havilland, saintly as ever)
but lusts after Scarlett nevertheless.
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett lusts right back. The film is all about desire, or the
lack of it there's plenty in her clutches with Ashley, none in her
marriages to two sad sacks, and quite enough to explode a warehouse
in her third, to Rhett. Underscoring lust are the movie's
brilliant, flame-red set-pieces: the burning of Atlanta, the
exhausted trek to Tara or those silhouettes of Scarlett against a
throbbing ruby sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``As God is my witness, I'll never be hungry again!'' she
swears, jiggling a radish at the heavens. Up swells Max Steiner's
effulgent Romantic music, signaling it's time to cry. It would be
sacrilege not to.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, after all, the dilemma: This movie is too well-loved
(by this moviegoer and by moviegoers in general) to rip apart.
Certain scenes inspire specific Pavlovian responses a knowing
laugh, a catch in one's breath, a gasp of suspense or a full-opera
sob of grief. A bonk on the head for anyone unfazed by the infamous
pony accident. But part of the joy in watching ``Gone with the
Wind'' is the sweet familiarity of it, like the moist scent of
perfume from a long-absent friend. To watch it again is to inhale a
cloud of nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of it will interest young audiences remains to be
seen. Why New Line Cinema chose to re-release ``Gone with the
Wind'' isn't entirely clear, but it might have something to do with
the millions of teen-age girls out there who shed fulsome tears
over ``Titanic'' presumably they're in the mood for another
star-crossed couple.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between the two films are striking and much
chewed-over (both are long, romantic epics set against backdrops of
massive human suffering), but just how those similarities will
translate into box office figures is hard to say. Will 13-year-olds
go ga-ga over Clark Gable's rough allure? Will pubescent boys do
back flips over Vivien Leigh? If not, who will pay to see it?
</P>
<P>
   Vintage-movie buffs. Viewers of a certain age. And, hopefully,
anyone of any age who enjoys the thrill of a terrific old film
which ``Gone with the Wind'' is, and always will be, regardless of
its standing as historical and cultural artifact.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The film looks and sounds gorgeous, thanks to a newly restored
print (the first to use the Technicolor dye process since 1961) and
a digitally remastered sound track. And although its square frame
looks jarringly boxy in a wide-screen multiplex, the tale is as
broad, as human and as minutely detailed as ever. Look there for
wounded Confederate soldiers lined up on the streets of Atlanta
(one out of three is a dummy); look there for Rhett and Scarlett's
hungry kiss against the rust-red sky outside Tara; look there for
the grand wine staircase where Scarlett argues with Rhett, then
falls.
</P>
<P>
   It's all there, right down to Mammy's rustling silk petticoat
(red again) and the nostalgic strains of ``Dixie.'' Unfortunately,
the film is nostalgic about Dixie there's no escaping its idealized
portrait of the master-slave relationship or the inherent racism in
some of its black characters.
</P>
<P>
   Prissy, the pip-voiced slave played by Butterfly McQueen, gets
the worst of it; she's portrayed as both stupid and boastful,
drawing harsh verbal rebukes and one nasty slap in the face from
the annoyed Miss Scarlett. The ``birthin' babies'' sequence does
not wear well. Nor does the movie's most celebrated scene, in which
a drunken Rhett threatens to crush Scarlett's head in his hands and
then carries her upstairs to rape her.
</P>
<P>
   This once qualified as romance (Scarlett coos kittenishly the
morning after); it now qualifies as domestic violence. Rhett Butler
is not a man made for post-feminist, late-20th-century world _ ``A
good lashing with a buggy whip would benefit you immensely,'' he
says _ and neither is Gable.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gable's schtick seems dated now, it was an appealing
movie fantasy: He embodied bullish masculinity scant years before
sex roles changed and culture veered toward the feminine. He was,
in a way, machismo's last hurrah.
</P>
<P>
   Scarlett herself is a tough chick independent, selfish,
ambitious, coquettish when it suits her and completely indifferent
to society's expectations. If Rhett is a retro-man, Scarlett is a
proto-feminist, a woman so unconfined by convention (she dances a
reel in mourning) that even her worst character flaws are proof of
a fiery rebel. Leigh's performance is all in the right eyebrow; it
waggles magnificently whenever Scarlett frets, or schemes, or plots
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   During a rare moment of self-doubt, Scarlett admits that she's
afraid of dying and going to hell. ``You look pretty healthy,''
soothes Rhett. ``And maybe there isn't any hell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scarlett needn't worry. So long as she as Rhett to snipe
at, Tara to run and radishes to wave, she'll always look healthy.
And she'll never go to hell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
