</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DECISIONS FAVOR VICTIMS OF SEX HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: REMOVES last clause beginning: and warned... in 8th graf
pvs.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court made it significantly harder
Friday for private and public employers to defend themselves
against sexual harassment charges by claiming they were unaware of
what lower-level supervisors were doing.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of 7-2 decisions, the court wrapped up its 1997-1998
term by ruling that employers cannot use this defense because the
federal civil rights law that bars employer sex discrimination or
harassment equates an employer with his or her ``agents'' or
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   So if a supervisor engages in harassment, the employer is
subject to ``vicarious liability,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices also made it more difficult for employers to claim
they are not liable in cases of threats by a supervisor to an
employee to have sex or else if the threats were not carried out
and the victim's career did not suffer.
</P>
<P>
   In its decisions, the court promulgated a new standard for
determining what kinds of defenses employers can raise in such
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person with supervisory authority discriminates in
terms and conditions of subordinates' employment, his actions
necessarily draw upon his superior position over people who report
to him,'' Justice David Souter wrote. ``An employee generally
cannot check a supervisor's abusive conduct the same way that she
might deal with abuse from a co-worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter's opinion involved charges by Beth Ann Faragher that when
she worked as a lifeguard in Boca Raton, Fla. between 1985 and
1990, supervisors had constantly made lewd remarks to her and had
engaged in ``uninvited and offensive touching.'' One supervisor
told her to ``date me or clean the toilets for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The other case involved a Chicago saleswoman, Kimberly Ellerth,
who quit her job with Burlington Industries Inc. in 1994 after 15
months because a supervisor had told her to ``loosen up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellerth's lawsuit said she quit because of the harassment by
Theodore Slowik, a New York-based vice president of sales and
marketing in her division. He actually supervised Ellerth's
supervisor but in the course of business dealt with her on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerth, now a homemaker in Belvidere, Ill., alleged that Slowik
touched her inappropriately and told offensive jokes. She said he
once told her, ``You know, Kim, I could make your life very hard or
very easy at Burlington.'' But he never followed through with the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court in that case, Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
found that Burlington was responsible. ``An employer is subject to
vicarious liability to a victimized employee for an actionable
hostile environment created by a supervisor with immediate (or
successively higher) authority over the employee.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``when no tangible employment action is taken, a
defending employer may raise an affirmative defense to liability or
damages, subject to proof by a preponderance of the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   But to succeed in such a defense, employers would have to show
they ``exercised reasonable care to prevent or correct promptly any
sexually harassing behavior'' and that ``the employee unreasonably
failed to take advantage of any preventive or corrective
opportunities provided by the employer or to avoid harm
otherwise,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia.
Thomas, writing for the two, said the court ``manufactures a rule
that employers are vicariously liable if supervisors create a
sexually hostile work environment, subject to an affirmative
defense that the court barely attempts to define.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas objected that the court's rule ``applies even if the
employer has a policy against sexual harassment, the employee knows
about the policy and the employee never informs anyone in a
position of authority about the supervisor's conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the high court made it much harder for students who
are sexually harassed by teachers to hold school districts
financially responsible. But that decision was based on a separate
federal law dealing with discrimination in education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's rulings revived Faragher's lawsuit against Boca
Raton, Fla., and kept alive Ellerth's suit against Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   The decision in the Burlington case conceivably could aid Paula
Jones' effort to revive her sexual-harassment lawsuit against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones accused Clinton of propositioning her when he was
Arkansas governor and she was a state employee. A federal judge,
relying on a standard imposed by the appeals court with
jurisdiction over Arkansas, threw out the lawsuit and said
employees can collect damages only if their refusal to submit to
sexual demands results in on-the-job retaliation.In Mrs. Jones'
case, the judge ruled that she had not shown any adverse on-the-job
consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
