r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEAVEN-HN     06-26 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-HEAVEN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEAVEN' LACKS VITALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Under Heaven'' is ``The Wings of the Dove'' set in late 20th
century America. As the Henry James novel has already been filmed
as is, it is easy to see how something in writer-director Meg
Richman's re-conception has let the air seep out of a pretty sexy
idea.
</P>
<P>
   As in the James novel, the set-up involves a poor girl whose
desires are not unreasonable. She merely wants the man she loves to
make enough money for them to marry. In this case, the girl is a
waitress named Cynthia (Molly Parker) and the guy is a drunken
loafer named Buck (Aden Young, a tall Australian good at accents
who plays another sex object in ``Cousin Bette'').
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with her boyfriend's torpor, Cynthia leaves him (could
Buck have been named a tad bit less obviously?) and takes a job
caring for a terminally ill and impossibly angelic young woman
named Eleanor (Joely Richardson). Eleanor is immensely rich, she
isn't going to live long, and she doesn't have any family. If
Cynthia plays her cards right, she calculates, she can get her
hands on some of that money.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ultimate plot isn't fully hatched at the start,
Cynthia introduces Buck to Eleanor with a lie. Hoping Eleanor will
hire Buck as a gardener, she says he is her half brother. She's
already described her ex-boyfriend as a screw-up, and why would
anyone hire a screw-up?
</P>
<P>
   Once Buck moves into the cottage on the estate, he and Cynthia
sneak about, hiding the true nature of their relationship. But soon
Buck's sympathy and hormones are aroused and it isn't long before
he and Eleanor have fallen madly in love.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor eventually figures out who Buck really is, which doesn't
dissuade her from wanting to marry him and leave him everything.
Cynthia begins to regret her folly but still believes she and Buck
can end up together with all of Eleanor's money. By the time this
is discussed in the movie, you don't really care what happens to
any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Richman's script and direction are sorely devoid of vitality,
which a story this emotionally and sexually convoluted must have to
work.
</P>
<P>
   That Buck, who customarily brought home dinner by shoplifting,
should suddenly develop a conscience at the end of the film seems a
bit farfetched. And that the movie should end with such sugary
sweetness belies all that came before it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
