<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-SIGHT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUT OF SIGHT,' OUT OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' is, like the terrific ``Get Shorty,'' based on
an Elmore Leonard novel and produced by Jersey Films. This time,
that teaming-up gave birth to a sad and deflated follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Scott Frank hit a home run with his ``Get Shorty''
adaptation. But he's brought down his batting average considerably
with this one. Perhaps, also, ``Out of Sight'' needed the energetic
and stylish hand of ``Get Shorty'' director Barry Sonnenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a sad-sackish Steven Soderbergh (``sex, lies and
videotape'') comes at this material looking as if his mind was on
something else, something much, much more depressing.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, a motion picture soundtrack reflects or enhances the
mood created by the picture itself. This is not the case here. The
jaunty music by David Holmes, reminiscent of the ``Get Shorty''
score, reminds us every time we hear it of what this movie
decidedly isn't. Interesting. Humorous. Upbeat. Succinct.
</P>
<P>
   The other big problem is that ``Out of Sight'' stars Bruce
Willis _ except George Clooney is playing him, and apart from the
fact that Clooney is wonderful to look at, he just doesn't wear a
smirk well. Willis looks cool when he says smarmy things with a
smile. Clooney just looks smarmy.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney plays Jack Foley, a recidivist bank robber who has been
busted many times. He is cheeky and, of course, handsome, but the
sad fact is that basically he is dumb, if you judge a person by how
well he learns from his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   When he botches a prison escape by throwing federal marshal
Karen Sisco (Jennifer Lopez) in the trunk of the getaway car, you
can't really figure out the sense of it. When he falls in love with
her while making small talk in the trunk together _ don't ask! _
the movie becomes a little too goofy for words. But when he decides
to take her along when they switch to a safer car, my faith in the
rest of the movie was seriously tested.
</P>
<P>
   The plot device of pushing a male criminal and a female law
enforcement officer together romantically is getting to be a habit.
We've seen it in ``Raising Arizona'' and ``Children of the
Revolution.'' But both of those were farces. ``Out of Sight'' is
filmed with a plodding ordinariness that precludes our just
suspending disbelief and going along for a kooky ride.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jack is regularly risking his freedom and
jeopardizing his next big job for the love of a woman who works for
the enemy, I had pretty much felt disinvited from entering the
fiction of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   With a lot of out of place slow-motion and freeze-frame
activity, Soderbergh seems to be trying for a stylish, almost
``Thomas Crown Affair'' look, but instead all the fancy footwork
serves to bog down the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Clooney, the movie is populated by a cast of great
actors. Ving Rhames, who is as fun to watch playing a villain as he
is doing the hero, plays Jack's best pal, Buddy. Don Cheadle is
Snoop, the psycho they know from prison. Albert Brooks, made up to
be bald and paunchy, is fine as an annoying white-collar criminal.
And Isaiah Washington, Catherine Keener and Steve Zahn are all good
in small parts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8622 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-INSOMNIAC     06-26 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-INSOMNIAC-HNS </SLUG>
  
 `INSOMNIAC' OFFERS A DREAMY DEBUT FOR DeBARTOLO  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARBARA SHULGASSER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writer-director Tiffanie DeBartolo's film debut is the admirable
``Dream for an Insomniac.'' Set in San Francisco (her father is
49ers owner Eddie DeBartolo), the story concerns an aspiring
actress named Francesca (Ione Skye), who is planning to move to Los
Angeles in 48 hours. Then she meets the love of her life and, in
the tradition of all great romances, everything is turned upside
down.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie works in Cafe Blue Eyes for her Uncle Leo (the affable
Seymour Cassel). She is an experienced insomniac and easily bored
by the men she dates. In other words, she is a tortured romantic in
the most fundamental sense: she believes that love isn't true if
not accompanied by blinding passion. When her uncle hires David
(MacKenzie Astin) as a counter man, she knows that she was right.
</P>
<P>
   David is an aspiring writer just in from the Midwest and he,
too, is immediately smitten. From the start, they are trying to
stump each other by citing arcane quotations. They can barely keep
their eyes off each other. Actually, who could blame them?
</P>
<P>
   Skye has an Ava Gardner slithery sultriness. She moves like a
cat, she smiles as if she knows showing her teeth is a lethal act.
It doesn't hurt that the cafe plays Sinatra music behind all that
slithering.
</P>
<P>
   Astin is as charming and beautiful as the young Gary Cooper. He
is a genetically perfect combination of his parents, Patty Duke and
John Astin, with a little Edward Burns thrown in. In fact, the best
reference would be to describe him as a happy Montgomery Clift.
</P>
<P>
   Frankie reads David's work, praises it and learns that he hasn't
written a word in ages. So they make a deal. He will try to cure
her insomnia and she will try to cure his writer's block. All of
the playful dialogue _ and this movie is joyfully full of talk _ is
handled well in DeBartolo's savvy script and given life by actors
who seem to truly embody the idealism of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, we know David is a catch when he reads Frankie a bedtime
story by Dr. Seuss. He's adorable. And so is she.
</P>
<P>
   And everywhere you turn, secondary characters are filling in the
slow moments with inspired performances. Jennifer Aniston is
terribly funny as Frankie's best friend and fellow actress, sliding
into accents, French, Southern, Larchmont Lockjaw and, just in case
she gets hired by a Toronto filmmaker, Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   For the obligatory dramatic tension there's cousin Rob (Michael
Landes), who can't tell Leo he's gay, and David's secret
girlfriend, Molly (Leslie Stevens), a perfectly nice girl who,
frankly, doesn't have a chance in a fairy tale like this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
