A8661 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CLINTON-FLAPS-0627     06-26 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CLINTON-FLAPS-0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DAY ONE IN CHINA: HOW THE SCRIPT WENT AWRY
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-0627.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ It was a scene so disagreeable that nobody could have
predicted it: a tough Chinese security man bellowing at two White
House valets on the tarmac outside Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   It happened at the Xi'an airport Friday, as President Clinton
was nearing the end of a day that already had the marks of a public
relations fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Before Air Force One reached Beijing, White House Press
Secretary Mike McCurry was accusing the Chinese security man of
mistreating the Clinton valets because ``these guys looked Asian.''
</P>
<P>
   Day One in the Middle Kingdom had been scripted by the White
House advance team as a glossy series of upbeat photo ops about
today's modern China. Apparently the idea was to give Americans the
tastiest possible appetizer Friday in advance of Saturday's
mouth-puckering images of Clinton in Tiananmen Square.
</P>
<P>
   Events started going off message when the three big
international news wires -- AP, AFP, Reuters -- began humming with
reports that three or four dissidents had been locked up in Xi'an
around the time of Clinton's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The reports originated with a Chinese exile living in Hong Kong.
He is Lu Siqing, a workahalic 35-year-old computer programmer who
makes a sidelight of faxing reports to Western news agencies about
dissidents harassed or jailed inside China.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton in China, all three wires moved small items Friday
morning on Lu's unconfirmed information about the Xi'an dissidents'
detention.
</P>
<P>
   The story escalated when a White House pool reporter asked
Clinton about it during the president's visit to discuss village
elections at Xiahe. That's when Clinton uttered his most newsworthy
words of Day One -- that if true, the news stories were
``disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   This one word swelled into a sandstorm of correspondents' follow
up questions during a daily news briefing by White House officials
at Xi'an's Shangri-la Golden Flower Hotel. That was where White
House national security adviser Sandy Berger let fly with charges
that China's detention of the dissidents was ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons had finally smiled their final adieus in Xi'an and
ascended the big ramp onto Air Force One when an American radio
pool reporter heard some loud shouting on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Chinese security man shouting at two Filipino-American
valets on the White House staff. With Air Force One about to take
off, there wasn't time for the White House press pool to straighten
out exactly why the Chinese security man was upset.
</P>
<P>
   What was clear was that the valets were trying to load the
Clintons' garment bags onto the plane until the security man
temporarily prevented them from boarding. The contretemps seems to
have ended when a Chinese-speaking American staffer showed up and
vouched for the two valets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese security guy said the baggage was the problem,''
McCurry told reporters after Air Force One was airborne. ``Our
security people said it didn't look to them like that was the
problem. It looked to them like the problem was that those guys
looked Asian.''
</P>
<P>
   If McCurry's interpretation is accurate, it suggests that the
Chinese agent may have been afraid the president was sneaking some
wanted dissidents aboard the presidential jet. Another possibility,
of course, is that the valets were suspected of smuggling out some
of Xi'an's famous antiquities.
</P>
<P>
   What really happened may remain an oriental mystery. So far as
was known early Saturday, none of the Americans who witnessed the
fracas spoke Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
