<HEADER>
A8663 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESEND-NEWS-QUESTIONS     06-26 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESEND-NEWS-QUESTIONS1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: But it isn't cola that has had caffeine added to it,
and then has been processsed again to take the caffine back out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At the recent meeting of the Southern Baptist Convention, a
statement was adopted stating that wives should submit graciously
to their husbands, and the husbands would provide for, protect and
lead their families. How many of those voting were female?
</P>
<P>
   A: An exact breakdown isn't available. The total number of
``messengers,'' as those attending conventions are called, was
8,586. No roll call was taken at the time of the vote on the
marriage and family statement, said Art Tolston of Baptist Press in
Nashville. So it isn't known precisely how many people were in the
hall at that time, ``let alone how many were men or women,'' he
told Q&AMP;A. The vote was taken by a show of hands, and was described
as being ``overwhelming'' in favor of the statement's adoption,
Tolston added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have dual questions dealing with the NBA. What team did
Phil Jackson, coach of the Chicago Bulls, play for in his pro
career? Also, during the Indiana Pacers series, why were the Pacers
wearing black armbands?
</P>
<P>
   A: The son of a minister, Jackson studied religion at the
University of North Dakota, where he also was a two-time
All-American. He spent 11 years with the New York Knicks, where he
was a member of the 1970 and 1973 championship teams as a backup to
center Willis Reed, and two years as an assistant coach/player with
the New Jersey Nets. The Pacers' armbands were worn in memory of
Bill Hart, longtime team employee and, most recently, its equipment
manager. Hart died of cancer April 14 at age 73.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was announced recently that a Swiss and American venture
was planning to finance and build a full-size replica of the
Titanic. Any details?
</P>
<P>
   A: Actually there are two competing plans for a new Titanic.
White Star Line Ltd., a company set up by a consultancy firm based
on Basle, Switzerland, and Las Vegas financiers, says it wants to
build such a ship and launch it on a maiden voyage from
Southampton, England, to New York in April 2002. That would be
exactly 90 years after the original set sail. The firm has held
talks with Northern Ireland's Harland and Wolff, builders of the
original Titanic, and said in May it was hoping to sign a deal
within several months on a preplanning phase for the project. The
replica's exterior would look like the original Titanic, but it
would have modern engines, instrumentation and safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a company based in South Africa, RMS Titanic Shipping
Holdings, also has announced plans for a Titanic replica. It would
be built in Durban, South Africa, to the ``exact specifications''
of the original, but with high-tech engines, navigation and global
communications facilities. The vessel would make its initial voyage
Dec. 29, 1999, a date the company called ``the eve of the new
millennium.'' The South Africa company said Harland and Wolff would
be consultants on the project.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies admit that their interest in constructing a new
Titanic was fueled by the phenomenal success of the blockbuster
Oscar-winning movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article listed 29 winners of MacArthur Foundation
``genius grants.'' I've also heard the MacArthurs mentioned
frequently as contributors to National Public Radio. Who are or
were they?
</P>
<P>
   A: John D. MacArthur (1897-1978) developed and owned Bankers
Life and Casualty Co. When he died, he was one of the three
wealthiest men in the United States and was sole owner of the
nation's largest privately held insurance company. In the 1960s,
MacArthur branched out into real estate and development. Over the
years, his holdings have included 100,000 acres in Florida,
primarily in the Palm Beach and Sarasota areas; several development
companies and shopping centers; paper and pulp companies; 19
commercial, office and apartment buildings in New York City;
several publishing enterprises; radio and TV stations; banks and 12
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Catherine T. MacArthur (1909-81), was intimately
involved in her husband's business, starting by keeping the books.
When he bought Bankers Life and Casualty Co. of Chicago in 1935,
she created the business procedures that would be used until
tremendous growth finally made them obsolete. In the records of the
various companies, she appears almost anonymously under her maiden
name (C.T. Hyland) in the positions of corporate secretary,
director or both.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the world population now? I keep seeing and hearing
varying numbers, some as high as 100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the U.S. Census Bureau's International Programs
Center, the total population of the world, projected to 18:28:47
GMT (2:28:47 p.m. EDT) June 16, was 5,923,383,463. They figure that
every second, five people are born and two people die, a net gain
of three people. If you have Internet access, you can keep up with
the World Population Clock at this site:
www.census.gov/cgi-bin/ipc/popclockw
</P>
<P>
   Q: A radio commentator said June 16 is ``Soweto Day,'' but
didn't explain what it was all about. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: Also known as International Day of Solidarity With the
Struggling People of South Africa, Soweto Day is sponsored by the
United Nations. It commemorates the start of the uprising in the
huge South African township of Soweto in 1976, when a student
protest led to clashes with police in which hundreds of people were
killed. When it was begun, Soweto Day's aim was to protest outrage
at South Africa's apartheid policies.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   NYT-06-24-98 1716EDT
</P>
