<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Managing editors, weekend editors)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features.
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, where indicated, have been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEWS AND FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-LUTHERANS-NYT (Undated) _ In a decision that ends a
divisive chapter of the Reformation, the Vatican said the Catholic
Church will sign a joint declaration with the world's Lutherans
that affirms that Catholics and Lutherans share a basic
understanding of how people receive salvation. The document,
approved last week by the Lutheran World Federation, declares that
Catholics and Lutherans have common ground to overcome the issue
that split the Western Christian world nearly 500 years ago _ the
question of whether `justification' comes solely through faith in
God, as Luther held, or whether a person's good works also play a
role, as Catholics emphasized. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 6-25.
</P>
<P>
   PREACHER-TEACHER-NYT (New York) _ Mildred Rosario was dismissed
as a substitute public school teacher after she admitted leading
her class in prayer and asking if anyone would accept Jesus. Now
she has emerged as an unlikely cause celebre, drawing the attention
of not only religious-minded parents and clerical leaders in New
York but also House Speaker Newt Gingrich and the conservative
Rutherford Institute. By Jacques Steinberg with Macarena Hernandez.
Moved 6-25.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-RELIGION-HNS (Washington) _ Conservative Republicans led
by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay called for the reinstatement
Thursday of a New York City substitute teacher who was fired for
allegedly sharing her Pentecostal beliefs with her students to help
them deal with the death of a classmate. By Greg McDonald. Moved
6-25.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RELIGION-COX (Beijing) _ China's Christians must choose:
restricted legal worship or underground risks. China controls all
Christian groups by forcing them to register as social
organizations, regulating what they preach and arresting or
detaining those who cross the government-drawn line of acceptable
religious practice. Both Protestants and Catholics must be part of
China's `patriotic' religious movement, which means they cannot
align with a foreign-based church. By Marcia Kunstel and Joseph
Albright. Moved 6-24 for 6-28.
</P>
<P>
   With sidebar: CHINA-HISTBOX-COX (Beijing) _ How China's
personality for the last two millennia has been shaped by
religions. By Joseph Albright and Marcia Kunstel. Moved 6-25 for
6-28.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-SUCCESSOR-NYT (Vienna) _ As the 78-year-old pope's health
declines, Vatican watchers cannot resist studying the roster of
cardinals for the few who could be tapped as his successor. A name
often mentioned is that of Cardinal Christoph Schoenborn, the
53-year-old leader of the deeply divided church in Austria. By
Alessandra Stanley. Moved 6-23.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-JEWISH-CEMETERY-NYT (Kalisz, Poland) _ A well-worn school
playground, where hard sports have left more dirt than grass but
that was once the site of a venerated Jewish cemetery, has prompted
a bitter dispute between Jewish organizations and the Polish
authorities. Jewish leaders say they that a distinguished
17th-century rabbi, Abraham Abele Gombiner, is buried beneath the
soccer field. They say it is an affront to the Jewish religion that
the body of such an important figure, whose legal works and
biblical commentaries are still in use, should be left in such a
sacrilegious way. By Jane Perlez. Moved 6-23. WITH GRAPHIC MAP.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-RELIGION-NYT (New York) _ A year after the U.S.
Supreme Court ruled that public school teachers in New York City
could hold remedial and other supplementary classes inside
religious schools, rather than in oversize vans off the school
grounds, school and union officials say there have been no
complaints from those teachers. By Jacques Steinberg. Moved 6-21.
</P>
<P>
   PRESBY-GUNS-NYT (Undated) Striking an unusally personal note in
the national debate on gun control, the top policy-making body of
the Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.) has passed a resolution calling on
the denomination's 2.6 million members to `work toward removing
handguns and assault weapons' from their homes and communities.
Presbyterian officials and other church leaders said the assembly's
resolution takes a new tack in asking directly for individual
action by church members, rather than seeking governmental
legislation. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 6-19.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-SEX-VIOLENCE-NYT (Undated) _ U.S. Roman Catholic bishops
issued an appeal Friday to the entertainment industry and the
government to reduce the public portrayal of sex and excessive
violence. Saying that pornography and images of violence `gravely
harm the moral and psychological health' of society, the bishops
offered a mixture of criticism and encouragement, specifically
warning about the use of the Internet to distribute obscenity and
prejudice, while also declaring that parents have more influence
over their children than they may realize. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved
6-19.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA-POPE-NYT (Vienna) _ Seeking to restore discipline to
Austria's deeply divided Roman Catholic Church, Pope John Paul II
instructed the country's bishops Sunday to stop their public
bickering. Without unity, the pope warned, `the teachings of Christ
dissolve into many individual voices. In the place of harmony comes
noisy confusion.' By Alessandra Stanley. Moved 6-21.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-AUSTRIA-NYT (Salzburg) _ Pope John Paul II, on a visit to
Austria, appeals to Austrians not to allow the sex scandal
involving the former archbishop to Vienna to turn them away from
the church. By Alessandra Stanley. Moved 6-19.
</P>
<P>
   POPE-AUSTRIA-NYT (Vienna) _ Speaking to a group of Austrian
officials and dignitaries that included former President Kurt
Waldheim, Pope John Paul II said Saturday that European Christians
had a moral obligation to fully reconcile with the Jews. By
Alessandra Stanley. Moved 6-20.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (New York) _ A touring statue of Pope John
Paul II by Polish sculptor Maksymilian Biskupski will adorn the
grounds of a Catholic shrine off Route 31 in Washington, N.J., for
the next six months. By Gustav Niebuhr. Moved 6-19.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS (Undatd) _ The Rev. Stephen Ayres, vicar of
the historic Old North Church in Boston's North End, tries to make
sure that people realize that one of America's most famous churches
is not a museum but home to a living, worshiping congregation. By
Diego Ribadeneira. Moved 6-24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
