<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-26 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGELESS WILLIE BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- John Updike and Willie L. Brown Jr., who live
and work three time zones apart, share the same fountain-of-youth
formula. Updike's curmudgeonly character Bech has a new female
companion in a New Yorker short story: ``He was 74, but they worked
with that. Seventy-four plus 26 was 100; divided by two that was
50, the prime of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's formula is also mathematical and fictional. The mayor of
San Francisco is what society writers called ``a man about town.''
``The rule of 100,'' which he learned in Sacramento from
gallivanting colleagues in the Legislature, specified of companions
that ``if our age and their age equals 100, they are too old.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, now 64, still gets around and still seems to be
having a good time. To those who wonder how he gets around the rule
of 100, he replies, ``I lie a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Updike's Bech had ``planted a flickering wedge of doubt beneath
the threshold of consciousness and brought down a media-savvy
smart-ass.'' Such a plan might succeed in New Yorker fiction but
not in San Franciscan reality. Brown is deadly earnest when talking
about the politics of his state or the economics of his city. But
even in the daytime, a touch of mischief flavors his conversation.
</P>
<P>
   On the political future of California:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the state is becoming increasingly centrist. I don't
think it's becoming more liberal, and I don't think it's becoming
more conservative. The advent of racial minorities participating in
greater numbers at the ballot box is offsetting the enormous
influence that the conservative majority has had in this state by
disproportionate voting. But it's not enough to move it to the
liberal side. It's simply enough to stop the slide toward
right-wingism.''
</P>
<P>
   On the 1998 gubernatorial election between Republican Dan
Lungren, whom Brown calls ``formidable,'' and Democrat Gray Davis,
whom Brown endorsed early:
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Gray has always had gray hair. When he was a kid, he
had gray hair. He's identical, same as he was years ago, physically
and otherwise. ... Lungren has transformed himself into this
charming, delightful, self-effacing, self-deprecating candidate. I
do believe that the public forgets the original Dan Lungren, and
the public must know that this new Dan Lungren is not a genetic
transformation. It is a cosmetic adjustment. ... It's going to be a
very close gubernatorial election. But Gray Davis is going to win
it.''
</P>
<P>
   On his city 10 years from now, after he is term-limited out of
office:
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco by the year 2008 will have all of the public
improvements that were initiated now totally and completely
functional. The 26 gates at the international airport will be
there. The new runway will be virtually finished. ... In Mission
Bay there will be 7,200 new living units as well as 5 million
square feet of biotech, retail and multimedia space. ... Also, by
then we will have upgraded the quality of public transportation out
of pure necessity. This city by then will be sparkling. We will
have no school older than about 10 years, because to renew our
schools, we pass bond issue after bond issue. Our libraries will
all have been renewed by then. ... The then-mayor will be a
caretaker of a municipal structure that will rival the best parts
of Paris in terms of its physical appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Paris? That's ambitious, and there's also something Cartesian in
the way Willie Brown thinks, the way he follows up a faux pas with
an initiative, the way his outspokenness balances his
accomplishments:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't start out to make mistakes. When I get in trouble by
virtue of my conduct, it usually is of the same proportion as my
successes.''
</P>
<P>
   On his own reelection contest in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure somebody will run. The more the merrier, maybe nine.
I want at least a baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The opposing team's lineup card is currently blank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
