<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8712 &Cx1f; taf-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINDOWS-PROVES-TO-BE-     06-26 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINDOWS-PROVES-TO-BE-A-PAIN-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WINDOWS PROGRAM PROVES PROBLEMATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 1998 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Windows 98, the eagerly awaited upgrade for the Windows 95
operating system, went on sale this week. But Windows 95 users who
have tried out a wide variety of software and hardware over the
past few years risk system crashes when they install the upgrade.
These ``power users'' may find their PCs become trapped in a
no-man's-land where neither Windows 95 nor Windows 98 works.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 300 million PCs in use today worldwide, 130 million run
Windows 95. The owners of these machines can now upgrade to Windows
98, which they buy on a CD-ROM. The software takes around an hour
to install. Before replacing Windows 95, it checks whether the
hardware and software already on the machine are compatible with
the new system. But this check may not identify one key problem.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95 relies on a ``registry'' _ an electronic index that
is automatically updated as the user adds or removes programs or
hardware. Windows 98 has a similar registry. The upgrade software
builds this by converting the records stored by Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But if the registry is large and complex, it may contain
inaccurate entries that the preupgrade check does not recognize.
Windows 98 then cannot build its new registry and so tries to run a
``plug-and-play'' check, in which it searches for all installed
hardware and software on the PC.
</P>
<P>
   This can take many minutes and can cause the PC to crash. It is
then unusable until all its software is reloaded from scratch onto
another part of the hard disc. Even then, Windows 98 cannot use
previously stored data and settings.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson from Microsoft's technical support team says it
has heard of the problem from power users who have installed test
versions of Windows 98. However, a spokeswoman says the company has
no plans to issue any special warnings. ``We expect consumers to
check that their PCs can run new software before using it,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   David Weeks, product marketing manager for Windows in Britain,
says that users who experience problems can get free technical help
from Microsoft's support line for 90 days after they first hit
trouble. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
