<HEADER>
A8718 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-26 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFINITI DOES A LITTLE BETTER WITH LATEST G20 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R. WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Infiniti showed off its latest generation entry-level luxury car
this week, choosing the grandeur of Boston's Museum of
Transportation as the setting for its newest jewel, the 1999 G20.
The G20 has, in past incarnations, been among this columnist's
least favorite cars. That may change.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, the new G20 has a real back seat, a bench that will
accommodate real people with real knees who wish to sit upright.
We're talking knee room with the front seat fully extended to the
rear, not what you might get if the driver were a midget. In
keeping with the added rear room is added rear entry room, a larger
door opening.
</P>
<P>
   I dwell on the rear accommodation because it was the back of the
G20 that most distressed in previous editions. The cramped rear, in
concert with a stiff suspension _ in the rear, bordering on vicious
one year _ that made one wonder why anyone would part with luxury
money for that very un-luxury cabin.
</P>
<P>
   The new G20 suspension is still an unknown on the road, at least
unknown to me, but Nissan, the mother company to Infiniti, claims
great strides forward. It is obvious that great strides have been
undertaken in several departments.
</P>
<P>
   The new G20 looks like an Infiniti for a change instead of an
overweight Sentra. There is a grace to the shape, a logic to the
interior layout, and styling allure front and rear. The current
edition is based upon a European model, the Primera, Infiniti says,
and is available in standard and touring variants. A
140-horsepower, 2.0-liter, 16-valve 4-cylinder supplies the power
delivering it through either a 5-speed, manual gearbox or a
4-speed, electronically controlled, automatic transaxle. The new
model comes with side air bags for safety and a Bose sound system
for your soul.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti is pinning high hopes on the front-drive G20, aiming
for US sales of 18,000 units, a considerable leap over the
13,000-plus sales last achieved by G20 and somewhat higher than the
peak annual sales total of 17,300-plus. It's aimed at the youthful
driver, Infiniti says, and it seemed to awaken the youth in more
than one of us among the New England Motor Press Association on
hand for the unveiling. A full-scale road test is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   General Motors continues to carom away from common sense. Since
last we left GM, the company, having convinced a corps of Wall
Street analysts that profits were continuing up and boosted
short-term sales results with coupons and incentives, has provoked
a crippling strike, blamed it on the employees, announced drastic
cash conservation programs, initiated moves to create another layer
of management, signed a deal to build trucks and sport/utilities in
China, intimated to its employees that it is ``losing $50 million a
year,'' and announced a Cadillac 2-seat roadster.
</P>
<P>
   GM, after lengthy bickering in Flint, moved dies out of a
stamping plant over a weekend, thus fueling union suspicions that
the company intended to move the Flint operation to Mexico, thus
provoking a walkout. The Flint shutdown was the first in a chain of
dominoes that have virtually crippled GM production and threatened
new-model introductions.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, while demanding new work rules and blue-collar
reductions, the General has come up with still another
management-fattener: GM will promote its brand managers to
positions of authority heretofore reserved for the division
managers and move division managers aside _ at least that's the
picture offered in the trade press. ``Brand management'' is the
buzzword these days, so it was only a matter of time until GM's
recruits from the ranks of diapers and cookies be elevated. This,
you may recall, is a company that while nearly halving its market
share and reducing its blue-collar work force, has added another
division _ read that as added management.
</P>
<P>
   While denying any intention to move Flint work to Mexico, GM has
signed an agreement with the world's lowest-wage country, China, to
build light trucks and SUVs _ that's in addition to the agreement
to build Buick Regals there, a car for which every Chinese over 16
lusts, right?
</P>
<P>
   I do recall some years back when GM's Bob Stempel, briefly the
CEO after Roger Smith retired, denied that Buick production had
been moved to Mexico, then explained that all 50,000 Mexican-built
A-body cars (which he had just told me weren't made in Mexico) were
bought by Mexicans. Yes, an economy that at the time barely
supported 400,000 car sales annually suddenly snapped up an
additional 50,000 new cars. Strangely, though, everybody else in
that Washington, D.C., room believed him!
</P>
<P>
   If you dial into the GM propaganda line _ 800-546-0709 _ you can
hear the GM litany for yourself and learn how the company is
instigating unprecedented ``cold shutdowns'' to avoid utility bills
in idle plants, is losing $50 million a year (presumably at Flint),
is in a crisis mode to conserve cash. And it's all the union's
fault. I hope those analysts spin that dial.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Cadillac 2-seater is to get a Northstar V-8
engine, be heavier and shorter than a Corvette, be shown ``with
production intent'' at the Paris auto show, and be a competitor for
such as Mercedes _ assuming GM doesn't melt down first. Maybe they
could call it Allante. Remember that Cadillac 2-seater? It took the
world by yawn and was killed as soon as GM got it right. General,
if you would survive, it is time to start trimming management,
jettison a few excess divisions, and stop beating up on the labor
force. Maybe if you listened more to the men and women who build
the cars instead of the accountants who cheapen them, the market
slide might slow down. Or maybe even turn around. It worked for
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1520EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
