<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV28-BO     06-26 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS SONG OF THE OPEN ROAD IS A DIESEL VOLUNTARY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, June 28 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What does an automotive columnist who drives constantly for a
living do on vacation?
</P>
<P>
   A) Lock the garage and hide.
</P>
<P>
   B) Pitch a tent on an uninhabited island.
</P>
<P>
   C) Enter a couple of stock car races.
</P>
<P>
   D) Become a cross-country truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the above came in a telephone call from the museum
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've decided to take the car to Colorado after all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How will you get it there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``With our new trailer, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pulled by ...?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dodge diesel that Chrysler lent us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I understand that, but pulled by who? Who's driving?''
</P>
<P>
   A silent pause ensues, followed by: ``Well ... I'm flying out.
... Expectant pause.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how D) became the answer to the original question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The car to be taken is a 1910 Model 70 Stanley Steamer owned by
the Stanley Museum, Kingfield, Maine _ the museum is the ``us'' to
whom Chrysler has given the use of a truck for the summer. The
destination is the new branch of the Stanley Museum at the Stanley
Hotel in Estes Park, Colo. The reason the Model 70 is being shipped
there is not to add to the artifacts on display but to participate
in a ``steam tour'' organized to celebrate the dedication of the
new branch museum. The artifact being preserved in this case is the
steam automotive technology rather than the steam car itself.
</P>
<P>
   You see, in 1909, F.O. Stamley, twin of F.E. who invented the
Stanley car (and a lot of other stuff), having found the Colorado
mountain clime conducive to restoring his health, built this
massive hotel _ and most of the rest of what made Estes Park tick:
bank, power company, clinic, roads, etc. That, in a nutshell, is
why there is a branch of a Maine museum in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The ``who'' of all this, you realize, is the columnist who,
equipped with a jar of peanut butter, a half-gallon of lemonade, a
loaf of bread, a kitchen knife, a blanket, a pillow, and an AAA
Road Atlas, set forth in a Dodge Ram diesel behemoth towing an
enclosed trailer, destination Estes Park some 2,400 give-or-take
miles distant. This is what becomes of being a museum
``volunteer.'' I had always wanted a long run in a diesel Dodge; I
had always wanted a cross-country road trip _ but not necessarily
together and not this badly.
</P>
<P>
   The truck is a beauty, a big red Dodge Ram 2500 with a 24-valve
Cummins diesel throbbing under the hood. The beauty, however, has
been specced (pronounced specked, meaning ordered with specific
equipment) by a teenager. The museum requested an expanded cab
model; this is a regular cab _ my gear is going into the trailer.
Museum asked for 2WD model with automatic; Big Red is 4WD with a
5-speed manual. The 16-inch chrome wheels look puny, out of place
on this monster _ but, it has a CD player.
</P>
<P>
   Day One: The truck has been prepared with auxiliary brake
control for the 22-foot-long-only-God-knows-how-tall Haulmark
trailer and said trailer loaded with steamer, tools, spare parts,
tires, pilot fuel, etc., by the heavy-lifting volunteers of the
Maine museum. Glenn Byron briefs me on the operation of the brake
auxiliary.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 seconds into the trip, I realize that the dual power
mirrors on this truck, though large indeed, are useless for seeing
around a trailer since they don't extend far enough. This becomes
an acute consideration when I miss a turn off Maine's Route 4 and
find myself on a road to nowhere with no option for reversing
direction other than to pull into a driveway and back out.
</P>
<P>
   I pick the wrong driveway, soon find myself sliding toward A) an
embankment and B) a car as the back wheels slip on loose gravel.
Suddenly, I am extremely grateful for the 4WD as I slip the
transfer case into the 4WD-low range mode. The front wheels grab,
the Ram inches the trailer rerarward, bending it toward the highway
_ a woman appears in the window of the house that goes with the
driveway. I smile broadly, wave as if I knew her. That trailer is a
22-foot billboard for the Stanley Museum; I hope she's friendly and
has a sense of humor. She smiles. I'm on the road again. That
evening, I pull into my own driveway; I have covered a mere 151.6
miles. Four days hence, I must be in Estes Park.
</P>
<P>
   Day Two: Before going anywhere, I start hunting bigger mirrors.
A Dodge dealer can supply extended mirrors suitable for a trailer,
but that sacrifices the power option for manual operation _ plus
they cost around $180, and it will take a day or two to get them. I
opt to hit the road with a couple of add-ons from U-Haul attached
by an ingenious clamp that's mainly heavy rubber straps _ less than
$25. Not perfect, but they add that extra measure of visibility and
safety.
</P>
<P>
   I decide to head west on Interstate 90, a well patrolled toll
road through Massachusetts and New York, rather than head through
Pennsylvania for Interstate 80. In Ohio, I'll take I-71 southwest
to I-70 west toward Denver. Compared to the museum's old trailer,
the Trailer from Hell, the new double-axle Haulmark is a thing of
beauty and a joy on the road. Relativelty speaking. There isn't
much joy as the wind picks up blowing broadside.
</P>
<P>
   The Ram has extra sound-deadening to muffle the diesel rattle
and rumble; you might as well be trying to muffle a rock concert.
But, when you settle into the 2,000 rpm groove and coast along in
overdrive at 65, that rumbly rattle is a comfort. The seat in this
thing is very good, offering good back support, thigh comfort. I
stop now and then to stretch, to refill the 34-gallon fuel tank, to
take care of other ncessities of the road. At a rest stop near
Rochester, N.Y., I decide I've about had enough for the day, find a
quiet spot to park the rig, clear the bench seat, break out the
blanket and pillow. There is almost room enough to stretch out full
length. Almost. Still it is comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a 447-mile day. Only 598.7 miles of this trip have
been accomplished leaving a long road ahead. It will prove to be an
interesting road. You're welcome to ride along again in next week's
column.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For the on-line browsers, I'll be available to chat on line
about cars Tuesdays, 2 p.m. to 3 p.m. Just point your Internet
browser to http://www.boston.com and enter the keyword chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
