<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARCADIA-CLUB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACED WITH TRIPLED RENT, ARCADIA GENTLY SLIPS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 28)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was very civilized,'' said Joan Rivers, a regular,
who called from London to commiserate. ``It's just a shame it
wasn't noisy enough for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Saturdays ago, like spring shad, Arcadia, the 14-year old
American restaurant at 21 E. 62nd St. slipped away and disappeared.
Executive chef and co-owner Anne Rosenzweig closed the restaurant
after unarcadian negotiations with her landlord for a new lease
failed.
</P>
<P>
   The urbane little dining room, with its pastoral mural of the
four seasons by Paul Davis, had been a retreat and a refuge for its
well-heeled neighborhood and its well-heeled clientele, including
many fashion folks, since its opening in 1984. It established Ms.
Rosenzweig as a culinary star.
</P>
<P>
   But to regular customers, of whom there were many, Arcadia was a
home and Ms. Rosenzweig and her staff were family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heartbroken; I just sort of depended on it,'' said
Geoffrey Beene, the fashion designer, who ate there once a week.
``It had the most wonderful atmosphere _ hidden away, fancy but not
fancy, which is hard to attain in New York. I love restaurants like
that; they're becoming fewer and fewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige Rense, the editor in chief of Architectural Digest, ate at
Arcadia three times a week. ``It was my neighborhood hangout,'' she
said. ``I ran into people I knew _ it was like a club. I could
never quite figure out why the room was successful. But it was very
simple. The banquettes faced each other. You always had the feeling
that you knew who was there, but it wasn't `living theater.'''
</P>
<P>
   William Lauder, whose family frequented Arcadia, said: ``It made
me think of my dining room in my own country house. I'll miss it
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of reservations in the restaurant's final week
were people trying to squeeze themselves in before the close. Not
all were regulars. One couple, arriving on the last night, June 20,
had never been before; in front of Arcadia, they asked themselves
whether they had found it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this it?'' he asked her, as though the open french doors
and casual candlelight and quiet sidewalk scene couldn't be the
institution they had come looking for.
</P>
<P>
   After a terrific thunderstorm, which cracked the sky like a
whip, Saturday became a beautiful evening, the kind of evening that
Arcadia was famous for: effort that resulted in ease. Chefs don't
cry; they sweat. From the five tables set outside, under Arcadia's
awning, 8 o'clock was as blue as the water that fresh fish come
from. The restaurant's air-conditioning system had quit the day
before. Sean Stevens, the maitre d'hotel, seated only the front
four tables by the windows and the tables outside. The muraled
dining room was empty, as though it had already passed into memory.
</P>
<P>
   The largest table was regulars, Joan and David Helpern, of Joan
&AMP; David shoes, with their guests Eleanor Lambert, the arbiter of
best-dressed, and Ms. Lambert's son and daughter-in-law, visiting
from San Francisco. The Helperns had come three nights running
since learning that the restaurant was closing. Ms. Helpern and Ms.
Lambert sat outside with Ms. Rosenzweig before leaving, showing the
interest and pride of women with a successful daughter. Ms.
Rosenzweig shared her recipe for vinaigrette, then made them leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I get into trouble with their families,'' she said,
protectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad to see it go,'' said Ms. Lambert, walking in her
silver Belgian evening slippers beside Ms. Rosenzweig in her red
chef's clogs, toward the long black Lincoln Town Car. ``Because it
was a perfect restaurant. It was a small restaurant run like a very
big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Diminutive and shy despite her professional stature, it is hard
not equate Ms. Rosenzweig with Arcadia. Faced with a lease demand
for a tripled rent, Arcadia's failure to survive has saddened her.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, there's a certain gentleness here that's reflective of
that time when we opened,'' she said, ``that I don't feel now. It's
harsher. I don't know that I would try to open something like
Arcadia today.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rosenzweig wished the last table departing a happy birthday.
``Good luck,'' they called. Then, like a captain going down with
the ship, she took her place behind Arcadia's bar and made
Cosmopolitans for the staff.
</P>
<P>
   The busboys hustled the last pail of garbage, as if in a
three-legged sack race, through the crowd to the street. A cheer
went up for the ``last parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartender Patrick Donovan pretended to answer the telephone from
which Stevens took Arcadia's reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Table for two?'' he asked. ``No problem. I have a lovely
corner table for you,'' he said. ``See you on Monday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
