<HEADER>
A8748 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV28-     06-26 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHASTA DAISIES: IDEAL TENANTS FOR GARDEN VACANCIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 28)  
 (bl)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 &HT;    It is said that Luther Burbank, the horticulturist and plant
breeder, made 65,000 unsuccessful crosses between berry varieties
before finding the one that produced a white blackberry. Except for
the inherent value to botanical science, I'm not sure it was worth
the trouble.
 &HT;    But there is a Burbank creation worth whatever effort it took to
achieve: the Shasta daisy.
 &HT;    Shasta daisies are the glue that holds a summer perennial garden
together. Tall varieties provide a tranquil backdrop to the intense
blue of delphiniums; dwarf varieties temper the fiery scarlet of
Maltese cross.
 &HT;    I plant them in clumps or drifts wherever the garden has a
vacancy. All have sturdy dark-green foliage and flowers with
glistening white petals and yellow centers. Shasta daisies are as
classic as a Greek column, as classy as pearl earrings. They look
good with everything.
 &HT;    Although taxonomists have changed the genus to Leucanthemum,
Shasta daisies are often listed as Chrysanthemum x superbum,
sometimes C. maximum. Technically, C. maximum is one of the species
Burbank used to create the Shasta about a hundred years ago, along
with the Portuguese daisy (C. lacustre), the Nippon daisy (C.
nipponicum) and several other daisy species. How he did it and what
species he used are not known. Burbank wasn't much for keeping
detailed notes.
 &HT;    But his colleagues in the plant-breeding business, knowing a
good thing when they saw it, have continued developing Shasta
daisies.
 &HT;    Early varieties tended to be tall _ at least three feet at
maturity _ and bloomed for several weeks in June. Now there are
compact varieties, some barely a foot tall, double-flowered as well
as single-flowered types, and a range of bloom time broad enough to
have Shasta daisies in flower from late spring into autumn.
 &HT;    For the cutting garden, I like a tall variety, like Polaris,
Alaska or Diener's Double. These varieties will top three feet in a
sunny site, and in partial shade can grow to four feet or more
without developing the weak stems that plague sun-loving flowers
grown in shady areas.
 &HT;    Polaris has the largest flowers, as much as seven inches across.
Alaska is a profuse bloomer, but with smaller flowers, three inches
across. Diener's Double's five-inch blooms are not so plentiful,
but they are double-flowered, meaning that two or more layers of
petals circle the center of each bloom.
 &HT;    Slightly shorter, but still fine for cutting, are Northern
Lights, Snow Bouquet, Summer Snowball, Exhibition and Switzerland,
which grow 24 to 30 inches tall. Northern Lights, Snow Bouquet and
Switzerland are single-flowered; Exhibition and Summer Snowball,
double-flowered.
 &HT;    On the petite side are the dwarf Snow Lady (a 1988 All-America
Selection), which stays a neat 10 to 12 inches tall, and Silver
Princess, 15 inches. Both are single-flowered.
 &HT;    Dwarf varieties tend to flower earliest _ late May in my
south-central Pennsylvania garden. Taller varieties bloom well into
July. All Shasta daisies will bloom again in the autumn if the
plants are cut back after their main flush of flowers is spent.
Alaska is especially long-blooming, producing flowers wildly in
June and sporadically until hard frost.
 &HT;    Some Shasta daisies, especially the doubles, do not reliably
come true from seed and are usually vegetatively propagated. To try
Exhibition, Summer Snowball or Switzerland, seek a plant at a
garden center.
 &HT;    But the others are easy to start from seed, which may be sown
now to produce plants large enough to set into the garden this fall
for flowers next year. Sow the seed thinly in a seedling flat; do
not cover it. Shasta daisies need light to germinate.
 &HT;    When the seedlings are large enough to handle, transfer them to
individual pots and let them grow until they are large enough to
plant in the garden. If the seedlings don't seem large enough by
mid-September, overwinter them in their pots in a cold frame or
sheltered area, and plant them out in early spring.
 &HT;    You may also start Shasta daisies from seed in the early spring.
The young plants will produce a few flowers their first year.
 &HT;    Although Shasta daisies are perennial, and hardy well into New
England, I like to grow the cutting varieties as biennials. I plant
daisies with biennials such as cornflower and Canterbury Bells, cut
the flowers the following year, and then replace the plants with
fresh ones.
 &HT;    The reason is that Shasta daisies, especially the tall ones,
need frequent dividing. The plant loses vigor in the center, even
though the outside rim is healthy. Every second or third year, in
the spring, you will need to dig up the plant and separate the
weakened center from the strong outside growth. The roots separate
easily, and I don't mind performing this chore in the perennial
garden planted for show. Vegetatively propagated varieties must be
divided, of course, since their seeds may not produce the desired
plant.
 &HT;    But I grow many daisies in the cutting garden, which is more of
a workhorse garden than an ornamental one. The seed is inexpensive,
and it's easier to start with fresh plants.
 &HT;    Besides, starting Shasta daisies every year means that I'll have
plenty of plants to use for filling any vacancies in the garden.
Burbank, no doubt, would approve.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THIS WEEK: A TIME TO PRUNE AND IMPROVE DRAINAGE
 &HT;    By PATRICIA JONAS
 &HT;    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roots of young rhododendrons may suffocate in waterlogged soil
and be susceptible to Phytopthora wilt, an overall wilting
beginning with new growth. If drainage is improved, the plant will
fight this fungal disease. If it succumbs, remove and destroy it;
do not plant another rhododendron (or azalea) in the same spot.
</P>
<P>
   Although pruning of most vines was best done in early spring,
restrict growth and limit size by selectively pruning vigorous
vines like ivy (Hedera species), trumpet creeper (Campsis radicans)
and honeysuckle (Lonicera sempervirens).
</P>
<P>
   Before planting a perennial vine, consider that some, like
Japanese honeysuckle (Lonicera japonica) and porcelain berry
(Ampelopsis brevipedunculata), are noxious weeds, but are still
sold in many garden centers. Some are serious problems locally,
like English ivy (Hedera helix) in California. Check with your
local Cooperative Extension Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
