<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE ENCOURAGES DIALOGUE BETWEEN CLERGY, MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Religion writers have never received so much attention
from distinguished religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pope John Paul II, through an emissary, sent us a message
during the ``Religion and Media 2000'' conference this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of the media is pervasive and powerful,'' the
statement declares.
</P>
<P>
   ``His Holiness fervently hopes your dialogue will produce a
shared vision of the human person and human society so that from
that basis religion and the media may work together for the good of
all,'' the statement says.
</P>
<P>
   It was read by Cardinal William Keeler of Baltimore, a strong
advocate for more cooperation among members of religious groups and
the media.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the meeting was to begin an ongoing dialogue between
journalists and religious leaders to improve the quality of
religion coverage.
</P>
<P>
   What set the conference apart was that it not only included
religion writers but also influential editors and publishers. On
the religious side, it included four cardinals. One of those,
Cardinal Francis Arinze, was recently listed by U.S. News and World
Report as a leading candidate to be the next pope.
</P>
<P>
   Gunther Lawrence, director of the Interreligious Information
Center in New York, coordinated Christian and Jewish leaders, the
Vatican and members of the Religion Newswriters Association, a
national organization of journalists who cover religion for secular
newspapers, magazines and broadcast outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, NBC and CBS networks were represented, as well as CNN,
which is contemplating hiring a religion specialist. National
Public Radio's religion reporter, Lynn Neary, was a speaker.
</P>
<P>
   In an opening address, Lawrence said many conference
participants believe that religion coverage will play an even more
important role in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is a window of opportunity to expand and
improve religion coverage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker, David Lawrence Jr., chairman and publisher
of the Miami Herald, minced no words in taking religion coverage to
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion is the greatest story seldom told,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that some news outlets cover religion well,
Lawrence said, ``Most of us do a profoundly inadequate job in
covering matters of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Navarro-Valls, director of the Vatican press office,
said there is room for improvement by religious leaders who
disseminate the news and by religion reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not pessimistic about religion coverage,'' he said.
``I see some good signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference participants had front-row seats at an audience with
the pope, and the pontiff was expected to meet some of the
conference leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Archbishop John P. Foley, an American who is president of the
Vatican's Pontifical Council on Social Communications, said future
meetings are planned between leaders of religion and the media.
</P>
<P>
   The conference participants will support efforts to train
journalists better in religion coverage. Discussions are under way
to hold regional conferences between religious and media
representatives, Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   The high goals for religion coverage expressed in the ``Religion
and Media 2000'' conference may bear fruit well into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have had a good beginning,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
