<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S A BILLIONAIRE. ENOUGH, ALREADY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Do you think that a simple, basic user (word
processing, E-mail, simple spreadsheets) has any use for Windows
98?
</P>
<P>
   _ 95 and Counting
</P>
<P>
   DEAR COUNTING: No.
</P>
<P>
   Look, if you're happy with the way everything is working on your
computer now, and you aren't one of those geeks who has to have the
very latest version of everything, I can't think of any compelling
reason for you to make Bill Gates any richer. Win 98 is just a
spiffed-up, less buggy version of Win 95.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you haven't bought a PC yet, I'd
definitely wait until you can get one with 98 pre-installed for
precisely the same reason: It's less buggy.
</P>
<P>
   On the third hand, if you'd just like to get Janet Reno's goat
by making all those antitrust suits even more pointless than they
already are, grab your copy today.
</P>
<P>
   I've been using the 98 beta for a couple of months now, and I
like it, but it's certainly nothing revolutionary. It definitely
hasn't improved my quality of life all that much, as if anything
but Ed McMahon standing on my doorstep with a really big check
could do that. Trust me, most casual PC users can get by with Win
95 until it's time to get a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: While browsing the Web during my lunch hour, I
spotted a link to ``The X-Files.'' Thinking it was the TV show, I
clicked on the link. Yep, you guessed it. It was XXX files.
Ordinarily, this is not a problem. I just back out of the page and
proceed to my next destination. This time it would not let me. I
tried to exit Netscape. Every time it closed a window another
opened. I had to turn my computer off to get it to stop. The attack
program somehow rewrote some of my system files. The computer gurus
here at work had to dump my hard drive and reload all my programs.
What happened?
</P>
<P>
   _ Innocent Bystander
</P>
<P>
   DEAR INNOCENT: Back in my day, the worst that could happen if
you looked at one too many dirty pictures was that you'd go blind.
These days you wind up losing your hard drive, too.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so you were just looking for Mulder and Scully and you wound
up _ completely by accident _ in porno-ville instead. I'm sure the
boys in Technical Services believed you.
</P>
<P>
   I think I found the site you described. It took hours of
painstaking research on my part, and I may well have lost sight in
one eye, but I see what you mean about all those irritating
secondary windows that keep popping up.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most annoying features of recent versions of HTML,
the language used to create Web pages, is its ability to launch a
concurrent browser session with another site. Click on your Back
button and a second window pops up. Go forward and get another. Try
one of the dozens of lurid links and two or three more may clutter
up your screen. And, at the site I visited, there was one
programming error that put me in an endless loop of come-ons from
what I can only assume wasn't the home page of a children's petting
zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your browser version and the amount o memory your
computer has, something's eventually going to go out to lunch. It's
unlikely that the smut peddler embedded any search-and-destroy
programs in the page, though. Turning Windows off with so many
things running probably goofed something up. If using Scandisk and
uninstalling Netscape didn't fix things, then a reformat was
probably the only way to go.
</P>
<P>
   You know, I think I need glasses now.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
