<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMP SWAPS LAUGHTER FOR AIDS BURDENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randy is 11 years old and already worried about death and dying.
And he shouldn't be. No child should, really.
</P>
<P>
   And so he and the others _ about 65 children affected in some
way by the virus that causes AIDS _ have gathered to set aside for
a time the burdens that have been thrust upon them.
</P>
<P>
   They have come together, for one week, to be children again.
</P>
<P>
   It is a few days before summer, and I am seated on a green park
bench under a billowing canopy of trees when Randy emerges from the
crowd to talk with me. He has already donned the signature Camp
Firelight T-shirt. He is small, with a sweet, narrow face to match
his sweet demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   He talks easily at first about his camp experience last year,
about his family, but he suddenly pulls back when he realizes that
he has just shared with a stranuer that his mother might die of
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know what it means,'' he says. ``I just hope
she doesn't die from it. I keep praying so she won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Before long, anxiety lets go of his face and drops from his
shoulders, and we are re-engaged. There are countless little boys
named Randy, he reasons, who live in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Randy has come to Camp Firelight, a program of the AIDS Outreach
Center, for the second time in as many years. He is looking forward
to another week of fishing, of arts and crafts and archery. Kid
things he doesn't get to experience very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're little like me,'' he says, ``some things you can't
do. Like sometimes you can't go fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, when the adult world beckons, when danger lurks
as it so often does in Randy's world, forfeiting one's childhood
may be the only way to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we know about this population of
children is that they are either homeless or live in neighborhoods
where they can't play outside,'' Trisha Kus told me recently as the
camp got under way at the Lockheed Martin Recreation Association.
``So many of them during the summer must stay inside to play, or
they don't play at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And so on this day, 62 children, including Randy, have come just
to play. Of those, 16 are HIV-positive. The remainder either have a
family member with AIDS or one who has died of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   At camp, though, they don't talk about HIV or AIDS. They don't
talk about death or dying. Not between 5:30 and 8:30 p.m., anyway.
Between those hours, for one week, they are simply themselves: kids
without a care in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children have adult-sized responsibilities,'' says LeAnn
Griffin, coordinator of youth services. ``Camp is a chance for them
to experience the therapeutic joy of being a child.''
</P>
<P>
   It is why the center, with funding from the Junior League of
Arlington and Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., started Camp Firelight two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really fun last year,'' Randy remembers. ``I can shoot
arrows here and find out all sorts of things I don't know about. I
can walk around. I can meet more people. It's a real fun camp.''
</P>
<P>
   And a cherished moment for a child haunted by death and dying.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
