s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEDDING-ANNOUNCEMENTS     06-26 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDING-ANNOUNCEMENTS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANCE BETWEEN THE LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  Stephan Talty is a critic and columnist.  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHAN TALTY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are people who read the obituaries
recreationally, and then there are people like me, who turn
immediately to the wedding announcements. What you have here is a
tug of war between the hard realists and the romantics.
</P>
<P>
   I once wrote obits, when I was a reporter trainee at The Miami
Herald. It was a job I took seriously. I spent hours on the
telephone with relatives (who were surprisingly eager to talk _ you
could hear the fresh emptiness of the house behind them) looking
for the human detail.
</P>
<P>
   But after writing 100 obituaries, you don't want to think about
coronary thrombosis and survivors anymore; you want to read about
beginnings, about great risk and social drama. There is no better
place to find these elusive things than the wedding pages. The
reasons are many:
</P>
<P>
   WEDDING ANNOUNCEMENTS ARE HOPEFUL. Where else can you find a
photographic representation of early love so fresh and convincing?
The couples on the wedding pages look so darn happy to be with each
other: their cheeks are touching, they lean into the future and
form small upside-down V's of closeness.
</P>
<P>
   Most married couples I see on the street look as if they're
having to-the-death boredom contests. Without the evidence of
wedding page photos, no one in his or her right mind would ever get
married.
</P>
<P>
   THEY ARE OUTLINES FOR NOVELS YOU WRITE IN YOUR HEAD. Start with
the photo, which is filled with clues to the marriage. Sometimes
you sigh and think, ``It's just not going to work.'' The bride or
the bridegroom has manipulated the physical space of the photo too
aggressively. I give those marriages two years at the outside. If
someone's going to crowd you out of your own engagement shot, you'd
better watch your back. But some people truly seem destined to be
together; even before they're married, their faces reveal a kind of
harmonic convergence.
</P>
<P>
   If I were writing the announcement, I would always include where
the bride and bridegroom met; it's essential to any imagining of
their courtship story. As it is now, I usually have to fill in the
blank myself. I'm convinced that all the stockbrokers and the
private-school elementary teachers (a classic combo) meet at the
Raccoon Lodge on the Upper East Side, a raging marriage bazaar of
the upper class. Since young lawyers have no real lives, I'm
convinced their marriages are arranged by a little old woman at the
New York Bar Association, who pairs them by using a complex
formula: law-school class rank times hours billed, divided by
height. The investment bankers who hook up with marketing
executives (very common, by the way), I see coming together while
Rollerblading in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else meets at Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   THE ANNOUNCEMENTS REVEAL THE ENDURANCE OF CLASS STRUCTURE IN
AMERICA. Marx never wrote much about marriage, but it is a much
more powerful class-forming tool than the country club swimming
pool or brunch in the Hamptons. People overwhelmingly marry people
of the same background. It makes you think that the next great
American revolutionary will operate an interclass dating service.
</P>
<P>
   But, once in a while, you get people who break free of the
unwritten code. As a son of the working class, I admit to being a
fan of the announcements where someone whose grandfather was one of
the founders of Standard Oil marries someone whose father operates
a gas station in Centralia, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases, I've noticed, the gas station heir, male or
female, is often blessed with great beauty. I believe this is a
Darwinian survival instinct built into rich people's DNA _ if they
didn't marry gorgeous people once in a while, they'd get so
lockjawed their kind would die out.
</P>
<P>
   SINGLE PEOPLE CAN PICK UP ALL KINDS OF TIPS. The announcements
reveal to the single man a breathtaking horizon of women-meeting
possibilities. When a Connecticut optometrist marries a salsa
dancer whose parents are sorghum farmers living in Shanghai, that's
bracing news to the guy who spends his mornings trying to think up
lines to use on the woman ahead of him at the local bagelry.
</P>
<P>
   The downside is that each Sunday, more beautiful, interesting
women are taken off the market. Blown opportunities shock me. The
worst is the homely girl I remember from high school who suddenly
appears on the wedding pages newly made-over, engaged and soon to
be rich. Some people have no self-restraint.
</P>
<P>
   I've realized that, at 33, a certain competitiveness has crept
into my reading. ``Getting hitched at 25?'' I think. ``Are they
insane?'' I think of anyone under 30 who appears in these pages as
tremendously rash, shoving to the front of the line. (I did consent
to attend my younger brother's wedding, although I thought he
should have waited. Birth order is obligation, James.)
</P>
<P>
   I silently thank all the 38-year-olds; they are my allies. If
their eyes are a little less giddy and their smiles touched with
wistfulness, so be it. They seem to nod at me from the photos. ``No
rush, old man,'' they say. ``Plenty of fish in the sea.''
</P>
<P>
   The 43-year-old bridegrooms, on the other hand, are terrifying.
``Getting hitched at 43? Is he insane?'' I ask. He's not, of
course. It's just that I can't bear the thought of a full decade
more of hanging out at clubs and saying things like, ``Where do I
put the quarter to get a smile?''
</P>
<P>
   MANY PEOPLE READ THE WEDDING ANNOUNCEMENTS TO SPOT THEIR
FRIENDS. I have to call these people what they are: dilettantes.
Most of my straight friends have gone down the long white linen
road already; my siblings are all married. Announcement-reading is
more than a personal gossip hunt for me; it's become a bittersweet
ritual of the single life.
</P>
<P>
   Only my gay friends are still unattached; but they don't seem to
share my pastime. When I told my college roommate about it, he
scoffed and called the wedding announcements ``the women's sports
pages.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a straight, single man and halfway athletic, I'm supposed
to turn to the sports scores every Sunday morning. And, believe me,
I do. It's just that there's so much more at stake on the wedding
pages, and the winners and losers have yet to be decided.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
