<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPLACING YOUR OS IS SERIOUS BUSINESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listen. Hear that sound? It's the siren song of Microsoft's
marketing, calling you to buy Windows 98 and slap it on your
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   The gang in Redmond, Wash., would have you believe that
installing Windows 98 is a breeze. And yes, installing Windows 98
usually is less hassle than installing Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake _ changing a PC's operating system should
not be considered minor surgery. You are switching out the core
software system that controls how your computer behaves, and doing
so should not be taken lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some steps you can take to prevent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Begin by making notes about the most basic components of your
system. Make a list of all your settings. That includes the phone
number for your Internet provider's dial-up line; networking
settings if you connect to the office intranet or have a
complicated Internet setup; any login names and passwords. In other
words, if you have made a change to one of Windows' standard
settings, find it and write it down.
</P>
<P>
   Why should you do this? The full version of Windows 98, which is
different from the upgrade version in that it can be installed on a
computer that doesn't yet have an operating system, overwrote some
of the network settings on two computers I tested. While the
upgrade version did not have this effect, it doesn't hurt to take
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Next, make a complete backup of your hard drives. If you don't
have a tape drive or a removable large-storage device, such as a
Zip drive, and you're not willing to spend an afternoon feeding
your machine dozens of floppy disks, at least back up any crucial
data. After all, you can always reinstall Quicken if you have the
original disk, but you can't replace the data files it generates.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you have a Windows 95 boot disk that will let you
reinstall the original operating system from the CD-ROM drive. That
means having AUTOEXEC.BAT and CONFIG.SYS files that contain lines
referring to your CD-ROM drivers on the floppy. During its
installation process, Windows 98 creates a boot disk that will
power a CD-ROM drive, but if something goes horribly wrong, you
should have a Windows 95 boot disk, too.
</P>
<P>
   Check the Web sites for the manufacturers of your various
hardware components _ graphics card, sound card, printer, etc. _
and grab the latest drivers. In most cases, Windows 95 and 98
drivers are the same, and you can install the latest drivers before
running the Windows 98 setup. But if you find Windows 98-specific
drivers, wait until the new operating system is installed before
you update them.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a utility package, such as Norton Utilities or First
Aid, contact the maker of the program to see if a software patch is
necessary to make it compatible with Windows 98. Programs such as
these, which often work with some of the ground-level components of
an operating system, are most apt to have problems.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Windows 98's disk defragmenter arranges files
differently on a hard drive, putting files related to each program
in consecutive order, and putting the most-used programs on the
fastest part of the disk. But if you run Norton Utilities'
SpeedDisk on a Windows 98 drive that's been set up this way,
SpeedDisk will undo those changes. Symantec has a patch for Norton
Utilities 3.0 that will fix this problem, but versions 1 and 2 of
Norton Utilities remain incompatible.
</P>
<P>
   It's also not a bad idea to check with the maker of your PC for
potential incompatibilities. I discovered that putting Windows 98
on an IBM ThinkPad 600 _ a new line of portables _ renders the
built-in modem unusable. PC Magazine reports that a fix is on the
way from IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether you're upgrading from Windows 3.1 or
Windows 95, you should pare your system down to its essentials.
That means disabling any software that runs in the background and
watches for certain events, such as virus-checkers, crash
prevention programs and installation monitors.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's not a bad idea remove all shortcuts from the
Startup group and store them in a temporary folder on your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Once you launch the Windows 98 setup program, installation takes
between 30 and 60 minutes. Your system will reboot several times,
and the way Microsoft has structured the installation makes it less
likely that your computer will lock up in the process _ a common
problem with the Windows 95 routine.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the entire operating system is loaded and your
computer rebooted before Windows starts trying to detect hardware
and install drivers. This strategy alone goes a long way to making
the Windows 98 setup a more pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98's install routine provides you with few choices when
you use the standard upgrade version. It does not, for example,
give you options about which components to install. It makes
decisions based on what's already on your system, presuming you'll
want to keep your current settings and features. You'll be asked
whether you want to save your Windows 95 files, in case you want to
go back to the older operating system. This will take up about 50
megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to report that the uninstall routine for Windows 98
works quite well. That's how I got the modem working again in that
ThinkPad! However, be aware that if you installed any software
while Windows 98 was on your system, you'll need to reinstall it.
Removing Windows 98 puts your system back exactly as it was before
you started on this, um, adventure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
