<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAZDA 626 GETS EVEN BETTER WITH REDESIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best midsize sedans on the market has gotten much
better for 1998 with the complete redesign of the Mazda 626.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda, the company that makes the highest-quality affordable
cars in the world, has raised the bar with the new 626, creating a
formidable competitor to its main Japanese rivals, the Honda Accord
and Toyota Camry.
</P>
<P>
   The new 626 has been largely patterned after Mazda's flagship
Millenia luxury sedan, with virtually the same front end, V-6 power
and smooth, quiet ride. The 626, whose leather-equipped premium ES
model is just $23,995, is so similar to the Millenia that it is apt
to steal sales away from that vehicle, which lists for $5,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers already are finding that the 626 offers more car for
the money that any midsize competitor _ foreign or domestic _ and
sales of the new model are booming.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you familiar with the previous 626, you'll find the
new one taller, longer, wider and roomier, with comfortable seating
for five adults and a trunk large enough for extended cruising or a
wagonload of groceries.
</P>
<P>
   Even the base DX model that begins at $15,695 comes with the
Millenia styling. Of course, to turn the 626 into a true
Millenia-like sedan with all the amenities, you'll have to choose
the top-of-the-line ES model, which we tested.
</P>
<P>
   The DX, designed as a value leader and most apt to be found in
rental-car and corporate fleets, comes with a 2.0-liter
four-cylinder engine rated at 125 horsepower and 127 foot-pounds of
torque. Power is adequate, although not impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Midlevel LX models, which begin at $17,895, also come with the
four-cylinder engine, but the 2.5-liter, 24-valve V-6 is available
for $1,900 more. The V-6 engine, which puts the 626 almost into the
performance-sports-sedan class, cranks out 170 horsepower and 163
foot-pounds of torque. The V-6 is standard in the ES.
</P>
<P>
   All 626 models can be ordered with either a five-speed manual or
four-speed automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Mazda chose to provide a manual-transmission model for our test
drive.
</P>
<P>
   That's unfortunate, because a manual transmission is an
unnecessary and somewhat silly option for a midsize family sedan
such as this. The vast majority of buyers will choose the
automatic. It's awfully hard to shift gears and talk on the cell
phone at the same time, especially in stop-and-go rush-hour
traffic, so the manual gearbox is actually a liability for most
people who buy cars in this vehicle class.
</P>
<P>
   But the V-6 engine is smooth and responsive, with plenty of
power for freeway merges and passing.
</P>
<P>
   Traction control is standard on V-6 models. This computerized
system senses wheel spin and gently applies brakes to the spinning
wheel to stop the spin and transfer power to the other front wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements in both the engine and the 626's body have reduced
noise, vibration and harshness considerably from previous models.
Mazda says structural rigidity has increased 43 percent through the
use of new frame supports.
</P>
<P>
   The ride is as quiet and smooth as that of most $30,000-plus
luxury cars, yet the Mazda offers sporty handling characteristics
that make it glide through twists and turns. That's due in part to
the speed-sensitive power steering (standard on all models), as
well as the front MacPherson-struts and unique twin-trapezoidal
rear suspension, with both front and rear stabilizer bars.
</P>
<P>
   ES models come with a whole list of luxury items, beginning with
the very nice leather seats. There are comfortable front bucket
seats and a rear bench with a split-folding seatback. The rear seat
has full seat and shoulder belts for all three passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Other ES amenities include a Bose AM/FM/compact-disc audio
system, 15-inch aluminum-alloy wheels (with locks), power driver's
seat, leather-wrapped steering wheel, power glass moon roof, power
antenna, and vinyl door-trim panels.
</P>
<P>
   Standard on LX and ES models are air-conditioning; cruise
control; dual power outside mirrors; power trunk release; auto-off
headlights; power windows and door locks; a security system with
remote keyless entry and a computerized setup that immobilizes the
car unless the special ignition key is used.
</P>
<P>
   There were no options on our test car; everything was standard
for the list price of $24,495 (including $450 transportation).
</P>
<P>
   Mazda builds the 626 at its Flat Rock, Mich., plant, and the
vehicles have more than 75 percent U.S. content. That qualifies
them as domestic cars. They're also union-made vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy for the V-6 is a respectable 21 miles per gallon in
the city and 27 on the highway. The tank holds 16.9 gallons of gas,
giving the 626 great cruising range.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At a glance:
</P>
<P>
   1998 Mazda 626 ES sedan
</P>
<P>
   The Package: Midsize, four-door, five-passenger, V-6 powered,
front-drive sedan, completely redesigned for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights: Outstanding quality; zippy V-6 engine; sporty
handling; roomy and comfortable cabin, standard four-wheel disc
antilock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Negatives: Automatic transmission is an $800 option, even on
premium models.
</P>
<P>
   Major competitors: Toyota Camry, Ford Taurus/Mercury Sable,
Nissan Maxima, Honda Accord, Chevrolet Lumina, Pontiac Grand Prix,
Buick Regal, Oldsmobile Intrigue, Volkswagen Passat, Hyndai Sonata,
Chrysler Cirrus.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel economy: 21 miles per gallon city, 27 highway (manual
transmission).
</P>
<P>
   Base price: $23,995 plus $450 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $24,445, including transportation.
</P>
<P>
   On The Road rating: A-plus.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III writes on transportation issues for
the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. His mailing address is
Star-Telegram/Northeast, 3201 Airport Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford,
Texas 76021; his E-mail address is chambers(at)star-telegram.com.
Fax: (817) 685-3883. Check out his Wheelin' new-car review column
weekly on the Internet at
ww.netarrant.net/today/news/opinions/necol.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
