u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS     06-26 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-HELPLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 95 LIKELY BETTER CHOICE FOR OLD 486 THAN THE 98 UPGRADE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I thought I was being real smart by bypassing Windows 95 and
waiting for Windows 98. Windows 3.1 runs just fine on my computer,
and I figured I'd wait until Microsoft got it right with Windows
95. Now, I have a real dinosaur of a computer, and I'm starting to
think I can't use Windows 98 on it. It's a 486, with a 33-megahertz
chip and eight megabytes of RAM. I presume I'll have to upgrade the
memory, maybe to 16 megabytes, but what about the rest of it? Oh
yeah, I have a 500-megabyte hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   A: Microsoft is infamous for understating the requirements for
its operating systems. Windows 95, for example, supposedly will run
with four megabytes of memory on a 386 system. But anyone who's
tried that knows the result is more pain than gain.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Windows 95's practical minimum is a 486 PC with at
least 16 megabytes of memory _ and that is indeed a minimum. As an
operating system, Windows 95 doesn't start to feel snappy until
you're using a 486 running at 66 megahertz or better, with 32
megabytes of RAM. And you can't say it's a ``fast'' operating
system until you move to a Pentium.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98's official minimum specifications called for a 486-66
PC with 16 megabytes of memory, and anywhere from 200 to nearly 400
megabytes of memory free on the hard drive. Given that the
browser-as-desktop interface is resource-intensive and can slow
down older Pentium systems, I wouldn't recommend it for a 486 PC.
I've seen Windows 98 running on a Pentium 90 with 32 megabytes of
memory, and it's not pretty.
</P>
<P>
   However, once you move into the upper strata _ say, a Pentium
MMX 166-megahertz system or faster _ Windows 98 feels snappier than
the Windows 95/Internet Explorer 4 combination.
</P>
<P>
   In your case, I'd recommend you get Windows 95 instead if you
don't want to buy a new machine. But definitely upgrade your memory
to at least 32 megabytes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I took your advice, upgraded from Windows 3.11 to 95, getting
a new 300 megahertz Pentium II in the process. This is the upside.
The downside is I lost use of my old faithful Procomm (MS-DOS
version), so am unable to access HAL-PC BBS. Can you suggest a
solution to my problem?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sounds like the computer you bought, while a powerhouse, has
a modem with limited capabilities. It's likely a Winmodem, which
only can be used with the Windows 95/98 operating systems. These
are made by various manufacturers, including U.S. Robotics and
Lucent Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that much of their ``guts'' is software-based,
loaded as part of Windows. When Windows isn't present, neither is
the modem.
</P>
<P>
   You have several options. The first is to use the built-in,
Windows-based terminal program called HyperTerminal, which may or
may not be installed on your system. If it is, you'll find it in
the Programs/Accessories/Communications folder off the Start menu.
If not, you can add it using the Windows Setup tab in the
Add/Remove programs module in the Control Panel.
</P>
<P>
   HyperTerminal is not a great solution _ I find it somewhat
awkward to use _ but it will do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to buy a copy of the Windows version of
Procomm Plus. It comes in two forms _ the full version, complete
with all kinds of Internet utilities you may or may not need _ and
a simpler edition called Procomm Connections. You can find out more
at www.quarterdeck.com.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, you could replace that Winmodem with a traditional
modem that will work in MS-DOS, but this is your most expensive
``fix.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
