<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE ARGUMENTS TO THE CONTRARY, THE GUNS BELONG TO US
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A well regulated Militia, being necessary to the security of a
free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall
not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Second Amendment to the Constitution of the United States,
ratified Dec. 15, 1791
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   A push to exact more stringent control over guns is once again
under way in this country, and far and wide one can hear the
familiar but tiresome refrain about how the Founding Fathers never
meant that individuals should be armed when they wrote the Second
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   My, but it do make me weary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1789, when James Madison first introduced what ultimately
became the Bill of Rights, he stated that the amendments ``relate
first to private rights.'' Reference to ``the right of the people''
appears in the First, Second, Fourth, Ninth and 10th amendments.
And the courts have time and again ruled that these rights belong
to individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Second Amendment originated in the United States
Congress in 1789, that august body has three times _ in 1886 with
the Freedmen's Bureau Act, in 1941 with the Property Requisition
Act, and in 1986 with the Firearms Owners' Protection Act _ passed
legislation to reaffirm this guarantee of personal freedom and to
adopt specific safeguards to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   Get a copy of the 1995 Tennessee Law Review devoted to the
Second Amendment and read the chapter by author Stephen Halbrook, a
Virginia attorney and former professor at the Tuskegee Institute
and Howard University. He provides a well-researched look at how
Congress has repeatedly interpreted the Second Amendment through
the years to reaffirm an individual's right ``to keep and bear
Arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the anti-gun folk spend a great deal of their energy
fomenting support for the abolishment of personal ownership of
firearms by defining the amendment's ``well regulated Militia'' in
today's terms of a national guard.
</P>
<P>
   Let's, just for the sake of argument, go with the anti-gun folk
on this. Let's assume that Americans are amenable to the idea of
assigning the duty of protecting individual citizens to the
government ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I saying?'' I can't even do this in the abstract. The
Second Amendment reaches beyond the guarantee of an individual's
right to protect hearth and home. It is the guarantee of an
individual's right to protection FROM a tyrannical government.
</P>
<P>
   It is at the very core of the American culture not to trust
authority. That is what has made this nation fiercely independent.
Our Founding Fathers deliberately decided to design a system of
government like no other on Earth, one that was the epitome of
human freedoms and individual liberties.
</P>
<P>
   David Kopel, author of ``The Samurai, The Mountie and the
Cowboy,'' summed up the feelings of millions of Americans about the
government's ability to take care of its people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans did not trust the government for protection in the
19th century, and they don't trust it today,'' Kopel wrote in his
1992 book about whether gun control laws in other democracies _
Japan, Great Britain, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Jamaica and
Switzerland _ would work in the United States. ``The failure or
inability of the modern American state to control crime makes it
particularly unlikely that Americans could be persuaded by statute
to give up their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Amen, brother. Overall, crime is down, and we can thank in large
part zero-tolerance initiatives, increased law enforcement spending
and enhanced community vigilance (some of us would include
concealed-carry permits on that list). But until the day comes when
all citizens are guaranteed that the police will be there when they
need them, and not just after the fact to pick up the pieces and ID
the bodies, we must strongly and loudly proclaim our right to
protect ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill of Rights is the mandate from the people to the
government about those rights we will not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   Is there still too much crime and violence in this country? Yes.
But people _ particularly politicians interested in snappy sound
bites _ get fixated on the hardware and not the individual using
it. It's easy, and judging by the continued attacks on the Second
Amendment, it works.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is a senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Her e-mail address is
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com, and her phone number is (817)
390-7599. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
