<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTING-VOICES-2TAKES-     06-26 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTING-VOICES-2TAKES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOICE MATTERS ON THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Singin' in the Rain,'' Stanley Donen's brilliant spoof of
old Hollywood, a squeaky-voiced, platinum-shagged silent film
goddess named Lina Lamont (played by Jean Hagen) is faced with a
terrifying reality: sound.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are starting to talk, and she's got a voice that pops
light bulbs. ``I ceeeeeen't steend 'im!'' bleats Lina in her
strangled helium soprano, asher voice coach reacts with stoicism
and dismay. Gently, she corrects her: ``I caaaahn't staaahnd him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lina tries again: ``I ceeen't steend 'im!'' The coach corrects
her. And corrects her. Finally, after weeks of struggling, Lina
repeats the line on screen: ``I caaaahhhhn't steend 'im!''
</P>
<P>
   It's a great moment in film, hilarious because it captures the
dilemma facing actors at the advent of sound in the late 1920s.
Stars with good voices Ronald Colman, for instance survived the
transition to talking pictures. The Linas of the world did not.
</P>
<P>
   But movie history is crammed with little ironies, and lovely
Lina could well have her revenge: Were she flesh and blood and
making films today, she might be starring for a few cool mil in a
flick with Harrison Ford. These days, a lot of bad voices are
making a lot of good money.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptical? Talk to James Spruill, an associate professor of
theater at Boston University and an acting pedagogue who has taught
the likes of Angela Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent and training often have nothing to do with (an actor's)
work, because casting is done cosmetically,'' said Spruill, who
says African-American actors have among the most naturally resonant
voices. ``The most important thing is `the look.'''
</P>
<P>
   Spruill knows whereof he speaks: he's heard a lot of shriekers
in his day. ``Especially,'' he said, ``the young women who have
voices that would shatter glass.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't name names, but two words spring to mind: Renee
Zellweger (the cheeping star of ``Jerry Maguire''). And three more:
Joey Lauren Adams (the shrilling star of ``Chasing Amy''). And
another two: Anne Heche (the whining star of ``Six Days, Seven
Nights''). Not to mention Maria Pitillo (peep), Rosie Perez
(squeak), Jennifer Jason Leigh (drone) and Fran Drescher (squawk).
</P>
<P>
   Nor are men excluded from the club of tweedlers and yawpers.
Chris O'Donnell projects his tenor directly through his nose,
seemingly bypassing his vocal cords entirely. Tom Cruise, certified
hunkdom notwithstanding, has one of the most nasal voices on the
planet; his scenes with Zellweger in ``Jerry Maguire'' are enough
to frizz your eyebrows. Tom Selleck is another nose-talker. Matthew
McConaughey isn't, but his voice is still as flat as toast he's the
It Boy with the vocal resonance of a bottle fly.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Pitt has a nice set of pipes, but he's never quite learned
to enunciate (did you understand anything he said in
``Sleepers''?). Talented Leonardo DiCaprio is too young to peg: In
a few years he'll either have a mature, ringing tenor or the
muffling jabber of a mouth stuffed with Cheerios. The gift is
there; the charisma is there; the voice, one hopes, will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Brando was swallowing his consonants years before
DiCaprio came along but Brando was Brando, and he got away with it
because he paired it with a full battleship of acting guns.
</P>
<P>
   Thespian prowess and innate vocal charms don't always go
hand-in-hand (or hand-in-mouth). Still, stardom has come a long way
since 1933, when Claude Rains stunned audiences with a
career-making debut in ``The Invisible Man'' using his voice alone.
Not until the film's closing moments does his face appear,
flickering into view just before the credits roll.
</P>
<P>
   Rains could pull it off because he had one of the best voices in
movie history: urbane but gritty, silken but laced with threat. It
was a golden throat for a golden era.
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few good voices out there. George Clooney has
the raw material for a gorgeous, rolling baritone. His erstwhile
``E.R.'' co-star, Sherry Stringfield, owns an alto made from melted
butter. Bassett can soothe or sing, Susan Sarandon fells men with
her breathy delivery, and James Earl Jones' deep, shuddering boom
could possibly rouse the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Women (and a few men) wilt before the rich British rumbles of
Sean Connery, Anthony Hopkins, Patrick Stewart. Kathleen Turner has
a sturdy, come-hither huskiness despite her geographically obscure
accent. Alec Baldwin's got a sexy rasp, while Mel Gibson has a
good, honest, meat-and-potatoes voice box (he even sang in
``Pocahontas''). As for Morgan Freeman, he can make anything sound
like Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for each one of these silky talkers, there's another whose
delivery rakes the blackboard. This isn't a new phenomenon limited,
unidimensional or otherwise imperfect voices have always had their
place in cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Arthur (``Mr. Smith Goes to Washington'') was the squeaky
talker to end all squeaky talkers (including Zellweger). And Clark
Gable, he of the swaggering Y chromosome, had a high-pitched voice
that started out nasal and only became more so with age. But Gable
knew how to hurl a line of dialogue, turning that schnozz-heavy
tenor into a powerful tool of seduction.
</P>
<P>
   No, you don't need a mellifluous throat to get the girl (or the
boy). Jack Nicholson is living proof that a bad voice, well-used,
can be as great an asset as the pearliest throat trained for opera.
And it's worth remembering that Humphrey Bogart had a triumphantly
awful voice, scabrous and flat, yet he used it to woo babes, and
moviegoers, for close to three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Movies are all about personality. And they're all about
connections: How the actor connects to his character, how the
character connects to the film, how the film connects to the
audience. A provocative or inviting voice can be the stuff that
glues an actor to his part and binds a viewer to the story.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACTING-VOICES-2NDTAKE     06-26 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTING-VOICES-2NDTAKE-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: x x x to the story.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If Grace Kelly is on the French Riviera with her mother, (her
co-star) is going to have to look like Cary Grant ... and he's
going to have to sound like Cary Grant, too,'' said David Downs, a
theater professor at Northwestern University and author of ``The
Actor's Eye: Seeing and Being Seen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to hear a pea-voiced man romance a Hitchcock
blonde; that's not what the movies are for.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the whole thing about voice and looks and eyes and
smile that all go together,'' Downs said. ``Well, the actor is just
part of the package of the film.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An ill-fitting or inappropriate voice can ``translate into a
kind of falseness,'' said Michael Hammond, an actor and
administrator at Shakespeare &AMP; Company in Lenox, Mass. ``Rather
than the film actor having to have a necessarily developed or
trained voice, he or she has to modulate the voice so it
corresponds with what we're seeing and what we're watching. ... An
actor has to be very, very careful that the vocal performance
doesn't bely the physical performance in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hammond was quick to point out, good movie voices are not the
same as good theatrical voices. ``Whereas the stage actor certainly
needs to concern himself or herself with being heard and being
understood, and can't necessarily rely on the idiosyncratic charm
of his or her voice,'' he said, ``a film actor can do just that can
have the most open, free, released, expressive voice, modulated for
film, or can have the most pinched, peculiar,
bordering-on-incomprehensible voice, and be all the more hireable
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Grant could speak in his mid-Atlantic lilt, Mae West could
purr with her sexiest see-saw whine, and James Mason could pour
vocal honey all over his leading ladies never fretting about the
audience's ability to hear. The downside, here, is that an actor
accustomed to film (and television) could lose her powers of
projection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more work you do in television and film, the more
destroyed your voice gets,'' Spruill said. The most commonly used
microphone on film and TV sets is so sensitive ``that actors don't
have to do any work at vocal projection. So that eventually, it
destroys their voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Many actors working today have been deeply influenced by Kristin
Linklater, who helped found Shakespeare &AMP; Company and whose writing
(``Freeing the Natural Voice'') promotes a whole-body method of
relaxation and emotional expression that expands range and adds
resonance. Nils Haaland, an actor and teacher at the Omaha Theater
Company for Young People, was trained in Linklater methods at the
State University College at Purchase, N.Y., and swears by their
results. They have ``absolutely'' made a difference in his career,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the one thing that people will really comment on ...
`Oh, you have such a great stage voice, you have such a great
voice,'' said Haaland, who has a broadly resonant tenor. ``Before I
went to school, before Purchase, I had a very high, squeaky,
nasal-pitched voice. I had no awareness whatsoever of my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   The training, he said, ``has given a real advantage to my acting
I just know where to pull from for different characters. It just
gives you a higher range.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no question that professional voice training can yield
career benefits. But Maggie Mancinelli-Cahill, artistic director of
Capital Repertory Company in Albany, N.Y., wonders whether
conservatory training also yields a sameness of accent and timbre a
lack of regional idiosyncrasy. She likes the unique voices of yore:
Gregory Peck (``a very beautiful voice''), Brando (``he can change
his voice, and is willing to, in so many different roles''), Lionel
Barrymore (``that voice is unmistakable'').
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cary Grants and the Jimmy Stewarts and the Katharine
Hepburns, they were urged to be personalities. They were hired for
their personalities. I'm not so sure that's true any more in
film,'' she said. ``It may be just a question of a voice coming
along as the voice and personality grow and develop.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no mistaking Jimmy Stewart (when he) made his
first movie (the voice) was there then! Or Cary Grant: His voice
was there in `Gunga Din.'''
</P>
<P>
   But maybe it's too early to tell. Perhaps, as Tom Cruise's
career progresses, his voice will assume the quirks and quavers of
a truly singular star. Perhaps Chris O'Donnell will sign up for
voice lessons. And perhaps, as the years fly past and filmmaking
enters its second century, the stars of talking pictures will once
again learn to talk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
