<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-WINDOWS-2TA     06-26 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-WINDOWS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEING WINDOWS 98 CLEARLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Windows 98 is now available in stores after a long,
bumpy legal and technical road as the successor to Microsoft's
best-selling Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But while Windows 95 was an instant hit _ helped along by
Microsoft's relentless marketing push _ Windows 98 has an early
reputation of being less than compelling. And so, the question is
this: Is Windows 98 an important enough upgrade that most users
should plunk down about $100 for it?
</P>
<P>
   The answer depends on what each user requires from his or her
operating system. Windows 98 is not a dramatic change from Windows
95.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the same architectural design, the same memory
management, the same instabilities at their cores,'' said Ed Bott,
a senior editor at PC Computing magazine who has been studying
Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a big Internet user, Windows 98 can make your time
online a lot easier, Bott said. ``It's obvious who wouldn't need
it, and that's those who neither want nor need Internet access. For
those people it will just be a royal pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Windows 98 is essentially Windows 95 with a prettier
face, it has some other features that make it easier to maintain,
troubleshoot and upgrade a personal computer. There are performance
enhancements that may or may not speed up your system, and there
are numerous bug fixes, though many of them already are available
through patches for Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got the latest version of Windows 95 _ dubbed OSR2 _
you have many of the improvements in Windows 98. If you've got
Internet Explorer 4 on your system and during installation you
agreed to the ``desktop update,'' then you already have most of the
interface improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Akers, a Microsoft product manager for Windows 98,
said that the integration of Internet Explorer 4 into the operating
system makes it snappier and more stable than the Windows 95
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Akers also argues that the maintenance features and
troubleshooting utilities alone are worth the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   As with Windows 95, the new operating system will be available
in two versions. One is designed to be used with computers that
already have Windows 3.1 or 95 on them; it has a list price of
$109. The other version is for use on computers that don't have an
operating system installed; it will sell for about twice that
figure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INTERFACE CHANGES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've been watching the news, you know that the Department
of Justice is not pleased with Microsoft's integration of its Web
browser into the operating system. Justice's concern is that making
Internet Explorer 4 one of the core features of Windows will spell
death for the external browser market _ primarily Netscape
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly is convenient. With the browser doubling as the
desktop, any folder window can double as a Web browser. For
example, open folders can be set to include a field that lets you
type in a Web address. One minute the window can be showing the
contents of your hard drive, and the next it's displaying a page on
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, folders themselves can be displayed as Web pages,
complete with background images and additional text. Windows uses
this capability to display basic information about each file _ just
hold your cursor over a file and its size, date and name will show
up on the left side of the window. There are some folder features
that are unique to Windows 98. Some graphics files _ such as GIF,
JPG and BMP files _ can be displayed in thumbnail style in the same
area where you'd see file information, again just by holding your
cursor over a file.
</P>
<P>
   How you launch programs and choose files is different if you
turn on the one-click option. Windows 98 and Internet Explorer 4
both let you start programs by clicking on them once with the left
mouse button, much the way you'd single-click on a Web address to
get to that page. Selecting a file is even simpler _ just hold your
cursor over the file's icon.
</P>
<P>
   While this is handy, it can also be confusing if you're a
longtime Windows 3.1 or 95 user. Single-clicking in those operating
systems is used to select a file, while double-clicking launches
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAINTENANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 includes the Maintenance Wizard, which automates the
process of checking and defragmenting hard drives, removing
temporary files and removing programs that launch at startup.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizard changes the way Windows 98's defragmenting utility
works. Normally, a defragmenter packs all the files on a drive
tightly together. This is done regardless of whether a series of
files is related. Corel's WordPerfect 8, for example, is made up of
hundreds of files, but in the past the defragmentation process did
not place them next to each other. Windows 98 places related files
side-by-side, and puts the files you use most on the fastest part
of the hard drive. This means the drive's read head doesn't have to
travel as far to pick up the files needed to get a program started.
</P>
<P>
   But how does Windows 98 know what programs you use most often,
and what files make up what programs? The operating system keeps a
log of what's launched. The Maintenance Wizard uses this as a kind
of map for the defragmentation process.
</P>
<P>
   Another nice under-the-hood feature is FAT32, a new way that
Windows organizes files on the hard drive. FAT32 cuts down on the
amount disk space required for each file on a large hard drive.
Converting to it can result in disk space savings of as much as 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the OSR2 version of Windows 95 came with FAT32, many PC
makers still ship systems using the old file system, FAT16. There
is no Windows 95 conversion utility, so users who want to take
advantage of the feature must use a third-party program, such as
Partition Magic from PowerQuest.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 comes with a FAT16-to-FAT32 converter. Once you've
made the change, there's no way to reverse it, though, unless you
use something like Partition Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Windows Upgrade is an Internet-based service that alerts you to
new features and bug fixes that can be downloaded from a Microsoft
Web site. This feature can be activated when you are away from the
PC, or even overnight.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TROUBLESHOOTING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't think you'll get away from General Protection Faults,
illegal operation errors or even random lockups _ it's still
Windows, after all. But you have more tools with Windows 98 to help
you figure out what's causing all that pain.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nicest tools is an oldie-but-goodie: Dr. Watson. The
utility found in Windows 3.1 and Windows for Workgroups 3.11 is
back. Just run Dr. Watson in the background when working with a
program that keeps crashing, and Dr. Watson will generate a log
with detailed information about the state of your system at the
time of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   You'll still see the Windows 95-style error box, and be able to
read the details from there. But Dr. Watson provides even more
information, which can be very useful when dealing with technical
support staff.
</P>
<P>
   Many troubleshooting features are packed into a single utility
with the misleading name of System Information. This program is
like a Swiss army knife, packed full of useful tools for poking
around in the guts of your machine. Among its many ``blades'' are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Incredibly detailed system information for hardware, software,
memory configuration and network settings. If it's happening on
your computer, you'll find it listed here.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Windows Report Tool, which gathers this information and
combines it with user notes for dispatch to technical support
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   _ The System File Checker, which scans for missing or corrupted
operating system files. If it finds one, it first searches for the
file on your hard drives, and then gives you the option of
extracting one from your Windows 98 setup disk.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Registry Checker, which scans the Windows Registry for
errors. If it finds one, it suggests a fix. It will also prompt you
to back up the Registry.
</P>
<P>
   _ The System Configuration Utility _ one of the most exciting
components. It lets you select which parts of your various
configuration files _ AUTOEXEC.BAT, CONFIG.SYS, WIN.INI and
SYSTEM.INI _ will be launched when Windows 98 boots. Rather than
calling up these files in SYSEDIT, or in a word processor, you just
click on the parts you don't want to run. This makes
troubleshooting a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Skip Driver Agent, which checks for drivers that gave
Windows 98 problems during the booting process. You can then
disable or reinstall them.
</P>
<P>
   As with Windows 95, Windows 98 has you create a startup disk to
be used for troubleshooting. Unlike Windows 95, this one's actually
useful. It includes a generic CD-ROM driver that lets you reinstall
Windows 98 from the CD without having the entire operating system
present. However, be sure and test the disk to make sure it works
after you've installed Windows 98. If the generic driver doesn't
work with your CD-ROM drive, you'll need to replace it with drivers
specific to your unit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HARDWARE SUPPORT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Windows 98's most-touted features is its ability to work
with TV-tuner cards, which allow you to hook up cable and view
programs on your PC. However, it ships with drivers for only the
ATI Technologies cards. Others reportedly are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has included WebTV for Windows 98 software, which has
two main features. The first is an onscreen TV listing that
downloads information at no cost and lets you create your own local
viewing schedule. You can search for the kinds of movies you like _
say, horror films _ and get a listing of everything in that genre
showing for the week.
</P>
<P>
   WebTV for Windows also will display extra information
transmitted by a broadcaster about a particular show. For example,
some television programs offer biographic information about stars
as a show airs. This appears in a window alongside the TV display.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 also has built-in support for Universal Serial Bus
ports and devices, which are faster and, unlike serial ports,
support plug and play. Windows 95 OSR2 has this as well, but it's
an add-on. In theory, USB support works better in Windows 98, but
keep in mind that it was a USB scanner that caused a late beta
version of Windows 98 to crash during a now-infamous trade show
demo by Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   There's also built-in support for DVD-ROM drives.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Windows 98 has built-in support for Firewire, also
known as 1394, a connection used to link home entertainment devices
to personal computers. A Firewire-capable VCR, for example, might
be able to talk to WebTV for Windows, allowing you to program the
VCR via the computer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
