<HEADER>
A8842 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-COURT-HARASS     06-26 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-COURT-HARASS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH COURT SAYS BOCA CAN BE LIABLE FOR LIFEGUARD'S SEXUAL
HARASSMENT
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In landmark rulings Friday, the Supreme Court made
it easier for employees to hold their employers liable for sexual
harassment committed by supervisors or more senior managers.
</P>
<P>
   The court's position was spelled out in two separate 7-2
decisions, with Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia
dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the cases involved claims that the city of Boca Raton,
Fla., is liable for the sexual harassment of a former female
lifeguard by two of her superiors. The other case involved an
Illinois woman who sued her former employer, Burlington Industries,
over alleged sexual misconduct by her boss's boss .
</P>
<P>
   In the 33-page Boca Raton opinion, written by Justice David
Souter, the high court reversed last year's ruling of the 11th
Circuit Court of Appeals and upheld the $1 damage award granted by
the U.S. District Court to former lifeguard Beth Ann Faragher.
</P>
<P>
   In the Burlington case Kimberly Ellerth, who worked as a
salesperson in a two-person office in Chicago, had sued Burlington
because, she said, she was harassed by the boss of her immediate
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling had the effect of allowing both lawsuits to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the two rulings, the Supreme Court sought to define
the circumstances by which an employer could be held responsible
for sexual harassment committed by managers and supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   The court rejected two extreme positions in the sexual
harassment issue: the theory that employers cannot be held
responsible for the actions of supervisors because their actions
are outside the scope of their employment; and the theory that
employers are automatically responsible for their supervisors'
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the court found a middle ground which held that
employers are liable for the actions of a supervisor, but that they
can be released from liability depending on the reasonableness of
their anti-harassment efforts as well as the conduct of the victim
in attempting to avoid harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Wu, staff attorney for the National Organization for
Women's Legal Defense Fund, said the court had adopted a ``sensible
standard'' that would give employers a ``strong incentive ... to
adopt and enforce anti-harassment policies. Hopefully it will send
a strong signal to employers that they should take it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   In his dissent, Thomas argued that ``absent an adverse
employment consequence, an employer cannot be held ... liable if a
supervisor creates a hostile work environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' 1991 confirmation hearing in the U.S. Senate focused
national attention on the issue of sexual harassment in the
workplace when Anita Hill, a former aide at two federal agencies
where they worked, accused him of making sexually suggestive
comments to her. Thomas denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boca Raton case, the court found that city officials
failed to disseminate a 1990 city policy against sexual harassment
to beach employees, failed to keep track of its supervisors'
conduct, and failed to exercise ``reasonable care to prevent the
supervisors' harassing conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Faragher, who worked as a part-time and summer lifeguard from
1985 to 1990, filed suit in 1992 with another former lifeguard
against supervisors Bill Terry, David Silverman and Robert Gordon.
They alleged that Terry and Silverman improperly touched them and
made lewd and vulgar comments in their presence. Faragher said she
discussed their behavior with Gordon, who did not pass on the
information to higher-ranking city officials.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, U.S. District Judge Shelby Highsmith ordered Terry and
Silverman to pay Faragher a combined $10,500 and Terry to pay the
other lifeguard $37,000. He also ordered the city to pay the women
$1 in damages and about $60,000 in legal costs and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   An 11th Circuit panel reversed the district court's decision in
1996 and that was upheld in a 7-5 ruling by the full appeals court
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's ruling, Souter sided with Highsmith's finding that
``the degree of hostility in the work environment rose to the
actionable level and was attributable to Silverman and Terry.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter noted that the two supervisors ``were granted virtually
unchecked authority over their subordinates'' and that Faragher and
her fellow female lifeguards were ``completely isolated from the
city's higher management.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court rejected the appeals court's characterization
that the city ``did not effectively disseminate'' its sexual
harassment policy among beach employees. Instead, Souter agreed
with Highsmith's ``explicit finding of a 'complete failure on the
part of the city to disseminate said policy.' ``
</P>
<P>
   The court also rejected a possible defense by the city that it
should not be held liable because there was no requirement that it
issue an anti-harassment policy between 1985 and 1990, the years
Faragher worked there.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that rulings by the Equal Employment Opportunity
Commission _ for which Thomas worked prior to joining the court _
had called for prevention of sexual harassment since 1980 and the
city had adopted its original anti-harassment policy in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The court also said there was no reason to consider the merits
of Faragher's efforts to mitigate her damages ``since the ($1)
award to her was solely nominal.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
