<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALHELP FOR YOUR PC 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big red box with white lettering brings to mind the
packaging of an aspirin product. Maybe that's because above the
software title, Realhelp, has the words ``extra strength'' written
above it and the phrase ``instantly cures PC headaches'' below it.
It also proposes to: diagnose and fix problems, prevent crashes,
provide virus protection, and update software over the Internet
with its TuneUp technology.
</P>
<P>
   Okay, I'll take two now and call you in the morning. Maybe I can
get rid of this headache that keeps popping up every time my
computer starts.
</P>
<P>
   It was a worrisome little habit that my computer had developed:
Sometimes, a box would pop up on start up labeled ``sage.exe,''
saying the program has caused a problem. The box wouldn't go away,
so I would drag it off the screen and go about my business. It was
hardly a headache, but more of a pain.
</P>
<P>
   Can Realhelp find the problem?
</P>
<P>
   It did. As it turned out, that was not the end of the journey,
but the beginning of it. It found much more than I bargained for.
Some of its discoveries I judged important enough to take care of.
It discovered some missing files for two or three programs.
Reinstalling them corrected that problem. So did locating a file
that was ``missing,'' but actually was only missing from the
directory in which it should have been. It was on the hard disk.
Relocating it to its proper home solved that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some things Realhelp found, I ignored. Shortcuts, for instance,
that were around long after the program had been removed from the
hard drive are a nuisance, but they can be dealt with anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Realhelp managed to find some other odds and ends that it
considered problems. But as long as they weren't causing me
trouble, I decided to leave well enough alone.
</P>
<P>
   Realhelp from Quarterdeck is the umbrella title for a collection
of programs designed to track down lost files (the problem that
generated the ``sage.exe'' message), unused shortcuts and conflicts
between programs.
</P>
<P>
   It also runs in the background during a computing session,
keeping track of how much of a system's resource is still
available. If the system crashes, Realhelp attempts to find the
problem and correct it, and allows the data to be saved.
</P>
<P>
   It has a virus scan and repair program and monitors the hard
drive for errors that could cause problems down the road. It can
create a bootable emergency disk and find conflicts between
software.
</P>
<P>
   The Extra Strength version of the software includes a free, one
year subscription to TuneUp, an Internet service. In connection
with it, Realhelp profiles a user's computer, then determines if
new patches, updates or service packs are available for
downloading. In case users need to contact software companies, a
list of suppliers and toll-free numbers, if available, are shown
on-screen.
</P>
<P>
   Realhelp comes in two versions: Regular Strength, with a street
price of about $35-$40, and Extra Strength ($55-$60), which
includes a six-month subscription to the online TuneUp service.
</P>
<P>
   PINBALL TALES
</P>
<P>
   Pinball games for the computer aren't just pinball games. For
some reason, they have to have story lines to them.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us who think of a pinball machine as something that
stood in a dark corner of a bar or restaurant, what's to story
line? A plunger propels a chrome ball to the top of a slanted
board, gravity rolls it toward a gapping hole in the bottom,
flippers and a player with luck and skill tries to keep the ball in
play. End of story.
</P>
<P>
   Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   Timeshock from Empire Interactive involves four pinball tables
representing four different time zones: Present day is represented
by Mount Rushmore, and the pinball player must scale it by going
over ramps and hitting drop targets. Ancient Rome, complete with
chariot racing, is another time zone. Dinosaurs are found on the
prehistoric table, robots on the table representing the future. On
each table, players try to collect one fourth of a shattered time
crystal to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   The storyline doesn't matter much. Smooth scrolling graphics and
realistic ball movement are the things that can make or break a
computerized pinball game. Timeshock works well in both those
areas.
</P>
<P>
   The game has settings for four skill levels ranging from novice
(which only gives the player one ball, but assures two minutes of
game play) to Tournament (which turns off the ``extra ball''
feature so all players have the same chances during a game).
</P>
<P>
   The program is available for Windows-based computers and was
recently released for the PlayStation game console. It is the first
entry into the console market for Empire.
</P>
<P>
   If you're new to the pinball-on-computer games and like the
idea, Epic Megagames (1-800-972-7434) has a nice collection of such
programs for DOS and Windows operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. An
archive of his recent computer columns is on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/data.htm.)
</P>
</TEXT>
