</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-FLFIRE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        ATMOSPHERE SAFE FROM FLORIDA FIRES BUT LUNGS BEWARE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark D. Preston  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 26 -- Florida's air quality has reached
critically dangerous levels, but scientists agree the state's
out-of-control wildfires -- which are scorching the landscape --
pose no long-term threat to the earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Herman, a NASA atmospheric scientist stationed at Goddard
Space Flight Center in Maryland, said the smoke and pollution
produced by the fires will have no effect on the atmosphere. Herman
analyzes ozone, smoke, dust, volcanic ash and pollution from data
collected by a NASA satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (wildfires) are not small to people who live in Florida,
but they are small compared to the amount of smoke needed to have a
negative effect on the atmosphere,'' Herman said. ``For the most
part, this smoke system is very small in relation to the total
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   Herman said large-scale fires ignited intentionally by cattle
ranchers and miners in Africa and South America are a much bigger
concern for atmospheric scientists than the Florida fires because
some of those fires burn for as long as four months.
</P>
<P>
   But while the atmosphere is not suffering from the smoke and
pollution, Florida residents afflicted with respiratory problems
will be subject to an array of health problems. Especially hard hit
are the elderly, children and people with asthma and emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, what you've got is something similar to a lot of
cars running around without catalytic converters,'' said Hal
Maring, a research professor at the University of Miami's Division
of Marine and Atmospheric Chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Maring said people living downwind of smoke and ash from the
wildfires are experiencing what Los Angeles residents suffered
during the smog-filled days of the 1970s. But Maring said the smoke
should be short term because Florida is a relatively flat
peninsula, while Los Angeles is situated in a basin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida winds are predominantly east to west, and the stuff
will eventually be blown out to sea,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Green, a graduate research professor at the University of
Florida's College of Engineering who is working on energy and
environmental issues, said the wildfire's smoke is similar to
second-hand cigarette smoke. Green said a few storms should clean
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald White, director of National Programs for the American
Lung Association, said the very small particulates released from
the burning wood and vegetation can penetrate deep into lungs,
causing an array of health problems.
</P>
<P>
   White said the elderly, young children and people with chronic
breathing problems should stay indoors as much as possible until
the air becomes clean again.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, staying indoors only filters out 20 percent to 30
percent of the pollution. Since particulates act more like a gas
than a solid, they are able to pass through walls, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
