<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-ITEMS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT ITEMS: DOG DAY CARE; SOCCER JERSEYS; MUSIC (ONLY) TV; CROQUET
REDUX
</HEADLINE>
 (For release Sunday, June 28) 
(bl) 
By KIMBERLY STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teacher's Furry Pets: Every Dog Has His Day (Care)
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ted loves nursery school. He looks forward to
flirting with his girlfriend, who likes to wear a pink cape, and
enjoys being read to while sitting with his best friend. Typical
kid stuff _ except that Ted is a Yorkshire terrier; his gal pal,
Tinkerbell, is a white Maltese, and his best buddy, Huggy Bear, is
a standard poodle.
</P>
<P>
   They all attend nursery school at Doggy Do and Pussycats, Too,
at 567 Third Ave. (near 37th Street). It is one of a dozen pet
day-care centers that have opened in New York in an era of latchkey
pets, when guilty masters are no longer content just to hire a
walker. Instead, they want some stimulating recreational
activities.
</P>
<P>
   For $30 a day, Doggy Do's canine nursery school offers story
hour, snack time, nap time and crafts. (Last week's project was
Father's Day cards.)
</P>
<P>
   Admission to the schools can be very competitive, said Larry
Roth, an owner of Doggy Do. ``Like the way parents are frenzied
about what exclusive nursery school their child will get into, it's
the same for us,'' he said. ``People vie to get their dogs in
during the day, and the dogs are cliquish on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Allure magazine fashion editor Kelly Delaney, who is Ted's
owner, marvels at the schoolyard dynamics. ``The parents don't
really know each other that well, but Ted went nuts on the street
last week when he ran into Huggy Bear,'' she said. ``I even know
which dogs are mean to mine. I caught myself checking out Jesse's
mother the other day and thinking, `So that's Jesse's mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring Jerseys
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ World Cup fever is adding color to the closets of New
Yorkers. Fans are heading to Soccer Sport Supply Co., 1745 First
Ave. (near 90th Street), one of the few places where they can find
the jerseys of all 32 teams in the tournament; they are $58.95
each.
</P>
<P>
   Teams like Brazil, Italy and the United States account for most
sales, but jerseys from underdog teams with winning designs are
also moving in record volume, said Jeffrey and Herman Doss,
brothers and owners of the store.
</P>
<P>
   Among the hottest sellers: Morocco's bright red shirt with green
stripe; South Africa's white, gold and green shirt, and Jamaica's
gold jersey emblazoned with a crescent moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jamaican jersey was a beautiful design and we had all the
reggae boys coming in to buy it,'' Scott Davidson, a salesman,
said. ``We have every ethnicity buying our shirts. You should see
this place on a busy day. Everybody's ribbing each other.'' So far,
no fan brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Must-Hear TV &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ready for the post-MTV age? Music Choice, a cable
television service that recently arrived in select neighborhoods in
New York, provides customers with 24 hours of commercial-free music
programming the old-fashioned way _ without pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With a click of the remote control, a menu appears on screen
listing 31 music channels to choose from: 1970s Super Hits, Big
Bands, Classical, Musica Latina, Jazz, Lite Jazz, Contemporary
Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers of Music Choice praise it for offering song
rotations, as on radio or music-television, but without commercial
blocks, deejays, veejays or the need to wait to learn a song's
credits. As each song plays, a simple black screen displays the
title, artist, label and an 800 number to order the CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like MTV, but you're not forced to watch
hygiene-challenged rockers,'' A.J. Jacobs, a writer at
Entertainment Weekly, said as he watched (oops _ listened to)
``Please Send Me Some Love'' by Dinah Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs ``pops it on'' when he has a friend over or is
``puttering around the house.'' Why not queue up a CD? ``I like the
glow of the TV,'' he said. ``It makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallets Swing Again
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Move over, Big Bertha. This summer's swingers are
grabbing croquet mallets. The genteel pastime is making a comeback.
When choosing a set of painted woods, it's the dustier, the better.
Players are combing antique shops for vintage sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``A croquet set allows this fantasy where I'm sipping iced tea
on the rolling front lawn of a beautiful estate,'' said Lou Sagar,
the owner of Zona at 97 Greene St. (Spring Street), which sells
sets for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   Marcello Soriano, an owner of the Lively Set, an antique shop at
33 Bedford Street, is swamped with requests for croquet gear from
those who crave a Gatsby ethos.
</P>
<P>
   ``A collection of croquet balls in a metal basket or a mallet
hanging on the wall is an extremely popular look,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Insiders Scream For This Cream
</P>
<P>
   Yon-Ka skin-care products are hard to get. Once available only
at destination spas like Spa Internazionale on Fisher Island in
Florida and Gurney's Inn in Montauk, N.Y., the pricey French line
(average product cost, $28) can now be found in Manhattan at the
Bliss Spa, the Paul Labreque Salon at the Reebok Club and a handful
of other day spas. But buying Yon-Ka is still a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Because the line of 58 all-natural products is so complex and
custom-tailored, the company recommends that before making a
purchase, customers get a treatment or consultation from a licensed
esthetician, who can suggest a regimen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get bombarded daily with product lines that want to be used
at the spa; I chose Yon-Ka,'' Regina Viotto, the director at Paul
Labreque, said. ``The products are so pure and complex and meet
very specific needs.'' For those who have trouble remembering if
the Optimizer cream is applied with or without the Phyto Contour,
there is a Yon-Ka help line: (800) 533-6276.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
