<HEADER>
A8872 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-CANADA-$ADV28-     06-26 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-CANADA-$ADV28-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WARMING TREND FOR CANADIAN STOCKS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 28)  
(lb) 
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Start with a strong, rebounding economy. Add an apparently
undervalued stock market. Throw in a national currency that seems
to have been pummeled by one arctic blast after another.
</P>
<P>
   To many investors, that sounds like a recipe for bargains. And
it explains why many are hungrily watching the Canadian stock
market.
</P>
<P>
   The mere mention of Canada, though, can stop some otherwise
eager American investors cold. Over the years, the nation to the
north has produced enough seedy mining companies and dubious oil
stocks to fill the St. Lawrence Seaway. Its smaller stock exchanges
have reputations for lax regulation and even slacker enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   And deep frustration can await an investor who tries to get the
same kind of detailed information about a Canadian company that is
readily available about companies whose stocks are traded in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts see in Canada something hard to find in the
United States: plenty of upside potential.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's domestic economy could hardly look more promising.
Growth is strong, inflation is low and upward pressure on wages is
almost nonexistent. And the weakness of the Canadian dollar is
bolstering the country's exports. They will soon account for half
the country's total output.
</P>
<P>
   Still, valuations of Canadian stocks have lately lagged behind
those of their American cousins. According to Fred Sturm, portfolio
manager of the Ivy Canada mutual fund, business prospects for
companies in sectors other than natural resources, Canada's
traditional strength, are still attractive, but their stocks are
currently trading at levels 10 percent to 20 percent below those of
their south-of-the-border counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   And because Canada's commodities businesses depend heavily on
exports, now depressed by the disruptions in Asian economies,
Canadian natural-resource stocks are even cheaper, trading at
discounts of 20 percent to 30 percent to similar American stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian stocks generally would be more appealing to Joseph
Scarella, a portfolio manager at Oppenheimer Capital, if he could
see a ``spikelike bottoming'' in commodity prices in three to six
months. Those prices are low because of worldwide oversupply as
well as the Asian situation. But he said improvement would be
gradual.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Root, who works at Goldman, Sachs as an analyst of paper
and forest-product companies, likes Donohue, Domtar and MacMillan
Bloedel, Canadian companies in that field. But he said he did not
expect their stock prices to crawl out of their trough ``until the
market gets its hands around the situation in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturm, whose Ivy Canada is one of the few Canadian-oriented
mutual funds available to American investors, says low commodity
prices have created a buying opportunity. He reasons that
commodities have nowhere to go but up and that when they do,
Canadian natural-resource companies can be expected to outperform
the broader market, as they have in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Chandler of Goldman, Sachs Canada pointed out that the
weakness of Canada's currency had helped to offset the damage from
the commodity slump, keeping Canadian output competitively priced.
</P>
<P>
   Because of strong prospects for the overall Canadian economy,
Chandler said he expects Canadian stocks to return about 10 percent
over the next 12 months, just as they have over the last 12. Such a
steady pace may not look like much compared with the 28 percent
run-up of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index in the past year, but it
could be soothing to investors who worry that the U.S. market is
due for a meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that profits for Canadian companies have not yet
peaked. For the first quarter of 1998, they accounted for just 8.9
percent of Canada's national income. ``That tells us that corporate
profits aren't yet overextended,'' Chandler said. ``The historical
average is closer to 10 percent.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One way for cautious investors to play the Canadian stock market
is to invest in companies that generate a high percentage of their
revenue outside Canada. Robert Reiner, who helps manage the BT
Investment International Equity fund, sees that advantage in three
of his four favorite Canadian stocks.
</P>
<P>
   BCE, the parent of Bell Canada, is one of the few big
telecommunications companies that also has a well-situated interest
in the telephone equipment industry, which is booming worldwide.
Cadillac Fairview, which owns and develops commercial real estate,
has almost a fifth of its assets in the United States, something
that he suspects most investors haven't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Newcourt Credit is currently Reiner's top pick. The company
arranges asset-based financing for large companies and
institutions, most of them outside Canada, and is the biggest pure
play within its respective market, which is led by GE Capital,
Reiner said. He expects Newcourt's earnings to grow 50 percent next
year, yet the company's stock is trading at just 23.6 times its
estimated 1999 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   His fourth recommendation, the Royal Bank of Canada, is somewhat
surprising. Canadian bank stocks have run way up recently, posting
much bigger gains than the S&AMP;P banking index showed this year and
last, and some investors might feel edgy parking money in the
sector.
</P>
<P>
   But the Royal Bank is a leader in consolidating and has a
pending merger with the Bank of Montreal. And unlike banks in the
United States, Canada's dominate the domestic mutual-fund industry,
which is just taking off with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lori Appelbaum, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs,
Canadian bank stocks are trading at a 10 percent to 15 percent
discount to those of their American counterparts, even though
expected earnings growth is just as strong, at 12 percent to 13
percent annually. She likes Canadian Imperial Bank and Toronto
Dominion as well as Royal.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two clouds on the horizon for Canadian bank
stocks, according to Scarella at Oppenheimer Capital, and they both
emanate from the Bank of Canada, the country's central bank.
Interest rates could be raised to stem the slide of the currency,
and there could be a move to block the Royal Bank-Bank of Montreal
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this merger has only a 50-50 chance of happening,''
Scarella said. ``There's a lot of momentum building up against it,
especially among rural Canadians who think it will cause banks to
close up offices.''
</P>
<P>
   But money managers like Reiner remain bullish. ``There's this
bias that all you can buy in Canada are commodity stocks, when in
fact the country has some of the best banks, industrials and
technology companies in the world,'' he said. ``There are a lot of
overlooked stocks in Canada, and for the most part, U.S.
mutual-fund managers still haven't discovered them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
