A8882 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROMEO-GIGLI-COLOGNE-$     06-26 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMEO-GIGLI-COLOGNE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCENT OF A MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, June 28) 
(th) 
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This stinks.
</P>
<P>
   The designer fragrance that has been my signature scent for
seven years _ my personal olfactory statement for the '90s _ has
been discontinued. I got wind of this tragic bit of fragrance news
when I tried to buy a bottle of Romeo Gigli per Uomo a week and a
half ago in the Italian designer's boutique in Milan. The clerk,
while cheerful and knowledgeable, could not produce any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is finish,'' he said. ``In five or six months, we get a new
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A new shipment or a new cologne?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new for-moo-lation,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   In plain Inglese, the smell is gone. This does not make me
happy.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive experimentation with fragrance _ everything from
Aramis to Z-14 has passed my wrists since I started wearing cologne
in high school _ I finally had found one to call my own. This one
has a fresh, citrus-y top note that is a blend of bergamot, orange
and other ingredients. It develops on the skin with touches of
woods and mosses. After you wear it a while, amber notes mixed with
fir take over. Best of all, it smells fabulous on me.
</P>
<P>
   There are other scents in my boudoir. Actually, my bathroom
looks like the main floor of Bloomingdale's. I have bottles of
Angel for Men, Chanel Pour Monsieur, Comme des Garcons, Bulgari
Cologne au The Vert, Acqua di Gio, Joop!, and Feeling Man and
Background by Jil Sander.
</P>
<P>
   There's even some Todd Oldham in there, too _ a woman's perfume
that happens to work on me. I wear all of them at times. But
mostly, they're just spray-bottle status symbols adding a bit of
glamour to the top of my toilet tank.
</P>
<P>
   Call me a fragrance victim.
</P>
<P>
   But these were all giveaways _ sample bottles handed out at
store openings, fragrance promotions and fashion shows. Romeo Gigli
per Uomo was the only scent I replaced whenever I started running
low. How could I not? This fragrance had become a part of my style
over the years. To my friends and loved ones, it didn't smell like
Romeo Gigli, it smelled like me.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't get dressed for a serious date or an important
meeting without it there to boost my self-confidence. Every spritz
smelled sexy and assured even when I felt like a frump. I have
rarely been so attached to a product. But scent is powerful that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Gigli per Uomo became the aroma of my 30s, the romantic
odor of my not-so-young adulthood. I would get old, but the back of
my ears could always smell the same. Or so I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Now that there is a finite supply of the cologne out there, I've
started haunting Cosmetics Plus and other fragrance purveyors. I
feel like Elaine on that episode of ``Seinfeld,'' searching for her
favorite contraceptive sponges once they've been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   I've been somewhat lucky, scoring a bottle of my favorite green
elixir here and there. The Gigli store in Manhattan is out, but
Barneys New York, I'm told, does have a stash of my favorite
splash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very new that we have it back in stock,'' Heidi
Manheimer, a divisional merchandise manager for fragrance at the
store, said the other day. She said she had no idea it was
discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's because Romeo Gigli per Uomo came and went
quietly. With a shy air of exclusivity, it hit the market in 1991.
The bottle didn't even bear a label, just a tiny clear sticker on
the underside with the designer's name. It was never a blockbuster
like Egoiste, which was introduced the year before by Chanel, but
it did garner a loyal following during its life span. A second
Gigli men's fragrance, called Sud Est, followed but didn't last
long enough for me even to try it. Apparently, many fragrances
vanish as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, between 60 and 70 fragrances are introduced and
maybe 10 make it in a meaningful way,'' explained Annette Green,
the president of the Fragrance Foundation, a nonprofit educational
arm of the fragrance industry. ``Another 10 may straggle along for
a while and then either disappear or find a tiny niche.'' Gigli,
she said, ``attracted a very solid audience, but the company that
was distributing it went under.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who love a scent stick with it through thick and thin. As
Ms. Manheimer said, ``People get very attached to their
fragrance.'' My allegiance to Romeo Gigli per Uomo has never been
high-minded. It is just that this cologne is to me what Viagra is
to other men.
</P>
<P>
   A little behind each ear and cappuccino baristas are asking for
my home number. With the right fragrance, life can be a Hai Karate
commercial _ strangers do run after you, bewitched by your smell.
</P>
<P>
   You don't get that with Old Spice.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gigli's Milan publicity office would not tell me
anything about the new fragrance it plans to introduce next year.
When the scent makes its debut, I will, of course, give it a try. I
trust the name. It could turn out to be wonderful. But just in
case, I'm stocking up. I want to smell like myself for as long as I
can. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1642EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
