<SLUG> BC-SPICE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 SPICE GIRLS: GIRL POWER _ AND MERCHANDISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scary Spice can sing. Sporty Spice can dance (or at least do
high kicks). Baby Spice and Posh Spice are passable at both tasks.
And competence is all the four Spice Girls need to activate the
most cleverly conceived and slickly marketed pop package since
Madonna showed them the blueprints.
</P>
<P>
   At the PNC Bank Arts Center in Holmdel, N.J., on a tour that
takes them to Madison Square Garden in New York on July 1, the
Spice Girls smiled and strutted their way through a pageant of what
might be called buy-me feminism.
</P>
<P>
   For a sold-out house filled with little girls, like an
elementary-school assembly with parents invited, the Spice Girls
worked the stage like a fashion-show runway. Through nearly a dozen
costume changes, they touted ``girl power'': a mandate to enjoy
female bonding, push men around, wear snazzy clothes and sell
things along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Albums, videos, T-shirts and programs apparently aren't enough
products for the Spice Girls to plug. Before the Girls' two sets
and during an intermission, commercials were shown for cosmetics
and sugar, two things little girls don't need. And as the group
sang ``Move Over,'' a cola logo was projected on the video screen.
In the Spice Girls' pop utopia, a fulfilled woman has loyal
girlfriends, a tractable man and a contract as a spokesmodel.
</P>
<P>
   The songs themselves, performed with a live band and taped
backup vocals, are an assortment of upbeat pop, from Motown to
disco to reggae to hip-hop to big-band swing to hard rock, and full
of benign messages.
</P>
<P>
   They tell would-be boyfriends to be honest, respectful and good
dancers; ballads like ``Two Become One'' and ``Naked'' (which the
Girls performed bare-shouldered and hidden behind strategically
designed chairs) promise that love will bring complete closeness.
</P>
<P>
   Their borrowed material, ``Sisters Are Doin' It for Themselves''
and ``We Are Family,'' proclaimed female solidarity. And in songs
like ``Spice Up Your Life,'' the Spice Girls advertise themselves
as a guarantee of fun.
</P>
<P>
   The Spice Girls themselves are dutiful and a little gawky,
vamping in ways they've learned from rock videos. But the songs,
more than the act, are the Spice Girls' real asset. Stealing widely
and well, the songs stay catchy as they spell out the group's
flirtations and demands. They're exuberant, direct and immediately
likable, and they've turned a group of hard-working but only
moderately gifted performers into stars.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, each Spice Girl acted out her nickname, more or less.
Emma Bunton (Baby) had her twin ponytails and sequined baby-doll
dresses, and sang ``Where Did Our Love Go?'' (which begins, ``Baby,
baby''); Melanie Chisholm (Sporty) flexed her muscles and wore, at
one point, the jersey for England's World Cup soccer team. Victoria
Adams (Posh), with a new short haircut, held herself with a hint of
reserve; Melanie Brown (Scary) was more vigorous than frightening
in her leopard-patterned clothes. Six male dancers played
deferential suitors, usually ending up at the Girls' feet.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger Spice (Geri Halliwell) has left the group but is not
forgotten. The Spice Girls haven't gotten around to revising their
video and audiotapes, so ``The Lady Is a Vamp'' still names Ginger
as a Spice Girl, and the video for ``Mama'' shows her baby photo.
But editing Ginger out, or replacing her, would take time, and the
Spice Girls, like all pop phenomena, know they have to seize their
moment while it lasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
