A8887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SPORTS-$ADV28-ART-     06-26 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPORTS-$ADV28-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADICAL! NEW YORK IS ADVENTURE-SPORT CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 28)  
 (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
 (ja) 
 By INGRID ABRAMOVITCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A couple of years ago, Eric Stiller, a kayaking
instructor who looks like Popeye in Polartec and who once paddled
halfway around Australia, was preparing to move to Seattle.
Stiller, who approaches kayaking with an almost religious fervor,
was giving up on New York, a city where some people's idea of an
adventure sport is diving through closing subway doors.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner had he packed his paddles than he got a call from
the newly opened Chelsea Piers sports complex inviting him to start
a kayak program from a dock on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like `Field of Dreams' _ build it, and they will
come,'' said Stiller, whose decision to stay proved propitious.
Since he founded the Manhattan Kayak Company, the city, once a mere
concrete jungle, has started to look increasingly like an urban
jungle gym. Clad in trail-running shoes and enough Gore-Tex and
microfleece to bivouac on Mount McKinley, New Yorkers have leapt
full force into adventure sports, like much of the rest of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stiller paddles up and down the Hudson from dawn to dusk,
gliding by fellow kayakers like John F. Kennedy Jr. and pointing
out the barnacles clinging to Manhattan's aging docks, a sign that
the water quality is improving.
</P>
<P>
   Validation that New York can compete recreationally with any
city on the planet came last year, when Outside magazine ranked it
one of the world's great towns for outdoor enthusiasts. ``Yes, you
read correctly,'' the editors wrote, clearly bracing for a barrage
of hate mail from readers who put up with 100 straight days of rain
for the privilege of paddling across Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   But who needs Boulder, Colo., when you can boulder in Central
Park, parasail by the Statue of Liberty or surf the Rockaways? New
York's diverse geographic terrain, with its tidal channels, deep
harbor and rocky outcrops so impressed the California-based
organizers of the 3-year-old Hi-Tec Adventure Racing Series that
they will hold their first urban adventure race here Sunday, in
Pelham Bay Park in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Epstein, executive producer of the series, said he
searched the country for a metropolitan area with terrain rugged
enough to hold the race _ in which 200 teams of three athletes each
run six miles on forest trails, kayak one hour and race mountain
bikes 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most cities are so developed they don't meet our parameters,''
Epstein said. ``For sure, New York is the best place.''
</P>
<P>
   Stefani Jackenthal, an Upper West Sider who is competing in the
Hi-Tec race, hoped that by training in and around New York she
would gain a home-field edge. Ms. Jackenthal, 31, who sports
diamond studs and black Adidas trail-runners with white mesh
inserts that civilians won't be able to buy until next year (she
tests them for the company), spends a typical weekend biking 50
miles, paddling on the Hudson and carrying a 40-pound pack through
the Ramble in Central Park. While many of her friends have moved to
San Francisco or Denver, Ms. Jackenthal insists it is possible to
live as an adventure athlete in New York. ``There's a pretty deep
community of triathletes, runners and cyclists,'' she said. ``You
can't believe how packed it is in Central Park from 5:30 to 9 in
the morning, with runners, cyclists and in-line skaters all
fighting for space.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while New Yorkers munch on Powerbars, available at every
corner deli, and shop at stores like Colorado in SoHo, where
mannequins rappel down a two-story climbing wall in the front
window, some might wonder if these urban gearheads venture any
further than the dance floor at Twilo. After all, if you want to
wear Ralph Lauren's Extreme Polo Sport men's cologne, or the Prada
Sport line of mountain clothes, the main muscle you'll need to flex
is financial.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a series of recent outings around the city turned
up all sorts of locales in which to pursue adventure sports, along
with New Yorkers who were the picture of rude health, carrying on
as though they were in the Alps. In Central Park, Rodney Weber, a
tanned and shirtless fashion model, was traversing the 16-foot-high
boulder known to climbers as Rat Rock.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to bring a brush and a rake with you to sweep away
the rubbish,'' said Weber, who scouts the park for other outcrops
of Manhattan schist to climb, but warns that there can be ``a lot
of needles'' at their base.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Wall Street bond traders who rather than
entertain clients with the usual after-work drinks and dinner, took
them parasailing instead. The group of five hopped a seven-minute
water taxi behind the World Financial Center to Liberty State Park
in Jersey City, where Alex Santoriello of Parasail New York was
waiting. He steered his small ocean boat, the Airgasm, toward lower
Manhattan, while a crewman hooked one of the Wall Streeters to a
large yellow parachute. The Airgasm raced ahead, and the woman was
lifted into the air until her chute was soaring 300 feet over New
York Harbor. Santoriello turned in the direction of the Statue of
Liberty, then steered toward the World Trade Center for a sunset
view.
</P>
<P>
   And off Pier 63 Maritime, at 23d Street and the Hudson River,
there was a scene out of ``Hawaii Five-O'': six paddlers from the
New York Outrigger canoe club chanted in Polynesian as they
propelled an ocean-going outrigger canoe along the city's
coastline. ``It's big surf, big waves,'' said Matt Herbert, a
28-year-old architect, who was one of the paddlers. ``When we get
down to Liberty, we have to really fight through the swell.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even in the water, it's hard to leave the city
entirely behind. James Arnold, who surfs weekdays at Rockaway Beach
in Queens to escape the stress of running his Manhattan
construction company, said he finds his outdoor sport
``infectious.'' He added archly: ``And that would cover the water.
It can get pretty funky out there.''
</P>
<P>
   For surfers, Rockaway isn't exactly the Banzai Pipeline. The
waves average three to six feet and break close to the shore.
Still, Arnold said, ``you can ride a block or two.'' (His sense of
distance is obviously different from that on Oahu.) The best
surfing is from August through December, when hurricanes far out in
the Atlantic Ocean increase the swell up to 10 feet. What's more,
Arnold said, surfers at Rockaway are welcoming to newcomers, not
always the case at popular beaches in California and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Jokes aside, experts say the waterways around New York City are
cleaner than they have been in decades, thanks to strict
environmental laws and new sewage treatment plants. And the
adventure athlete can always get out of town. One reason New York
qualifies as a great outdoor city, according to Outside, is its
proximity to a wide variety of natural landscapes, from hiking
gorges at Bear Mountain to trout streams in the Catskills.
</P>
<P>
   On weeknights, at the 46-foot-high textured fiberglass climbing
wall at Chelsea Piers, many of the regulars are staying in
condition for weekend trips to the Shawangunk Mountains, west of
New Paltz, N.Y., considered one of the top climbing ranges in the
country. ``I think New Yorkers are sick of stinky gyms in the
basement,'' said Les Pawlak, who teaches climbing every other day
at the Chelsea Piers and on alternate days drives the 2 1/2 hours
to the ``Gunks'' (as climbers call the Shawangunks). ``Seven years
ago, there would be 20 cars at the Gunks on a warm Sunday,'' he
said. ``Now, you have 50 cars there on weekdays, and hundreds on
weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Others with high-pressure New York careers have substituted
noon-time power outings for power lunches. Glenn Lazzaro, who
directs films and commercials, works mornings in NoHo, then drives
to Harriman State Park in Rockland County to ride a wake board, a
type of surfboard, on a lake, or to ride a mountain bike on his
lunch hour. By midafternoon, he is back in his office. ``If I left
right now,'' he said one afternoon at his desk, ``I could be
mountain biking in 45 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazzaro pretty much has to leave the city to do his trail
riding, because off-road mountain biking is the one sport not
welcome in the concrete jungle. Although mountain bikers have been
spotted on the horse trails at Clove Lakes Park on Staten Island,
among other places, mountain bikes are permitted only on paved
paths in city parks. Ride off-road, and you're likely to be slapped
with a summons and a $50 fine. An exception was made for Sunday's
Hi-Tec race.
</P>
<P>
   (Of course, many city cyclists choose a mountain bike for
ordinary street riding, since the pot-holed pavement and kamikaze
traffic present a fair approximation of wilderness obstacles.)
</P>
<P>
   Many adventure athletes say that what propels them to cling to
the side of a cliff by their fingertips are those moments when they
feel especially mortal. In a city where everyday survival can
sometimes feel like a death-defying act, adventure pursuits might
seem redundant. But the New Yorkers engaged in these sports love
the intense focus and physical exertion. It takes their minds off
of urban routines, they say, giving them a new-found sense of
place.
</P>
<P>
   From the cockpit of a kayak at 8 in the morning, Manhattan looks
especially glamorous. Its spires sparkle in the early-morning
light, and the honking trucks and steaming asphalt are far away.
This is nature, wild and free _ give or take one or two floating
Snapple bottles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
