<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GALLO-PROFILE-2TAKES-     06-26 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLO-PROFILE-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER'S VISION HITS HOME IN BUFFALO, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (Duplication warning: also sent with `e' code)  
 (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his new movie, ``Buffalo 66,'' Vincent Gallo plays Billy
Brown, a young man newly released from prison who kidnaps a pouty
tap-dance student. Desperate to prove to his parents that he has
made something of his life, he forces her to play the part of his
adoring young wife.
</P>
<P>
   The pair visits Billy's parents at their house in Buffalo, N.Y.,
where the mother, an obsessive football fan, interrupts intimate
conversations with a son she hasn't seen in five years to watch a
tape of a Super Bowl game. She tells Billy's ``wife'' that one of
her great regrets was having missed a Buffalo Bills game because
she was giving birth to Billy.
</P>
<P>
   Billy's father announces when he sees his son at the door,
``Jan, your son is here,'' and turns away.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo, long a fixture of Manhattan's eclectic art community _ he
was a painter, actor and Calvin Klein model before he became a
writer-director _ has acknowledged the autobiographical basis of
``Buffalo 66.'' It is set in his hometown, and he shot scenes in
his own childhood home and used his father's 1960s crooning on the
soundtrack. The portrayal of the two pathologically tough,
unfeeling parents is not for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed an odd and even zanily self-destructive gesture to
hold the premiere of ``Buffalo 66'' in Buffalo, and to take part in
a big family picnic on the afternoon preceding it. As one cousin of
Gallo's, a former boxer named Louis ``Kid'' Gallo, said after
seeing the movie: ``If he had made that movie about my parents, I
would have punched his lights out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the picnic last Saturday, in a public park outside Buffalo,
the filmmaker's mother, Janet Gallo, wore a gold necklace and
pinkie ring that spelled out ``Bills'' in looping script. In the
movie, the character of the mother, named Jan, is played with
frantic, self-absorbed intensity by Angelika Huston.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmaker's father, Vincent Gallo Sr., was playing boccie
with Uncle Eugene. Vincent Jr. strolled up to Vincent Sr. and the
father shook his son's hand, then kissed him stiffly on the cheek
in the manner of Italian men, evoking familial love along with a
courteous detachment. And that was all. The two men barely spoke
for the rest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my family,'' Gallo said as he surveyed the park, where
the all-American drama of a Little League game unfolded behind the
barbecue pit. In his flared brown pinstripe pants, tight T-shirt
and motorcycle boots, his hair in wild curls, Gallo looked very
much the hip Manhattan dandy come home to show off his new duds and
new life.
</P>
<P>
   As he put a Led Zeppelin compact disk in the portable stereo,
his bright blue eyes took in the dozens of family members lunching
on hamburgers and hot dogs, beans and sausages, chopped salad and
barbecued chicken. ``Can you believe it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo ran away to New York City when he was 16, he said, and has
rarely returned. He began his career as a painter, showing with the
Soho dealer Annina Nosei and playing in rock bands with Jean-Michel
Basquiat. He educated himself. He picked up acting and has appeared
in 15 movies of a decidedly avant-garde slant, including Abel
Ferrara's ``The Funeral'' and Kiefer Sutherland's ``Truth or
Consequences, N.M.'' He appeared as a scruffy, suspicious-looking
monologuist in several commercials shot by Richard Avedon for
Calvin Klein's fragrance CK Be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buffalo 66,'' which opened in New York on Friday, is the first
film he has written and directed. He spent $100,000 of his own
money (``and that's a lot, a lot, for me,'' he said) on the film.
When it was shown at the New Directors/New Films Series in New
York, Janet Maslin praised it in The New York Times as ``a deadpan
original, mixing pathos with bravado.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the time I was a teen-ager to now, I've only visited
Buffalo a handful of times,'' the filmmaker said a few days after
the premiere. ``Until I met people in New York, people who were
adult and who understood my pathology slightly, until that moment
in my life, I was in deep agony. I couldn't tell anybody that I was
severely depressed or anxious or out of my mind, really. All the
voices of my mother and father I thought I could transcend by
leaving Buffalo I actually continued to inflict on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo said that when he was 9 years old, he got a job so he
could get out of the house where his frequently unemployed father
was a permanent fixture. ``Dad was this kind of dark, raging
figurehead,'' he remembered. ``That's not who he is today, but when
I was a child there wasn't a day when he taught me anything, spent
time with me, encouraged me _ not a day when he didn't hit me,
punish me, yell at me or tell me something I did wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing the script was a big catharsis for me,'' he added. ``I
started writing it in 1989, so all the family scenes were written
years ago, all the family characters. I gave my parents a copy of
the script back then, almost taunting them, daring them to read it.
And they pretended they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo seems to thrive on conflict in both his personal and
professional lives. He doesn't rely on public-relations advice to
the extent that other actors do, and the resulting frank talk with
reporters gets him into trouble. In the months leading up to the
film's release, he entered into a tabloid battle with Ms. Huston.
``And she'll probably never speak to me again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither, probably, will Sharon Stone, who Gallo said stole an
idea of his, interviewing herself for Harper's Bazaar after Gallo
had interviewed himself for a magazine called Grand Royal. Last
month, Gallo accused Icon magazine of using the one photograph for
their July/August cover that he did not approve, which also landed
him in the gossip columns.
</P>
<P>
   And when ``Buffalo 66'' wasn't accepted into the Cannes Film
Festival, he publicly announced that he had given up his passport,
saying that Cannes had become pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo not only conceived, wrote, directed and starred in
``Buffalo 66,'' he also scored and performed the soundtrack, and
designed the glittering post-disco makeup and the baby-doll dress
worn by Christina Ricci, who plays the blond teeny-bopper he
presses into wifely service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous how good-looking she is,'' he said. ``You just
want to pick her up and marry her and love her and kiss her.''
</P>
<P>
   After the family picnic, everyone drove convoy-style to the
premiere of ``Buffalo 66'' at the North Park Theater on Hertel
Avenue in downtown Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Packs of pierced teenagers hovered outside the theater, looking
for movie stars. It was Buffalo's first movie premiere since ``The
Natural'' in 1984. Ms. Ricci and actresses Gaby Hoffman and Asia
Argento showed up. There were also Manhattan friends of Gallo's,
like Jane Pratt, the editor of Jane magazine; Anna Condo, an
art-world figure, and Paige Powell, a former editor of Interview
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo _ stepping from a limousine, wearing leather and looking
like a rock star _ led some of his former classmates from Buffalo's
Sweet Home High School through the throng. During his opening
remarks, he eschewed the squealing microphone and shouted, ``I'd
like to thank my parents for . . .'' and then he paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inspiration!'' someone shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo stroked his chin. ``For coming tonight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The movie rolled, and the audience laughed in recognition at the
familiar Gallo-family mannerisms of Ms. Huston and Ben Gazzara, who
played the role of the father. When Wendy King _ a former Buffalo
Bills cheerleader whose maiden name was lent to the unattainable
former beauty queen played in the movie by Rosanna Arquette _
recognized herself, she shouted out in an admonishing, mothering
tone, ``Vincent!'' and hundreds of people laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the film, Billy Brown leads his faux wife to a
hotel, where he plots to murder a Bills place-kicker whom he blames
for a bad bet with a bookie that landed him in prison. Ms. Ricci's
character has by now fallen in love with Billy, and it seems as if
she has persuaded him to fall in love with her, too.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gallo's mother had seen an advance screening of
``Buffalo 66'' in New York in March, Gallo's father was watching it
for the first time. He sat stonily through its often brutal
portrait of family life, laughing only occasionally. The central
plot of the film is interposed with flashbacks from Billy Brown's
childhood. In one, the father strangles his young son's puppy after
the dog wets the rug. Gallo Sr. never strangled his son's puppy _
but the moment obviously had a metaphorical truth for Gallo Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the filmmaker's father incongruously pronounced ``Buffalo
66'' ``an all-around terrific movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Was he disturbed by scenes showing the father as violent and
remote? Gallo said ``No,'' then ``Yes,'' then ``No'' again.
``Vincent did very well in it,'' he concluded. And that's all he
would say.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents and I have never really done any activities
together. Apart from my mother coming here a few months ago for the
screening, we had no real conversations about my work in any way.
When she saw the film, it was the first time she was ever involved
in my art like that. She was never involved.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mrs. Gallo said, ``I might have overlooked Vincent
a little. It's true that he did all of this on his own. We didn't
support him at all. Which is sad. You know, the first child gets
everything, and the baby is always the baby _ cherished, you
know?'' ( Gallo has an older brother, Charles, and a younger
sister, Janine).
</P>
<P>
   ``So the middle child is the one who gets overlooked, who gets
the hand-me-downs and not enough attention,'' she said. ``I guess I
overlooked Vincent because he had a strong personality. With
Charles, if I gave him a cookie and put him on a blanket he'd sit
there for seven hours. If I did that with Vincent, he'd look at me,
mash the cookie and then go off and jam his fingers into an
electrical outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably heard that middle-child stuff on TV,'' Gallo
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what he considers a tormented childhood, Gallo doesn't
see ``Buffalo 66'' as an excuse to punish his parents. And it seems
he has partially resolved his relationship with them. The day after
the movie's premiere, he spent Father's Day with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good day,'' he said. ``I'm not looking to get revenge
and external approval to find the serenity and self-approval I
should live with some day. Making this movie gives me, well, it's
not the satisfaction you get when you're a twisted kid and kill a
bug or something. It's not a destructive satisfaction. It doesn't
come with hurting anyone else. It comes from exciting someone else.
It's like cooking a big delicious meal for all of your friends.''
</P>
<P>
   At Recckio's Bowling Lanes in South Buffalo _ another site used
for one of the film's more surreal scenes _ the Gallo family
mingled after the screening with the actresses and editors who
showed up from Manhattan. There was iced coffee, beer, heart-shaped
cookies and Buffalo wings. Everyone had an opinion. Rose Cerasa, a
family friend, said, ``We know that Janet's OK. She's cool. But her
husband, we're not so sure about.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip Mussen, a classmate from Sweet Home High School, jerked his
thumb at the quasi-Shriner's hat Ms. Powell, the former Interview
editor, was wearing and said, ``This is a bit wild for Buffalo.
It's not often we get hats like that up here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Gallo, munching on a Buffalo wing, said she didn't
think anyone in the family would be upset about the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people in Buffalo will have a negative outlook about the
movie,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its wrenching portrayal of the parents?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' she said. ``Because we lost that Super Bowl. But we
lost three other ones after that. We lost four in a row! But you
know what? It's tough. You just have to pick yourself up and move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   And she said: ``I don't think Angelika Huston added anything to
this film.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
