<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-LIBRAR     06-26 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINCOLN-CENTER-LIBRARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECOND ACT: THE PERFORMING ARTS LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Behind all the monumental structures at Lincoln
Center is a seemingly small, unobtrusive building. On one side is
the high-vaulted Metropolitan Opera House and on the other is the
Vivian Beaumont Theater with neon lights billboarding its current
theatrical attractions.
</P>
<P>
   The middle building, the New York Public Library for the
Performing Arts, looks like an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The library has long been invisible on this campus,'' says the
architect James Stewart Polshek. It is, however, one of the most
popular and essential elements of Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, it surrounds the Beaumont, spreading out into the
large, windowless travertine block that sits atop the theater. When
the $30 million renovation of the library, as redesigned by
Polshek, is completed in 2000, the building will have considerably
expanded its facilities, insuring its role as one of New York's
primary cultural resources.
</P>
<P>
   This will be, said Robert Marx, the executive director of the
Performing Arts Library, ``the most comprehensive rehabilitation of
a Lincoln Center building since Philharmonic Hall was turned into
Avery Fisher Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   The process will be similar. The occupants will move out at the
end of July, and except for a few spaces, the interior of the
library will be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure will be named the Dorothy and Lewis B. Cullman
Center after its primary benefactors. The Cullmans gave $30 million
to the Public Library, $12.5 million earmarked for the Performing
Arts structure. Financial support will also come from the family of
Donald and Mary Oenslager and the City of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Built 33 years ago, the library has long since outgrown its
quarters. Marx credits the original architect, Gordon Bunshaft,
with a visionary plan: ``It was an attempt to make it more than a
library, a place where collections would be illuminated by
performances and exhibitions,'' but the building was designed to
accommodate growth for only 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, it was not evident that it would be of such enormous
value to a wide range of people or that the theater collection
would be the most frequently used division.
</P>
<P>
   Marx added, ``At the end of his life, Bunshaft actually
apologized for this building, saying it was an instance where his
personal esthetics were allowed to override the needs of the
client, which happens a lot with architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially the library houses eight million items. Among those
singular items is the entire theatrical clipping file of 20 million
pieces. There are four major research collections: theater, dance,
music and the Rodgers and Hammerstein Archives of Recorded Sound,
the second largest sound archive in the United States, after the
Library of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Within the collections are two other important archival
resources, Theater on Film and Tape (known as TOFT) and the Jerome
Robbins Archive of the Recorded Moving Image, which serves a
similar purpose for dance. In addition, there are special bequests
and purchases, all of which make the library an invaluable
repository of the historical and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   The library will be redesigned so it can more comfortably handle
the 350,000 visitors that it has every year, plus telephone, fax
and Internet inquiries. There will be new listening and viewing
rooms and perhaps most significant, a central reading room that
will coordinate the services of the collections.
</P>
<P>
   That room will be on the top floor of the library, where there
has been a large exhibition space, and new windows will face
Amsterdam Avenue. The exterior of the building facing the Lincoln
Center plaza will not be altered.
</P>
<P>
   The TOFT archive (of 3,880 items) includes productions in New
York, regional theater and foreign companies like the Piccolo
Teatro of Milan, dialogues with theater artists and such oddities
as a complete set of television commercials by the actor Jack
Gilford. There are also outtakes of Broadway shows shot for use by
television theater critics.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Siegel of ABC contributed 20 minutes of that Broadway
fiasco ``Moose Murders,'' otherwise unrecorded by the library.
Along with other archival items, the videotapes are available only
for private viewing and not for commercial release.
</P>
<P>
   The dance archive, which Robbins financed with royalties from
his production of ``Fiddler on the Roof,'' constitutes more than 50
percent of the dance collection, which also includes tapes given to
the library by visiting companies.
</P>
<P>
   Leading a private tour behind the scenes, Marx revealed a world
that is sharply divided between the users (including scholars and
authors working on projects) and a library staff of 138.
</P>
<P>
   In every room people were listening to music, watching videos or
doing research, often at laptop computers. Meanwhile, backstage,
staff members were gathering items from the stacks and files or
programming them to appear on television screens.
</P>
<P>
   Acting as docent, the director walked to the basement, an
artifact-filled jumble, and pointed out the one door that links the
library to the Beaumont. He then went to a small, windowless room
occupied by Adrian Cosentini, the chief audio engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Among many other things, Cosentini was responsible for the
transfer of the Mapleson wax cylinders to audiotape. These were the
secret recordings made by Lionel Mapleson, the Metropolitan Opera
librarian, of performances at the opera between 1901 and 1904. In
the mid-1980s, those performances were released as a set of
long-playing records. Similarly, there are pirated tapings of
Broadway musicals in the theater collection.
</P>
<P>
   Down a long hallway near the theater collection was an
exhibition of letters from the library's archive: Robert Moses
demanding the removal of Joseph Papp from Central Park (letters
signed Moses, as if the signature were an act of God), letters to
and from Cheryl Crawford and Lillian Gish, production
correspondence of Richard Rodgers and Joshua Logan and, rarest of
all, a letter from Houdini, who seldom wrote letters, perhaps
preferring telepathic communication.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning July 20 all these objects will be moved, with the
circulating collections going to the mid-Manhattan library at Fifth
Avenue and 40th Street and the research collections to the library
annex at 521 West 43rd St., and performance programs shifted to
Cooper Union.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if all goes according to schedule, by the end of 2000,
everything will return to Lincoln Center to the grand new library,
now visible, which Paul LeClerc, president of the New York Public
Library, calls the ``cerebellum of the performing arts industry in
New York _ and the world.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
