<HEADLINE>
IN ACCOUNTING MERGER, STOCK MUST GO, SO WORKERS FACE TAX BILLS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANNE TERGESEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With stocks both volatile and expensive, it's not easy to find
good investments these days. Imagine how much more difficult it
would be if a quarter of all public companies and more than half
the mutual funds were off limits.
</P>
<P>
   That is the situation confronting many of the 140,000 employees
of Price Waterhouse and Coopers &AMP; Lybrand, the accounting giants
that will officially become _ deep breath, please _
PricewaterhouseCoopers on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ethics rules forbid accountants from owning stock in a client.
So many Price Waterhouse employees must scramble to unload
investments in the clients of Coopers, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Among the forbidden holdings are many blue-chip stocks and
mutual funds considered investment staples, like IBM, AT&AMP;T,
Hewlett-Packard, Exxon, Ford Motor, Chase Manhattan, Johnson &AMP;
Johnson and the Fidelity and Vanguard fund families.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have until the end of July to comply, with no leeway,
said Gerald M. Ward, a partner at Price Waterhouse. With the stock
market near record highs, those who must sell may face big tax hits
unless they have losses to offset the capital gains.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants can face this problem every time they accept new
clients, but not on this burdensome a scale, Ward said. This time,
some of the bean counters are not going quietly.
</P>
<P>
   There is no official plan to help affected employees shield
gains when they sell, though there was talk of setting up a sort of
joint blind trust that would have allowed Price Waterhouse
employees to pool their forbidden shares in a professionally
managed partnership and defer some taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was rejected in part because it would have meant
sharing one another's investing mistakes, too, said Lawrence
Portnoy, a Price Waterhouse partner.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, neither firm says it has done much besides reminding
employees to purge their portfolios of the 3,217 public companies
that the two firms audit.
</P>
<P>
   Informally, individuals sitting on steep capital gains have
weighed various options. One is to give appreciated stock to
dependent children over age 13. Under the rules, the children
themselves must sell by the deadline, but their capital gains tax
rate on the first $20,000 is likely to be 10 percent, half that of
the parents, said Bernard Kent, a tax partner at Coopers &AMP; Lybrand.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to give shares to charity. Donor-advised
funds offered by community foundations and mutual fund companies
like Fidelity accept and manage cash and securities, distributing
gifts to charities at the donors' recommendation. Besides skipping
capital gains taxes, the donor gets a tax deduction and the fund
earns tax-free interest for further gifts, Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   A variation on the theme, more suited to younger employees with
sizable gains, is a charitable remainder trust. The stock must
still be sold, but the trust, which is tax-exempt, can do the
selling, and the donor can retain some of the profits through an
annuity, Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   One retired Price Waterhouse partner, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity, used methods like these to sidestep nearly all of a
potential $42,000 tax bill and secure a tax deduction. The partner
sold $80,000 worth of losers and marginal performers for a net gain
of $7,000, but he gave his winners _ $250,000 worth of stock in
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand clients _ to children, grandchildren, and
charities, making the charitable contributions directly and through
foundations and a donor-advised fund.
</P>
<P>
   Others say they plan to simply sell their stock, pay the tax
bill and reinvest what remains in a shrinking list of acceptable
replacements. Kent, for one, is unloading his family's Vanguard
funds, which comprise about a third of their portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife has been with Vanguard longer than she has been with
me,'' he said. ``It was extremely traumatic for her to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   The firms, too, must purge 401(k) and other retirement plans of
funds run by each other's clients, with Coopers replacing all six
funds in one plan, Kent said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock-ownership rules are part of a broad ethics code
intended to prevent conflicts of interest for auditors, who might
otherwise be tempted to sign off on cooked books to improve stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Retired and current partners who share in an auditing firm's
profits are barred from investing in every client, while salaried
managers need only avoid stock in clients audited by the office
where they work, said Kenneth E. Dakdduk, a partner at Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand.
</P>
<P>
   Spouses, children and support staff are also covered under
certain conditions; violations can result in lost licenses.
</P>
<P>
   The profession's self-regulatory organization is working to
overhaul the ethics rules. While the stock ownership restriction is
not currently on the table, Ward said, the standards may change
because of a general feeling that, as accounting firms grow larger
and develop large consulting practices, rules that made sense for a
simple auditing practice are becoming obsolete.
</P>
</TEXT>
