<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WATCH-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW A CLOSED-END FUND AIMS TO TAME ITS DISCOUNT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Mass.)   (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shareholders have complained for ages that closed-end funds
often trade at steep discounts to their net asset values. For just
as long, fund managements have, by and large, shrugged their
shoulders over the matter. But now one fund seems determined to
prove that it takes the issue seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The France Growth fund, with $275 million in assets, has adopted
a plan intended to reduce the fund's discount to net asset value,
in part by cutting the fund adviser's fee by a percentage equal to
that of the discount.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, announced on June 16, the fund adviser's current
fee would be cut some 18 percent to reflect the fund's current 18
percent discount.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike open-end mutual funds, which issue and redeem shares at
net asset value, closed-end funds issue a fixed number of shares
that trade like those of ordinary companies. As such, they may
trade at a premium or discount to their net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   Activist shareholders have increasingly sought to force
closed-end funds to convert to open-end status as a way of
eliminating the discount. Some shareholders have filed lawsuits or
engaged in proxy fights that can become nasty.
</P>
<P>
   France Growth is not involved in any such battle, but it could
feel pressure down the road.
</P>
<P>
   According to Frederick J. Schmidt, vice president and treasurer
of the fund, the fee-cutting move is meant to align the fund
management's interests with those of its shareholders. ``This is
something that is to our mind unique to the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Others agree. ``This is historic _ it's never been done,'' said
David Schachter, a vice president at Thomas J. Herzfeld Advisors, a
closed-end fund research and advisory firm based in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's adviser, Indocam International Investment Services, a
unit of Credit Agricole, the big French bank, currently receives a
management fee equal to 0.9 percent for the first $100 million of
assets under management, according to Schmidt, and 0.8 percent on
assets above that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new policy, Schmidt said, Indocam will not be entitled
to a higher fee if the fund's shares begin to trade at a premium to
their net asset value.
</P>
<P>
   In another move to reduce fees, the fund has adopted a policy,
subject to Securities and Exchange Commission approval, to pay
quarterly distributions that amount to at least 3 percent of the
fund's assets, or 12 percent annually. By cutting into assets, this
will have the effect of reducing management fees if the fund fails
to grow at an equal or greater rate.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will try to make sure that distributions are in the
form of long-term capital gains, which are taxed at the minimum
capital gains tax rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether the two moves will have the desired
effect of reducing the fund's discount. And the answer will be
watched closely by managers of other closed-end funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can really say for sure _ you'll have to wait and and
see,'' Schachter said. ``But it raises the bar of responsibility of
what a fund can do.''
</P>
<P>
   France Growth has recently had a stellar performance, returning
57.1 percent for the 12 months ended June 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Subadviser Factor
</P>
<P>
   Let's say a fund megacomplex has done a great job managing your
portfolio of domestic stocks. But now it's time to shift some
assets abroad, and you're wondering whether to use the same firm to
manage your international fund.
</P>
<P>
   It may pay to consider whether the international offering is
run, or subadvised, by an outside manager. According to a recent
study by the Financial Research Corp., a fund research and
consulting company in Boston, that can have a significant effect on
returns.
</P>
<P>
   The study reviewed 566 international and global stock fund
portfolios, of which 156, or 27.6 percent, used subadvisers. The
returns for the funds run by subadvisers lagged behind those
managed in-house by an average of 2.3 percentage points,
annualized, for the three years through February 1998. Performance
lagged for other periods, too, but not as much.
</P>
<P>
   A small part of the poorer performance may be accounted for by
the extra layer of fees that subadvisory arrangements sometimes
foist on shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   For international or global stock funds managed in-house, the
average management fee is 0.76 percent, compared with 0.90 percent
for funds with subadvisers.
</P>
<P>
   More important, outside managers may assume more market risk to
generate bigger returns that compensate for the higher fees, said
Raymond D. Libertore, a Financial Research analyst who studied the
data.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe fund families like Franklin Resources' Templeton and
Scudder that keep their international and global funds in-house are
likely to have the expertise to generate superior performance.
</P>
<P>
   The study also looked at domestic funds, but found the
performance gap to be far smaller. Over three years, annualized
returns for domestic funds with subadvisers were less than 1
percent behind those of comparable funds handled in-house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1722EDT &QL; 
