<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-NORWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY'S TALL STRIKER LOOMS OVER WORLD CUP'S FAVORED TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ The five Flo brothers grew up along
Norway's northern fjords, playing soccer inside the house with
Ping-Pong balls. The brothers divided into teams, but the only real
loser was the furniture, according to midfielder Jostein Flo.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we became professionals, we bought all new furniture,''
Flo said with a laugh at Friday's final training session before
Norway's second-round World Cup match against Italy on Saturday in
Marseilles.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Flo brothers went on to play high-level football in
Norway. Two of them, Jostein and Tore Andre, are playing in the
World Cup. Their cousin, Havard Flo, is also on the team. The star
is unquestionably Tore Andre, who scored a goal and drew a penalty
that his teammate Kjetil Rekdal converted into the winning goal in
Wednesday's stunning 2-1 victory over Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   While Jostein Flo joked that he crushed the Ping-Pong balls on
his feet, thus relegating himself to a supporting role in midfield,
his brother could juggle them effortlessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has that extra to score goals,'' Jostein said of Tore Andre
Flo.
</P>
<P>
   Tore Andre Flo, 25, does not always play regularly for his club
team, Chelsea, in the English Premier League, which is blessed with
a full supply of goal scorers. But he is indispensable to Norway's
national team, having produced 13 goals in 28 matches. He scored
twice in a 4-2 victory over Brazil last year and once on Wednesday
in the Norwegians' third 1998 World Cup game. Is there another
country that has played Brazil three times and never lost?
</P>
<P>
   Norway's tall players are renowned for their play in the air,
but at 6 feet 5 inches, Tore Andre Flo seems equally comfortable on
the ground. He drove Junior Baiano to distraction Wednesday,
whirling like a rodeo bull and leaving the Brazilian defender's
only defense in the final minutes to grab Flo's shirt and pull him
backward.
</P>
<P>
   Esse Bahamarst, the American referee who awarded Norway a
penalty kick, was roundly criticized for what appeared to be a
phantom foul, but newly released television footage showed Baiano
clearly yanking on Flo's jersey as if it were taffy.
</P>
<P>
   There are more famous strikers in this World Cup _ Ronaldo of
Brazil, Roberto Baggio of Italy, Gabriel Batistuta of Argentina,
Juergen Klinsmann of Germany _ but none is more vital to the
success of his team than Tore Andre Flo.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, he is among the best in the world,'' Norway
Coach Egil Olsen said. ``I wouldn't trade him for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Italy defeated Norway, 1-0, in the World Cup,
despite having its goalie, Gianluca Pagliacu, ejected in the 21st
minute for touching the ball with his hands outside the penalty
area.
</P>
<P>
   Dino Baggio later provided the game's only goal. He scored off a
free kick with a header, an unforgivable offense in Norway (players
are supposed to be dominant in the air).
</P>
<P>
   Scoring figures to be miserly again in the rematch. Perhaps the
first goal will be the only goal, Tore Andre Flo said. That is the
way Norway tends to play, using the long ball, clogging the middle
and using Tore Andre Flo as a lone striker. Mario Zagallo, the
Brazilian coach, dismissed this approach as ``anti-football.''
Perhaps, but there may not be a team more feared by the traditional
soccer powers than Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to score against us,'' Rekdal said. ``It's not
the nicest football, but we can't play like Brazil. We play our
way. We bring the ball to the opposing penalty box and try to
attack as fast as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Tore Andre Flo is always there, standing like a lightning rod,
ready to create electricity. To his mother's everlasting
appreciation, he has taken his game outdoors and the furniture
survives as furniture, not fireplace kindling.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got mad sometimes,'' he said. ``But after two or three
minutes, she was glad again.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
