<SLUG> BC-SF-AIR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA YANKS SAN FRANCISCO AREA'S CLEAN-AIR STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Environmental Protection Agency has punished
the San Francisco Bay area by taking away its coveted clear-air
status, leaving nine counties vulnerable to tougher pollution
controls on cars, factories and households.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in unhealthful levels of smog in 1995 and 1996
represented a trend toward worsening air quality, and triggered the
official ruling that the region no longer complied with the federal
Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're correcting the label to account for reality. The Bay
area has been out of attainment of the law for the past three
years,'' EPA Regional Administrator Felicia Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a truth-in-advertising issue so the public can hold us
all accountable for the actions that the district and we need to
take for the public's health protection,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area Air Quality Management District, which has fought
the redesignation along with the state and Metropolitan
Transportation Commission, expressed displeasure with the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that this has happened. We don't feel the
EPA action today will further protect public health,'' said Ellen
Garvey, executive officer of the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the coming months, we will continue to work with EPA, the
public and industrial stake holders on a realistic and responsible
ozone attainment strategy,'' Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Bay area was the eighth smoggiest metropolitan area
in the nation. In 1996, it was the sixth worst. The new
designation, which is part of a periodic review, won't immediately
affect industrial permits or place curbs on cars.
</P>
<P>
   Cars and trucks, consumer products, industry and homes that use
petroleum products and fossil fuels are main sources of
ground-level ozone, the primary ingredient in smog.
</P>
<P>
   Under the EPA guidelines, regional agencies will have to work to
reduce traffic, promote mass transit and improve smog-inspection
programs, and tighten permits on oil refineries, dry cleaners and
factories.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the EPA's designation will cost the region $8
million in federal money next year earmarked to control traffic
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, they have to do more. It's not for the
feds to come in and tell them what to do. It's their job to meet
the law. There are plenty of communities that have stricter plans.
All they have to do is go shopping in the L.A. (clean air)
measures,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Bay-area Environmentalists applauded the EPA's action, which was
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Sierra Club and Communities for a Better
Environment petitioned the EPA to take away the Bay area's
clean-air designation that it had conferred with much fanfare in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to take responsibility to reduce air
pollution,'' said Julia May, an analyst for Communities for a
Better Environment. ``Individual people want to have non-polluting
consumer choices and are doing their part. But in the short term,
the first thing you do is crack down on the big sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like the Bay area to get tough on the biggest sources.
The oil refineries belch out air pollution, and they get special
exemptions while the air district requires the little people to
meet standards,'' May said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
