<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MADZA-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1999 MAZDA MX-5 MIATA: THE LURE OF THE OPEN ROADSTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.
Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, who could have predicted that a small, open-top
car reminiscent of British-made MGs and Triumphs of the 1950s and
'60s would be so wildly successful that it would spawn a wave of
imitators, reviving the virtually dead market for sports roadsters?
It was, after all, an era of largely sensible, aerodynamic,
look-alike sedans.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mazda Miata, introduced in 1989 as a 1990 model, turned
out to be a breath of fresh air. Mazda has now sold more than
450,000 Miatas worldwide, more than half in North America to young
people buying their one and only car and to nostalgic baby boomers
who have made it the second or third car in their household fleets.
</P>
<P>
   Now, nearly a decade later, Mazda has come out with its first
redesign of the Miata, and a weeklong test drive proved that this
sequel improves on the extraordinary original. Everything that was
good about the first Miata has been made even better in the 1999
MX-5.
</P>
<P>
   Casual observers will notice little difference between the old
Miata and the new one. The black test model parked in my driveway
for a week drew little more than a matter of fact, ``Oh, the
Miata.'' There is no question in anyone's mind of what the car is,
which is precisely Mazda's point.
</P>
<P>
   In unveiling the car at the auto show in Detroit in January, Tom
Matano, designer of the original Miata who now heads Mazda's
California design studio, succinctly stated the company's design
philosophy for the roadster: ``We want people seeing the Miata from
a distance to ask, `Is that a Miata?' '' he said. ``As they get
closer, we want them to say, `Yep, that's a Miata, but that's a new
Miata.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Evolutionary redesigns do not always come out well, but the new
Miata's styling accomplishes its goals without unnecessary
additions.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be confused with the many other roadsters on the
highways. With dimensions virtually identical to the model it
replaces, the Miata continues its classic, timeless and simple
design. Yet, it appears fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant exterior differences appear on the front
end. Front fenders are more sculpted and the built-in head lamps
replace the pop-up variety of the original. The tail lamps are
updated but the back maintains the simple, uncluttered appearance
of the original.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the interior remains familiar but freshened. The
air-bag housing in the center of the beefy three-spoked steering
wheel is more compact for a better view of the instrument panel.
The instrument panel layout is the same as the original design, but
the chrome trim around the gauges has been discarded for a cleaner,
more contemporary look.
</P>
<P>
   (Interestingly, as Mazda eliminates the chrome trim, other
manufacturers, including Chrysler and Mercedes-Benz, are adding it
to create a nostalgic look.)
</P>
<P>
   I miss the chrome trim, and I bet original Miata owners will as
well. Also gone are the optional speakers built into the headrests,
another distinctive feature that I suspect others will miss.
</P>
<P>
   Still intimate, the inside of the Miata uses more rounded
surfaces and a dash that sweeps back onto the doors for a more
spacious feel. The use of door panels made of rounded
plastic-molded surfaces instead of the flat panels has allowed for
built-in door handles and storage pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Storage in the trunk has been increased 10 percent by moving the
spare tire and battery below the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The armrest-center console has been redesigned to include cup
holders, but they are not particularly convenient; they are at
elbow level and interfere with shifting.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, the Miata's seats continue to provide the same grip
and support of the original's, ideal for holding its passengers in
place on quick turns and sweeping bends.
</P>
<P>
   A significant improvement is the addition of a glass rear window
with a built-in defroster. The previous Miata required that the
plastic rear window be unzipped before lowering the top.
</P>
<P>
   Folding the top of the new Miata now is a simple one-person job
that can be performed without leaving the driver's seat _ at a
stoplight, for instance. Wind blockers have been added behind the
seats to prevent air that rushes over the rear of the vehicle from
swirling about in the passenger compartment.
</P>
<P>
   Other substantial changes were made under the skin.
</P>
<P>
   The Miata's 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine, the only engine
available, has been bolstered to 140 horsepower from 133. Torque
has also been improved slightly. While the differences don't look
huge on paper and only improve zero to 60-miles-an-hour performance
a scant half-second or so, the increased power and torque make the
car feel substantially faster taking off from stoplights and making
highway passing maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   The engine is paired with a standard five-speed manual
transmission or the optional four-speed automatic, which has
undergone some improvement. Still, the stick shift is the best
choice for this sports car.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements have also been made in the Miata's four-wheel
double-wishbone suspension. Those, combined with the roadster's
more rigid body structure and lower weight, improve handling
noticeably.
</P>
<P>
   The new Miata has more grip going into corners and around curves
but provides a smoother ride. Yet, you can still fishtail the Miata
if that's your idea of a good time.
</P>
<P>
   The other feature that made the original Miata so attractive
remains as well: the price. The new Miata starts at $20,200
including destination fees. Fully outfitted, the Miata can be had
for under $25,000, about the same as its predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The simple, classic design, the fun-to-drive performance and the
affordable price of the new Miata will maintain the Mazada's
position as the leader among roadsters for fun per dollar. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The MG for modern times, now even better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
