<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SATURATION-DANCE-REVI     06-26 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SATURATION-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SATURATION': UPROAR ALTERNATING WITH SERENITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An ambitious company called Complexions: A Concept in
Dance is letting a big production evolve. ``Saturation,''
choreographed by Dwight Rhoden, will achieve its finished form in
2000. But before that, bits of it will be shown as they take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Dancegoers got their first look at ``Saturation'' on Thursday
night in an unusual setting. The enterprising troupe, directed by
Rhoden and Desmond Richardson, found a temporarily vacant space at
15 Mercer St. in SoHo and turned it into a loft theater just for
this engagement, which concludes Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographic tone was set by the ``Ave Maria,'' which began
the program. Far from being pious, this was a passionate duet for
Christina Johnson and Ryan Brooke Taylor in which Rhoden
choreographically proclaimed the worth of flesh as well as spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the current version of ``Saturation,'' a suite to a
potpourri of live and recorded music. Each section had a separate
title. But the choreography for all of them blended modern dance
with jazz dance and ballet, including steps on point. And the large
company proved admirably versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Turbulence prevailed. Dancers stormed and rushed, slithered and
squirmed. They rose on their toes, only to fall on the floor and
then rise again. No one ever seemed to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen de Lavallade, an actress and dancer with a dignified
stage presence, was a guest artist for the occasion. Throughout the
production, she recited poetic texts in praise of the universe. But
although she has a fine speaking voice, she was hard to hear, for
the musical accompaniment occasionally drowned her out.
</P>
<P>
   That exemplified the problem of ``Saturation'' in its present
state. Rhoden made every sight and sound in it unremittingly
dazzling. Yet carefully devised contrasts between uproar and
serenity, and between simple and ornate steps, might have provided
the piece with even greater impact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
