<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIBET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP CHINESE OFFICIAL REJECTS IDEA OF AUTONOMY FOR TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TIANANMEN, CHINA-RUBIN) 
(ps) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's senior religious official Friday vehemently
rejected proposals, to be advanced by President Clinton during his
summit meeting on Saturday, that China engage in discussions with
the Dalai Lama over greater autonomy for Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Clinton arrived in Beijing for a state visit, the
official condemned the exiled Tibetan Buddhist leader as a relic of
the Dark Ages who wanted to trick China into letting the vast
mountainous territory on China's western border break away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we send Tibet back into the original feudal serfdom, so
dark, so savage, so cruel?'' asked Ye Xiaowen, director of State
Administration for Religious Affairs, of proposals to allow the
Dalai Lama to return and wield power. ``If so, what human rights
are we talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   Ye's remarks came in response to reporters' questions at a
government press briefing on religion in China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is under pressure from Congress and rights advocates to
make China's rule in Tibet, which critics say is repressive, an
important issue in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be no chance Clinton will make any progress
during his trip in defusing the Tibet issue, and American officials
have already said as much. And today, Ye criticized the
administration's appointment last year of a Special Coordinator on
Tibet as ``inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ye's statements Friday did not represent a change in policy for
the Chinese government, which has long mistrusted the Dalai Lama
and often condemns him in the harshest of terms.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, in an interview with the American
government-sponsored Radio Free Asia, Clinton said, ``We think it's
wrong to deny the Dalai Lama access to his people in Tibet,'' and
``We think it's wrong for the people of Tibet to be subject to any
sort of religious, cultural or economic discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added that the United States does not seek independence
for Tibet, and that he understood China's historical fears of
disintegration.
</P>
<P>
   The Dalai Lama, spiritual and political leader to many Tibetan
Buddhists, fled Tibet in 1959 as the Chinese Communists crushed a
rebellion and began to remake the old society. He now lives in
exile in India.
</P>
<P>
   In recent statements, the Dalai Lama, who was awarded the 1989
Nobel Peace Prize, has said he does not seek independence, but
rather autonomy over civil affairs, with China retaining
sovereignty and control of foreign relations.
</P>
<P>
   But Ye said on Friday that the talk of autonomy was merely a
trick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is turning a one-stage strategy for independence into a
two-stage strategy for independence,'' Ye said. If the Dalai Lama
continues on his current course, Ye said, he ``will meet
retribution according to the Buddhist scriptures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a well-known fact that the Dalai Lama has betrayed his
motherland by going into foreign exile and has engaged in
separatist activities,'' Ye said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a matter of religious belief,'' he said. ``The
Chinese government has never interfered in the religious practices
and beliefs of the Tibetan people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ye acknowledged that during the Cultural Revolution of 1966 to
1976 religion was repressed throughout the People's Republic,
including Tibet, where many monasteries were destroyed and monks
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years the Chinese government has supported the
rebuilding of some monasteries and supported aspects of Tibetan
culture. But it has limited the numbers of monks and nuns and gone
to great lengths to weed out or imprison those deemed to support
the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   Although officially Tibet is an autonomous region with the
People's Republic, it remains tightly controlled by the Communist
Party.
</P>
<P>
   China is now promoting economic development in the region, which
it often trumpets in the official press.
</P>
<P>
   At the press briefing, Ye more broadly defended China's
religious policies, which have been attacked abroad as repressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government has made relentless efforts to
guarantee its citizens freedom of religious belief,'' he said. ``At
the same time, we believe that the distinct features of each
country should be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   In China, that means that Christian churches that accept the
oversight of the government have been allowed to grow, even thrive.
But some evangelical Protestants who reject government control, and
Catholics who insist the pope is their spiritual leader, have faced
fines or arrest, leading to charges of religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning, President and Mrs. Clinton will attend
services at the largest officially sanctioned Protestant church in
Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
