<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOLIE-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LA JOLIE FILLE DE PERTH'': VAPID THEATER, EXHILARATING MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bizet's ``La Jolie Fille de Perth,'' which the Opera
Francais de New York revived at Alice Tully Hall on Thursday
evening, features a fiery and smoky gypsy mezzo, a tenor who is a
fool for love, a swaggering baritone and a chorus singing several
lusty numbers, all in an exotic setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carmen,'' though, this is not. The plot, adapted from a Walter
Scott story, is innocuous, the characters bubble-thin. Opera
Francais' style of semi-staging suited the piece rather well. Here
were these fragile people, trapped in their love affairs and
intrigues to the front of the stage, at the mercy of the orchestral
machine behind them.
</P>
<P>
   And that machine was running smoothly. Not for the first time in
this company's history, a vapid piece of music theater was saved by
an exhilarating orchestral performance under Yves Abel. The zest,
attack and fineness of the playing suggested careful preparation
and pointed up where the qualities of the piece lie.
</P>
<P>
   Bizet no doubt found it difficult to care too much about the
inhabitants of a minor Scottish town in an indiscriminate
once-upon-a-time, but he evidently did care about a solo clarinet
or, especially, a detachment of cellos (beautifully represented on
this occasion). Where the orchestra is concerned, the score
constantly hovers on the borders of ``Carmen'' or of
``L'Arlesienne'' without quite coming up with what distinguishes
those works: strong tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Bizet imagined Catherine Glover, the Fair Maid of the title, as
a coloratura soprano and so created the rather awkward paradox of a
simple character expressing herself in ostentatiously ornamental
music. Tracy Dahl sang the role brightly and readily, though her
control was uncertain until the point in the fourth act where she
abruptly comes on with a mad song.
</P>
<P>
   Among the rest of the cast, Lyne Comtois was impressive as Mab,
the gypsy schemer, her singing rich in tone and dark in color, at
once sensuous and ironic. John Hancock, as the baritone Duc de
Rothsay, added likable singing to the strong effect of his stature:
There was welcome comedy when he fell to his knees beside Ms. Dahl
and was still taller than she was. Kevin Deas, a singer always good
to hear, did a lovely job with the part of Simon Glover, the Fair
Maid's father, and Gerard Edery gave a sterling performance as
Ralph, especially in his drinking song, the second such in the
opera. Gregory Mercer had the long role of Henri Smith, the hero.
</P>
<P>
   James Robinson staged the piece ably, though we could have done
without the vain attempts to signal things by illuminating one or
another of five tawdry hearts on the back wall. The vagaries of
love in this opera are clear enough and not really important.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
