A9072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-LMAY27-COX     06-26 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-LMAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaving home too often spells trouble in garden
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a wonder gardeners ever leave home. When you do, you're
certain to miss something that sprouts, grows or blooms. Moreover,
you come back to face rampant growth _ like the myriad wisteria
vines whipping around my garden. Too, there's always the chance
that something might keel over and die for lack of attention.
</P>
<P>
   And for me, it seems that leaving home means a damaging storm is
sure to show up. At least that's what Lyn says. Going back several
years, she cites numerous occasions when big winds and rains,
including a hurricane, blew in just as I blew out. Lights are off,
I'm not home.
</P>
<P>
   Each time, I return to find something broken or killed in the
garden.
</P>
<P>
   One year, a huge pecan tree was uprooted in the courtyard behind
the house. Another time, a neighboring oak got snapped in two,
landing within feet of our fence.
</P>
<P>
   And last week, I was away again when the blowdown struck.
Reporting it on the phone, Lyn sounded calm; she'd seen it all
before: ``It broke a limb off one of the pines _ the limb you were
bending down by hanging the stone from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, I was greeted by a roughly pruned Japanese black
pine (I'd been training that limb for years), as well as several
injured shrubs and an amazing number of broken branches, mostly
from the tulip tree, which uses any excuse to throw down its
various parts.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, the damage was slight, the cleanup easy.
More difficult was my missing the dramatic appearance of the
amorphophallus, which is known in some places _ India, for example
_ as snake plant. It is also called voodoo lily, stink lily and
snake palm and leopard palm.
</P>
<P>
   By any name it is a striking plant.
</P>
<P>
   So striking that I cannot believe I would have failed to see it
spurting out of the ground. At the same time, I find it difficult
to believe it grew three feet during the week I was gone. In any
case, there it was, standing a yard high in the back garden, amid
the rhododendron, ferns, sweetshrub and sweetspire.
</P>
<P>
   Rising from ground level is a brown sheath, about 8 inches high.
Within that is the stalk _ green with white speckles. The top
sprays into three huge frondlike leaves. It's a very
vigorous-looking specimen.
</P>
<P>
   It began as a bulb, sent to me last October by Reese
Danley-Kilgo, a talented poet, author and gardener who lives in
Huntsville, Ala. She said a friend from India had noted that the
plant's snakelike appearance inspires one of its common names and
that it serves as camouflage for the reptiles.
</P>
<P>
   I planted the bulb the same day I got it, in a hole about 8
inches deep, covering the spot with decayed leaves _ protection
against cold and squirrels. Throughout the spring, I checked for
signs of life, seeing nothing as late as early June. Then, as soon
as I left town, the big stem shot up like a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   In describing the plant, some experts mention a bloom that comes
before the leaves. The large flower stinks, as my Alabama ancestors
would say, ``like k'yawn'' (it took me a long time to realize they
must have meant ``carrion'').
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, my plant did not bloom. All the more reason to
lament missing its rapid rise. Yet another reason to regret time
away from the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Reason enough to keep me home. Until the next storm gathers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1737EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9073 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CARDINAL-COX     06-26 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CARDINAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Bernardin' offers insight into life of late cardinal
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Living saint, church icon, Christlike figure _ the late Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin is quickly becoming one of those transcendent
spiritual figures whose lives become the subjects of Sunday school
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But Eugene Kennedy remembers Bernardin another way. They were
sitting on a Chicago pier, peering into a June sky one evening,
when Bernardin pointed toward a neon-lit Ferris wheel nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go for a ride on that, I'll go with you,'' Bernardin
said.
</P>
<P>
   That story is taken from a superb documentary on the life of
Bernardin. ``Bernardin,'' which airs Tuesday at 7 p.m. EDT on PBS
(Check local listings), is filled with rich glimpses into a man who
asked that people not regard him as a Catholic heavyweight, but as
``Joseph, your brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong film is filled with unexpected details: the Ferris
wheel story, Bernardin's encounter with the man who almost
destroyed his career, and recollections from a prominent Jewish
rabbi who saw Bernardin as his brother.
</P>
<P>
   Any new insight into the life of Bernardin is no small
achievement. He is now a spiritual celebrity. His memoirs, ``The
Gift of Peace'' (Loyola Press, $17.95), became a best seller. In
the slim volume, Bernardin details the final two battles of his
life _ one against a false charge of sexual misconduct and another
against cancer. Bernardin lost his final struggle, dying of cancer
at 68 just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary is produced by Journey Films, a company based in
Alexandria, Va. Martin Doblmeier, the film's co-producer, said
Bernardin intrigued him because his life was gripped by issues that
rock America: abortion, poverty, nuclear war, sexuality, death.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people primarily know Bernardin today through the sexual
misconduct charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole story was yet untold,'' Doblmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary fills in the blanks. It traces Bernardin's rise
from his childhood as an Italian Catholic in South Carolina to a
shrewd, inside worker in the Catholic Church. It relies on
interviews with family, friends, theologians, and even the longtime
companion of Bernardin's accuser, Steven Cook.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the film, Bernardin is portrayed by those who knew
him as a reconciler. He just didn't cross lines _ he erased them.
Jews, Protestants, African-Americans, the rich and poor, and even
the terminally ill, were drawn to Bernardin, Doblmeier said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a bridge builder,'' Doblmeier added. ``He built bridges
between left and right, between hawk and dove, between the accusers
and the accused, and then at the end of his life, as much as
humanely possible, he built a bridge between this life and what
lies beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the film is full of humor. Doblmeier and fellow
producer Frank Frost unearthed plenty of footage of Bernardin where
his self-deprecating humor was on display. Bernardin's gentleness,
his warmth with people, and his ability to inspire love from those
closest to him are also evident.
</P>
<P>
   In the final segment of the documentary, Kenneth Velo, his aide
and driver, gives a moving eulogy at his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long and beautiful ride, Cardinal,'' Velo said as
he stood above Bernardin's casket. ``But now you're home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
