<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNGUS-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN THE WAR AGAINST PORIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENIFER HANRAHAN 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Houses that are poorly constructed are most
susceptible to Poria incrassata. The best way for homeowners or
homebuyers to make sure they are protected is to hire a termite
inspector who is familiar with the conditions that favor Poria and
the signs of infestation.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many pest-control experts are not.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Willis, president of the League of California Homeowners,
recently discovered vinelike tubes growing through decorative wood
trellises at his Upland home.
</P>
<P>
   Willis suspected he had Poria after reading a description of it
in a magazine. He called a pest-control expert he had employed for
years, but the man had never heard of Poria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't assume that the experts know,'' Willis said. ``Ask
questions and make sure.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a report prepared for the U.S. Department of
Agriculture, Forest Service and the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, Poria warning signs include:
</P>
<P>
   _Sunken areas in baseboards or trim, or separation of the
baseboard from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   _Whitish mats of mycelium under carpets or linoleum, in cabinets
or even behind furniture. Poria is susceptible to drying out in
sunlight or high temperatures, so it prefers unventilated, dark
areas, usually basements or crawl spaces.
</P>
<P>
   _The presence of fruit bodies on rotten wood on the underside of
flooring or in a cabinet. Fruit bodies are flat, succulent, up to a
half-inch thick and a pale olive gray, brown or black.
</P>
<P>
   _Swelling or crumbling of plaster or sheetrock, usually in a
straight, vertical column where it is fastened to a wall stud.
</P>
<P>
   _Vinelike rhizomorphs branching from the soil to foundations,
framing or the underside of flooring. They are dirty white, brown
or black.
</P>
<P>
   _Some seemingly innocuous projects or problems around the house
also can give Poria a chance to attack, including:
</P>
<P>
   _Building up flower beds so that the soil touches siding.
</P>
<P>
   _Wetting walls with lawn sprinklers for long periods. This can
allow the fungus to form rhizomorphs that connect the soil to the
wood, so that even after the sprinklers are shut off, the decay
continues.
</P>
<P>
   _Plumbing leaks.
</P>
<P>
   _Piling wood or other debris in crawl spaces or against the
sides of a house.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
