<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-RUBIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE ASSURE RUBIN THEY DO NOT PLAN A CURRENCY DEVALUATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-TIANANMEN) 
(th) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On the day before President Clinton was scheduled to
get down to business with President Jiang Zemin, China on Friday
gave the United States its strongest assurances yet that it does
not plan to devalue its currency.
</P>
<P>
   Playing economic advance man for Clinton, U.S. Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin held a daylong series of meetings with
senior Chinese officials here, in which he said ``there were
unambiguous statements of intent to maintain'' the exchange rate of
the Chinese currency, the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   Persuading China to maintain a stable currency has become a top
priority of the Clinton administration, which fears that a
devaluation by Beijing could spark another wave of copycat
devaluations across Asia. Rubin praised China on Friday for being
an ``island of stability'' in a region buffeted by economic
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Countries that devalue their currency can usually sell their
goods more competitively, and the concern of the United States and
several other nations is that the Chinese would devalue to avoid
being disadvantaged by several other Asian countries whose currency
has been weakened from the economic crisis that has shaken the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Although Friday's meetings were held in Zhongnanhai, the walled
compound in the heart of Beijing that is the inner sanctum of the
Chinese government, the focus of the talks was hundreds of miles to
the east, in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Asia's latest economic relapse was caused by a sharp decline in
the Japanese yen, and Rubin used the meetings here to keep up the
pressure on Japan to mend its fractured economy. He said that
Chinese officials told him they were very concerned about the
economic turmoil in Japan, in large part because the weak yen was
having an ``adverse impact on the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said that we, too, were deeply concerned about the economic
condition in Japan,'' said Rubin in a briefing with reporters after
he met Prime Minister Zhu Rongji, who is leading China's economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between a stable, reform-minded China and a shaky,
equivocating Japan has become a favorite theme of policy-makers and
currency traders in recent months. While Rubin was careful not to
criticize Japan, he drew some pointed distinctions between Beijing
and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Chinese decision not to devalue, Rubin said, ``They were
very prescient and they are getting and deserve a great deal of
respect in the world for this decision.'' Of Japan, he said, ``I've
not spoken to any person in the financial or political world who
does not believe Japan must solve its problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the drop in the yen prompted the United States and
Japan to prop up the value of the currency by buying $4 billion of
yen in foreign exchange markets. Many financial experts believe
China played an influential role in forcing the intervention by
complaining about how the weak yen was hurting its exports and by
dropping hints that the yuan might have to be devalued.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, before their morning meeting, the Chinese central bank
governor, Dai Xianglong, made a show of thanking Rubin for the
intervention. Dai had been among the Chinese officials who raised
alarms in recent weeks about how a weak yen was putting pressure on
the yuan.
</P>
<P>
   But the effects of the move have largely worn off. After a brief
rebound, the yen has settled to about 142 to the dollar, and
currency traders are once again betting on when the United States
will be forced to buy yen to raise its value again.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin was resolutely noncommittal Friday about whether the
United States would continue propping up the yen. But he is known
to be skeptical about the efficacy of such interventions. He would
clearly prefer that Japan tackle its more deep-seated economic
problems, which include a banking sector that staggers under $600
billion in bad loans and a web of onerous financial regulations.
</P>
<P>
   As for China, Rubin said it, too, faced formidable economic
challenges. Zhu is embarking on a broad reform of China's banking
system, as well as privatizing thousands of state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``You certainly got the feeling of people who understand the
problems,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Chinese leaders are sticking to their forecast of 8
percent economic growth in 1998. But with exports dwindling and
domestic demand sluggish, he added, ``It's not clear where they
expect to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the questions about China's economy, this was
probably the most trouble-free stop on Rubin's trip. In the coming
week, he will travel to Malaysia, Thailand and South Korea _
countries that are grappling with more nettlesome problems than
slowing growth.
</P>
<P>
   In Malaysia, Rubin will face a potentially unstable political
environment. On Wednesday, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahatir Mohamad
named his close adviser, Daim Zainuddin, as a cabinet minister in
charge of the economy. That would appear to undercut Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim, who had overseen the economy and has been
widely considered to be Mahatir's heir apparent.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim has clashed publicly with his boss in recent weeks over
how Malaysia should respond to the economic downturn. Although
Ibrahim says he is loyal to Mahatir, political experts in Malaysia
believe Ibrahim might challenge him if he felt he was being shunted
out of power.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand and Korea, the governments are struggling to impose
harsh economic reforms mandated by the International Monetary Fund
in the face of mounting opposition from labor leaders and populist
politicians. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
