A9097 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-COURT-COX &UR;      06-26 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-COURT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ELECTRONIC COURTROOM OFFERS A LOOK AT TRIALS OF THE FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
     &HT;     By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;     c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You won't hear much paper shuffling in Courtroom
No. 9, the most coveted room in U.S. District Court here.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving heaps of paper evidence at home, attorneys instead use a
bar code pen to scan numbers off of a sheet that stores their
evidence. Once the document appears on the screen in the
courtroom's control center, it is transmitted to monitors placed in
the jury box, counsel tables, the judge's bench and the witness
stand.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers lobby six months in advance to try their cases in the
state-of-the-art, $128,000 courtroom. One of ten in federal courts
nationwide, it's considered a model for how technology can speed
the wheels of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the purpose of a trial is the search for truth, this allows
the fact finder to be more thorough and efficient,'' said Luke
Bierman, judicial division director of the American Bar
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say this type of fully-integrated technological
courtroom is the wave of the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a short period of time, every courtroom is going to
have some of this technology,'' said Barry Boss, a defense attorney
who tried the first case in Washington's facility.
</P>
<P>
   As glitches are being fixed in the year-old courtroom, federal
court officials are considering whether to install another one.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic courtroom, the first of its kind in U.S. District
Court here, has drawn visitors from as far as Israel and Kenya. It
was paid for from fees that lawyers must routinely pay to practice
in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom's gadgets include software that records testimony
as it is being spoken, a souped-up sound system for playing
audio-taped evidence and an overhead projector that can blow up
evidence and display it throughout the courtroom. Also, a witness
can circle a suspect in crime scene photograph using a ``John
Madden pen,'' long employed by sportscasters and weather announcers
but new to courtrooms. A 37-inch television monitor allows those in
the audience to get a better view of the proceedings, including
enlarged views of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In some courtrooms, computer and video wires ran amok. In this
state-of-art courtroom, however, they are tucked away under a
four-inch-high raised floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should look like a courtroom and feel like a courtroom,''
said U.S. District Judge Thomas Hogan. ``It shouldn't look like a
Circuit City showroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ``electronic courtroom,'' jurors no longer wait for
documents to be handed to them or squint to see physical evidence.
Now, they can study evidence longer on eight 10-inch monitors in
the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers scan documents, photographs or even video clips into
computers before the proceedings begin. Each one receives a bar
code. Once the trial starts, the lawyers simply highlight bar codes
from a ``menu'' of evidence, and the evidence pops up on the
courtroom monitors.
</P>
<P>
   This system, Hogan said, allow greater scrutiny of evidence by
jurors. For example, a jury often has a limited view of such
objects as X-rays, photographs or guns. But with a high-powered
overhead ``ELMO'' projector, the image of a gun can be enlarged.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the operation is the control center ``podium'' from
which an attorney can zoom in on details of evidence, such as
fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   And if the judge decides that the jury shouldn't see certain
images, the courtroom deputy can tap a ``kill switch'' that shuts
off certain monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's bench also holds a docking station, where he or she
can plug in a laptop computer. This allows the judge to check
e-mail, do legal research or view real-time testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The technology can mean speedier trials, attorneys and judges
say. It also means jurors are more alert during trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fewer jurors sleeping,'' said Betsy Paret, chief
deputy for court administration. She has conducted training
sessions for lawyers with court budget analyst John Cramer.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors are ``curious to see what's going to happen next,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This makes sense to defense attorney Boss, who tried the first
case in the electronic courtroom nearly a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're so used to obtaining everything over a video
screen, the electronic courtroom allows us to take an antiquated
form of presentation and make it current and contemporary,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boss, who tried a federal weapons possession case in the
courtroom, said the technology helped him weed out inconsistencies
in the testimonies of police officers. His client was acquitted in
about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my closing argument, I was able to juxtapose the real-time
testimony of both the officers on the monitor,'' he said. ``It
revealed to the jury the stark contradiction between the two
accounts.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For use by clients of The New York Times News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
