<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9100 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV28-B     06-26 1129
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURTAILING THE GOP'S INVESTIGATION MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great things about our country is the way you are
free to bad-mouth those in authority, a blessed relief valve for
two-and-a-quarter centuries, a tenet that has probably prevented
three or four more revolutions or civil wars than the one of each
we already survived.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of the current president's enemies in Congress and
in the country, I am in favor of having Mr. Clinton go to China.
And unlike most of them, I am also in favor of having him come
back.
</P>
<P>
   Every president who goes to China has to watch his step, never
mind the water, the food, the luggage. Because the relationship
between the largest country on earth (them), and the most powerful
(us) is fraught with fear of being taken for granted, of losing
face. That goes for us as much as them.
</P>
<P>
   We are very insecure vis a vis the 1.2 billion Chinese. For
decades after World War II, the conservative politicians in this
country made hay with the war whoop: ``Who lost China?'' A lot of
us younger Americans wondered: How can you lose the most populous
nation on the planet? One that we never ``had'' to begin with?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the miracle of television, any congressman, senator,
or preacher with his own television network or talk show can
denounce the president for a.) going b.) kowtowing to c.) groveling
at the feet of d.) toadying up to, etc., the Butchers of Beijing.
It's always an irresistible opportunity for the opposition party
here to wax wroth about whatever president is doing to whatever
Chinese regime. If your sound bite is particularly pithy or
insulting, you get onto the cable network loop, and can lie awake
for 24 hours straight to catch yourself saying the same pithy or
insulting thing. Hey, this is America.
</P>
<P>
   To prove my point that we enjoy freedoms that the Chinese can
only dream about, I provide as a public service a complete list of
the voluminous Clinton scandals, courtesy of the US House. While
some for-profit publications such as the Wall Street Journal and
the Rev. Jerry Falwell's church bulletin have attempted this task,
we owe it to the lower chamber of Congress for an up-to-date list
of the 55 congressional committee investigations into what Clinton
and his crew have been up to.
</P>
<P>
   I wrote Friday about how Speaker Gingrich's ledership team has
spent $17 million on just the 55 House committee investigations the
Democrats yowl about. When you throw in the various special counsel
probes like the $40 million-plus effort of Kenneth Starr ($1
million a month), the Senate forays into the get-Clinton business,
and other federal man-hours spent tracking down various scandals,
the taxpayer tab will probably exceed $100 million before Clinton
departs for the history books.
</P>
<P>
   But what are we getting for our money? Here's a smattering from
the GOP menu: Going alphabetically, with the Agriculture Committee,
we have the House Republican investigation of Hillary Clinton's
commodity transactions. That was closed with no action taken, after
spending a measly $105,000 to investigate how she made less than
that on her trading.
</P>
<P>
   Moving on to Appropriations, we have the ongoing probe of
Democratic contributors getting to snooze in the Lincoln Bedroom. B
means Banking, and that's the biggie: Whitewater. At least, it was
the biggie, until Monicagate erupted. The Banking Committee is also
in charge of seeing if Clinton laundered drug money and smuggled
narcotics at the Mena, Ark., airport when he was not playing the
saxophone, chasing girls or otherwise being governor.
</P>
<P>
   We have more committees investigating whether contributors got
contracts for giving campaign cash, but it is only Democratic
contributors who get investigated, even though Republicans raise
more money by a wide margin. The House is investigating unions, and
how promotions are granted in government jobs, how some FBI files
got into the hands of a political hack on the White House payroll,
and whether people such as former Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary,
or Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, engaged in hanky-panky in the
course of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Grim Reaper can put an end to some Republican
prying. The late Ron Brown's tenure as Commerce secretary was
exhumed, like the remains of the late US Ambassador Larry Lawrence,
whose corpse figured prominently in GOP outrage over the alleged
selling of burial plots in veterans' cemeteries. That investigation
was shut down quickly, however, when it turned out that a prominent
Republican congressional committee staff chief had wangled a crypt
for a nonveteran.
</P>
<P>
   We will be hearing much this week of the Clinton crew's
solicitation of campaign money from Chinese-Americans with
connections to the Beijing regime and military machine. Some in the
GOP leadership have denounced Clinton for selling out America's
national security for a mess of campaign contribution pottage.
</P>
<P>
   These tend to be the same people who complain about labor
unions, immigrants, makeup of trade missions, the law enforcement
performance in Waco in the Branch Davidian disaster, IRS audits of
right-wing groups, and whether Al Gore used a White House phone to
schmooze big contributors.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are hot under the collar because some of the
information subpoenaed by the Republicans ends up leaked to the
news media, like the confidential phone logs of former Commerce
Department insider John Huang.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions have had their files ransacked by GOP investigators
or government agents acting for same. The GOP was blocked from
subpoenaing the private personal files of 22,000 Hispanic students
at Rancho Santiago Community College in California when a defeated
congressman, Robert Dornan, tried to find out if any illegal aliens
voted against him.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee and various state committees
have been forced to photocopy hundreds of thousands of pages of
files and turn them over to probers, and the legal bills for the
Democrats have run well over $10 million, with no end in sight.
This Congress has done wonders for Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   It would all change if the Democrats took back control of the
House this fall, but the GOP has a 12-seat edge in the 435-seat
chamber, and despite some brave talk by the Democrats, I look for
more of the same next year, and the year after.
</P>
<P>
   For your own copy of the Democrats' 51-page catalogue of the
GOP's hydra-headed Investigation Machine, write to House Democratic
Leader Richrd Gephardt, chairman, US House Democratic Policy
Committee, H-204, US Capitol, Washington DC.
</P>
<P>
   David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
