</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARSSS-2DLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT DECISIONS FAVOR VICTIMS OF SEX HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In twin landmark rulings, the Supreme Court made it
significantly harder Friday for employers to defend themselves
against sexual harassment charges by claiming they were unaware of
what lower-level supervisors were doing.
</P>
<P>
   In both 7-2 decisions, the court said employers in most cases
cannot use this defense because the federal civil rights law that
bars sex discrimination or harassment equates employers with their
``agents,'' or supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   So if a supervisor engages in harassment, the company could be
subject to ``vicarious liability'' even if its top officials were
ignorant of the supervisor's actions, the court said, wrapping up
its 1997-1998 term.
</P>
<P>
   In the decisions, which made it easier for workers to sue
employers for harassment, the court for the first time promulgated
standards governing the kinds of defenses, if any, the employers
may use.
</P>
<P>
   Women's rights advocates hailed the rulings.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Greenberger, co-president of the Washington-based
National Women's Law Center, an advocacy and litigating group,
said, ``I think these cases provide an important win for women. The
court's new rules provide powerful tools for those complaining
about sexual harassment in the workplace, but at the same time they
provide powerful incentives for employers to eliminate sexual
harassment before it takes place.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Lichtman, president of the National Partnership for Women
and Families, an advocacy group, said that ``by insisting that the
buck stops with the employer, the court's decisions will help make
sure that sexual harassment is really taken seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   William Kilberg, representing the National Association of
Manufacturers and the Manufacturers Alliance, said: ``Employers
ought to be happy with the decisions because they reject the notion
that the employer is automatically liable. Nonetheless, the court
(put) a very heavy burden on employers to show that they have an
effective complaint policy in place.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lawrence Lorber, a Washington lawyer who represents
employers in sexual harassment cases, said, ``On balance, these
decisions were about as pro-employee as you could get out of any
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorber said he had advised employers that ``if they didn't train
managers in addressing sexual harassment, `you're in big trouble.'
And now I'd tell them, `You're in deadly trouble.'''
</P>
<P>
   The main winners, he added, are consulting firms that run
seminars on sexual harassment for employers. ``For those people,
this has to be Christmas in 99-degree June.''
</P>
<P>
   In the cases Friday, the justices also made it more difficult
for firms to claim they are not liable in cases where bosses tell
employees to have sex with them ``or else'' even if the threats
were not carried out and if the victims' careers did not suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a person with supervisory authority discriminates in
terms and conditions of subordinates' employment, his actions
necessarily draw upon his superior position over people who report
to him,'' Justice David Souter wrote. ``An employee generally
cannot check a supervisor's abusive conduct the same way that she
might deal with abuse from a co-worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Souter's opinion dealt with charges by Beth Ann Faragher that
when she worked as a lifeguard in Boca Raton, Fla., between 1985
and 1990, supervisors constantly made lewd remarks to her and
engaged in ``uninvited and offensive touching.'' One supervisor
told her ``date me or clean the toilets for a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court in Miami ruled that Faragher's
supervisors had harassed her, but an appeals court reversed the
ruling, saying the city of Boca Raton was not liable.
</P>
<P>
   In overturning that decision, the Supreme Court said the city
had failed to rebut the allegations of its liability. Thus,
apparently all that remains to be determined in the case is how
much money Faragher, now a public defender in Denver, can collect
from Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   The other case involved a Chicago saleswoman, Kimberly Ellerth,
who quit her job with Burlington Industries Inc. in 1994 after 15
months. Ellerth, now a homemaker in Belvidere, Ill., said she quit
because a supervisor, Theodore Slowik, had touched her
inappropriately, told offensive jokes, advised her to ``loosen up''
and warned, ``You know, Kim, I could make your life very hard or
very easy at Burlington.''
</P>
<P>
   But he never carried through on the threat, and Ellerth in fact
earned a promotion before quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony Kennedy, writing for the high court, said it
didn't matter whether the supervisor delivered on the threat.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum he created a hostile work environment and Ellerth
should have the right to go to court and prove it, Kennedy wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases marked a major effort by the court to refine sexual
harassment law. In 1986 the justices said such harassment was a
violation of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, which bars
discrimination based on race, ethnic origin, gender or religion.
</P>
<P>
   But the court had set few rules for determining exactly when an
employer is liable for conduct by a supervisor that creates a
hostile working environment. In the 1986 case, all the court said
was that an employer is not ``automatically'' liable even when a
supervisor's harassment creates that environment.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the court issued new guidelines to clarify where an
employer's responsibilities begin and end.
</P>
<P>
   First, it said, employers always are subject to liability for a
hostile environment created by a supervisor over subordinates.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where an employee is not fired or demoted for failing
to submit to the supervisor's advances, employers have two lines of
defense, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   They can show they took steps to prevent sexual harassment or
corrected any improper behavior. Also, they can argue that the
employee charging sexual harassment did nothing to take advantage
of any ``preventive or corrective'' aspects of employer policies
against such harassment.
</P>
<P>
   But the court said no such defense is available when harassment
culminates in firing, demoting or undesirably reassigning the
employee. In such cases, the employer's only recourse is to try to
prove that there was no harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Kennedy and Souter in the opinions were Chief Justice
William Rehnquist and Justices John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day
O'Connor, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia, the court's most
conservative members, joined in a dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court today manufactures a rule that employers are
vicariously liable'' for sexual harassment by supervisors, Thomas
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Thomas said, ``an employer should be liable if, and
only if, the plaintiff proves that the employer was negligent in
permitting the supervisor's conduct to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas himself was the focus of explosive sexual harassment
charges by a former subordinate, Anita Hill, during his Supreme
Court confirmation hearing in 1991. He denied Hill's charges and
won confirmation, but the brouhaha catapulted workplace sexual
harassment into the mainstream of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's rulings followed the court's 5-4 decision Monday making
it much harder for students who are sexually harassed by teachers
to hold school districts financially responsible. That decision was
based on a separate federal law dealing with discrimination in
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision in the Burlington case conceivably
could aid Paula Jones' effort to revive her sexual-harassment
lawsuit against President Clinton, one of her lawyers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court's decision affirms ... that regardless of tangible
job detriment, sexual harassment in the form of unwelcome advances
and either threats or promises of employment action is sufficient
for women to receive remedies in a court of law,'' said Jones'
co-counsel, John Whitehead, president of the Rutherford Institute,
which is paying her legal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Jones accused Clinton of propositioning her when he was Arkansas
governor and she was a state employee. A federal judge threw out
the lawsuit and said employees can collect damages only if their
refusal to submit to sexual demands results in on-the-job
retaliation. The judge said Jones had not shown any adverse
job-related consequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
