<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, June 27, 1998, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potent thunderstorms will erupt over the upper Middle West on
Saturday as a cool front associated with a sluggish low pressure
system in western Canada wedges under and lifts humid air pouring
north from the Gulf of Mexico. Storms will ignite across western
Minnesota and eastern South Dakota and then forge eastward across
the Great Lakes region. A few storms will reach severe levels, with
hail, damaging winds and tornadoes possible.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of thunderstorms will flare up Saturday night across
the central Plains as a wedge of warm air aloft, which inhibited
storm development during the day, is eroded by cooler air
associated with a jet stream disturbance arriving from the Rockies.
Heavy rain is possible, with the main threat directed at Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, downpours will batter parts of the upper Texas and
Louisiana seaboards as a tropical low pressure area works in tandem
with air teeming with moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy showers and thunderstorms are possible later Saturday and
Saturday night from lower Michigan across parts of Ohio, West
Virginia and southwestern Pennsylvania as a stalling front teams
with jet stream disturbances and a flow of very humid air from the
southwest.
</P>
<P>
   Humidity will gradually lower in the Northeast on Saturday and
Saturday night as dry air filters south behind a weak cool front.
Hit-or-miss showers and thunderstorms will escort the front
southward across the region. Meanwhile, isolated heavy storms will
boil up over parts of North Carolina as cooler air aloft arrives
over hot, humid surface air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: For Good Measure
</P>
<P>
   Great care is taken to insure accurate temperature measurements.
Official thermometers are mounted in white enclosures so that
sunlight does not fall on them and warm them. Because air does not
readily absorb sunlight, a thermometer exposed to sunlight would
register too high a reading for the actual air temperature.
Similarly, thermometers are located five feet above the ground and
away from buildings so that infrared radiation from these objects
is not readily absorbed by instruments. Thus, home and bank
thermometers often read too high for the actual air temperature.
</P>
</TEXT>
