<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, June 27. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Beijing) _ President Clinton was formally received
by President Jiang Zemin on Saturday in a military ceremony on
Tiananmen Square, the vast tombstone of a failed revolution. He
stood mute throughout, as is customary at such arrival ceremonies.
Clinton and Jiang then inspected army troops and reviewed an honor
guard on ground that human rights advocates around the world
consider stained with the blood of martyrs. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Serbia) _ Belgrade has ordered its military
and special police to mount widescale attacks in Kosovo to
recapture pockets held by ethnic Albanian rebels and reopen roads
the separatist rebels have blocked for weeks, Western diplomats and
military officials said on Friday. The escalation of the fight
against the rebels came as Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. special
envoy, left Pristina on Friday emptyhanded after four days of
shuttle talks with the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and
ethnic Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-ELECT (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Parties committed
to the Northern Ireland peace settlement emerged winners in the
election for the new Assembly on Friday, but candidates opposed to
the accord won enough seats to call into question the value of that
victory. The results showed that the province's two biggest
parties, the Ulster Unionist Party of David Trimble and the Social
Democratic and Labor Party of John Hume, would get the chance to
fulfill their historic pledge to work together to end the sectarian
conflict. But the ongoing count of the ballots from Thursday's
election, which will not be complete until Saturday, was exposing
deep divisions in Trimble's support as many party members deserted
him to cast their votes for other Protestant candidates wary of
cooperation with the Catholics. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court clarified the law
on sexual harassment in the workplace today, making some lawsuits
against employers easier to win while limiting the legal exposure
of companies that have effective anti-harassment policies in place.
The two 7-to-2 decisions cut through a thicket of confusing and
contradictory lower-court rulings that had grown up in the 12 years
since the justices first ruled that sexual harassment was a form of
employment discrimination. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LANDLORD (New York) _ Over the last 20 years the families at
Bedford Gardens, a sprawling Brooklyn apartment complex, have grown
accustomed to encountering the name Kraus at every turn. At the
center of an empire of companies bearing his name is Herman Kraus,
a tall, methodical, 70-year-old lawyer. Year after year, through
legal maneuvering and sheer tenacity, he has managed to award his
own companies almost every major contract to operate and maintain
the 639-apartment complex, which gets more than $3 million a year
from the federal government in rent assistance for its
working-class tenants. The unusual arrangement has made the complex
into what city officials have described as the closest thing to a
monopoly in the city's assisted housing system. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ When finance ministers and investment
strategists have nightmares these days, they often involve huge
financial institutions whose names are hardly household words in
the West. Yet if names like Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank or Ashikaga Bank
make Western tongues trip, there is a growing apprehension that
they and other Japanese financial institutions may threaten the
long boom on Wall Street and even the stability of the global
economy. There is increasing agreement in world financial capitals
that Japan's recessionary problems center on a problem the
government is only beginning to confront: the mountain of bad debts
at the nation's banks. By Sheryl WuDunn and Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL (New York) _ Jury returns a guilty verdict in
federal trial of Francis X. Livoti, former police officer accused
in choking death of Bronx man.
</P>
