<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT HEARS ARGUMENTS ON EXECUTIVE PRIVILEGE FOR SECRET SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal appeals court Friday greeted with
considerable skepticism the Clinton administration's claim that
Secret Service agents should not have to testify in the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing before the three-judge panel, Justice Department
lawyer Stephen Preston came under a barrage of difficult questions
about who could invoke the novel privilege created by the
administration, how long such a privilege might last, whether the
administration could use it to limit the testimony of retired
agents, and how broadly it could be applied.
</P>
<P>
   One of the judges, Douglas Ginsburg, referred to the contours of
the proposed privilege as ``odd'' and ``bizarre.'' Another member
of the panel, Stephen Williams, said it was ``unique'' for the
administration to seek a privilege for protecting the president
that the president himself does not invoke.
</P>
<P>
   The third judge, A. Raymond Randolph, questioned how the
government could continue to exert authority to limit the testimony
of retired agents. He also suggested that the proposed privilege
conflicts with a federal law that requires all federal employees to
report evidence of crimes to the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   The judges' questions strongly suggested that Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel investigating the nature of the president's
relationship with the former White House intern Monica Lewinsky,
would prevail, at least at the appeals court level, in defeating
the claim by the Secret Service that confidentiality is essential
to protecting the president.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigators have sought to question Secret Service
officers and an agency lawyer about President Clinton and others in
the White House as part of the inquiry into whether anyone lied or
obstructed justice in the Lewinsky inquiry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The tone of Friday's hearing was the first welcome sign for
Starr this week. Thursday, he suffered two setbacks. Over the
objections of prosecutors, a federal judge in Arkansas ordered the
release of Susan H. McDougal, a former business partner of Bill and
Hillary Rodham Clinton, shortening her prison term by eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday the Supreme Court ruled that Starr was not
entitled to the notes of a lawyer representing the former White
House aide Vincent Foster because they were protected by the
lawyer-client privilege. Foster committed suicide five years ago,
and the Supreme Court held that the lawyer-client privilege
survived the death of the client.
</P>
<P>
   In the Secret Service case Friday, Starr made reference to the
court's decision, during a series of questions about whether former
agents under the administration's privilege theory could testify
about former or dead presidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned yesterday that people have a keen interest in their
posthumous reputation,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of us,'' Starr replied, ``learned that in a very keen
and acute way.''
</P>
<P>
   The sixth floor of the federal courthouse Friday was like a
kaleidoscope of Clinton scandal and investigation. Down the hall
from the appeals court hearing, a federal district judge was
considering motions by Webster Hubbell and his wife, Suzanna, to
throw out a tax case on the grounds that Starr had no authority to
bring such a case. The courtroom was crammed with defense lawyers
representing other targets of other independent counsels examining
the Clinton administration. And James Robertson, the federal
district judge hearing the oral arguments, was also supervising a
jury that Friday began deliberations in a case brought against two
defendants by the independent counsel investigating former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1814EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODMAN-ARTS-490&AMP;ADD-     06-26 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODMAN-ARTS-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEERING ROY GOODMAN, FOR THE SAKE OF THE ARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Calling himself ``a most cogent argument for term
limits,'' Roy Goodman celebrated his 30th anniversary in the state
Senate at a fund-raising dinner on Thursday night that drew many
arts figures sustained over the years by grants he has delivered
from Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Among his toasters and roasters at the Waldorf-Astoria hotel was
his fellow Republican Gov. George Pataki who recently vetoed some
of the arts appropriations that Goodman tried to add to the latest
state budget. But the governor called the arts ``one of the things
that has made this city different'' and praised Goodman for his
advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our party screws this up in Washington, Roy Goodman is
going to make sure we get it right in Albany,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, 68, announced in March that he was seeking state arts
grants of slightly over $52 million, but the total has since been
cut to below $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still in the kind of maneuvering Goodman is known for, he has
rounded up an additional $7 million in capital grants for Carnegie
Hall, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Intrepid Sea-Air-Space
Museum, the radio station WNYC and the new 42nd Street, among other
cultural institutions, as so-called member initiatives written into
bills. About $1 million more in operating grants to other groups is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner, attended by 360 guests, raised about $300,000 for
Goodman's 16th Senate race this fall, for a rematch against his
last Democratic challenger, Robert Bellinson, a lawyer whom Goodman
beat, with 62 percent to 36 percent of the vote in their 26th
District on the East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The independently wealthy Goodman, whose immigrant father
developed pharmaceuticals, including Ex-Lax, has raised a campaign
war chest of $1 million that he said may also underwrite a bid for
higher office.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to be more specific but he ruled out another
campaign for mayor. He ran and lost to Edward Koch and other
challengers in 1977. He began his career in government and politics
as Mayor John Lindsay's first director of finance and city
treasurer in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians of all stripes, including Democrats like former
Mayor Abraham Beame and Rep. Charles Rangel, chairman of the House
Ways and Means Committee, were on hand for the bipartisan salute
that often took on a lampoonish edge, depending on the speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been remarkable,'' said Kurt Vonnegut, the writer,
adding, ``and may I say, un-Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush, who served as co-chairman of the event
but could not attend, because of a scheduling conflict, sent a
``Dear Roy'' letter with thanks for all the jokes passed along over
the years. ``Keep them coming,'' Bush wrote. ``But, Roy, don't give
up your day job.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, noting that he had entered office backing term limits
for politicians, said: ``Tonight we're celebrating failure. Who
needs term limits?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, starting with his well-worn
Mafia-godfather imitation, praised Goodman's legislative efforts to
investigate mob control of the carting industry.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Andrew Eristoff, who said that Goodman has been
his state senator for just about his whole life, urged him to keep
spinning his tales, ``even if your polysyllabic but wise
loquaciousness has us mystified.''
</P>
<P>
   Celeste Holm, the actress, and Roberta Peters, the soprano, also
spoke. Goodman's daughter Claire Goodman Cloud, a singer,
entertained with her band. Tony Randall, rushing off stage after
``The Sunshine Boys,'' made it in time to hail Goodman. If anyone
was surprised he was there, the septuagenarian Randall said, ``I'm
surprised I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Adams, the gossip columnist, wouldn't say that Goodman has
been around a long time but, she said, ``if you look at an
enlargement of `The Last Supper,' he's third from the right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
