A9150 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARLINS-COLUMN26-COX     06-26 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLINS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mac's moonshots over Miami may set homer mark
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've done the math. Regardless of the chaos that may ensue, it
is my duty to inform you that it really could happen.
</P>
<P>
   No, not a direct hit from a barn-sized meteor. This is bigger
than that. This is so enormous, it could actually make the Florida
Marlins matter once more.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this. Or better, listen to the distant, rumbling
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   It is the end of August in Miami, with September waiting at the
gate. The Marlins are 35 games out of first place in the NL East.
The field at Pro Player Stadium is looking a little tired. By this
time, you see, the Dolphins will have played a couple of exhibition
games there, chalking up the baseball diamond with lines of
football authority and scoring it with signs of the temporary
bleachers being rolled back and forth across left field.
</P>
<P>
   To fill the stadium under ordinary conditions would take
something more than a cap giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   What we're talking here, though, is almost beyond the
imagination. We're talking Mark McGwire, baseball's answer to King
Kong, marching into Pro Player Stadium ahead of an army of
satellite TV trucks and a squadron of news helicopters with the
unstated but undeniable goal of erasing Roger Maris' asterisk once
and for all.
</P>
<P>
   With the slightest adjustment to McGwire's current pace, turning
it up just a quarter of a notch, baseball's most majestic
single-season record could be tied and possibly even toasted at Pro
Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the logic, but please don't read it aloud. Big Mac
doesn't like to hear this stuff and we don't want to upset him, not
at this delicate moment in the hyping process.
</P>
<P>
   The man has 35 homers already. That's an average of one goner
for every 2.2 games St. Louis has played this season. Now you could
factor in that McGwire has missed four games because of injury and
two more because Tony La Russa wanted to give him a rest. That
changes the ratio to one homer for every two games that Big Mac has
played, an unrealistic standard given the fact he's sure to miss a
few more.
</P>
<P>
   Let's agree, then, on 2.2 games for every McGwire homer, on the
average. Starting today, he'd need just less than 61 games to tie
Maris' record of 61 homers. To break it, he'd need 63 games.
Drumroll, please.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for the first landmark has McGwire tying Maris'
record at Pro Player Stadium on Sept.1, the middle of a three-game
series with the Marlins. And if he picks up the pace just a bit,
the second, grander landmark could come here, too.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I hear you out there. Foolish conjecture, you're saying. The
ultimate example of overbearing statistical manipulation.
</P>
<P>
   Guilty and guilty. McGwire might not break the record, or if it
is broken, somebody else might do it. Have you checked Sammy Sosa
or Ken Griffey Jr., lately?
</P>
<P>
   All the same, it's a kick to contemplate. Remember McGwire's
first visit to Miami last August? An upper-deck moonshot, and then
another. Two upper-deckers in one game. Only Game 7 of the 1997
World Series produced more spectacular footage at Pro Player.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm pulling for it big-time. Nothing could be more
fitting of baseball's modern legacy than McGwire making history
here. Then we'd have Hank Aaron breaking the career home run record
in a ballpark that no longer exists and Big Mac breaking the season
record in a ballpark nobody wants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
