<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARLINS-GUIDRY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guidry takes time to help a Cajun
 &HT;    By Dan Graziano
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Fontenot was a year old in 1978, when Ron Guidry was a New
York Yankees hero, pitching hundreds of miles away from Fontenot's
Louisiana hometown of Lafayette. Fontenot was too young to really
notice.
</P>
<P>
   He was 18 in 1995 when he was drafted by the San Francisco
Giants and went off to play professional baseball. By then, he was
aware of the significance of Guidry, the slightly built Cajun
left-hander living 15 minutes from Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Guidry's nephew, Brooks Badeaux, was a teammate of Fontenot's at
Acadiana High School, just outside of Lafayette. So when Fontenot's
parents called Guidry and asked if he'd talk with their son about
life in pro baseball, Guidry was happy to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to his house,'' said Fontenot, now a Marlins starter
who will pitch tonight against the Red Sox. ``What a great guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he said a lot of things just trying to prepare me for
some of the things I'll probably be facing, and just to encourage
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry enjoys it. He just took a job as a pitching coach with an
independent minor-league team in Lafayette, called the Bayou
Bullfrogs. He teaches young players how to pitch and how to
prepare.
</P>
<P>
   But since the Texas-Louisiana League isn't exactly churning out
big-leaguers, Guidry also works with prospects such as Fontenot and
Phillies rookie Carlton Loewer, who's also from that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is from Cajun country,'' Guidry said. ``He is the next
Cajun.''
</P>
<P>
   Approached with this information, Fontenot shakes his head. He's
got the roots, he admits, and the surname. But he doesn't have the
accent. Not in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get away from the Cajun accent, I lose it,'' Fontenot
said. ``But all you've got to do is go back to your parents' house,
or your friends' house or your grandparents' house, and it comes
right back.''
</P>
<P>
   Guidry, whose accent is thick and whose roots are thickly
embedded in the soft Louisiana soil, takes pride in being a Cajun,
and wouldn't bestow such a tag on someone of whom he didn't think
highly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey is a good one,'' Guidry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime we have a pitcher from this area, I watch him pretty
close, and he's got what it takes to be a good one. I'm glad he's
up (in the majors), because that's the best way to learn fast.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the advice he gave him, Guidry remembered one part
clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, your privacy is the first thing you lose,'' Guidry
said. ``So you have to respect your own privacy, because no one
else will. It's something you have to give up if you want to be a
big-leaguer.''
</P>
<P>
   When he remembers his pre-professional encounter with a
Louisiana (and New York) legend, Fontenot is thankful for the time
Guidry took.
</P>
<P>
   And he's still a little awe-struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing him pitching on TV, but I was so young,''
Fontenot said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things he did tell me was, when you go into a game,
you don't necessarily have to have your 95 mph fastball right away,
that you can get by without your best stuff and still win
sometimes. But he had nasty stuff, man. I still remember watching
him on TV and hearing them talk about his slider. He was awesome.
Like a little Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, approachable and helpful as any coach he could have
talked to before heading off for his first year in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like everybody's buddy,'' Fontenot said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My area's really not a big baseball area at all, and so I
don't think people there know how good he was. But he was great,
and I'm just glad to have gotten to know him.''
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-26-98 0019E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
