<SLUG> BC-PANTHERS-PLAYER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Panthers to lose a player today
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Florida has no first-round pick in the NHL
draft, but that doesn't mean the Panthers won't have a busy
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Bryan Murray has been negotiating with Nashville
GM David Poile in an effort to land a top goaltending prospect this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Florida also will lose one player in today's 2 p.m. expansion
draft. And while Murray hopes he's talked Poile into taking Johan
Garpenlov, Poile could select Dave Gagner or Kirk Muller, who were
also left unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   Poile can select up to five goaltenders, and Murray has talked
for months about trading for one that could team with Kevin Weekes
to make up Florida's goalie tandem of the future.
</P>
<P>
   After studying the talent available, however, Murray talked as
if he might have to settle with what he's got: Weekes and veteran
Kirk McLean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston got by last year with Byron Dafoe and Rob Tallas, and
other teams have had success without a big-name guy,'' he said
Thursday. ``We've got Kevin and Kirk, and they can play in the
league. Kevin hasn't proven he can win, but he's a good prospect.
Kirk is not in the upper echelon, but he's played a long time.
We're not desperate. If we can do something, fine. If we don't,
we'll survive.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bryan Murray still hadn't discussed the situation with new
coach Terry Murray, his brother, he has indicated the chances of
signing John Vanbiesbrouck, who can become an unrestricted free
agent Wednesday, are not good.
</P>
<P>
   Murray admitted he was ``disappointed'' that a couple of
last-minute trades shortened the list of goaltenders available. He
said he was interested in Steve Shields, who was traded from
Buffalo to San Jose and then protected by the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are others,'' he said. ``Kevin Hodson (of Detroit),
Jim Carey (Boston), Mike Dunham (New Jersey) and Jamie McLennan are
all guys who can play in the league, though most of them haven't
had the chance to be a number one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Murray said his expectation that Poile will take Garpenlov
in today's draft, meanwhile, stemmed from conversations he's had
lately with Poile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's asked a lot about him, and I've told him he's a good,
smart player who can score, but maybe didn't get enough opportunity
with us last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, Florida's first pick would be the second pick
of the second round, or the 29th overall.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
