<SLUG> BC-WEB-DR-INFO27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Check out your physician's credentials on the Web
 &HT;    By Mary Warejcka
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time, consumers worried about their doctors'
credentials will be able to check them on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   By July 1, 1999, information about Florida doctors' training,
liability insurance, malpractice lawsuits concluded for more than
$5,000 and discipline is expected to be on one Internet site.
Still, patients shouldn't rely solely on that information, both a
physician and patient advocate warn _ albeit for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles, which were approved by legislators in 1997, will
cover 56,000 medical doctors, osteopaths, chiropractors and
podiatrists. By next summer, the Florida Department of Health will
also have a plan to place background on the rest of the state's
more than 700,000 health workers on-line.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 board members and staff for the various medical
professions are meeting today in Palm Beach Gardens to discuss the
physician profile and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   People without computer access will be able to get the
information sent to them, said Pam Potter-Ricco, a health
department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be leaders in the country,'' said Ray McEachern,
president of the Association for Responsible Medicine, a
patient-advocate group with offices in Tampa and Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   But he said one key piece of information will be missing _ a
list of lawsuits the doctor won. McEachern contends that a doctor
with three won lawsuits could still signal a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Douglas Dedo, past-president of Palm Beach County's Medical
Society, said the number of suits does not always predict a bad
doctor. Patients need to rely more on what friends have to say and
their own experiences, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also worries incorrect information will be published on the
Internet. When Massachusetts became the first state to start a
doctor profile program in 1996, some records were not complete.
</P>
<P>
   But Potter-Ricco said all information will be verified with both
the doctors and with health department records. That includes
ensuring that doctors haven't lied about lawsuits or discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone caught lying can be disciplined, Potter-Ricco said. And
if doctors fail to turn in the profile, the health department can
fine them $50 a day.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the profile information is already available from the
department but takes at least several days to get. And the profile
will provide new training information, Potter-Ricco said. For
example, a person wanting a face lift can verify his doctor is
certified for the surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Staff researcher Xiao Kai Chen contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
