A9158 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACK-FARMER26-COX     06-26 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACK-FARMER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Farmer-Patrick continues to chase vindication
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Sandra Farmer-Patrick, an Olympic silver medalist in
1992, wasn't in New Orleans for the U.S. Track and Field
Championships. Technically, she could have been. Even though the
Wells Branch hurdler is still waiting to hear about an appeal to
USA Track and Field, which suspended her for a disputed positive
drug test two years ago, she believes she can now legally get her
career back on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``My time is up. The suspension is over,'' Farmer-Patrick said.
A pregnancy _ she and husband David are expecting a boy in late
July _ is what's currently keeping Farmer-Patrick out of
competition. She expects to start training again in the fall and
hopes to be vindicated by then.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began for Farmer-Patrick at the U.S. Olympic trials in
1996. Both she and Mary Slaney were tested and registered elevated
levels of testosterone to epitestosterone (T.E. ratio). Both
substances are found naturally in the body, but testosterone is
also used as a performance-enhancing steroid.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and experts for both Slaney and Farmer-Patrick contended
that the test was flawed, that a positive 6-to-1 T.E. ratio can
also be caused by a lowered level of epitestosterone, which can be
caused by a variety of factors in females.
</P>
<P>
   Slaney was cleared for competition by USA Track and Field in
September. Farmer-Patrick, meanwhile, kept waiting and waiting and
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent all the relevant facts. They refused to accept those
facts. They refused to reverse anything, but we were still waiting
to hear from them. I can't believe it has taken this long,''
Farmer-Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jamaican-born Farmer-Patrick can't help but compare her case
to that of the popular Slaney.
</P>
<P>
   ``They suspended her after me and they exonerated her before
me,'' she said. ``I had a lot of faith in USA Track. I'm saddened
to think that the process is not fair for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer-Patrick said that she had a hearing with USA Track and
Field in February 1997 and that they reached a decision to suspend
her in May. Although the process is supposed to be confidential,
word soon got out. Farmer-Patrick missed the world championships in
June of last year and has not competed since.
</P>
<P>
   She said she furnished test results and other evidence as part
of the appeal process, but has heard nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess one of the holdups was the transcripts. They were
missing some information,'' Farmer-Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlhough she knew her two-year ban would be up this summer
anyway, she has not been training for competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally I was so drained,'' Farmer-Patrick said. ``I
didn't have the same fire and intensity. Sometimes I just get
really numb. They took a part of me away.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Farmer-Patrick said it will take her about a
year to get in top competitive shape. Her main goal _ to compete in
the 2000 Olympics _ remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-25-98 2045E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
