<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-REBELS-ART-2TA     06-26 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REBELS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATHS OF 11 PEASANTS MAY NURTURE SEEDS OF REBELLION NEAR ACAPULCO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 28) 
(Photo available on NYT photo service) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AHUACACHAHUE, Mexico _ Mauro Feliciano and Honorio Garcia were
simple men, dirt farmers who shared the grinding poverty of their
Indian neighbors in the forgotten mountains of southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The desire to better their world, say family and friends, led
Feliciano and Garcia to the nearby village of El Charco three weeks
ago to hear the ideas of a band of rebels. There, in a small
hilltop grammar school, Mexican army bullets took their lives along
with those of nine other people the government says were leftist
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The bloody deaths lay bare the seething frustration and anger
among Mexico's peasants, many of them Indian, that has propelled a
growing number to consider the guerrillas' gospel of violence, say
people in this Mixtec-speaking village where Feliciano, 49, and
Garcia, 32, lived.
</P>
<P>
   That willingness to listen has transformed this slumping corner
of Mexico into fertile soil for the Popular Revolutionary Army, or
EPR, a still vaguely defined leftist group that first appeared
nearly 100 miles from here two years ago Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Like past killings of peasants at the hands of government
forces, the deaths of the 11 people at the school in El Charco, 75
miles east of Acapulco in Guerrero state, may nurture the seeds of
rebellion already germinating in these mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has the idea of seeing whether this (rebellion) is an
alternative for the problems they find themselves in,'' says
Inocencio Silverio, a 30-year-old Roman Catholic priest and Mixtec
Indian for whom Garcia worked until recently as a catechist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is so desperate,'' he says. ``They want a solution,
whatever it might be. They are willing to listen to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPR first appeared June 28, 1996, in the mountain hamlet of
Aguas Blancas, where exactly one year earlier state police gunned
down 17 unarmed farmers heading for an anti-government protest. The
guerrillas, carrying AK-47 assault rifles and dressed in new
uniforms, showed up at a ceremony commemorating the anniversary of
the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the rebels stunned Mexico by attacking the
Pacific coast resort of Huatulco and other towns across the
country's south, leaving scores dead. Soon after, government
security forces and secret police arrested suspected EPR members in
Guerrero, Oaxaca and other states.
</P>
<P>
   The EPR seemed to all but disappear. As Mexico's attention
returned to the insurgency of the Zapatista National Liberation
Army, which began in 1994 in southernmost Chiapas state, the newer
guerrilla group was largely forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The June 7 shootings at El Charco brought the EPR back into
focus. Since the killings, EPR guerrillas and government forces
have clashed several times. Last Monday, three soldiers were killed
in what the government says was a guerrilla ambush in the mountains
north of the resort of Zihuatanejo.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas, primarily Maya Indians, have always based their
insurrection on the call for greater rights for Mexico's indigenous
minority. In contrast, the EPR has espoused the leftist
revolutionary principles of movements that sprang up in the 1960s
throughout Latin America. The group's statements have condemned
Mexico's political system and economic policies, which have
produced stark income disparities.
</P>
<P>
   But almost from the start, much of the EPR's armed activity has
taken place in indigenous areas of Guerrero, Oaxaca and other
southern states, where Indians remain among the poorest of Mexico's
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 11 people killed in the early morning hours of June 7 in
El Charco, 10 were Mixtec villagers from Ahuacachahue (pronounced
ah-wah-kah-CHA-way) and other nearby towns, and one was a student
at the National Autonomous University in Mexico City. All had spent
the night in the school after attending the guerrilla assembly
there the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels leading the meeting belonged either to the EPR or to
a small offshoot that had broken away from the guerrilla group in
March. A communique printed in the Mexican press and attributed to
the rebels claimed the new group was formed because its leaders
were frustrated with the lack of action by the EPR command.
</P>
<P>
   What was discussed at the assembly remains unclear. Peasants who
were there insist that the rebels simply talked about how to better
organize communities to petition the government for fertilizer and
other aid. Government officials say the guerrillas were giving
tactical training to new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Officials insist that all the people killed took part in a
firefight with government soldiers. But survivors and human rights
groups say that innocent people were killed and that some of the
dead may have been executed after surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost nobody was armed,'' says Odilon Romero, the 39-year-old
leftist mayor of Ayutla de los Libres, whose jurisdiction includes
the villages where the dead Indians lived. ``There are many strange
elements to all of this, a lot of things that don't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`PEOPLE DIDN'T WANT THE VIOLENCE' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the killings, word spread throughout the
Mixtec Indian towns near El Charco that the guerrillas wanted to
meet with villagers.
</P>
<P>
   There had been other such meetings since last summer, villagers
say, and each community had sent people. This time, Feliciano and
Garcia went for Ahuacachahue, a town of 4,000 about 10 miles across
the mountains from El Charco.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were serious sorts, those who knew them say. They
talked frequently about finding ways to lift their families _ and
their community _ out of the poverty that engulfed them.
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano was identified by the government as Mauro Morales, a
name, family members say, he also used. A father of 12, he had
taken part in local political and social organizations before being
elected ``comisario,'' the village's top official, late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Short and dark with solemn demeanor and intense eyes, Feliciano
fed his family by growing corn, beans, vegetables and fruit on
about 10 acres.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia _ Feliciano's brother-in-law and the father of five
children under the age of 11 _ was a religious man who had served
as a catechist, or lay leader, in the local Catholic parish. He
farmed his own small parcel of land.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
