<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-HATCH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATCH VOWS MORE CONGRESSIONAL HEARINGS ON MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee
Friday vowed to open a new set of hearings into whether Microsoft
is poised to dominate the rapidly growing world of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, issued a report criticizing Microsoft
for allegedly misleading his committee about a variety of the
company's practices, and he complained that the company has tried
to use public relations to distract the public from its conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, who has been a persistent critic of the software giant,
said he would open his hearings after the Senate returns from its
July 4 recess. The hearings are unlikely to lead to any change in
law, but would provide a forum for Microsoft's critics to air their
grievances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this is one of the more important policy issues of
our day, one which will have far-reaching ramifications for years
to come, and that it would be remiss for lawmakers and law
enforcers not to be paying close attention to this issue,'' Hatch
said in a speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the hearings will focus on Microsoft's BackOffice
family of server products, which are designed to integrate various
computer functions for businesses. He said the hearings will also
focus on ``practices and developments affecting access to, and
transactions on, the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said the company has not been
informed of any plan to hold hearings, but that ``Sen. Hatch's
comments were very unfortunate and inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., blasted Hatch's ``lonely and
increasingly unsuccessful battle against Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sen. Hatch and the Department of Justice are little interested
in the facts or merits of the case, but surely interested in
bringing the most successful software company in the nation to its
knees so that less successful, less competitive companies that do
not have the ability to succeed on their own can do so,'' Gorton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's comments came just a day after Microsoft formally
launched Windows 98, the latest version of the company's operating
system for personal computers. And earlier this week, Microsoft won
a significant victory against its critics when a federal appeals
court threw out an order requiring changes in Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But the company still faces a now-weakened but still significant
lawsuit challenging Windows 98. That case is set for trial in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch Friday raised several new concerns about Microsoft's
conduct. In particular, the senator accused Microsoft of having
``seen fit to engage in a game of hide the ball,'' misleading his
committee and the public through a combination of misinformation
and a distracting public relations offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has, regrettably, seen fit to deploy a massive p.r.
campaign grounded in spin control and misdirection, as opposed to
engaging the American public on the basis of the facts and the
merits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said Microsoft misled the Judiciary Committee about its
licensing agreements with Internet service providers, about its
contracts with Internet content providers, and about several other
matters.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft denied misleading the committee, and said its spending
on public relations was necessary to counter similar actions of its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch also complained that Microsoft and its allies _ namely
Gorton _ have prevented the Justice Department from getting a
budget boost to pay for antitrust activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it rather surprising that any one company would ...
have the hubris to ... seek to restrain a federal law enforcement
agency that has an obligation to enforce the laws,'' Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   But Gorton said the antitrust division shouldn't get extra money
because ``these (legal) actions are a waste of the taxpayers' money
and represent the use of the taxpayers' money for the pursuit of
private antitrust remedies that, if they are appropriate at all,
should be financed by the competitors who seek them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
