</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REBELS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
AHUACACHAHUE, Mexico: parcel of land.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although he could not read or write, Feliciano pushed education
on his children, scraping together money from his meager income to
help one of his sons work his way through college in Chilpancingo,
the Guerrero state capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I was little, my father told me I had to study and
study. It was his dream,'' says Nicolas Feliciano, 21, the third
oldest of Mauro Feliciano's children and the first person in his
family ever to attend college. ``He was eating just tortillas and
salt in order to send me money for books.''
</P>
<P>
   After becoming an elected leader in January, Mauro Feliciano
spent months wheedling cement and other materials out of the city
government in Ayutla in order to build a Catholic church in his own
village.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia gave up his work with the church last month, Silverio
says, in order to help his brother-in-law with municipal matters.
</P>
<P>
   The priest says Garcia told him about his growing interest in
the guerrillas' message.
</P>
<P>
   Still, neither man was an active fighter, members of their
family insist. Like many of their neighbors, Feliciano and Garcia
were reluctant to pick up arms against the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``People didn't want the violence,'' Nicolas Feliciano says.
``They said the government was just waiting for us to do
something.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
VILLAGERS SEEK IMPROVEMENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mixtec farm villages that perch in the mountains down the
coast from Acapulco are as poor as any in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The rush in recent years to industrialize and join the global
economy has left behind millions of Mexicans, especially those in
the countryside. Nearly 75 percent of Mexico's Indians make their
living by farming.
</P>
<P>
   A surging population has meant less land to go around. The
eroding, thin soil has worn out in many places, making expensive
fertilizer and other farm products essential to raising crops. A
lack of good roads makes it difficult, if not impossible, to get
cash crops to market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Indians are on the very bottom,'' says Silverio, who was
born near El Charco. ``Those in power don't know anything about us.
They come looking for votes and, then once they are elected,
quickly forget about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since returning to the area three years ago after studying for
the priesthood, Silverio says he and other community leaders have
pushed for improvements, such as secondary schools, health clinics,
clean drinking water and electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people haven't received anything. None of our petitions
have been answered,'' the priest says. ``The first response of the
government is blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that people are sympathetic with the (guerrilla)
movement,'' he says. ``It is just that no one else has offered any
other plan.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In the dry season, the roads that climb into the mountains
toward El Charco and Ahuacachahue are kidney-busting ribbons of
deep ruts and rocks. The torrential downpours of the tropical rainy
season, which is beginning now, mean the tracks will cease being
roads at all.
</P>
<P>
   With rain clouds now forming most afternoons, farmers stand in
the fields that hug the steep mountainsides, poking holes into the
soil to plant seeds.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Ocean shines like a broken mirror beyond the ridges
that roll away to the south. Other mountains embrace the horizon to
the west and north.
</P>
<P>
   Overripe mangoes litter the rocky soil in the orchards that
cover much of these mountains in a thick blanket of green. Poor
roads and a lack of marketing skills have kept the area's produce
from being sold in the cities.
</P>
<P>
   The scent of fallen fruit assaults the nostrils, a pungent
reminder of wasted promise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LEARNING BITTER LESSONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People from surrounding villages continue to trek to El Charco.
They come not to talk rebellion but to collect government handouts.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't much.
</P>
<P>
   Each family gets a few sheets of corrugated roofing, a kilo of
rice, another of beans, a can of tuna and some cooking oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to make them forget the shooting,'' says
Celestino Maximo, a Mixtec Indian schoolteacher helping distribute
the goods. ``The officials justify themselves by giving some
roofing, a bag of rice.''
</P>
<P>
   The state government has sent work crews to repair the school
complex where the killings occurred. Workers patch the
shrapnel-peppered roof, plaster over the hundreds of bullet holes
in the walls, and clean the dried blood from the floor and the
basketball courts where people died.
</P>
<P>
   The complex's three small buildings will never serve as the
village school again, teachers say. Local beliefs hold that the
bloodshed has created an evil environment that could sicken the
children. The 60 students now study in squat adobe buildings down
the hill from the school buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Their teachers say the complex, built barely a year ago, could
be used as a library. Or perhaps, they say, the buildings could
serve as a community center.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to organize more because of this,'' Maximo
says.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that organization will lead to more violence is
uncertain. But the lessons learned three weeks ago at the school
are bitter ones, teachers say. And they will be long remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (officials) were accustomed that we indigenous peoples
would accept anything, that we would never lift our heads,'' says
Valentin Zavala, also a Mixtec teacher. ``And now if we do, they
try to repress us. Whenever someone rises up to defend the people,
they finish them off.''
</P>
<P>
   After his father was killed, Nicolas Feliciano quit college and
returned home to help with the farming. His father had planted five
acres of corn shortly before he died, and Nicolas says he'll help
bring in the crop. He hopes to resume his studies in a year, maybe
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a peasant,'' the articulate young man says on the back
patio of his family's two-room house in Ahuacachahue. ``I am
Indian. I speak Mixtec. I am not ashamed of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government considers us garbage, animals,'' he says.
``There is no respect for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Feliciano's voice tightens and his jaw clenches as he talks
about the killings of his father and uncle.
</P>
<P>
   But he won't look for trouble with the government, he says. With
a widowed mother and nine younger brothers and sisters, Feliciano
says, too many mouths depend on him for that. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The government only did this so people would be afraid,'' he
says of the El Charco clash. ``I don't fear the government, (but) I
am going to control myself for my mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one day soon, the people are going to rise in arms,''
Feliciano predicts. ``People are completely tired of all this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
