<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9168 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TELEPHONE-TAX     06-26 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TELEPHONE-TAX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    TELEPHONE BILLS TO GO UP IN JULY
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For use the weekend of June 27-30 
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid strenuous protests from lawmakers and consumer
groups, residential phone customers can expect a new charge to
appear on their monthly long-distance bills beginning July 1 to
help defray costs for hooking the nation's schools and libraries
into the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Households that use AT&AMP;T services will be charged a flat 93
cents, while Sprint plans to charge its customers a rate of 4.5
percent on long-distance calls. MCI, the other top long-distance
carrier, has not determined the rate, although spokeswoman Claire
Hassett estimated that MCI would be charging about the same level
as Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the companies had quietly paid the fees, set by
the Federal Communications Commission as of last January, to its
new high technology subsidy fund for schools and libraries. But the
long-distance carriers' decision to pass those charges directly to
customers has stirred cries of ``taxation without representation''
from critics who say that the un-elected FCC is raising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., told a computer trade show
in Atlanta in early June that it is ``wrong for five un-elected,
appointed commissioners to establish a tax on every telephone line
in the United States.'' He predicted then that Congress would
``probably block it in the next two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   However, on the eve of the new surcharge, Congress has yet to
act. The speaker ``still feels that this is unconstitutional,''
said spokesman Andrew Weinstein. ``There's a good chance that
action will be taken to address the issue in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what action is far from certain in the increasingly
politically complex dispute that affects nearly every household and
tens of thousands of schools in a program that would cost an
estimated $20 billion over the next 10 years. Since Vice President
Al Gore has been its most prominent cheerleader, the technology fee
has given Republicans an opening to dub it the ``Gore tax'' and
highlight the program's many early stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   At least one lawmaker, Rep. James F. Sensenbrenner, R-Wisc., has
introduced a bill to cancel the program altogether. But some
Republicans fear that would be seen as anti-education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have to be careful about the 'soccer moms,''' said
Ken Johnson, spokesman for Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of
the House telecommunications subcommittee. Tauzin is calling for
replacing the controversial fee with proceeds from a long-standing
3 percent telephone excise tax . Tauzin would cut that tax, first
enacted in 1914, by half and dedicate the proceeds to block grants
for states to buy technology for schools and libraries, but he has
yet to get a green light from Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has said that
long-distance carriers should not add the surcharge to customers'
bills. FCC Chairman William Kennard said recently that
``long-distance rates have never been lower,'' and added that the
``e-rate,'' as the technology subsidy fee is nicknamed by
supporters, should not cause telephone bills to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fee controversy, the program has had more than its
share of start-up problems:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About 30,000 applications for subsidies of up to 90 percent
for the cost of telephone and Internet service have been waiting
for approval since last April. Although the new fund has already
collected $650 million, no funds have been distributed. A
spokeswoman for the Schools and Library Fund, a private corporation
that was set up to run the federal program, could not predict when
the money would begin flowing to qualified schools.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some of the schools sent in the high technology equivalent of
a letter to Santa Claus, asing not only for the electronic hookup
but also a long list of advanced computer gear, as well as interior
redecorating, such as painting and new carpet, for rooms once they
have been wired.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Schools and Library Fund has been found to have a shaky
legal foundation. The General Accounting Office, the investigative
arm of Congress, has released a report saying that the
Telecommunications Act of 1996, on which the fund is based, does
not authorize such a private organization.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The fund's chief executive officer, Ira Fishman, was given a
$200,000 annual salary, equal to President Clinton's. In response
to a flap, the FCC pared his pay to $150,000 as of July.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Expenses outpaced expectations and reached $7 million in the
first six months. Setting up the fund's Internet ``web site,'' for
example, cost more than half a million dollars, double the amount
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC responded to critics on June 12 by reducing the total
fee level for the first year to $1.9 billion instead of the $2.25
billion originally set. It also ordered the Schools and Library
Fund to focus on subsidies for basic Internet and phone connections
for the neediest school districts. Kennard called the move a
``slowdown'' for the first year.
</P>
<P>
   That has satisfied no one in the debate. Supporters want the
money sent to schools faster, and critics continue to point to
mismanagement. Senate Commerce Chairman John McCain, R-Ariz., has
scheduled a hearing in mid July to examine whether some schools are
asking for ``gold-plated'' computer equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
