<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF EXPRESS STOPPED   SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If one of the first Russians to play tennis, a
scribbler named Leo Tolstoy, had been at bleak, damp, chilly
Wimbledon Friday, he would have written a short story entitled
``The Eighteenth Time Never Fails'' with his countrywoman Natasha
Zvereva as the heroine.
</P>
<P>
   Tolstoy, a hacker with a court in the backyard, would describe
her trying decade of trying to avoid a beating by a superior (in
this case Steffi Graf) but getting stomped, anyway, 17 straight _
and then ... sweet deliverance, 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   In Tolstoy's 1877 novel, ``Anna Karenina,'' the namesake throws
herself in front of a train. Natasha Zvereva has been prostrating
herself before the Graf Express since being run over and crowned
with a double bagel in a gory 1988 French Open final. But Friday
she not only crawled off the tracks in time but derailed the
locomotive, the comeback journey, and the hopes of 13,120
Grafanatics filling Centre Court.
</P>
<P>
   This was a lot to ask of a loosey-goosey 27-year-old from Minsk
in Belarus, who loves to boogie, go her own way, and makes most of
her money playing doubles, having won 20 majors. Her singles, good
enough for a No. 22 ranking, is often a so-who-cares proposition in
which not even Hulk Hogan or Atlas could hold up her concentration.
</P>
<P>
   However, anybody back home in Minsk would tell you, ``Nobody
beats our Natasha 18 straight times.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the Natasha they know and love, though. Just as
Graf, working only her eighth gig in her current revival, third at
the Big W, ``wasn't myself ... tight ... nervous,'' neither was
Zvereva herself. Which she happily confessed after ``the best match
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Her short pigtails shook as she laughed, ``I never concentrated
on every point before. Every point. Everybody in the locker room
asked me if I was sick. They gave me a lot of you-know-what
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 4-all in the second, I started to think I could win.'' No
such thought had ever graced her wayward mind along the long, long
track that ran from Paris through such whistle stops as Key
Biscayne, Fla.; Montreal; Leipzig; Worcester, Mass.; Indian Wells,
Calif. ``I told myself to stop thinking immediately. Get it out of
my head. `Don't get distracted this time,' I said to myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In her life with Steffi Graf, Natasha impersonated the
Washington Generals while Graf was the Harlem Globetrotters. The
fall girl. Little Miss Zero. Graf was not uncharitable. Bones were
thrown: three of 37 sets were Natasha's to gnaw.
</P>
<P>
   Her Freedomless Trail began at Stade Roland Garros after
Zvereva, a 17-year-old Soviet, stunned the favorite, Martina
Navratilova, in the French semis. Ever in a hurry, Graf, at the
second stop of her Grand Slam travels of '88, was more emphatic
than usual, 6-0, 6-0. The most memorable passage of that 32-minute
crushing was the hour rain delay that divided it into two grim
acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sure, I remember that 6-0, 6-0. Pretty bad. I was too
young, too nervous,'' Zvereva said. ``But I don't remember the
rest. I don't say, `Well, No. 8 wasn't too bad,' or `No. 12 was
better.'''
</P>
<P>
   Few can do as much with a tennis ball as Natasha, who considers
herself ``a Russian'' even though she plays for Belarus. Her touch
is creative and imaginative with groundies and volleys. ``But ...
mindwise?'' she shrugged and smirked at herself.
</P>
<P>
   A free spirit _ ``I'd call myself a loner'' _ she doesn't
clutter her life with a coach or retinue, preferring to figure out
the game on her own. ``I just wanted to get the ball over the net,
get it on Steffi's backhand. That's the only plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Her low slice, topspin changeups, flawless reflex volleying, and
solid serving were sufficient to hang on to her own serve
throughout a close struggle. She pierced Graf just twice (opening
game, 11th game of the second). Uncharacteristically, Natasha hung
tough like Tolstoy's gallant Natasha of ``War and Peace.'' In the
tense closing game, she was firmness plus _ through the claque's
incessant ``Come on, Steffi!'' pleading, two deuces, a break point,
and a failed match point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it!'' she shrieked, kicking up her sneakered heels,
raising a fist, and trying to punch a hole in one of the
long-lingering, low-hanging charcoal clouds to celebrate Steffi's
sixth Wimbledon defeat in 74 matches. What better place to wreck a
hex? Centre Court, where Graf has triumphed seven times.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mother Freedom of Soviet tennis in 1989, Zvereva demanded
that her colleagues be permitted to keep all their prize money
rather than accept a meager stipend from the tennis ministry that
seized most of their cash. Natasha won that battle, though
pilloried in the press. Now she's liberated herself _ from Steffi
Graf.
</P>
<P>
   Can't you see the last line of Tolstoy's story? ``Natasha looked
her oppressor in the eye and was no longer Minsk meat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
