u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHIS-IRL-BOS &LR;      06-26 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHIS-IRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRE GOING TO JUMP IRL? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ New Hampshire International Speedway's Bob Bahre
was among the first track owners in the country to defect from
Championship Auto Racing Teams three years ago when he aligned his
1-mile oval with the breakaway Indy Racing League. But because of
sagging attendence figures and considerable financial losses from
staging IRL events, Bahre may be ready to part ways when his
three-year contract with the series expires after Sunday's New
England 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would work out better, but it hasn't been any
better,'' Bahre said. ``CART's not been doing that bad; IRL's not
doing that bad, either. But neither of them are doing great. I just
think they've got to get together. This has not been good.''
</P>
<P>
   After failing to draw more than 55,000 combined in the four
years that CART races were held at NHIS from 1992-95, Bahre had
hoped the fledgling series founded by Indianapolis Motor Speedway
president Tony George would be the answer. But, he said, that has
not been the case. Attendance declined from 24,000 two years ago to
22,000 last year. ``We need to get at least 25,000 (fans) this year
to break even,'' said Bahre.
</P>
<P>
   Be it CART or IRL, that's something Bahre has not done for any
of the open-wheel, Indy car events at NHIS. This weekend, without
the financial cushion a title sponsor would provide, Bahre
estimates he stands to lose as much as $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has staged wildly successful NASCAR Winston Cup
events at NHIS before crowds that have grown progressively larger
each year, Bahre is not certain how much longer he can afford to
sustain heavy losses with IRL events. ``Loyalty means a lot to us,
but there comes a point,'' Bahre said. ``I'm not saying we will
(leave), but I think Tony would understand if we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahre's solution? A CART and IRL reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you took (IRL executive director) Leo Mehl and (CART owner)
Roger Penske and threw them together in a room and you took (CART
CEO) Andrew Craig and Tony George out, you'd have a deal done in
three hours,'' Bahre said. ``I'm convinced of that _ but that's
only my opinion now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bahre said it was imperative to ``get rid of the egos'' in
order to reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told Andrew Craig that we were going with the IRL, he
said to me, `OK, well, then we're going to run right against
you,''' said Bahre, who noted that CART scheduled a race at Elkhart
Lake, Wis., that went head to head with his inaugural IRL race in
1996. ``The day he said that, he showed me what kind of man he was.
From that day on, I lost a lot of respect for the guy. There's a
lot of good people in CART, and a lot of good teams, but I have
absolutely no respect for Andrew Craig _ and that's only my
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not likely, then, that Bahre would go back to CART. But if
the series were to return to NHIS, it could be viewed as a
considerable victory in its ongoing battle with the IRL for
open-wheel supremacy. Still, Bahre said that if Sunday marked the
last IRL event at NHIS, he would move forward with his two Winston
Cup dates.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any discussions were planned with George, Bahre said,
``We haven't talked about it. The last time we talked was at
Daytona (in February). But we'll probably talk (this weekend). I
have no idea if they would stay or not. If they decided to pull
out, it would be up to Tony George.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9195 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      06-26 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SULLIVAN PICKED BY PREDATORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Nashville Predators stocked their inaugural team
Friday in Buffalo during the National Hockey League expansion
draft, and one of their selections was veteran forward Mike
Sullivan, plucked from the Bruins' roster.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the season, Bruins management went to Sullivan,
who was slated to become a Group 2 (restricted) free agent July 1,
and told him they wanted to sign him before the end of the year to
have enough players to meet the league requirement for exposure in
the expansion draft. At the time, the Bruins told Sullivan, who
made $550,000 last season, that he would likely be left
unprotected. Sullivan said he knew it was a possibility but felt it
was a fair contract and signed it.
</P>
<P>
   Now Sullivan will be packing up his family _ wife Kate and their
children, Kaitlin, Kiley, and Matthew _ and leaving the South Shore
for the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, I have a mixed reaction,'' said Sullivan,
reached by phone during a golf match at Hatherly Country Club. ``In
one regard, I loved playing in Boston. There was the excitement of
playing on a rebuilding team. But the reality of the business is
that when something like this comes up, you have to take it in
stride. Now I'm part of the optimism of starting a new franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old Sullivan, a native of Marshfield, Mass., was a
dependable cog in the Bruins' defensive wheel, and coach Pat Burns
often would utilize him to take key faceoffs in the defensive zone
late in the game or when the club was clinging to a one-goal lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan played 77 games and collected five goals, two of which
were game-winners, and 18 points. He had come to the Bruins just
over a year ago in a trade with the Calgary Flames.
President-general manager Harry Sinden said he believed that with
center Joe Thornton having a year under his belt and Jason Allison
having blossomed, the club could absorb the loss of Sullivan.
Veteran Tim Taylor, who is a Group 2 free agent but proved to be an
invaluable asset as the team's top defensive center, is expected to
be back next season. And if the Bruins elect to re-sign Group 2
free agent Ted Donato, he can also play center if need be.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the team projects to promote Randy Robitaille, Shawn
Bates, and Cameron Mann from AHL Providence, so management felt
that if Sullivan was taken, there also would be enough depth to
compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five guys out there (that would be candidates for the
Predators),'' said Sinden Friday. ``I wouldn't want to put them in
order. We did our homework and figured it was going to happen. It's
not that we wanted to lose Mike. We didn't. We wanted to keep him
but we felt he was the most expendable. It sounds like Mike
Sullivan wasn't appreciated. He was. I think he can extend his
career down there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that Nashville might not be the former Boston
University forward's last stop. During the expansion draft,
Predators GM David Poile said what you see is not necessarily what
you'll get, meaning there might be further roster tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little bit of talk about movement but nothing
concrete,'' said Sullivan, who has been in close contact with his
agent, Bob Murray. ``My agent said he'd be in contact if anything
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sullivan will enjoy the summer in Scituate, Mass.
before heading to his new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' he said. ``When we came home, it was nice to play
in front of my family, and my wife lives 10 minutes from her
mother. There are a lot of things we're going to miss about playing
in Boston. It was a terrific year. I was glad to be part of this
franchise. But in talking to my agent the last couple of days, I
kind of had the sense this was going to happen, so you try to
prepare yourself for it. But then the reality hits and it causes a
bit of turmoil. But it'll be good for our kids to experience a
different part of the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
