<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-SELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK MUTUAL LIFE PLANS LARGE REAL ESTATE SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a surprise move to cash in all at once on the country's
booming property markets, John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
said Friday that it would sell off most of its real estate
portfolio this year.
</P>
<P>
   The step is the latest by an asset management company to unload
prime real estate holdings. Last month, the Prudential Insurance
Co. of America, the nation's largest insurer, further liquidated
its outsized property portfolio by selling its Embarcedero Center
in San Francisco to Boston Properties Inc. of Boston for $1.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McGuire, head of Hancock's real estate investment group,
said Hancock would sell off around 150 of its 200 properties
starting this month. The sale will not include the company's Copley
Square, Boston headquarters, a glass skyscraper that is one of the
city's premier buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this is just a good time to take some profits out of
some of the properties we're holding,'' McGuire said. When asked
whether Hancock had considered securitizing its property holdings
as a real estate investment trust, or REIT, McGuire said, ``This
strategy (selling) is better for us.
</P>
<P>
   A phalanx of top-notch trophy properties has come onto the
market in recent months, as property-holding companies seek to reap
gains from the strongest real estate prices in a decade. The Sears
Tower and Merchandise Mart, both in Chicago, and the Chrysler
Building in New York, were sold earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is rare to see a company sell off most of its real estate
holdings in one fell swoop, as Hancock is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our opinion, it's not the proper time to divest all your
properties at once,'' said Catherine Polleys, vice president and
strategic consulting director at Torto Wheaton Research, an
industry consulting firm, in Boston. ``It is quite surprising to us
that they're selling off all of their portfolio. There has to be
another strategic move behind this.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Hancock, which manages total assets of $116
billion, declined to state the book or market values of the
properties, which are spread out across major metropolitan areas
and include one of the Watergate office buildings in Washington,
DC. Hancock owns all of the properties outright.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to use the proceeds to invest in its existing
businesses, which range from insurance products and mutual funds to
commercial mortgage and securitized lending operations. McGuire
declined to say whether the money would be used to finance
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, the nation's fifth largest mutual insurer, announced
earlier this month that it planned to convert into a publicly
traded company under an expensive and lengthy process known as
demutualization. The company has hired investment bank Morgan
Stanley &AMP; Co Inc. to dispose of its major office buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The John Hancock Center, a 100-story building that is one of
Chicago's most recognizable edifices, is already on the block.
Industry analysts say it could fetch $250 million and upwards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
