<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9213 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-26 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF INTEGRITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are masters of misguided sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts House Speaker Charles Flaherty pleads guilty to
tax evasion and liberals hesitate to demand his resignation.
(itals)He had such an admirable legislative record on behalf of the
poor.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Dianne Wilkerson violates the conditions of her
house arrest on similar charges and her colleagues hold their fire.
(itals)She had such a promising political future.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Louise Woodward kills an 8 1/2-month-old baby and the public
rationalizes her act of violence. (itals)She was only 18 years
old.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Patricia Smith, a columnist for this newspaper who
fabricated people, conversations, and scenes in columns that
appeared in this space on Monday and Friday over the last four
years.
</P>
<P>
   We cannot stop ourselves from bemoaning the ``tragedy'' that has
befallen her as if she were not the architect of her own demise. We
condemn the lies and praise the voice in the same breath, as if
they are not inextricably linked. In a piece criticizing her
fabrications, Dan Kennedy, media critic for the Boston Phoenix,
actually describes Patricia Smith as a journalist who ``spoke truth
to power.''
</P>
<P>
   The ombudsman for the Boston Globe reported dozens of phone
calls running in Smith's favor in the wake of her forced
resignation. Sadly, a lot of readers apparently think she didn't do
anything the rest of us don't do routinely.
</P>
<P>
   Compassion has its place _ no one wants to see another human
being self-destruct _ but what ever happened to righteous anger?
Why are we so afraid to condemn unequivocally the betrayal of a
public trust?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is race, the single subject we are unable to
discuss without shifting in our seats and averting our eyes.
Harvard Law Professor Alan Dershowitz would have us believe that
Patricia Smith was the victim of a double standard. To the
contrary, she was the beneficiary of one. Her fall had nothing to
do with her race; her rise had everything to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant newspaper in a city with a troubled racial past was
so seduced by the power and lyricism of her words it forgot that we
publish a daily newspaper here on Morrissey Boulevard, not a poetry
anthology.
</P>
<P>
   An honorable commitment to open these pages to people long
unrepresented led to a less-than-honorable tradeoff. Patricia
Smith's images were so mesmerizing, her rage so galvanizing, that
we chose not to see the deceit at their core.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst sort of racism that kept us from confronting
the fraud we long suspected. If we did ask, and she did tell, we
might lose her, and where would we be then? Where would we find an
(itals)honest(unitals) black columnist who wrote with such power
and grace? A white institution is paying now, just as much as a
black columnist, for its decision to trim, to cut corners, to roll
the dice.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Smith did not speak truth to power or to anyone else in
this space. On stage at the Cantab Lounge, she might give voice to
the voiceless. In this space, she gave voice to no one but herself.
</P>
<P>
   It might well be argued that there is more truth in the work of
Langston Hughes or Anne Sexton than in all the newspaper columns
laid end to end. But journalism makes no claim on ultimate truth.
We are charged only with holding up a mirror on the day's events.
That mirror either reflects the real lives of real people, or it is
no more than a funhouse distortion of this city and the ordinary
people at its heart.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those people open their lives to journalists and trust
us to tell their stories. Most of us privileged enough to do this
work are always amazed to hear the words, ``Come in and sit down.''
We are always humbled by the responsibility that trust engenders.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a double standard at The Boston Globe, Professor
Dershowitz? Sure there is. Mike Barnicle began work here as a
columnist at about the same time I began as a secretary. Isn't the
same double standard just as securely in place at the Harvard Law
School? Isn't that why Professor Derrick A. Bell Jr. refused to
teach his classes until the law school granted tenure to a black
woman? Isn't that why he finally gave up and left Cambridge for New
York?
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is harder for a woman, harder still for a black
woman, to break through the entrenched ranks of white men who
dominate this institution and others like it. But the events of the
last week are not about gender or racial bias or the glass ceiling.
They are about journalistic integrity, a phrase Patricia Smith and
her enablers at this newspaper have reduced to an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
