<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDUCP-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US TEAM AN INCH AHEAD, A MILE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Some of the old boys posed for pictures on the
field inside the Stade de La Beaujoire at halftime of their final
match Thursday night. This was the last roundup, after all, and
once the US World Cup soccer team scattered it would never be
together again.
</P>
<P>
   Not these players. Not this coach. Not this federation
president. At least half of this team won't be around for the next
World Cup in 2002 _ assuming the US even qualifies. Steve Sampson,
whose coaching contract ends with the tournament, almost certainly
won't be asked back. And Alan Rothenberg, who's been president
since 1990, leaves office in August.
</P>
<P>
   So where do the Yanks go from here? Though its three-and-out
performance here was no better than what the overmatched college
kids managed in 1990, the US undeniably is further along the road
than it was eight years ago. The Americans were 500-1 shots then.
They were only 150-1 here. Such is progress in a country where
soccer is the fifth professional sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are inching forward as a world soccer power,'' Rothenberg
said after the US had lost respectably _ but still lost _ to
Germany, Iran, and Yugoslavia. ``We are not leaping forward. We are
inching forward.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Americans have the A team on the field, they have
proven they can play with anybody. On an exceptional day, they can
beat a Brazil, an Argentina, a Nigeria, an England, a Colombia _
and they have. But on the average day, they're around 25th in the
world and they'll admit it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not among the elite, but we can compete with any
second-tier European country or top South American country,'' says
Sampson. ``We are not at the point, player to player, to compete
with the best teams in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The best teams, the Germanys and Brazils and Italys and
Argentinas, have 100 or more international-level players to choose
from. The Americans have fewer than four dozen. The best teams' top
players are stars in Germany's Bundesliga, Italy's Serie A, the
English Premier League, and the Spanish league.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, the top US players are stars in the
fledgling Major League Soccer, playing against other Americans.
That's good enough to qualify from the North and Central American
and Caribbean region, but not to make it to the second round of the
Mondial. ``You need players at a highly, highly competitive level
for a long period of time to get results at this level,'' says
Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   But what really keeps the Yanks in the second tier is their
narrow pipeline, the trickle of fresh talent that is barely enough
to replace the thirtysomethings on rebuilt knees. They saw that
clearly at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta, when the US lost by two
goals to Argentina. ``Argentina had six players who were starters
in Serie A,'' says Rothenberg. ```You know what this proves?' I
said to (secretary general) Hank Steinbrecher? `Their college kids
are a lot better than our college kids.'''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's kids, of course, don't go to college. Nobody else's
kids do. They sign with pro clubs as juniors and are fast-tracked
to the national side. Ronaldo, Brazil's newborn king, was on its
Cup roster at 17. Michael Owen, England's boy wonder, is only 18.
The youngest player on the US squad here (Frankie Hejduk) is 23.
``We're always playing catch-up,'' says Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   So the US federation has decided to bypass the college route and
get its promising 18- to 22-year-olds playing against pros as
quickly as possible. With Project 40, which began last year,
players like the Revolution's Brian Dunseth may go to college (with
tuition paid) but they work out with MLS clubs (making minimum
salary), play in the A League, and train with overseas clubs like
Glasgow Rangers, Chile's Catolica, and Mexico's Atlas FC.
</P>
<P>
   US Soccer also wants to pull promising under-17s out of high
school and put them in a year-round residency program in Florida
with all expenses paid. It's all part of the federation's bold
(some would say delusional) Project 2010, with $50 million targeted
toward winning the World Cup a dozen years from now. ``If we can
put a man on the moon,'' says Steinbrecher, ``we can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting a man on the moon may have been easier, because only the
Soviets were in the same game. The federation's plan has the Yanks,
who scored one goal here, reaching the quarterfinals next time. For
a start, they'll try to qualify again with a new plan, a new coach,
and new players and forget their three-and-out this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can try and rebuild and do better next time,'' old-boy
striker Eric Wynalda says. ``Because we can't let this happen
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
