<HEADER>
A9233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIGHT-FILM-REVIEW-HNS     06-26 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIGHT-FILM-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITES ATTRACT IN `OUT OF SIGHT' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early in ``Out of Sight,'' bank robber Jack Foley and federal
marshal Karen Sisco spend unplanned time together locked in the
trunk of a big Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   How they got there is not really important. What they do there
is essential to the movie. They talk.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the situation _ she's his hostage, he's covered with
sewer mud _ they find out they share interests, such as a love of
movies. They learn that they can immediately do what some couples
never learn to do, enjoy chatting with each other.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is a small part of the movie, but the rest of the
story grows from it. Like the same scene in Elmore Leonard's novel,
it lets us know right away that this movie has a quirky sense of
humor and romance, and that the relationship of these characters is
more important than the specifics of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   When you read a minireview of the movie next year in some TV
guidebook, it will probably say the movie is about some guys
pulling a diamond caper. As far as that goes, it's true. There is a
home break-in at the climax of the movie, and through most of the
film, the principal characters are working toward making that
happen.
</P>
<P>
   But that misses the point.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of ``Out of Sight'' is the impossible romance between
Foley, a career criminal who George Clooney plays as charming and
smart but not very practical, and Sisco, who Jennifer Lopez plays
as a dedicated officer, one who figures you should never let a good
man get away, even if you plan to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who has just escaped from prison in Florida, is America's
busiest bank robber. He has knocked over hundreds of banks, all
without a gun.
</P>
<P>
   We get to watch one of Foley's bank jobs. He strolls to the
teller's window and tells her to look over at the manager's desk.
The guy sitting with the manager, Foley tells her, is his partner,
and he is holding a gun and will shoot the manager if she does not
fork over some cash.
</P>
<P>
   It's not true _ Foley doesn't even know the guy. But he is so
confident and charming that she believes him and pays up.
</P>
<P>
   Jersey Films, which brought Leonard's ``Get Shorty'' to the
screen, has put together this movie, again using the services of
screenwriter Scott Frank. Frank has wisely played up the most
interesting part of the book, the relationship between male robber
and female marshal. He's also kept the humor and smart dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Frank has not succumbed to the temptation of
turning this into an overblown action movie, even though there are
several action scenes and a climactic heist.
</P>
<P>
   In the same vein, Steven Soderbergh (``sex, lies and
videotape,'' ``King of the Hill'') was brought in to direct. You
don't hire someone of Soderbergh's subtle touch with characters and
dialogue when you're trying to sell explosions and car chases. It
turned out to be a splendid choice. Soderbergh thrives on nuance
and conversation, and his actors and the audience profit.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Get Shorty'' emphasized comedy and ``Jackie Brown'' (the
movie adaptation of Leonard's ``Rum Punch'') emphasized character
quirks, dialogue and violence, this movie is a mellower blend. The
result is entertaining, at once sexy, funny, quirky and romantic,
with dashes of excitement from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get the idea this is a romantic comedy to take the kids
to. The movie does have violence, some played as dark humor. Crime
language and nasty types abound.
</P>
<P>
   While Foley is trying to figure a way to get together with Sisco
again without having her haul him to jail, he teams with an old
partner, Buddy, played in the best trusty-pal style by Ving Rhames.
Buddy is determined to keep Foley out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   They reluctantly get into a heist plan orchestrated by a former
prison mate, hilariously played by Steve Zahn. Zahn (``The Object
of My Affection'') just might get an Oscar nomination out of this
role. He's delightfully pathetic as an amoral, dumb druggie and
steals every scene he's in.
</P>
<P>
   Also involved: Don Cheadle (``Devil in a Blue Dress''), scary as
a low-life violent criminal named Snoopy; Dennis Farina as Sisco's
dad, a former cop who makes wisecracks about his daughter's
infatuation with a bank robber; and Albert Brooks as the
millionaire who talked too much about his hidden diamonds when he
was in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In an uncredited inside joke, Michael Keaton shows up as Sisco's
boyfriend Ray Nicolet, the same law officer Keaton played in
``Jackie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   The core of the movie depends on Clooney and Lopez, however, and
they make an unusual but fun romantic team.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney's personal likability really shows up on screen, and
it's a good thing, since we have to like his outlaw character or
the movie doesn't work. His Jack Foley is an easygoing guy, the
kind who can't help waving when he sees someone he knows, even if
she is trying to arrest him.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez (``Selena'') gives Sisco enough of an edge so that we can
believe that, just maybe, she could look beyond Foley's bad habit
of robbing banks and find him charming. But she's still a good
officer and not likely to let him go free.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is light as a feather fluff. Just what Leonard fans
would hope for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' is rated R for language and some strong
violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
