<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-HARASS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULINGS FAVOR VICTIMS OF SEXUAL HARASSMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a victory for sexual harassment victims, the
Supreme Court ruled Friday that employers are liable for
supervisors who fire, demote or reassign a subordinate for spurning
unwelcome sexual advances, even if the companies were unaware of
the misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of 7-2 rulings, the justices also said employers are
presumed liable for harassment by supervisors even when the
misconduct does not result in the victim's dismissal, demotion or
reassignment.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can avoid liability if they prove they acted quickly
to prevent the harassment and that the victim failed to take
advantage of the employers' procedures for reporting the workplace
harm, the court added.
</P>
<P>
   A women's rights group hailed the broad interpretation of Title
VII of the 1964 Civil Rights Act as a ``great day for working
women.'' Martha Davis of the NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund,
added, ``The decisions affirm that the purpose of Title VII is to
prevent harm ... and that employers are in the best position to do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A leading business group said the high court made clear that
employers and employees both play roles in preventing harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The employer is responsible for setting guidelines, and the
employee is responsible for following them,'' said Stephen Bokat,
the U.S. Chamber of Commerce's general counsel. ``That's a position
the chamber has held for a long time, and finally the Supreme Court
has recognized that employees have certain obligations, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court, over the objection of two of its most
conservative members, said companies have a heavy legal burden in
harassment cases because they hired the supervisors and gave them
authority over other employees. Having bestowed the authority, the
companies cannot claim ignorance of what their supervisors are
doing, the court said on the last day of its 1997-1998 term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recognition of employer liability when discriminatory misuse
of supervisory authority alters the terms and conditions of a
victim's employment is underscored by the fact that the employer
has a greater opportunity to guard against misconduct by
supervisors than by common workers; employers have greater
opportunity and incentive to screen them, train them and monitor
their performance,'' Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court in
Faragher vs. Boca Raton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the high court held the city liable for the
unwelcome touching and lewd comments that Beth Ann Faragher endured
from supervisors Bill Terry and David Silverman while working as a
lifeguard at a Boca Raton beach. The city has no defense to the
harassment claim because it took no action to keep track of its
supervisory lifeguards and failed to disseminate its policy
prohibiting harassment to its beach staff, the court said.
</P>
<P>
   In the other case, the justices said a company could be held
liable for a supervisor who allegedly harassed _ but nevertheless
promoted _ a female subordinate who rejected his unwelcome
advances. In sending the case back for trial, the justices said
Kimberly Ellerth would first have to show she was harassed by her
supervisor, Ted Slowik.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Industries Inc. could then avoid liability by showing
it ``exercised reasonable care to prevent and correct promptly any
sexually harassing behavior,'' the court said. The company also
would have to show that Ellerth ``unreasonably failed to take
advantage of any preventive or corrective opportunities provided by
the employer or to avoid harm otherwise,'' the justices added.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for the majority in the
Ellerth case, said a corporate policy prohibiting harassment is not
necessary for defending against a lawsuit, but it can help the
company show the victim had a way to stop the harassment short of
litigation. However, even the strongest anti-harassment policy will
not save a company from liability if a supervisor's shenanigans led
to a ``tangible'' employment action, such as the victim's
dismissal, discharge or undesirable reassignment, Kennedy added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tangible employment actions are the means by which the
supervisor brings the official power of the enterprise (company) to
bear on subordinates,'' Kennedy wrote. ``In that instance, it would
be implausible to interpret (legal) principles to allow an employer
to escape liability.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the ruling in the Ellerth case indicates liability for
harassment is possible even without tangible employment action such
as demotion or firing, the case may make it easier for Paula Jones
to revive her lawsuit against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jones accused Clinton of propositioning her when he was Arkansas
governor and she was a state employee. A federal judge threw out
the lawsuit, ruling that employees can collect damages only if
their refusal to submit to sexual demands results in retaliation on
the job. The judge ruled Jones could show no adverse employment
consequences from spurning Clinton's alleged advance.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the high court's ruling for Jones' case could be
limited because the judge who dismissed her lawsuit said she did
not show that Clinton ever made a clear threat of retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia dissented in both
cases decided by the high court. Thomas, joined by Scalia, said a
company should not be held liable unless the harassing supervisor
fired, demoted or reassigned the victim or the company negligently
permitted the misconduct to occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is, liability should attach only if the employer either
knew, or in the exercise of reasonable care should have known,
about the hostile work environment and failed to take remedial
action,'' Thomas wrote. ``Harassment is simply not something that
employers can wholly prevent without taking extraordinary measures
_ constant video and audio surveillance for example _ that would
revolutionize the workplace in a manner incompatible with a free
society.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
