<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9258 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-HATREDS-BOS &LR;      06-26 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-HATREDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON CULTURE SEEN SPAWNING RACIST VIOLENCE AMONG YOUTHFUL POOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TENNESSEE COLONY, Texas _ Tensions are rising with the
temperature, which has just hit 100 degrees, in the gritty
penitentiary where two white supremacists accused of James Byrd
Jr.'s brutal slaying were schooled in racial hatred.
</P>
<P>
   On a sweltering cellblock where John William King and Lawrence
Russell Brewer were caught two years ago with drawings of swastikas
and tattoo stencils for symbols of the Ku Klux Klan, groups of
black, white and Hispanic inmates linger in a crowded day room.
They are separated by steel benches and self-imposed segregation.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a corrections officer totes a ``gas gun'' to unleash
chemical agents if violence erupts.
</P>
<P>
   This is the George Beto Unit of the Texas corrections system, a
sprawling, steel-roofed prison ringed with glistening razor wire
and occupied by 3,264 felons in an unforgiving world of fear and
enmity. The population is ruled largely by separatist gangs prone
to violence, notably the Aryan Brotherhood, the Mexican Mafia and
the Crips.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their racial feelings were before they entered the
unit, King, 23, and Brewer, 31, left as converts to its distorted
values. They had yet to reach their first anniversary away from
Beto when they were charged with killing Byrd, a 49-year-old
disabled grandfather, by chaining him to the back of a pickup truck
on June 7 and dragging him nearly three miles on a country road in
Jasper, Texas, tearing his body apart.
</P>
<P>
   A third suspect, Shawn Allen Berry, 23, told police that King,
the alleged ringleader, ranted racist-laced vulgarities throughout
the atrocity.
</P>
<P>
   As the FBI, state and local authorities braced Friday for a Ku
Klux Klan rally Saturday in Jasper that black militant groups have
vowed to attend, specialists in prison hate groups offered an
answer to the painful question King's father, Ronald, reportedly
asked his son before the killing: ``Where did the hatred in your
heart come from?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer, the specialists said, may rest in the prison culture
that feeds on young, poorly-educated inmates vulnerable to racist
ideology. When King and Brewer were paroled last year from the Beto
Unit, they bore little resemblance to the petty criminals whose
drug and property crimes had landed them behind bars, friends and
relatives said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prisons are really graduate schools of hate,'' said Brian
Levin, director of the Center on Hate and Extremism at Richard
Stockton College in New Jersey. ``Even people who are not hard-core
hatemongers when they go in can get caught in the web of hatred and
be stuck in it when they come out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beto Unit's senior warden, Herbert L. Scott, said many
inmates join gangs as a form of self-defense _ ``to make their
lives more comfortable,'' as Scott put it. But Scott said King and
Brewer have no one to blame but themselves for their actions beyond
the prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had an opportunity to go out there and do good,'' he
said. ``They are the ones who made a choice to do what they are
alleged to have done, not the gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who served 25 months of an 8-year sentence for burglary,
``was a real quiet kid, always very sweet'' when he was growing up
in Jasper, said Deanna Job, who described herself as a distant
cousin and former classmate of King. ``He always went with us to
church.''
</P>
<P>
   But King, it seemed, changed in prison. ``I barely recognized
him when he came out,'' she said. ``He was much bigger and had a
lots of tattoos, and none of them said, `Mom.'''
</P>
<P>
   At Beto, King hooked up with Brewer, who was serving six years
of a 22-year sentence for burglary and drug possession. The pair
served two years together in a towering, three-tier cellblock with
nearly 400 other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Beto Unit, home to every category of felon from embezzler to
serial killer, is situated on a remote country road 150 miles
northwest of Jasper, a city of 8,000 near the Texas border with
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,700 inmates confined this week in the general
population, 48 percent were black, 31 percent, white, and 20
percent, Hispanic. Rarely do they mingle across racial or ethnic
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Beto, like most prisons, ``has a large problem with gangs,''
said Captain Robert Emerson, as he led a visitor through cellblocks
teeming with inmates clad in sweat-soaked white clothing. ``A lot
of the guys here succumb to the pressure to join the gangs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer and King, who were monitored in prison for possible
affiliation with the KKK and an affiliated group, the Confederate
Knights of America, bore tattoos associated with both organizations
when they were arrested a day after Byrd's mutilated body was
found.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials said Brewer was disciplined in 1995 for joining
other whites in ``a rumble'' with Hispanic inmates. And relatives
said King had increasingly expressed racist ideology, even after he
was paroled last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went in a street punk and came out a white supremacist,''
said John R. Craig, who is familiar with King's family and is
co-author of ``Soldiers of God,'' a recently published book on
white supremacy. ``It was a complete metamorphosis.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry, who was sharing a small apartment in Jasper with King and
Brewer at the time of Byrd's murder, was the only member of the
group who bad never experienced the pressures of a lengthy prison
term. Berry and King were arrested together for burglary in 1991
and ordered to a 90-day boot camp for youthful offenders, which
both successfully completed in lieu of 10-year prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But only Berry met the terms of his parole. In 1995, King was
charged with technical parole violations and and sent to Beto, for
his first, harsh taste of prison life.
</P>
<P>
   In prison, authorities said, most inmates join gangs or looser
affiliations for fear of being beaten, raped or killed. Or, as
Brewer's lawyer, Bill Morian Jr., has said, they join gangs to
avoid becoming another inmate's ``wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Protection, however, often comes with an enforced ideology.
Before leaving Beto, King had switched his religious affiliation
from Baptist to Odinism, an ancient Nordic doctrine based on white
superiority. And Brewer, who reported no religious affiliation when
he entered Beto, joined Christian Identity, a movement whose
leaders also preach neo-Nazi beliefs about white supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in their lives, guys like them are told
they are special by the prison preachers,'' Craig said, referring
to self-appointed inmate proselytizers. ``They are told, 'You are
an Aryan, God has chosen you. We need to take the country back.'
And they become consumed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   When King and Brewer returned to Jasper, a struggling timber
town, vestiges of racism lingered nearly 30 years after racial
segregation ended in the county schoools. Although the mayor and
several other civic leaders were black, a KKK chapter purportedly
has operated in the county since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   That year, white supremacists burned crosses throughout the city
of Kountze, south of Jasper, after three black men, including a
Jasper teen-ager, were charged with raping two white girls.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the KKK threatened violence in nearby Vidor after a
federal judge ordered the city's all-white housing developments to
be racially integrated.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time King and Brewer had returned to Jasper, Craig
said, a white militia group was operating a 200-acre training
ground in the county. In addition, a Christian Identity faction had
taken over a small, independent church in the county, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said King and Brewer attacked Byrd out of anger that
Berry offered Byrd a ride late at night as he was walking on Martin
Luther King Drive near his childhood home in Jasper. At the height
of the horror that followed, police said, Berry asked King to let
him out of the truck as it pulled Byrd through a remote, nearly
all-black neighborhood. But King refused, as the truck churned past
the Rosebloom Bapist Church and approached a cemetery gate, where
the assailants unchained the remainder of Byrd's body.
</P>
<P>
   Police said there was no room for Berry's unease in King's code
of racial hatred. ``You're just as guilty as we are,'' a police
affidavit quoted King as telling Berry. ``Besides, the same thing
could happen to a n----- lover.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
