<HEADER>
A9265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-MERGE-560&AMP;ADD-N     06-26 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MERGE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 JAPANESE BANKS IN TALKS ABOUT MERGING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also JAPAN-BANKS) 
(mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Long-Term Credit Bank, one of Japan's biggest and
weakest financial institutions, is in negotiations to merge with a
smaller, stronger rival, a move that could turn the combined bank
into a showcase for the government's first blueprint to clean up
the nation's bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   If Long-Term's talks with Sumitomo Trust &AMP; Banking Co. succeed,
it would create a bank with $316 billion in assets, slightly behind
Chase Manhattan Corp., the biggest bank in the United States with
$364.7 billion in assets. It could also end several weeks of
worries that financial troubles at Long-Term could spread and
endanger financial stability in Japan, which already is suffering
from its worst postwar economic performance, a weakening currency
and a jittery stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese news media reported Friday that a deal was possible,
and both banks confirmed later in separate news conferences that
they were in talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a bit of a crisis of confidence in the financial
system, and confidence needs to be restored,'' said James Fiorillo,
a financial analyst at ING Barings. ``Investors have demanded
action and they're getting it.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal would effectively mean that Sumitomo Trust, with $118
billion in assets, would absorb Long-Term, the nation's
10th-largest financial institution, with $198 billion in assets.
Though trading was halted in the stocks of the two companies after
word of the talks surfaced, Long-Term shares rose nearly 26
percent. Sumitomo shares fell 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Koichi Kato, secretary general of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, welcomed the talks, though he denied reports that
party leaders had helped broker them. Nonetheless, a deal would
offer a timely opportunity for the government to put into practice
a blueprint it calls the Total Plan, aimed at tackling the nation's
$600 billion in bad debt held by banks, considered an underlying
cause of Japan's economic malaise.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that plan, Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto Friday
called for the establishment of a ``bridge bank'' to assume the
loans and clients of a failed institution. It would operate like
Resolution Trust Corp., set up by Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
under a 1987 law aimed at resolving the savings and loan crisis in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between Sumitomo Trust and Long-Term is by no means
certain. The talks already have raised questions about the role of
Swiss Banking Corp., which just began joint ventures with Long-Term
in asset management and securities.
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo Trust officials, who said they were approached by
Long-Term about a merger, suggested Friday night that Sumitomo
itself was interested in becoming a ``global player.''
</P>
<P>
   Sumitomo is one of Japan's largest trust banks, which specialize
in managing funds for large institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term is one of three Japanese credit banks established at
the end of World War II to provide long-term business loans in an
effort to rebuild Japan's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers and analysts say Long-Term had been encountering
increasing difficulty securing funds in the interbank loan market,
a critical source of financing for all banks. On Friday the bank
said it met routine repayments on five-year and one-year debt
securities, worth roughly about $2.8 billion. Long-Term's
president, Katsunobu Ohnogi, insisted that the bank was ``not
insolvent.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But analysts say that some foreign financial institutions,
concerned about Long-Term's health, were not eager to continue
purchasing the bank's debt securities. Moreover, such concerns make
the bank highly vulnerable to any sudden shocks, so that it needs
to conclude a rescue deal quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the deal would depend partly on the degree of
public funds Sumitomo could get from the government in exchange for
absorbing Long-Term, which has about $10.4 billion in bad loans.
Sumitomo said Friday that it had no plans to take over that bad
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Atsushi Takahashi, president of Sumitomo, said he had received
assurances from the governor of the Bank of Japan, the nation's
central bank, and from the commissioner of the Financial
Supervisory Agency, that Sumitomo would receive full support if it
absorbed Long-Term.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't set a deadline for the merger,'' Takahashi said at a
news conference. ``I think the merger would be better if it comes
earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there has been concern that Long-Term may be burdened
by problems with its affiliate leasing and financing companies,
which bankers say have billions of dollars worth of outstanding
loans _ many of them property-related.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers say one reason for Sumitomo's decision to negotiate with
Long-Term may have been that it, too, has large amounts of
outstanding loans to affiliate companies of Long-Term. So, by
rescuing Long-Term, Sumitomo may be seeking to avoid greater
troubles of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Takahashi made it clear that if the talks
succeeded, Sumitomo would be running the new operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts worried that the proposed takeover was a reversion
to the old-style of arranged unions. Others suggested that if the
government created a bridge bank that took over Long-Term's bad
loans, and if Sumitomo received public money to help it manage the
expanded institution, then Long-Term's shareholders might lose out
and the value of their shares could plummet.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the United States, where investors generally like
to own stocks in companies that are rescued, in Japan the opposite
could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is decided that LTCB shareholders lose everything, then
immediately, the market will divide the Japanese banks into the
predators and the prey,'' said Brian Waterhouse, financial analyst
at HSBC Securities Japan Ltd. ``And the prey, you don't want to
own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
