<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-WATCH-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING ALL THE EGGS IN ONE BASKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ AT&AMP;T's planned $31.8 billion merger with
Tele-Communications Inc. threw the spotlight last week on a bit of
Wall Street arcana, the so-called tracking stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger happens, AT&AMP;T will float a new tracking stock that
will reflect the fortunes of its consumer services division, a mix
of long-distance, wireless, cable and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   Should investors rush to buy AT&AMP;T's new stock when it is issued?
Should current AT&AMP;T shareholders hang on to the tracking stock they
will receive in the merger?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily, in either case. Because of their structure,
tracking stocks are great for the corporations issuing them. For
investors, they pose more risks.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of tracking shares have neither voting rights nor
ownership in the specific corporate assets whose performance the
stocks reflect. All a tracking stock gives investors is a way to
bet on one aspect of a diversified company's operations.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate issuers are hands-down winners in tracking stocks.
Because the stocks focus investor attention on a particular piece
of a company, they are usually issued with the hope that they will
receive a higher market valuation than the parent company receives
from investors confused by its jumble of properties. This means
more money to the company bringing the tracking stock public.
</P>
<P>
   Companies usually issue tracking shares on a hot piece of their
business. Sprint, for example, recently announced plans to issue a
stock to track its wireless telecommunications business, known as
PCS Sprint is new to this business, but rivals' stocks trade at
enviable price-to-earnings multiples.
</P>
<P>
   Airtouch Communications, for example, trades at 60 times its
latest 12 months' earnings. Sprint's overall multiple is 35.
</P>
<P>
   David Eidelman, a money manager at Eidelman, Finger &AMP; Harris in
St. Louis, has never owned tracking shares for his clients. ``I
wasn't exactly sure what I was getting in a tracking stock,'' he
said. ``And I always wondered if the parent company can monkey with
them.'' To fetch a high price on a tracking stock it planned to
issue, Eidelman said, a company could tweak profits at the related
subsidiary before the offering. Earnings subsequently could fall,
disappointing investors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, because tracking stocks are often issued by a company to
capitalize on a business that is strong at the moment, many of the
newer ones are now trading below their offering prices. The
electronics retailer Circuit City Stores issued tracking shares on
its used-car operation, Carmax, on Feb. 7, 1997, at $20 each.
</P>
<P>
   The stock hit $21 four days later but fell to $6.50 in January.
On Friday, Carmax shares closed at $8.5625. An investor in the
parent company would have had a 40 percent gain for the period.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples include the Genzyme Corp.'s tissue-repair
subsidiary, a developer of products for cartilage and burn damage,
which issued a tracking stock last November at $7.75 a share. It
rose to $9.125 in March but traded at $5.75 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia-Pacific issued a tracking stock on its timber operations
last December, which began trading at $28.25. It is now at $23.
</P>
<P>
   Not all tracking stocks go down, of course. TCI has two, Liberty
Media Group and TCI Ventures, that are up 68 percent and 40
percent, respectively, this year. But investors in tracking stocks
are making a very narrow bet on a company. If proved wrong, they
will have none of a company's diversified activities to cushion a
fall. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1902EDT &QL; 
