<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DISSIDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID SLOW PROGRESS, CONCERN FOR HUMAN RIGHTS IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Nine years have passed since Chinese troops rolled
down the Avenue of Eternal Peace to Tiananmen Square, killing
hundreds or perhaps more than 1,000 peaceful pro-reform
demonstrators, and much has changed in China. Yet the government
has never admitted any wrongdoing for June 4, 1989, and Dai Qing
still cannot hold back a stream of tears when she tries to talk
about it.
</P>
<P>
   A writer who supported the student protestors and was detained
for 10 months without being charged following the crackdown, Dai,
lives under intermittent surveillance, is not allowed to hold a job
and cannot publish her writings in China. It is a fate similar to
that endured by countless others whom the government considers a
threat to the state.
</P>
<P>
   And yet outside the high-profile human rights fight erupting
during President Clinton's visit, Dai and many other government
critics say that human rights are far better in China than at any
time in the history of the communist state. There are fewer
restrictions on where people can live and work, on who they can
marry and what property they can own. Surveillance is spottier and
punishments lighter. Efforts are under &UR;  &LR; way to revise the law and
make the government more accountable. Perhaps most significantly,
people are beginning to develop an awareness of individual rights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite the progress, China has a poor human rights
record by Western standards. This is still a one-party state that
prohibits direct challenges to its authority. Democracy campaigners
are routinely harassed, detained without charges or jailed after
summary trials. Religious expression outside state-approved venues
is severely restricted. Forced prison labor and trafficking in
convicts' organs has been documented.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is damning fodder for critics of President Clinton's
policy of engaging China, who say he has subjugated the human
rights of 1.2 billion Chinese citizens to business interests of
Americans eager to enter the Chinese market. But defenders _
including many prominent Chinese dissidents _ say that while they
aren't thrilled to see Clinton receiving a military welcome
Saturday in a square that was the scene of bloodshed, maintaining
close ties with Beijing is the best way for the US to promote human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students withdrew from the Square and tanks followed and
killed them, and our regime hasn't punished those soldiers or
officials,'' Dai said, choking on sobs. But after taking a deep
breath, she added: ``Yet worse things have happened in China, but
only this is known by the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Human rights is not just political prisoners. It is ordinary
people changing their living standard bit by bit. This is the most
important thing, along with using the law to defend them and
building their independent spirit,'' she said. ``Business links
with China keep the door open so the whole situation will change,
including human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been a quarter-century since President Richard M. Nixon
made his first overtures to a far more hermetic and repressive
China, and several years since Clinton began to melt the
post-Tiananmen freeze and approach Beijing's leaders as partners
rather than pariahs. So how far have human rights progressed since
then?
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International's 1998 annual report,
hundreds or possibly thousands of suspected opponents of the regime
were detained last year, while thousands of political prisoners
remained behind bars _ often as a result of unfair trials. Torture
and ill-treatment were widespread, Amnesty said. And minorities
considered threats to national unity _ Tibetan Buddhists, Xinjiang
Muslims, Roman Catholics who recognize the Pope and Protestants
belonging to unofficial churches _ were persecuted. Protests by
laid-off workers and people displaced by forced relocations were
halted.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, when China is in an international media spotlight,
government critics have been detained or sent out of their
hometowns to prevent them from encountering or disrupting President
Clinton's state visit.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, any repeat visitor to China can see that the lives of
the common people who far outnumber activists and persecuted
minorities seems to be steadily improving. Most advances are
economic ones, but they have allowed freedoms of choice that in
themselves represent expanded rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole society is getting richer bit by bit, and with that
comes more stable education, a middle class, independent voices and
a more independent press,'' said Dai. ``Eventually independent
parties will emerge.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu Yonghai, 37, is a psychologist and member of an underground
Christian church who was kept in solitary confinement from 1995 to
1997 after signing a letter calling for reforms. He is still
watched and his Bible study groups are sometimes stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``But remember: Twenty years ago, I could have been sentenced to
death; 10 years ago, maybe (sentenced) for many, many years. Now
they just watch me,'' he said, gesturing to a small brick
watchhouse security forces built outside his home. ``I agree that
Clinton should engage China, because if he isolates us, our
democratic process will stop. If they engage us, we can learn from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Xu Wenli, 54, a leading figure in the 1978-79 Democracy Wall
movement who was sentenced to prison in 1981 and released 12 years
later only when China was applying to host the Olympic Games, said
outsiders miss the point when they think of human rights mainly in
terms of dissidents like himself.
</P>
<P>
   True, he lives under constant surveillance, has had his computer
and notes seized, and twice this year, has been detained for a few
days. This week, he was prevented from leaving his home for an
interview with the Globe and had to speak to a reporter by
telephone. But he sees limits on his freedoms as far less important
than the expansion of common people's awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more about changing society's sense of human rights.
Over the last 20 years, people are waking up gradually,'' he said.
``Awareness of rights has improved a lot, even in simple ways.
Today, at the supermarket, if a guard wants to search someone's
pocket, the person would probably feel humiliated and fight him.
Before, they would have thought it was normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can help promote that grassroots sentiment only if he
presses leaders and demands they implement the reforms that they
are touting _ such as signing UN charters on rights and overhauling
the legal system, Xu said. Last year, China abolished the crime of
``counterrevolution,'' yet it has not reviewed the cases of some
2,000 imprisoned under that charge.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Munro of the human rights group Asia Watch complained that
China has failed to abide not only by international norms, but by
its own laws. ``If the PRC were to observe its own Constitution,
that would do more for human rights than the signing of any new
document. The Constitution guarantees freedom of speech and freedom
of assembly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, says Dai, as much as the Party cracks down out of
fear, human rights abuses undermine rather than strengthen its
authority.
</P>
<P>
   She tells of a young man she met who was almost mowed down by a
tank in Tiananmen Square, just as the central post office clock
struck 6 a.m. and began to play the classic Communist Party song,
``The Sun Rises in the East.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had loved this country and the Party, but that morning when
he heard that song as the People's Army turned against him, all his
love disappeared,'' recounted Dai, who publicly renounced her Party
membership after the massacre. ``And so who lost? The Communist
Party killed hundreds of people. But the Party is the loser.
Because today, people only love money, they are empty inside. Who
loves the Party?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
