<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9272 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-DIAMONDS-BOS &LR;      06-26 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DIAMONDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAUTIONARY TALE OF CHICANERY IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Not long ago, Andrei Kozlenok was a poster boy for the
Russian new rich, a brash young magnate with powerful Kremlin
friends, a lucrative gem-processing business in the United States
and a talent for spending huge sums on luxuries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kozlenok, 38, has become a symbol of the darker side of
post-Communist Russia's early years, when senior government
officials are believed to have routinely signed off on deals that
bilked the state out of hundreds of millions of dollars
</P>
<P>
   None of these scams has ever been brought to light, and no
minister has ever been brought to trial for corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Kozlenok (pronounced Kaz-len-OAK) has been charged with
swindling the Russian government out of $180 million worth of gold
and diamonds. As he awaits his fate in Moscow's notorious Sailor's
Tranquility prison, Kozlenok claims that what he knows could bring
down some of Russia's leading politicians.
</P>
<P>
   And therefore, Kozlenok says, his own life is in danger _ a
claim that gained credibility after his business partner, Sergei
Dovbysh, mysteriously died in police custody in February.
</P>
<P>
   As Western countries consider a new $10 billion-$15 billion loan
to save Russia from its latest financial crisis, Kozlenok's story
should serve as a cautionary tale of what can happen to state funds
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The sums involved in Kozlenok's case are relatively minor
compared to the billions in illegal earnings, unreported income and
misappropriated funds that have been spirited out of Russia since
1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Kozlenok's case is one of the most blatant examples of how
close connections to President Boris Yeltsin's government could
produce a fortune in the years of chaos, corruption and conspicuous
consumption that followed the Soviet collapse.
</P>
<P>
   It all began in 1992, when Kozlenok allegedly became acquainted
with Yevgeny Bychkov, who was head of the state committee in charge
of selling precious metals and gems from Russian mines.
</P>
<P>
   A company called Golden Ada was established in California, with
Kozlenok as the majority stockholder. The idea, according to
details of the case published in the Russian press, was for Russia
to export diamonds directly to the West, circumventing the
stranglehold held over Russian sales by De Beers, the South African
monopoly that controls the sale of diamonds worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Golden Ada begin receiving shipments of gems and gold.
In one case, $90 million in polished diamonds and tsarist coin
replicas were delivered to the company's San Francisco office. In
another, government officials signed a contract under which Golden
ADA was to process $88 million in rough diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   At least four ministers were allegedly involved, including
former Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who plans to run for
president in 2000, and former Finance Minister Boris Fyodorov, whom
Yeltsin recently named Russia's chief tax inspector.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning the proceeds to the Russian government,
Kozlenok and his associates went on a buying spree: a San Francisco
office building, two Tiara yachts, a Gulfstream jet, a helicopter,
luxury cars and five Lake Tahoe condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlenok has maintained in interviews with the Russian press
that these purchases were necessary to project a ``solid financial
image.'' He has said that the terms of his deal with the Russian
government gave him until next year to return the money he owes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities beg to differ. In 1996, when the Russian
government sensed something was wrong and sued to take over Golden
Ada's assets, only $50 million of the goods and money remained.
Kozlenok fled to Belgium, which has no extradition treaty with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   But when Kozlenok recently went to Greece, he was arrested by
Greek authorities at Moscow's request. Last week, Greek officials
turned down his appeal and extradited him to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlenok says he was set up, and fears that he will be killed to
be kept from talking. Taking no chances, authorities provided
heavily-armed special forces troops and snipers to guard Kozlenok
at his arrival in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am being charged with something that I have basically never
done,'' he said in a recent interview in Izvestiya. Prosecutors
aren't buying. Last week, Ruslan Tumayev, the lead investigator of
the case, charged Kozlenok with fraud, illegal arms possesion,
forgery and violations of hard currency rules.
</P>
<P>
   But Valery Zhitov of the Russian Interior Ministry's Department
of Economic Crimes, said ``It is unlikely that Kozlenok was an
orphan acting alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is how far the scandal will go. Bychkov was
fired in 1995 and charged with abusing his position, but was later
pardoned.
</P>
<P>
   Both Chernomyrdin and Fyodorov appear in documents approving the
deals, authorities say. Both men deny wrongdoing, but Fyodorov has
been questioned and Chernomyrdin may soon be asked to give
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Kozlenok announced through his lawyer that he did not
plan to call any high-ranking officials as witnesses. Asked if
Kozlenok had made the statement to protect his own life, the
lawyer, Georgy Zuzulya, told NTV television: ``My client also asked
me to say that he has no intention of committing suicide, under any
circumstances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
