<HEADLINE>
JONES' LAWYERS SAY HIGH COURT RULING WILL AID THEIR APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Paula Jones' lawyers said Friday that the Supreme
Court's decision in favor of a Chicago businesswoman would help
them in their appeal to have Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment suit
against President Clinton reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're obviously very pleased,'' said Mrs. Jones' main lawyer,
Donovan Campbell of Dallas. His co-counsel, John Whitehead,
president of the Rutherford Institute, which is paying Mrs. Jones'
legal expenses, said the Supreme Court ruling improved the chances
that the Jones lawsuit would go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's lawyer, Robert Bennett, disagreed. The facts
in the case decided Friday ``are clearly distinguishable from the
Jones case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a federal judge dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit. Her
lawyers obtained an extension of time in which to file their appeal
so they could see how the Supreme Court decided the businesswoman's
suit.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled Friday that the woman, Kimberley Ellerth, could
claim sexual harassment after she was subjected to advances by a
superior, even though she had suffered no adverse consequences in
her job for rejecting him.
</P>
<P>
   One reason U.S. District Court Judge Susan Webber Wright
dismissed the suit against the president was that in her view Mrs.
Jones had failed to show any tangible detriment in her job.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones maintained that in 1991, when Clinton was governor of
Arkansas and she was a state employee, he called her to his hotel
room in Little Rock, where she rebuffed a crude sexual proposition.
Clinton has denied the assertion.
</P>
<P>
   In her case, Ms. Ellerth sued Burlington Industries, charging
that a vice president for whom she worked made frequent comments
about her legs, said he could make life at the office miserable for
her, asked her to have sex with him and said that he was reluctant
to promote her because she would not comply. She was promoted
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wright was aware of the Burlington case when she dismissed
the Jones suit and said that it was not relevant because Ms.
Ellerth had been threatened and Mrs. Jones had not.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he would file an appeal in the Jones case next
month. He said that he was especially heartened because the court
described the advances on Ms. Ellerth as ``boorish and offensive.''
Those are the words Judge Wright used to characterize what Mrs.
Jones claimed Clinton had done.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said that he thought the court might be sending a
signal to the appeals court in the Jones case. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
