<SLUG> BC-COURT-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT'S HARASSMENT RULINGS PUT COMPANIES ON NOTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court Friday put every company in
America on notice by ruling that an employer may be held liable
when a supervisor sexually harasses a worker, even if the
employee's job isn't harmed.
</P>
<P>
   The two 7-2 decisions that dramatically ended the court's term
could make it easier for employees to sue for sexual harassment,
but also provide employers with clear guidance on how to defend
themselves in such suits.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings also could help Paula Jones's appeal of her
sexual-harassment lawsuit against President Clinton. Jones's case
was dismissed April 1, when a federal judge ruled she did not
suffer any adverse consequences in her state job after she rebuffed
an alleged sexual advance from Clinton, then governor of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   John Whitehead of the Rutherford Institute, the conservative
Virginia organization that provided legal assistance to Jones, said
Friday's decision ``greatly enhances the chances'' that an appeals
court would rule in Jones' favor.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Bennett, Clinton's lawyer, said the facts were
radically different in the Jones case, and he predicted the high
court decisions would not ``undercut'' the judge's decision to
throw out her lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the decisions Friday, the Supreme Court ruled against
the city of Boca Raton, Fla., where two Parks Department
supervisors, Bill Terry and David Silverman, sexually harassed Beth
Ann Faragher when she was a city lifeguard. The court said the city
was liable for the supervisors' conduct because it did not take any
steps to prevent the harassment or monitor the conduct of the
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   In the second case, the court ruled in favor of Kimberly Ellerth
of Chicago, a former Burlington Industries saleswoman who quit her
job because a supervisor repeatedly made sexually explicit remarks
to her. The court said Ellerth could sue the company even though
she did not suffer any adverse job consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerth, like Faragher, did not bring a complaint while she
worked for the company and only mentioned the harassment after she
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's rulings should be a wake-up call to employers to take
action to wipe out sexual harassment, and if they do, it will
benefit women and men alike,'' said Marcia D. Greenberger,
president of the National Women's Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions were also welcomed by the US Chamber of Commerce
because it helped clarify the responsibilities for employer and
employee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today the court has set a clear, bright-line standard for
establishing when an employer is or is not responsible for sexual
harassment in the work place,'' said Stephen A. Bokat, general
counsel for the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting from the majority in both cases were Justices
Clarence Thomas, whose Senate confirmation became embroiled in
allegations that he sexually harassed Anita Hill, and Antonin
Scalia.
</P>
<P>
   ``An employer should be liable if, and only if, the plaintiff
proves that the employer was negligent in permitting the
supervisor's conduct to occur,'' Thomas wrote in the Burlington
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``A supervisor's creation of a hostile work environment is
neither within the scope of his employment, nor part of his
apparent authority,'' wrote Thomas. ``Indeed, a hostile work
environment is antithetical to the interest of the employer. In
such circumstances, an employer should be liable only if it has
been negligent.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling in the Boca Raton case found that the city failed to
distribute its sexual-harassment policy to the beach employees and
made no attempt to keep track of the conduct of the supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under such circumstances, we hold as a matter of law that the
city could not be found to have exercised reasonable care to
prevent the supervisors' harassing conduct,'' Justice David Souter
wrote in the majority opinion.
</P>
<P>
   An employer can be liable if it fails to take reasonable steps
to prevent sexual harassment in the work place, Souter said. The
court also found, however, that an employee has the responsibility
to take steps to report and stop the harassment if a complaint
procedure is in place.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Souter in the majority opinions were Justices William
Rehnquist, John Paul Stevens, Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony Kennedy,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, writing the majority opinion in the Burlington case,
set a new two-part test for employers. A company can defend itself
if it shows it took ``reasonable care to prevent and correct
promptly any sexually harassing behavior'' and if the employee
neglected to take advantage of ``any preventive or corrective
opportunities provided by the employer'' such as a complaint
process.
</P>
<P>
   The decisions effectively say that an employee no longer needs
to show a ``quid pro quo'' to sue for sexual harassment. Under the
quid pro quo principle, an employee had to prove that refusing a
sexual advance from a boss cost the worker a raise or promotion or
had other negative consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The court underscored that to sue, the harassment needed to be
``extreme'' and not just a casual teasing comment. In addition, the
court said, a single instance would not necessarily qualify as a
hostile work environment.
</P>
<P>
   The two decisions were handed down four days after the Supreme
Court set a higher standard for sexual harassment in schools. In
Gebser v. Lago Vista, which was decided under a different federal
law, the court ruled that students who have been sexually harassed
must prove that school officials were both ignorant of, and
indifferent to, the harassment for the students to receive money
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Reesman, general counsel of Equal Employment Advisory
Council, an association of 300 large private-sector companies,
called Friday's decisions ``a mixed bag for employers''.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, we are not unhappy with the outcome because it
could have been a lot worse. It is important that the court support
the employer who takes proactive efforts to prevent sexual
harassment, but we are disappointed that the court did not extend
that defense to all cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol M. Merchasin, a lawyer at Day, Berry &AMP; Howard in Boston
who trains managers and supervisors in sexual harassment, said the
court gave companies an opportunity to defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has made it clear that if you are doing the right
thing, those things will be considered,'' she said in a telephone
interview. ``You are going to bear risk for your employees'
supervisors and managers conduct whether you knew what they did or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the standard would have been far more difficult for
emplif the court had not indicated that a company can protect
itself from lawsuits by adopting sexual-harassment policies,
distributing those policies, and monitoring its supervisors'
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The cases are Faragher v. City of Boca Raton, 97-282, and
Burlington Industries v. Ellerth 97-569.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
