<SLUG> BC-EARN-FUTURISTS-$ADV28-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COOL HUNTERS, TOMORROW'S TREND IS THE TROPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
(af) 
 By ROY FURCHGOTT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Ladies Who Lunch at Bergdorf ask Claire Ramsey where
she found that f-a-a-a-a-bulous outfit, she knows that she's on to
a trend, and that she has just earned a few hundred bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ramsey, 30, a New York University graduate student in public
health, works as a cafe hostess at Bergdorf Goodman in Manhattan.
But she is also a ``cool hunter'' _ a person whose taste is so
ahead of the curve that a trend analysis firm pays her a
$200-to-$500 bounty for helping to identify the Next Big Things to
sweep popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many cool hunters are prowling America's malls
and streets, but cool hunting is one of the latest trends in trend
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the late 1960s, marketing research pioneers like
Yankelovich Partners and Roper Starch Worldwide measured opinion by
conducting scientific polls, following up with focus-group
research.
</P>
<P>
   Now firms like Iconoculture, Sputnik, Agent X, Lambesis and
Youth Intelligence, which employs Ms. Ramsey and nine other
part-time cool hunters aged 14 to 30, are incorporating cool
hunting, an anthropological field-study approach to trend spotting.
</P>
<P>
   The hunters prowl inner-city basketball courts, fashionable
nightclubs and houses in the Hamptons, observing the arbiters of
coolness whose tastes may eventually be adopted by the general
populace. (Hey, someone had to be the first to wear a baseball cap
backward.)
</P>
<P>
   These firms report to a corporate Who's Who that includes
Coca-Cola, MTV, General Mills and Wendy's International. The
companies, in turn, use the information to formulate new products
and to devise marketing campaigns that grab the attention of the
crucial youth market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trendsetters are the ones breaking new ground in consumer
product areas, and they give you insights into what will be widely
developed down the road,'' said Janet Taylor, director of college
marketing for Sprint and a client of Youth Intelligence, a firm
based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when Youth Intelligence's analysis suggested
that tattoos would become popular, Sprint wound up luring students
to a calling-card promotion with marketing that included temporary
tattoos. Sprint declined to discuss exact figures for the campaign,
but said it had produced twice as many sign-ups as had been
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wicks, the director of the Sony design center in San
Francisco, said the company had made use of cool-hunter insights
when designing a new Walkman, the Freaq, for young athletic users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It uses special graphics, it uses special materials to hold it
to the body, and the Freaq logo is more prominent than the Sony
logo,'' Wicks said. ``It was using heavy-duty clips, much like
chains you see them wearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cool is the reason people buy things,'' he added. ``A shirt is
a shirt and it fulfills a function, but you buy the one with the
logo you think is cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the qualities of cool are hard to pin down, so are the
criteria for becoming its hunter. The firms say their hunters have
a taste level that is avant-garde, but not so far out that it won't
become mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Rinzler Buckingham, the founder of Youth Intelligence, for
example, saw Ms. Ramsey in a cafe about four years ago wearing
Mhendi _ an intricate Indian henna-based skin decoration _ ahead of
the pack that would soon follow. Ms. Buckingham asked about the
Mhendi, and found Ms. Ramsey articulate about why she liked certain
items and fashions. And that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't just about her taste _ it was that she didn't care
about trends, yet naturally anticipated them,'' Ms. Buckingham
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Ramsey, the job isn't work. She and other hunters file
their reports informally, and not on a regular basis, though if
Youth Intelligence does not hear from a hunter it will call at
least three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   One of Ms. Ramsey's research methods is to be her own laboratory
rat. ``I can't necessarily afford the high-end fashion, so I make
my own things up,'' she said. If a particular item draws comments,
it may make her list.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a knack for spotting up-and-coming fashions on
others. Three years ago, she noticed an elderly woman wearing an
attractive ring. It was a Lalique ring, and Ms. Ramsey ran out and
bought one, reporting this to Youth Intelligence. ``Recently young
people started buying them,'' she said. ``There are all of these
plastic knockoffs of it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though being a cool hunter sounds, well, cool, trend analysis
companies consider the term derisive, applying it only to hired
hands like Ms. Ramsey. Cool hunting, the firms say, doesn't require
sophisticated analysis of why an item is cool, a service that the
research firms provide.
</P>
<P>
   One firm, Sputnik, refused to discuss the topic without a
guarantee that the words ``cool'' and ``hunter'' would not appear
in the article.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a career track for former cool hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Tru Pettigrew, 30, started out surveying schoolyards for cool as
research for Converse, the sneaker company. But now, at Arnold
Communications, an advertising agency in Boston, he is the ``Voice
of the Consumer'' _ a broader job researching youth culture.
Between that position and his publication of Tru Flava, a quarterly
newsletter on youth trends, Pettigrew said he earns $40,000 to
$60,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Pettigrew plies his trade scouring schoolyards and clubs for new
cool _ he says, for instance, that clothes with big logos are old
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are getting away from having a Hilfiger all across the
chest,'' he said. ``They want the smaller logo. They don't want to
look like they are trying too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He also runs informal focus groups, taking products _ and,
sometimes, company executives _ out on the street for a sort of
urban cool safari. Pettigrew has a retinue of teachers and coaches
in Los Angeles, San Francisco, Baltimore, Houston, Chicago and
Boston who put him in contact with teen-agers. Though the young
people are seldom paid cash, they usually receive products, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cool-industry specialties are popping up, too. For instance,
Richard Rushfield and Adam Leff founded Agent X, a cool-hunting
firm in Los Angeles that advises the entertainment industry
exclusively. ``We help them decide what movies to make because they
are working on projects for two and three years down the road,''
Rushfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Rushfield, a former political consultant, and Leff, who wrote
screenplays including ``The Last Action Hero,'' offer their clients
trend tours, showing studio executives what is hot. More often they
lecture, then field questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask, `Will pirates be in?''' Rushfield said. The answer
is no _ witness 1995's epic pirate bomb, ``Cutthroat Island.''
</P>
<P>
   But Agent X gives a thumbs-up to upbeat road pictures and films
embracing ``traditional community values.'' Each genre, in its own
way, is an escape from complex moral choices, Rushfield said; road
movies are ``a subset of the trend toward a desire for fun removed
from a moral context,'' while traditional-value films appeal to
audiences ``looking to go back to simple, basic ways.''
</P>
<P>
   That means that future cinematic good guys are less likely to be
businessmen, who may be seen as morally tainted, than firefighters,
whose image remains largely uncorrupted, Rushfield said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firemen represent simple, straightforward decency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pair work by traveling to big cities around the country,
using their radar to spot cool stuff. They compile much of it into
a one-page chart, called ``Intelligence Report,'' that runs
occasionally in Vanity Fair magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Now at work on a humorous how-to book on spotting trends, the
pair say their firm will bring in $1.2 million next year.
</P>
<P>
   Back in New York, Ms. Ramsey cannot claim such a hefty payday.
Still, she appreciates the money she does get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pennies from heaven,'' she mused. ``I can rely that it's
there, but I can't rely when it's coming.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
