<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9283 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPEND-PHONE-NUMBERS-$     06-26 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-PHONE-NUMBERS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR LONG-DISTANCE DISCOUNTS, MORE NUMBERS TO DIAL  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By DEBRA WEST    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before the actor John Lithgow started urging people to save
on long-distance telephone calls by dialing 10-321, officials at
MCI Communications knew that the easy-to-remember code would soon
be complicated by a couple of extra digits.
</P>
<P>
   Before introducing the service in mid-1996, MCI executives had
to make a choice: they could either promote their ``dial-around''
service with the seven-digit code it would eventually have to
carry, or use a catchier five-digit number for as long as the
Federal Communications Commission allowed, then go through the
expense of re-educating customers when the change inevitably came.
</P>
<P>
   They took the latter path, investing nearly $79 million on the
10-321 ad campaign in 1997 and another $38 million in the first
quarter of this year to establish the service, according to
Competitive Media Reports, which tracks ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were less numbers and it was easier to remember,'' said
Brad Burns, a spokesman for MCI and Telecom USA, the subsidiary
that runs 10-321. ``This product lives on advertising. We wanted to
keep it in the top of the mind. Now, considering 10-321 has such
great brand awareness, we'll just roll it over.''
</P>
<P>
   Judgment day is nigh. As of Wednesday, customers of the service
will have to dial 10-10-321 to gain access to MCI's lines and
discounted long-distance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Though it declined to disclose how much the new campaign was
costing, MCI has been promoting the new number ferociously, with
direct mailings and new TV ads featuring Lithgow. Last Wednesday,
the service went so far as to offer one free 20-minute phone call
to anyone using the new number from 5 p.m. to midnight that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be a little bit of a hiccup,'' Daniel E. Zito, a
telecommunications analyst at Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore,
said of the short-term prospects for the new number. ``It will
require some consumer education. But I think it will still be
successful. It's a very mass-market way to tap into the casual
long-distance user.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of companies now operate dial-around telephone services,
which promise lower long-distance rates in return for dialing the
codes that direct the telephone network to connect the call to a
specific carrier. The size of the discount from dial-around
services is a matter of debate, since they usually compare their
lower rates with the highest nondiscounted residential rates
available.
</P>
<P>
   Many dial-around services will be making the adjustment to seven
digits _ a change intended in part to accommodate the growing
number of carriers. But because the MCI service, the most heavily
marketed, dominates the niche, it faces the most public
re-education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``MCI, by putting all the dollars it has in, has made the whole
category float,'' said Amanda McCarthy, an analyst at the Yankee
Group, a telecommunications research firm in Boston. She said 9.4
percent of American households used a dial-around service in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCarthy estimated that MCI controls more than 50 percent of
the dial-around segment, which had revenues of $1.5 billion in
1997. That figure could grow to $2 billion this year, in large part
because of MCI's push for its new number, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dial-around numbers allow users to gain access to different
phone companies' lines, one call at a time, without making a
commitment to switch their long-distance carrier permanently.
</P>
<P>
   A subscriber to the AT&AMP;T long-distance service, for instance,
could dial 10-321 before making a call to route that call over
MCI's network. Similarly, an MCI customer could dial 10-288 (for
10-ATT) to route a call over AT&AMP;T's system.
</P>
<P>
   Why the change in the number? The first two digits in the code _
1 and 0 _ exist only to inform the telephone system that a
three-digit code identifying the desired carrier is about to
follow. That means that only 1,000 dial-around codes have been
available.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, telecommunications companies have known that the
supply of those three-digit numbers, called carrier identification
codes, would run out eventually. Indeed, the numbers, which are
also used by wireless carriers and large corporate accounts, were
exhausted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives and the FCC debated when to start requiring
the seven-digit numbers, which make about 10,000 codes available
for use. A transition period began in 1995, with carriers having
the option of using their five-digit numbers or switching to seven.
</P>
<P>
   Last October _ a month before MCI expanded 10-321 from 19 test
markets into a national service _ the FCC set July 1 as the
mandatory changeover date. Kris Monteith, a senior lawyer for the
FCC, says the seven-digit rule is intended to give all the
competitors a level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this was coming,'' said Burns of MCI. ``It was a
business decision to wait. We think customers will adjust to the
change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
