<HEADER>
A9284 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-$ADV28-     06-26 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S STANCE ON CHINA SHOWS DRAMATIC SHIFT DURING PAST SIX
YEARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, June 28) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As votes in the U.S. presidential election were
tallied six years ago, hundreds of diplomats and academics crowded
into a hotel ballroom for an American Embassy party to watch Bill
Clinton march to victory and ponder the meaning for U.S.-China
relations.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. envoy recalls being told by a Chinese official, ``My
government knows that pre-election rhetoric may not have much to do
with future policy.''
</P>
<P>
   What a prescient observation. Because on few, if any, major
issues have Clinton's actions in office regarding China been more
divergent from his campaign oratory.
</P>
<P>
   Candidate Clinton's rhetorical brimstone regarding China has
been replaced by President Clinton's policy of friendly
accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's pledges to exact radically different behavior from
Beijing in return for engagement with Washington were dropped
within weeks of his taking office, and any questions about
inconsistency have been brushed aside as unsophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly during the 1992 campaign, Clinton, then the governor
of Arkansas and lacking much foreign policy experience, sought to
show he would stand up to China. Clinton berated President Bush for
continuing to engage the Communist nation in the wake of the
slaughter of hundreds of pro-democracy demonstrators at Tiananmen
Square in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In an Aug. 13, 1992, speech to the Los Angeles World Affairs
Council, Clinton laid out his concern:
</P>
<P>
   ``When China cracked down on pro-democracy demonstrators,
exported advance weapons to radical regimes and suppressed Tibet,
this (Bush) administration and this president failed to stand up
for our values. Instead, he sent secret emissaries to China,
signaling we would do business as usual with those who murdered
freedom in Tiananmen Square.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has not sent secret emissaries, he has come himself, and
was welcomed at an official ceremony Saturday on Tiananmen Square
as part of the first visit of an American head of state since the
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the midst of a nine-day visit to China, where the
government still strictly limits the right of political dissent,
sought as recently as this year to export chemical weapons to Iran
and rides herd on religious expression, including severe strictures
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton contends that China, with its authoritarian view of
human rights, remains ``on the wrong side of history'' but argues
that his ``principled and pragmatic'' plan for engaging the regime
in Beijing makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   That was essentially the same argument advanced by President
Bush in 1992 but denounced by candidate Clinton, who promised in
his speech accepting the Democratic nomination an America ``that
will not coddle tyrants, from Baghdad to Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years have transpired since that statement,'' said
Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger.
``Things have changed in China, I think, to some degree. I think we
are no less assiduous or vigorous in promoting human rights today
than the president's advocacy earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who before joining the Clinton administration had
lobbied as a lawyer against granting China most-favored-nation
trade status, now argues that ``essentially threatening to sever
our economic relationship was no leverage on human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's severest criticism on China comes from
Democrats in Congress, including Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., who
said the president has not only ``flip-flopped'' but also
``reneged'' on campaign promises to get tough with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal campaign manifesto, ``Putting People First,''
spelled out how he would deal commercially with nondemocratic
governments:
</P>
<P>
   ``We will condition favorable trade terms with repressive
regimes _ such as China's communist regime _ on respect for human
rights, political liberalization and responsible international
conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1992 Democratic platform echoed the sentiment, promising
that ``favorable trade terms for China'' depended on ``respect for
human rights in China and Tibet, greater access for U.S. goods and
responsible conduct on weapons proliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than four months after entering the White House, Clinton
proposed an extension of China's MFN status, which was accepted by
Congress. The next year, in 1994, Clinton formally dropped any
linkage between China's human rights record and trade policy.
</P>
<P>
   China has taken full advantage of the commercial ties, and the
U.S. trade deficit with Beijing during Clinton's tenure has
totaled, through fiscal 1997, $175 billion. An estimated $57
billion will be added to that in the fiscal year that ends Sept.
30. The biggest U.S. export to China, according to the Commerce
Department, is airplanes and parts; China's biggest export to the
United States is toys and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The week after Clinton's convention speech, and its denunciation
of the ``tyrants'' in Beijing, Richard Holbrooke was in the Chinese
capital. Holbrooke, long a Democratic foreign policy mandarin, was
then a former assistant secretary of state in the Carter
administration and is now Clinton's nominee to be ambassador to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke told the Los Angeles Times that he was in Beijing on
behalf of Lehman Brothers, the investment banking firm with which
he has been associated when not in government.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said he met with Chinese leaders _ including the still
powerful Zhu Rongji, who is now premier _ but denied as ``totally
false'' allegations of Chinese dissidents that he had told the
officials to discount Clinton's campaign rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he did or not, it would have been sage advice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
