<HEADLINE>
DNC CHIEF WON'T AID BOSTON'S EFFORT TO NET 2000 CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Democratic National Committee chairman and
Massachusetts native Steve Grossman, who has the clout to steer the
Democratic convention to Boston, said Friday he's going to stay
neutral on the choice of a host city and will abide by the
recommendations of the party's site selection committee.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, who was in town Friday for a meeting of the state
party chairmen, said in an interview that the ``door is wide open
for Boston'' and that this week's site visit by the selection
committee ``could not have been more successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he won't intervene to make sure the convention goes
to his home state, as the late Ron Brown did as DNC chair in 1992
when he insisted the event be held in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The credibility of the process is very important to me,''
Grossman said before addressing the gathering of state party
chairs. ``I would find it overwhelmingly difficult to override the
site selection committee ... I have to be objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Both city officials, who have been making a strong pitch to have
the convention at the FleetCenter, and Democratic party observers
said Grossman has to respect the process publicly even if he pushes
for Boston privately. But some say it is genuinely Grossman's style
not to ``wire'' the convention for Boston in any way, in contrast
to Brown, who was outspoken about having the convention in New York
through the entire site selection process in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiddling with the process might run counter to what his tenure
has been about, involving all 50 states'' in party decisions, said
Ernest J. Corrigan, spokesman for the Massachusetts Democratic
State Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman's reluctance to intervene is disappointing news for
city officials, however. The conventional wisdom after this week's
visit to Boston by the site selection committee was that the city
showed it could handle the convention both in terms of logistics
and image.
</P>
<P>
   There was also much talk by committee members that Vice
President Al Gore, at this point the likely presidential nominee in
2000, was genuinely not swayed by arguments that the convention
should be held in Los Angeles or Philadelphia, for their larger
media markets and electoral-vote quarry.
</P>
<P>
   All those factors being relatively equal, Boston boosters had
hoped Grossman could step in and push the city over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Leibowitz, director of the city's intergovernmental
affairs office and a leader in the convention bid, said the
important thing was that Boston established itself as a viable
candidate this week. Site selection committee members gave rave
reviews to the FleetCenter and the job Mayor Thomas M. Menino did
showing off the city _ including soothing concerns about traffic
and construction associated with the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've proven this week that we can host the convention and do
an excellent job with it. Whether we will depends on political
factors, some of which are beyond our control,'' Leibowitz said.
``But let there be no doubt, we can produce a first-rate
convention. Our challenge was to prove that part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And there will be no shortage of homegrown political influence
in the party despite Grossman's vow to stay objective. State party
chair Joan Menard was elected president of the Association of State
Democratic Chairs Friday, and Menard is also on the site selection
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The site selection committee begins its tour of Philadelphia on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
