<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAF OUSTED BY ZVEREVA; DAVENPORT ADVANCES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ROBIN FINN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ Her racquet hand turned limp as a noodle,
her serve had no sting and the forehand she has always depended on
to scare her challengers half silly went totally missing. Although
it was cold and wet enough Friday to make her teeth chatter, panic
had already set in and had the same effect.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf, who has made a career of being an Iron Maiden on
these lawns, was quaking. And across the net, the mercurial Natasha
Zvereva seemed to have morphed Graf's legendary willpower and made
it her own.
</P>
<P>
   This was a double aberration. The fourth-seeded Graf, seven
times a Wimbledon champion and 17 times the victor against Zvereva,
had an attack of stage fright this gloomy Friday and could not
recover. And Zvereva, five times a Wimbledon doubles champion but
never again a Grand Slam singles finalist after Graf's pitiless
6-0, 6-0 annihilation of her in their 1988 French Open finale, kept
her own composure from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-4, 7-5 victory for the 27-year-old Zvereva forwarded the
pigtailed doubles specialist into the Round of 16 and stranded the
29-year-old Graf on the sideline. The German has been able to play
just four tournaments since undergoing career-threatening knee
surgery a year ago, and she had gone through feverish training and
rehabilitation just to get herself fit for her favorite slam. The
early-round setback put her back in a familiar spot: out of
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the 22nd-ranked Zvereva, who replaces Graf as a
potential quarterfinal opponent for sixth-seeded Monica Seles,
second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, Zvereva's occasional doubles
partner, reached the fourth round with a 6-3, 1-6, 6-2 defeat of
Venezuela's Maria Alejandra Vento.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, where the constant interruptions of rain
delayed the completion of the second round until Friday,
sixth-seeded Patrick Rafter, the U.S. Open champion, became the
first man to reach the Round of 16. Rafter, of Australia, advanced
with a 6-3, 6-7 (7-9), 6-2, 6-1 dismissal of Sweden's Magnus
Gustafsson.
</P>
<P>
   And 14th-seeded Goran Ivanisevic of Croatia, like Rafter a
serve-and-volleyer hoping to redeem himself here after a horrible
first half of 1998, finally finished his second-rounder against
Andrei Medvedev with 26 aces and a last set flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play like this, anything is possible, but I have to play
five more rounds at least to do something,'' Ivanisevic said after
his 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 4-6, 6-0 victory. ``You know, it's been my
worst six months ever in my career, but that's passed. The last
time I felt this good was maybe '94 when I played the final here.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Graf felt this paralyzed was last week at
Eastbourne when, struck by a similar onset of anxiety, she was
ousted in the quarterfinals by 17-year-old Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played so little that for some reason I can't find the
confidence playing out there,'' said the red-eyed Graf, who seemed
resigned to her present inconsistency until the future brings more
matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing nervously in the beginning, the return of
serve was terrible, and every time it was important, I didn't play
the points very well at all.'' Graf's conversion rate on her paltry
trio of break opportunities was a thoroughly uncharacteristic zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problem is pretty clear,'' Graf said. ``It's lack of match
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Too, Graf's problem Friday was Zvereva, a sporadically brilliant
shotmaker who chose Friday to play the match of her life. Zvereva
broke Graf with a backhand that skittered off the sideline in the
opening game and held fast to her momentum until Graf's last
mistake, a netted backhand return, validated the upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's by far the best match of my life; I was mentally
tough on every point, and I don't think that ever happened
before,'' said Zvereva, whose coup received special attention not
just from Graf, but from a locker room full of astonished
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva, a confirmed goofball, said her colleagues reacted to
her victory with hilarity and asked her if her unnatural powers of
concentration during the match were an indication that she was ill
or, possibly, lobotomized. ``But I can take some jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   And Graf, rarely a communicative loser, acknowledged Zvereva's
table-turning victory with an actual concession speech when the two
shook hands at the net. ``She said,'' Zvereva reported, `` `By the
way, very nice match,' which coming from her to me right after the
match was very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus she looked me in the eyes,'' said Zvereva who hadn't ever
received such intimate treatment, or such glowing praise, from Graf
since that initial 12-game French Open final 10 years ago. ``That
meant a lot to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva, a Minsk, Belarus, native who spends ample time in her
adopted beach haunts in southern California, said she had not gone
into the match particularly confident as she waited for the Center
Court tarpaulins to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never confident against top people, especially certain
people like Steffi, or hard-hitting people, because my game doesn't
really match up,'' said Zvereva, whose career-best showing in the
singles rankings was No. 5 in 1989. ``I don't move that great, so
it's hard to get to the ball. But today I think I was in a kind of
mechanical mood, just try to get the ball over the net, and hit as
much as possible to the backhand.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
