<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-ART-N     06-26 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TIANANMEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON INVITES CRITICISM WITH APPEARANCE AT TIANANMEN SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
 (See also: CHINA-SUMMIT, CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-RUBIN) 
(ja) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Tiananmen Square is the symbolic center of Communist
China.
</P>
<P>
   It is where Mao Tse-tung proclaimed the founding of the People's
Republic in 1949, where millions of Red Guards gathered in the
political frenzy of the 1960s, and where students spontaneously
convened the largest demonstrations in the nation's history to
demand greater democracy during the spring of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But to most of the outside world, ``Tiananmen'' is still
synonymous with the massacre that occurred in Beijing on June 4,
1989.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton attends a formal welcoming ceremony in the
square on Saturday morning, simply setting foot here offers fuel to
critics of his China policy, who argue that he is sending the wrong
message about human rights or is insulting the memory of hundreds
of unarmed civilians who were killed near the square by the
People's Liberation Army in the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Sensitive to this concern, arrangements by the White House and
the Chinese government call for the ceremony to be positioned so
that the square will not appear in photographs, The Associated
Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Yet from the moment he agreed to come to China at all, Clinton
was effectively required to appear at the welcoming ceremony in
Tiananmen Square. It was not negotiable. American officials did not
even try to engage the Chinese on that point, one official said,
because the Chinese would not seriously discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the ceremony is held in front of the Great Hall of the
People, in an oblong plaza at one side of the square, American
officials have tried to argue that Clinton will not actually stand
in Tiananmen Square itself. That is sort of like saying that
standing at the corner of 43rd St. and Seventh Avenue in Manhattan
is not being in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite image from 1989, of a lone young man standing down a
tank, is commonly believed to have occurred in Tiananmen Square,
though it actually happened on the Avenue of Eternal Peace,
slightly to the east of the Square's entrance. (He has never been
identified.)
</P>
<P>
   Tiananmen is known as the site of the massacre, but was actually
the site only of protests.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence of events, in essence, was this: After seven weeks
of demonstrations only a few thousand hard-core, student-led
activists were left in the square by the night of June 3, when the
Communist Party decided to send in the army to clear the protesters
away.
</P>
<P>
   A few dozen policemen might have done that job, since by then
most demonstrators had gotten bored and gone home. But after a
wrenching power struggle at the top of the party _ party chief Zhao
Ziyang had been purged _ Deng Xiaoping apparently thought it
necessary to show the nation that the leadership was finally
united.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of armed soldiers approached Tiananmen Square in tanks
and open-back trucks from the east, north and west, but for a
reason that still remains unclear, only those coming from the west
opened fire. Shortly before midnight, soldiers about three miles
west of the square began indiscriminately shooting at unarmed
civilians in the street.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the first troops reached the edge of the square and
stopped shooting, at roughly 2 a.m., the students huddled around
the Monument to the People's Heroes at the square's center were
terrified. Four intellectuals siding with the students were able to
negotiate with an army commander to let the students leave
peacefully, and, after a voice vote seemed to approve that
decision, they filed out of the southwest corner.
</P>
<P>
   It is now considered unlikely that anyone was actually killed in
Tiananmen Square itself. But the army sealed it off, and with the
government in crisis mode, people on the streets of Beijing spread
their impression _ inaccurate but fully understandable, under the
circumstances _ that Tiananmen Square had been washed in the blood
of thousands of innocent students.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the killings _ hundreds, probably _ had occurred almost
exclusively on Changan Dajie _ the Avenue of Eternal Peace. And
though sporadic killings occurred just outside the square for the
next two days, when the authorities later assembled their
Orwellian-sounding defense of the massacre, they latched onto the
fact _ perhaps true, but clearly beside the point _ that no one had
died on the square.
</P>
<P>
   To this day, the authorities have never revealed how many people
were shot and killed that night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
