<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RETURNS SHOW NEW ULSTER ASSEMBLY OPPOSITION OUTNUMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST -- Preliminary results and projections by the BBC show
that more than 70 percent of the members of the 108-seat Northern
Ireland Assembly will be made up of members who have vowed to make
the new legislature work.
</P>
<P>
   Dissident unionists who want to obstruct its operation will fall
short of the seats needed to block progress, initial returns
showed. But they did better than expected and could cause problems
for Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble, who will probably be
elected first minister of the assembly at its inaugural sitting
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the early results, Catholic nationalists made a
strong start, while a rift was opening among Protestant unionists.
The vote count, complicated by the proportional representation
system which allows voters to transfer votes to other candidates in
order of preference, was expected to continue today.
</P>
<P>
   Projections show that candidates who oppose the Good Friday
agreement that created the assembly will get nearly the 30 seats
needed to force any measure passed by the assembly to have majority
support from both nationalist and unionist members. But they are
expected to fall well short of the 36 seats needed to block
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But there appear to be deep divisions within the Protestant
unionist community, which wants to remain part of the United
Kingdom, and strong showings by the two main nationalist parties,
which aspire to unity with the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in Northern Ireland's 77-year history, a
nationalist organization, the Social Democratic and Labor Party
(SDLP), received the largest number of first preference votes in an
election. But under the proportional representation system, the
largest unionist party, the Ulster Unionists, will gain many
transfer votes and are projected to win 29 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Projections by the BBC suggested the SDLP would win 25 seats,
while other pro-agreement parties are expected to win the
following: Sinn Fein, 17 seats; Alliance, 6 seats; Progressive
Unionists, 3.
</P>
<P>
   Of the anti-agreement parties who have made veiled threats to
make the assembly unworkable, the Democratic Unionists are
projected to take 21 seats and the United Kingdom Unionists five
seats. There are several Ulster Unionist dissidents who are also
expected to win seats.
</P>
<P>
   Dissidents within Trimble's party and its chief rival, the
Democratic Unionists, did better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll make a lot of noise, but the wreckers will not have
enough seats to wreck it,'' said Alliance leader John Alderdice.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble acknowledged that the early results and the forecasts
are ``not as decisive as we would have liked.'' But he said there
will be a majority within the unionist community to make the
assembly work.
</P>
<P>
   While the unionist vote was fractured, the Irish nationalist
vote was higher than expected. Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, the
first member of the assembly elected, said his party's vote was up
2 percent. That is important to show dubious members of the Irish
Republican Army that its leadership's decision to let politics take
precedence will pay dividends.
</P>
<P>
   With its projected vote, Sinn Fein, which has close links to the
IRA, will probably get two seats in the 12-member shadow cabinet
that will steer the assembly until it gets running next fall.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of Sinn Fein sitting in the cabinet before the IRA
disarms will be the first dispute of many in the new assembly.
Dissident unionists refuse to sit in the assembly with republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout of 68 percent was well down from the record 81
percent who voted in last month's referendum which approved the
Good Friday agreement which calls for power sharing and
cross-border cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
