<SLUG> BC-CBS-NUCLEAR-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS TO SELL WESTINGHOUSE NUCLEAR UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Idaho, Britain)  (bl) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS Corp. will sell its Westinghouse nuclear and government
services operation to a joint venture formed by Morrison Knudsen
Corp. and a British nuclear-fuel processor, the companies said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For CBS, which changed its name from Westinghouse Electric Corp.
in December, the sale rids the company of the last vestige of its
industrial past.
</P>
<P>
   For Morrison Knudsen, a $1.7 billion construction and
engineering company based in Boise, Idaho, that came near to
bankruptcy because of severe debt earlier this decade, the deal is
a way to increase its nuclear business quickly.
</P>
<P>
   For Westinghouse, it means a final end to speculation about its
future. ``We've worked under a lot of uncertainty in the last few
months, and we are really glad it's over,'' said Charles Pryor Jr.,
who will remain Westinghouse president.
</P>
<P>
   So is CBS management. Until last fall, CBS had said that it
would spin its industrial businesses off to shareholders. Analysts
had projected that even in a booming market, the entire group,
which included conventional power systems and process controls,
would garner no more than $3 a share; at an anticipated 700 million
shares, that would have brought no more than $2.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement announced Friday, Morrison Knudsen and
British Nuclear Fuels Ltd. will pay $238 million in cash and assume
$950 million in liabilities and other obligations of the nuclear
operations.
</P>
<P>
   CBS spokesman Jack Bergen said the money would probably be used
to buy back stock and to acquire more radio and outdoor media
companies like Transportation Displays Inc., its bus-stop
advertising company.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture will retain the Westinghouse Electric Co. name
and will remain in Monroeville, Pa. Morrison Knudsen is providing
$168 million of the $238 million in cash, but will assume only $30
million of the $950 million in liabilities. Still, it will get 60
percent of the equity in the company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That structure may go a long way toward getting the deal
approved by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about foreign countries having influence
on the nuclear industry, and Morrison Knudsen probably had to be in
control for this deal to fly here,'' said George Davies, an analyst
with ADDco Investment Research who also owns Morrison Knudsen
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that was the trump card that some American bidders for
the company hoped they held. ``This is an important strategic
business, and it would be better if it had remained under 100
percent U.S. ownership,'' said Linden Blue, vice chairman of
General Atomics, a San Diego technology company that had bid for
Westinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   William Wicker, a spokesman for the Energy Department, said,
``We provided CBS with our assessment on the impact a sale might
have on security, and they indicated willingness to address our
concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   British Nuclear Fuels, a $2.5 billion company whose stock is
owned by the British government, is no stranger to U.S. projects.
Its U.S. subsidiary, BNFL Inc., operates cleanup and
decommissioning contracts at five Energy Department sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have unique security relationships with the United States
government,'' said BNFL president Thomas Crimmins.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are the companies strangers to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ability to work together is proven,'' said Dennis
Washington, Morrison Knudsen's chairman and largest shareholder,
adding that his company and BNFL were already teamed up on a
project to clean up the Energy Department's Rocky Flats plant near
Denver and that Morrison Knudsen and Westinghouse had worked
together on projects at the department's Savannah River plant. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
