<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN-COX     06-26 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Do teachers, minorities carry political clout
ascribed to them?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unreported, when Bill Archer said the words, was whether his lip
quivered.
</P>
<P>
   Quivered when he said the words ``intense lobbying from special
interests,'' that is.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the Republican congressman is steeled when the subject is
``intense lobbying from special interests.'' Heaven knows Capitol
Hill Republicans try to insulate themselves. And when the going
gets too rough for a congressman besieged by special interests, the
tobacco industry can always supply a condo and a jet to get away.
</P>
<P>
   To what ``special interests'' was Archer referring the other day
in defending a piece of legislation that, true to the forces that
insulate him and his cohorts, would be a boon to the condo-jet
getaway set? It appears the villainous foes would be: school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is tax-free savings accounts that were created last
year to help families save for college. This week the House and
Senate voted to make them apply also to elementary and secondary
school.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton threatens a veto, for good reason. A Treasury
Department analysis found that 70 percent of the benefits would go
to the top 20 percent of income earners. That's up to $2,000 a year
sheltered from the tax man.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what this country needs _ another tax break to make
the wealthy wealthier.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents like teachers associations know that there's more
to this seemingly benign notion. It fits into the never-ending
effort to undermine public schools by siphoning tax dollars to
private schools, with vouchers as the endgame.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful groups?
</P>
<P>
   What one should find humorous in Archer's mock fright about
``special interests'' is that, as is so often the case, folks of
his ilk feign fear about groups of people whose power is generally
marginal, in this case teachers associations, when compared with
the real big-money interests.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, any union has power. That's the design of a union. But
the constant harping against the influence and designs of teachers
unions would make one think they're on a political par with the
Pentagon and Big Oil.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians on either side of the aisle know how to play the
special-interest game, whether it be to strum to the tune of big
labor or to invite industry to sit in at the table as environmental
regulations get sliced and diced.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the current majority party in Congress can stretch
credulity when it talks about some of the ``special interests''
that supposedly carry so much power.
</P>
<P>
   Most comical is the tremble that consumes those who inveigh
against the powerful ``gay lobby.'' Here is a shadow population of
people, most of whom dare not admit what they are. The fact that
some activists know how to punch a fax machine, however, makes them
the powerful gay lobby.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of its power, note the tremblers, an openly gay man
is nominated to become ambassador to Luxembourg. Egads.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, the world
</P>
<P>
   And we know full well that after the gay lobby gets Luxembourg
it would demand Andorra.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``special interest'' that gets the tremblers trembling
is minority groups, whose power is so fulsome among all that
Washington starch. Why, just look at all those black and brown
powerbrokers in Congress, in board rooms, and on the Forbes
billionnaire registry. What a mighty force.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the tremblers have us convinced that through affirmative
action, minorities will have us all under their powerful thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're white and very wealthy, goes the warning, be prepared
to become a stain on the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing there's always someone to turn to, some
champion of the underdog, say, Big Tobacco, to which a congressman
can phone in his getaway reservations.
</P>
<P>
   _John Young is the editorial page editor for the Waco
Tribune-Herald
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
