<HEADLINE>
NUREYEV FOUNDATION IS UPHELD IN DISPUTE WITH FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., France)  (bl) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge in Manhattan has ruled in favor of
the Rudolf Nureyev Dance Foundation in Chicago in a dispute with
Nureyev's family over the $7 million from the dancer's estate used
to establish the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Nureyev, the Russian-born ballet star who defected to the West
in 1961, died of AIDS in January 1993 in Paris. U.S. District Court
Judge Denny Chin ruled Thursday that Nureyev was of sound mind when
he instructed Barry Weinstein, his lawyer in Chicago, to transfer
the U.S. assets from his $21 million worldwide estate to the newly
created dance foundation two months before he died.
</P>
<P>
   Roza Nureeva-Francois, the dancer's sister, and her daughter,
Gouzel Noureeva, who live in France, objected to the transfer of
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Chin noted that they contended that Nureyev was unduly
influenced by Weinstein, whom Nureyev appointed to head the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm of Schulte, Roth &AMP; Zabel in Manhattan then sought
to obtain a judgment declaring the gifts valid. Nureyev's family
filed counterclaims seeking to void the transfer. Nureyev relatives
also named as defendants included another sister, Razida Evgrafova,
and two nephews.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, the judge said: ``Rudolf Nureyev was a
strong-willed person who dared to defy a government. He was not a
person who could be manipulated or unduly influenced and this
remained true even near the end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted his name and spirit to carry on after his death, and
he created the foundation for that purpose,'' Chin added.
</P>
<P>
   The Nureyev family stated in court papers filed in November that
Weinstein had charged the foundation for rent and hired his wife
and daughter to work for the foundation. The judge said, ``I find
that Weinstein and his family acted only in Nureyev's best
interest, sometimes at their own expense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9312 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TEACHERS-TESTS-BOS     06-26 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHERS-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI CHANGES MIND, URGES TEACHER COMPETENCY TESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three days after he said he could do nothing about the
falling standards for teacher certification, Acting Governor Paul
Cellucci Friday called for competency testing for all teachers and
said he would fire those who failed the exam.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also said he has asked John Silber, the chairman of the
Board of Education, to re-convene the board next week and take a
fourth vote to raise the passing standard on certification tests
for student teachers. In addition, Cellucci said he would introduce
legislation next week to forgive college loans for bright students
who choose to become teachers _ even though he once tried to kill
the very same ``Attracting Excellence to Teaching'' program.
</P>
<P>
   In an election year dominated locally and nationally by the
subject of education, Cellucci Friday sought to contain the almost
certain political damage after 59 percent of the state's aspiring
educators flunked Massachusetts' first-ever teacher test. The vote
earlier this week by the Board of Education to lower the tests'
passing grade so fewer teachers would fail, intensified criticism
that the administration was promoting incompetent teachers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, House chairman Thomas Finneran railed at the test
results and called those who failed the test ``ignorant and
foolish'' for expecting they could still teach.
</P>
<P>
   While calling the majority of public school teachers capable and
competent, Cellucci said Friday he was concerned there are
thousands of classroom educators who are not meeting standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't allow mediocrity to be the standard for our students
or our teachers,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Silber Friday said he assured Cellucci that the vote to lower
the standards on the tests, which affects only the next two rounds
of testing, will be reversed next week. Silber, whose own calls to
test all teachers won him scorn from the teachers' union, said he
was pleased Cellucci was taking up the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very fine idea to require by law that the
teachers who are already in the field pass the test,'' Silber said.
``It's ambitious and right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci's surprise announcement drew criticism from his
political opponents and angered representatives of the teacher's
unions, who accused him of election-year teacher bashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insulting,'' was the way Kathleen Kelly, president of the
Massachusetts Federation of Teachers, described Cellucci's proposal
to test longtime teachers for literacy skills. ``These kind of
attacks on the teaching profession are the fastest way to
discourage people from becoming teachers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kelly, and Stephen Gorrie, president of the Massachusetts
Teachers Association, said teachers who are already certified
should not have to take the exam and risk losing their jobs. Both
said that there are already job performance reviews and a system in
place to evaluate teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am shocked at such a suggestion,'' said Ronald Hambleton, a
professor of education and psychology at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, a nationally known teacher testing
expert. ``I would take the 20 years of experience over eight hours
of tests. If a good number of experienced teachers failed it, then
the problem would be in the test.''
</P>
<P>
   Hambleton noted that Massachusetts students fare well on
standardized tests, a clear indication that solid teaching is going
on in the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   And Mark Roosevelt, the principal architect of the 1993
education reform law, said ``there are reasons to be hesitant.
Let's say you test current teachers and 50 percent fail. Who are
you gong to replace them with?''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph D. Malone, the Republican State Treasurer who is
challenging Cellucci for their party's nomination for Governor,
said Cellucci had demonstrated his inability to lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have felt all along that the highest possible standard
should be applied to people seeking to become teachers,'' Malone
said. ``The difference between Paul Cellucci and myself is that I
would have made sure the Board of Education understood my position
prior to their first vote on this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia McGovern, the former state senator running for the
Democratic nomination for governor, repeated her call for the
firing of every member of the Board of Education and blasted
Cellucci for his late arrival to the matter of improving public
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing catch up,'' McGovern said. ``He puts his finger
up in the air and tests the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Lane, a spokeswoman for Brian Donnelly, another Democratic
gubernatorial candidate, noted that Silber and the Board of
Education serve at Cellucci's pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his board of education that lowered the test standard
but when he gets beaten up in the press and there's an outcry from
the voters he starts to back track,'' Lane said.
</P>
<P>
   And Scott Harshbarger, the Democratic attorney general who is
also running for governor, described Cellucci's change of heart as
``an incredible example of damage control from an administration
that has utterly failed for the last seven years to take the lead
on the most important challenge we face.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides testing current teachers and raising the bar on would-be
teachers, Cellucci said he would forgive college loans for people
who become teachers in order to attract the best and the brightest
to the profession.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not a new proposal. The ``Attracting Excellence to
Teaching'' program was created in the 1993 education reform law to
help debt-ridden teachers repay student loans. Former Governor
William F. Weld and Cellucci had actually tried to kill the
initiative in their 1995 plan to downsize state government.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Cellucci said the best way to attract bright
students to teaching is to reduce barriers to certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you got rid of all these bureaucratic hurdles, you wouldn't
need a program like this,'' Cellucci said. ``You'd be able to
attract quality people from all walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the current budget process, Senate President Thomas
Birmingham said the Senate budget would appropriate 30 percent more
for the excellence program than Cellucci would. He said the program
had not been properly marketed over the years, nor used to attract
bright students to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Of Cellucci, Birmingham said, ``His conversion is welcome, even
if it's a deathbed conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Jordanna Hart contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
