<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-26 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THIN-SKINNED U.S.A. 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By FRANK RICH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A show must be censored because it is not only ``pornographic''
but presents an ethnic group as ``backward and ignorant.'' Who
could be speaking?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the Catholic League for Religious and Civil Rights, which
has campaigned against Terrence McNally's ``gay Jesus'' play,
``Corpus Christi''? Or was it the Hispanic groups that protested
``Seinfeld''? Or was it the black employees at the Library of
Congress, whose protest led to the dismantling of an exhibit about
slavery? Or was it the Southern Baptist Convention, which found a
clergyman in purported sexual arousal in Disney's animated ``Little
Mermaid''?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was none of the above. The censorious words I read
in the paper were from cultural commissars in Shanghai who have
blocked the Kunqu Opera Company's production of ``The Peony
Pavilion'' from traveling to New York's Lincoln Center next month _
an outrageous act of totalitarian thought-policing that has
appalled Americans and cast another shadow on President Clinton's
trip to China.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news about this incident is that it reminds us
that we have a Bill of Rights. Our government may deny grants to
artists it regards as indecent _ as the Supreme Court seemed to say
in a muddled ruling this week _ but it can't shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we should congratulate ourselves too much. If we don't
have censorship, we now have an increasing wave of self-censorship,
in culture both high and low. Let any theater, museum or
entertainment company float a project that might offend someone _
even sight unseen _ and that someone will scream, tempting the
offending party to retreat or stick to the tried, the safe and the
PG-rated in the future.
</P>
<P>
   No one can call this insidious syndrome censorship, because the
protesters are always careful to say they are not demanding
censorship and their targets are equally careful to say expressly
that they do not back down in response to protests.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a disingenuous dance. Does anyone believe that NBC
elected not to rerun the Puerto Rican Parade ``Seinfeld'' episode
for any reason other than the public complaints? Or that the
Library of Congress postponed an exhibit on Freud solely for
budgetary reasons rather than because of a heated petition campaign
by such prominent anti-Freudians as Gloria Steinem?
</P>
<P>
   This cautious cultural climate _ fueled by the right, the left
and virtually every religious, ethnic and racial group _ can't be
accurately described by that tortured term PC, which is always in
the eye of the beholder anyway. A better term would be that
old-fashioned adjective thin-skinned.
</P>
<P>
   People have the right to protest ``Seinfeld'' _ and Jewish
groups did so more frequently than Hispanics _ but it is a sitcom,
for Heaven's sake. Should it be labeled ``racist'' because Kramer
accidentally set a Puerto Rican flag on fire and then tried to
stomp the fire out?
</P>
<P>
   When the Catholic League isn't campaigning against ``Corpus
Christi'' _ a still unseen and unfinished work that will be viewed
only by voluntary patrons in an off-Broadway theater _ its web site
is citing as ``anti-Catholic'' everyone and everything from Jackie
Mason, Mad magazine and a Rudolph Giuliani sketch on ``Saturday
Night Live'' to the musical revue ``Forever Plaid,'' the New York
Metropolitan Opera's ``The Voyage'' and TV's ``Chicago Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   The more self-censorship that ensues, the more our culture
becomes pablum. Since its Enola Gay disaster, the Smithsonian
Institution has postponed (apparently forever) an exhibit on the
Vietnam War, even as its National Air and Space Museum has staged
an elaborate, debate-free exhibit on Hollywood's fictional ``Star
Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   The forthcoming ``Corpus Christi'' notwithstanding, it's the
lack of unpredictable large-scale theater pieces in New York right
now that made ``The Peony Pavilion'' such a hot ticket for famished
local culture vultures in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The innovative director of this derailed opera, Chen Shi-Zheng,
is now a U.S. citizen, having arrived here in 1987, seeking
artistic freedom. Speaking of his current tussle with Chinese
authorities, he told The New York Times, ``It reminds me of the
Cultural Revolution, when things that have no relevance to artistic
debate take over, like ideology and politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He needn't worry about that kind of nonsense here, of course _
at least as long as he sticks with Ming Dynasty works like the 1598
``Peony Pavilion'' that don't hit too close to his new home of
America, 1998. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
