<P>
   MICROSOFT-HATCH (Washington) The chairman of the Senate
Judiciary Committee Friday vowed to open a new set of hearings into
Microsoft. Sen. Orrin Hatch issued a report criticizing Microsoft
for allegedly misleading his committee about a variety of the
company's practices, and he complained that the company has tried
to use public relations to distract the public from its conduct.
Hatch said the hearings will focus on Microsoft's BackOffice family
of server products. He said the hearings will also focus on
``practices and developments affecting access to, and transactions
on, the Internet.'' Sen. Slade Gorton blasted Hatch's ``lonely and
increasingly unsuccessful battle against Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (story has moved in the ``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-WASHINGTON-CANADA (Undated) Washington Gov. Gary Locke
cut a limited salmon deal with Canada that will entail additional
sacrifices by U.S. fishers. Washington boats will reduce coho
harvests but get some added Fraser River sockeye catch. Washington
salmon fishers, especially recreational fishing businesses, are
expected to protest that they have already been squeezed too much.
But Locke wanted to offer something in response to Canada's tough
restrictions on its own fishers to protect disappearing Canadian
coho runs and reduce its harvests of Washington's dwindling
chinooks. Canadian fishing interests may dismiss Washington's
sacrifices as minimal. Alaska was unable to come to terms with
Canada this year, and Washington's Indian tribes remain a
question-mark.
</P>
<P>
   By Rob Taylor. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
