<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-ART-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RECEIVED BY CHINESE PRESIDENT NEAR SITE OF MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-TIANANMEN, CHINA-RUBIN) 
(EDS: Will update through the night as developments warrant.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton was received by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin on Saturday in a military ceremony on Tiananmen Square,
the vast expanse through which modern Chinese history has flowed,
from the declaration of the communist state in 1949 to the crushing
of democracy demonstrations 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood mute throughout, as is customary at such arrival
ceremonies. He and Jiang then inspected army troops and reviewed an
honor guard on ground that human rights advocates around the world
consider stained with the blood of martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has defended his appearance before the Great Hall of the
People on the edge of Tiananmen Square as the expected behavior of
a state visitor to China. The square is the site of the student-led
demonstrations that ended in terror and bloodshed on June 3 and 4,
1989, when Chinese troops moving into the city center mowed down
hundreds of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance on Saturday morning dramatized China's
struggle between memory and forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leadership hopes to consign to history the events of
the spring of 1989, when indelible images of blood-letting in the
streets and of a lone protester standing before a column of tanks
were broadcast around the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, harshly criticized in the United States for lending
his prestige to Beijing's leaders by attending the ceremony, hopes
that his presence here will force the world to remember that bloody
night nine years ago. He was expected to speak of the lessons of
Tiananmen at a speech scheduled for Monday morning at Beijing
University.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the White House sharply criticized Beijing for the
harassment of dissidents on the first day of Clinton's state visit,
calling the detentions ``thoroughly unacceptable.'' But the
president did not take steps to impose any punishment or withhold
any favors in response.
</P>
<P>
   China demonstrated little concern about the detentions, denying
that anyone had actually been ``arrested'' and offering American
diplomats no explanation for their actions. Chinese authorities
routinely round up dissidents and other potential trouble-makers
before important events.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing is also showing little flexibility on the major items on
the summit agenda, hoping to win last-minute concessions from the
American side, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes dimmed for substantive progress on human rights and
missile technology transfers, and the White House has so far been
thwarted in its pleas to allow live television coverage inside
China of the rhetorical centerpiece of the president's visit, the
Beijing University speech. An official denunciation of the Dalai
Lama and criticism of the Clinton administration's appointment of a
coordinator for Tibetan issues promised few advances on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Using unusually harsh language, Sandy Berger, the president's
national security adviser, said that the Chinese internal security
apparatus was ``doing what comes naturally'' by harassing outspoken
opponents of the government who officials fear might embarrass
Beijing during Clinton's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not debris to be swept up for a visitor,'' Berger
said at a briefing for reporters on Friday in Xian, before the
presidential entourage flew to Beijing for the summit meeting. ``We
certainly will not accept this.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups reported that four dissidents were detained
in two Chinese cities and one was removed from Xian in the hours
before Clinton's arrival on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese authorities added to the friction on Friday night by
impeding two Asian-American White House staffers who were trying to
load the president's luggage aboard Air Force One at Xian's
airport. Mike McCurry, the White House press secretary, attributed
the incident to ``over-eager'' Chinese security officials who were
not expecting to find Asians in the presidential party.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was resolved in a few minutes and the stewards were
allowed to board the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Berger tried to explain Beijing's crackdown on dissidents as a
remnant of its police-state past, a preference for order over
political freedom. He said the repression was improving, if slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is changing, but there are still forces that are pulling
the other direction, that are resisting,'' Berger said. ``I think
China's human rights record is terrible. I think China is an
authoritarian nation, as I've said before. I think there's been
some progress in human rights, but it has been not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the area of public dissent, they are still totally
unacceptable. I don't think this is directed at President Clinton.
The fact that it happens generally in connection with these kinds
of visits, it is not appropriate, it is not necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Clinton said he found reports of the
detentions ``disturbing,'' but gave no indication that he would
change his approach to China in response. ``I think it makes the
case, it makes it all the more important that we continue to work
with the Chinese and engage them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jendrzejczyk, director of Human Rights Watch Asia, said
that the administration's unwillingness to respond with more than
words was a sign that the White House was ``desperate not to offend
the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is walking on eggshells, determined to
demonstrate that this visit represents a major breakthrough in
relations,'' Jendrzejczyk said. ``The Chinese are being tough, they
know their bottom line, and the administration seems willing to
accommodate them at any cost.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He called on the president to signal his displeasure by
withholding something the Chinese want, such as the planned visit
to the United States later this year by Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   But Berger said the United States planned to do nothing beyond
verbal protests. He said it would be against American interests to
impose any punishment or withhold any agreements as a result of the
police action. And he offered a partial excuse for the Chinese
action, saying it was not as severe as previous roundups of
dissidents before the arrival of important foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been pressing for China to permit the live,
nationwide broadcast of Clinton's speech on Monday, in which the
president is expected to deliver his strongest message on human
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has resisted and White House officials said on Saturday
that it appeared likely that the speech would be seen virtually
everywhere in the world but China.
</P>
<P>
   A largely symbolic agreement to retarget nuclear-tipped missiles
away from each other's cities appeared to be slipping away because
the Chinese continue to insist that the deal be linked to an
American pledge not to be the first to use nuclear weapons. Berger
said the right to launch a nuclear first strike was a core tenet of
American military doctrine and was not negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   There was also hope that the summit meeting would produce a
commitment by China to formally join the international
non-proliferation agreement known as the Missile Technology Control
Regime. But those hopes have faded in recent days as China demanded
to be exempted from certain of its provisions, particularly those
regarding export of missile technology.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had also hoped to win commitments from Beijing
on human rights, including the release of jailed dissidents and a
relaxation of the suppression of the Tibetan autonomy movement. The
American side also was seeking a firm date for China to sign the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, but Beijing
has so far not delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said on Saturday: ``I would not anticipate that we would
see the fruits of those discussions while we are here.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the release of three prominent dissidents came only
weeks or months after the first Clinton-Jiang summit last October,
and that the two countries had made progress on other fronts,
including the environment, health care and legal reform projects.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour meeting on Saturday morning, the two presidents
planned to make public statements and take a few questions from
reporters. Clinton was then scheduled to have lunch with Zhu and
attend a state dinner in the Great Hall of the People on Saturday
evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
