<SLUG> BC-SOC-ENGLISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE TO FACE WITH THE `LAGER LOUTS'
</HEADLINE>
 FANS-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, FRANCE _ They were berating the woman in front of the
train when I arrived, threatening to slap her silly unless she
allowed them to climb aboard. All three of them had near-empty
bottles of Budweiser --- the ``official beer of the World Cup'' ---
in their hands, and by the looks of them, it wasn't their first.
</P>
<P>
   What they didn't have were tickets for the last leg of their
journey from jolly olde ``Ingerland'' to Lens, and the woman from
French rail wasn't about to let them on the train without them.
Then --- bad news for the rest of us --- the conductor arrived,
welcomed them into the car, and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   It was my first experience with England's ``lager louts,'' and
although there was nothing present to suggest they might be the
hooligans we've watched on Sky news, I'd just as soon not run
across them again.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the conductor left our car and the train began to
depart Lille, the loudest of the bunch --- which had now swelled to
seven --- decided the best thing to do was urinate against the
door, all the while singing some dirty ditty that was, for the most
part, incomprehensible. The rest of the train --- those of us who
hadn't been drinking the previous seven hours, since 6 a.m. ---
looked on in horror, but what could we do? Shout, ``Stop that
now!'' Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   When he was done, he joined his mates at the next door of the
car as the puddle of pee started rolling around the floor. There
they sang and shouted, things like ``In-ger-land, In-ger-land,
In-gerland!'' and ``No surrender!'' Then another in the group threw
up on the floor, and they retreated further down the car.
</P>
<P>
   So we were penned in by urine and vomit, a World Cup experience
if ever there was one. A 40ish couple next to me, from England ---
both wearing England jerseys --- just shook their heads. ``They
give real England fans a bad name,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   She was curious about news reports that the German neo-Nazis
were heading to Lens to battle the Brits. ``Hopefully,'' she said,
pounding her fist into her palm, ``they'll meet up with that lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
