<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HORMEL-NOMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE SENATORS CONTINUE TO BLOCK HORMEL NOMINATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As senators departed for a weeklong recess Friday,
they left behind what has become an increasingly nasty debate over
the stalled nomination of James Hormel, who is openly gay, to be
ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of conservatives has blocked a confirmation vote,
charging that the heir to a meat-packing fortune is a gay activist
who has offended religious people.
</P>
<P>
   But Hormel's supporters say that the 65-year old nominee, a
former dean of the University of Chicago law school and a major
philanthropist, is being held hostage by a few Republicans eager to
please socially conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicion that conservatives intend to make Hormel an
election-year issue was heightened in the past few weeks by the
incendiary remarks of some GOP leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who has refused to
schedule a vote on Hormel, called homosexuality a sin and compared
gays to kleptomaniacs and alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   Another Senate leader, Don Nickles, R-Okla., charged that Hormel
was promoting ``immoral behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   James Inhofe, R-Okla., one of the first senators to openly
oppose Hormel, likened him to David Duke, the former Ku Klux
Klansman and politician.
</P>
<P>
   David Smith, a spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, a gay
rights group which Hormel helped found, said that Lott and some
other senators are ``pandering to religious political activists who
have identified this nomination as one of their core issues in
'98.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's comments have not gone over well with all of his
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think we should be characterizing people that
way,'' Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While Hutchison has not decided how she would vote on Hormel,
she said his sexual orientation is not an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly do not think we should not have a vote (on Hormel)
because he is homosexual,'' she said. ``I am looking carefully at
questions raised about any impropriety in his behavior that would
bear on his representation of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who has not shied away from
criticizing gay rights in his previous campaigns, said that
Hormel's homosexuality should not disqualify him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In and of itself, I don't think it should, no,'' said Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   The Texan said he recently met with Hormel and called the get
together a ``very positive step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with the meeting. He is sending me material to
read,'' said Gramm, who has not decided how he would vote on the
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed, Hormel, who was nominated by President Clinton
last fall, would be the first openly gay U.S. ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative activists have argued that Hormel's activities
in the gay community should be an issue for senators considering
his credentials to be an envoy to an overwhelmingly Catholic
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``James Hormel has made his life career promoting what should be
his private sexual behavior,'' said Steven Schwalm, a senior
analyst at the Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   Schwalm said that Hormel has supported an organization that goes
into schools to educate students about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives are also upset that he helped finance a gay wing
at the San Francisco public library that includes books they find
objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   To indicate Hormel is not respectful of religion, opponents have
distributed a video of a San Francisco gay pride parade that
features the nominee laughing as ``the Sisters of Perpetual
Indulgence,'' a group of men dressed up as nuns, passed by.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel's supporters say that his opponents have distorted his
activities, arguing that the foundation he heads, Equidex Inc.,
gives to a wide range of cultural and civic groups. They say he
can't be held responsible for every activity of every group that
his foundation has funded over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Hormel is exactly the kind of person who should be
encouraged to engage in public service,'' said Jim Hock, a
spokesman for California Democrat Dianne Feinstein, the lead
senator working on Hormel's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein's office has compiled a list of more than 60 senators
who believe that at least a vote should be held on the nomination.
Neither Hutchison nor Gramm are on that list.
</P>
<P>
   Hormel has garnered endorsement from some unlikely quarters,
including Sen. Orrin Hatch, a staunch conservative from Utah, and
George Schultz, former Secretary of State under President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Al D'Amato, who is waging a tough re-election campaign in
New York, also wrote to Lott urging action on the nomination and
charging that Hormel's confirmation ``is being obstructed for one
reason and one reason only, the fact he's gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Hormel's former wife and his five children have also rallied
behind him.
</P>
<P>
   A Minnesota native who has lived in San Francisco since 1976,
Hormel has been a big donor to the Democratic Party. He was
initially considered for an ambassadorship to Fiji, but that was
rejected because of strict anti- sodomy laws there.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Relations Committee voted 16-2 last November to send
him to the tiny European nation of Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   But then a number of Republicans, including Inhofe, Bob Smith of
New Hampshire and Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas, employed Senate rules
to block full consideration of the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate could override those objections with 60 votes if Lott
chooses to bring the matter up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
