r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-UNITEDSTATES-LADN     06-26 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-UNITED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP WAS DISASTER FOR U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 STATES-LADN (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ Debate on how well, or how poorly, the United
States' adventure in France went rages on, with two schools of
thought dominating the discussion:
</P>
<P>
   The Americans' World Cup performance a) was horrible, a complete
disaster, terrible enough to bring an end to Steve Sampson's reign
as coach and several players' international careers; or b)
demonstrated the progress American soccer has made over the past
four years and was, all in all, a success.
</P>
<P>
   The truth, this time, probably doesn't lie somewhere in between:
No matter how hard Sampson and U.S. Soccer officials try to place a
positive spin on Yanks' showing in France, it appears obvious to
everyone that this was an unmitigated disaster.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, after the losses to Germany, Iran and Yugoslavia
left the Americans the second-worst squad in the 32-team field,
team unity was shattered, the most respected players were openly
ripping into their coach, and Sampson was ready to issue
``significant'' fines and banish star players from ever wearing the
stars and stripes again.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he'll get the chance to make such determinations won't
be known for at least another month, until Alan Rothenberg and his
cronies make official their decision on the future of the national
team, but in a news conference that followed Thursday night's 1-0
loss to Yugoslavia, U.S. Soccer's president certainly made it sound
like there was little doubt what would come next.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg talked of two jobs ``to be filled by U.S. Soccer,''
one of them the national team coaching position. And Sampson, who
has been adamant that he should not be fired, acknowledged Friday
that he'd like the other job, as director of Project 2010 --- the
program designed to make the United States a world soccer power
within 12 years --- should he be released.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (U.S. Soccer) considers (failure in France was) a matter of
poor execution by the players,'' he said, ``I think they should
retain me. They have every reason to dismiss me if they think it is
a case of poor preparation or tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of his players, most prominently three-time World Cup
veterans Eric Wynalda and Tab Ramos and 1994 Cup star Alexi Lalas,
have charged that Sampson and his staff are at fault for the poor
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Cup was not about the U.S. national team, it was
about Steve Sampson trying to prove his worth,'' Wynalda told the
San Diego Union-Tribune on the eve of the game with Yugoslavia.
``He wanted to prove he didn't need experience and he didn't need
anybody or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point, clearly, was Sampson's decision to drop
captain John Harkes from the squad just before the April 22 match
against Austria in Vienna, a 3-0 U.S. rout that cemented a 3-6-1
(defenders-midfielders-forwards) alignment and relegated several
established players, including Lalas and Marcelo Balboa, to the
bench. At the time, it seemed to answer lingering questions about
the team, shoring up its porous defense, utilizing a wealth of
talent in midfield, and taking advantage of its speed on the wings
without surrendering defense.
</P>
<P>
   But the results in the preparation matches that followed weren't
so impressive, and the squad suffered from stage fright in the
disastrous first half against the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Steve made all his decisions based on the Austria
game,'' said Ramos, who overcame two major knee surgeries to earn a
spot on the 22-man roster. ``That might have been a fluke for all
we know.''
</P>
<P>
   Harkes' departure, for ``leadership'' issues and declining
performance, also appeared to give the team a lift, providing
playmaker Claudio Reyna the responsibility to take charge in
midfield. Several veterans say the loss of Harkes proved a major
blow to the team's chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned,'' Wynalda said, ``when (Sampson) cut
John Harkes, he tore the heart out of the team and threw it on the
floor and expected us to pick up the pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was amplified when Reyna, often fragile against
physical foes, struggled through the World Cup; the attack
suffered, managing just one goal --- a Brian McBride header that
squeezed past an Iranian defender late in the second game --- in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson says the criticism was sour grapes by players whose
playing time had diminished, and veterans' objection to the coach's
reliance on ``inexperienced'' players flails in the face of the
performances by World Cup debutants Frankie Hejduk, Eddie Pope,
Brian Maisonneuve and David Regis, the four best U.S. players in
France.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who repeatedly has claimed his team showed vast
improvement over the 1994 World Cup, when it reached the knockout
phase, that it ``achieved our goal of showing we've grown as a
soccer-playing nation,'' said the Americans performed well in five
of the six halves they participated but were victims to poor
finishing.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether they had learned any lessons in France, he
replied: ``Of course. The first half against Germany was probably
the greatest learning experience for us. Very quickly we had to
learn to wake up to the level of soccer at the World Cup, how
important it is to be together on and off the field, and how
important it is to finish your chances --- goal-scoring
opportunities are not easily created in world championships.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the core of what went wrong for the United States. They
had one pathetic half --- the first 45 minutes against Germany ---
but yielded few outstanding scoring chances to their opponents in
any of the three games. Had they been able to find the net,
especially against Iran (against whom they hit the post or crossbar
three times), the results might have been different and 1998 might
be thought a success rather than abysmal failure.
</P>
<P>
   But 0-3, 31st place and rampant dissension adds up to anything
but success.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a tremendous disappointment ... a nightmare,'' Lalas
said when it was over. ``There has to be some accountability all
around. As players, we have high expectations ... and there were
problems that have to be addressed. I'm sure there will be
assessments, critiques and probably criticism for a long time to
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Wynalda: ``I don't think people should focus on this being
a catastrophe, because it isn't. It's a wakeup call in a sense,
that we need to know what to do when we get here.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Americans didn't know.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
