</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US CRITICIZES CHINA OVER DISSIDENT ROUNDUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ As President Clinton prepared for his visit to
Tiananmen Square, White House officials lashed out at Chinese
authorities Friday for their abrupt roundup of several dissidents
at the outset of the summit. Once again, they said, the issue of
human rights proved to be an unbridgeable gulf separating the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, Clinton directed the United States ambassador to
China, James Sasser, to lodge an official protest with the Beijing
government. The move was followed by similar protests from national
security adviser Samuel (Sandy) Berger and other aides to their
counterparts in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not debris to be swept up for a visit, and we have
expressed our concern about this to the Chinese government,'' said
Berger in a meeting with reporters Friday afternoon in Xian.
``Their response so far has not been terribly satisfactory. They
dispute the facts or otherwise explain these incidents away.''
</P>
<P>
   In more pointed language later, Berger added, ``China's human
rights record is terrible. China is an authoritarian nation. There
has been some progress on human rights, but it has not been nearly
enough. In the area of public dissent, they are still totally
unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Robin Munro, the head of Asia Watch, a human rights group, put
the first two days in a broader perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good start, but it is good that the president is
experiencing first-hand the hard line that the Chinese government
takes against its dissidents,'' Munro said. ``The Chinese have a
saying that it is better to see something once than to hear about
it 100 times. If this does not result in action rather than just
words, than one must really start to question the whole dialogue
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups said that Chinese authorities detained at
least three dissidents on Wednesday and Thursday, as Clinton and
his massive entourage arrived in the country to an elaborate
welcoming pageant in the city of Xian. While the location of the
dissidents was unknown Friday, it was widely believed that they
were being held in jail.
</P>
<P>
   US officials at first seemed reticent to address word of the
roundup. Clinton, for example, silently walked past a reporter
Thursday night who asked for his reaction. By Friday, though,
Clinton and his senior aides, with an eye toward the American
audience, appeared comfortable acknowledging the situation and
criticizing the Chinese government for it. Still, they took pains
to avoid the impression that the roundup was intended by the
Chinese as a direct affront to Clinton and his quest for improved
human rights in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not distract from the atmosphere of the trip,'' said
Sasser in a brief interview at a remote village event Friday. ``The
president and the country will be seeing a lot of China, both good
and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the elaborate welcoming ceremony, which took place on
Tiananmen Square and moved to the Great Hall of the People, White
House officials were visibly anxious. Rare are the moments in a
president's day -- and especially those on diplomatic tour -- that
are not scripted to the most minute detail. But this ceremony, and
the statements that followed it, veered toward the unrehearsed.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony had already attracted the disdain of congressional
Republicans and human rights advocates, who argued that by
appearing on Tiananmen Square, Clinton was effectively overlooking
the actions of Chinese authorities from June &UR;  &LR; 4, 1989, when troops
killed hundreds, perhaps thousands, of democracy protesters.
Clinton has argued that protocol required him to appear on the
square.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the trip did not appear to be proceeding
particularly well for the US delegation either. Unlike most
summits, where agreements and treaties are prearranged weeks in
advance and are presented for a world audience when leaders meet,
officials were still unclear Friday what, if anything, would be
concluded from today's two meetings between Clinton and Chinese
President Jiang Zemin. Indeed, officials seemed to take pains to
downplay prospects for any breakthroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would raise human rights issues with Jiang,
but added, ``I would not anticipate that we would see the fruits of
those discussions while we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that even a largely symbolic agreement for the
two countries to reposition nuclear missiles away from each other
appeared unlikely to be resolved, largely because the US would not
accept a doctrine of no first strike. Even if such a pact were
reached, the two countries could retarget their weapons at each
other in a matter of minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a confidence-building measure and a statement
about the evolution of our relationship, since adversaries point
their missiles against each other and not countries that are
working to build a better relationship,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The one apparent agreement Friday was an offer by US officials
to provide Chinese judges, lawyers and legal officials guidance and
training in rules of law, with a particular focus on personal
rights rather than property rights.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides had hoped that Chinese authorities would allow
Clinton's Monday address on US-China relations at Peking University
to be broadcast live throughout the country, as did George Bush
during his visit to China in February 1989. But Friday, Chinese
leaders refused to say whether they would allow an uncensored
national broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best of all worlds would be to have the address carried
live so that the people of China can hear it, and I think there is
sufficient demand in China for it if anyone is going to make the
judgment based on news value,'' said White House spokesman Michael
McCurry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
