<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-SAMPSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPSON VOWS TO FINE CRITICAL PLAYERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ U.S. national soccer team coach Steve Sampson
promised Friday that players who had publicly criticized him during
the World Cup could expect ``significant'' fines and would never
play for him again if he continues as coach, an increasingly
unlikely scenario.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Tom King said ``two or three'' players would be
fined, and Reuters reported that Alexi Lalas, Tab Ramos and Jeff
Agoos would be penalized. All three, critical of their coach's
personnel decisions in France, have said they wouldn't play again
for Sampson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any level of unprofessionalism is acceptable,''
Sampson said Friday from the team's camp in Pornic, singling out
Ramos' comments following Thursday's loss to Yugoslavia. ``It's
unfortunate he feels so free to voice his opinions about me when I
have given him so much repsect and credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos was highly critical Thursday, saying, ``From the
beginning, the whole World Cup has been a mess. We showed at times
we're a good team, but overall I blame the coaches for the losses.
I don't have a problem saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Lalas, Sampson said: ``His professionalism was top class, but
his mood once we lost (to Germany in the opener) changed
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Preki Radosavljevic, who railed against Sampson for not
including him in the starting lineup against Yugoslavia, also may
be disciplined, Reuters reported, but there was no word on what
sanctions may await Eric Wynalda, who also condemned the coach.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the fines hasn't been determined, but Sampson said
they would be informed by post ``over the next few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the U.S. team departed for home on Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
