<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV28-B     06-26 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV28-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAWYER AND THE COLUMNIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 28 1998; f and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One way that I think of Mike Barnicle is as the guy who replaced
me on the ``The News Hour'' with Jim Lehrer. After giving me a
brief tryout as the Boston voice on its regional panel years ago,
the show went straight to the Globe metro columnist, and he has
been there ever since, a great success. There as elsewhere, he is
Boston Mike.
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle today is probably the second best pure newsman in
Boston, after Eileen McNamara (the paper's other metro columnist),
not counting Will McDonough, who covers sports. On a wide range of
topics, Barnicle is the go-to guy _ when you absolutely,
positively, have got to know what happened on one of his beats.
(There are some conspicuous exceptions, but I'll come to that.)
</P>
<P>
   His name got dragged through the mud last week, thanks to
Harvard Law School professor and defense attorney Alan Dershowitz,
who compared Barnicle to Patricia Smith, a third Globe metro
columnist whose resignation was sought and received after the paper
discovered she had fabricated material for her columns. In a series
of faxes, the Harvard professor accused the Globe of maintaining a
double standard.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz's attack was low, deceptive, and, up to a point,
effective. It forced the newspaper to mount a defense of a man who
for eight years had been accused of nothing much more serious than
a parking violation. &UR;  &LR; It impugned the newspaper's handling of a
very painful problem.
</P>
<P>
   The proximate reason for Dershowitz's complaint was Barnicle's
attribution to him in 1990 of a remark made in 1982: ``I love Asian
women, don't you? They're...they're so submissive.'' Barnicle said
the quote had been recalled from a chance sidewalk conversation of
eight years earlier; it was injected into a column about a feud
between Dershowitz and Barnicle's friend William Bulger, then the
Senate president.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz denied ever having said it. He threatened mightily,
eventually reaching a resolution of the matter with the
newspaper &UR;  &LR; _ thereby avoiding the process of mutual discovery that
would have shed light on the question of whether the youthful Dersh
had been racist, sexist, or, in his own words, a potential
adulterer, or Barnicle a liar.
</P>
<P>
   The statute of limitations on complaints like this one ran out
long ago. Barnicle has been writing his column for 25 years. It is
the hardest job on the paper.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1973 that Barnicle was recruited by Globe political
columnist Bob Healy and editor Tom Winship to be groomed to replace
legendary columnist George Frazier. ``His column will start in the
Evening Globe as soon as he learns to type,'' said the
announcement. Before that he had booted around Washington for a few
years as a Capitol cop, an elevator operator, speechwriter, and
screenwriter _ Robert Redford's ``The Candidate'' was partly of his
devising.
</P>
<P>
   Having never been apprenticed as a reporter, the boy writer had
a rough enough time of it in the 1970s before he began to settle
down. He was accused of ventriloquism, borrowing (by Mike Royko
regularly), and even fabrication. He denied it all and went on
turning out columns that firmly established him as the newspaper's
premier stylist.
</P>
<P>
   For Barnicle had the sine qua non, the inimitable voice of the
city. Born in Worcester, Mass., he grew up it Fitchburg, went to
school at Boston University, when it was still a loose
confederation of Methodist schools. Having lived in Washington and
New York, he returned to Boston to make a living. He understood the
city in its most intimate particulars: its tribal loyalities, sense
of humor, smoldering rage. Founded in 1630, Boston's motto even
today is, ``We wouldn't tell you if your shirt-tail was on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnicle is about nothing if not connections. He has friends and
fans in every conceivable part of the city. It helps that he has a
brother who is an influential Boston homicide detective. It helps,
too, that his wife is the advertising and public relations chieftan
for a major bank, and that they live with their children _ his,
hers, theirs _ in Lincoln, Boston's single fanciest suburb. But he
commutes most days to Dorchester, Cambridge, Roxbury, and every
other corner of the city.
</P>
<P>
   There he hangs out with cops, often being taken for one, which
helps him get his juiciest quotes. He takes batting practice with
the Red Sox in Florida, haunts park benches and newsstands, goes to
enough wakes to qualify as a professional mourner. He moves easily
in a city where the Senate president's brother was the town's top
mobster and where the confidence, and even the protection, of the
local office of the Federal Bureau of Investigation may have
extended to each.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, remember, is not Chicago or New York; Massachusetts is
one of the few states in the union where the political capital was
not long ago moved away from the commercial center as as way of
cutting down on temptation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Barnicle had character and grit. He learned,
experimented with forms, discrarding some, retaining others, a
pocket O. Henry one year, the reincarnation of Jimmy Cannon the
next. He raised the bar, like a weak-gloved ball player who batted
.245, .270, then finally .305. And so he became a star, adding a
regular gig on ``Chronicle,'' a nightly television news magazine
show; mixing it up between times with Don Imus on the radio in the
morning, on the MSNBC cable network at night. He is Boston Mike, a
man who grew into his role.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years or so, Barnicle regularly has hit the newspaper
equivalent of .300, improving his fielding at least to average (if
not exactly Golden Glove), playing a lot, and participating in many
of the biggest games. He writes three times a week. When he is not
reporting (or raising kids), he turns out a mix of sentiment,
shrewd observation, and one-liners with flashes of wonderful
writing. (He once described a certain politician as being ``cuter
than his baby pictures.'') He is too loyal to his friends, too
tough on his enemies, but then that is just another Boston trait.
He is not Breslin, not Hamill, not Cannon, not Caen, not Royko. He
is not DiMaggio either, nor Mays, nor Mantle: more like Duke
Snider, with some Carl Yastrzemski thrown in on the side.
</P>
<P>
   (If Patty Smith had had the same help as Barnicle, she might
have made it here too, though I doubt it. Her orientation to news
was too weak; her orientation to Boston nonexistent. She was a
Chicago woman through and through. And she came to her newspaper
column 20 years after Barnicle, in more-demanding, less-forgiving
times).
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Fifty years ago, Boston was called ``the poor farm of American
journalism,'' and deservedly so. But the economics of the business
changed, and thanks to the Globe's Taylor family and Tom Winship,
and secondarily to Rupert Murdoch &UR;  &LR; (when he owned the Boston
Herald), Pat Purcell (who does now), and Don Forst (a highly
regarded former Herald editor), Boston became one of four or five
centers of journalism in the country. At the top of the heap are
city columnists like Barnicle, Howie Carr, Shelley Cohen, Margery
Eagan, Peter Gelzinis, Ellen Goodman, Alan Lupo, Christopher Lydon,
Eileen McNamara, Brian Mooney, Martin F. Nolan, David Nyhan, and
Joan Vennochi. Boston journalisam is still famously eccentric, but
it has become nationally first rate, perhaps even the best in the
nation. No organization has had more to do with this than the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   I bring all this up to call attention to the source &UR;  &LR; of last
week's midslinging against Barnicle.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that Harvard Law School, where Alan Dershowitz hangs
his hat, has been a far more troubled place in recent years than
has the Globe. First it was the ``crits,'' a band of legal
nihilists whose shenanigans turned faculty meetings into
battlefields. Then there was an ongoing controversy over the
school's inability to appoint female and minority professors. &UR;  &LR; And
of course there is the unsolved murder of Mary Jo Frug, whose
husband, Gerald, is a law school professor. The police
investigation of her death was hindered and hushed through a
combination of legal bluster and arrogance &UR;  &LR; from a circle and
friends from the law school.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And through it all there was the man his students know as
``the Dersh,'' flamboyantly representing a series of famous
clients: Claus von Bulow, O.J. Simpson, Louise Woodward,
proclaiming all the while that here was the heart of the legal
system.
</P>
<P>
   Granted that a professional school does not seek to impose the
same tight scrum of ethical conduct on its members as does a a
newspaper. Granted, too, that Dean Robert Clark has calmed it down
and cleaned it up; the Harvard Law School has ceased to be a
circus. And Alan Dershowitz is a fine defense attorney. He
criticizes the powerful without fear or favor. He has proven he
came hold a grudge with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Dershowitz throwing rocks at The Boston Globe from the
shelter of Hauser Hall is still a spectacle. We do a better job
maintaining our standards and ventilating our problems here at the
newspaper than they do over there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
