<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEEKS `PROTECTIVE' PRIVILEGE FOR SECRET SERVICE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration tried Friday to convince
three skeptical appeals court judges to create a new privilege that
would allow Secret Service officers to avoid disclosing what they
know about the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that presidents would keep their protectors at an
unsafe distance if they can be compelled to testify about what they
see or hear on the job, Justice Department lawyer Stephen Preston
urged the three-judge panel to overturn an order requiring Secret
Service employees to testify before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is about the safety of the president and what is
necessary in the judgment of the Secret Service to protect him from
assassination,'' said Preston, who argued for the protective
service and its parent agency, the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
   The agencies want the courts to recognize a ``protective
function privilege,'' much like executive privilege and
attorney-client privilege. Preston said the new privilege would be
invoked by the Treasury secretary, not the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're asking for sounds bizarre,'' Judge Douglas
Ginsburg said during a series of comments and questions that at
times left Preston groping for a response.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, a former solicitor general
and member of the appeals court considering the case, urged the
judges _ all Republican appointees _ to leave intact an order
requiring Secret Service agents to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is evidence of wrongdoing, that evidence must be
reported,'' Starr said, citing a federal law that governs the
behavior of law enforcement officials, including Secret Service
agents.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Secret Service officers Gary Byrne and Brian
Henderson and agency lawyer John Kelleher must answer questions
before a federal grand jury investigating whether President Clinton
engaged in a cover-up of his alleged sexual indiscretions with
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Lewinsky have denied under oath that they had a
sexual relationship. Clinton has publicly denied having sex with
Lewinsky or urging her to lie about it.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his case, Starr wants to show that Clinton and
Lewinsky met alone at the White House, and the prosecutor has
asserted that Secret Service agents have information to support
that contention.
</P>
<P>
   Starr argued that if the Secret Service needed an exemption from
testifying in criminal cases, the agency should ask Congress to
pass a law and not seek a court ruling for which there is no
precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Starr pointed out that the Clinton administration's position is
inconsistent with past practices. The prosecutor referred to the
agency's willingness to provide Congress with information about the
whereabouts of President Bush. When congressional investigators
wanted to check out claims that he was abroad, Secret Service
officials testified that he was playing tennis in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it odd for a law enforcement agency to willingly testify
(only) when it helps the president,'' Starr said. ``But if the
testimony could hurt him, (agents) will not provide it or he will
push them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg, Randolph and Judge Stephen Williams, who a month ago
agreed to quickly review and decide the Secret Service privilege
case, ended the hearing with no indication of how they would rule.
Their decision is expected to be appealed to the full 11-judge
court, then to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
