<HEADER>
A9357 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-BOS &LR;      06-26 1368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM, UAW LOCKED IN CONTEST FOR SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ It doesn't look much like the bitter dispute it
is said to be. The mood of striking General Motors autoworkers,
gathered in a ragged knot near the vast, empty parking lot of GM's
hulking metal fabrication plant, is almost congenial. They hoist
the usual signs, wave at passing traffic, amiably receive the
occassional honk of support. They apply sun screen and eat fried
chicken. All in a day's work in this eminently union town.
</P>
<P>
   There is little to betray what labor experts say is really going
on: The death struggle of two aging Titans, GM and the United Auto
Workers union, engaging in what each believes is a final contest
for survival.
</P>
<P>
   The strike, now beginning its fourth week, has all but closed
down the automaker's North American operations, idling nearly
150,000 workers and costing the company $40 million a day. GM has a
long history of meeting union demands. But top management has vowed
to break the lock of UAW contracts in order to compete with Ford
and Chrysler, which won big concessions during the auto recession
of the 1980's.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to carve out the heart of the UAW and pursue it to
destruction,'' says Sean McAlinden, a research scientist at the
University of Michigan's Office for the Study of Automotive
transportation. ``There's real hatred here.''
</P>
<P>
   And the union knows it. With roughly half the membership of a
decade ago and a string of lost labor battles, the union's power _
once among the most feared forces in American commerce _ has
palpably slipped. Now, labor experts say, this strike will decide
not only whether workers can squeeze concessions from GM, but
whether the union can ever restore lost power.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a larger theme to the confrontation, labor experts
say: A struggle to make unions relevent in an age &UR;  &LR; of prosperity
and disappearing blue-collar jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that it just doesn't matter to the public the way
it used to,'' McAlinden says. ``It doesn't even matter to the
union's rank and file the way it used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers at GM's Flint Metal Center walked out June 5 after the
company refused to hire more staff and replace broken-down
equipment. A week later, in keeping with a union strategy to
disrupt the release of a new line of pickups, employees at a parts
factory across town joined the strike. Without parts to work with,
26 of GM's 29 assembly plants nationwide were idled. forcing the
company to lay off more than 146,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although GM traditionally has refrained from airing grievances
with the union in public, the company has lashed out against the
UAW this time around. In announcements and interviews, GM
complained that workers in Flint, protected by layers of union
contracts, are among the nation's slowest yet highest paid. GM even
set up a toll-free hotline with a taped union brow-beating by vice
president Donald E. Hackworth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; On Thursday, the company said it may drop car lines and
permanently close some North American plants, hinting that the
escalating fight is forcing it to decide the fate of marginal
operations sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   That the company would even speak out ``is historic,'' said Bill
Donohue, a former priest who on behalf of local business leaders
has tried to broker compromises between the union and GM. ``Those
guys never do anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, GM's public attacks have prompted little reaction from
striking workers, most of whom won't bear the brunt of future job
cuts. Thanks to UAW contracts, most will retire with full pensions,
and even those who are laid off are guaranteed 70 percent of their
base pay. Many now lead financially secure lives, and some view the
negotiations as a political squabble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like they're sticking knives in each other. I don't know
how productive that is,'' Richard Andrykovich, a stamping plant
pipefitter told the Fint Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the strike so far has failed to capture the nation's
attention in the way auto strikes of a decade ago did. One reason
is the sheer number of walkouts has numbed public sympathy, labor
experts say. In the past 30 months, UAL locals have staged 23
strikes against GM alone.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be that the country's working sensibilities have
shifted as high-tech giants like Microsoft and Intel have
overshadowed union struggles, making them seem like epic dramas of
a bygone era.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say it is fitting that the confrontation is
playing out in Flint, the birthplace of both GM and the UAW. Union
officials have even compared the current walkout with the historic
Depression-era sit-down strike in Flint that forced GM to recognize
the union in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Flint is one of the nation's best examples of how manufacturing
giants like GM and powerful unions like the UAW grew up together
and forged comfortable middle-class lives for thousands of
laborors. But GM's retreat from Flint beginning in the 1980s,
cutting jobs from 77,000 in 1978 to 33,000 now, has been
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   While city leaders say the economy is diversifying, block after
block of boarded storefronts, weeded lots and vacant or sparsely
inhabited downtown buildings remain decayed reminders of the city's
dependence on GM _ and on the fading era of life ``at the plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Blame for Flint's slide has in the past rested squarely on GM,
whose profits remained high while it laid off workers. Increasingly
though, Flint's business leaders point the finger at the union,
which they say has made labor so expensive that the company is left
with few choices but to leave. Working with GM to reduce costs,
they say, might at least salvage some of what is left of the
company's Flint presence.
</P>
<P>
   GM says it has the highest costs of any automaker in the
country, a fact it blames on UAW. It's share of the US car market
has slipped from 50 percent to barely more than 30 percent. It says
its metal fabrication plant loses $50 million a year while some
workers are allowed to work half-days while getting paid full-time
wages. The company says the plant's average worker makes $98,000
annually including benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you expect the company to pay the highest wages in the
world for four hours of work and still keep jobs in Flint?''
Donohue says. ``The union doesn't have a business strategy. It gets
what it wants and it gets it by force. Nobody in America works that
way anymore. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the city remains one of the nation's most militantly
pro-union towns, there are signs some of UAW's iron-grip power is
flagging in Flint. A recent survey by the local Mott Foundation
found just 20 percent of county residents viewed UAW favorably.
Flint Mayor Woodrow Stanley, in a move that would have amounted to
political suicide even a few years ago, defied union requests to
come out in favor of the strike.
</P>
<P>
   As for the outcome of the current showdown, no resolution is &UR;  &LR; in
sight. Talks between the union and GM have stalled, and the strike
appears destined to extend well into the summer. Though the strike
could cost GM as much as $300 million a week, analysts say the
company can afford to wait the union out.
</P>
<P>
   But few go so far as to predict UAW's demise. Its ranks still
include a healthy core of die-hard loyalists like Larry Gauthier, a
union representative who said his father, a pipefitter, told him
stories of the original sit-down strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what the union has done for the country,'' he said
recently, while taking a turn on the picket line. ``Nothing could
stop me from being a proud part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Labor experts say that for the union to survive in the long run,
however, it must fill a slightly different role.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've still got a social job to do,'' says the University of
Michigan's McAlinden. ``They've got to be more actively involved in
the training of workers, in keeping them able to handle a quickly
changing work place. They've got to work on striking new kinds of
deals. The leadership knows that, but their hands are tied. There
are still too many people who want things done the old way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
