<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      06-26 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANDARD &AMP; POOR 500 INDEX HITS RECORD HIGH
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market finished a strong week Friday as
blue-chip issues rode into record territory despite longstanding
fears about the economic crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts continue to warn about a slowdown in
corporate profits this year, partly because of Asia, but investors
are sending most of the major stock indexes significantly higher.
</P>
<P>
   After falling sharply just over a week ago, dropping nearly 5
percent below its record high, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock
index soared this week to a record 1,133.20 Friday, pushing the
index up nearly 16.8 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average also gained, rising 231.67
points, or 2.7 percent this week, to close at 8,944.54, about 3
percent below its record of 9,211.84, set on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were even stronger, led by Microsoft, which
soared about 10 percent this week after a federal appeals court
made a ruling in Microsoft's favor in the company's dispute with
the government over competition issues. The composite index of the
Nasdaq stock market, where Microsoft trades, gained 88.24 points,
or 4.9 percent, on the week to close at 1,869.53.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the midst of a summer rally,'' said Harvey
Hirschhorn, the chief investment strategist at Stein Roe &AMP; Farnham
in Chicago. ``The market had been oversold for a while, but we're
seeing a lot of support from the bond market, where yields are at a
decades-long low.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, bond prices soared again Friday, dropping the yield on
the benchmark 30-year bond to 5.63 percent, close to its lowest
level in nearly 30 years. Inflation fears continue to diminish, and
a flood of cheap imports from Asia promises to keep prices low,
traders believe.
</P>
<P>
   As for share prices, Friday's gains were meager, just 8.96
points on the Dow and 3.92 points in the S&AMP;P 500. But the weekly
gains were an impressive show of confidence after months of seesaw
trading over concerns that a slowdown in Asia would curb corporate
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Asian worries, a steady flow of government reports
depicting a vibrant American economy, with lower interest rates and
soaring consumer confidence, has put investors in a jubilant mood.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, for instance, the government said consumer spending
accelerated in May. That followed a Thursday report that the
economy in the first quarter grew at an annual rate of 5.4 percent,
the second-fastest pace in a decade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of numbers seem to have served as a counterweight to
concerns about slowing profit growth at home, and the prospect of
an even sharper pinch from falling demand for American-made goods
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say they believe that investors are
overlooking the profit slowdown and banking on a powerful economy
that will eventually create another wave of hefty profits in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent weeks, Wall Street has been subjected to a steady
stream of profit warnings. ``We think the economy is in a profits
recession,'' said Richard Bernstein, the chief quantitative analyst
at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Abbott, a research manager at IBES Inc., which tracks
earnings, said that profits for the companies in the S&AMP;P 500 are
projected to rise just 2.6 percent in the current second quarter,
down from double-digit gains a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And the strike at General Motors plants could cut that figure
even more. Friday, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. lowered his
second-quarter earnings estimate for GM. If profits at GM are
sharply reduced, in line with the Goldman forecast, IBES says
growth in S&AMP;P profits would shrink to just 1.6 percent in the
quarter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Hill, who compiles forecasts for First Call Inc., said
earnings expectations were falling at a faster-than-normal rate
this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing more negative pre-announcements,'' he said. ``And
there could be significant disappointments in the third and fourth
quarters. Asia is certainly not going to get better that quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschhorn at Stein Roe projects that profit growth will decline
in the third and fourth quarters largely because of rising wage and
price pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not overly excited about the next 12 to 16 months,'' he
said. ``We've had nirvana, and now we're moving into
post-nirvana.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
