<P>
   NIRELAND-ELECT (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Parties committed
to the Northern Ireland peace settlement emerged winners in the
election for the new Assembly on Friday, but candidates opposed to
the accord won enough seats to call into question the value of that
victory. The results showed that the province's two biggest
parties, the Ulster Unionist Party of David Trimble and the Social
Democratic and Labor Party of John Hume, would get the chance to
fulfill their historic pledge to work together to end the sectarian
conflict. But the ongoing count of the ballots from Thursday's
election, which will not be complete until Saturday, was exposing
deep divisions in Trimble's support as many party members deserted
him to cast their votes for other Protestant candidates wary of
cooperation with the Catholics. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
