<P>
   NY-LANDLORD (New York) _ Over the last 20 years the families at
Bedford Gardens, a sprawling Brooklyn apartment complex, have grown
accustomed to encountering the name Kraus at every turn. At the
center of an empire of companies bearing his name is Herman Kraus,
a tall, methodical, 70-year-old lawyer. Year after year, through
legal maneuvering and sheer tenacity, he has managed to award his
own companies almost every major contract to operate and maintain
the 639-apartment complex, which gets more than $3 million a year
from the federal government in rent assistance for its
working-class tenants. The unusual arrangement has made the complex
into what city officials have described as the closest thing to a
monopoly in the city's assisted housing system. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
