<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-SEQUOIA-$ADV28-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUFFET EFFECT ON SEQUOIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
(af) 
 By RICHARD TEITELBAUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warren Buffett's announcement this month that his company,
Berkshire Hathaway, was spending $21.7 billion in stock to acquire
General Re was of more than passing interest to investors in one
mutual fund: Sequoia, the $4.8 billion offering that closed to new
investors in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   The fund counts Berkshire Hathaway as its largest holding by
far: 26.4 percent of the portfolio was in Berkshire stock as of
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   So when Berkshire's class A shares fell 4.2 percent on the
Monday after the acquisition was announced, to $77,500 a share, it
was hardly surprising that Sequoia sagged, too, by 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett and the co-managers of Sequoia, William J. Ruane and
Richard T. Cunniff, share more than a common interest in the
performance of Berkshire stock. All are former students of the
grandfather of value investing, Benjamin Graham. Their portfolios
are similar, too.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 stocks owned by Sequoia, at least three _ Walt Disney,
Wells Fargo and Freddie Mac _ were also held by Berkshire as of
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises a question: What would Sequoia's performance
have been of late if it weren't for Berkshire? Given that laws
require only infrequent disclosure, the best an outsider could hope
for is a back-of-the-envelope figure.
</P>
<P>
   Using net asset and total return figures from Morningstar Inc.,
the financial publisher in Chicago, the Money and Business section
did a series of calculations to see how the fund's Berkshire
holdings _ which appear to have remained constant _ affected
performance each month from June 1995 through May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By subtracting the value of the Berkshire stock from total
assets, and the Berkshire-generated growth from total
performance-related growth, the performance of the rest of the
portfolio can be roughly estimated. The figures show Sequoia had an
average annual return of 35.2 percent over the three years.
Excluding Berkshire, the return would have been less: 30.8 percent.
(Berkshire, helped by great year-to-date performance, returned 46
percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Does all this cut the storied Sequoia down to size? Hardly. Its
three-year return, even without Berkshire, was still better than
the 29.5 percent annualized return of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index. And Cunniff pointed out that the methodology
assigned all cash to the fund's ex-Berkshire return, hurting its
relative performance in an up market.
</P>
<P>
   But the figures do suggest a way to close in on Sequoia's
returns. Investors could buy an S&AMP;P index fund with half their
money and put the rest into Berkshire stock. ``That's not a bad
idea,'' Cunniff said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
