A9362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARASS-REACT-BOS &LR;      06-26 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASS-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OBSERVERS SEE INCREASE IN SEXUAL HARASSMENT ACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON AND CHANA SCHOENBERGER   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Supreme Court has opened the door wide for employees who
want to file lawsuits against their employers for sexual
harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Employment lawyers and human resource executives said Friday's
decision would certainly increase the number of harassment
complaints that employees file against their employers in the
future _ and make it easier to win them.
</P>
<P>
   A growing caseload would add to the escalating liability of
employers battling harassment claims, which have risen sharply in
recent years. Employers last year paid nearly $50 million to settle
federal sexual harassment claims, according to the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission. That is nearly double their cost in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Things will only get worse for employers and better for
employees, experts said in reaction to Friday's decision by the
nation's highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court has lowered the bar'' and ``made it easier''
to prove sexual harassment under federal law, said Paul Stanzler,
an employment lawyer and managing partner at Burns &AMP; Levinson in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Employers in recent years have been under attack by a myriad
harassment decisions, often not in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision is the second this year by the Supreme Court
broadening what constitutes a legitimate claim of sexual
harassment. Justices in March for the first time allowed employees
to file lawsuits claiming same-sex harassment in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the latest decision, companies that do not
already have precise procedures for handling complaints of
harassment brought internally by employees, must implement them,
consultants said. That may mean keeping careful records of any
employee who comes to the human resource department to report a
lewd remark or inappropriate behavior by a coworker or boss.
</P>
<P>
   More employers may also be forced to purchase insurance to
protect themselves against harassment complaints, in much the same
as they buy insurance for workers injured on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers are liable for supervisors' sexual harassment unless
the employers can affirmatively show that they took action to
prevent it,'' said Jody L. Newman, a partner in the Boston law firm
of Dwyer &AMP; Collora who defends sexual harassment victims. ``It's an
improvement, a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While ``sexual harassment'' is now a widely recognized term,
individuals who sued employers often stumble in court when asked to
show how they were harmed _ whether fired or passed over for a
promotion or raise _ or if they rebuffed sexual advances or lewd
remarks by a supervisor. Friday's Supreme Court ruling removed that
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Chicago case, Kimberly Ellerth sued her
former employer, Burlington Industries, maintaining that her boss'
boss made comments such as, ``You know, Kim, I could make your life
very hard or very easy at Burlington.'' The court said those
threats, though they were never carried out, create a hostile work
environment that could leave an employer liable.
</P>
<P>
   Many large corporations have strict harassment policies in
place. ``We have a procedure that's clearly understood,'' said
Libby Sartain, whose title at Southwest Airlines is vice president
of people.
</P>
<P>
   But, for employers who do not take harassment claims seriously,
the court's decision ``is a wake-up call to US businesses,'' said
Marilyn Stempler, a partner at Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP; Gesmer in
Boston. The court's message: ``Put policies in place. Have a rapid
response to people who complain, and have a really good reporting
process.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the court's ruling made it more difficult for
employees to bring a lawsuit if they failed to register any
complaints with employers in a timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``That employers can avoid liability if they can show that the
employee failed to complain, is new and extremely significant,''
said Louis A. Rodriques, head of the employment law practice group
at Sullivan &AMP; Worcester in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers said that this new onus on employees pales compared with
the increased ease of making _ and winning a sexual harrassment
case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
