<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-U.S.-ANALYSIS-HNS     06-26 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-U.S.-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN P. LOPEZ 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LENS, France _ In the immediate future, we know where U.S. soccer
is going.
</P>
<P>
   Home.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the larger question?
</P>
<P>
   Where will U.S. soccer be four years from now? What about 10
years? What about the much-hyped Project 2010, which is the U.S.
dream plan of winning the World Cup by 2010?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, everything seems less like a plan and more like a
joke. Much like its 1998 World Cup team, U.S. soccer seems to be
making good time but going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole World Cup has been a mess,'' U.S. midfielder Tab
Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the year U.S. soccer scored with the
home fans and soared at the World Cup, riding the momentum into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it bounced off the post. And limped home.
</P>
<P>
   Despite bringing to France a nice team of proven veterans,
talented imports, an American-born coach and, most significantly, a
core of young players with apparent world-class skill, the United
States went three-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   The team never seriously threatened in any game, although it
seemed to make good time _ showing flashes of great play but
inevitably falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   It scored but one goal in three games. It played as if it was in
awe of Germany. It lost to Iran, not just a political rival but a
team that was supposedly vastly inferior to the Americans. It made
good time against Yugoslavia but again went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   And it came apart at the seams, with several players letting fly
with criticisms of coach Steve Sampson, the system, the plan or the
experience in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's frustrating is a lot of work has been put into this
team,'' said forward Eric Wynalda, the all-time leading U.S. scorer
who was left off the starting roster for the Iran and Yugoslavia
games. ``For me, this was the most tragic of the three World Cups
I've played in. We can try to rebuild and not let this happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has a project ahead of it in the wake of
France '98. Specifically, instead of riding the anticipated good
showing in this tournament, rebuilding the national team seems in
order.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the coach. Sampson's status is shaky at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if he'll stay,'' U.S. goalkeeper Kasey Keller said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ramos: ``He was in way over his head.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Sampson junked his midfield-heavy philosophy immediately
after the opening loss to Germany was a sign of anxiety or lack of
confidence in the system. The change also could have come by order
from above _ specifically U.S. Soccer Federation president Alan
Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament, the 3-6-1 system _ six midfielders, three
strikers and a man back _ worked nicely for the Americans, but in
the Germany game it created few chances and was weak defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Sampson's handling of the lineup was confusing and
disjointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, the team that got us to the World Cup,'' Wynalda
said, ``was not the same as the team that played in the World
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson inserted 10 new players as starters over the course of
the three games, which in one respect was what the team needed.
Players such as Claudio Reyna, 24, and Eddie Pope, 24, are skilled
American-born players who could carry this team a long way.
</P>
<P>
   But why 10 first-time starters?
</P>
<P>
   It seemed too much, especially after even Reyna and Pope were
overwhelmed against Germany. The likes of hardened veterans such as
Ramos, Marcelo Balboa, Jeff Agoos and Alexi Lalas stayed on the
bench. And back home, there was the veteran John Harkes, whom
Sampson left off the team after the two clashed over Sampson's
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas and Agoos never played in France. For Agoos, it was
especially bitter, considering he was the last player cut from the
1994 World Cup team and lost his starting spot to a Sampson import
_ Martinique-born David Regis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deserved better than this. That's all I can say,'' Agoos
said.
</P>
<P>
   Balboa played only in the waning minutes of the final game.
Ramos was benched in the first game, then yanked in the second half
of the second game against Iran and sat again in the finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to see it end,'' Ramos said. ``It's been
disappointing the whole way. I don't think we got the best out of
the talent we had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had spurts. But if you have to blame people, blame the
coaches. Steve Sampson and (assistant) Clive Charles didn't get the
most out of what we had. We could have done a lot better. As long
as Steve Sampson or Clive Charles are around, I don't want to be
any part of it. I hope somebody new comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg has not fired Sampson; he said Sampson's status would
be reviewed in the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the decision could be Rothenberg's short-term
status as president of the federation. The architect of the 1994
World Cup in the United States, Rothenberg will move on when his
second term as federation president expires in August.
</P>
<P>
   His relationship with Sampson could lead to the duo joining
forces again in Major League Soccer, where Rothenberg has an
interest.
</P>
<P>
   But the players seemed to fire Sampson long before this
tournament was over.
</P>
<P>
   Lalas said if Sampson's tactics were part of a master plan, then
U.S. soccer was in trouble. Sampson admitted he considered sending
Lalas home after hearing those comments after the Iran game.
</P>
<P>
   Ramos tore apart the coach. Wynalda quietly seethed over the
starting snub.
</P>
<P>
   And down the roster the ill feelings went, disintegrating all
World Cup hopes and leaving a bad feeling about where U.S. fortunes
are headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play the role we had hoped to play in this
tournament,'' Balboa said. ``We expected to improve on what we
accomplished in 1994 (a second-round appearance). I don't know
what's going to happen now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with a much stronger financial base than ever, more
exposure through the MLS and numerous national-team programs, U.S.
soccer could be at another crossroads in the wake of this 1998
experience.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the likes of Lalas, Ramos, Agoos, Wynalda and Balboa
likely have played in their last World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Cobi Jones, Joe-Max Moore and Ernie Stewart _
long considered the bright, young faces of American soccer _ will
be in their 30s at the next World Cup. And Reyna and Pope, the
super-kids, were average.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity to accomplish something in this World Cup and
raise interest in the game across the country was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the next generation of players come from?
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg says he feels good about the Under-20 and Under-17
core of players in place, but there are few inner-city soccer
programs such as that of the Houston Parks Department, which
Rothenberg cited by name as an ideal developmental program for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   There also is little street and sandlot soccer in the United
States, unlike other countries where it is common.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, we need to do a better job attracting the best
athletes the United States has to offer into the sport,''
Rothenberg said. ``We need to generate more interest for more
players.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. soccer had a golden opportunity to do that here. But it hit
the post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
