<SLUG> BC-TVCOL-TEX </SLUG>
 
Spanish station is down on World Cup rating 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Last week, we suggested that televised soccer is on life support in
this country, World Cup ratings on ABC and ESPN being what they
are.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lousy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we should rephrase that. Actually, soccer isn't doing
bad at all on America's leading Spanish-language TV outlet, the
Univision Network.
</P>
<P>
   Univision executives boasted last week that World Cup games
broadcast on their network are attracting one-and-a-half times the
number of viewers tuning in to World Cup games airing at the same
time on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   They also point out that with ABC and ESPN's biggest drawing
card, the United States, eliminated from the tournament, the ABC
and ESPN ratings are likely to head further south.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, they add, ``the continuing outlook for Univision is
promising, with several Latin and South American teams strong
contenders to advance to Round 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, you say, given the relative passion for soccer
among Spanish-speaking American soccer fans.
</P>
<P>
   I think it's something else. I think it's Univision's voice of
Futbol, the man who would make us forget Michael Buffer, Andres
Cantor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gooooooooal!'' Girls' fortnight out Tennis' greatest annual
moment, Wimbledon, gets the full TV treatment starting this weekend
when NBC joins HBO in carrying the championships through next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly going to be a remake of ``Where The Boys Are''.
More like, ``Girls Just Wanna' Have Fun''.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Preen Queen, Anna Kournikova, down with an injury, all
eyes and cameras will be trained on the ladies of the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   As for the guys of the grass, they ought to be relegated to the
secondary courts _ so boring is their game, so lacking are the men
in charismatic stars or intriguing shot making.
</P>
<P>
   Even network commentators agree that the show this year is
Martina Hingis and Venus Williams and Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the women's draw, and you see matches you really
want to see,'' HBO commentator John Lloyd said. ``In the men's game
right now, that's lacking. Who do we really want to see play? We're
lacking any substantial rivalries.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO executives say this year could be a turning point in the
coverage of tennis, with the women drawing more air time than the
men thanks to the rivalries among top players as well as the
brashness exhibited by stars such as Hingis and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   While their cock-sure attitudes offend some, it sure makes for
great press, and that makes for great match-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women have personalities at the moment,'' says NBC's John
McEnroe, a man who knows something about being a colorful
character.
</P>
<P>
   What men's tennis really needs, he didn't have to add, is
another McEnroe. X marks the spot X Games athletes will tell you
their sports are all about defying gravity. Watching the X Games is
all about defying the commercialism that weighs down the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   There's no getting away from the fact that the X Games are about
commerce first. They were created by ESPN to provide itself
programming and to attract the 12-year-olds to 34-year-olds who
either have lots of cash to burn on advertisers' products or will
some day.
</P>
<P>
   If you can remove yourself a bit from the shallow commercial
rants of the games' sponsors and from the network's
entertainment-first approach, though, you might actually find that
some of the competitors are as athletic in their skills as
Olympians are in their sports.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you regard the X Games as nothing more than the sporting
version of a made-for-TV movie, you will see dedicated athletes.
Who else could perform in-line skating, climbing and barefoot
water-ski jumping at the level seen in San Diego?
</P>
<P>
   You've got a few more days to catch the X Games, which run on
WFAA/Channel 8, ESPN and ESPN2 through Tuesday. (David A.
Markiewicz is a sports media columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.) &QL; 
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web at
www.star-telegram.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
