<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MUNI-$ADV28-A     06-26 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MUNI-$ADV28-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-YIELD ALTERNATIVE TO THE MONEY MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic showing
fund fact box will be sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
(af) 
 By TIMOTHY MIDDLETON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a time when many money market funds are yielding more than 5
percent, and some more than 5.5 percent, investors could be
forgiven for yawning at a fund that threw off just 5.1 percent. So
what makes the Heartland Short Duration High-Yield Municipal fund a
heart-thumper? It's in the tax-free category, making its yield the
equivalent of 8.4 percent to someone in the top 39.6 percent income
tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   A money market-like fund with a junk bond-like yield is the idea
behind this offbeat offering, the brainchild of Thomas J. Conlin,
44, and his partner, Greg D. Winston, 33. They moved from Strong
Capital Management to Heartland Advisors Inc. in 1996 and managed
to persuade William J. Nasgovitz, the firm's president, to try
their approach.
</P>
<P>
   Their aim was to take advantage of a potentially profitable
anomaly in bonds: the near absence of a market for junk-rated muni
bonds with very short maturities.
</P>
<P>
   Other mutual funds often buy long-term bonds to reap their
higher yields. For example, the other fund managed by Conlin and
Winston, Heartland High-Yield Municipal Bond, has a yield of 6
percent. But it has to make a trade-off in the so-called effective
duration of its bond portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Duration is a measure of a bond's economic life; the higher the
number, the more sensitive the bond is to interest-rate swings.
</P>
<P>
   The Short Duration fund has an effective duration of 2.2 years,
versus 7.4 years for High-Yield Municipal Bond. ``In the past,
there hasn't been anyone who's interested in the securities that
we're looking at,'' Winston said. Bank trust departments, for
example, buy only high-quality short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the Heartland portfolio as one of only a few
customers for such bonds. ``This is a good concept,'' said Alice
Lowenstein, fixed-income editor of Morningstar Mutual Funds, the
investment newsletter. She said she knew of no other similar funds
_ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Since it started in January 1997, the Short Duration fund has
delivered an average annual return of 6.6 percent, through May 31,
the same as the Lehman Brothers One- to Three-Year High-Yield
Municipal Index, which tracks these relatively scarce bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the fund looks like a money market fund. Its net
asset value is relatively steady, having varied only slightly from
the $10 initial offering price; shares are currently worth $10.13.
Check-writing is also offered, in minimum amounts of $250. But
checks amount to a redemption of assets and can thus incur
capital-gains taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this clearly as a money-market alternative,'' said
Conlin, the more effusive partner. But Winston, the quieter
partner, interrupted: ``We have to be careful with our phrasing. We
manage for a low degree of share-price variation, but not for a
stable net asset value.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston, who counts exercise and music as his outside interests,
admits to being ``a little more risk-averse'' than Conlin, who is a
recreational pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The counterbalancing of personalities is reflected in the fund's
management style. Both men must agree to buy a bond, but either can
force a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Greg wakes up and something bothers him about a bond, and
he comes in and says, `I want to sell it,' it's gone,'' Conlin
said. ``We think that's a nice check in our process.''
</P>
<P>
   How do the two reduce credit risk in what, despite its tame
interest-rate exposure, is still a junk-bond fund? They start by
focusing on bonds that underwrite essential community services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like projects that affect a large number of people, like
water and sewers,'' Winston said. ``We try to avoid projects that
affect a more limited number of people, like a golf course or an
aquarium.'' The latter type is more likely to sour, he said,
especially in a recession.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The partners also like borrowers with relatively little debt and
plenty of cash flow to service it _ and they prefer bonds with
legal covenants that protect bondholders' capital.
</P>
<P>
   The fund often buys short-term portions of issues that also
include longer-term bonds. Relatively little yield is lost: The
spread between long and short rates in the junk muni market is
about 72 hundredths of a percentage point, compared with 95
hundredths in the high-quality universe.
</P>
<P>
   One such issue is the Connecticut Development Authority's 6.875
percent bonds due to mature on Aug. 15, 2004, issued on behalf of a
nursing home in Southington, Conn., that specializes in treating
Alzheimer's disease. The bonds' structure gives them an effective
duration of only three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a first mortgage on the facility and a first lien on
revenues,'' Conlin said. ``We think it's well-managed and, best of
all, it's 100 percent occupied, with a waiting list.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes ``junk'' is a misnomer: More than half the time, the
bonds in the fund are simply unrated by agencies like Moody's and
Standard &AMP; Poor's. Issuers must pay to have their bonds rated, so
small issuers can save by selling unrated paper, even if they have
to pay junk yields.
</P>
<P>
   An example is a 5.4 percent industrial revenue bond of Topeka,
Kan., due April 1, 2005, issued on behalf of Reser's Fine Foods, a
food processor based in Beaverton, Ore. Topeka is home to the
biggest factory operated by the company, which makes potato salad
and other prepared foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a family-owned business whose president has been there
since the 1950s,'' Conlin said. ``They cover their niche very well,
and their financial numbers are outstanding _ 1997 revenues are
just shy of five times debt-service coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund also buys longer-term bonds nearing maturity. An
example is the 8.2 percent bonds issued in 1984 by O'Hare
International Airport of Chicago on behalf of United Airlines. The
bonds are rated as junk by S&AMP;P because the airline, not the city,
stands behind the revenues generated from lease payments on landing
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our belief is that if United misses a payment, there will be
countless other airlines lining up to take those gates and make
those payments,'' Conlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The bonds are callable on May 1, 1999, at $103 per $100 face
amount. The fund bought them last month for a price that gives an
effective yield to the call date of 4.8 percent. ``If we were to go
buy a money market security we'd get 3.25 percent, and here we're
getting 4.8 percent,'' Conlin said. ``This is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The men see themselves as value investors who aim to buy
cheaply, usually because a bond is under a cloud for some reason.
``We buy things when they're down,'' Conlin said. ``Then we're very
patient. We both understand it takes a lot of time for your credit
stories to play out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
