<HEADLINE>
VECCHIONE TO HEAD LIFESPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lifespan Inc. said Friday it has tapped George A. Vecchione  &UR;  &LR; to
be its next chief executive, effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Vecchione, 51, is executive vice president in charge of network
development for the New York and Presbyterian Healthcare System, a
network of 28 hospitals. He will replace William Kreykes, who will
become vice chairman of Lifespan.
</P>
<P>
   Lifespan, based in Providence, R.I., owns five hospitals,
including New England Medical Center in Boston. The company lost
$14 million from operations in its fiscal year ending last October.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Kreykes requested that Lifespan's board develop a
succession plan.
</P>
<P>
   Vecchione helped usher in the January merger between New York
Hospital and Presbyterian Hospital to create New York City's
largest medical center, with about $1.5 billion in yearly revenue
and 12,400 employees. The merger was unusual in that it involved
major teaching hospitals of two prominent medical schools. New York
Hospital, a 1,077-bed facility, is the principal teaching hospital
for Cornell University Medical School, while Presbyterian Hospital,
a 1,093-bed facility, works with Columbia College of Physicians and
Surgeons. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been some deficits in recent months and years'' at
Lifespan, Vecchione acknowledged in an interview Friday. ``But that
is a condition I'm very used to dealing with. In New York, many
hospitals have financial trouble, especially the academic medical
centers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fortunate to have a person with such a strong
background in academic medicine,'' said Dr. Thomas O'Donnell, chief
executive of NEMC.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said Vecchione's experience in New York will serve him
well at Lifespan, whose hospitals also have ties to two medical
schools, Tufts University and Brown University schools of medicine.
In addition, New York City, like the Boston area, is home to
numerous world-class medical centers, all fiercely competing with
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an eminent guy from an extraordinarily prestigious
institution,'' said Thomas Reardon, a health care attorney with
Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky &AMP; Popeo.
</P>
<P>
   But because Boston has a more aggressive and competitive managed
care insurance market, Vecchione will ``have his work cut out for
him,'' Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   Vecchione is the second chief executive in recent months to be
plucked from outside the region to lead New England hospitals. Dr.
James L. Reinertsen &UR;  &LR; , head of HealthSystem Minnesota, will next
month become CEO of CareGroup, which owns Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a changing of the guards,'' said Ann Thornburg of
Coopers &AMP; Lybrand in Boston. ``New leaders all want to make their
mark, and that means big changes in the equilibrium. Stay tuned.''
</P>
<P>
   Vecchione, a certified public accountant who owns two race
horses, was born in Queens, New York, the son of a postal worker.
He went St. Francis College in Brooklyn and received a masters
degree in health care administration from Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute in Troy, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
