<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-ELECT-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES COMMITTED TO NORTH IRELAND PEACE WINNING, BUT BARELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Parties committed to the Northern
Ireland peace settlement emerged winners in the election for the
new Assembly on Friday, but candidates opposed to the accord won
enough seats to call into question the value of that victory.
</P>
<P>
   The results showed that the province's two biggest parties, the
Ulster Unionist Party of David Trimble and the Social Democratic
and Labor Party of John Hume, would get the chance to fulfill their
historic pledge to work together to end the sectarian conflict that
has cost more than 3200 lives since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   But the ongoing count of the ballots from Thursday's election,
which will not be completed until Saturday, was exposing deep
divisions in Trimble's support as many party members deserted him
to cast their votes for Protestant candidates wary of the
cooperation with Catholics called for in the peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The split in the vote came only among Protestants, as the other
Catholic party besides Hume's, Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
Irish Republican Army, also supports the peace plan and ran
strongly. Its president, Gerry Adams, an easy winner in his West
Belfast district, will become a minister in the Assembly's 12-man
executive.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed results, reflecting fiercely held political and
community convictions, placed in doubt the prospects for a
smooth-running legislature, the centerpiece of the new
constitutional arrangements aimed at bringing stability to this
long-troubled province.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been as great a success as we would have wanted, but
it is enough to enable us to move forward and progress,'' said
Trimble, who most likely will be the speaker of the Assembly.
``It's just that we have to continue to drag behind us this dead
weight of people who have difficulty moving into the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The accord called for the creation of the Assembly to return
local government to Northern Ireland after 27 years of direct rule
from London, and it structured the body under a strict
power-sharing formula.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, agreed to on April 10 after 26 months of
negotiations, also laid out other provisions to try to bring
Northern Ireland's long warring Protestant and Catholic communities
together. In referendums May 22 in Ireland and Northern Ireland, it
was endorsed by an overwhelming number of Catholics but only a
slight majority of Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble in recent weeks had sought to win over reluctant
Protestants, abruptly transforming himself from a tribal politician
defending the diminishing Protestant majority in Northern Ireland
to a leader daring to talk of forming inclusive government and
reaching accommodations with Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   Six of his nine Ulster Unionist colleagues in the British
Parliament, however, failed to back him, and the Protestant
politicians who voted no in the referendum, led by the gruff
preacher Ian Paisley, vowed to elect enough people to the
108-member Assembly to frustrate its efforts to share authority
with Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   The election was conducted under a complicated ``single
transferable vote'' procedure which is designed to guarantee
proportional representation. Voters filled in the names of up to 20
candidates in the order of their preference. Friday's count first
tabulated all the first preferences and then moved on to figuring
out who the closest finishers were and how many surplus votes from
the winners could be ``transferred'' to them to gain them election.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the complexity of the ballot, the tabulation was
going slowly with only one third of the voter choices counted by 11
p.m. when the tabulation stopped for the night. A BBC forecast
showed the Ulster Unionists with 30 seats, the Social Democratic
and Labor Party with 24, the Democratic Unionists with 20, Sinn
Fein with 17, and the other 17 going to smaller parties. The
network said the anti-agreement forces accounted for 29 seats, one
shy of the number felt necessary to give them the power to obstruct
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to nail the hide of Trimble and the hide of
Blair, two liars, to the fence,'' Paisley said with jubilation as
he followed the count from his North Antrim district. British Prime
Minister Tony Blair was a sponsor of the peace talks that led to
the settlement and had tried to shore up Trimble when he came under
attack from dissident Unionists.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As he followed the results in his Upper Bann district, Trimble
said: ``I hoped we were making progress since the referendum, but
it might even be we are slipping back a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Adams expressed concern at the dents in Trimble's
leadership. ``The Unionist vote has shredded, and that's
regrettable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Assembly's early obligations is to create a
cross-border council that will bring together members of the
government of Ireland and the new government of Northern Ireland.
Paisley and his followers have vowed to stymie that, saying today
that they intended to ``destroy the pan-Nationalist front.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist is the term for people, largely Catholic, who seek
eventual absorption into Ireland, the nation to the south.
Unionists are those, mostly Protestant, who favor remaining within
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Campbell, a member of Paisley's Democratic Unionist
Party, who won a seat from Londonderry, said: ``Anything in the
Assembly that is likely to lead us closer to the Republic of
Ireland, we will block, will vote against and we will endeavor to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The new speaker, known as the ``first minister'', and his deputy
will be chosen next week at a preliminary meeting of he Assembly.
The likely pair are Trimble, though in a far weaker state than he
had hoped, and Hume.
</P>
<P>
   What appeared to have cost Trimble support were disputes in
recent weeks over when disarmament of paramilitary groups like the
Irish Republican Army would begin and whether paramilitary
prisoners would continue to gain early release in the absence of
any guns being turned in. His critics said that without firmer
conditions governing those two matters than existed in the final
settlement document, members of parties like Sinn Fein that are
linked to paramilitary groups could take office in the new Northern
Ireland government without making any permanent commitment to
ending violence.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein has pledged itself to the principle of nonviolence,
and the IRA has maintained a cease fire for nearly a year. But in a
place where mistrust is so deep and the memory of bloodshed is so
fresh, these steps and Trimble's calm reassurances and lunge for
the statesmanlike stance have not dissuaded opponents from their
blocking tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions in the assembly will require majority support from
both the Protestant and Catholic blocs in an arrangement designed
to forestall sectarian exploitation. But it also makes the body
susceptible to obstruction by Protestant politicians opposed to
carrying out the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Hume's party succeeded in turning back a bid from Sinn Fein to
cut into its position as the largest Catholic party. In recent
elections, Sinn Fein had been capturing more and more of the
Catholic vote, but it was Hume and his party that made gains this
time at the expense of Sinn Fein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
