<HEADER>
A9378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-US-SAMPSON-BOS &LR;      06-26 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-SAMPSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US COACH RESPONDS TO CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ US soccer coach Steve Sampson, who had said
repeatedly that he would not criticize his players publicly, lashed
back at three-time World Cup veteran Tab Ramos Friday as the
winless team left for home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here is an individual I essentially held a spot open for eight
or nine months,'' Sampson said about Ramos, who had vowed he'd
never play for the coach again after being benched for Thursday
night's finale against Yugoslavia. ``I played Tab in the most
critical match against Iran. Tab was responsible for the first goal
against us. It's unfair he feels free to voice his opinion about me
when I gave him so much respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramos, who had played in every Cup match in 1990 and 1994, was
questionable for this year's roster after tearing up the same knee
twice in less than a year. But Sampson, citing Ramos's value to the
team over the years, had promised he would hold a spot open for him
as long as he could. Ramos ended up coming off the bench for the
final 20 minutes against Germany after the US was already behind,
2-0, and being replaced after 57 minutes against Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Also outspoken Friday were defenders Alexi Lalas and Jeff Agoos,
who were the only field players not to get playing time. Lalas, one
of the team's most recognizable players with his flowing red hair
and goatee, had played every minute in 1994 and competed in 12 of
the 16 qualifying matches. Agoos, who burned his training gear when
he was cut from the 1994 team, had played more minutes than anybody
else during qualifying. But two blatant errors _ a giveaway that
provided Jamaica with a 1-1 tie in a critical home match and a red
card that forced the US to play a man down for the final 58 minutes
at Mexico _ caused Agoos's stock to plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Once Sampson went to a 3-6-1 formation with only three defenders
and brought in newly naturalized citizen David Regis just two weeks
before the team left for France, Lalas and Agoos were virtually
doomed to the bench. So was defender Marcelo Balboa, who had more
caps (127) than any other US player in history but played only a
token eight minutes at the end of the Yugoslavia match.
</P>
<P>
   ``You earn the right to represent your country every time you
step on the field,'' said Sampson. ``No one should feel they have
the right to represent their country. That right is earned every
single day.''
</P>
<P>
   Though US Soccer Federation president Alan Rothenberg had denied
reports that the players had been threatened with retribution if
they made their unhappiness public, Sampson said the dissidents
would be fined for ``bringing the federation into disrepute'' with
their comments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
