<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-EDUCATION-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN CONTINUE TO OUTPACE MEN IN EARNING COLLEGE DIPLOMAS, CENSUS
BUREAU SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release 12:01 a.m. Monday, June 29)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The number of women with college degrees continued
to outpace men last year, while young blacks have erased their
historic gap with whites in earning high school diplomas, a new
Census Bureau study says.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be released Monday, the bureau also said the
number of Hispanic students with high school diplomas grew,
although the graduation rate lags considerably behind other ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 29 percent of women ages 25 to 29 had earned at least
one college degree, whereas 26 percent of young men had completed a
college education, the annual report said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, 24 percent of men and women 25 to 29 had at least one
college degree, but women began gaining a year later and that trend
continues, the Census Bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect women will continue to be a majority because men, as
well as women, are convinced that a middle-class family needs two
wage earners. They both want to see her bring home a good secure
paycheck ... there is continual pressure to get as much education
as they can,'' said Geraldine Clifford, a retired professor of
education at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Men dominated the ranks of students receiving diplomas for many
years, but significant changes in college attendance for women have
been recorded for 30 or more years.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Day, author of the Census report, said women's
achievement in education is a ``straight line going up ... in terms
of this particular issue, they are on par and succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, 12.7 percent of women 25 to 29 had attended and
completed college, whereas 18.3 percent of men in the same age
group had earned at least one degree.
</P>
<P>
   In the next decade, college graduation rates for each sex had
grown at the same pace _ 10 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   But the percentage of men receiving college diplomas fell in the
1980s. And by 1990, the sexes were even.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford attributed much of the increase for women over the
years to changing attitudes about their role in the workplace. In
addition, anti-discrimination legislation such as Title IX gave
women more opportunities in education.
</P>
<P>
   In the overall population, men still hold the majority of the
college diplomas, but Clifford said that would change as more and
more women graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The education gap between black and Caucasian high school
graduates no longer exists, based a survey of those 25 to 29. Among
both races, an average of 87 percent had completed high school, the
1997 report said.
</P>
<P>
   The high school graduation rate among young African Americans
grew about 3 percentage points in the previous decade while the
rate for whites grew 1.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Hispanics who had received a high school diploma
grew from 51 percent to 55 percent between 1987 and 1997. In the
same period, the number of Hispanics who had earned a college
diploma increased from 22 percent to 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of high school completion for Hispanics is considerably
less than the nationwide average of 82 percent, but Day said the
discrepancy was due in large part to the foreign-born Hispanic
population.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, 43 percent of foreign-born Hispanics
hold a high school diploma, while 70 percent of native-born Latinos
have finished their secondary schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Among Asian Americans, 84.9 percent had earned high school
diplomas, according to the 1997 figures, while 50 percent of those
25 to 29 had earned a college degree.
</P>
<P>
   Education levels varied from region to region as well, with
Alaska and Wyoming maintaining the highest levels of high school
completion _ more than 90 percent of the young people in those
states had earned a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The District of Columbia, Maryland and Massachusetts surpassed
the national college completion average of 23 percent, with an
average of 33 percent of young adults in those areas holding
college diplomas.
</P>
</TEXT>
