<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND STOCK FALLS IN NHL ENTRY DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Business used to be good, booming. When it came
to sending top talent to the National Hockey League's entry draft,
New England once was a cottage industry.
</P>
<P>
   It was hottest of all in the early 1980s. In a span of 24
months, Bob Carpenter of Peabody, Mass., dubbed The Can't-Miss Kid,
was selected third overall by the Washington Capitals in 1981, and
the Minnesota North Stars in '83 made Brian Lawton of Woonsocket,
R.I., the first American ever to be selected No. 1. New England was
first in seafood and a close second on frozen ponds.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened down there?'' Jim Gregory, the National Hockey
League's vice president of hockey operations, recently mused. ``It
seems we used to go down there and just drool over the talent. It
doesn't seem quite the same anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinions vary regarding our good New England stock gone bad.
There are those who contend that the six-state region is doing just
fine, thanks, as shown by the likes of Bryan Berard of Woonsocket
going first overall in 1995 and Paul Mara of Belmont (Mass.) Hill
being taken seventh by the Tampa Bay Lightning last year, one slot
ahead of the Bruins' Sergei Samsonov, who Thursday night was
crowned the 1997-98 rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are still plenty of good players in New
England,'' said Mara's agent, Jay Fee. ``I'd be more concerned if I
didn't see these kids making it to the NHL. But draft position
aside, I'd say look at the overall success some of them have had
... the job (Boston University's) Mike Grier's done in Edmonton,
and I think Joe Hulbig (of Wrentham, Mass.) will make an impact for
them, too. I think the talent's still there. Kids like (Chris)
Drury, (Tom) Poti, and (Chris) Kelleher (all from BU) are going to
make an impact in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   For those keeping track in the six-state region, here are the
draft positions of the aforementioned native sons: Grier (219/'93),
Hulbig (13/'92), Drury (72/'94), Poti (59/'96), and Kelleher
(130/'93).
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given it a lot of thought,'' said another
Boston-based agent, Bob Murray, whose client list includes Medford,
Mass., superstar scorer Keith Tkachuk. ``These things tend to go in
cycles, fits and spurts, and why that is, I can't tell you.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
A lean crop
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The NHL holds its annual teenage lovefest Saturday here at
Marine Midland Arena, and New Englanders won't play a very
prominent part in the picture. The highest-rated local is Bobby
Allen, the 6-foot-1-inch defenseman from Hull, Mass., who helped
Boston College reach the NCAA final this year. The NHL's Central
Scouting staff ranks Allen No. 34 among all North American
defensemen and forwards. Factoring in Europeans and all goalies,
home and abroad, Allen still could be there for the taking when the
Bruins make their first pick at No. 46. He also could shift higher
or lower, depending on everything from individual teams' needs to
barometric pressure over Lake Erie. In other words, it isn't
exactly a science, folks.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth time in the last seven years, New England won't
place someone from Our Town among the top 10 NHL prospects. It's a
stark and striking contrast to 1986, for instance, when Connecticut
had two of its own _ Brian Leetch and Craig Janney _ hear their
names called within the first 13 picks. Another example: the same
year Lawton was selected No. 1, Tom Barrasso of Acton-Boxboro
(Mass.) went No. 5 to the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do acknowledge the downturn in homegrown talent aren't
sure of its root cause. Some agree with Murray, that it is simply
cyclical, and believe New England again shall rise from beneath the
rink. Others suggest that while Canadian junior players have
maintained their solid foothold in the draft, Americans have been
muscled and finessed off the puck by their teenage counterparts
from Russia, Sweden, Finland, and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, we've found out that the Can't-Miss Kid of '98
most likely doesn't live next door. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Excess baggage?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The reason? One large school of thought is that too much hockey
is not a good thing and too many American teenagers are putting in
excessive, unproductive time on skates. By no means has the
six-state region seen a downturn in the numbers of young men
playing hockey, but some experts believe some of the best players,
those who are often projected as potential stars by their early or
mid-teens, place themselves on an unending treadmill of game after
game, playing hockey 12 months a year without a break, not
necessarily seeing their skills improve and sometimes losing their
passion for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season's so long, it takes the sparkle out of the sport
for some of these kids,'' said Ben Smith, the longtime college
coach from Gloucester, Mass., who directed the US women's squad to
the Olympic gold medal in Nagano and was an assistant coach with
the US men's Olympic squad in '88. ``You find these young men who
want to get the exposure, be noticed by scouts, and they're out
there in June or July playing in a three-game tournament for all
the marbles. One week later, they're in another tournament for all
the marbles. Well, gee, how many marbles are there?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
