<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EXPANSION-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION DRAFT SENDS DEVIL GOALIE MIKE DUNHAM TO NASHVILLE
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Goalie Mike Dunham used to be a Devil, and now
he is a Nashville Predator. People can conjure in their minds the
image of a devil. But what figure represents a Predator?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know,'' Dunham said with a smile after being chosen
as one of Nashville's first 26 players in Friday's expansion draft.
Judging by the front of the jersey he wore, Dunham said: ``It's an
animal with a big tooth.'' But, he added: ``If I had to explain it
to school kids, I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A team official said the beast, which is gold, blue, silver and
orange, is a saber-toothed tiger. Dunham, the only selection to
appear here and wear the jersey, is one of the players likely to
stay in Nashville. He said he is happy about the prospect of
playing more games after serving as backup to Martin Brodeur for
the last two seasons and making only 41 National Hockey League
appearances. Although General Manager David Poile announced 25
other names, he also said he expects to make trades soon.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the shuffle is that Poile chose six free
agents from other teams, including Mike Richter of the Rangers, who
can become an unrestricted free agent on July 1. Should Richter or
the other free agents sign with other teams, the Predators would
have the rights to any compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In Richter's case, it would be not directly from the team
signing him but as an at-large pick added to next summer's entry
draft, probably in the second round. Neil Smith, president and
general manager of the Rangers, said Friday he would ask Poile and
the league if it is legal for Smith to negotiate with Richter
before July 1, in that it is unlikely that Poile will offer Richter
the multi-year contract he wants ($5 to $7 million per year with a
no-trade clause).
</P>
<P>
   Last season, in similar circumstances, Smith's Rangers lost Mark
Messier through unrestricted free agency to the Vancouver Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, unless he signs before then, the Rangers could lose
defenseman Brian Leetch through the same process. Jay Grossman,
agent for Leetch, said this week that he has talked casually about
Leetch with Smith but that no formal negotiations have begun. Under
the collective bargaining agreement, veterans over 31 have strong
free-agency leverage that increases during their final contract
seasons, a dynamic that still seems to escape some team executives.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders lost defenseman J.J. Daigneault to the Predators.
Mike Milbury, general manager of the Islanders, said: ``We knew we
would lose a good player, but it's tough to lose J.J. He filled an
important role. We're looking at ways to fill that role.''
Daigneault joined the Islanders on Feb. 6 in a trade with Anaheim.
Milbury also is seeking to hire an associate coach to run the bench
while he maintains the official title of head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury said earlier this week that Ted Nolan, former coach of
the Sabres, had taken his name out of consideration. However, Nolan
appeared on the scene Friday seeking a meeting with Milbury. An
Islanders spokesman, Chris Botta, said the two would probably meet.
</P>
<P>
   The other unrestricted free agents chosen by the Predators are
Uwe Krupp of Colorado and Rob Zettler of Toronto. The restricted
free agents are Patrick Cote of Dallas, Chris Armstrong of Florida
and Andrew Brunette of Washington. Of the players under contract,
the best-known names are Doug Brown of Detroit, Tony Hrkac of
Pittsburgh, Mikhal Shtalenkov of Anaheim and Al Iafrate of San
Jose. Because the Devils and Rangers both technically lost goalies
Friday, neither can lose a goalie next year, when another draft is
held to stock the Atlanta team.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's draft is the preliminary to Saturday's entry draft of
18-year-olds. The Rangers will choose seventh on the first round,
the Islanders ninth and the Devils 26th. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9388 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NENGLAND-ENTRY-2N     06-26 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NENGLAND-ENTRY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BUFFALO, N.Y.: ... are there?  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Some of them just aren't getting a break, and it doesn't seem
like they're getting any better, either. Maybe they just don't need
to be playing 13 months a year. They get locked in that syndrome,
you know: `I got to make the doughnuts.' After a while, the fun's
out of it. And when you lose your passion for something, you lose
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Look at Leetch, said Smith, and you see a hockey athlete who
``just loves to play the game.'' Ditto Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know Bobby Carpenter well,'' said Smith. ``But he must
love the game. Everything he's been through, including some pretty
serious injuries (including a shattered kneecap in his Bruins
days), and being a superstar in the NHL for a while, to going out
there and just playing his rear end off year after year. Now some
people will say he's like that just for the money, but I'd say,
(`Ridiculous'). Hey, no one ever got a better lesson in that that I
just did, from 20 girls. They went out and played hockey for one
reason _ passion for the game _ in a time when a lot of them were
told, `Hey, forget hockey, that's a boys' game. Get off the rink.'
They played because they loved it, pure and simple, and I can tell
you there are a lot of guys playing who don't share that same
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Massachusetts men, Dan Esdale and Bob Richardson, are strong
advocates of getting top teenage hockey players out of skates for a
number of weeks each year in hopes that they'll perform better when
the puck is dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Esdale, a regional director for USA Hockey, feels New England
teenagers were better-rounded athletes in the '60s and '70s, even
into the '80s. They played a wider array of sports. A hockey
athlete might also have played football in the fall and baseball in
the spring. It still happens, but not as much. The serious hockey
player gets mainstreamed almost upon puberty, sets his eyes on the
net, and doesn't look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our kids got into hockey 12 months a year,'' said Esdale,
``we gave up. We lost our athletes. We said just one thing too
often: `Play.' We did the games, which is what Canada did, too, but
we stopped taking breaks _ and you need those breaks for physical
and mental reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, a longtime hockey booster in the inner city and a
part-time scout for the Dallas Stars, is disheartened when he sees
local kids playing ``12 months times 12 months times 12 months. And
if it did (help), I'd be encouraging them to do it, because I'm in
the hockey business. But it doesn't work for the kids and it
doesn't work for the parents, who get caught up in believing
they've got to get their kid in some Canadian tournament, at a cost
of, say, $3,000, just so they're `seen.' They get bled dry, and for
what? So their kid can squeeze in 12 minutes of hockey? Forget
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Esdale and Richardson have helped form and shape the
Massachusetts Satellite Training Program, encouraging top hockey
athletes to emphasize off-ice training in the summer, augmented
with limited playing time. Both men feel that European players long
ago subscribed to off-ice training, getting away from the game, and
have seen their skills develop faster and better than their
American counterparts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alternative avenues
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Local young men who have developed into top draft prospects in
recent years also have jiggled to the top of Central Scouting's
list via significant change in routes. In the days of Carpenter and
Lawton, high school hockey did the trick. Carpenter went to St.
John's Prep in Danvers, Mass., and Lawton to Mount St. Charles in
Woonscocket. They weren't getting the megadose of games that the
Canadian Junior A kids were getting, but they were winning the ink
and praise of the media, as well as capturing the admiring eye of
Central Scouting.
</P>
<P>
   In recent drafts, however, the New England kids deemed best and
brightest by Central Scouting have tuned up in Junior A for at
least one year leading up to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of '94, at age 17, Berard left high school hockey
and played two seasons for Detroit in the Ontario Hockey League.
Some nine months after leaving home, he was chosen No. 1 overall by
the Senators, who later swapped him to the Islanders. The only
other New Englander to go in the first round in '95, goaltender
Brian Boucher, also from Woonsocket, spent the 1994-95 season
playing for Tri-City in the Western Hockey League. After one season
there, he was chosen 22d overall by the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   Mara, the other blue-chip prospect from New England, bid adieu
to Belmont Hill on the eve of his 17th birthday in '96 and played
for Sudbury in the Ontario Hockey League. The following spring, he
was the Lightning's top pick, and he could be ticketed for the
Tampa Bay defense within three months.
</P>
<P>
   For now, if you're from New England, Junior A appears to be the
way. USA Hockey also has structured an elite program in Ann Arbor,
Mich., which this fall for a second time will bring in many of the
country's best teenagers for a full season of training and playing
under national coach Jeff Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Ron DeGregorio of Salem, N.H., among those who spearheaded the
formation of the national program, said it was formed partially in
response to the Canadian junior system.
</P>
<P>
   ``It allows some of our kids to seek their dream here,'' said
DeGregorio. ``Over time, it may be a percursor to (Canadian) Tier 1
or Tier 2 hockey, with each player keeping his eligibility intact.
Education is still very important, a very important element. I
think some (American) kids have felt a need that they have to catch
up with the Canadians, and now other countries, and they think
because of that, they have to play all year. But there are some
good US players _ Kevin Stevens (Pembroke, Mass.) and John LeClair
(St. Albans, Vt.) _ who dispel that myth. In both cases, they took
up the game late and they played other sports, too, and they made
it work. Hockey doesn't have to be everything you do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
