   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-HARASS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court makes it
significantly harder for private and public employers to defend
themselves against sexual harassment charges by claiming they were
unaware of what lower-level supervisors were doing. By DAN
FREEDMAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   SECRET-SERVICE (Washington) _ The Clinton administration tries
to convince three skeptical appeals court judges to exempt Secret
Service officers from having to tell a grand jury what they know
about the president's relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. JOHN C. HENRY. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   HORMEL-NOMINATION (Washington) _ Senate Republican leaders have
put gay issues onto the front burner by denying a vote on James
Hormel, President Clinton's nominee to be ambassador to Luxembourg.
Critics say the former University of Chicago law dean and
businessman shouldn't get the job because he has actively pushed
gay issues, while supporters accuse the GOP of pandering to
religious conservatives. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DISSIDENTS (Beijing) _ President Clinton responds
cautiously to the Chinese government's ham-handed roundup of
prominent dissidents in the opening days of his historic visit. The
president said the arrests underline the importance of his policy
of engaging China. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKES (Beijing) _ When Clinton and Chinese leader Jiang
Zemin sit down for formal leader-to-leader talks, one of the
central questions will be how to cooperate to limit proliferation
and export of nuclear technology. By CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-YELTSIN (Paris) _ With Boris Yeltsin's government caught
in a deepening economic morass as interest rates have risen to 150
percent, some analysts fear that the vast Russian Federation may be
stretched to the breaking point and could even split apart. By
BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LUCAS-EXECUTION (Austin, Texas) _ Gov. George W. Bush is
reviewing the Texas parole board's recommendation that serial
killer Henry Lee Lucas be spared execution Tuesday. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   LUCAS-LAURA (Houston) _ Life for Laura Jean Donez, 16, was just
beginning when it ended, brutally, in April 1983. The horror of her
death remains fresh for her sisters, and Thursday's decision by the
Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles to recommend sparing the life of
her killer, Henry Lee Lucas, has devastated them. By SUSAN
BARDWELL.
</P>
