</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Beijing) _ As a candidate in 1992, Bill Clinton
accused President George Bush of ``coddling'' the regime. But as
president, Clinton has basically followed his predecessor's lead on
engaging the Asian giant on everything from trade to security
issues. An overview of Clinton's 180-degree turn on China policy.
By CRAGG HINES. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-REBELS (Ahuacachahue, Mexico) _ Two years after rebels of
the leftist Popular Revolutionary Army appeared in Guerrero state,
the guerrilla organization is growing in Mexico's rural south. The
recent army attack on a school in the village of El Charco, where
the rebels and their supporters were staying after a meeting,
points to the attraction that the group holds for many of Mexico's
rural poor. By DUDLEY ALTHAUS. (Already filed; art available on New
York Times photo service)
</P>
