<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON TRIMS CONSTRUCTION UNIT; CHIEF RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. said Friday that it had laid off 1,500 workers from
its struggling engineering and construction unit, 500 more than the
company originally expected when it announced cutbacks at the
division in January.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Raytheon said that the head of the subsidiary had
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Q. Miller, the 52-year-old chairman and chief executive
of Raytheon Engineers &AMP; Constructors in Cambridge, Mass., quit ``to
pursue personal interests,'' the company said. The move casts a
further cloud over the unit's struggle to restructure amid a drop
in business.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon appointed Shay D. Assad, 48, currently E&AMP;C's president
and chief operating officer and a 21-year company veteran, to
replace Miller on an acting basis. &UR;  &LR; Miller had been at
Lexington-based Raytheon for 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   The shake-up at E&AMP;C, which has been fighting to survive amid
defense industry cutbacks &UR;  &LR; and Asia's economic turmoil, comes just
one week after Raytheon selected Daniel P. Burnham, vice chairman
of aerospace giant AlliedSignal Inc., as president and future
successor to Raytheon chairman and chief executive Dennis Picard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck has made a personal decision to resign,'' Raytheon
spokesman Robert S. McWade said. He declined to say whether Miller,
who leaves on July 2, had been asked to leave &UR;  &LR; or &UR;  &LR; if his departure
was related to Burnham's appointment. Miller had been seen both
inside and outside the company as a potential successor to Picard.
</P>
<P>
   McWade, who said E&AMP;C had laid off 1,500 workers so far this
year, also declined to say if there would be further job losses at
the unit. The cuts are part of an across-the-board trimming of more
than 9 percent of Raytheon's total work force as the company seeks
to convert more of its defense technology into commercial
applications. &UR;  &LR; The company employees 119,000 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, the world's third largest aerospace company, has
doubled in size in recent years through acquisitions of the defense
units of Texas Instruments Inc. and General Motors Corp.'s Hughes
Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   E&AMP;C faces a drop in its business of building and operating
large-scale industrial projects ranging from nuclear power plants
and airports to roads and food-processing facilities. Most of the
unit's customers are overseas, and Asia's woes have depressed
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not lived up to what they thought they would do,''
said analyst Paul H. Nisbet of JSA Research Inc. in Newport, R.I.
``There seems to be an underlying, systemic problem that is also an
industry-wide problem.''
</P>
<P>
   With $2 billion in revenues last year, the unit accounted for
nearly 10 percent of Raytheon's $21 billion in revenues and around
5 percent of its profits.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon class B shares rose 1 15/16 Friday on the New York
Stock Exchange to close at 56 7/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
