<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AIDS-CASES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE RECORDS STEEP DROP IN AIDS CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Officials this week reported an unprecedented 46
percent decline in new AIDS cases last year, and said they expect
continued progress as a result of the AIDS drugs, more prevention
efforts and a more finely tuned reporting system.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors reported 466 new cases of the disease last year,
compared to 863 the previous year. New cases have been dropping
steadily since 1993, but the annual decreases have been nowhere
near as steep as last year's
</P>
<P>
   ``Primarily,'' said Dr. Howard Koh, commisioner for the state
Department of Public Health, the decline in new cases is due to
``the new triple drug therapies and state of the art cocktails.''
Other factors he cited were ``better medical care of the entire
patient, access to care for HIV-positive individuals, and education
on safe sex, condoms, and needle exchange.''
</P>
<P>
   A new reporting system should also help, Koh said. Until now,
officials have tracked the spread of the deadly disease through new
diagnoses of the full-blown disease AIDS. However, last February,
public health officials acted to require tracking of the HIV
infection that precedes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get a handle on the number who are nowhere close to
AIDS,'' Koh said. ``The new surveillance system is going to be
really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Koh said he expects the system to be designed by fall and
implemented early next year. ``It will be one of the few in the
nation to use unique identifiers, not personal names,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want an environment where people feel they can trust the
medical system and have as many come forward as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Once doctors start reporting HIV _ not just full blown AIDS _
authorities will be able to track trends in infection and pinpoint
where prevention efforts are working, and where they are still
needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, said Linda Warren-Kato, a spokesperson for the
state's AIDS bureau, public health officials ``can make sure we're
putting our prevention dollar where infection seems to be going,
and make sure our infrastructure is there for people who are going
to be needing them five, six, seven years down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the disease takes more than ten years to develop
from infection to AIDS diagnosis. And time is frequently lost
between infection and HIV testing.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, more than 13,600 people have full-blown AIDS.
And health department experts estimate there are more than 36,000
HIV-infected individuals, many of whom are unaware that they are
infected.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans have a disproportionate incidence of AIDS, Koh
said. While they make up just 5 percent of the state population, 32
percent of new AIDS diagnoses in 1997 were among African Americans,
an increase from 26 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   There is particular fear among African Americans of finding out
HIV status, ``and fear of the stigma of HIV,'' Koh said. ``Our
message is that this disease is treatable and ultimately
preventable.''
</P>
<P>
   So Friday, Koh kicked off a mass media campaign to encourage
African Americans in particular to get free, confidential testing
in centers throughout the state. Through its ACT NOW program, the
state also offers free primary health care to people who are
uninsured, low-income, and HIV positive. They can call a special
Hotline at 1-888-I-ACT-NOW.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
