<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GM-STRIKE-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      06-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-STRIKE-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HARD FOR EITHER SIDE IN GM STRIKE TO CLAIM VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. _ Losses to General Motors Corp. and members of the
United Automobile Workers union from strikes at two parts factories
here have soared far beyond the actual money involved at the
factories, making it harder with each passing day for either side
to paint an eventual settlement as a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts now estimate GM's after-tax costs from the
strikes at $1 billion, and rising by $75 million a day, while the
UAW's members have lost more than $150 million in pay.
</P>
<P>
   Based on previous strikes, GM and its workers can expect to
recoup up to half their losses through extra production and
overtime pay in the months after the strikes. But the rest of the
losses are likely to be permanent, as customers buy Ford
Expeditions and Toyota Camrys instead of Chevrolet Suburbans and
Luminas.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the issues in the Flint strike negotiations involve
sums in the tens of millions of dollars. But as the strikes
lengthen, each side has also begun to see them as a showdown over
the future course of labor-management relations at the world's
largest automaker, making it much harder to settle.
</P>
<P>
   For the UAW to declare victory after the strikes, it must be
able to reassure members that it is doing as much as possible to
slow GM's steady elimination of jobs in the United States. But the
union faces a difficult task in controlling the expectations of
workers who, much more than the union's leadership, see the strikes
as a way to force GM to back away from its plans to expand
production overseas.
</P>
<P>
   GM faces a more difficult task. It must convince skeptical
institutional investors and Wall Street analysts that a settlement
in Flint will allow it to shrink its work force at other factories
without further costly strikes. ``I want to be able to sleep at
night knowing that GM can downsize without having a strike,'' said
Nicholas Lobaccaro, an auto analyst at Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with steady increases in earnings, quarter after
quarter, have been rewarded by Wall Street with fast-rising share
prices. Mainly because of 16 strikes over the last five years, GM's
quarterly earnings have zigzagged unpredictably, with record
profits alternating with heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
   With the UAW now threatening strikes in Indiana and Ohio after
any settlement in Flint, GM's stock has been weakening, and its
price has dropped 11.4 percent since the first strike June 5, even
as the share price at its rival Ford Motor Co. has risen 6.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts assert that GM needs to shrink its work
force because the automaker's uninspiring designs are capturing a
shrinking share of the market. GM held 40 percent of the market a
decade ago but has been bouncing around 30 percent in the last
year.
</P>
<P>
   That means GM needs to produce about 1.5 million fewer vehicles
even in good years, so fewer workers are needed. GM closed some
factories during the last recession in the early 1990s, but still
has the manufacturing capacity and work force to supply 35 percent
of the market, rather than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Auto analysts look at these figures and want the strikes to end
with an acknowledgment by the UAW that GM is in trouble. ``What is
necessary is a public recognition by the union leadership, that is
communicated to the rank and file, that GM's situation is serious
enough that we need to all collectively work together to put the
company back on a competitive footing,'' said Joseph Phillippi at
Lehman Brothers, who predicted Friday that the strikes could last
at least until mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   GM has taken the unusual step in the strikes of publicly
criticizing the union's leadership in a bid to convince UAW members
that the company has a problem. Thursday, GM gave local television
stations a videotape in which a top Flint factory manager explained
how inefficient work practices cost the company money.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy has predictably infuriated top UAW officials, who
were angry at GM even before the strike. Union leaders have said
for months that workers are punished for bad decision making by GM
executives, such as the company's only now getting around to
developing a sport utility vehicle and a mid-size sedan for Saturn,
its most successful brand. The union has also been upset that GM is
trying to cut costs while still making some profits and paying top
executives large bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontational stance of GM executives has been the last
straw for the union. ``You've got some heroes in GM that are all of
a sudden becoming stars and want to talk about they're going to do
this and do that _ they're just not making any sense whatsoever,''
said UAW president Stephen Yokich on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   But the union's only weapon for fighting the company is a blunt
one that hurts workers, too. A strong economy appears to have
produced very strong auto sales this month, and GM dealerships had
scant supplies of popular models when the strikes began. GM faces
further loss of market share this summer for lack of cars and light
trucks to sell. The strikes also threaten to delay GM's
introduction this fall of new full-size pickup trucks, a mainstay
of its profits.
</P>
<P>
   And union leaders in Brazil warned Friday that some huge and
highly profitable factories there might have to close soon for lack
of parts from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Workers on the picket lines in Flint recognize the costs of the
strikes on all sides and are worried about the eventual settlement.
``I don't think anybody's going to win,'' said one, Doris Motley,
an operator of computerized stamping equipment. ``They'll
compromise, but that's about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
