<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9407 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-26 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: CHAMPION OF INTERFAITH COOPERATION IS HONORED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PETER STEINFELS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Doesn't Sir Sigmund Sternberg, the British
businessman, Jewish philanthropist and inveterate promoter of
interfaith understanding, ever get tired of receiving awards?
</P>
<P>
   It may not have been the most diplomatic question to ask Sir
Sigmund, who was in New York for a ceremony at the United Nations
honoring him for receiving the $1.23 million Templeton Prize for
Progress in Religion, but it also seemed unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, when Sir Sigmund was named this year's Templeton
Prize winner, his biographical fact sheet listed more knighthoods
than there were at King Arthur's Round Table, and enough
``commanders'' and ``orders of merit'' to supply an imperial army.
The honors came from Poland, Spain, Austria, Germany, Hungary,
Greece, Sweden, Israel and the Vatican as well, of course, as
Britain and any number of international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Bell of The New York Daily News York noted, ``If he
wore all his decorations, Sir Sigmund Sternberg would look like a
comic opera admiral.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clifford Longley, a longtime religion writer in Britain,
once said of Sir Sigmund that ``an important part of his social
life seems to consist of giving and receiving medals and honors,''
adding, however, that ``he has the great merit of not taking any
part of it too seriously, though seriously enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is pretty much the way he responded Thursday morning in a
hotel room overlooking the United Nations building and the East
River. ``I don't look at these as though they were given to me, but
to the cause,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause is building the kind of contact and cooperation among
religious groups that the Hungarian-born Sir Sigmund is convinced
could have prevented the Nazi-led anti-Jewish drive from achieving
the horrors of the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not consider myself in any way more worthy than many
others,'' he said. ``I'm just lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   And practical, too. For Sir Sigmund. awards are another means to
an end. He has often told a story about his efforts, ultimately
successful, to get a group of Polish Carmelite nuns to move from
the convent they had established on the perimeter of the Auschwitz
concentration camp site. When he sought to speak to the nuns
directly, he found that they had never heard of Sir Sigmund
Sternberg. But a crumpled photograph of him standing next to Pope
John Paul II and wearing all the regalia of the knighthood the pope
had bestowed on him became his entry card for a face-to-face
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the only sign of Sir Sigmund's honors was the red and
gold rosetta of his papal knighthood worn in the lapel of a blue
blazer. He looked not a bit the comic opera admiral, but a
77-year-old businessman of slight build and medium height who sang
the praises of swimming (and the hotel pool) as his means of
keeping fit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sternberg fortune began with salvaging scrap metal in World
War II and eventually expanded into real estate and computer
software. Asked how a business leader approached interfaith
relations, he said, ``Business calls it negotiations, and religion
calls it dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it all comes to one thing: communications,'' he added.
``I'm not a theologian or academic, but as a businessman, I'm
probably more flexible. This skill in negotiation has probably been
of help to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Sigmund wants to mobilize the same skills in others. The
text of the speech he prepared for Friday night's ceremony called
``for those of us who are both in business and have a religious
faith _ if I may use the phrase _ to come out of the closet.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Sir Sigmund helped found the Institute of Business
Ethics, which has joined in supporting an earlier effort at drawing
up an interfaith code of ethics for international business based on
Christian, Muslim and Jewish teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Sigmund, a longtime supporter of the Labor Party (he
included praise for British Prime Minister Tony Blair in the text
of Friday night's remarks), wants union leaders ``welcomed on equal
terms'' in this search for common spiritual and ethical guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But his enthusiasm for nurturing like-minded spirits in the
business world does not exhaust his attention. On Thursday, the
conversation skipped from the new Councils of Christians and Jews
that he helped get under way in Eastern Europe, most recently in
Ukraine, to the Three Faiths Forum he founded with Muslim and
Christian leaders to expand the Christian-Jewish dialogue to
embrace Islam and foster a genuine three-part discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that believers sometimes have more trouble talking amiably
to differing members of their own religion than with members of
other faiths, he has floated the wry suggestion of starting a
British ``Council of Jews and Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And here is something that hasn't been reported yet,'' he
said, with the air of a man who knows journalists' susceptibility
to any scrap of novelty: A monument to Raoul Wallenberg, the
Swedish diplomat who saved the lives of 100,000 Jews in
Nazi-occupied Hungary, will be unveiled in Buenos Aires next
November. The monument, which is part of Sir Sigmund's efforts on
behalf of Wallenberg's memory, replicates one that Queen Elizabeth
II unveiled in London last year.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of the Buenos Aires monument led to Sir Sigmund's role on a
commission investigating past Nazi activities in Argentine and the
agreement of the Argentine Catholic Church to open its relevant
archives, which, in turn, led to his interest in getting the
Vatican to open archives about the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In a message prepared for the ceremony Friday night, U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan, who is married to Wallenberg's niece,
recalled participating in the unveiling of the London monument and
how ``it forced me to dwell on difficult questions''-''the dark
side of human history.''
</P>
<P>
   The world is now ``in an era in which identity politics based on
religious and ethnicity have intensified, and in which intolerance
still finds its way into textbooks and official pronouncements,''
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is remarkable individuals such as Sir Sigmund who represent
the correct and countervailing trend,'' he concluded, ``who give us
hope for the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9409 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORWAY-JEWISH-PAYMENT     06-26 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORWAY-JEWISH-PAYMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORWAY PROPOSES $60 MILLION COMPENSATION FOR JEWS WRONGED DURING
WWII
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ Norway has proposed a $60 million payment to
Norwegian Jews and international Jewish organizations as
compensation for property seized during World War II, the
government announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Norway as a nation should take collective responsibility for
what happened in our country during World War II,'' Justice
Minister Aud-Inger Aure said. ``I see it as our duty to seek a
broad, moral reconciliation and to let this be expressed
economically.''
</P>
<P>
   Before and during five years of German occupation, most of
Norway's 2,100 Jews fled to neutral Sweden. About 750 were deported
to Nazi concentration camps, where all but a handful died.
</P>
<P>
   The small number of Jews who returned after the war were given
their houses back, but most of their possessions had been
confiscated or auctioned off by the collaborationist regime of
Vidkun Quisling. Some items were taken by neighbors and never
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Jewish population numbers 1,200, of whom at least
several hundred apparently qualify for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
called the Norwegian proposal a ``shining example of moral
decency.'' He said he hoped that it would be an example for other
European countries wrestling with the issue of complicity with the
Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 16 national commissions investigating the issue of
Holocaust era assets,'' Steinberg said. ``Norway is the first to
announce a comprehensive compensation package. It has confronted
its past honestly, the dark chapters as well as the heroic
chapters, so that it can have an honorable future.''
</P>
<P>
   Norway's centrist coalition government sent the settlement
proposal to Parliament, which is expected to approve it with little
or no opposition in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   A committee that investigated the wartime confiscations
concluded in a majority report last fall that $15 million would be
appropriate compensation. But two dissenting members declared that
the majority had failed to grasp the complexity of what Norwegian
Jews had faced.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Kjell Magne Bondevik, an ordained Lutheran
minister, accepted the minority report as the basis for settlement.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement proposal is divided into two parts: some $33
million for Jewish organizations and Holocaust studies in Norway
and abroad, and up to $27 million for Jewish survivors of the war
and their children who can show that family belongings were lost
during the occupation of Norway. Individuals will be eligible for
about $27,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   In this relatively unlitigious country, it was not legal
pressure that led to a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Katz, chairman of the Norwegian Jewish Community, said
the initiative started three years ago when a doctoral student
uncovered aspects of the German occupation not previously discussed
and the government appointed an investigative committee.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Paltiel, 73, of Trondheim spent three years in Auschwitz
and Buchenwald and lost his entire family there. Just before the
war ended, in a deal with the collapsing Nazi regime, the Swedish
Red Cross rescued more than 500 Scandinavian prisoners from
Buchenwald.
</P>
<P>
   But it was recently documented by Norway's state television that
the only five Jews in the group were left behind. Among them was
Paltiel, who marched to the Danish border and eventually made his
way back to Trondheim alone.
</P>
<P>
   The postwar Norwegian government provided $2,600 to make up for
his lost household belongings but nothing for his family's clothing
store, which had been run by Nazi sympathizers and laid bare.
</P>
<P>
   Paltiel says he looks forward to giving most of the new
restitution to his grandchildren. ``Whatever the amount is,'' he
said, ``it was nothing that we asked for at all. It just comes as a
gift from heaven.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
