<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MOVES TO TAKE OVER CAMDEN'S FINANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unprecedented intervention into local affairs, Gov.
Christie Whitman has proposed that New Jersey officials take
control of virtually all of Camden's financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, included in the pending $18 billion state budget
approved by Senate and Assembly committees Thursday, would
establish a seven-member financial review board appointed by the
governor with sweeping powers over Camden's budget, labor contracts
and borrowing plans.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the full Legislature on Monday, the proposal
could eventually give the board daily control of Camden's spending.
The proposal would allow the city to retain control of its welfare
department, which state officials had tried to hand over to the
county.
</P>
<P>
   With an unemployment rate of nearly 14 percent, almost triple
the state average, and a per-capita income of $7,276, the lowest in
the state, Camden is in dire need of a financial recovery plan,
officials say. During the last four years, the state has given
almost $50 million in aid to Camden, more than half of the city's
total budget in that period, and the Whitman administration has
moved to seize control of the city's finances to insure that this
level of support does not continue to be necessary, said Jane
Kenny, commissioner of the state Department of Community Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Kenny said that the state had never before tried to
delve so deeply into municipal finances, she balked at the notion
that Camden, a city of 85,000, would effectively become state-run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we have far-reaching power,'' she said, ``we intend to
work with Camden.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While city officials said they would welcome advice from the
state, they contended that the governor's proposal seeks too much
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our city government to be under the thumb of any
outside entity,'' said Keith Walker, assistant business
administrator for the city. ``We don't need a stern father figure
looking over our shoulder. We need a compassionate brother or
sister.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said the city and state had initially discussed the
creation of a ``financial recovery team'' composed of visiting
state officials, who would bring their expertise and talents to
Camden to guide the city to fiscal solvency. But Walker said the
proposal was discarded in favor of the more stringent review board
after much discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Camden is no stranger to intervention from outside governmental
bodies. Last summer, the federal government seized control of the
city's housing authority, claiming that scores of public-housing
residents lived in deplorable conditions. In 1996, Whitman sent a
detachment of state troopers to Camden to help the Police
Department patrol the streets after a rash of murders.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials in Camden called the proposed review board
excessive.
</P>
<P>
   It would deprive residents of their right to elect their own
representatives, said state Sen. Wayne Bryant, a Democrat who
unsuccessfully fought the governor's plan in Thursday's voting
session. By placing Camden's crippled economy in the hands of
outsiders who have yet to come up with a clear recovery plan, the
proposal would also perpetuate the city's economic woes, he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
