u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYC-COLUMN-SCHOOLS-NY     06-26 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COLUMN-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PARENTS SEEK ANSWERS AT TROUBLED MIDDLE SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The final seventh-grade report card Moises Ayala
received Friday from Middle School 136 in Brooklyn had enough 55's
on it that it resembled a decent regional weather forecast for the
fall. His mother, Marlin Mazier, did not have to look at it to know
what it really predicted for September. She had decided weeks ago
to yank her son from the Sunset Park school and make him repeat the
seventh grade in a local parochial school.
</P>
<P>
   During the two years that Moises has been at the troubled public
school _ where only a third of the students read at or above grade
level _ he has shown little improvement. That was despite his
having been placed in a different class earlier this year, where
she hoped he would get more attention. But it came too late, she
said, and she grew anxious that he would just be passed on to the
next grade. He wasn't, but Ms. Mazier had already made up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm taking him out of that school because two years were
wasted,'' she said. ``My son doesn't have another two years to
waste. I don't feel he has more time left. Not if the same teachers
are going to be there. I'm not going to take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   She used to think that maybe it was just her problem, until she
became active in Brooklyn Interfaith for Action, a community
advocacy group that in recent years has begun to question the
quality of education and other public services. In the group, she
met parents whose children had also faced repeated frustrating
failures at MS 136 and other local schools. With mixed results,
they have since been after the principal and district
superintendent to meet with them to give them answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your child can't read, you think it's just your child,''
Ms. Mazier said. ``But almost 70 percent of them are not reading at
grade level. It's got to be something more. I know my son's not
perfect, but it has to be something deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as they have learned, working outside the usual channels of
the Parent-Teacher Association is not easy. Their group is
affiliated with the Industrial Areas Foundation, known for its
confrontational style of grass-roots organizing that trains
neighborhood residents to understand and identify community
problems and hold public officials accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The group had met in late March with Francis DeStefano, the
superintendent of District 15. They said he promised to follow up
with reports on the school's progress, as well as help them arrange
a meeting with principals at other schools. Members of the group
said that they still have difficulty getting through to principals
and that DeStefano has yet to deliver on his follow-up meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Lawrence, executive assistant to the superintendent,
said he has been focusing much of his attention on the school,
which has been on the state's list of troubled schools since 1994.
She said that a recently completed plan to restructure the school
was praised by state authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lawrence said that while the PTA had been informed about
these moves, she was unsure about the motives of the members of
BIA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know who they represent,'' she said. ``They have not
indicated exactly what's their intent or how they can help the
school. They have not involved themselves in the PTA or schoolwide
meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is because when they have gone to meet with some
teachers and administrators, they feel they have been either talked
down to or ignored. Elizabeth Cubero still bristles at how one of
her son's teachers suggested she place the child in a behavior
modification class and put him on Ritalin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got up and walked out,'' Ms. Cubero said. ``My son does
not have a mental problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mazier said she once asked another teacher about her son's
curriculum. ``She looked at me like I had four faces,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Both women attended MS 136 themselves in the 1970s, and
remembered it as a school where education was no-nonsense and
teachers took extra time to help them. Now they want to help, too,
by having a say in how projects are created and funds are
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   They want their children to get the same kind of attention young
people in better-off communities receive, rather than being pushed
through grade school to become future high school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get to know the teachers and principals,'' Ms.
Cubero said. ``Why is it so difficult? Then they complain about no
parent involvement.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
