<HEADLINE>
BUSH SPARES LIFE OF CONVICTED KILLER LUCAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, in an extraordinary
move Friday, spared the life of convicted murderer Henry Lee Lucas,
but promised that the 61-year-old former drifter would remain
imprisoned until the day he dies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush followed the recommendation of the Texas Board of Pardons
and Paroles and commuted Lucas' death sentence for the 1979 slaying
dubbed ``Orange Socks'' to life imprisonment. Bush added, though,
that Lucas' newly commuted sentence would not begin until after all
five of his other life sentences are served.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Lee Lucas is unquestionably guilty of other despicable
crimes for which he has been sentenced to spend the rest of his
life in prison,'' Bush said. ``However, I believe there is enough
doubt about this particular crime that the state of Texas should
not impose its ultimate penalty by executing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he should not walk out free again,'' he added. ``This is a
bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Notified of the governor's decision, Lucas said from death row:
``I can only thank them for believing the truth and having guts
enough for standing up for what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   The parole board voted 17-1 Thursday to recommend that Bush take
such action. Board chairman Victor Rodriguez said a 1985
investigative report by then-Attorney General Jim Mattox carried
significant weight in convincing the board that Lucas' death
sentence was inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Mattox's investigation _ undertaken after news reports cast
doubt on the veracity of some 600 slayings around the country to
which Lucas confessed _ determined it was unlikely that Lucas
committed the slaying for which he was sentenced to die. Work time
sheets and a cashed check indicate that Lucas was in Florida when
the young woman was slain.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Dan Morales later reached the same conclusion,
although his office had been prepared to carry out the legal battle
to see that Lucas was executed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that Lucas' case is the first one in the 80 he has
reviewed since becoming governor that has raised doubt in his mind
about the condemned person's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no doubt, no doubt in my mind up until this,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was reluctant to second guess a jury and the
courts, but he added that the jury ``did not know and could not
have known'' in 1984 when they sentenced Lucas to death about his
``pattern of lying and confessing to crimes that evidence later
proved he did not commit. Today's knowledge about his pattern of
lies raises doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas had been scheduled to die by lethal injection Tuesday for
the 1979 rape and strangulation of a young woman, who remains
unidentified. Her body was found in a ditch along Interstate 35
near Georgetown, north of Austin. The case was named for the only
item of clothing the victim was wearing when her body was found. It
is the only murder for which Lucas was ever given a death sentence.
He has been convicted in eight other murders in Texas and one in
West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas gained notoriety in the 1980s after he confessed to some
600 murders around the country, but he later recanted those
confessions. He said he confessed to make a mockery of police and
because they fed him sufficient details about the crimes that he
could confess in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a supporter of the death penalty for those who commit
horrible crimes, I feel a special obligation to make sure the state
of Texas never executes a person for a crime they may not have
committed,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson County District Attorney Ken Anderson, whose
predecessor prosecuted Lucas in the ``Orange Socks'' case, remained
outraged at the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has all originated from one big lie,'' Anderson said.
``The lie is that the information about Lucas' work records and
bank deposits, which the defense tried to use as his alibi, are
new. All of that was given to the jury to consider years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Some jurors in that case agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lucas) is pulling everyone's strings and probably laughing
while he's doing it,'' said Mary Ann Desrosiers of San Angelo.
``It's a crying shame. There really hasn't been any new evidence
that we haven't considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility that he could have been out of town at the
time of the murder was brought up. But the overwhelming amount of
other evidence (proved) that he was guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas was tried in San Angelo on a change of venue.
</P>
<P>
   With Lucas' date with death now canceled, Texas Department of
Criminal Justice spokesman Glen Castlebury said Lucas would be
moved from death row at the Ellis I Unit outside Huntsville to the
Diagnostic Unit, where he will be assigned a new prison number and
a new unit. Castlebury was uncertain when that move would occur.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas' attorneys said they were relieved that their client had
been vindicated, but disappointed it took so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disappointing and discouraging that we came so close to
an execution given the substantial doubts that have surrounded this
case since 1986,'' attorneys Rita Radostitz of Austin and Danny
Burns of Fort Worth said in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Mattox, who is seeking re-election as the Democratic
nominee for attorney general, applauded Bush's decision, saying it
was politically risky but will ``make our death penalty punishment
stronger than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattox's Republican opponent, though, former Texas Supreme Court
Justice John Cornyn, disagreed with Bush's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence both in the jury who heard the case and in
the more than 23 judges who reviewed the evidence,'' Cornyn said.
``I believe their decisions should be respected and their sentence
carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, however, said that ``the clemency process is intended as a
fail safe for unusual or exceptional circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas remains convicted of eight other Texas murders for which
he is serving five life sentences plus 210 years. He also has a
life sentence without the possibility of parole for a West Virginia
killing, but his confession to that crime also has been called
bogus.
</P>
<P>
   If Lucas were ever to be released from a Texas prison, he could
also be sent to Colorado or Florida where he is a suspect in at
least four other murder cases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Associated Press contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
