<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9423 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LANDLORD-925(2TAKE     06-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LANDLORD-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROOKLYN LANDLORD FACES INVESTIGATION OVER SERVICE COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the last 20 years, the families at Bedford
Gardens, a sprawling Brooklyn apartment complex, have grown
accustomed to seeing the name Kraus at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   Their rent checks go to Kraus Management, they are watched over
by uniformed guards from Kraus Security. When their toilets break,
Kraus Maintenance fixes them, and when they fall behind on rent,
the stern letters have often come from the law firm of Kraus &AMP;
Kraus.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over this growing empire of companies is Herman I.
Kraus, a tall, methodical 70-year-old lawyer who grew up in a
working-class family a few blocks to the north. Not only do Kraus'
companies make millions by serving the complex, but he is also its
principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, through legal maneuvering and sheer tenacity,
he has managed to award his own companies almost every major
contract to operate and maintain the 639-apartment complex, which
gets more than $3 million a year from the federal government in
rent assistance for its working-class tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual arrangement has made the complex into what city
officials have described as the closest thing to a monopoly in the
city's assisted housing system.
</P>
<P>
   But that is only where questions begin about Kraus, who owns or
manages more than 2,400 other subsidized apartments in the city.
</P>
<P>
   But a brighter light is now being focused on Kraus' businesses.
The United States Department of Housing and Urban Development,
which subsidizes Bedford Gardens, has blocked the latest rent
increase after questions were raised by tenants and tenant
advocates and this month began an audit of Bedford Gardens and
other federally subsidized developments Kraus controls.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors in the New York HUD office wrote recently in an
internal memorandum that they were faced with a crucial question:
Should the federal government use rent subsidies to help a
developer out of a city tax debt, especially when questions persist
about whether that debt mounted so the developer could enrich his
own companies?
</P>
<P>
   In interviews in his spartan offices in Queens County, Kraus
said that he hired his own companies because they did a better job
than any others he had used, and that that was why they cost more _
some services are two to three times more expensive than those used
by comparable developments. Kraus said that city and federal
officials would not acknowledge what it really cost to maintain
subsidized housing.
</P>
<P>
   But displaying a confidence that acquaintances say is
characteristic, Kraus dismissed the planned federal audit as a
charade and expressed more weariness than anxiety about its
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government, in my opinion, has changed from the friendly
government I knew 25 years ago,'' he said. ``I grew up thinking
that Uncle Sam was the greatest partner in the world, with his arm
around you, trying to help. But not anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In court papers and city records, and in interviews with former
and current city and federal officials, a portrait emerges of an
elaborate, mazelike system for extracting public subsidies from
Bedford Gardens that has frustrated authorities for two decades:
Kraus has often asserted that the complex's bills _ nearly all
charged by his own companies _ are too high. This has helped him
win permission from the city to raise rents, meaning that millions
more in federal dollars flow his way.
</P>
<P>
   When he has not won rent increases, Kraus has simply stopped
paying municipal taxes. He has not paid in almost a decade and now
owes more than $11 million, making him one of the city's biggest
tax scofflaws, even as his service companies have flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus' practices raise larger questions about the laws that
govern subsidized developments like Bedford Gardens, which house as
many as 200,000 city residents. Under those state laws,
self-dealing is allowed as long as the owner informs the
authorities. Kraus says this is why his name is appended boldly to
all his satellite companies.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Joseph Lentol, who represents the area and has been
a critic of Kraus' practices, said the laws were meant to permit
flexibility in hiring that could lead to lower expenses. But ``then
you have a guy like Kraus who may be turning it around to make more
money for himself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Former city officials say Kraus may have escaped more intense
scrutiny because he defies the stereotype of the cagey subsidized
housing operator in one way: He is not a slumlord. His buildings
have been praised as among the cleanest and safest in the city's
assisted housing system, and Kraus says he is proud of that record.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents find darkness even in that virtue, though.
Deteriorated conditions would almost certainly draw action by
authorities, they say. In addition, the city has long suspected,
although never proved, that Kraus' service companies perform
unnecessary work _ like repainting floors instead of cleaning them
or renovating kitchens that need no renovation _ simply to generate
income.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus' maneuverings reached their apex early this year when city
officials, virtually backed into a corner, again allowed him to
raise rents, as part of a deal to help him secure a private loan to
pay off his back taxes and refinance his mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has really always been in a class by himself,'' said
a former city housing official who dealt with Kraus and who, like
other former officials, spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any other kind of business, somebody would have stopped
this kind of thing long ago.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Years before the concrete buildings of Bedford Gardens rose
alongside the Brooklyn-Queens Expressway, Kraus was already a
master at gathering the public housing money rolling into
inner-city neighborhoods in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Using the Municipal Loan Program, which provided low-interest
rehabilitation mortgages, he first rescued some crumbling buildings
on South Second Street in Williamsburg, including the modest tan
brick building where he was raised, No. 359.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, he became the first developer in the state and one of
the first in the nation to be granted a now widely used Federal
subsidy known as project-based Section 8, to renovate a group of
ravaged buildings in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus, who had worked his way through Brooklyn Law School
managing battle-scarred buildings in Red Hook and
Bedford-Stuyvesant, threw on overalls and helped repair the
buildings himself, in a neighborhood few other developers would
even visit. ``We sometimes had practice sessions on how to use bomb
blankets,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several years, aggressively pursuing money from
local and Federal programs, he bought and rehabilitated dozens of
other buildings in the South Bronx and Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a failed investment in luxury apartments in the early
1990s, Kraus has stuck solely to subsidized housing, and it has
been rewarding. The son of a house painter, he lives in a
multimillion-dollar apartment on Park Avenue. His companies have
been hired recently to manage properties for the New York City
Housing Authority and to work for housing agencies from Long Island
to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But even by the time tracts of small family homes were being
cleared to make way for Bedford Gardens in the mid-1970s, Kraus was
already in debt to the city, owing more than $350,000 on mortgages
of $7.9 million. It was the beginning of a pattern of debt that was
to continue for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, in 1973 he was granted the $26 million mortgage for
Bedford Gardens, and he was soon more than $1 million in debt to
the city on that mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Kraus had begun building the satellite companies
_ Kraus Maintenance, Kraus Management, Kraus Security System, Kraus
Hi-Tech Security, Kraus Holdings, Kraus Parking, Kraus Vending, and
Kraus Advertising, among others _ that derive almost all their
business from Bedford Gardens or other developments he owns.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, for example, he incorporated Kraus Security two days
before it began supplying armed guards to Bedford Gardens, at a
monthly cost of $18,400, more than double what the previous company
had charged, according to city auditors.
</P>
<P>
   Kraus contends that he formed his companies out of desperation
because independent contractors he hired always did shoddy work.
(He said one pest-control company even watered down its bug spray.)
``I said, `Wait a minute, if I'm going to take the heat, I might as
well go out and form my own,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent tour of Bedford Gardens, the buildings' common areas
were in sparkling shape _ even the boiler rooms were spotless. When
asked about the complex, tenants, most of whom are Orthodox jews,
generally express a mixture of praise and puzzlement. ``Do you know
how many times they painted the stairs on my floor this month?''
said Thomas King, a bank loan processor who has lived there for 17
years. ``Three times. Instead of cleaning them, they repaint.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Kraus has had extensive debt problems at other
developments and officials have questioned self-dealing throughout
his system, Bedford Gardens has long been the focus of their
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Department of Housing Preservation and
Development has repeatedly ordered Kraus to stop using certain of
his companies or to bid out contracts because his rates have been
two or three times what other companies charged. Kraus has either
ignored the orders or conducted bidding in such a way that his
companies were the lowest bidders, according to city records and
former city officials.
</P>
<P>
   While such self-dealing is prohibited or closely watched in many
other industries, it is legal under the state laws that govern
developments like Bedford Gardens, known as Mitchell-Lamas.
</P>
<P>
   The Mitchell-Lama system, created in 1955, gave nonprofit
organizations and private developers like Kraus property tax breaks
and low-interest mortgages to build apartments for middle-class and
working-class tenants. In return, the owners agreed to limit their
profits and keep rents low.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, other Mitchell-Lama owners have begun to exercise a
degree of self-dealing, including using their own management
companies so they can have more control over their buildings. But
Kraus has remained alone in pressing to the outer boundaries of the
law and fighting to remain there.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Kraus has also helped his cause by
contributing faithfully to campaigns across the political spectrum
and has always hired the most politically powerful law firm of the
moment to protect his interests.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been aided mostly by the nuances of the law.
</P>
<P>
   One official who now deals with Bedford Gardens said simply that
``there's no affirmative legal prohibition against what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The city has granted Bedford Gardens four rent increases over
the years, allowing the rents to grow by an average of more than 60
percent. It has long made the complex, whose rents are supposed to
be much lower than those in the open market, among the most
expensive in the Mitchell Lama system. With its latest increase
request delayed for years, rents there now rank somewhere in the
middle. If those increase go through, a two-bedroom apartment at
Bedford that rents for $716 would increase to $889, or 23 percent,
over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Because three quarters of Bedford's tenants receive some rent
help from the federal government, this means that last year, $3.2
million in federal tax dollars went to Bedford Gardens. If Kraus
receives his latest requested rent increase, the federal government
will end up paying an additional $2.5 million over the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   While the federal inquiry may prove the most serious, it is
hardly the first time Kraus' practices have been questioned, and in
each case he has emerged mostly unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   A 1982 audit by the city Comptrollers' Office charged that over
a four-year period Kraus authorized nearly $2 million in excessive
payments for goods and services, mostly to his own companies.
Kraus' companies, for example, performed simple tasks like
replacing stove knobs that were usually handled by building
superintendents in other developments. The companies charged a
minimum of $1 for every part, even if a washer or other tiny part
cost 10 cents, the audit found.
</P>
<P>
   At a rent increase hearing three years later, city officials
stated in a report that at Bedford Gardens ``the selling Kraus
entity bills the buying Kraus entity for parts on a cost-plus
basis'' _ in other words, a markup, of sometimes 35 percent or 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``These conditions enrich Kraus,'' the city's audit concluded,
``because as sole stockholder and president of his related service
companies, he receives salaries, fringe benefits and any net
profits.'' How much the service companies make is difficult to
determine since they are private and not required to disclose their
finances.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the city briefly took over the complex
because of concerns about the expenses, but Kraus immediately filed
federal bankruptcy _ which allows the debtor to remain in
possession of his property _ and records show that he apparently
wrested it back within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, a group of Kraus' own partners in Bedford
Gardens unsuccessfully petitioned the city to take over the
development because, they said, Kraus' ``mismanagement,
overcharging and improper self-dealing'' jeopardized its financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the partners compared Bedford to 17 other
housing projects, and concluded that the annual expenses for repair
and maintenance was often three times as high _ $1,608 per room for
Bedford compared with about $515 for a group of other developments.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration contends that, despite what Federal
officials now say, it had imposed rigid controls on Kraus before
approving the latest rent increase. For example, it required that
the city oversee the bidding process for several service contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But in their initial review, Federal auditors suggested that the
new rules were not nearly strong enough. ``Missing from the
agreement,'' the auditors said, ``is the requirement that the owner
competitively bid its maintenance and security services'' _
performed by Kraus' companies _ ``which represented almost 90
percent of the project's 1996 operating and maintenance costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Roberts, the city's housing commissioner, declined to
comment specifically on why those contracts were left out, except
to say that the city had ``fashioned a solution that, I think,
balanced a lot of competing interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, other city officials still seem content _ so long as
the development remains clean and safe and the city is able to
recoup its mortgage and taxes _ to allow Kraus to continue the
extensive use of his own companies at Bedford Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk about the ethics of doing that,'' the official
said, ``and we can talk about whether there are controls on prices.
But the fact is that his final product is a good product.''
</P>
</TEXT>
