<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9427 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-ASSES     06-26 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-ASSESS-$ADV28-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTTERING THE P-WORD WITH SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Pa., Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Graphic showing current Social Security system vs.
partial privatized system will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
(af) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An idea that sounded heretical only a year or two ago is
suddenly popping up in all corners.
</P>
<P>
   Privatizing Social Security _ having individuals divert a
portion of their payroll taxes into personal retirement investment
accounts _ is part of the overhaul plans offered by Democratic and
Republican leaders, from moderates like Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., to conservatives like Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It is also at the core of a plan proposed in May by the National
Commission on Retirement Policy, a private group formed by the
Center for Strategic and International Studies and led by Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., and three other members of Congress. The plan has
become a focus of debate over privatization in part because of its
influential bipartisan support and because its detailed provisions
have been scrutinized by government actuaries.
</P>
<P>
   According to its proponents, privatization will help cure Social
Security's financial and philosophical flaws _ among other things,
giving young workers, who have grown disillusioned with the New
Deal program, a shot at earning a fair return on their payroll tax
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing chorus of economists says the benefits of
privatization are illusory. The critics contend that private
accounts will not help achieve long-term solvency and,
counterintuitive though it seems, that they will not outperform the
sad-sack Social Security trust fund into which payroll taxes now
go.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, on a level playing field, the critics argue, private
accounts as a whole are bound to do worse than the trust fund. And
all this change, they add, poses a needless risk, because Social
Security is only mildly out of fiscal whack.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't difficult to understand why the political ground has
shifted so quickly. Republicans have controlled Congress since
1994, and Social Security, as a gargantuan government program, has
never been the darling of conservatives. Another reason is that the
program is running out of money; in about 20 years, when the baby
boomers begin to retire, the system will be paying out more in
retirement checks than it will be collecting in payroll taxes. So
some kind of fix is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the stock market has been soaring, just when Americans
are becoming accustomed to investing some of their retirement money
in self-directed 401(k) plans. Many, especially younger workers who
don't expect Social Security to survive until their retirement, are
unhappy about seeing their payroll contributions tied up in the
low-yielding trust fund rather than some high-flying stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   And so, like other would-be reformers of Social Security, the
commission set out both to restore the system to solvency and to
create a new political constituency for a national retirement
system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The so-called crisis confronting Social Security is this: It
would take a reserve of $3 trillion today to pay the difference
between benefits that will be distributed and taxes that will be
collected over the next 75 years. This ominous-sounding number is
cited by those who advocate extensive changes.
</P>
<P>
   But the defenders of the current system say the budget hole is
not formidable, and can be filled by raising payroll taxes by about
two percentage points, to about 14.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Crisis or not, the commission, unwilling to buck the anti-tax
mood in Congress, would achieve long-term balance by cutting
benefits. The cuts could, for example, reduce the first-year
benefits of an individual born in the 1980s by about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking provision calls for raising the normal
retirement age to 70 by 2029 and the early retirement age to 65 by
2017. Thereafter, the commission calls for these retirement ages to
rise in line with life expectancy. In other words, as medical
breakthroughs allow people to live longer, the commission would
have them spend all of the additional years at work.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles W. Stenholm of Texas, a co-chairman of the
retirement commission, says the commission proposes raising
retirement ages in this way to avoid ``imposing higher payroll
taxes or substantially reducing retirement benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of this proposal, like Peter Diamond, a professor of
economics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, call the
proposal ``unrealistic.'' It runs counter to ``a century of trend
toward earlier retirement,'' Diamond said.
</P>
<P>
   Though the commission's initial round of benefit changes would,
by themselves, achieve long-term financial balance for Social
Security, the 24-member panel does not stop there. Instead, it adds
a proposal to partially privatize the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   Workers would deposit 2 percent of their earnings in private
accounts, choosing among widely diversified stock and bond funds
authorized by the federal government. That would leave 10.4 percent
of earnings in the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the idea is to restore younger workers' faith in Social
Security, explained Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., a co-chairman of the
commission. Workers who think of their payroll tax contributions as
an investment often see the Social Security trust fund as a raw
deal: For every $100 that young workers pay into the fund today,
they are likely to get back at retirement 30 years hence only about
$150, an annual rate of return of between 1 and 2 percent after
taking account of inflation. Gregg said private accounts would
``offer much higher rates of return.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission also wants to turn Social Security into a
national savings program, a change from the current approach of
paying today's retirees with today's workers' taxes. The
commission's idea, Gregg explained, is to encourage workers to save
and invest, helping the economy grow richer and making tomorrow's
workers better able to afford the burden of supporting their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledges that merely diverting existing taxes into
private accounts does not raise national savings. But the
commission also invites workers to deposit up to $2,000 a year
extra into these tax-advantaged savings vehicles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The rub is that privatization _ which, remember, is not needed
to ``save'' Social Security _ would worsen the system's financial
balance, at least temporarily, by diverting payroll taxes that
would otherwise be available to pay current retirees.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's solution is to propose a second round of
temporary benefit cuts for retirees who are not poor. It would set
each year's benefits for new retirees at between 98 and 99 percent
of the previous year's figure.
</P>
<P>
   While cuts of less than 2 percent sound small, they add up. By
the 20th year of the program, the benefit of a middle-class family,
now about $1,000 a month, would have fallen about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the commission, pointing to actuarial projections, says
workers would fare better with privatization because income from
the investments would more than make up for its second round of
benefit cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say privatization won't benefit workers or the
economy very much.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds bizarre: After all, how can a portfolio of stocks
and bonds yielding, say, 5 percent above inflation, not beat the
trust fund's 1 percent return? The critics say the comparison is
misleading.
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund looks bad in part because, unlike private
accounts, under current law it can't invest in stocks. Also,
returns on the trust fund look measly because it bears the burden
of paying off unfinanced claims _ $9 trillion in benefits that the
system has promised to pay but against which it has accumulated no
reserves. The private accounts bear none of this burden.
</P>
<P>
   If it were not for the fact that private accounts would be
allowed to invest in stocks _ and critics have a lot to say about
the misleading nature of that advantage _ they would provide no
financial benefit to workers.
</P>
<P>
   In a forthcoming book on overhauling Social Security, the
economists John Geanakoplos of Yale, Olivia Mitchell of the Wharton
School and Stephen Zeldes of Columbia University point out that,
with or without private accounts, workers must pay for the system's
unfinanced claims _ unless Congress does the unthinkable and breaks
its promise to several generations of retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Either lawmakers will tax the necessary money out of the new
private accounts, reducing their yield, or they will cut future
benefits for today's young workers.
</P>
<P>
   These economists argue that the extra profit that workers earn
on the dollars they deposit into their private accounts is exactly
offset by the extra loss that they suffer on their deposits into
the trust fund _ assuming, still, that the private accounts invest
in the same low-risk securities held by the trust fund. So the
income of retirees would not change, the economists say.
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of privatization counter that most individuals
will invest in stocks and outperform the trust fund. The actuaries'
projections bear them out. Individuals who invest in stocks under
the commission's plan are likely to have slightly more income upon
retirement than they would under the current system once it is
brought into long-run balance.
</P>
<P>
   But critics warn that comparisons among yields on private and
public retirement funds don't take into account that stock
purchases would expose workers to risk that the trust fund does
not.
</P>
<P>
   A fair test would compare private accounts to a trust fund that
would, as many economists propose, invest in corporate stocks and
bonds. By that standard, Diamond, along with Henry J. Aaron, an
economist at the Brookings Institution, contend that the trust fund
would actually outperform private accounts. Private accounts, these
economists say, would be more expensive to administer.
</P>
<P>
   Just think, they say, of the costs of more than 140 million
itsy-bitsy accounts versus one giant government investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron worries, too, about exposing the retirement income of
individual workers to the risks of investing in the stock market.
He would rather see the Social Security trust fund build reserves _
his preferred way to bolster national savings _ and invest in
corporate stocks and bonds while continuing to pay a set level of
benefits to retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why move to a system that produces, after taking account of
administration expenses, lower returns and subjects the elderly to
unwanted risk?'' Aaron asked scornfully. Besides, he added,
privatization plans like the commission's would inevitably widen
the gap between rich and poor because poor workers could be
expected to load their accounts with low-yield bonds while the
wealthier and more knowledgeable focus on stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The critics' arguments veer quickly from arithmetic into
politics, as do those of the proponents of privatization.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists who favor privatization _ notably Professor
Martin Feldstein of Harvard, chairman of the Council of Economic
Advisers in the Reagan administration _ vigorously oppose any plan
that has a government-run retirement fund buy big chunks of
American business. He fears political manipulation of investment
decisions _ for example, by ruling out the purchase of shares in
tobacco companies _ though Aaron and other liberal economists say
government investments could be insulated against that threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Feldstein plan, broadly embraced by Gramm, would make up for
the 2 percent of earnings workers could put in private accounts by
directing $1 trillion in federal surpluses over the next decade
into the Social Security fund.
</P>
<P>
   At retirement, workers would collect a benefit from the trust
fund equal to that of the current law, plus 25 percent of the money
that has accumulated in their individual accounts. The balance of
the private accounts would be turned back to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, Feldstein says, would come out ahead, countering
Aaron's worries about exposing the elderly to unwanted financial
risk. Aaron dismisses the plan's rosy outcomes as distorted by its
tapping of temporary government surpluses. The windfall could be
used at least as effectively, Aaron suggests, to build up reserves
in the trust fund.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The political distance between the combatants appears at least
as great as the economic distance.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg embraces private accounts, saying they ``will create a
sense of ownership and control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, that is the capitalist system,'' he said. ``You take
a personal interest in what you personally own.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., calls the existing program
``the most successful federal program ever enacted'' and says
privatization would ``risk turning Social Security into social
insecurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Economists are no more reconcilable. Aaron says tough-minded
safeguards would allow government to buy perhaps 15 percent of the
equity on Wall Street, free of political influences. Feldstein
refuses to seriously entertain the notion, no matter what
safeguards Aaron concocts.
</P>
<P>
   So what starts out as a fight over actuary tables becomes a
battle over the role of government. The numbers will no doubt be
easier to resolve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
