<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  New York Times Votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 216.
WASHINGTON, June 26 -- The following chart shows how senators and
house representatives voted on key bills and amendments in the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved Wednesday, 59-36, legislation that would
allow tax-free education savings accounts for parents or
scholarship sponsors that could be used to defray school costs.
Supporters of the bill said it will lower education costs.
Opponents said that the bill will subsidize private school
education, help mostly the affluent and lead to public school
neglect. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: MILITARY
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted Thursday, 48-45, to pass an amendment to the
defense budget which would make it harder to shut down more
military bases. Supporters of the amendment said they want to
insure that Congress receives all the information it needs before
deciding to close bases. Opponents said the amendment sends the
message that protecting unnecessary bases and civilian jobs takes
precedence over military preparedness and personnel. A ``yes'' vote
favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved, 88-4, the Pentagon's $270 billion budget
for fiscal year 1999. Supporters expressed satisfaction with what
the bill did for their individual states and for the nation as a
whole. Opponents voted against it for individual reasons. A ``yes''
vote favors the budget.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, June 19, the House rejected, 155-254, an amendment to
a campaign finance bill. The measure would have wiped out the
entire reform bill if any of its provisions were declared
unconstitutional. Supporters said that if any part of the bill was
found unconstitutional, it would change the bill's character.
Opponents said the amendment would enable members not in favor of
campaign reform to add unconstitutional provisions for the sole
purpose of killing the bill. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   The House approved Wednesday, 223-254, an amendment to the
annual agricultural spending bill that would prohibit research
funding for the abortion-inducing pill, RU-486. Supporters of the
measure said that supporting research of life-taking substances was
unethical. Opponents said that the amendment infringed upon the
privacy of the patient to choose her treatment. A ``yes'' vote
favors the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: IRSREFORM
</P>
<P>
   The House voted Thursday, 402-8, to pass an IRS overhaul and tax
bill. The measure would establish a citizens' oversight board and
increase taxpayer rights in collection disputes with the IRS.
Supporters said the bill would protect taxpayers from any abuse
from the tax agency. Opponents objected to changing the capital
gains holding period from 18 months to 12 months, calling it a tax
break for the wealthy. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   The attendance record tracks the cumulative attendance of
members to date when they are physically present for roll call
votes.
</P>
