<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9440 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARASS-BOCA-COX     06-26 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARASS-BOCA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supreme Court rules city officials are liable for managers'
sexual harassment
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg and Larry Lipman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON _ City officials are responsible for sexual
harassment by supervisors even if they didn't know about it, the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled Friday in a case that will affect
employers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also means the city must pay legal fees for the two
former lifeguards whose complaint took them from their cramped
oceanfront headquarters to the high court. The tab could be as much
as $500,000, their lawyer says.
</P>
<P>
   In the 33-page opinion written by Justice David Souter, the
court upheld a federal judge's 1994 ruling ordering the city to pay
$1 in damages, plus legal fees, to former lifeguards Beth Ann
Faragher and Nancy Ewanchew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any civilized society would be doing exactly what these
justices did with this ruling,'' Ewanchew said Friday from the
living room of her Boca Raton home. Faragher did not return several
calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Boca Raton decision was one of two 7-2 opinions _ Justices
Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia dissented in both _ on employer
liability for harassment by managers. The other involved an
Illinois woman whose supervisor's boss made sexually harassing
comments and threatened her job.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas argued that ``absent an adverse employment consequence,
an employer cannot be held ... liable if a supervisor creates a
hostile work environment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the majority found that employers are liable for the actions
of a supervisor, saying that employers can be released from
liability depending on the reasonableness of anti-harassment
efforts and how the victim tried to avoid harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The justices found Boca Raton officials failed to distribute a
1990 city policy to beach employees, keep track of supervisors'
conduct, or exercise ``reasonable care to prevent the supervisors'
harassing conduct,'' Souter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The court allowed employers a defense when they properly issue
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything the court suggests an employer should be doing,
Boca Raton has been doing since 1991,'' said Harry Rissetto, the
city's lawyer in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an employer's perspective it could have been worse,''
said Ann Reesman, general counsel for the Equal Employment Advisory
Council, a coalition of 300 large private employers. ``It supports
the employer who makes proactive efforts to fight sexual
harassment. We're just disappointed that they didn't extend that
defense to all cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Amlong, the lifeguards' attorney, called Friday's ruling
``the most important employment law decision of the century because
it will reshape the American workplace. No longer can employers
simply play `Hear no evil, see no evil.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A hearing will decide total legal fees, but Amlong said they
would be close to $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The city will pay from a liability fund, City Manager Donna
Dreska said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is financially sound,'' Dreska said, ``(but) this
will obviously be an expenditure we had not planned upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Faragher and Ewanchew sued in 1992, charging supervisors Bill
Terry and David Silverman improperly touched them and made vulgar
comments. The two were later hit with large judgments and the city
with the $1 ruling, leading to the parade of appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spent thousands of dollars to fight this but they should
have cut their losses,'' said Sheila Jaffe of Boca Raton, acting
president of the Florida chapter for the National Organization for
Women. ``They thought they were right. But they weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the NOW's South Palm Beach County chapter that another
supervisor, Robert ``Flash'' Gordon, contacted after the female
lifeguards told him of their abuse. In court, Gordon said he didn't
contact his superior, because that would have been Terry.
Silverman, Terry and Gordon could not be located Friday for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Souter wrote Friday that the two supervisors ``were granted
virtually unchecked authority over their subordinates'' and that
Faragher and her fellow female lifeguards were ``completely
isolated from the city's higher management.''
</P>
<P>
   The court ``ruled that an employer can't escape its
responsibility by hiding its head in the sand and ignoring sexual
harassment in the workplace,'' said Deborah Brake, senior counsel
for the National Women's Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a substantial change in sexual harassment law,'' said
Richard Seymour, director of the employment discrimination project
for the Lawyers Committee for Civil Rights Under the Law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision streamlines and simplifies sexual harassment law
and makes it far easier ... for a plaintiff to succeed,'' Seymour
said.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling for the city ``would have created an enormous loophole
in the sexual harassment laws for future cases,'' said Jonathan
Turley, a Georgetown University constitutional law professor who
had predicted the court would rule against the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court clearly did not want to make ignorance of
conditions a defense when the employer failed to take efforts to
monitor those conditions,'' Turley said.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth du Fresne, a Miami attorney specializing in management
law and labor who represents and trains employers, said holding
employers responsible _ even for harassment they don't know about _
will lead to frivolous suits.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the ruling helps employers who establish policies
for preventing and reporting harassment: ``I've been telling them
they should do it and now the courts are telling them they should
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Alexandra Navarro Clifton and staff researcher
Sammy Alzofon contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
