<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATCHER-DEATH27-COX     06-26 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATCHER-DEATH27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta environmentalist commits suicide
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The death of a prominent Atlanta environmentalist who
police say jumped from the 17th floor of a downtown hotel Thursday
night was officially ruled a suicide Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Boyd Hatcher, 62, president and CEO of the Georgia
Conservancy and a former Atlanta Parks Commissioner, died of
injuries to her head and chest received during her fall inside the
atrium of the Hyatt Regency Atlanta at 265 Peachtree St. N.E.,
officials with the Fulton County Medical Examiner's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher gained recognition for her leadership of the Georgia
Conservancy, regarded as the state's premier environmental
organization. As commissioner of Atlanta's Parks, Recreation &AMP;
Cultural Affairs in the early 1980s, she was largely credited as
the person who made Zoo Atlanta one of the best zoos in the country
after it had been ranked as one of the worst. She also was a
founder of Trees Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police were called to the hotel at 8:40 p.m. Thursday. A
hotel employee told police that while checking for leaking pipes on
the 16th floor on the opposite side of the hotel, he saw a woman in
a planter near the edge of the balcony. He then watched helplessly
as she jumped, the police report said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher's purse, found near the hotel elevators, contained two
notes, one listing an emergency contact and another note directing
police to Hatcher's car in a nearby parking garage where her
identification could be found in the trunk, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said she had recently been taking medication for
depression.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
