<HEADER>
A9442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICE-CONTROVERSY-CO     06-26 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICE-CONTROVERSY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police crime statistics dispute roiling ranks
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Once again the Atlanta Police Department has been
ruptured by a controversy that appears to be depleting morale and
polarizing the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a slap in the face,'' said Atlanta robbery Detective
Ed Christian, a 25-year veteran with the department. ``It's
frustrating because most of us work hard and we've done good work.
And those things should come out, too. People shouldn't tear down
the department without cause or proof.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian is talking about a very public dispute between Capt.
Louis Arcangeli and Police Chief Beverly Harvard, as are many of
the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-May, when Arcangeli was demoted from deputy police
chief, the department's top officers have been in a nearly constant
state of public charges and countercharges. Within a few days of
Arcangeli's demotion, a series of memos he wrote to Harvard in 1997
became public. In them, he accused Harvard and two other deputy
chiefs of allowing the department to manipulate crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are taking sides on this and it's causing some
separation within the department,'' said Sgt. Archie Ezell. ``I
wouldn't say this is exactly a black eye for us, but I would say it
has cast a shadow over us.'' Ezell, a 12-year veteran who works in
the Zone 2 precinct, said he's spoken to colleagues who are on both
sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   After the Arcangeli memos were reported by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution on May 21, the City Council Public Safety
Committee held a series of public hearings that ended in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   Some council members clearly believed Arcangeli was unable to
back up his allegations when they asked for specific examples of
how crime reports were changed. The hearings ended with four hours
of angry testimony from Harvard, much of it aimed at Arcangeli, and
focusing on what she called attacks on her integrity. At least one
council member suggested Harvard was responsible for the public
dispute because she declined to call in the GBI to investigate when
Arcangeli requested such a review.
</P>
<P>
   The GBI has since begun an audit of the department's reporting
of crime statistics.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of how much impact this has had on the department
is the degree of public comment from ranking officers. Some believe
Harvard and her deputy chiefs have done nothing wrong; others
believe Arcangeli, who has a good reputation in the department,
would not have raised questions unless he had solid evidence.
Others are angry that Arcangeli made the allegations without having
sufficient proof to convince City Council members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general view is one of disappointment,'' said Sgt. Lou
Moore, a 25-year veteran who works in the robbery unit. ``This has
certainly not been good for morale because of these allegations.
Doubts have been raised and, really, no answers have been given.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Police Department has a history of such divisive
issues.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, several officers _ mostly from Zone 3 in
southwest Atlanta _ were convicted of federal corruption charges
after the FBI and Atlanta police found they had extorted money from
neighborhood drug dealers. Later that year, an officer was accused
of fatally shooting an unarmed customer at a downtown motorcycle
repair shop.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, a promotion cheating scandal rocked the
department.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation ordered by then-Mayor Maynard Jackson concluded
that then-Public Safety Commissioner Reginald Eaves not only knew
about the cheating, but authorized it. The scandal led to the
firing or demotion of several officers and the eventual resignation
of Eaves.
</P>
<P>
   Promotions on the force were stalled until six years later when
another test was given.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta City Councilman Lee Morris said such incidents are
unfortunate but they should not mold the public's opinion of
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public should not view rank and file officers differently
because of this,'' Morris said, referring to the latest brouhaha.
``They have nothing to do with this. To me, this is nothing more
than politics. But I agree it probably has had an impact on morale
within the police department. The officers themselves must be
shaken because of all this infighting among their supervisors.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue should be resolved so that officers can move on, said
one veteran police lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this has reflected badly on everyone in the blue suit,
because our main concern is to save lives and solve problems,''
said Lt. Tony Biello, a 19-year veteran and commander of the
homicide unit. ``But if there's a problem here, let's solve it and
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   M.K. Clayton, a 25-year-old, five-year police veteran who
patrols downtown streets on a bicycle, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's right or wrong here; there's always
conflicting stories,'' Clayton said. ``But I think there are far
more important things affecting this department such as low pay and
low morale. As far as my colleagues go, these are the things we're
mostly affected by.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
