<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-RETIR     06-26 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-RETIRE-ART-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TO RETIRE? PLANNERS AND WORKERS ARE ON OPPOSITE PATHS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo will be sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)  
 (af)  
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKEWOOD, N.J. _ They are the boys of endless summers, measuring
lives in golf putts and long winter vacations in Florida and saying
daily prayers of gratitude that they had the wisdom, foresight and
luck to take early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   And they are not reluctant to add a note of thanks to Social
Security for helping to make it all possible.
</P>
<P>
   For those who scoff at early retirement as a fast track to
redundancy, who say that life without work well into one's 60s is,
well, pointless, the men in the clubhouse at Woodlake County Club
here in the piney woods of the Jersey Shore patiently acknowledge
that added years of leisure may not be for everyone. But they can't
hide their delight at having left the rat race before they were too
old to realize their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every plan to put Social Security back on a sound
financial footing calls for pushing back the retirement age from 65
and trimming the benefits of early retirees. But that proposition
flies in the face of Americans' conduct over the last three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of those choosing to retire before they are
eligible for full Social Security benefits has more than doubled,
to 71.1 percent of those receiving benefits in 1996, from 31.7
percent in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodlake golfers represent the trend. So do many people
interviewed recently in other towns in Ocean and Monmouth counties,
which have some of the highest concentrations of retirees outside
Florida and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   To this sampling of people who have retired early _ or are about
to do so _ the idea of of giving up the daily grind has enormous
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marvel at people driven by the need to make money and have
few other interests in life,'' reflected Joe Albowicz, 59, a former
mortgage banker who essentially retired four years ago when his
company was acquired by another and he was let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being without a job and an office gave me a chance to ask
myself, `Where am I going? How much money is enough?' '' he said
after completing a round of golf with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Albowicz, who has no pension, said he had accumulated enough
money to live the next quarter-century in comfort just by drawing
on the principal, without benefit of interest or dividends. Though
without a pressing need to draw an early Social Security retirement
benefit at age 62, he nonetheless said he was entitled to it, a
sentiment echoed by others who, for the most part, are more
dependent on the added income.
</P>
<P>
   Job dissatisfaction or burnout was often cited as the motivation
to leave work early for those who could afford to do so. For many,
fattened retirement programs, bolstered by zooming individual stock
investments, helped move up the target date for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that explained why the television set in the clubhouse
bar was tuned to CNBC, the financial news network, with stock
prices streaming across the bottom of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be the last generation able to enjoy this quality of
life in our early 60s,'' said Marty Stern, 63, a retired
manufacturer's representative. ``If in the future you can't retire
until you are in your 70s, you are going to be a lot older and a
lot less active. Who wants to sit at a desk all your working life
and then sit around when you retire?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're still alive and breathing at that age,'' said
another golfer, Ralph Arbia, half-jokingly. At age 59, Arbia has
the sturdy build of a much younger man.
</P>
<P>
   Death, particularly early death, was a specter haunting some men
who opted for early retirement. ``My father was 62 when he retired,
and he dropped dead a while later,'' explained Joe Mento, who
played a round of golf with some friends earlier this month to
celebrate his 63rd birthday, days after returning from a gambling
vacation in Las Vegas, Nev. ``Let's face it: Men die early, so why
hang around in a job if you can afford to have some fun before you
check out?''
</P>
<P>
   Mento sold his Brooklyn company, which rebuilt auto
air-conditioners, and moved to the Jersey Shore to be near his
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted out; it was just a way of making money, and I hated
it,'' he said with emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   For Luis Alvarez, 56, a construction worker on a road project in
Monmouth County, the issue is enduring the rigors of outdoor work
until he turns 62 and can collect early Social Security benefits.
He said painful arthritis in his hands nearly cripples him on cold
winter days, and speculated that those who wanted to push back the
Social Security retirement age never carried a lunch pail to a job
site on a raw day in January.
</P>
<P>
   As gingerly as Washington deals with Social Security, it seems
more loath to address the spiraling costs of Medicare. And for many
older workers, medical benefits are as much an issue in retirement
planning as is a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Lewis, 57, of Manalapan, N.J., is a supervisor in the
state employment services office in Freehold, and plans to retire
at the end of this year, citing job burnout. Her husband, Michael,
58, is a self-employed paperhanger with no pension or medical
benefits of his own.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lewis has 34 consecutive years of service with the state
and can claim a $30,000 annual pension with full medical coverage
for both her and her husband.
</P>
<P>
   When she turns 62, she expects to start receiving $980 a month
in Social Security payments, which she says gleefully ``will be
like winning the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words resonate with Bob Matthews, 64, who retired eight
years ago from teaching at a middle school in East Orange. ``I was
burned out dealing with all the problems of an inner-city school,
trying to figure out a way to retire at age 55 and keep myself
going on a pension until I was eligible for reduced Social Security
benefits when I turned 62,'' said Matthews, of Toms River. ``Then I
hit the state lottery jackpot of $1.5 million, which gave me a nice
annuity for 20 years,'' he beamed.
</P>
<P>
   The grin fading, he said that for future generations, hitting
the lottery may be among the few ways of achieving the dream of
early retirement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
