<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-LAURA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S DECISION TO SPARE LUCAS ANGERS FAMILY OF DEAD TEEN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By S.K. BARDWELL 
and PATTY REINERT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Laura Jean Donez had just started her first year of
high school. She was in the ROTC. She had a boyfriend, and
permission to wear makeup. Life was just beginning for the
16-year-old when it ended, brutally, in April 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Jean has been dead now nearly as long as she lived. The
horror of her death remains fresh for her sisters, and Thursday's
decision by the Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles to recommend
sparing the life of her killer, Henry Lee Lucas, left them
devastated.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, who is serving a life sentence for Donez's murder, was
scheduled to be executed in another case Tuesday. Rosanna Fuentes,
Laura Jean's big sister, had planned to attend. It would have been
the first time that the relative of a victim in a case other than
the one in which the death sentence was given would be allowed to
witness the execution.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, Gov. George W. Bush had taken the parole
board's recommendation and stopped the execution, commuting Lucas'
sentence to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very angry. I'm very disappointed in George Bush, and very
disappointed in our court system,'' Fuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely convinced that he killed my sister. He took the
... sheriff's deputies where he left her. They made a wrong turn,
and he corrected them. He lay down on the spot where he left her
body, in the position how he left her there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucas got life for what he did to Donez. The irony of it is not
lost on her sister: Noting she has fought for seven years to see
Lucas die, Fuentes said she wishes she could have used that time
and energy, instead, to fight for Laura Jean to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another year, another two years _ the rest of her life,''
Fuentes said. ``She hadn't even started living yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The events of that April 15 years ago are also seared into the
memory of Laura Jean's younger sister, Virginia Donez. Fuentes, who
already had married and left home, said Virginia and Laura Jean
were inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was my life,'' Virginia said. ``My mother, my father, my
big sister, my everything.'' The two had big plans: It was Laura
Jean's first year in Reagan High School in Houston and Virginia's
last year of middle school.
</P>
<P>
   The girls had often watched the Reagan ROTC drilling after
school, and Virginia said: ``It was a promise we made to each
other, that when we got out of middle school, we would join ROTC
and join the drill team, and we'd be in together when I got there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that was her first year and her last year, so that, that
plan didn't last too long.''
</P>
<P>
   That Friday was ROTC Day at Reagan, when all the members of the
corps wore their uniforms all day. When Virginia went downstairs in
the family's house that morning, Laura Jean was sitting in the
living room. She had a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't have any pantyhose,'' Virginia said, and that was
part of the required uniform for women in the corps. Missing any
part of that uniform resulted in an ``F'' in ROTC for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't want to get an F, so she said she wasn't going to
school that day,'' Virginia said. The younger sister told Laura
Jean she'd see her after school.
</P>
<P>
   She never saw her again.
</P>
<P>
   Before an older sister left that afternoon to pick up various
children at their schools, Laura Jean went to a hamburger joint
around the corner from their house.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got her hamburger,'' Virginia said. ``That's what the
coroner said.''
</P>
<P>
   But Laura Jean never made it home.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia was the one who called all Laura Jean's friends when
she got home from school that day and couldn't find her sister. It
was Virginia who called their mother at work; Virginia who argued
with police that her sister did not run away, would not leave
without telling her.
</P>
<P>
   A week went by. On Thursday, Virginia was walking down a school
hallway with a friend and saw Rosanna from the back. ``I yelled,
`Hey, Rosa,' and she turned,'' Virginia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she turned around, her face was so red, and so wet,''
Virginia remembered. ``I knew something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna cried and told her little sister, ``They found her, they
found Laura Jean.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Virginia said, detectives approached her with a little
cup. They uncovered it, and asked if she could identify the pieces
of jewelry inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew every piece by heart,'' she said. ``I started to cry. I
ran inside and ran into her room and just sat there a long time. No
one had ever told me yet she was dead, but I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Jean was found in thick woods near the Sam Houston
National Forest in Montgomery County, just north of Houston. She
had been beaten in the head, strangled, sexually abused and set
afire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
