</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-LUCAS-350&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR COMMUTES A DEATH SENTENCE TO LIFE TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush agreed Friday to save the
life of one of the nation's most notorious multiple murderers
rather than see him executed for a killing he may not have
committed.
</P>
<P>
   In commuting the death sentence of Henry Lee Lucas to life in
prison, the first time the governor has done so for a death row
inmate, Bush said Lucas was undoubtedly guilty of other crimes for
which he has already received several life sentences.
</P>
<P>
   But he noted that there was strong evidence that Lucas was in
Florida at the of the crime for which he faced death, the rape and
murder of an unidentified hitchhiker 19 years ago. He said Lucas'
confession, later called into question and recanted, was the only
evidence linking him to the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a supporter of the death penalty for those who commit
horrible crimes, I feel a special obligation to make sure the state
of Texas never executes a person for a crime they may not have
committed,'' Bush said in a statement. ``I take this action so that
all Texans can continue to trust the integrity and fairness of our
criminal justice system.''
</P>
<P>
   For many politicians, showing mercy to a killer could be risky.
But Bush, a leading, but unannounced contender for the Republican
presidential nomination, has balanced a reputation for conservative
firmness with a greater sense of moderation than some of his
Republican rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Rescuing Lucas is an especially delicate matter in Texas, which
leads the nation by far in executions, with many citizens clamoring
for more.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Bush accepted the recommendation Thursday of
the state Board of Pardons and Paroles, whose members he appointed.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 61, was scheduled to be executed by lethal injection at
6:01 p.m. Tuesday. He is already serving six life terms, two
75-year terms and one 60-year term for nine other killings.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, Lucas claimed to have committed as many as 600
murders in more than 20 states around the nation. But he later
admitted that most of these confessions were hoaxes, a revelation
that compounded his notoriety.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jim Mattox, a former attorney general who also supports the
death penalty, reviewed the case and concluded that work records,
statements from neighbors and other evidence offered compelling
evidence that Lucas was in Florida at the time of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused four months ago to spare Karla Faye Trucker, a
convicted pickax killer, despite the pleas of conservative
Christians that her life be spared because she had gone through a
Christian conversion and shown remorse.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison, Lucas seemed like an unlikely candidate for
clemency. He has been downright boastful of crimes including the
1960 slaying of his 74-year-old mother. His prosecutors have said
that they still consider him guilty of the ``Orange Socks'' murder,
the state's current attorney general has said he wouldn't question
a jury's decision, and state and federal courts have consistently
ruled that he received a proper trial.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was attending a meeting with Mexican governors in
Brownsville, on the border, took pains to distinguish the Lucas
case from others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am reluctant to second guess a verdict of a jury and the
courts, he said. ``However, the clemency process is intended as a
fail safe for unusual or exceptional circumstances. In this case,
at the time it made its decision, the jury did not know and could
not have known that Henry Lee Lucas had a pattern of lying and
confessing to crimes that evidence later proved he did not
commit.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's aides said he had left for a vacation and would
be not be available for any further comments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
