<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ENGLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLAND BEATS COLOMBIA 2-0
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ROGER COHEN     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ A revitalized England, inspired by the return of
midfielder David Beckham, surged to a 2-0 victory Friday over
Colombia and qualified for the second round of the World Cup
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia, with its aging team revolving around its captain,
Carlos Valderrama, could find little space for its close passing
game and bowed tamely out of the tournament. But for the remarkable
goalkeeping of Farid Mondragon, the defeat would have turned into a
rout.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, England striker Michael Owen is half the age of
Valderrama, and the difference showed. Owen brought new width and
pace to the English attack, constantly unsettling the Colombian
defense. His extraordinary acceleration left defenders gaping.
</P>
<P>
   With Brazil, Argentina, Chile, Paraguay and Mexico in the Round
of 16, Colombia's exit amounted to the one shadow on an impressive
Latin American performance in France.
</P>
<P>
   England, which came in second in Group G behind Romania, will
meet Argentina on Tuesday in what promises to be an explosive
battle. Romania will meet Croatia on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   The England-Colombia game, which ended the first-round matches,
was played in this soccer-loving northern city, where the joyous
expectation of World Cup games has turned into the nightmare of
violence. Helmeted police roamed Friday with tear gas and dogs, and
alcohol was banned in a 30-mile radius of the city. No serious
incidents were reported.
</P>
<P>
   After fielding defensive efforts in his team's opening two
matches _ a 2-0 victory over Tunisia and a 2-1 loss to Romania _
Coach Glenn Hoddle brought in Beckham, England's best passer who
plays for Manchester United.
</P>
<P>
   Beckham and right wing Darren Anderton repeatedly created space
on the right, and England's first goal came in the 20th minute.
Beckham crossed, the ball was headed out and Anderton blasted an
unstoppable shot into the top right-hand corner of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Nine minutes later, Beckham helped sting Colombia again. After
English midfielder Paul Ince was brought down about 25 yards out,
Beckham stepped up and curled a free kick over the Colombian wall
and just inside the post. Mondragon's flailing dive, as he scurried
to the right, could not stop the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was simply a superb free kick,'' Hoddle said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   With Colombia seldom threatening, except for briefly at the
start of the second half, England held on to its lead and could
have increased it. Owen, the third youngest player to play in a
World Cup, after Norman Whiteside of Northern Ireland and Brazil's
Pele, almost scored in the 60th minute when he raced past the
Colombian defense. But his shot was blocked by Mondragon.
</P>
<P>
   The striker, who was signed by Liverpool at age 11 and this year
became the youngest player to score for England, was irrepressible,
popping up on the left and right and creating spaces for England
Captain Alan Shearer, who twice went close with shots that were
saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``England closed down the spaces; they were simply better,''
said Hernan Dario Gomez, the Colombian coach.
</P>
<P>
   Passions should run high in England's game against Argentina
next week. The teams last met in the World Cup in 1986, four years
after the countries went to war over the Falkland Islands.
Argentina won, 2-1, in the quarterfinal match, thanks to two goals
by Maradona. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
