<HEADER>
A9472 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-ODYSSEY-SPI &LR;      06-26 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ODYSSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODYSSEY BEGINS ITS EPIC JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A 20-story high converted North Sea drilling platform called the
Odyssey has set out on an epic journey worthy of its name.
</P>
<P>
   The self-propelled platform is the centerpiece of a
multinational effort led by The Boeing Co. to do something never
attempted before _ launch large communication satellites into orbit
from the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   It left a Russian shipyard June 20 for Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   If the 70- to 80-day trip goes as planned, the Odyssey will
berth near the end of August at its future homeport about a mile
from the Queen Mary, the ocean liner turned tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The public can track Odyssey's journey to Long Beach on the
Internet at
www.boeing.com/defense-space/space/sealaunch/platformroute.html.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Odyssey, some 436 feet long and 220 feet wide, is
too big to pass through the Panama Canal, it was to have made the
trip to Long Beach around Cape Horn at the tip of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But project officials decided in recent days to send the Odyssey
through the Suez Canal, which is wider than the Panama Canal.
Odyssey will then cruise along on pontoons bigger than a Trident
submarine at a speedy 13 knots as it crosses the Red Sea and Indian
Ocean to Singapore, where it will have a straight shot to Long
Beach across the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The new route avoids Cape Horn, which boasts some of the most
ferocious seas in the world, especially at this time of year. It is
now winter south of the Equator.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were concerned about significant weather delays, and even
the possibility that a winter storm could damage the Odyssey,''
said Tim Hansen, Boeing project director for Sea Launch in Seattle,
of the route change.
</P>
<P>
   Had a severe storm come up during the trip around Cape Horn, the
plan was to have the Odyssey lay off the Faukland Islands until the
weather improved, Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   The new route will take about 10 days longer than had Odyssey
gone around Cape Horn in ideal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are adding a few days, we are lessening the
risk,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is already several months behind schedule and it is
important to get the Odyssey to Long Beach as soon as possible so
it can be readied for its historic first rocket mission, now
scheduled for October.
</P>
<P>
   That debut ocean launch from Odyssey of a Ukrainian-built Zenit
rocket carrying a U.S. satellite will mark not only a space-age
first, but an important new chapter for Boeing as it further
establishes itself as a major player in the booming and lucrative
launch vehicle business.
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, Odyssey has been at the Vyborg shipyard near
St. Petersburg, Russia, being outfitted with a rocket transporter
erector, rocket fueling equipment and other systems necessary to
turn the former oil-drilling rig into a floating launch complex.
</P>
<P>
   That work was to have been completed in January, but the Odyssey
did not leave Vyborg until June 20. It will stop at Kristiansand,
Norway, for supplies and some additional system testing before
heading off around Wednesday for the Mediterranean Sea and the Suez
Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's web site now shows the Odyssey's route as a dotted line
from Vyborg to Long Beach. Once the Odyssey leaves Norway, its
progress will be tracked by satellite and its location updated
daily as a solid line on the web site map, Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When that dotted line turns into a complete solid line, we
will be in Long Beach,'' he said. Odyssey's 14-acre homeport at
Long Beach is a converted Navy base.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Odyssey, the Sea Launch project also includes
the Sea Commander, a 660-foot, specially designed rocket-assembly
and mission control ship that will carry up to 250 technicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Commander, constructed at Govan Shipyard in Glasgow,
Scotland, left St. Petersburg on June 12 with the first Ukrainian
rocket. It will follow a different route than the Odyssey and will
pass through the Panama Canal before arriving in Long Beach July
11.
</P>
<P>
   Future rockets will be transported in pieces to Long Beach for
final assembly on the Sea Commander.
</P>
<P>
   Satellites will be mated to the 200-foot-long Zenit inside the
ship. The rocket will then be transferred to the Odyssey before a
10-day trip to the launch site near Christmas Island, which is
about 1,000 miles south of Hawaii. During that voyage, the rocket
is carried in a horizontal position.
</P>
<P>
   Before each launch, the Odyssey will be lowered into the ocean
to make it more stable. Its two giant pontoons can be filled with
15,000 tons of water, dropping the Odyssey so that 70 feet of the
20-story structure is below the water.
</P>
<P>
   The launch site in international waters was picked because it is
on the Equator, where the Earth's surface is moving eastward at
better than 1,000 miles per hour. A rocket fired there needs less
fuel to reach the 17,500 mph velocity need to reach orbit because
the the rocket is able to get the maximum boost from the Earth's
rotation. Less rocket fuel means less weight, which allows
increased payload capacity. What it all adds up to is that a rocket
launched from Odyssey can carry a heavier satellite at less cost to
the customer _ the key selling point for Sea Launch.
</P>
<P>
   Also, by firing the rocket in such a remote ocean location, the
first and second stages can fall harmlessly into the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is a partner in Sea Launch with the European shipbuilder
Kvaerner of Oslo, Norway; Russia's RSC-Energia in Moscow; and the
Ukrainian company Yuzhnoye/Yuzhmash.
</P>
<P>
   Energia is the company that launched the first Sputnik and
designed the Russian Mir space station. It is also building
hardware for the International Space Station, for which Boeing is
prime contractor. The Ukrainian company is best known for building
the former Soviet Union's most mighty ICBM, the SS-18, dubbed by
the Pentagon as ``Satan.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than building a rocket designed to destroy U.S. cities,
Yuzhnoye/Yuzhmash workers are now producing the Zenit rocket for
Sea Launch and other commercial customers. It has been used more
than two dozen times to launch satellites into space. The third
stage of the rocket is the Block DM, developed by RSC-Energia. It
has successfully flown more than 150 times.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has a 40 percent stake in Sea Launch. The other partners
have shares ranging from 15 percent to 25 percent. Boeing will not
give figures, but it reportedly has invested $500 million in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   It should prove to be a great investment, coming at a time when
not only more but new and cheaper rockets are needed to launch a
growing number of communication satellites. More than 1,000 such
satellites are scheduled to be sent into orbit over the next
decade, and customers must wait in line for available rockets.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Sea Launch has contracted 13 launch slots to Hughes
Space and Communications. The first rocket launched from Odyssey in
October will carry a new-generation Hughes communication satellite
into a stationary orbit 22,300 miles above Earth. Sea Launch also
has sold five launch slots to Loral Space &AMP; Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The project was conceived to win contracts from such
California-based satellite companies as Hughes. They can save money
because they do not have to pay the cost of transporting their
satellites to far-away launch sites in Russia, Japan, China or
French Guiana, as well as the two U.S.sites at Kennedy Space Center
and Vandenberg AFB in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   It can costs upwards of $500,000 to haul a satellite in a Boeing
747 to most present-day launch sites.
</P>
<P>
   Sea Launch plans about 6 launches a year, with a typical launch
costing from $70 to $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Odyssey may be left at its launch site so it
does not have to return to Long Beach after each firing. Instead
the Sea Commander would bring the rocket to the launch site. The
time saved could allow a dozen or more commercial launches a year,
the same number that now take place at launch sites such as Kennedy
Space Center, according to Sea Launch executives.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Commander can also process two Zenits at a time, so
Odyssey could launch two rockets before the command ship has to
return to Long Beach for another rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the launch site is in international waters, one
non-technical hitch has developed in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The South Pafific Regional Environmental Programme in Somoa is
concerned that launching rockets so close to Christmas Island will
cause ecological damage. Each launch, according to the
organization, will result in 36 tons of carbon monoxide and 181
tons of carbon dioxide being emitted into the lower troposhpere. In
addition, it says, 4.5 tons of residual kerosene will produce a
slick when the first two stages of the rocket fall into the ocean
after after blast off.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's findings have been sent to its 22 member
countries for possible action, though its not clear what, if
anything, could be done to prevent this latest and most radical
entry into the satellite launching game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
