<HEADER>
A9473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS &LR;      06-26 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN--ROBERTSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   Graf should draw &QL; 
curtain on career
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ Natasha Zvereva left the Wimbledon grounds
Friday thinking she had played the greatest match of her
journeywoman career.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe she had. You beat Steffi Graf on Centre Court here,
and you have a right to believe you have done something big.
Particularly when, going in, you stood 0-17 against Ms. Graf.
Natasha spoke afterward of her mental toughness, of how she blocked
out ``all the distractions'' and the abject futility of the past,
and never lost her way.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't mention was how Steffi, so tentative in her
shot-making and so lacking in the killer tenacity that carried her
to heights few players have known, never resembled the woman who
possesses seven Wimbledon titles.
</P>
<P>
   A woman who had lost only one match _ to Houston's Lori McNeil
in 1994 _ at the All-England Club from 1991 through 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If this is what it has come to for Graf, succumbing in straight
sets to a Natasha Zvereva in the third round, she should give
serious consideration to aborting her comeback and retiring with a
measure of dignity intact.
</P>
<P>
   We want to remember the real Steffi, the Panzer in a skirt, not
the slow-footed, error-prone cardboard cutout of same who went down
in 78 minutes to an opponent she had once routed 6-0, 6-0 in a
ridiculous 34-minute French Open final 10 summers ago.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence shattered
</P>
<P>
   Graf never broke Zvereva's serve. At the end, with a double
break point in hand and a chance to stay alive with Natasha's knees
all but shaking and her racket trembling, Steffi made two startling
errors, the kind the other player used to make against her.
</P>
<P>
   Zvereva thus would survive in spite of herself 6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not feeling any confidence out there,'' Graf said,
fighting back tears. ``I don't feel any rhythm at all.''
</P>
<P>
   She has a rebuilt knee but a broken game. At 29, with the
teen-age assassins such as Martina Hingis and Venus Williams taking
over the, ahem, women's tour, she has no hope of reclaiming the No.
1 ranking she held for the better part of a decade.
</P>
<P>
   No hope whatsover.
</P>
<P>
   And if Steffi can't be No. 1, settling for anything less seems
pointless.
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame she has to leave in such a fashion. Hingis snatched
Graf's crown by default, not by overtaking her, one on one, on the
court. Hingis ascended without having to defeat Graf in a major
final. But injuries are part of any sport, and Graf, who turned pro
shortly before her 14th birthday, has worn out. The grind defeated
her, not a peer.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, she had none. Granted, Monica Seles might have become
one, but we can't change her tragic history. We'll never know, will
we?
</P>
<P>
   Based on the evidence, on what we know, Graf deserves
consideration as the finest player in history. Her 21 Grand Slam
titles eclipsed Martina Navratilova's Open era record of 18 and
rank second only to Margaret Court's 24, nine of which were won at
the Australian Open during a period when many of the top players
didn't make the trip Down Under.
</P>
<P>
   The heart and guts that drove Graf to the top, then kept her
there through an extraordinary series of personal travails, stoked
her bid to return. But her talent, the third crucial part of the
equation, has been compromised by the extensive knee surgery that
followed a semifinal defeat at Roland Garros in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries take severe toll
</P>
<P>
   Other injuries, byproducts of her long period of inactivity,
have followed, setting her back repeatedly. In early May, after she
had to pull out of the French Open, Graf conceded in an interview
with Tennis magazine: ``I can't live my life like this anymore.
It's just too difficult to keep training for months and then have
another injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Training has consumed the entire day, every day. I've been
trying whatever it takes to come back, but I can't let this end up
ruling my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Another setback before Wimbledon, she swore, and she would call
it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time since I was 100 percent,'' Steffi said.
``I just hope 65 percent is good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, even against an aging doubles specialist like
Zvereva.
</P>
<P>
   Now? Graf said she would honor her commitments in the weeks to
come but stopped short of promising to play the U.S. Open, much
less returning to Centre Court next year. Although she would love
to equal Navratilova's record of nine Wimbledon titles and top
Court's Grand Slam total, she must realize how slim-to-none her
chances have become on either count.
</P>
<P>
   It's time, Steffi. It's time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
