<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HUNGARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: IS VIKTOR ORBAN TOO OLD TO LEAD HUNGARY? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TINA ROSENBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viktor Orban, the prime minister-designate of Hungary,
celebrated his 35th birthday last month, and many are wondering if
power has not found him too late.
</P>
<P>
   Across the former East Bloc some of the most dynamic,
Westernized politicians are relatively youthful. The most
influential are Sergei Kiriyenko, Russia's 35-year-old reformist
prime minister, and his deputy Boris Nemtsov, 38. In American terms
they are free-market Republicans on economics, liberal Democrats on
social issues. Orban, whose statist politics are just the reverse,
was like them once, back when he was young.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s Orban's party, the Federation of Young
Democrats, or Fidesz, was the most popular in Hungary. Its selling
point was that it was open only to those under 35. Hungary's youth
grew up in a free and Westernized country by communist standards,
without the listlessness of those who lived under a harsher regime.
To voters, youth meant energy and efficiency. It meant Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Fidesz was born at a Budapest college that Orban and several
other students established in the early 1980s so they could study
democracy, largely in English. Once communism fell, the students
formed Fidesz. Hungary already had a party of Vaclav Havel-type
dissidents, but many Hungarians considered them soft and naive, and
disdained their warnings about the shallowness of capitalist
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, the dissidents based their politics on morality,
not the political game,'' Orban told me in an interview in 1992.
``That is in the nature of the underground, and they have not been
able to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Fidesz, by contrast, was a party of Thatcherite sharks. Led by
the brash and arrogant Orban, its politicians dressed like models _
one parliamentarian posed for a Levi's ad _ and held campaign rock
concerts.
</P>
<P>
   While other parties' TV ads resembled the old commie spots
urging increased potato production, Fidesz ads looked like MTV.
They were produced by the East Bloc's first political consulting
firm, which Fidesz, touchingly naive about its cynicism, publicly
touted as a great stride westward.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next elections, in 1994, Fidesz did poorly.
Hungarians liked the image of Fidesz, but in an era of economic
trouble did not want to see their social programs cut. Orban began
to revise his ideas. Some Fidesz members split off and joined the
traditional dissident party. Those who remained emulated Orban's
about-face. He is now an economic populist and on social issues
takes a conservative Catholic line. The party no longer has an age
limit.
</P>
<P>
   As prime minister he will lead a coalition that includes a party
of small farmers, which has endorsed such dubious ideas as a ban on
foreign ownership of land. Orban himself has made some alarmingly
nationalist statements and unrealistic economic promises. The day
after the elections, Hungary's stock market dropped 8.7 percent.
Now he is once again shifting positions, trying to reassure foreign
investors that they should keep flooding Hungary. The stock market
has bounced back.
</P>
<P>
   Orban's politics may yet lurch a few more times before his
career is over, but so far, political expediency seems to have
trumped youth. Age is not a foolproof predictor of politics. The
worst leader in the former communist world is probably Belarus'
president, Alexander Lukashenko. A former director of a state farm,
he speaks of his admiration for Hitler and Stalin. His policies are
firmly frozen in the 1950s. He is 43. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
