<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKES-HNS &LR;      06-26 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, JIANG TO TARGET NUCLEAR WEAPONS, TECHNOLOGY DURING TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ A retired U.S. general recently recalled one version
of how China came to join the nuclear club.
</P>
<P>
   When military advisers proposed building an atomic bomb 50 years
ago, supreme leader Mao Tse-tung asked: ``Why should I do this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other nations have them,'' came the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess we should have some,'' Mao supposedly replied.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not China began developing its atomic arsenal in such
an offhand manner, there can be no question that when President
Clinton sat down Saturday for talks with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin, the proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology was a
key item on the agenda. It will also be one of the most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the important basket (of agenda items) is ... the
control of weapons of mass destruction,'' U.S. Ambassador James
Sasser said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Tests late this spring by India and Pakistan confirmed that two
more nations have nuclear capabilities. Given China's overarching
interests and intrigues in Asia, and the U.S. position as the
founding and leading member of the nuclear elite, the issue moved
to the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   How Clinton and Jiang can significantly advance the nuclear
debate is not clear, with any progress expected to be incremental.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating discussions are allegations that because of a
Clinton administration waiver, a U.S. satellite company, Loral
Space and Communications, gave China advice on making its missile
targeting more accurate. Loral's chief executive, Bernard Schwartz,
was the largest individual donor to the Democratic National
Committee in the 1996 election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   For China, the nuclear issue is difficult because it has been
accused of supplying critical nuclear technology to Pakistan as
well as exporting nuclear-capable missiles to Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the Indian and Pakistani tests, the Clinton
administration has been careful not to wag its finger at China, in
part because of the critical role Beijing can play in turning back
the nuclear clock in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of its history with both countries, China must be part
of any ultimate resolution of this matter,'' Clinton has said.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear highlight of Clinton's nine-day visit may be a
symbolic announcement that the nations have decided to remove each
other as targets for intercontinental nuclear missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Bates Gill, director of the East Asia Nonproliferation Project
at the Monterey (Calif.) Institute of International Studies, said
other deals might include a belated Chinese pledge to publish a
formal list of nuclear-related materials that cannot be exported.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of a formal list has been part of an argument that the
Chinese top leadership does not know exactly what military
officials are selling other nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Chinese themselves are finding and starting to
concede is that they do have some problems enforcing the writ of
the central government ... over the whole spectrum of people who
export technology or expertise,'' Ambassador Sasser told Agence
France-Presse.
</P>
<P>
   A series of steps could also be advanced to heighten contacts
between the Pentagon and the Chinese Defense Ministry _ an
unthinkable relationship only years ago and one which still
troubles some U.S. critics of Clinton's China policy.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the progress on nuclear and other defense issues is
slow, some Americans question truly engaging the Chinese on the
issues at all, primarily because the critics doubt whether the
Communist nation can be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who chairs the Foreign Relations
Committee, believes the White House has deliberately overlooked
evidence that China has sold M-11 missiles to Pakistan in order to
escape ratcheting up sanctions against Beijing _ including a ban on
satellite exports.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Oehler, former director of the CIA's Nonproliferation
Center, told Helms' committee earlier this month that there was
``no question'' that China had sold the entire missile, not just
parts as the administration contends.
</P>
<P>
   An administration finding that entire missiles were sold would
have triggered an automatic ban on almost all high-tech sales to
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has sought to shield China,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts support Clinton's plan for engagement on the
nuclear issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly cannot afford to isolate (China), particularly in
areas of such important security concern,'' Gill said. ``To do so
weakens our ability to understand Chinese views, Chinese
approaches, Chinese doctrinal and strategic viewpoints. And that
would be a mistake over the longer term.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is what is known as ``dual-use'' technology and
equipment _ goods and know-how that have both commercial and
military applications.
</P>
<P>
   Direct sales of military equipment from U.S. firms to China are
forbidden, even though some analysts believe that if a U.S. firm
does not sell the Chinese what they want, a firm from another
nation will.
</P>
<P>
   ``To what extent could you slow down China's progress if you
wanted to?'' asked Nicholas R. Lardy, a senior fellow at the
Brookings Institution in Washington. ``It's very modest, since
almost all the technology that China would like to buy from us they
can also buy from the French, the Germans or ... the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   But money can't buy everything, an analyst observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simple access to the technology does not translate, by a far
stretch, into deployed systems capable of threatening the United
States or other interests in the Western Pacific,'' Gill said. ``In
fact, in the case of China, they've had enormous difficulties
integrating these kinds of technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese nuclear program was initially subsidized by the
former Soviet Union, but the Beijing-Moscow relationship had turned
cold by 1964 when China exploded its first atom bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian and Pakistani tests are a dramatic reminder of the
edgy geopolitical game that has run for years across the Himalayas
and to the northwest, including one war between China and India and
three between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   China has long sided with Pakistan and believes that Washington
is equally firmly aligned with New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts contend that Beijing believes Washington knew
about India's plans to test and let them happen to throw the Jiang
government off balance. At any rate, Beijing almost certainly knew
in advance about Pakistan's retaliatory testing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, China and the United States have in response
``been more together than apart,'' said Bruce D. Larkin, a
political scientist at the University of California at Santa Cruz.
He finds that encouraging, given Beijing's history on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once upon a time, the Chinese line was leave us alone,''
Larkin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
