<SLUG> BC-BRAWLEY-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DENIES MOTION TO DISMISS SUIT AGAINST TAWANA BRAWLEY'S
ADVISERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ps) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The judge in the defamation case against Tawana Brawley's
advisers ruled Friday that the plaintiff, Steven Pagones, had
provided enough evidence to get his case to the jury, perhaps as
soon as early July.
</P>
<P>
   More than seven months after the trial began in the decade-old
dispute, Justice S. Barrett Hickman of State Supreme Court denied a
request by the three defendants, Alton Maddox Jr., C. Vernon Mason
and the Rev. Al Sharpton, to dismiss the lawsuit. The three men
were advisers to Miss Brawley, a black teen-ager who said she had
been raped by a group of white men in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suffice it to say,'' Hickman said in his ruling, ``in the
court's opinion, there was adequate evidence, both direct and
circumstantial, presented by plaintiff that would support a
reasonable jury finding that plaintiff Steven Pagones has
established actual malice with convincing clarity.'' The decision
was released in Poughkeepsie, N.Y., where the trial is being held.
</P>
<P>
   The courts require a finding of ``actual malice'' for there to
be a verdict that a public official was defamed. Actual malice has
been defined as reckless disregard for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Pagones was an assistant district attorney in Dutchess County
when the three advisers named him as one of Miss Brawley's
attackers. Pagones filed his suit in 1988, after a grand jury
exonerated him and discredited Miss Brawley's account.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman's ruling Frisday dismissed one count in Pagones'
complaint. The judge agreed with the advisers that one of the many
statements they made at the time was not defamatory. He also ruled
that another count was duplicative. But more than 20 claims by
Pagones that he was defamed were left intact for the six-person
jury to consider.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For days, Hickman has been meeting with the lawyers in an effort
to agree on the instructions that he will give to the jurors before
they begin deliberating. One disputed issue has been what the judge
will tell the jurors about how to evaluate the fact that the
defendants did not call Miss Brawley as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with the negotiations who spoke on the
condition of anonymity said Hickman has concluded that he will tell
the jurors that they can draw negative inferences, such as that
Miss Brawley's testimony might have contradicted the defense
position.
</P>
<P>
   Hickman has apparently concluded that, of the three defendants,
Maddox had the closest ties to the Brawley family, the lawyers
said, and therefore could have exercised some control over whether
she appeared as a witness. For that reason, they said, the judge
will tell the jurors that Maddox is the only one against whom they
can draw such negative inferences.
</P>
<P>
   Closing statements are tentatively scheduled to begin Tuesday
and may last at least until July 7. If the jurors find that Pagones
was defamed, a second phase of the trial would then be held to set
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Pagones, who is 36, said he was pleased by the judge's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am anxious to get this case to the jury and close this
chapter of my life,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
