<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEMOCRATS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE WHIPS UP TEXAS DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vice President Al Gore, shouting like a Southern
preacher, urged Texas Democrats on Friday to unite and defeat a
Republican ticket that is ``all sizzle and no steak.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on you Texas Democrats to do the hard work in the
trenches; register the voters, get that turnout and get people to
the polls,'' said Gore, who delivered the keynote speech at the
two-day state Democratic Convention, which will end Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president took credit for the booming U.S. economy,
saying that, thanks to the policies of the Clinton administration,
the unemployment rate is at its lowest level in 28 years and wage
growth has risen to its highest level in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also delivered several sharp partisan attacks, accusing
Republicans of selling out to tobacco companies and proposing to
squander a government surplus ``on large risky and indiscriminate
tax schemes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must reject the Republican agenda that is all sizzle and no
steak,'' Gore said. ``All show and no go. All windup and no pitch.
All hat and no cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president arrived in San Antonio Friday morning after
helping Garry Mauro, the Democratic nominee for governor, take in
an estimated $150,000 at a fund-raiser Thursday in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro introduced Gore, calling him ``the next president of the
United States,'' and describing Texas as ``Gore country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore is going to be coming back to Texas in the
year 2000,'' Mauro said. ``And when he comes back to Texas to
campaign in 2000, he's going to have a friend in the Texas
Governor's Mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is the odds-on favorite to become the Democratic nominee
for president in two years, but it is not certain that he will have
a friend in the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who is running for re-election but may seek
the presidency, is running far ahead of Mauro in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   And despite support by Gore and Clinton, Mauro has found it
lonely at the top of the ticket, as many Democratic office seek to
distance themselves from him.
</P>
<P>
   John Sharp, the Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor,
has declined to endorse Mauro. And the state's top Democrat,
outgoing Lt. Gov. Bob Bullock, has thrown his support to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   One statewide candidate who had no trouble embracing Mauro is
state Rep. Richard Raymond, the Democratic nominee in the race to
replace Mauro as state land commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support Garry Mauro and the whole Democratic ticket,'' said
Raymond, who pointed to Bush's huge lead in the polls to explain
Mauro's lack of explicit support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that the same people who are not overtly endorsing
Garry now would be glad to endorse him if he were up 20 points in
the polls right now,'' Raymond said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans reacted with glee at the lack of fervor for their
top candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas Republican team is united and strong,'' said Matt
Mathews, director of the Republican group Victory 98. ``The
Democrats won't even say whether they'll support, campaign with or
vote for Garry Mauro.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro spokesman Joe Cutbirth dismissed the comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been Democrats supporting Garry Mauro at every
rally he's been at,'' Cutbirth said. ``That kind of silly rhetoric
is what the Republicans use to get their names in the newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidates speaking Friday mostly stuck to
bread-and-butter issues such as education and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said Texas will make the oil and cotton booms of
yesteryear ``look like a barn dance'' if it makes education its top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hobby, the Democratic candidate for state comptroller,
underscored the importance of diversity, telling delegates that
``diversity doesn't mean quotas or set-asides; it means we are
inclusive in our processes.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the candidates _ including Sharp and Hobby _ delivered
lines in Spanish, as Bush did at the GOP state convention in Fort
Worth. Gore left out the verb in his: ``Mis amigos. Familias
fuertes,'' or ``My friends. Strong families.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving the closing speech Friday, the Rev. Jesse Jackson focused
on the need to help the poor. In an interview before he addressed
delegates, Jackson said many Americans feel insecure despite a
booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big challenge during this period of growth, prosperity and
wealth is to leave no American behind,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the convention has centered on partisan
politics, Gore used his visit to bring Texas some federal bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Gore announced that Texas will get a $76 million
``Welfare-to-Work'' grant, the largest any state has received, and
$6.1 million in retraining funds for employees at San Antonio's
soon-to-be closed Kelly Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have these good economic times in our nation's
economy, this is the time to fix the problems that have led to such
a high percentage of our people receiving welfare,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
