<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-CAMBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY HAS NO EXCUSES NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Canada)  (mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was nothing frail in his voice _ which neither broke nor
cracked _ making Marcus Camby's first major move as a Knick injury
free.
</P>
<P>
   He survived questions about his fragile past as a Toronto Raptor
and his slip-ups on and off the court Friday in his first full day
as an official Knick. His first full day of not being Charles
Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is going to replace Oak,'' said Camby, who on Wednesday
night was traded to the Knicks from Toronto for Oakley. ``He was
the heart and soul and a team leader. He's irreplaceable. I just
want to bring something different, a lot of versatility. I'm a guy
who can play a number of positions and give this team a different
outlook than it had in the past couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference is, there is a future to the Knicks now. If Camby
is not used in a trade to grab a point guard, he has a chance to
find inspiration from the veteran Knick players who will surround
him, and reach the star potential that is etched on his
6-foot-11-inch athletic frame. He can shoot the open jumper, rise
like a flare to block a shot and lap the rest of the plodding
Knicks in a race around the court. But there is his reputation for
being soft. All of these characteristics _ good and bad _ make him
the un-Knick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can fit in,'' Camby said. ``Playing physical is not
really one of my strengths, but I'm going to come here and add
something different. I think we're going to try and run this year,
make things happen and get it in the open court for some easy
baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds good, sounds fun. But Camby's flight plans will have
to revolve around Patrick Ewing, just like the rest of his
teammates. Unlike his life as a Raptor, Camby will not be a go-to
man, but a next-to-last resort when Ewing, Larry Johnson or Allan
Houston are covered.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this new, less-pressured status is best. His two years as
a star for an expansion team seemed to hinder Camby more than help
him. Instead of rising above a difficult situation, Camby seemed to
become a product of his environment in Toronto. He was inconsistent
and prone to injury as much as the Raptors' franchise was unsettled
and dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was really no stability,'' said Camby, who was the
second overall pick in the 1996 draft out of Massachusetts. ``We
had to worry about trades and who was going to be gone tomorrow. I
think I'm in a stable franchise now with a lot of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a firm footing, and no excuses now. If Johnson can play
nearly an entire season on a badly sprained ankle, Camby can learn
to play in pain, too. In Toronto, Camby called in sick because of
everything from back strains to ankle sprains, from the flu to a
jammed neck. Once, the former Raptors coach Darrell Walker _ in an
attempt to force Camby to play through pain _ refused to send a
trainer to aid Camby when he was wincing on the court.
</P>
<P>
   This is as good a time as any for Camby to shake the
hypochondriac label and take a step toward maturity in his contract
year. If this 24-year-old is to succeed, he cannot afford the
missteps that have dogged his past. In college, he violated NCAA
rules after accepting cash from an agent. Last summer in
Manchester, Conn., he was arrested and charged with possession of
marijuana, a charge that was later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through a lot of adversity in my life,'' Camby said.
``There are always going to be doubters out there, people who doubt
me as a person and as a player. My goal is to have the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to prove anything but to myself and to my
teammates. What people say is not going to make or break me.''
</P>
<P>
   No breaks, no cracks. Camby's first full day had a healthy glow
to it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
