<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' POTENTIAL OWNERS CONSIDER SITES IN NEWARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of New Jersey businessmen that plans to buy
the controlling interest in the Nets next week is still trying to
determine exactly where the team will play.
</P>
<P>
   The group, led by Stan Gale and Fin Wentworth of the
Gale-Wentworth Group of Florham Park, will pay $150 million to
acquire approximately 65 percent of the team in a deal that is
expected to be completed on Tuesday, the deadline for executing the
purchase option.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' lease at the Meadowlands expires in 2030, but there
are windows to escape in 2000 and 2004. The new owners hope to move
the team to Newark as part of a plan to revitalize the city, with
2004 a more realistic date for having a new arena ready.
</P>
<P>
   The group has the support of Raymond Chambers, a New Jersey
businessman and philanthropist who is chairman of the Amelior
Foundation and was active in bringing the New Jersey Performing
Arts Center to Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The group has three sites in mind, with its top choice being on
Market Street, near the Gateway Complex. The complex, a group of
four office towers, was bought by Steven Witkoff and the Witkoff
Group earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   An arena there would help extend the Newark revitalization
project out from the center of the city, along the Passaic River.
The arena would anchor the south end of the area and a minor league
baseball stadium would be be on the north end, with the Performing
Arts Center already in place in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Gale-Wentworth group envisions a move to Newark,
leaving the vacant arena to serve either as a conference center or
a retail shopping center, the New Jersey Sports and Exposition
Authority has not ruled out improving the Meadowlands' appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underlying all of this quietly is a move afoot to renovate the
Meadowlands property,'' said an official involved in the Newark
dealings. ``Being what's going on with other sites, it has become
clear that the Meadowlands needs to make the property more
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said the Giants might be looking to finance a
solution that could include a retail mall at the complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have the bells and whistles for public use that would
be available for the ticket holders,'' the official said.
``Literally adjacent to the arena, there would be stores, hotels, a
bowling alley, movie theaters, and all of it open to tickets
holders and also to the public. Now the Meadowlands would start to
be attractive again.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DON CASEY, the Nets' assistant coach, interviewed with the
Detroit Pistons on Thursday. The Pistons are seeking a veteran
coach to serve as the top assistant to ALVIN GENTRY. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
