<SLUG> BC-GLF-CADILLAC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER, WALKING, SHOOTS 75 ON BLISTERING DAY
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON, N.J. _ It's the game, and you have to honor it, no
matter how tired you are, no matter what the temperature, Arnold
Palmer suggested Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worst irons I ever hit in my life,'' he said after making a
bogey at the 12th hole of the Cadillac NFL Golf Classic Friday. ``I
can't even get the club face on them.'' But he said it so softly,
only a few people heard him. The game, after all, must be honored.
A bad hit merits a slight shake of the head. Nothing more.
</P>
<P>
   He was the oldest man on the course at the age of 68 but, except
for several short excursions in a cart, he walked the entire way as
the temperature hit 97 degrees and the humidity made it feel like
110. He realized that many in the crowd had come to see him and
wanted to see him walking, not sitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walk for a number of reasons,'' Palmer said. ``To stay in
shape. And mostly, it's a part of the game. People need that. Too
many players are out here saying, `I've got to do this.' But this
is a special game. There is no game in the world like this. When
you hit a bad shot, you can't get mad at anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth hole, in another grouping, the 60-year-old Charles
Coody had had enough of walking in the heat. Although he would end
up leading after Friday's opening round of this Senior Tour event,
which included National Football League players, he grew tired and
hopped into his cart. Who could blame him? Everyone was sweating
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer was in a good mood, though, at least on the back nine,
which he toured in 35. His drives were smashed 270 yards, nestling
into the fairways, and his irons, which troubled him earlier,
finally reacted as he wanted. He shot a three-over-par 75, leaving
him nine behind Coody and eight behind Bruce Crampton, the
defending champion, and Dave Stockton.
</P>
<P>
   When the round ended, Palmer went to the driving range and began
pelting balls. ``He's in a good mood now,'' said his friend, and
longtime dentist, Howdy Giles. ``He's really hitting the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Tom Wargo, one of his playing partners, was paying homage
to Palmer. Wargo was dressed nattily in an Arnold Palmer plantation
hat. He played Arnold Palmer clubs, as well.
</P>
<P>
   By No. 18, Palmer was feeling pretty good. He had made a couple
of birdies on the back nine and now he was set to drive on the
finale, a par-5. His other partner was Jim Harbaugh, the Baltimore
Ravens quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you hit it in two, I'll buy you a beer,'' Palmer said as
Wargo was set to tee off. Palmer outdrove his playing partners, as
he had throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go for it, Arnie!'' someone shouted in a plea from the 1950s
as his drive left him 320 yards from the hole, which measures 590
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer acknowledged the ovation that he hears at every golf
tournament as he approached No. 18 in three. He sank the birdie
putt, and heard more ahs than oohs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beat Wargo for a couple of beers on that last hole,'' said
Palmer, finally getting into a cart that was surrounded by
children, teen-agers and adults. ``That made my day.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
