<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COP-SEX-ABUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICER CONVICTED OF SEXUALLY ABUSING WOMAN IN CUSTODY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KIT R. ROANE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A city police officer was convicted Friday of
sexually abusing a 35-year-old woman who had been taken to the 79th
Precinct station house in Brooklyn after a fight with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Benjamin Rodriguez, 26, of Suffolk County was found
guilty of four misdemeanor counts of sexual abuse after a trial
before state Supreme Court Justice James Starkey, said Brooklyn
District Attorney Charles Hynes.
</P>
<P>
   Hynes said the officer had ``betrayed his badge and disgraced
himself.'' Rodriguez faces up to 90 days in jail when he is
sentenced Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The officer was acquitted of more serious felony charges of
sodomy and sexual abuse. His lawyer, Neil Cohen, said Rodriguez
continued to ``maintain his innocence,'' despite his decision to
resign from the police force.
</P>
<P>
   The abuse occurred in December 1996, after Rodriguez responded
to a disturbance at the woman's home, police said. Investigators
said she was taken into custody and charged with assault when her
husband said she threw an object at him during a fight.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who had apparently been distraught at the recent
death of her sister, was taken to the 79th Precinct station house
in Bedford-Stuyvesant, where Rodriguez began to check whether she
had any outstanding warrants, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At several points during this routine procedure, Rodriguez
groped the woman, moving her to a different portion of the station
house every time he was interrupted by noise or the presence of
other officers, investigators said. After the booking was
completed, they said, he gave the woman his beeper number and urged
her to call him. The woman's assault charge was later dismissed,
the district attorney's office said.
</P>
<P>
   The department's Internal Affairs Bureau began to look into
Rodriguez's behavior after an officer who had witnessed some of the
suspicious activity reported it, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose name was withheld by the district attorney's
office because of the nature of the crime, is suing the city, the
Police Department, police officials and Rodriguez for $171 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time my client closes her eyes, she relives a
nightmare,'' her lawyer, Peter Bongiorno, said. ``The fact that
this was perpetrated by a police officer, employed to protect
citizens, shocks the conscience. And the fact that it occurred in a
station house should spark an extensive investigation into police
procedures regarding the supervision of officers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
