<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REPORT CARD ON RUDY CREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Th New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, June 27:
</P>
<P>
   New York City school bells rang at noon Friday, tolling a
two-month summer break for the 1.1 million students in what is not
only the country's largest public school system but also one of its
sorriest.
</P>
<P>
   As Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew moves into his third year on the
job, this is still a system with an old physical plant and an
ungainly bureaucracy. Yet it is time to recognize a few green
shoots of hope in what has too long been a field of failure.
</P>
<P>
   Test scores are up, and while the improvement was so slight at
some schools that it could take years for students to perform at
grade level, the scores for both reading and math are moving in the
right direction. That is encouraging because the hurdles are going
to get higher. By 2001, students will confront tough new exams in
order to graduate. Crew has also announced plans to phase out
``social promotions,'' sending those who fail to summer remedial
care.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Regents is also thinking of more rigorous
qualifications for new teachers and teaching colleges. The Regents
want to add ``incompetence'' to the list of reasons a teacher can
be dismissed. The list of disappointments, however, is still long.
Shabby facilities are a scandal. The voters' rejection of a school
bond issue last fall, Gov. George Pataki's veto of $200 million in
repair funds this spring and a long history of incompetence at the
School Construction Authority have left most city schools horror
stories to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the school population booms with many new students
from immigrant families. Educators are also quietly frantic about
where they will house the 14,000 new pre-kindergarten students
added to the rolls next fall. Finding enough talented educators is
a constant concern. Crew tried hard to persuade Albany to remove
tenure protections from principals, but he sidestepped the hard
issue of removing untenured principals from some of the city's
least productive schools.
</P>
<P>
   Given the talent shortage, the departure for San Diego of
Anthony Alvarado, superintendent of lower Manhattan's District 2,
was a painful loss to the city and the chancellor, even though he
was sometimes at odds with the independent-minded Alvarado.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Crew seems to be winning control over this unwieldy
system and has asked for a new contract to let him finish out his
term in 2001. So far that looks like a good bet, especially if the
chancellor continues to tackle the big problems that have made it
difficult to provide sound teaching in safe buildings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
