<HEADER>
A9526 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC--WORLDCUP-HNS &LR;      06-26 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC--WORLD </SLUG>
 CUP-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For good or ill, England carries the day
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LENS, France _ It was England 2, Colombia 0 in regulation time
Friday. Which means the French police must continue to work
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Amid thundering support from its legion of fans, who were
raucous but well-behaved inside Stade Felix Bollaert, England
played near-perfect soccer on the way to the easy victory, a
second-place finish in Group G and a berth in the second round of
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The thorough whipping, which came thanks to the terrific play of
youngsters David Beckham, Darren Anderton and Michael Owen, was
good news for the English, who advance to face nemesis Argentina on
Tuesday in Saint-Etienne.
</P>
<P>
   But for the French security forces, who continued to scuffle
with bands of English hooligans outside the stadium before, during
and after the game, England's presence for at least four more days
probably was met with apprehension.
</P>
<P>
   Still, England deserved and earned this berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have scored four or five goals tonight if we
would have taken a few more risks,'' England coach Glenn Hoddle
said. ``I was extremely pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Extremely pleased only began to describe the sentiment of the
huge throng of English fans who found tickets, squeezed into Stade
Felix Bollaert and saw the all-around English game at its best.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderton rocketed the first goal just inside the near post
from 10 yards out in the 20th minute, the chanting, flag-waving and
singing began.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later when Beckham curved a free kick over the
Colombian wall and into the net from 25 yards away, a full-fledged
party broke out, with streamers sailing to the field from the
grandstands, a group of English fans doing the conga around the
stadium and noise reaching deafening levels.
</P>
<P>
   A few English fans climbed the restraining fence that encircled
the stadium, and others stood on railings in the second-level
terrace but were quickly restrained by security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, as tense and unsettling as things were outside the
stadium throughout the night, where more than 1,200 police officers
struggled with various groups of drunken, bottle-throwing
hooligans, the English team and its fans were calm and in control
inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always felt in control of the game,'' Anderton said. ``It's
great to be moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   It never was in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia controlled possession, especially in the first half,
but holding the ball only proved to be a farce. The Colombians
rarely finished buildups against the English defense and never had
a legitimate scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   England, on the other hand, worked its long-ball offense to
perfection, with Owen, the speedy 18-year-old striker starting his
first World Cup game, starting numerous attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Owen had a pair of wide-open chances to increase the lead in the
second half, but both were stopped by Colombian goalie Farid
Mondragon, who on this night was the best and busiest Colombian
player on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased with the way Michael played, but I'm pleased with
everybody tonight,'' Hoddle said. ``I knew we were ready to go, and
after I saw how we started the game, I knew the result would be a
good one. They didn't cause us a lot of problems, and we were able
to play our game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tactically, we got it right tonight. I couldn't believe all
the chances we created for ourselves. We're on our way, but let's
not get carried away. We've got a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what the French police must be saying, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
