<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic will be sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)  
 (af)  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELECOMMUNICATIONS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T in Deal for TCI &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a merger that is expected to change the way consumers buy and
use communications services, AT&AMP;T agreed to acquire
Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2 cable television provider, for
$31.8 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   C. Michael Armstrong, chairman and chief executive of AT&AMP;T, and
John C. Malone, chairman of TCI, said they wanted to market the
companies' services jointly as soon as possible, selling digital
phone and data services over the cable system. ... The European
Union approved Worldcom's &UR;  &LR; $43.7 billion deal for MCI, and American
regulators are expected to back it soon.
</P>
<P>
   To win European approval, MCI agreed to sell its Internet
business. Analysts said Britain's Cable and Wireless was the likely
buyer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Victory in Court &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft soared 5.15 percent on Tuesday after a
federal appeals court overturned a lower court's order against the
company, undercutting the government's central argument in its
antitrust suit. The stock ended the week at $104.4375.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling allows Microsoft to sell its computer operating
software with its Internet browsing feature. Windows 98 officially
went on sale last week, and even though Microsoft did not give the
new operating system software the same hype and publicity it used
to promote Windows 95 three years ago, the new version was snapped
up by consumers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Domino Effect &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With few signs that the strikes and layoffs now crippling
General Motors would be settled soon, the United Automobile Workers
union raised the prospect that its walkout could last into
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   The company called the strikes illegal and said it would seek to
take the UAW to speedy arbitration. Some 147,900 production workers
have been idled, and the economic effects of the shutdowns have
been slowly rippling across North America, hurting both big
suppliers like ITT &UR;  &LR; and businesses as small as workers' favorite
lunch counters.
</P>
<P>
   Farther from home, GM placed a vote of confidence in China's
auto market, despite Asia's slump. The company said it would invest
$100 million in a joint venture with a Chinese company to make
pickup trucks and sport utility vehicles in Shenyang. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ECONOMY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vigorous Growth &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Businesses and consumers went on a spending spree in the first
quarter, causing the economy to grow much more quickly than
originally believed. The nation's gross domestic product increased
at a seasonally adjusted 5.4 percent annual rate in the period, the
Commerce Department reported, revising the estimate a month ago of
4.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In May, however, orders for durable goods fell 2.6 percent, to
$184.3 billion, as the economic crisis in Asia reduced orders for
transportation- and electronics-related goods. But no matter how
strong the economy, consumers can find reason for complaint: Prices
of important services like dental care, hotels and car maintenance
have been climbing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bull Returns &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a two-week nap, the market's bull seemed to awaken with
new vigor. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed to a
record at midweek, but moved slightly higher on Friday, ending the
week at 1,133.20, still up 32.55, and the Dow Jones industrial
average, after crossing the 9,000 hurdle for the first time since
June 10, relaxed a bit, to end the week at 8,944.54, up 231.67.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks propelled the week's gains. Analysts said the
market's next direction would depend on second-quarter corporate
profits.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAXES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Break for Investors &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders agreed to give investors a break on
capital gains taxes, attaching the measure to an overhaul of the
IRS that appears headed for speedy passage. The holding period for
long-term gains _ which are taxed at a maximum of 20 percent _
would be cut to 12 months from the present 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-month rule, created a year ago in a compromise between
Republican leaders and the Clinton administration, greatly
complicated calculations for many taxpayers. And the Senate
approved a bill that would provide tax breaks for parents who save
for education costs, including private-school tuition. President
Clinton has said he will veto the legislation. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Less Production. Really? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 11 members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, along with Mexico and Norway, planned to cut production
by 3.2 million barrels a day to reduce a global oil glut. But
traders cast a jaundiced eye, noting that some OPEC members
traditionally ignore their quotas, and oil prices retreated from a
four-day rally, ending the week at $14.13 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The recent drop in oil prices has prompted several oil-producing
countries to borrow money and reduce social spending to make up for
lost income from oil exports. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Saks on the Block &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The board of Saks Holdings, the holding company for the New
York-based retailer, approved a sale or merger of the 97-store
chain, and retained Goldman, Sachs and Merrill Lynch to assist.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would end the majority ownership by Investcorp
International, the Bahrain-based investment bank, which has
profited by investing in other luxury retailers like Tiffany and
Gucci &UR;  &LR; and selling them.
</P>
<P>
   Investcorp bought Saks in 1990 for $1.6 billion, and sold 20
percent of Saks to the public in 1995 for $25 a share, or $425
million. Who might buy? Saks executives? Federated or May
Department Stores? Nordstrom? Harcourt General, which owns Neiman
Marcus?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows. Nor does anyone know how much a Saks sale would
bring, but $1.8 billion to $2.5 billion seems likely. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Forward and Backward &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IBM has begun the first large-scale production of a type of chip
combining silicone and germanium that could reduce prices and
improve performance and portability of cellular phones and other
wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   IBM began research on the chips in the early 1980s for mainframe
computers. ... Paul Kocher has the banks and credit-card companies
that market smart cards _ credit-card sized devices that contain a
tiny computer chip and can be used for storing so-called digital
cash _ gnashing their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   His four-man consulting firm, Cryptography Research of San
Francisco, &UR;  &LR; has figured out how to break into the cards' digital
codes. The firm is trying to warn businesses about the risks in
hopes of selling them possible solutions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FAT-FREE CONUNDRUM &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Believe It or Not, There's a Shortage of Butter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andre Boulanger shovels freshly made butter into the processing
line at the Cabot Creamery plant in Cabot, Vt. An unexpected
shortage of butter at a time when Americans appear to be obsessed
with low-fat diets is driving up the prices of foods like ice
cream, cheese and baked goods. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
