A9537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOT-WEATHER-NYT &LR;      06-26 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOT-WEATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALMY SUMMER TURNS INTO NEW YORK AREA INTO A SAUNA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Friday was the kind of day when the humid air was as
palpable as a damp rag. It was the kind of day that brought to mind
an expansive health-club steam cabinet or, if you were a Russian
immigrant lolling on the boardwalk in Brighton Beach, a banya, the
rustic Russian equivalent of a sauna.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A banya is pleasant,'' said Lisa Reysish, 63, as she paused in
desultory conversation with friends under a sun-scorched aluminum
awning at Brighton Fourth Street. ``This is not. At least you can
get out of a banya.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the weather dissolved into heavy thunderstorms and
brought the temperature down to the low 80s late in the afternoon,
the New York area was swimming through a steamy haze that left many
people hot, bothered and bewildered after an early summer of
relatively cool temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to recall, but it was just two weeks ago, on June
12, that the temperature in Central Park climbed to a high of only
65 degrees. During the first half of the month, it was never hotter
than 73. On May 13, it was a chilly 44.
</P>
<P>
   Summer appeared with the heat of a furnace Thursday, when a high
of 90 was recorded in Central Park. At 2:28 p.m. Friday, the high
in the park was 92. It may have been 8 degrees cooler than the 1952
record high of 100. But it still felt like 100, according to the
National Weather Service heat index, which factors in humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Cool sounded good to New Jersey beachgoers, who ventured into
the chilly 65-degree water off Manasquan and Point Pleasant, said
Frank Storino of Jenkinson's Pavilion, which operates the beach at
Point Pleasant Beach. In the Hamptons, 19-year-old John Miller
played hooky from his job at a Brooklyn warehouse, ostensibly to
attend a wedding but more to escape the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have tried to take off anyway,'' he said. ``It's a
metal building. I feel sorry for the people who were there today.''
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison reported the third-highest electricity usage
in the utility's history, although spokesman Michael Spall said it
had no problem meeting demand. Although no records were broken
Friday _ the highest-ever demand was on sweltering July 13, 1997 _
Spall said they might fall later this summer due to low office
space vacancies in New York City and increased air-conditioning
usage.
</P>
<P>
   However, Connecticut power companies, hampered by the shutdown
of Northeast Utilities' nuclear power plants two years ago, were
forced to put emergency conservation measures into effect as the
temperature climbed in the early afternoon. The companies appealed
to commercial and industrial users to cut back on their power use
and instituted brownouts across the state by reducing voltage by 5
percent. Across New England, other electric utility officials also
asked customers to shut off unnecessary appliances to help conserve
energy.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the Fire Department said it responded to 63
incidents of heat stroke or heat exhaustion between midnight and
4:30 p.m., when rain broke the heat spell. Area airports reported
delays of up to one and a half hours for takeoffs, reflecting not
only stormy weather elsewhere in the country but also the effects
of heat and humidity on aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   That same brand of heavy heat affected male sartorial habits,
making many men curse the day the necktie was invented. In midtown
Manhattan, lawyers and executives walked tieless, coatless and in
one or two cases, shirtless.
</P>
<P>
   At the tie counter at Saks Fifth Avenue, Charles Worrell
admitted that even he, a tie salesman for eight years now, will go
so far as to loosen his when he leaves the air-conditioned comfort
of the store. ``Sales go down in the summer,'' he said. ``Today is
a really slow day.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, at the Fifth Avenue entrance to the Plaza Hotel, a
doorman, Ed Trinko, said he just puts his wartime experience to use
when the weather turns dangerously hot. Decked out in brimmed hat,
jacket, white gloves, black slacks and heavy black shoes _ plus
tie, of course _ he advised a course of steadfastness and plenty of
liquids.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is not to go inside,'' he said. ``You go inside, you
come out, you feel hot. I stay outside six, seven hours. I drink a
lot of club soda. You get a little breeze from the park. I got
training for being in heat in Vietnam, in the jungles. As soon as I
get off, I put on shorts, loafers. I feel great.''
</P>
<P>
   In Long Island City, Joe Rossi, manager of Tops Appliance City,
could feel the scorcher coming. He said he ordered 10 additional
sales people in to work Friday. By 1 p.m., he said, the store sold
300 air-conditioners _ almost double the 160 sold on the same day
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm burning up,'' explained one happy customer, Faye Evans,
51, who was buying her second air-conditioner. ``I'm in an
apartment over a boiler. In my bedroom, it's as hot as it is
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   If the weather seems capricious this year _ remember March had
both snow and balmy 80-degree weather within the space of a week _
that's because it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hostage to Mother Nature,'' said Ingrid Amberger, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service office in Upton,
N.Y., which monitors New York City, Long Island, southern
Connecticut, northeast New Jersey and the lower Hudson Valley.
``There's just been a slight shift in the jet stream. Before we
were on the cool side and now we're on the hot side. It's not the
end of the world _ it just feels that way.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the weather in the New York area should begin to cool
off a bit today, with a high temperature in the mid-80s, and by
Sunday daytime temperatures will drop to the 70s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
