<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8-FIGHT, $30 MILLION DEAL MAKES TRINIDAD SMILE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Felix Trinidad, the International Boxing Federation welterweight
champion, was beaming Friday, because for the first time in a long
time he felt like a star. Main Events and HBO held a news
conference to announce an eight-fight, $30 million deal with
Trinidad, one of the best, but most unheralded boxers in the most
competitive division in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a star right now,'' Trinidad, a 25-year-old from Puerto
Rico, said through an interpreter. ``With Don King I didn't receive
the treatment as a star. With this contract I expect HBO and Main
Events to put me on the level of a star.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes as expected, Trinidad, who has a 33-0 record (28
knockouts), will start his tenure with Main Events and HBO with a
flourish, going against Ike Quartey, the World Boxing Association
welterweight champion, on Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the signing of Felix Trinidad to take Main Events
into the next century as far as big-time boxing is concerned,''
said Dino Duva, the Main Events president.
</P>
<P>
   It was an even bigger coup for HBO, which now has all of the
welterweight world champions _ Quartey, Trinidad, and Oscar De La
Hoya, the World Boxing Council champion _ under contract. So, the
network will be able to set up a long-talked-about match between
Trinidad and De La Hoya.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest fight in the sport is Trinidad versus De La
Hoya,'' said Seth Abraham, president of Time-Warner/HBO Sports.
``We're square in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham said the earliest possible date for that fight would be
next May and the latest is September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Duva, Trinidad, and his attorney, Jose Medina, expect Don King,
Trinidad's former promoter, to challenge his new contract with Main
Events. Medina has filed a lawsuit against King in U.S. District
Court in Manhattan seeking an injunction against King to keep him
from interfering in Trinidad's new contract. King is disputing
whether Trinidad is free to sign a new contract, because he
contends that Trinidad's contract has two more years left. Trinidad
claims his contract with King expired June 11.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese's Future
</P>
<P>
   Lou Savarese put an end to James (Buster) Douglas' dreams of any
rematches against Mike Tyson or Evander Holyfield in the near
future with a first-round technical knockout on Thursday night's
pay-per-view card at Foxwoods Resort Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Savarese's thundering right hands exposed Douglas' chin as being
brittle now and threw a wrench into promoter Bob Arum's plans to
make those lucrative matches for Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Arum is Douglas' promoter, but he did not have an option on a
championship fight for Savarese, who will continue to be promoted
by Cedric Kushner. Whether Savarese can now take Douglas' place in
the heavyweight championship derby remains to be seen. After the
Thursday night bout there was talk that Savarese might get a shot
at Lennox Lewis, the World Boxing Council champion, if a
Lewis-Holyfield unification bout can not be made by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   A Reid Homecoming
</P>
<P>
   It will be something of a homecoming for David Reid tonight when
the young junior middleweight with a 9-0 record fights from the
Apollo at Temple University.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, a Philadelphia native and the only U.S. boxer to win a
gold medal in the 1996 Atlanta Games, will meet the wily veteran
Simon Brown (47-7), who is coming off a February knockout loss to
Bernard Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Mosley (27-0), the IBF lightweight champion, will defend
his title against Wilfrido Ruiz (25-3) of Monteria, Columbia.
</P>
</TEXT>
