<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-ENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLAND ADVANCES _ PEACEFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENS, France _ This seemed a recipe for disaster. Approximately
70,000 fans, some hoping to instigate a ``world hooligan
championships,'' were to invade a pastoral setting north of Paris,
one of the smallest venues ever to play host to the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   But the anticipated problems were either controlled or dispersed
by limiting the supply of alcohol and discouraging ticket-less fans
from congregating for England's 2-0 victory over Colombia Friday,
which enabled the Britons to advance to the second round. Just to
make certain, French riot police turned the area into a garrison,
turning away suspected troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   The Stade Felix Bollaert, which has a capacity nearly 7,000
greater than Lens's population, was surrounded by police carrying
tear gas guns and clubs and leading attack dogs, determined to
avoid the incident which left gendarme Daniel Nivel, 43, comatose
after last Sunday's Germany-Yugoslavia game.
</P>
<P>
   But if English hooligans, and possibly rival Germans,
represented a threat outside the stadium, English fans inside
provided song and dance in a festive celebration of their team's
victory. It was easy to see why so many of their countrymen would
want to be part of such a passionate display, which included an
effective and inspiring brand of soccer by the national team.
</P>
<P>
   The English fans far outnumbered the Colombians and were in a
peaceful and celebratory mood, filling the stadium with banners and
flags and chanting and singing loudly enough to reach the English
Channel 50 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   They had much to cheer as England qualified to meet Argentina
Tuesday in St. Etienne.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Owen, an 18-year-old Liverpool striker, started for the
first time in the World Cup and had a field day.
</P>
<P>
   Owen helped set up the first goal by easily outmaneuvering
Antonio Moreno and sending a cross, which was headed away by Jorge
Bermudez. Darren Anderton settled the clearance and roofed a shot
from the edge of the penalty area in the 20th minute. Ten minutes
later, David Beckham crashed a free kick into the upper left
corner, igniting a conga line in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   Owen was too active and quick for the much bigger, more
experienced Moreno. And he typified England's greater
maneuverability in midfield, where Beckham and Paul Scholes were
constantly threatening. The Colombians, eliminated in the first
round for the second straight World Cup, had several enterprising
forwards despite having sent Faustino Asprilla home, but none were
as effective as Alan Shearer.
</P>
<P>
   And Carlos Valderrama lacked his usual magic touch, though coach
Hernan Dario Gomez crowded the midfield with too many like-minded
players and failed to find a complementary strike force.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's starting lineup failed to connect in the first half,
relying on Valderrama, Harold Lozano, and Freddie Rincon, all
possession-type midfielders. Then Gomez brought on another, Victor
Hugo Aristizabal, in the second half. Gomez added size at forward,
replacing Antony de Avila and Colombia's answer to Owen,
21-year-old Leider Preciado, with Hamilton Ricard and Adolfo
Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   The Colombians became more dangerous on offense but more at risk
defensively. Bermudez and goalkeeper Farid Mondragon prevented a
worse rout.
</P>
<P>
   Though none of the English players showed the individual
imagination of Paul Gascoigne, the team is creative enough. Beckham
and Scholes, bolstered by Paul Ince in midfield, provided dynamism.
And the strike force was effective, especially with Owen replacing
Teddy Sheringham alongside Shearer. Sheringham risked being cut
after a wild drinking binge in Portugal just before the World Cup
and appears superfluous now. Owen provides England with a younger,
better-behaved, and, simply, better player.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
