<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (ja) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS FINISH STRONG WEEK AS S&AMP;P 500 HITS RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The stock market rallied to close a week of solid gains, despite
resilient fears about the year-old economic crisis in Asia and its
eventual impact on corporate profits in this country. Investors bid
many blue-chip issues into record territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 3.92 points, to a
record 1,133.20, giving it a 3 percent gain for the week and nearly
16.8 percent gain for the year. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 8.96 points for the day and 231.67 points for the week, or 2.7
percent, to close at 8,944.54. The average is 3 percent below its
record high of May 13.
</P>
<P>
   CLEARER SEXUAL HARASSMENT LAW
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court clarified the law on workplace sexual
harassment, making some lawsuits against employers easier to win
while limiting the legal exposure of companies that have effective
anti-harassment policies. The rulings were praised by management
and civil rights groups for bringing coherence to the law and
providing incentives for preventing harassment and dealing with
problems.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN DEBT SEEN AS WEAKEST LINK
</P>
<P>
   There is increasing agreement among Japanese politicians that
the economic malaise afflicting Japan and indirectly threatening
the global economy centers on a problem that the Japanese
government is only beginning to confront: the mountain of bad debts
at the nation's banks.
</P>
<P>
   CBS TO SELL NUCLEAR OPERATIONS
</P>
<P>
   CBS agreed to sell its Westinghouse nuclear and government
services operation to a joint venture formed by Morrison Knudsen
Corp. and a British nuclear-fuel processor for $238 million in cash
and the assumption of $950 million in liabilities and other
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   SPENDING AND INCOMES STRONGER
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending and incomes rose in May, demonstrating the
economy's firm underpinnings as brisk domestic demand offset the
impact of the Asian slowdown on manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE DEAL IN CANADA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fonorola, Canada's fourth-biggest long-distance provider,
advised shareholders to accept Call-Net Enterprises' sweetened
takeover offer of $1.2 billion (U.S.) and the assumption of debt.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA TRIP AVOIDS BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   So far during his trip to China, President Clinton has played
down commercial links between the two countries. The president's
focus on diplomatic strategy, culture and tourism instead of
commerce is a sign that business ties have in some ways outgrown
the contract-by-contract nurturing of the 1980s and early 1990s.
Indeed, investing in China has gone from adventurous to ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   China gave the United States its strongest assurances yet that
it does not plan to devalue its currency, the yuan. The Clinton
administration fears that a devaluation by Beijing could spark a
wave of devaluations across Asia.
</P>
<P>
   KARL MARX, MARKET VISIONARY
</P>
<P>
   The globalization of national economies? Periodic crises like
Asia's financial turmoil? Long before any Wall Street pundit, Karl
Marx foresaw how the wealth-creating power of capitalism would
conquer the world. (Of course, he may not have been particularly
pleased with that outcome.) Still, on the 150th anniversary of The
Communist Manifesto, readers on the political left and right have
marveled at how Marx's description of capitalism resembles the
restless, anxious and competitive world of today's global economy.
</P>
<P>
   DEAL NEAR FOR SWISS BANK UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Assicurazioni Generali SpA of Italy is close to buying Swiss
Bank Corp.'s Banca Svizzera Italiana unit for as much as $1.3
billion in a bid to expand its money-management operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
