<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-MAIN27-COX     06-26 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-MAIN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking to link school lunchroom, water park
 &HT;    By Diane Lore and M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Public health officials confirmed Friday that a
strain of E. coli that infected at least four children swimming at
White Water park has the same genetic fingerprint as bacteria found
in hamburgers served this spring in a Madison County elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   All of the samples also were found to match E. coli samples from
two Hull, Ga., sisters who did not visit White Water, but were
confirmed to be infected on June 2 and released Friday from
Egleston Children's Hospital in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond a ``laboratory match,'' there is no evidence linking
the burgers, the sisters and the water park, said Dr. Kathleen
Toomey, director of the Division of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a connection is discovered, she said, it isn't
significant to the investigation because there is no continuing
risk from the beef, which was recalled in May after being sent to
Madison and three other Georgia county school districts. Anyone who
had eaten any of it would have become sick by now, Toomey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's scientifically interesting ... but in this case, that's
not really what we care about,'' she said. In fact, Toomey said the
investigation is not focusing on a ``Baby Zero'' _the first child
to contract E. coli and spread it to others _ but how the cluster
at White Water park happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all part of unraveling the mystery, but from a public
health perspective, that's not the key,'' she said. ``What we are
interested in is how this transmission can occur in the water, and
understanding how kids use public pools and how E. coli can
overwhelm chlorination in a fecal accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen children are confirmed with E. coli O157:H7 that was
traced to White Water park _ nine from Georgia and four from
out-of-state, Toomey said. Stool samples from four of those
children were also subjected to a test called ``pulsed-field gel
electrophoresis'' (PFGE) that can distinguish among subtypes of the
O157 strain by reading its genetic pattern. All four, the agency
said, have identical genetic profiles.
</P>
<P>
   That profile also matches PFGE tests done on samples from the
sisters from Hull, which is in Madison County, about 70 miles east
of Atlanta. After public health investigators interviewed the
families, they found no link between the sisters and the White
Water cases.
</P>
<P>
   They also have failed to find a connection between the sisters
and contaminated meat that was served at Danielsville Elementary
School. The frozen beef-and-soy patties, manufactured by a Florida
firm in December, were recalled in mid-May because they were
believed, but never proven, to have caused a case of hemolytic
uremic syndrome (HUS), a life-threatening complication of E. coli
infection, in a Danielsville boy in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show that just because you've got the same
genetic material doesn't necessarily mean you have the same
original source,'' Toomey said. ``It could be that that particular
genetic strain is just more prevalent in a given community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Danielsville HUS case was confirmed Friday by the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, the agencies said, the boy developed symptoms
consistent with E. coli O157 infection _and which rapidly
progressed to HUS _ after eating part of a burger in the
Danielsville school lunchroom. The child, whom officials would not
identify, was admitted to an Atlanta hospital April 27; he is
diabetic and has other chronic health problems.
</P>
<P>
   The case was reported to the district and state public health
departments, and then to the school system, which told its
supplier, Bauer Meat Co. of Ocala, Fla., of the suspected link. The
company tested the meat and found O157; after consultation with
USDA, the company voluntarily recalled 38,000 pounds of fresh and
frozen patties on May 15. Roughly 11,800 pounds had gone to four
Georgia counties _ Madison, Hall, Green and Forsyth _ but officials
said none was consumed outside Madison County. The rest was sent to
overseas U.S. military facilities and several North Carolina school
districts, where no illnesses were reported.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, the Madison County school board notified parents that
meat patties contaminated with the O157:H7 strain possibly had been
served until May 8, and testing of patties began May 9.
</P>
<P>
   The Danielsville boy was released from the hospital May 2.
Because no cultures were done on his stool, he was never
definitively diagnosed with O157, said USDA spokeswoman Jacque
Knight. But the culture done by Bauer on its beef product was sent
to USDA's outbreak lab for PFGE analysis. The genetic fingerprint
obtained was lent to the CDC and to Georgia this week, and matched
the genetic profile from the White Water cases and the Hull
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be surprising if the strain in any sort of cluster
would resemble a strain that has been seen before,'' said Dr. Larry
Slutsker, a CDC epidemiologist and E. coli expert. ``One might
expect that a waterborne transmission (such as at White Water)
would ultimately have its source in a foodborne illness from
somewhere else. But it doesn't change the message that we need to
get out, about keeping children with diarrhea out of public
pools.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDC and the Georgia public health department are
collaborating to complete genetic tests on the remaining White
Water cases, Slutsker said. Results are expected by early next week
and will be shared with health departments in other states; if they
match with genetic profiles done on potential out-of-state cases,
the extent of the White Water outbreak will be defined.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer Meat Co. officials declined to comment, referring phone
calls to the National Meat Association, a California-based industry
group.
</P>
<P>
   There is no known link between the recalled Bauer meat products
and any of the White Water cases, said Rosemary Mucklow,
association director. She said the USDA had not notified her or
Bauer about a genetic link between the White Water cases and the
beef that Bauer voluntarily recalled May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just doesn't sound possible,'' Mucklow said. ``I haven't
heard there is a genetic link to any recall, and the USDA normally
alerts us immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Mucklow said the meat industry is instituting safeguards aimed
at killing the O157 microbe, changes that began after the 1993 Jack
in the Box outbreak that killed four children and sickened
hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying very, very hard to ensure the safety of the
meat. We've done all kinds of interventions to make sure this
microorganism doesn't get in,'' Mucklow said. One new method is
aimed at destroying the bug with the 160-degree temperature known
to kill it by using a ``steam vacuum'' that blows steam over the
carcass.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, public health workers are waiting for
confirmation on Monday from several lab tests on remaining cases,
said Joyce Goldberg, DPH spokeswoman. They also are interviewing
families and friends about habits in the past two weeks, including
restaurants they visited, food eaten, handwashing, children's
playmates and other people who might have come in contact with the
sick patients.
</P>
<P>
   And she said several more cases are expected to be confirmed in
coming weeks, partly because public health officials are expecting
a second wave of infections _ caused by those initially infected
spreading E. coli to friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to see some cases crop up as secondary infections,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
