<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9562 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-OUTBREAK-COX     06-26 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-OUTBREAK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E. coli investigations are familiar choreography for the
scientists
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The investigation into this week's outbreak of E.
coli O157:H7 followed a pattern that's puzzling to the public but
comfortably familiar to disease scientists. Like a soccer ball
being moved downfield, detection moves from field work to lab work
and back again - and like a well-strategized play, it eventually
ends up at the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Infection with E. coli O157:H7, the toxin-producing strain of a
usually benign intestinal bacteria, is an immediately reportable
disease in Georgia. That means that, whenever a child or adult
seeks help for symptoms that resemble those of E. coli - chiefly
severe and bloody diarrhea - health-care workers must report the
case to the county or district health department. Those reports are
sent to the state Division of Public Health. And if something
appears unusual - such as a high number in a small area or a short
period of time - that triggers an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Patients, family members and associates are interviewed for
common traits and experiences. Investigators log and track
activities, diet, places visited and other factors that may link
the cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start by basically doing shoeleather work: Is there some
way the cases are related?'' said Dr. Larry Slutsker of the
foodborne diseases branch of the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, which informally advised the state this week on the
White Water outbreak. ``Did they attend a common event, eat a
common food, swim in a common pool?''
</P>
<P>
   Once the epidemiologists - scientists who specialize in studying
how diseases move through a population - think they've identified a
cause or common route of transmission, the investigation may move
to the lab for a second stage of scientific inquiry. There they can
examine whatever materials seem important to the case: food, water,
materials from the environment, or samples taken from patients such
as blood or stool.
</P>
<P>
   In the White Water outbreak, lab work has required several
steps.
</P>
<P>
   First, technicians cultured stool samples from the patients
believed to have been infected with E. coli at White Water.
Cultures, grown on a gel medium, were done to establish whether the
infection was E. coli; two additional steps sought to determine
that the strain of E. coli was O157:H7 -- a life-threatening strain
-- by identifying two proteins found in two positions on the
bacterium's outer coat.
</P>
<P>
   In some of the cases, technicians performed a final test called
pulsed-field gel electrophoresis, which can distinguish between
subtypes of O157 by determining a unique ``genetic fingerprint''
linking the cases to a single, common source.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only four of the 13 confirmed cases of E. coli traced
to White Water have been linked, through this genetic technique.
Health officials are awaiting test results on the others.
</P>
<P>
   Some times, lab results force investigators back to the field
for additional interviews. Other times, the initial field work
points so strongly to a potential source of the disease that lab
work merely confirms the guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to formulate a public health action early on,''
Slutsker said. ``Sometimes you may be in the position of
implicating a food or an activity with just epidiological
information, without the benefit of lab confirmation.''
</P>
<P>
   Every step - identifying a disease, notifying authorities and
attempting to control it - takes at least a few days, and many
diseases resolve on their own, without treatment. Investigators are
frequently in the position of chasing something that remains just
out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a produce item is involved, it may no longer be on the
market; if it's an illness in which people were sick two, three,
four weeks ago, you're unlikely to be able to culture an organism
from them,'' Slutsker said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigations can take from a few weeks to months, depending on
many variables from the type of organism to the number of steps it
passed through to reach its eventual victims. But technology is
allowing shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
