<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9567 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-1STLD-WR     06-26 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SUMMIT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RECEIVED BY CHINESE PRESIDENT NEAR SITE OF MASSACRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs to include additional material throughout. No pickup.)  (See also: CHINA-TIBET, CHINA-TIANANMEN, CHINA-RUBIN) 
(EDS: Will update through the night as developments warrant.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(th) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ President Clinton was received by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin on Saturday in a military ceremony on Tiananmen Square,
the vast expanse through which modern Chinese history has flowed,
from the declaration of the communist state in 1949 to the crushing
of democracy demonstrations 40 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood mute throughout, as is customary at such arrival
ceremonies. He and Jiang then inspected army troops and reviewed an
honor guard on ground that human rights advocates around the world
consider stained with the blood of martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has defended his appearance before the Great Hall of the
People on the edge of Tiananmen Square as the expected behavior of
a state visitor to China. The square was the site of student-led
demonstrations that ended in terror and bloodshed on June 3 and 4,
1989, when Chinese troops moving into the city center mowed down
hundreds of civilians. Clinton was expected to discuss the 1989
demonstrations in his remarks later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stood stiffly as the People's Liberation Army band
played ``The Star Spangled Banner'' and an evocative 21-gun
cannonade rang out across the square. The gunfire continued through
the playing of the Chinese national anthem, ``March of the
Volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   The two presidents then inspected an honor guard in green, white
and blue uniforms bearing rifles with fixed bayonets.
</P>
<P>
   As they finished reviewing the troops, Clinton and Jiang turned
and walked along a red carpet toward the steps of the Great Hall of
the People, smiling and chatting. In 13 minutes, the ceremony,
which stirred such memories and generated such controversy, was
over.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony came at the start of a one-day summit meeting that
had already been marred by the detention and harassment of several
Chinese political dissidents. The dispute forced Clinton and his
senior aides into a defensive crouch and threatened to undermine
China's central goal of the summit _ a portrait of a ``new China''
of greater economic and personal freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance on the square Saturday morning dramatized
this nation's struggle between memory and forgetting.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leadership hopes to consign to history the events of
the spring of 1989, when indelible images of blood-letting in the
streets and of a lone protester standing before a column of tanks
were broadcast around the world. The events are the subject of a
continuing dispute in China.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the party's Central Committee, Zhao Ziyang, who
has been under house arrest since he was ousted as Communist Party
chief at the time of Tiananmen, challenged the nation's leaders to
admit that the incident was reprehensible as well as an immense
political blunder.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, harshly criticized in the United States for lending his
prestige to Beijing's leaders by attending the ceremony, hopes that
his presence here will force the world to remember that bloody
night nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   After the Tiananmen Square ceremony, a news conference by the
two presidents was planned to deliver statements about the results
of their 90-minute meeting.
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official said they had agreed on several
items, including a pledge to redirect the nuclear-tipped ballistic
missiles now aimed at each other's cities. The step is largely
symbolic, because such weapons can be targeted in a matter of
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang also agreed that China would ``actively study'' joining
the Missile Technology Control Regime, an international agreement
governing the sale of certain missiles and missile technology.
China has resisted the pact because missile exports are a key
money-maker for the military. No timetable was set for China's
actually joining the regime.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries also agreed on a joint statement on the
nuclear arms race now under way in South Asia, including pledges
not to export to India or Pakistan any missiles, missile equipment
or materials capable of delivering nuclear weapons. The agreement
covers only medium- and long-range missiles, however.
</P>
<P>
   China has also agreed to permit inspections of Chinese sites
receiving high-technology equipment from the United States to
assure that it is being put to its intended use and not diverted
for military purposes.
</P>
<P>
   This provision has gained increased importance in recent weeks
with disclosures that China may have used commercial satellites for
military communications, and earlier revelations that computers
supposedly for industrial applications had been diverted to
military installations.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no concrete progress on a number of American human
rights concerns, including the treatment of Tibet and an accounting
for hundreds of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   An American official involved in the summit talks said he was
hopeful that signs of progress on rights might come in the weeks
and months after Clinton leaves China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things are not announced at the summit, but happen
afterward,'' this official said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also agreed to expand of the Peace Corps presence
here and to work toward new cooperation on legal reforms,
environmental programs and a new clean energy project to reduce the
emissions of coal-burning power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The summit results amount to a ``pretty substantial package,''
the official said. But many of the military and nonproliferation
items were expected and represented at best incremental steps.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
