<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIPLOMATIC APPROACH WINS LITTLE IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Among the biggest losers in Albany this month, by his
own admission, was Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew.
</P>
<P>
   Crew was stymied on virtually all that he sought, whether it was
eliminating tenure for principals, gaining approval for a
year-round school calendar, getting an additional $200 million to
repair city schools, or finally settling the long-running fight
over the city's fair share of state education aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's like a guy who went out with a trick-or-treat bag but
didn't get any candy,'' said Norman Adler, a longtime lobbyist
whose clients include Local 891 of the International Union of
Operating Engineers, which represents school custodians. ``Maybe
next year he should change his costume.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, Crew acknowledged his losses and said
he bore ``a substantial amount of the fault.'' But he defended his
instinct for quiet, patient diplomacy, which he said will pay off
in the long run. ``This is just round one,'' he said. ``You might
not like my style. You may not like that there is not much blood
and guts. That's OK''
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, the chancellor's failures were largely out of
his hands. Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, vetoed the
Legislature's $500 million school construction package _ $200
million of it intended for the city _ in part because the measure
was championed by the state's highest-ranking Democrat, Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver, in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   And many chancellors have trouble getting what they want from
Albany, where their quest to persuade upstate and Long Island
legislators to raise school aid for New York City can seem
quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the obstacles, some of those who watched the chancellor
negotiate said that he had demonstrated surprisingly little
inclination to expend political capital on the issues that, at
least publicly, he ranked as high priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Despite drawing headlines early in the legislative session for
his bid to strip principals of lifetime tenure, for example, Crew
did not seriously work behind the scenes to push the issue in
Albany, officials said. This, despite the fact that he had the
blessing of his political patron, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   That the chancellor would take such a cautious tack seems a bit
remarkable to some education lobbyists, given that he is among the
most popular figures in the city, whether measured by political
polls or the conga line of adults who seek his firm handshake
wherever he goes. The sheer size of the school system makes his a
potentially formidable constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you represent a million schoolchildren, the governor and
legislative leaders are never going to tell you they won't talk to
you,'' said one education lobbyist. ``He can do a lot of damage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Crew has rarely been anything but a polite guest in the
halls of government. He almost never criticizes the mayor or
governor or Assembly speaker or Senate majority leader by name, and
almost always responds to political setbacks with faxed press
releases, rather than by taking to the airwaves or seeking to rile
up parents on the steps of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he doesn't show more anger on behalf of the children
he represents, Crew said that any short-term gain would be
outweighed by long-term harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could get a one-shot bang,'' Crew said of the idea of
going on the attack, much as Giuliani does. ``That, at the very
least, as I see politics played in New York state, gets you on the
nightly news and gets your children nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, you could lose everything,'' he said. ``You could
lose the art of ever being able to walk in the governor's door or
have your phone call taken.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all his conciliating, Crew has so far compiled an uneven
record in Albany as he finishes his third school year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, in one of the biggest political victories by any
chancellor, the Legislature stripped the city's 32 community school
boards of their hiring powers and effectively awarded them to Crew.
Though the pressure had been building on the legislators for years,
Crew seized the moment, knitting together a coalition that helped
prod Albany into action.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Crew has been reluctant to push the Legislature
further, even on the issue of eliminating principal tenure, despite
his contention that only by holding principals accountable can he
fully exercise his new authority.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor is nothing if not a political realist, and he was
well aware that the teachers' union, the United Federation of
Teachers, supported the principals. Though there is no love lost
between the two groups, the teachers' union could ill afford to
advocate curbing anyone's rights of tenure. And no lobbying group
gives more to the legislators' campaigns than the teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is the right issue,'' the chancellor said. ``I
think I'm in the wrong time. There's just no political will to lift
this one.'' In an interview, the mayor agreed, saying, ``I think
Albany is capable of only so much reform each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the chancellor came away from Albany empty-handed, he did
leave with one new chit. After the governor vetoed an annual
allocation known as teachers support aid _ which adds about $1,000
each year to the paychecks of each city teacher _ Crew wrung the
$63 million needed from the school system's budget.
</P>
<P>
   That should serve him well as he attempts to persuade the
teachers' union to agree to his year-round school plan, for only
with the union's assent will he be able to move the Legislature to
finance the venture, which it has rebuffed two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not finished,'' said the chancellor, who is seeking a
two-year contract extension that would make him, by 2001, the
school system's longest-serving chief executive since Eisenhower
was president. ``What people don't count on is long-term, sustained
tenacity.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
