<SLUG> BC-NY-CONSTRUCTION-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARPENTER IS KILLED WHILE WORKING ON TOWER IN TIMES SQUARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted earlier as NY-CONSTRUCTION-MISHAP)   (bl)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A carpenter working on the Conde Nast skyscraper in
Times Square was fatally injured Friday morning when he was crushed
by an elevator that was lowered as he worked in an elevator shaft.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the elevator was working properly and that
they were trying to find out why the man was in the shaft, where he
was caught between the elevator and the structure's scaffolding on
the 43rd floor about 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue crews used an adjacent elevator to reach the man and
tried to revive him for nearly 10 minutes before he regained a
pulse, said Lt. Wayne Baskin, the emergency medical specialist who
gave the man CPR.
</P>
<P>
   But the man was pronounced dead at Bellevue Hospital Center
about 10:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the company managing the project, Tishman
Construction Corp., said that many workers at the site at 4 Times
Square were sent home after being made available to federal and
city investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not release the victim's name Friday, but
construction workers identified him as Charles Robbins, 43, a
carpenter with Universal Building Supply, a subcontractor hired to
operate and maintain the elevators used to haul building materials
at the site.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators deemed the death an accident, according to
a spokeswoman for the department. Investigators from the federal
Occupational Safety and Health Administration and inspectors from
the city's Buildings Department were also looking into the death.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Birkhahn, a spokesman for the Buildings Department, said
that city inspectors determined that the elevator was working
properly.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said
he was baffled as to why the victim was working in the elevator
shaft while the elevator was in use.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kielar, a spokesman for Tishman, said that OSHA
inspectors visited the construction site last week and gave it a
clean bill of health. OSHA officials said that they could not
confirm the results of that inspection and that an accident history
for the project would not be available until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in mid-1999, the 48-story, 1.6
million-square-foot building will serve as the headquarters for
Conde Nast Publications, the publisher of The New Yorker, Vanity
Fair, GQ, Glamour, Vogue and dozens of other magazines. It will
also be home to the Manhattan law firm Skadden Arps Slate Meagher &AMP;
Flom.
</P>
<P>
   The death was the first fatality since construction began at
Four Times Square in 1996, but it was the third accident at the
building since January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
