<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, June 28, will move Saturday in the `a' category.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-NINETIES-REVIEW _ Suddenly, these are nervous times for
prosperity fans. The stock market has the jitters. The Asian
economic boom, another great engine of American prosperity, is
over. And the nation's economy shows signs of slowing. Is this the
beginning of the end of the Soaring Nineties? By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERCOMPUTERS-REVIEW _ In supercomputing, the time separating
the world's fastest computer from the scrap-metal heap is
appallingly short. But when it comes to supercomputers, to become
obsolescent isn't necessarily to become useless. While many of
these machines are mothballed in dank basements, a few are proudly
displayed in private homes as though they were objets d'art. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CRIME-REVIEW _ Not so long ago, Mexico seemed a
reasonably safe place, especially when compared with the violent
inner cities of the United States. But that has changed. Now
virtually every day, terrifying new crimes dramatize the country's
public security crisis. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-WAR-REVIEW _ A clamor is rising on all sides for an end
to decades of political violence here, so a weekly news magazine,
Cambio 16, had the novel idea of asking each of the parties to
state its goals for waging war. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   EXECUTIVE-POWER-REVIEW _ A look at President Clinton and
executive power. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH-STATE-REVIEW _ If the separation of church and state
mandated by the First Amendment means anything, surely it bars
state-paid teachers from evangelizing to public schoolchildren in
state-provided classrooms during school hours. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PITFALLS-REVIEW _ Pitfalls aplenty have lurked around
every corner during President Clinton's visit to China. Political
pitfalls: What to say about Tiananmen Square? Protocol pitfalls:
How to overcome the president's habitual tardiness, which would
surely grate on Chinese ideas of punctuality? By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM-REVIEW _ What Jerusalem has become. By Serge Schemann.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-REVIEW _ Our trouble with China, and vice versa. By
Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   IRS-REFORM-REVIEW _ After building a case that the Internal
Revenue Service all too often harasses and intimidates taxpayers,
Congress wrapped up work last week on a bipartisan bill to rein in
the agency. Taxpayers will get more legal protections when they get
into disputes with the IRS. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   RECOVERED-MEMORY-REVIEW _ A blockbuster of a story launched a
highly touted current-affairs television program. But its central
allegation was false and based on a disputed interviewing technique
involving recovered memories that the American Psychiatric
Association has condemned. According to the report on ``Newsstand:
CNN &AMP; Time,'' U.S. Special Forces troops dropped sarin nerve gas in
1970 while attacking a Laotian village that was presumed to be
harboring American defectors. By Joe Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW _ Highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
