<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-JEOPARDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUBLE JEOPARDY DOESN'T APPLY TO SENTENCING, COURT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The constitutional protection against double
jeopardy does not ordinarily apply to criminal sentencing, the
Supreme Court ruled Friday in a decision that removed a legal cloud
from the operation of some states' ``three strikes'' sentencing
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 decision, upholding a ruling by the California Supreme
Court, means that a state can have more than one chance to prove
that a previous conviction qualifies as a ``strike'' that counts
against a defendant in calculating an enhanced sentence for a new
offense.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have some form of enhanced sentencing for
previously convicted offenders. Had the court ruled that double
jeopardy applied to sentencing, the operation of those laws could
have been placed in doubt to the extent that a state permitted
defendants to contest the validity of an earlier conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In California, a defendant can get a jury trial on the question
of whether a previous conviction qualifies as a ``strike.''
Typically, not every previous offense counts. It must have been a
serious felony that, in the case of an assault, for example,
involved use of a dangerous weapon or great bodily injury to the
victim.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a man who was convicted of selling marijuana faced
a doubling of his five-year sentence if the state proved that he
had a single prior qualifying conviction. He said that his previous
conviction, an assault in which he had hit someone with a stick,
did not count. The trial judge held that the evidence of the
previous conviction was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   When the state tried to appeal, the California Court of Appeal
ruled that a new trial on the allegation would amount to double
jeopardy. The California Supreme Court, in turn, reversed that
decision, holding that double jeopardy did not apply to sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The court Friday affirmed that ruling in an opinion by Justice
Sandra Day O'Connor that was joined by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist and Justices Anthony Kennedy, Clarence Thomas and Stephen
Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said that historically, double jeopardy applied only to
a determination of guilt or innocence, not sentencing. She noted
that in 1981, the court had made an exception to that rule in a
death penalty case, Bullington vs. Missouri, in which a murder
defendant who had received a life sentence got a new trial in
which, if found guilty, he faced a renewed chance of being
sentenced to death. The court ruled then that a defendant who had
avoided the death penalty in an initial sentencing proceeding could
not be forced to face it again in a resentencing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said Friday that the decision in the Bullington case
had depended on the ``unique circumstances'' of the death penalty
and should not be extended to other types of sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissenting opinion, Antonin Scalia said he agreed with the
conclusion that the Bullington case should not be extended. But he
said that the current case, Monge vs. California, No. 97-6146,
should not be regarded as a simple sentencing case. Rather, he
said, a sentencing enhancement was in effect a conviction for a
separate crime, for which full procedural protections should apply.
Justices David Souter and Ruth Bader Ginsburg joined Scalia's
dissent, while Justice John Paul Stevens dissented separately.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate case Friday, the court refused without comment to
hear a constitutional challenge to a federal law, the Military
Honor and Decency Act of 1996, which prohibits the government from
selling or renting ``sexually explicit material'' on military
property. The effect of the law is to bar the rental of sexually
explicit films and the sale of such popular magazines as Penthouse
and Playboy _ previously sold by the hundreds of thousands of
copies a year _ from the PX on a military base.
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of Penthouse, along with other plaintiffs, brought
a First Amendment suit against the law and won an initial ruling in
U.S. District Court in New York. But late last year, the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals held that the law was constitutional as a
reasonable restriction on speech in the particular context of a
military base.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court appeal, General Media Communications Inc. vs.
Cohen, No. 97-1535, said the law, and the ruling upholding it,
``will result in massive restriction of the First Amendment rights
of our country's military personnel and their dependents.''
</P>
<P>
   Military personnel may still own sexually explicit material and
may buy it from sources other than the PX.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
