<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PLANS CUTS DESPITE BUDGET SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Despite others' projections of a hefty budget surplus
next year, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Friday that he plans $427
million in cuts to counteract what he called overspending by the
city council.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials asserted that the cuts, from a budget
of $34 billion, would be felt by few New Yorkers. The officials
said some of the savings would be realized through efficiencies
that would barely be noticed _ for instance, by reducing overtime
payments. But in other cases, the officials acknowledged, the cuts
are likely to come from the council's additions to the mayor's
proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has denounced many of these additions, made at the
behest of individual members, as shameless pork. The new budget
year begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani made the announcement at the annual meeting of the
State Financial Control Board, which has overseen the city's
financial management since the fiscal crisis of 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of Friday's reports were accounts that the city
was financially flush, Giuliani said his $427 million in spending
reductions would protect the city even if the current boom fades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistakes the city has made in the past, in the 70s
and in the 80s, were at times when the economy was booming,''
Giuliani said. ``It was in those times that rather than seriously
restraining the urge to spend every penny, the city outspent the
growth of its economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lhota, the mayor's budget director, said memos would be
sent next week to the heads of city agencies, asking them to
propose cuts that would meet a chosen target. Giuliani will review
the proposed reductions, Lhota said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani had been keeping the council in suspense about how he
would curb spending ever since the council overrode his vetoes of
some items in the 1998-99 budget, which the council passed without
his agreement on June 5.
</P>
<P>
   Although the council passes the budget, it is the mayor who
spends the money, and even if his vetoes are overridden he can
still order spending cuts. At first he threatened to refuse to
spend money allocated in the budget, which would probably have
resulted in a court fight with the council. But his aides said the
cuts would make that unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Council Speaker Peter Vallone said the council would fight any
budget cuts that ``end up hurting valuable services and people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor's math just doesn't add up,'' Vallone said. ``We
have a $2 billion surplus, but he still wants to cut agency
spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has sparred with the Financial Control Board in the
past, but Friday's meeting was all mutual congratulations. The
board's chairman is Gov. George E. Pataki, who opened the meeting
but then departed unexpectedly, without explanation to the mayor,
before Giuliani began speaking.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, Pataki praised Giuliani for the city's balanced
budgets and record surpluses. The men, both Republicans, have had a
frosty relationship that has seemed to warm up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor, I think we should all be very, very proud and grateful
for the record of accomplishment over the course of the last five
years,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats on the Financial Control Board, Alan Hevesi and H.
Carl McCall, also had praise for Giuliani. Hevesi, the city
comptroller, said the city was should finish this budget year with
a surplus of about $2.2 billion, and should have a surplus next
year of $576 million to $806 million.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the state comptroller, said he expected the city to end
this budget year with a surplus of $2.1 billion and have ``a
significant surplus'' next year. But he warned that the budget
discord ``threatens to distract the city from making headway on
pressing long-term budget issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
