<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHOPRITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM, FOUR OTHERS SHARE FIRST-ROUND LEAD
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ALEX YANNIS     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABSECON, N.J. _ After finishing second last year and third in
1996, Annika Sorenstam of Sweden again is challenging for the title
in the $1 million ShopRite LPGA Classic, the richest three-day on
the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, the top woman golfer in the world last year, shot a
five-under 66 Friday at the Seaview Marriott's renovated Bay Course
to share the first-round lead with Tina Barrett, Alicia Dibos of
Peru, Caroline McMillan of England and a qualifier Moira Dunn.
While Sorenstam has 15 victories in five years on the tour, the
four who share the lead with Sorenstam have combined for two
victories in a total of 31 years on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy King, the two-time winner of the event and a member of the
Hall of Fame, was a shot behind at 67. She was tied with with seven
others, including Julie Inkster, another two-time winner of this
tournament, which returned here this season after 11 years at
Somers Point.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, who lost the tournament last year because Michelle
McGann shot 64 on the final day, had no bogeys and five birdies on
the 6,024-yard course. The course is rather short by LPGA
standards, but it is challenging because of high fescue and small,
undulating greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some short par 4's, but it's a links course and I
had some super saves,'' Sorenstam said. ``I'm very pleased with my
game. It's good to see that my momentum from St. Louis is still
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett attributed part of her success to switching putters for
the first time in eight years. She birdied four holes with putts
longer than 15 feet, but she also three-putted the last hole from
30 feet for her only bogey of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's lone victory on the tour came in her rookie season in
1989. She started the season fairly well, but she has been in a
funk for the last month or so. Barrett's 66 matched her best round
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Dibos' 66 is her best round this season and it came on five
birdies and no bogeys, while McMillan's round included six birdies
and a bogey. She has been without a victory since her triumph in
the JAL Big Apple Classic two years ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
