A9600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MARKETSPAN-LILCO-5     06-26 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARKETSPAN-LILCO-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETSPAN FORMS PANEL TO DEAL WITH LILCO FUROR 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Facing a mounting array of investigations
and lawsuits, Marketspan's board Friday appointed a special
committee to deal with all litigation arising from $67 million in
payments made to its executives who were at Long Island Lighting
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was intended to prevent the board from being
preoccupied by the compensation issue. It was also intended to
refocus the board's attention on the reorganization and expansion
of Marketspan, which was formed by the merger of part of LILCO with
Brooklyn Union Gas and its affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's first board meeting, on June 10, was devoted
entirely to the compensation issue and was held in a crisis
atmosphere. Gov. George Pataki had demanded the removal of Dr.
William Catacosinos as Marketspan's chairman for having taken $42
million in payments when he was chairman of LILCO. An additional
$25 million was paid to 25 other executives.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that he has the support of major stockholders,
Catacosinos has refused to quit and Friday presided at the board's
second session.
</P>
<P>
   After the board's four-hour meeting, Marketspan released a
statement announcing the creation of the special committee to deal
with the executive compensation issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special committee will have full authority to make any and
all decisions related to these matters,'' Marketspan said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan was created on May 28 as the Long Island Power
Authority, a state agency, took over LILCO's electricity service.
The remainder of LILCO merged with the Brooklyn Union group to form
the new company. Marketspan is operating the old LILCO electricity
system under a contract with the power authority.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had promoted the partial takeover as a way to deliver a
20 percent cut in electricity bills that, under LILCO, has been the
highest in the continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   But a week after the takeover and merger, Pataki angrily
disclosed the executive payments, which he said violated the
state's agreement with LILCO barring layoffs and severance pay.
Neither Catacosinos nor the 25 other executives missed a day's pay,
and all of them automatically assumed new positions at Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   Catacosinos and Marketspan's president, Robert Catell, who was
Brooklyn Union's chairman, hold their new jobs under an arrangement
approved by the stockholders of their old companies, and they also
serve at the pleasure of the new board.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's press office declined to comment on Catacosinos'
continuation as head of the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's other executive appointments are interim and have
not yet been ratified by the new board.
</P>
<P>
   The former LILCO executives contend that their payments were for
retirement and other benefits they were entitled to under personal
contracts that were properly disclosed in the agreements with the
state, although the exact amounts of the payments were not
specified. They say that the state's representatives did not object
to the planned payments until now.
</P>
<P>
   Marketspan's directors had already hired a law firm in
Manhattan, Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett, to review the compensation
issue, and that firm will now advise the board's new committee.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's members are Edward Miller, who served on the
board of Brooklyn Union's holding company; Frederic Salerno, who
was chosen by the LILCO side, and Vincent Tese, a new director
chosen jointly by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 11 lawsuits have been filed by shareholders seeking to
overturn the executive payments. The Suffolk County Legislature has
scheduled a vote for Tuesday on authorizing a lawsuit seeking to
nullify the payments and recoup the money.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The compensation issue is also being investigated by the power
authority, the state attorney general, the state public service
commission, the state assembly and the federal Energy Regulatory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the federal Securities and Exchange Commission,
which enforces rules on the disclosure of compensation, said its
policy is to not comment on whether it has a pending investigation.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Dennis Vacco's investigation was
criticized Friday by Eliot Spitzer, who is seeking the Democratic
nomination to run against Vacco, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Vacco should be disqualified for a conflict of
interest because he was involved in the takeover proceedings, and
for ineptitude for having failed to uncover the executive
compensation in the takeover agreements.
</P>
<P>
   But Vacco's spokesman, Christopher McKenna denied the
accusations, saying, ``It's ridiculous.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
