<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      06-26 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets, Barkley make part of franchise's future feel at home
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
A few bridges to the future joined the Rockets' family Friday, and
for Michael Dickerson, bringing the Rockets into the next
generation is particularly challenging.
</P>
<P>
   But somebody has to follow Clyde Drexler, so the shooting guard
from Arizona figures it might as well be him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about that,'' said Dickerson, who celebrated his
23rd birthday Thursday. ``Obviously, I'm not a Clyde Drexler, a
Hall of Famer. But I feel like I can come in and give the coaches
what they want. They need penetration and outside shooting and just
to have some of the pressure taken off of Charles (Barkley) and
Hakeem (Olajuwon).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to disappoint anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the prevailing theme among the three guards and one
forward who were drafted by the Rockets on Wednesday and introduced
at their practice facility Friday. Joining Dickerson were guards
Bryce Drew and Cuttino Mobley, as well as Turkish forward Mirsad
Turkcan.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson was taken 14th, Valparaiso's Drew 16th and Turkcan
18th in the first round. Mobley, from Rhode Island, was taken in
the second round at No. 41 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Drexler, who coaches the University of Houston men's basketball
team, leaves a large void, to be sure. And the Rockets won't expect
one player, let alone a rookie, to take up all of the slack.
</P>
<P>
   But neither are the Rockets downplaying the potential possessed
by Dickerson.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Rudy Tomjanovich said he's looking forward to the 6-5
Dickerson creating his own legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get caught up in those kind of things,'' Tomjanovich
said of Dickerson replacing Drexler. ``You have to be who you are,
and he's pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clyde is a player who did so much for basketball for Houston,
and it's not fair to put that kind of a burden on a young player. I
feel confident that he's an all-around player, that he's going to
find his own niche in the NBA and in 10 years people are going to
be talking about what a great player Michael Dickerson is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson has a high school national championship and an NCAA
title. That puts him in elite company. But he says he would like to
complete the hat trick and get a ring at the NBA level, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they said Magic (Johnson) is one of the only guys who
has won the high school, the college and the NBA titles,''
Dickerson said. ``So hopefully, I'll try to do that too. So I'm
looking forward to winning a championship. Obviously, we have the
players to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Olajuwon and Barkley are in the twilight of their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles called and was joking that he was on his last legs,''
said Dickerson, who might not have understood Barkley could have
been serious. ``I'm just glad that he feels like we can come in and
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night, I spent two hours talking to him, and I already
love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley made telephone calls to all of the Rockets' new recruits
in the hours after they were drafted. As always, he made an
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in the house with my mother, and Charles Barkley
called,'' Mobley said. ``He said, `Hey, Cuttino,' And I was
wondering, `Who is this?' He said he was Charles Barkley and was
just calling to congratulate me. And I said, `Oh, how you doing,
Mr. Barkley?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like a kid in the candy store. Just to be playing with
Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon I mean, you practice their
moves on playgrounds, and now you're going to play with them. I'm
just flabbergasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me and Michael his two sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding four youngsters to the Rockets' roster, along with
second-year man Rodrick Rhodes, means the transformation has begun
in earnest. The Rockets are getting younger. And they're doing so
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be the biggest offseason for us since the year we
added Hakeem Olajuwon,'' Tomjanovich said. ``We feel this is a
crucial time for this franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Step one was the draft. These guys not only complement the
veterans we have in Charles and Hakeem, but they are the foundation
for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich called Dickerson ``the best athlete in the draft,''
and the coach believes the 6-3 Drew is the sort of point guard who
will be perfect for the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a player that everybody got to know during the NCAA
Tournament with his heroics (a last-second shot to beat
Mississippi),'' Tomjanovich said. ``But we were watching him
throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good with the basketball, good on the pick-and-rolls
and can create his own shot. We also see him as being one of the
best shooters with range in this draft.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Dickerson and Mobley, Drew got a call from Barkley the
night of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Mr. Barkley, I don't know what to say,''' said
Drew, who added Barkley, a free agent, gave indications he would be
back with the Rockets. ``He'd better come back. He's going to have
four rookies really upset if he doesn't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   And once the younger players get over the urge to call them
``Mr.,'' they plan on benefiting by having a couple of future Hall
of Famers with whom to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to learn so much this year,'' Drew said. ``But on
the other hand, we want to contribute as much as we can and
hopefully get back to the playoffs and see what we can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
