<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court clarified the law
on sexual harassment in the workplace today, making some lawsuits
against employers easier to win while limiting the legal exposure
of companies that have effective anti-harassment policies in place.
The two 7-to-2 decisions cut through a thicket of confusing and
contradictory lower-court rulings that had grown up in the 12 years
since the Justices first ruled that sexual harassment was a form of
employment discrimination. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-HARASS-JONES (Washington) _ Paula Jones' lawyers said the
Supreme Court's decision in favor of a Chicago businesswoman would
help them in their appeal to have Mrs. Jones' sexual harassment
suit against President Clinton reinstated. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-JEOPARDY (Washington) _ The high court rejects a
prisoner's appeal that California's ``three strikes'' law does not
amount to violation of the constitutional protection against double
jeopardy. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ A federal appeals court greeted
with considerable skepticism the Clinton administration's claim
that Secret Service agents should not have to testify in the
Lewinsky matter. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-CIA-HIRING-SPIES (Washington) _ The CIA is beginning
the largest recruitment drive for new spies in its history, in an
ambitious effort to rebuild its espionage service, which has been
severely damaged by spy scandals, budget cutbacks and high turnover
since the end of the Cold War, officials say. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH-ASSESS (Washington) _ In unveiling a health plan
to patch up managed care with such measures as expanding a
patient's ability to choose a doctor and to receive emergency care,
were House GOP leaders simply providing political cover for the
November elections, or genuinely trying to pass a law to address
patients' concerns? The answer, say close associates of Speaker
Newt Gingrich, is both. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DISABILITY-REACT (Washington) _ _ Millions of Americans
with conditions like diabetes, epilepsy and even infertility and
alcohol addiction appear to have won important new protection
against discrimination as a result of a Wednesday Supreme Court
ruling, advocates say. The ruling came in the case of a woman who
had HIV but no symptoms of the condition. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-DRAGGING-DEATH (Jasper, Texas) _ The Klan is coming to
Jasper to march Saturday and spread its current message that it is
not in favor of violence but wants to fight immigration. Meanwhile,
Black Panthers also plan to show up and the town is trying to
ignore both groups. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CNN-NERVE-GAS (Undated) _ Robert Van Buskirk, one of the main
sources for the disputed CNN-Time nerve-gas report, tells Fox News
he was badly misquoted. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (New York) _ Doesn't Sir Sigmund Sternberg, the
British businessman, Jewish philanthropist and inveterate promoter
of interfaith understanding, ever get tired of receiving awards? He
is being honored at the U.N. for receiving the $1.23 million
Templeton Prize for Progress in Religion. By Peter Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-POLITICS (Birmingham) _ The Alabama Republican gubernatorial
race between Gov. Fob James and Winton Blount has been dominated in
its final week by the possibility that it may be decided by
Democrats. Birmingham Mayor Richard Arrington, a Democrat,
announced that his powerful get-out-the-vote machine was supporting
Blount. Although Tuesday's contest is a runoff for the Republican
nomination, it is open to voters regardless of party. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SUMMIT (Beijing) _ President Clinton was formally received
by President Jiang Zemin on Saturday in a somber military ceremony
on Tiananmen Square, the vast tombstone of a failed revolution. He
stood mute throughout, as is customary at such arrival ceremonies.
Clinton and Jiang then inspected army troops and reviewed an honor
guard on ground that human rights advocates around the world
consider stained with the blood of martyrs. By John M. Broder. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIBET (Beijing) _ The director of the Religious Affairs
Administration calls the Dalai Lama a traitor who planned to split
the motherland and restore feudal serfdom in Tibet. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIANANMEN (Beijing) _ Beijing's Tiananmen Square and its
historical and political significance. By Seth Faison. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RUBIN-NYT (Beijing) _ China gave the U.S. its strongest
assurances yet that it does not plan to devalue its currency. U.S.
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin held a daylong series of meetings
with senior Chinese officials here, in which he said ``there were
unambiguous statements of intent to maintain'' the exchange rate of
the Chinese currency. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-BUSINESS (Undated) _ After two decades of U.S.
investing in China, hyperbole has given way to sober assessments of
the pluses and minuses of doing business in what many call the
world's most challenging emerging market. SOme American companies
have been runaway successes; others have proven dismal failures.
Most big companies say they are there for the long term and are
prepared to take their lumps along the way. By Joseph Kahn. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina, Serbia) _ Belgrade has ordered its military
and special police to mount widescale attacks in Kosovo to
recapture pockets held by ethnic Albanian rebels and reopen roads
the separatist rebels have blocked for weeks, Western diplomats and
military officials said Friday. The escalation of the fight against
the rebels came as Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. special envoy,
left Pristina emptyhanded after four days of shuttle talks with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and ethnic Albanian leaders.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-ELECT (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Parties committed
to the peace settlement emerged winners in the election for the new
Assembly, but candidates opposed to the accord won enough seats to
call into question the value of that victory. The results showed
that two biggest parties, the Ulster Unionist Party of David
Trimble and the Social Democratic and Labor Party of John Hume,
would get the chance to fulfill their pledge to work together to
end the conflict. But the count of the ballots from Thursday's
election, which will not be complete until Saturday, was exposing
deep divisions in Trimble's support. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WAR-CRIME (Washington) _ The Justice Department used a new
watch list for suspected Japanese war criminals for the first time
this week by barring two former Imperial Army soliders from
entering the country. But the men had originally been placed on the
watch list because they had publicly recanted their crimes in
Japan, becoming pariahs in the process, and were coming to America
to join a lecture tour about the horrors of the Pacific War. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TOBACCO (Cornwall, Ontario) _ This town is divied over
former Mayor Ron Martelle's outspoken stance backing the American
tobacco industry's campaign against higher cigarette taxes. In a TV
commercial, he complains of a sharp rise in cigarette smugling and
bootlegging. By ANTHONY DePalma. WITH PHOTO and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   NORWAY-JEWISH-PAYMENT (Oslo) _ Norway has proposed a $60 million
payment to Norwegian Jews and international Jewish organizations as
compensation for property seized during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-SUBMARINE (Tokyo) _ There is evidence that only four of
the North Korean submariners died by suicide and that the five
others died in a fight. By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   BOLIVIA-DRUGS (Villa Rosario, Bolivia) _ Government efforts to
crack down on coca producers have set off increasing violence by
the growers, including blockades of crucial roads and ambushes
against the security forces here. Such expressions of determination
in the battle against cocaine represent a break from the past. By
Clifford Krauss. WITH GRAPHIC MAP.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILES (Washington) _ When two American satellite makers
shared technical information with Chinese rocket scientists, they
committed three major security breaches, according to a
confidential assessment by the Pentagon. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
