<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEADMASTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUSTEES FORCE RETIREMENT ON ECCENTRIC HEADMASTER OF HARLEM SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thirty-two years ago, an eccentric poet named Ned
O'Gorman hatched a neighborhood preschool inside a battered Harlem
storefront and tended it as it grew into a private, tuition-free
academy from prekindergarten through eighth grade. Since then, he
has taught his charges to read Greek and perform Shakespeare,
escorted some of them to exclusive prep schools and buried others
in early graves.
</P>
<P>
   Now the trustees who run the Children's Storefront school, which
is housed in three brownstones on East 129th Street between Park
and Madison Avenues, say they want a new headmaster, one who will
introduce a more rigorous curriculum and build the school's
endowment. After unsuccessfully pressing O'Gorman to step down for
years, the 24-member board voted this week to force him to take a
sabbatical beginning on Wednesday and then retire in 1999. This
ouster has unleashed an unusual and emotional response.
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman says he will leave the school, but will rent a room on
the street, pack it with a few books, perhaps serve hot chocolate
to the pupils in winter, and just be there for the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the kids don't feel like I've just gotten up and
disappeared,'' he explained. ``I must be where the kids and
teachers can come to see me. I've been on that street for 32 years
every bloody day!''
</P>
<P>
   Parents have planned a rally in front of the school Saturday in
his support.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees said several factors prompted them to take the
action: the need for an orderly succession and for an increase in
the endowment and O'Gorman's broken promises to retire. Two years
ago, for example, O'Gorman had set a retirement date for this June,
but then reneged, said the board president, Christine LaSala.
Ultimately, she said, the trustees felt compelled to set a firm
departure date.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board had grappled with an open-ended time frame for a
long time,'' said Ms. LaSala, who is also the managing director of
J &AMP; H Marsh &AMP; McLennan, the insurance company. ``It couldn't
grapple with an open-ended time frame any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The board plans to appoint an interim head this fall and select
a permanent successor by next year. Ms. LaSala said she could not
comment on O'Gorman's plan to set up a post on East 129th Street,
except to say that the board would not seek to ``exile Ned from the
school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't prevent him from exercising his basic human
freedoms,'' she said. ``What I am saying is that the management of
the school will not be in the hands of Ned O'Gorman in September
1998.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, O'Gorman said the members of the board, many of
whom are corporate executives, ousted him because they could no
longer tolerate what he described as his ``poetic inability to
contain myself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very short temper,'' he said Thursday. ``I tend not
to be, what do you say, acquiescent to the trustees. I don't care
about the trustees; I care about the kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel,'' he added, ``I must make vital decisions about the
school without consulting the trustees.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman, who was inspired by the radical Brazilian philosopher
Paulo Freire to try to empower the poor through education, said he
had had different plans for a succession: He and the parents would
help to select the next headmaster, with whom he would work for a
year before easing himself out. He said he had long ago issued a
retirement date _ he says he does not remember exactly when _ but
rescinded it after the board publicized his departure without
consulting him.
</P>
<P>
   Several trustees interviewed this week said it had been
impossible to build the school's endowment, now a little over $3
million, without a successor. Would-be donors, they said, simply
wanted evidence that the school could survive without O'Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I analogize it to a start-up company _ until it has grown
enough to be a survivor, it's a very risky proposition,'' said a
trustee, Robert Rylee. ``It shouldn't be shocking, surprising or
anything. It's sort of standard corporate management _ planning for
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. LaSala said the school, which has 155 students and an annual
operating budget of $1.8 billion, also needed to strengthen
students' computer skills and to shore up the math and science
curriculum. With O'Gorman, she said, ``it was hard to make changes
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When told of the trustees' plans to revamp the curriculum,
O'Gorman groaned. He said he feared for the neediest pupils _ ``the
devastated children'' he called them, ``who are the basis, the soil
of our school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear for the straightening of the Storefront,'' he said.
``It's a crooked little place, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   While the retirement mandate seems most painful for O'Gorman,
who has been synonymous with the Children's Storefront since he
established it in 1966, it has also wrenched the parents, who have
one representative on the board.
</P>
<P>
   One parent, Brian Jacobs, said he was shocked to learn of the
board's decision. He said he had been relying on O'Gorman's
assistance and considerable contacts with private schools for help
in choosing a high school for his 13-year-old daughter, Jasmine,
who is to graduate from the Storefront next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been counting on Ned being around for this,'' he said.
``This is a very important year for these eighth graders _ and to
have the school caught up in this turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had long known of O'Gorman's prickly relationship
with the trustees, but said the ouster would bring only turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ned is eccentric to say the least, but his heart is in the
right place,'' Jacobs added. ``Ned is not going to be plucked from
it and go quietly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
