<SLUG> BC-ALA-POLITICS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S SUPPORT OF GOVERNOR'S RIVAL MUDDLES ALABAMA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ As if Alabama's Republican gubernatorial race
has not been odd enough, the campaign between Gov. Fob James Jr.
and Winton Blount III has been dominated in its final week by the
possibility that it may be decided by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, one week before the June 30 runoff, Mayor
Richard Arrington Jr. of Birmingham, a Democrat who has been
elected five times, announced that his powerful get-out-the-vote
machine was supporting Blount. Although Tuesday's contest is a
runoff for the Republican nomination, it is open to voters
regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement by Arrington, who is black, has added a racial
element to a campaign that has already encountered questions about
body shape, inherited wealth and a deadly car wreck, along with the
customary accusations of lying and underhandedness. Polls show that
the race is close, and the prospect for crossover voting has made
it utterly unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   Because James, 63, is a defiant defender of religious expression
in schools and other public places, the election is considered a
critical test of the voting strength of Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The governor took a break from campaigning on Wednesday to fly
to Dallas, at state expense, to address an institute for Christian
missionaries. On Thursday night, in the last of four televised
debates, James asserted that ``this country at one time was a
Christian nation'' because Americans recognized that the
Constitution was founded on Judeo-Christian principles. A recent
James television advertisement features a tribute by the wife of a
judge who displays a tablet of the Ten Commandments in his
courtroom and who has been defended by James.
</P>
<P>
   Blount, 54, has stressed that he, too, supports returning prayer
to the schools. But he maintains that governor James has
embarrassed the state by threatening to defy Supreme Court rulings
on the question.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have grown concerned over the campaign's negative
tone, worrying that the obvious beneficiary will be the Democratic
nominee, Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman. When Blount was slapping backs at
a seniors center in Huntsville on Thursday, Robert Thibeault, a
65-year-old retired engineer, asked the candidate, ``Why are you
fellows cutting one another?''
</P>
<P>
   Blount, a wealthy Montgomery businessman and longtime party
loyalist, quickly blamed James. But the attacks continued in the
Thursday night debate, which ended with a tit-for-tat about which
candidate was the most deceitful.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the unprecedented endorsement by his Jefferson
County Citizens Coalition, Arrington said the group was still
likely to support Siegelman in the general election on Nov. 3. But
the mayor said he wanted to influence the Republican nomination
because he had not been pleased with James' treatment of his city
and that he hoped to provide Birmingham voters with ``the best of
both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Citizens Coalition has set a goal of turning out 40,000 of
Jefferson County's 360,000 registered voters, of whom 115,000 are
black. Only 25,000 votes separated James and Blount in the
five-candidate primary on June 2, when James finished with 48
percent of the vote to Blount's 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians and strategists question whether it will be
possible to turn out 40,000 voters. But the Citizens Coalition
seems to be planning a full blitz, complete with radio advertising,
mass mailings, and bullhorn canvassing. Most of the costs will be
paid by Blount's campaign, which is largely self-financed.
</P>
<P>
   Financial disclosure reports filed on Thursday show that Blount
has outspent James by $5.4 million to $2.5 million during the
campaign. Some $3.7 million of Blount's money came from loans from
himself or his family members.
</P>
<P>
   James' campaign clearly takes the threat of crossover voting
seriously. ``If it were a traditional Republican primary, I think
James would win handily,'' said state Sen. Bill Armistead, a James
supporter. ``But when you add in the Democrats coming in to vote in
our primary, it's in question.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, James' campaign consultant, said Arrington might be
the key to the election. ``If he turns out 30,000, Blount might
win,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   After unsuccessfully pursuing the mayor's support, James'
campaign now hopes that the endorsement of Blount will generate a
backlash that energizes its own supporters. Reed contends that
Blount must have cut a deal with the ``liberal Democratic boss''
involving promises of appointments and road financing, a charge
denied by both Blount and Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the endorsement was announced, some
300,000 fliers raising questions about such a deal were mailed
across the state. The fliers include a two-decade-old photograph of
Donald Watkins, a political aide to the mayor, who is shown with an
Afro haircut that has long been shorn.
</P>
<P>
   Blount said the fliers were ``trying to use race to inflame the
voters of Alabama.'' The author of the fliers, Joe Dickson, a black
Republican newspaper publisher and a James ally, said the
photograph of Watkins was the only one he could find in his files.
</P>
<P>
   Both Dickson and James said the governor had had no advance
knowledge of the fliers. Dickson says he did not pay all of the
$135,000 cost himself but has refused to say who paid the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, James has pledged not to increase state
taxes. Blount, while refusing to take such a pledge, has said he
will eliminate the state's 4 percent sales tax on food within seven
years, for tax cuts totaling $260 million. He has not specified how
he would make up for the loss of revenue, other than through
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the sniping has had little to do with policy. James has
said that Blount is fat. A pair of James television advertisements
suggest that Blount, who owns automobile dealerships and a plastics
company, was a failure when he worked previously for his father's
manufacturing company. His father, Winton Blount, called the charge
a ``terrible damn lie.''
</P>
<P>
   In another ad, a female narrator taunts: ``Everybody knows that
Daddy had to loan you the money to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Blount has also been forced to address a 1969 car accident in
which he was driving a Jaguar at an estimated 90 miles an hour and
struck another car. His first wife was killed in the crash. A
police report said Blount, who was returning from a party, was
``obviously drunk.'' He was charged with misdemeanor manslaughter,
but the charge was later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   James has not raised the accident as an issue, but Blount blames
the governor's campaign for an anonymous smear sheet that was
mailed to reporters. ``I don't think the people of Alabama will see
it as an issue,'' Blount said. ``I made a mistake, and I pay for it
every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
