<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jays outslug Javy; Braves still blue
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- The AL East has the Braves gagged and strapped to a
chair. One team's interleague schedule is another's dental torture.
</P>
<P>
   Staked to a five-run lead off a pair of two-run homers, the
Toronto Blue Jays opened a weekend series with a 6-4 victory over
Atlanta that only continued the discomfort the Yankees wrought upon
this town.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz (5-2) struck out a season-high 10 but was done in by
two-run shots by Carlos Delgado in the first and Jose Canseco in
the sixth. Despite a two-homer game by Javy Lopez, the Braves fell
to their fifth loss in six games and their seventh in nine games,
the club's first serious tailspin since the season began. The
Braves have lost seven of their 11 games thus far to the AL East
and are now 12-11 this month.
</P>
<P>
   And say what you will about the bullpen, but in the last three
games Atlanta starters have given up 15 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Down by four in the seventh, the Braves tried and failed to
start a comeback with a Lopez solo homer _ his second in three
games _ and with two outs, Andruw Jones came within inches of
hitting another, the ball striking the yellow line atop the wall in
center for a long double. Pinch-hitter Ozzie Guillen followed up
with an infield single and Walt Weiss followed with a check-swing
single over third for his second RBI to bring the Braves to within
5-3.
</P>
<P>
   After 15 scoreless innings, the Braves finally broke through in
the sixth, following an Andruw Jones single, a Smoltz sacrifice and
Weiss' RBI single. Weiss, making his first start in six days
because of his son's illness, drove in his first run since June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto picked up the night's second two-run homer in the sixth,
after Smoltz had already recorded eight strikeouts. Shawn Green
singled to left to bring up Canseco, who had been retired twice on
strikes by Smoltz. But on an 1-0 pitch, Canseco drove a low
breaking ball over the center field wall for his 23rd homer of the
season and a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blue Jays weren't finished. Delgado followed Canseco
with a single and advanced to second on a Darrin Fletcher single.
With two outs, Ed Sprague next lifted a soft liner into shallow
right that Michael Tucker failed to handle in a diving attempt,
scoring Delgado for a 5-0 lead. In his first nine starts, Smoltz
had given up more than three runs only once.
</P>
<P>
   Jays starter Pat Hentgen faced the minimum through the first
three innings and when the Braves finally scratched out a hit _ a
Keith Lockhart infield single _ Jays shortstop Alex Gonzalez
worsened the situation by throwing into the Braves dugout, giving
Lockhart second base. But Hentgen responded by keeping the Braves
in the infield, retiring Tucker on a pop-up and Chipper Jones on a
ground-out to retire the side.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
