<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chipper working way out of first slump
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Chipper Jones figures he goes through two stale
periods at the plate each season, and even while he ranked in the
top six in the National League in homers (18) and RBI (62) when
play began Friday night, he has determined he's in Period No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With his left-handed average slipping to .304, Jones took early
batting practice, working on line drives and sending the ball back
up the middle, trying to work out of a 5-for-31 slump (.161) over
the last eight games. On June 2, Jones was batting .342 and has
dropped more than 30 points since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real disappointed in my hitting with runners in scoring
position,'' said Jones, who is hitting .279 with men on second or
third. ``There's no reason I shouldn't have 70, 75 RBI right now.
I'm hitting behind two guys (Walt Weiss and Keith Lockhart) who
have been on base all year and I'm hitting .270 with runners in
scoring position? That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is still fighting a case of flu that zapped his strength,
but is also recovering from medication that kept him from sleeping.
On top of that, he endured four days of remarkable New York Yankees
pitching when he estimated he saw two pitches over the middle of
the plate _ an Orlando Hernandez fastball he hit for a two-run
single and a David Cone first-pitch fastball that Jones fouled off.
</P>
<P>
   Jones entered Friday night without a homer in 31 at-bats. Before
the slump, he averaged one long ball every 15.1 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``My left-handed swing is terrible,'' said Jones. ``A lot of
weak outs and wasted at-bats. I haven't felt real good for about
two weeks and being sick has something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to feel better now and I know I'm going to start
hitting again because my contact is getting better. I went through
about 10 days when I'd hit a ball right on the screws in batting
practice and couldn't get it out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
