<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-SIDEBAR27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers looks for the answer
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ More than 20 minutes into his daily workout, Mark
Wohlers has yet to pick up a baseball. But already his gray Braves
T-shirt is soaked nearly black.
</P>
<P>
   As the midday Florida sun beats down relentlessly, the
right-hander repeats and repeats the pantomime that he and the
Braves hope will start him on the road back to his rightful place
as Atlanta's All-Star closer.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers should be at Turner Field, coming out of the bullpen in
the ninth inning to record a save for one of Atlanta's celebrated
starters _ and earn the $4.1 million he's making in the second year
of a three-year contract. Instead, he's at the lowest rung of the
team's minor-league system, learning how to pitch all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so messed up, I had to start from the beginning,''
Wohlers said. ``It's almost like learning how to pitch all over
again.''
</P>
<P>
   So, over and over, he throws an imaginary ball to an invisible
batter, making sure the delivery of his make-believe pitch is
perfect every time.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers says he is making progress. But a week into his
self-imposed Florida exile, he still had not thrown a pitch to a
hitter, not even in batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my mechanics are back to where they should be, maybe
even better than they've been in over a year,'' Wohlers said. ``But
I still need work on the mental part. That's where I'm still
struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark has worked hard and picked up the changes we wanted to
make in his mechanics very quickly,'' said Braves special assistant
Guy Hansen, who was dispatched to Florida to work with Wohlers.
``But when he picks up a ball, he's still thinking too much and not
just throwing naturally. When you were as messed up as Mark was,
you can't turn things around in just a couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers proves that as he heads to a warmup mound for a throwing
session. At first, nearly every other pitch bounces in front of the
plate. Then, as he tries to compensate, Wohlers releases one pitch
too quickly and it sails over the 8-foot fence behind the catcher
and rolls nearly to the grandstand of a field where a Gulf Coast
Rookie League game is in progress.
</P>
<P>
   As the catcher runs to retrieve the wayward pitch, some of the
young Braves prospects look on in wonderment. Can this really be
the Mark Wohlers they had read about and watched on TV?
</P>
<P>
   Other big-league pitching stars have lost their ability to throw
the ball over the plate. In the early 1970s, Pittsburgh's Steve
Blass went from World Series hero to washout and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers, 28, knows nothing of Blass' struggles a quarter century
ago. But like Blass, he knows the cause is mental, not physical.
The arm remains strong. The psyche is weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``My problems are all up here,'' says Wohlers, pointing to his
head.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Herbison, a sports-performance consultant, worked with
the mental side of Wohlers' pitching development in the minors.
Wohlers called Herbison in Mississippi this week and asked him for
help again. Herbison caught the first plane for the Braves' complex
at Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark is very, very hard on himself,'' said Herbison, who
mainly works with college athletes. ``I just have him visualize
being successful and then let his natural ability take over. It's
important for an athlete to use the right side of his brain and not
let the left side confuse things. You can't be thinking too much
every time you throw a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   As the bullpen continues to struggle, the pressure grows for
Wohlers to return to the majors as quickly as possible. He watches
the games on televisionand admits it isn't easy to be 400 miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' said Wohlers, whose control problems
began in spring training. ``I feel I've let myself and my teammates
down. I want to be up there helping to win games again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers hopes to pitch at Class AA Greenville or AAA Richmond as
early as next week. He has faced only one batter in nearly three
weeks, and the four-pitch walk June 12 against Montreal signaled
that something was very wrong with the pitcher who has saved 97
games the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a timetable (for getting back to Atlanta),''
Wohlers said. ``I need to get my head back together, and then I
need to pitch nearly every day again. I've only pitched 16 innings
all season. When I started to feel I was getting it back together,
I got hurt (a slight tear of his left oblique muscle in early May).
Since then, it has been all downhill.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish it was spring training instead of June,'' said
Hansen, a former pitching coach with Kansas City who once helped
get Bret Saberhagen and Tom Gordon back on track. ``Mark will get
it back together. But it will take a little time. And that's
something you don't have a lot of at this time of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lonely, Wohlers had his wife and 2-year-old daughter join him
for a few days. He hopes to be back with them in their new
Alpharetta home shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given up,'' Wohlers said. ``Not at all. I'm getting
it back. I hope no one has given up on me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
