<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carson selects Palmolive executive to be next CEO
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Carson Inc. said Friday it has tapped Gregory J.
Andrews, a 20-year personal care products industry veteran, to be
its new CEO.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes a day after Standard &AMP; Poor's revised its
outlook on the Savannah-based ethnic products maker to negative
from stable, amid concerns about the company's soft earnings from
its core businesses of hair relaxers, hair colorings and men's
shaving products.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, 46, vice president and general manager of a
Colgate-Palmolive subsidiary in Buenos Aires, Argentina, will
assume the new position within the next month. He succeeds Roy
Keith, who relinquished the title earlier this month but remains
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks like a positive (move) for the company,'' said Lucy
Patricola, an analyst with S&AMP;P in New York. ``Colgate-Palmolive is
an outstanding consumer products company, so no doubt they will
have a well-trained executive to lead Carson.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews will help ``develop Carson's brands and brand loyalty
and identity,'' said Carson CFO Robert Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews joins Carson after nine years with Colgate-Palmolive. He
also held positions with Clairol Inc., The Gillette Co., Corning
Inc., and Johnson Products Co., which Carson recently announced it
planned to buy for $70 million cash.
</P>
<P>
   Industry watchers say Andrews will help refocus the ethnic
marketing and business strategies at Carson, which makes Dark &AMP;
Lovely, Excelle, Beautiful Beginnings and Magic. Carson has
announced it plans to sell its Cutex nail products business, which
represented a big departure from its core market.
</P>
<P>
   In recent quarters, the company has suffered from flat domestic
growth, due in part to distribution problems with retailers. Also,
margins have been adversely affected because of product mix,
production inefficiencies and higher infrastructure costs incurred
to support the company's growth, said S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the ethnic hair care and beauty products industry is
seeing slower growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the companies that manufacture and market (ethnic
products) is creating excitement and news at the consumer level,''
Pierce said. ``There's nothing to encourage consumers to think
about buying these products.''
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY J. ANDREWS FILE
</P>
<P>
   Title: CEO, Carson Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 46
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Bogalusa, La.
</P>
<P>
   Current job: VP-General Manager of Colgate Argentina, based in
Buenos Aires. Colgate-Palmolive Co.
</P>
<P>
   Other positions include: Vice president and general manager,
Johnson Products; general manager, Colgate Puerto Rico; group
product manager of all retail hair colorings, Clairol Inc.; head of
acquisitions and investments in hair care ventures for Clairol
Venture Products; marketing executive, Corning Inc. and The
Gillette Co. Also started an ethnic hair care products company.
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bachelor's degree, University of Connecticut (1973);
MBA from University of Wisconsin (1975).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
