<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENTIFICATLANTA-COX     06-26 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENTIFICATLANTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta cutting 125 jobs
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Scientific-Atlanta on Friday announced a
restructuring that will cut costs, shift some manufacturing to
Mexico and eliminate 125 jobs in its Atlanta operations.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are part of an effort to sharpen the Atlanta-based
company's competitive standing among telecommunications
manufacturers. They will result in estimated one-time charges of
$60 million to $75 million for the fourth fiscal quarter, which
ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But the company will also book a $100 million one-time gain as
part of revaluing its 1.5 million share stake in Broadcom, a maker
of various computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   None of these various moves will adversely affect the company's
financial results for the fourth quarter, executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measures we are announcing today are necessary to improve
our competitive position,'' said James F. McDonald, the company's
president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In its biggest move, Scientific-Atlanta will transfer its radio
frequency amplifier line to Juarez, Mexico, from Atlanta. The
company said the high-volume, low-skill work required can be done
more cost-effectively in Juarez. Scientific-Atlanta has had a plant
there since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Scientific-Atlanta will consolidate manufacturing
that requires skilled engineers in Atlanta, closing operations in
Vancouver, British Columbia, and Melbourne, Fla. The company
estimates about 150 positions will be moved to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The moves will result in a net loss of 125 jobs in Atlanta, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the company has created 1,500 jobs at
its Atlanta-based manufacturing and headquarters operations in
Norcross. The company is also completing the construction of a $40
million facility on 280 acres in Duluth.
</P>
<P>
   The first building is expected to open early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Atlanta area remains the site of our worldwide
headquarters and a major manufacturing location,'' said McDonald.
``Our new facility in Gwinnett County will be the centerpiece of
our company's operations going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Scientific-Atlanta will move its European
headquarters to Frankfurt, Germany, from London to ``better address
market opportunities.'' Its Asian regional headquarters will be
moved to Singapore from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would combine its satellite networks and
tracking business units.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
