<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-CLEMENCY-COX     06-26 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-CLEMENCY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush spares Lucas' life
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush, in an unprecedented and
politically risky decision, on Friday spared the life of Henry Lee
Lucas, once considered the nation's most prolific serial killer
after he confessed to murdering more than 600 people.
</P>
<P>
   Pronouncing Lucas ``unquestionably guilty of other despicable
crimes for which he has been sentenced to spend the rest of his
life in prison,'' Bush commuted Lucas' death sentence to a life
term in the Halloween 1979 slaying of a still-unidentified woman
known only as ``Orange Socks'' near Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, 61, had been scheduled for execution Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe there is enough doubt about this particular crime
that the State of Texas should not impose its ultimate penalty by
executing him,'' Bush said in announcing his decision in
Brownsville, where he was attending a conference of U.S.-Mexico
border governors.
</P>
<P>
   His decision was likely the first time since the 1930s that a
Texas governor commuted a death sentence based on a convicts'
claims of innocence without a court intervening first.
</P>
<P>
   From his death row cell at a prison outside Huntsville, Lucas
thanked Bush and the parole board ``for believing the truth and for
having the guts to stand up for what's right.'' Prison officials
said Lucas will move to another prison by Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As with the other 600-plus murders Lucas confessed to and then
recanted, he has for years maintained he was innocent of strangling
``Orange Socks,'' the only thing the woman was wearing when her
body was found near a culvert along I-35 north of Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   No witnesses or physical evidence linked Lucas to the crime,
only his four confessions. But the jury that convicted Lucas in
1984 rejected as unbelievable his alibi that he was working as a
roofer in Jacksonville, Fla., the day the slaying occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision came a day after the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles, by a 17-1 vote, had recommended Lucas' sentence be reduced
to an unspecified lesser penalty. Bush rejected their
recommendation to delay Lucas' execution 270 days, a move rendered
moot by Friday's commutation.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where the death penalty always has enjoyed support
from about 70 percent of Texans, where the record number of
executions is a bragging right, Bush may not have made political
points by siding with Lucas. But no immediate political damage was
evident Friday, as one of the state's most vocal anti-crime groups,
the Houston-based Justice for All, supported the decision. Like
Bush, the group has been a staunch supporter of executions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush worded his two-page clemency proclamation to ensure that
Lucas will die in prison. Otherwise, prison officials confirmed,
Lucas could have been eligible for parole in as few as five years _
even though his chances of freedom were virtually non-existent
because of his notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   Though Lucas has five other life sentences, plus two 75-year
terms and a 60-year sentence, for other Texas murders, officials
said those terms are being served at the same time. And after about
20 years, he becomes automatically eligible for parole
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has been behind bars since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Bush erased Lucas' parole review by mandating that Lucas' new
life sentence begin only after he completes his other five life
terms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Texas charges, Lucas also faces a life term
without the possibility of parole in West Virginia for killing a
policeman Clemmie Curtis in 1976. And Florida authorities want to
question him in at least three killings in the Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Orange Socks'' case was Lucas' only death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Bush's decision, Jim Mattox, the former attorney
general who discredited many of Lucas' confessions during a 1985
investigation and had recently called for him to be spared, said
Bush's decision will ``make out death penalty stronger than ever.
But it was still politically risky, and I'll be glad to stand up
and defend him against any attack.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cornyn, Mattox's GOP opponent in the November election,
said he thinks Lucas should be have been executed. ``I have
confidence in both the jury who heard this case and the more than
23 judges who reviewed the evidence. I believe their decisions
should be respected,'' Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a leading advocacy group for crime victims'
rights, Justice for All, hailed Bush's move as the right decision.
``The State of Texas should not execute anyone whose guilt they
doubt _ and that was the case here,'' said president Dianne
Clements.
</P>
<P>
   Before the parole board's decision on Thursday, Bush's office
had received about 100 letters favoring clemency and six urging
execution. On Friday, though, the office received 178 phone calls
favoring Lucas' execution and only 18 favoring clemency.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after Bush announced his decision, the family of
one of Lucas' victims _ in a 1978 murder to which Lucas confessed _
decried the outcome and said they were sorry they had remained
silent for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a joke going around that if you kill two people with a
pickax and never do another bad thing, you get executed,'' said
Georgetown resident Ninfa Salazar Sheppard, sister of Rita Salazar.
``If you confess to being a serial killer, you are psychological
curiosity worthy of keeping alive. If you exaggerate and claim to
have killed half the state, you become a poor, bumbling innocent:
you therefore cannot have been guilty of anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me a break!''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
