<HEADLINE>
DISNEY HOME VIDEO AIMS TO TEACH CHILDREN ABOUT CASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Walt Disney Co. is making a foray into the
world of financial advising with next month's release of ``Money
Rock,'' a collection of finance-themed songs that will teach kids _
and probably a lot of parents, too _ about money.
</P>
<P>
   The home-video primer has seven songs covering banks, weekly
allowances, checking accounts and Wall Street. The federal budget
is covered by Tax Man Max and Tyrannosaurus Debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Rock'' is one of five ``Schoolhouse Rock'' videos that
Disney will release to retailers beginning July 21 at a suggested
price of $14.99 each.
</P>
<P>
   The animated cartoons on ``Money Rock'' run about four minutes
each and offer a lighthearted view of the often-cold world of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a decent living, it's true, but we gotta pay these
bills when they come due,'' a father tells his son in ``Where the
Money Goes.'' ``Now when a man had to settle, he pulled out coins
of precious metal'' is part of the history of barter in ``This for
That.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Rock'' uses the same style as ABC's Saturday morning
series ``Schoolhouse Rock.'' The video collection includes
``Grammar Rock,'' ``America Rock,'' ``Multiplication Rock'' and
``Science Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0456 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LUCAS-RETRO-COX     06-26 2299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-RETRO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On-again, off-again confessor found notoriety behind bars
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Henry Lee Lucas came to the world's attention on June
21, 1983, while being arraigned in Montague County on an indictment
of murdering an 82-year-old woman. The judge asked if he understood
the seriousness of the murder charge. ``Yes sir,'' he replied, ``I
have about a hundred of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next couple of years, he confessed to hundreds of
murders across the country, then denied it all. Then he would
confess again, and then again he would deny it. One of many
prosecutors who crossed his path wrote that Lucas was ``the
greatest mass murderer in American history, the greatest liar in
American history, or both.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, he once more was in the spotlight he so came to love
when he first forced its warmth on himself 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the State Board of Pardons and Paroles urged Gov.
George W. Bush to spare Lucas, who was scheduled to die Tuesday in
the death chamber at Huntsville. Friday afternoon, the governor
did, commuting Lucas' sentence to life in prison. In something of a
conundrum, the parole board chairman said, ``We firmly believe that
this man remains guilty as found by that jury.'' But, by a vote of
17-1, the board did not believe firmly enough to carry out th e
jury's sentence of death.
</P>
<P>
   That jury, in 1983, found Lucas had murdered a young woman,
never identified, whose body was found in a culvert next to
Interstate 35 north of Georgetown on Halloween 1979. Because of the
only clothing she wore, she has been known ever after as Orange
Socks.
</P>
<P>
   There was no physical evidence to connect Lucas to the crime.
But he confessed and, on the strength of that, was convicted. Of
his 11 convictions for murder, it was the only one that brought a
death sentence. Now, he denies that he did it. Indeed, the attorney
general of Texas says he considers it highly unlikely that Lucas
did the crime, and the man who was attorney general when Lucas was
convicted says there is no way he's guilty. But the Texas Ranger
who investigated another murder of which Lucas was convicted says,
``If anybody deserves to die for something he didn't do, I've never
met a better candidate than Henry.''
</P>
<P>
   A petty, grubby life
</P>
<P>
   Henry Lee Lucas' childhood was squalid and debased, mean and
devoid of anything that childhood is supposed to be. His adult
existence was at best a petty, grubby, physically filthy one,
wafting him around the country on the strength of an ill wind that
blew no good, a life that neither held nor brought any joy. If he
is to be believed, it was a life so perverted and degraded as to
slip beneath what can be considered human. His trademark, if he is
to be believed, was to slaughter his victims and have sex with
their corpses.
</P>
<P>
   He was born into the Great Depression, in 1936, in dirt-poor,
dirt-floor, rural Virginia. His mother was a 50-cent prostitute
described by someone who knew her as ``mean as a rattlesnake,''
according to author Mike Cox in his book ``The Confessions of Henry
Lee Lucas.'' Viola Lucas abused her son constantly and violently.
Once, she hit Henry in the head with a board, knocking him
unconscious for three days. He suffered from dizzy spells and
blackouts from then on.
</P>
<P>
   A childhood injury to his left eye resulted in the glass
prosthesis and droop-lidded look he bore for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He was in and out of jails and prisons all his life, beginning
at age 15 for a burglary.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, the 23-year-old Henry was living with a half-sister in
a small town in Michigan when his mother came to visit. After
drinking, he stabbed and killed her. He served 10 years, five of
those in a psychiatric unit. Then he did five more years for
attempting to kidnap two teen-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   Drifting south to Jacksonville, Fla., he ran into an old
acquaintance named Ottis Toole, a dim-witted pyromaniac and
sometimes transvestite who also had been in and out of trouble with
the law since his early teens.
</P>
<P>
   It was that chance meeting that led to the hellish tangle of
crimes, real or imagined, that would begin to unravel with Lucas'
``I done about a hundred of them'' in the Montague County
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas and Toole, in one junker car after another, traveled the
nation's interstate highways, usually with no particular
destination. According to what they said later, they killed as they
went, for money, sex or simply blood lust. At one point, they
claimed to have killed people in 48 states. Toole died in a Florida
prison in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes traveling with Lucas and Toole, sometimes with Lucas
alone, was Toole's niece Becky Powell, with whom Lucas had fallen
in love when she was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Powell was 15 in 1982, and living with Lucas while he worked as
a handyman for 82-year-old Kate Rich in Montague County, on the Red
River northwest of Fort Worth. She wanted to go home to Florida,
and she and Henry made it as far as Denton County, where they were
spending the night in a field when they got into an argument. Lucas
later led lawmen to that field, where he had stabbed her to death,
dismembered her body and scattered it.
</P>
<P>
   The bombshell
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, back in Montague County, he offered Kate Rich
a ride to church, stabbed her to death and stuffed her body in a
drain pipe. Held on a weapons charge, Lucas confessed to murdering
both Powell and Rich. It was an arraignment for Rich's murder that
brought him to the courtroom where he dropped his bombshell.
</P>
<P>
   He then began confessing to Texas Ranger Phil Ryan, who had
investigated Rich's murder, details of other killings, 126 of them,
some complete with drawings of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1983, convicted in the deaths of Rich and Powell, Lucas
was in the Williamson County jail in Georgetown, awaiting trial for
the murder of Orange Socks, for which he made four separate
confessions.
</P>
<P>
   Besieged by requests from law enforcement officers around the
nation who were eager to interview Lucas about unsolved murders,
Williamson County Sheriff Jim Boutwell asked the Texas Department
of Public Safety for help. DPS established a task force to serve as
a clearinghouse for information.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of months, Lucas had talked to more than 100 law
officers who had ``cleared'' 23 crimes they believed were committed
by Lucas and another 36 by Lucas and Toole together. And his
schedule was full for weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Lee was important for the first time in his life. He was
receiving constant attention. A copious drinker of coffee and
chain-smoker of Pall Malls, he had all he wanted of both. He had
been flown to other states to assist in unsolved cases. On the
road, if he wanted steaks, he got steaks. He was, one of his
court-appointed lawyers said, ``bouncy.'' Aside from being in
custody, it was probably the best he had ever lived. To keep that,
all he had to do was keep confessing.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to enjoy telling people what he thought they wanted to
hear. Law officers who came to Georgetown were cautioned not to
give him too many details of their cases, not to give him enough to
let him make a believable confession. Several times, he had been
tested with fake information about fictitious cases and had taken
the bait.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, though, the man who seemingly would confess to
anything at first denied the murder for which he was sentenced to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Unidentified woman
</P>
<P>
   Ranger Phil Ryan had asked Lucas about an unidentified white
woman in her mid-20s, 5 feet, 9 inches and 138 pounds, who had been
strangled, her nude body dumped on the highway in Williamson County
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not take that one,'' Ryan says. ``He said 'No.' Later,
I saw Boutwell on TV, . . . and then I hear (Lucas) confessed to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Walsh, then the district attorney who prosecuted Lucas for
the Orange Socks murder, says that a key point to him was that when
Boutwell was driving Lucas to Georgetown from Montague County,
Lucas pointed out the culvert where the body was discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan says he asked Lucas about that, because of his initial
denial, and Lucas told him, ``'I knew I was looking for a culvert,
and when (Boutwell) slowed down, I just took the next one.' That
was just Henry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Socks trial began in March 1984 in San Angelo in Tom
Green County on a change of venue from Williamson County. The
prosecution offered written, audiotaped and videotaped confessions.
Lucas said he had picked up the woman hitchhiking in Oklahoma, had
sex with her at a roadside picnic area, strangled her and dumped
her body in a culvert on I-35.
</P>
<P>
   The defense said work records and a cashed check showed that
Lucas was in Florida when the murder occurred. Prosecutors said the
records might have been falsified and that Lucas had plenty of time
to get to Florida to cash the check.
</P>
<P>
   The jury took 40 minutes to find him guilty of capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years later, David Lindemann, who was on that jury,
says, ``The trial just seemed so overwhelming that he did it. He
went into details about how he killed the girl. . . . He admitted
to everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, then the district attorney, says he also has no doubts.
To the suggestion that Sheriff Boutwell might have in some way
hinted to Lucas where the body was found, Walsh says, ``He was not
the type of man who would do that.'' And, Walsh says, ``If I really
thought that an innocent man was about to be executed, I should be
and would be the first one to say, 'Wait a minute, let's take
another look.' I just don't have any of those feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   After his conviction, Lucas remained in Georgetown more than a
year, as the task force continued and yet more officers came to
talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilson was then Boutwell's chief deputy. The question of why
Lucas would continue to confess to other crimes after a conviction
for capital murder, he answers with another question. ``Once you
have the death penalty on one, why not tell officers anything they
wanted to hear? They can only kill you once.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear cracks
</P>
<P>
   While the law officers who came from near and far to question
Lucas had been cautioned all along to be wary of what he said, now
clear cracks began to appear in the mountain of confessions he was
piling up.
</P>
<P>
   In May of 1984, Henry Lee confessed to the 1975 murder in
Lubbock of Deborah Williamson. But when her parents read Lucas'
statement, they thought it was all wrong, that he did not do it.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1985, Dallas Times-Herald reporter Hugh Aynesworth, who
had interviewed Lucas, wrote a story that said Lucas had told him
that he'd killed his mother, Becky Powell and Kate Rich. All the
rest were hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas denied it. He said that since talking to Aynesworth, his
newfound religious beliefs had compelled him to confess to all of
his murderous sins.
</P>
<P>
   Vic Feazell, the McLennan County district attorney, had convened
a grand jury in Waco to investigate three murders there to which
Lucas confessed. Feazell didn't believe him and asked for help from
the state attorney general's office. After meeting with Feazell and
with Lucas, Attorney General Jim Mattox said, ``I am convinced
Lucas is not guilty of some of the cases he has confessed to.''
From there, Mattox launched an investigation into Lucas' multitude
of confessions.
</P>
<P>
   That April 23 in Waco, Lucas set off another bomb. He said that
he had never killed anyone except his mother, 25 years earlier. He
put the blame for his confessions on Texas Rangers and other law
officers eager to clear unsolved cases. He said that God was the
reason he had ``decided to tell the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Six days later, Lucas was interviewed on audiotape by a radio
evangelist named Bob Larsen. Recanting his recantation, Lucas told
Larsen, ``I killed the people. . . . The truth is I killed 360
people, and the only way I can prove it is with the help of the
police in Georgetown and the Rangers.''
</P>
<P>
   Two days after that, Larsen aired the tape. But, he told his
listeners, moments before the show went on the air, Lucas had
called him from Waco and said to him, ``What I told you . . . was a
lie.''
</P>
<P>
   No further questioning
</P>
<P>
   A judge in Waco shortly thereafter barred media access to Lucas
and said law officers were not to question him without his lawyer
present. His lawyer said there would be no further questioning of
Lucas without permission, which effectively shut down the
long-running Henry Lee Lucas confession -denial show. Two years
after he blurted ``about a hundred of them,'' he was in Huntsville,
on death row.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Attorney General Mattox released his office's Lucas
Report. While ``we found no evidence to prove that any members of
law enforcement in Texas deliberately tried to bring about this
scheme of deception,'' it said, ``we have found information that
would lead us to believe that some officials 'cleared cases' just
to get them off the books.''
</P>
<P>
   And, the report said there was a notable lack of physical
evidence linking Lucas to the crimes to which he confessed, except
for those of his mother, Becky Powell and the elderly widow, Kate
Rich.
</P>
<P>
   In the Orange Socks case, it concluded that Lucas was in Florida
at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this year, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
held that ``the Lucas Report does not contain any significant new
evidence that in substance was not presented to the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   The unsatisfying answer to whether Henry Lee Lucas was any kind
of serial killer or simply an adept and confident liar may best be
found in Jim Mattox's words when he first met Lucas in Waco 13
years ago. ``I'm not sure anybody really knows. I'm not sure even
he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
