u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-O'NEIL     06-26 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-O'NEILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL'S BAT SALVAGES TORRE'S EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (sidebar with BBO-METS-YANKS)  
(bl) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill walked across the Shea Stadium outfield
alone four hours before Friday night's game, wandering like a fan
trying not to get noticed. Joe Torre and a dozen of O'Neill's
teammates had already vanished into the third base dugout, and he
crept along so deliberately that it was easy to overlook him.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the monumental matchup between the Yankees and the
Mets was over Friday night, it was impossible not to notice O'Neill
and impossible to overlook what he had done. O'Neill might have
breezed across the grass like a nobody in the afternoon, but he
breezed around the bases like a somebody in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill saved the first-time first baseman Jorge Posada from a
dubious distinction and saved Torre, his manager, from criticism
for putting the catcher at first base in place of Tino Martinez. By
clubbing a three-run homer off Mel Rojas in the seventh inning to
erase a 4-3 deficit, O'Neill helped catapult the Yankees to an 8-4
victory before 53,404 fans.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neill reached a rowdy dugout, a slice of the Bronx had
invaded Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have two teams that are both from New York, there's
no in between,'' O'Neill had said earlier. ``You can't like the
Yankees and the Mets. It's either one or the other. That's what
makes this so important to the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also important to the man who signs O'Neill's checks, who
was surely unhappy when Posada almost turned the night into a
nightmare. Posada was blunt when asked what Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine might do against a catcher making his major league debut
at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit it over there,'' Posada said. ``Find out if he can play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did precisely that, and that is why they almost
defeated the Yankees in the back-and-forth clash. Whenever a
manager tries to use an inexperienced player at a new position,
there is the danger that the player will be involved in a critical
sequence. Posada was in that position Friday night, and he
faltered.
</P>
<P>
   With the score at 3-3 in the sixth and Mets perched on first and
third with none out, the Yankees moved Posada and third baseman
Scott Brosius in for a potential play at the plate. So when Carlos
Baerga smacked a sharp one-bouncer to Posada, he should have
whipped the ball home to Joe Girardi to nab Mike Piazza from third.
</P>
<P>
   But Posada's adventure started once he took two steps to his
left and touched first base for the first out. Though it was a
risky choice, Posada still had time to gun Piazza down at home.
Instead, he flipped the ball to Derek Jeter at second base, and
Jeter eventually tagged John Olerud for a double play. The Yankees
got two outs, but the wrong two, and the Mets got one pivotal run
for a 4-3 lead. Posada got one huge demerit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to have the instincts,'' he had said. ``I've
never played first. I won't be like Tino. It's not going to come
natural to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not. Posada conceded he did not know how adequate a first
baseman he would be, but he proved adequate enough until the sixth.
Posada was more productive offensively as a one-night replacement
for the slumping Martinez as he ripped three hits, drove in one run
and scored another.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing first?,'' Martinez, who had lobbied Torre to
start him against the left-hander Al Leiter, said before the game.
Martinez, who bats left-handed and who has a sore right shoulder
after being hit by a pitch from Atlanta's John Rocker on Thursday
night, quickly changed his tone of surprise and said: ``He will do
fine. He's a good athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a good athlete does not automatically become a good first
baseman. Posada, who was drafted by the Yankees as a shortstop and
often fields grounders during batting practice, said he played
first base for Santurce in the Puerto Rican winter league. It was
the first time Posada had made such a revelation; he previously had
said he was used as a designated hitter in about 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop lying to the reporters,'' Jeter shouted to Posada. ``You
never played first.''
</P>
<P>
   The amusing scene was still amusing to the Yankees after the
game because of O'Neill. Once O'Neill went deep off Rojas' first
pitch in the seventh, the Yankees exhaled. They had walked across
Shea in the afternoon, with O'Neill trailing them, and they bolted
from Shea in the night, with O'Neill leading them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this weekend, these games mean something,'' O'Neill said.
``But later in the season, they won't mean anything. We lost once
to the Mets last year. I don't remember that. The only loss I
remember is losing at the end to Cleveland.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
