<HEADLINE>
JUDGE REJECTS RESULTS OF AFFIRMATIVE ACTION VOTE IN HOUSTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif.) 
(See optional ending) 
 
By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A judge Friday threw out the results of last fall's
election in which voters upheld Houston's affirmative action
program.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Sharolyn Wood said the city's language on
the Nov. 4 ballot did not reflect the intent of the more than
20,000 people who had signed petitions to put the question to
voters. Opponents had argued that the city purposely changed the
language in order to defeat the referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The program sets an overall goal of 20 percent participation for
women and minorities for city contracts. The issue also put the
national spotlight on Houston for its bucking of a growing
dissatisfaction with set-aside programs.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, Proposition A, was soundly defeated by a 54 percent
to 46 percent margin. Former Mayor Bob Lanier, who led opposition
to the affirmative action referendum, was applauded by President
Clinton for his efforts in defeating the measure.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Mayor Lee Brown, in San Antonio
attending the Texas Democratic Convention, said Friday that the
city will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very disappointed that Judge Wood agreed that the
ballot language did not fairly convey the subject matter. Unless
the city appeals, the city will be obligated to hold a second
charter election at a cost of more than one million dollars to city
taxpayers,'' the mayor's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   William Helfand, attorney for petition organizer Ed Blum and two
others, said his clients want an election as soon as possible,
although he expects no such election will happen until after the
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be judged in contracts and hiring on the basis
of their ability and not on the basis of their race,'' said
plaintiff Edward Chen, 61, a chemistry professor who is
Chinese-American. ``Unless people stand up for what they believe,
our country will fall into the hands of City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Blum, 46, who spearheaded the ballot petition drive and who
originally filed the lawsuit contesting the election, has declined
to comment recently on the matter. The third plaintiff, high school
teacher Al Vera, also was unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   During Tuesday's summary judgment arguments, Wood said the city
has some flexibility in changing the wording of a proposition
brought by voters as long as the original meaning is preserved. But
her ruling Friday indicates that language on the ballot that was
composed by the city was significantly different from that of the
petitions.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition originally submitted by Blum read: ``The city of
Houston shall not discriminate against, or grant preferential
treatment to, any individual or group on the basis of race, sex,
color, ethnicity or national origin in the operation of public
employment and public contracting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of Lanier, City Council changed the wording to:
``Shall the charter of the city of Houston be amended to end the
use of affirmative action for women and minorities in the operation
of city of Houston employment and contracting, including ending the
current program and similar programs in the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Helfand told Wood on Tuesday that Lanier chose the language
because polls taken before the election showed the new phrasing
``would significantly change results.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city clearly purposely injected emotionally charged
phrases like `affirmative action' and identified women and
minorities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Helfand said because it is unclear if the term affirmative
action means ``equal opportunity or preferences,'' a California
court rejected the use of the phrase on Proposition 209, an
initiative in which voters ended that state's use of affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney also argued the city improperly substituted a
specific policy for a philosophy that could have had larger
implications.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Lanier said that his purpose in changing the wording
was so voters would know exactly what the impact of the proposition
would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The petitioners tried to get it on the ballot without saying
they wanted to end affirmative action,'' Lanier said. ``To my mind
they are the ones who were trying to be deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wood's ruling did not resolve all the issues in the case,
including one raised by the city because Blum no longer lives in
Houston and another because Chen and Vera joined the suit after the
summary judgment motions were filed.
</P>
<P>
   Wood ruled Blum could contest the election because he was
eligible to vote in November, but said he does not have standing to
ask for a new election because he now lives in West University
Place. Helfand said he is confident Wood still will order a new
election because Chen and Vera live in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wood set a trial date of Aug. 17 to hear arguments on whether
she can order a new election.
</P>
<P>
   A pending case challenging the constitutionality of the
affirmative action program might make the issue of a new election
moot.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge Lynn N. Hughes is expected to rule
this summer on a lawsuit filed by grass and sod contractor Robert
Kossman, who says the city denied him contracts, even though he was
the low bidder, because he is white.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the same judge struck down the Metropolitan Transit
Authority's affirmative action program in language so broad that
the city's seemed to also be in danger. The case currently is
before the U.S. 5th Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the program interpreted the statement as an
indication Hughes is leaning toward dismantling the program, but
city leaders said Hughes was only advising them to make stronger
arguments showing a history of discrimination than those made by
Metro.
</P>
<P>
   The goals for minority participation in the program are 17
percent of construction contracts, 11 percent of purchasing and 24
percent of professional services.
</P>
<P>
   These goals were drafted by Lanier in 1995, modifying a 1984
affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Rob Todd, an outspoken opponent of affirmative
action, said the city should ``absolutely'' spend the money for a
new election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let this be an example to all council members that just
because the city attorney says something is correct, that doesn't
mean that it is,'' said Todd, who applauded the ruling as a
vindication of those on council who opposed rewriting the ballot
measure.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, said she was ``extremely
disappointed'' at the ruling and hopes that the city appeals it to
the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public knew what it was voting for,'' said Jackson Lee,
who was also attending the Texas Democratic Convention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Alan Bernstein and Julie Mason contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
