u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-TIANANMEN-SCENE062     06-26 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-TIANANMEN-SCENE0627-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIANANMEN QUIETED FOR CLINTON, JIANG CEREMONY
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON0627-2NDLD.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Tiananmen Square was quiet as a mausoleum early
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The world's biggest public square was flat and broad and nearly
empty, a circle of red flags high on central poles waving under
gentle breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Not a kite-flier was there to float a brilliant-colored dragon
or bird through the sky. Absent were the crowds of Chinese who
daily come from the provinces to snap photos at their country's
famous memorials.
</P>
<P>
   It was a peoples' square that blocked out the people for half of
one hot morning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, two soldiers walked two German shepherds up and down
the gray paving stones, sniffing for anything that might spoil the
soon-to-come moment of glory for China's leaders and even for many
of its common people.
</P>
<P>
   A short row of soldiers in green stood at attention for more
than an hour behind eight cannons lined up below the flags, near
the Monument to the People's Heroes at center square.
</P>
<P>
   The metro was closed. The streets were closed. The cars and
bicycles and pedestrians were held at bay by soldiers or police
standing like ramrods at every conceivable entry point to the vast
space.
</P>
<P>
   This was the square with the Chinese government in full control,
on this particular Saturday morning sending the message that this
is not a government to trifle with.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message because this was the ceremony for U.S.
President Bill Clinton, and he would soon become the first American
president to visit this place since the 1989 horrors unfolded when
tanks rolled through the streets and into the square and mowed down
hundreds of Chinese people. Some had been protesting and demanding
democracy. Others had just gotten in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Americans had protested Clinton's agreement to be welcomed here,
saying it was an endorsement of a Chinese government that never
admitted it had done wrong here nine years ago. But he chose to
come anyway. The Chinese had asked. How could he said no?
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony itself began sharply at 9 a.m. (China time) when
Clinton and his wife and Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his wife
appeared on the smaller plaza adjacent to Tiananmen fronting the
monstrously-big Great Hall of the people.
</P>
<P>
   It was sober and solemn once the four finished glad-handing the
dignitaries who came -- a couple dozen Chinese VIPs and hundreds of
Americans invited to drop their normal activities as students or
teachers or business executives and come watch their President.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Jiang stood on a red-carpeted podium with brass
rails and listened to the military band play their national
anthems, as the canon in the square boomed out the 21 shots in
salute.
</P>
<P>
   It was majestic, somber and sad.
</P>
<P>
   As the two presidents walked past in review of the troops,
Clinton was stiff and serious, almost looking pained, though he
never seemed to look over the heads of the soldiers and into the
square beyond that symbolizes the killing of a notion of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
