<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OYSTERS-RECALL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTED TEXAS OYSTERS SICKEN 51 AS SHIPMENTS RECALLED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Calif., Colo., Fla., La., N.M.) 
(Eds.: Sub for minor editing throughout) 
 
By KEVIN MORAN 
and CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ Oyster wholesalers scrambled Friday to recall
shipments from throughout Texas and five other states as health
officials warned that an outbreak of illness from contaminated
Galveston Bay oysters could become the worst in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Texas health officials had recorded 51 cases of the illness as
of Friday, with six involving people who had eaten Galveston Bay
oysters in Florida restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Coastal Leaseholders Association who harvest from
state-controlled Galveston Bay oyster beds were working with state
and federal officials to track shipments taken from seven beds
known to have produced oysters that made people sick.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters from the bay also have been shipped to restaurants in
California, Colorado, New Mexico and Louisiana, said Doug McBride,
spokesman for the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd be surprised if there aren't a bunch more cases
reported,'' he said, adding that calls were coming in to a health
department toll-free number.
</P>
<P>
   The illness is caused by a bacterium called Vibrio
parahaemolyticus, which normally causes diarrhea and abdominal
cramps, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, this is the second-largest outbreak of Vibrio
parahaemolyticus in the country, and it has the potential of
surpassing the one a year ago in the Pacific Northwest, where they
had 208 cases and one fatality,'' said Dr. Ralph Morris, director
of the Galveston County Health District.
</P>
<P>
   For most people the organism is not life-threatening, Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By and large, this is a fairly mild disease, with diarrhea and
abdominal cramping,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials said some victims also could suffer
nausea, vomiting, fever and headache. They said symptoms can occur
from three to 30 hours after people eat contaminated oysters and
could last from one day to a week.
</P>
<P>
   Although death is rare, the disease can be particularly
dangerous to people who have liver problems or weakened immune
systems, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   After agreeing late Thursday to quit harvesting oysters for at
least two weeks, Galveston Bay wholesalers were working Friday to
recall shipments of potentially harmful oysters from around Texas
and the other five states, McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said 17 cases of the illness have been reported since
June 5 in Galveston County. Those involved people who had eaten raw
oysters at Landry's Seafood Restaurant and Joe's Crab Shack in
Kemah and Willie G's restaurant in Galveston, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All three restaurants are owned by Houston-based Landry's
Seafood Restaurants Inc. The company announced Thursday it will
serve only oysters from Louisiana until Galveston Bay oysters are
declared safe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Kemah and Galveston, people are known to have
gotten sick in Texas after eating oysters in restaurants in
Amarillo, Arlington, Austin, Athens, Abilene and Frisco, McBride
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said oystermen voluntarily ceased harvesting in the bay
and began recalling some shipments during a meeting with health
officials Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real hard decision for them to come to, but I think
they're obviously acting in the interests of the public,'' Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oystermen said while they could have kept harvesting in some
areas, they decided to quit taking oysters until the state tests
water and oysters from all of the beds.
</P>
<P>
   Marine scientist Dr. John Schwarz of Texas A&AMP;M
University-Galveston will conduct those tests and expects to have
results in 10 days, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa and Johnny Halili own Johnny's Oysters in San Leon and
employ about 150 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We voluntarily surrendered our permits and closed ourselves
because we care about the public's health,'' said Lisa Halili, who
with her husband leases about 500 acres of oyster beds in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Halilis and five other wholesalers lease about 2,500 acres
of Galveston Bay oyster beds from the state. From May 1 to Nov. 1
each year, the leases are the only bay areas from which oysters can
be harvested, according to state regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters taken from the leased beds are transplanted from
polluted waters and allowed to purge themselves of impurities for
several weeks before being harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the outbreak of the illness probably is related to
this year's unusual weather. The prolonged, early heat wave and
lack of rain changed the normal temperature and quality of the bay
water around the oyster beds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organism multiplies more readily in water that has high
salinity,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak will be costly and hard on fishermen's families,
Lisa Halili said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 70 or 80 fishermen and they all have kids,'' she said.
``We'll see if some can go to Louisiana, but it's expensive to get
an out-of-state license.''
</P>
<P>
   Processing plant workers will not get paid if there are no
oysters, she added.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials urged people not to eat oysters from
Galveston Bay unless they are cooked thoroughly. There is little
risk from eating other seafood from the bay, they said, as long as
it is cooked.
</P>
<P>
   People who experience symptoms of the illness for more than 24
hours are advised to see a doctor. Anyone who has eaten seafood one
or two days before experiencing the symptoms is asked to call the
state Health Department at 1-888-883-9997.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
