u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT &LR;      06-26 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-YANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DRAW FIRST BLOOD FROM METS, 8-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also METS-YANKS-O'NEILL and METS-YANKS-PITCHING) 
(mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rivers of blue hats formed in the aisles at Shea
Stadium after the eighth inning Friday night, Mets fans, depressed
and departing. Above them, a mocking chorus started: ``Hey, Hey,
Na, Na, Goodbye.'' Yankee fans were serenading their counterparts
out of their own park.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had won the city's bragging rights for at least one
day, after Paul O'Neill ripped a three-run homer in the seventh
inning off Mel Rojas, propelling the Bronx team to an 8-4 victory
over the Queens team. A crowd of 53,404 was on hand, the largest of
the season at Shea, the enthusiasm hardly dampened by the
sweltering heat.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's home run turned a 4-3 deficit into a 6-4 advantage,
and the Yankees added two late runs. Ramiro Mendoza pitched 2 2/3
scoreless innings to earn the victory in relief, and Mariano Rivera
picked up his 19th save by getting the final two outs.
</P>
<P>
   A defensive lapse by Jorge Posada, making his first major-league
appearance at first base, allowed the Mets to take a 4-3 lead in
the sixth. Mets fans, who constituted perhaps 60 percent of the
crowd, howled and shouted and chanted, nine outs from seizing the
first game of the series that continues Saturday afternoon and
Sunday night. But Al Leiter, the Mets' starting pitcher, had
labored through the middle innings, and eventually a contribution
would be needed from the Mets' slumping bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter walked Chuck Knoblauch with one out in the seventh, and
Derek Jeter chopped a slow roller toward the first-base hole.
Leiter, a left-hander, flies off toward third base as he completes
his delivery, and knowing he would have to cover first, he twisted
awkwardly with his first step. Jeter beat out the play, and Leiter
was limping on a strained knee. He would have to come out.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine called on the right-handed Rojas to
pitch to O'Neill, the Yankees' left-handed-hitting right fielder.
Valentine knew the numbers: While right-handed batters have hit
.397 against Rojas, lefties had batted only .182 against him, with
no home runs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill stood in the on-deck circle and watched Rojas warming
up, then strolled to the plate. Rojas fired his first pitch
homeward, a fastball _ and O'Neill blasted it high and long into
the left-field stands.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill slapped his hands together as he rounded first base, his
teammates joyously spilling out of their dugout, high-fiving each
other. O'Neill paused at home plate before stamping on the base,
then high-fived Jeter and Knoblauch and plunged into a sea of
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Yankees pretend that they like the other
organization, and that this series is just like any other
regular-season series. But those polite gestures hardly explain why
some in the Yankee offices have lived in fear of consecutive losses
to the Mets and the reaction they could generate from a certain
principal owner, or why the Mets engaged in unsubtle gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Yogi Berra, a Yankee legend who has vowed to avoid Yankee
Stadium because of his feud with George Steinbrenner, threw out the
first ball at Shea Friday night. The Mets changed uniforms for the
game, stripping their names off the back. And a day before the
series was to begin, Valentine hinted to reporters that Hideki
Irabu, the Yankees' starter, was tipping his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both the Yankees and the Mets believe that Irabu is
providing clues that contributed to his beating in Cleveland last
Sunday (five runs and three home runs in three innings). But, as
the two sides prepared for Friday night's game, they had completely
different ideas on what clue Irabu is giving.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, according to a member of the organization, believe
that Irabu's intentions can be read from his feet: When he's
throwing a fastball, his front foot bursts forward quickly; when
throwing an off-speed pitch, a curveball or a splitter, the Mets
say Irabu is much more deliberate with his front foot.
</P>
<P>
   Fast foot, fastball. Slow foot, curveball or splitter.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankee pitching coach, disagreed. He
thought Irabu was tipping his pitches somehow with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu may or may not be tipping his pitches, and the Mets may or
may not have been reading him correctly. But this much is true:
They were all over everything he threw Friday night. Edgardo
Alfonzo, the Mets' first hitter, fouled off five pitches during his
10-pitch at-bat _ and the first time through the batting order, the
Mets had 14 foul balls and only one swing and miss, that by Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's stuff was too good for the Mets to exploit, however, and
he was fortunate to survive a potentially disastrous first inning.
After Alfonzo walked and scampered to third on Bernard Gilkey's
hit-and-run single through the right side, Irabu walked Mike Piazza
on four pitches, filling the bases. A couple of hits might have
finished Irabu that quickly, but John Olerud bounced into a doube
play, Alfonzo scoring from third, and Carlos Baerga grounded out to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   With the reprieve, the Yankees began trading the lead with the
Mets. Posada tied the score at 1-1 with a run-scoring single in the
fourth, and Knoblauch drove home the lead run in the fifth, putting
the Yankees ahead by 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets responded when Brian McRae timed an Irabu fastball
leading off the fifth _ fast foot, fastball _ and whacked it off
the right-field foul pole for a home run. Three batters later,
Alfonzo waited perfectly for a curveball _ slow foot, curveball _
and slammed a home run over the left-field fence. Advantage Mets,
3-2, before the Yankees tied the score on a double by Posada and a
single by Scott Brosius in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   With Tino Martinez slumping, his shoulder sore, Yankee manager
Joe Torre started Posada at first base. For 5 1/2 innings, the
Yankees got away with it. But with Met runners at first and third
and nobody out in the sixth, Posada fielded a grounder and should
have thrown home to cut off the tie-breaking run. Instead, he
stepped on first base, then threw to second to complete a double
play, allowing Piazza to score and give the Mets a short-lived 4-3
lead.
</P>
<P>
   When Torre replaced Irabu later in the inning, a chant of
``Let's go Mets'' reverberated around Shea.
</P>
<P>
   But those who participated were silenced, if only for one night.
The Yankees and Mets play Game 2 of the series Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The Mets very nearly turned a triple play in the second inning.
With Tim Raines on second and Jorge Posada on first, Chad Curtis
hit a liner toward the shortstop hole, with Raines breaking from
second. But Rey Ordonez, the Mets' shortstop, dived to his right
and speared the ball, flipped over and started to throw to second,
but held the ball. At that moment, Raines was nearing third and
Posada was more than halfway to second. After his pause, Ordonez
threw to second to double Raines, but the Mets had lost their
chance to get Posada at first, leaving the crowd twittering about
what could have been. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
