<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0465 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9761 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-26 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A SEQUEL WORTHY OF THE SANDLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 C.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At about 3:30 Friday afternoon, Manager Joe Torre led
the Yankees into the Shea stadium. This was an odd scene. Normally
the visiting team enters through a back entrance. Friday, the
Yankees sauntered through the Mets bullpen in right field and
walked across the outfield grass.
</P>
<P>
   If it were not for the backdrop of the stadium, with a big-time
scoreboard and tiers of seats, this could have been a team from one
neighborhood coming to play a sandlot game against a cross-town
rival. There were no sport coats, no slacks. Instead, the players
wore jeans and some even wore shorts. Subway apparel for a Subway
Series. Year 2, Game 1, of a series for the battle of New York's
baseball soul.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in three scintillating games wrapped in the fervor
of a playoff series, the Yankees prevailed two games to one. They
won the rubber game of the series with a game-winning hit in the
10th inning by Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Friday the series shifted 10 miles and several levels of
ambition down the Grand Central Parkway to Shea Stadium. Publicly,
a number of players said this was simply another game, another
series, three more games on the schedule. Certainly for the
Yankees, who won Friday night, 8-4, and continued to be a team on
track to compile one of the best records ever in baseball, this
series could be seen as an opportunity to gobble up more victories
and the Mets along with them.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for this night, this series, the Mets and Yankees tore off
the labels and cast away the designations. No white collar, no blue
collar; no American League, no National League. This wasn't about
interleague play. These games are about the continuation of a good
old-fashioned knockdown drag-out sandlot game with deep roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I got here, everyone started talking about it,
talking about how exciting it was,'' said Mike Piazza, the Mets'
recently acquired catcher. ``I wondered, `How exciting can it be?'
But you get caught up in the excitement. You try to keep it in
perspective, remind yourself that it's still the middle of the
season but there's no question that there are bragging rights and
pride at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   When Piazza was with Los Angeles last season, the Dodgers played
four games against the Anaheim Angels. ``But it was nothing like
this,'' he said. ``The tradition here goes so far back. Ever since
the Mets were formed, they have been trying to get to that level as
far as tradition is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Yankees were defending champions and the Mets
were in yet another rebuilding year. This season the Mets and
Yankees are trains racing toward each other. The Yankees just took
three of four games from the Braves; the Mets did the same to
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is our year to win, there's no question that this is a
great matchup as far as seeing how we do against the cream of both
leagues,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all of the buildup of a series between teams with
drastically different roots, there is excitement but not
electricity. This year, the stadium is not part of the drama, it
simply houses the drama. A large part of last year's rivalry was
the historic novelty: in the first year of interleague play, the
Mets were making their first regular season appearance at Yankee
Stadium, a place with a physical presence that resonates history.
</P>
<P>
   Shea Stadium isn't drenched in tradition; the Mets don't have to
carry the burden of history week to week, season to season. The
drama and interest are created by the game.
</P>
<P>
   At Shea, there is no neighborhood, per se. The stadium is
surrounded by parkland, an industrial park dotted by clusters of
auto-body shops.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Yankees want public money to build new stadiums.
The Mets want an old-style park fashioned after Brooklyn's
long-gone Ebbets Field; Steinbrenner wants to abandon the Bronx for
a new stadium on the West Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   For Brian McRae, the Mets' outfielder, leaving Yankee Stadium
would be a great equalizer for Yankee opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You drive here and its just a stadium; you drive there and
you're in awe, because it's Yankee Stadium,'' McRae said. ``Even
when I was in Kansas City there was something about that. You got
the train tracks running by, the river, you got the bat outside. If
they move, they got to start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be like the Cubs moving from Wrigley Field, the Red Sox
moving from Fenway. ``You won't be scared to go to the Bronx to
play the Yankees,'' McRae said, ``because the stadium won't be
there anymore. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980626.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-26 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9764 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-POSADA-NYT &LR;      06-26 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-POSADA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S ON FIRST? POSADA MAKES UNLIKELY DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jorge Posada, the Yankee catcher, turned first
baseman on a night that happened to be of the biggest of the
season. He was blunt when asked what he would do if he managed the
Mets and saw a neophyte playing first. Posada never hesitated to
guess Bobby Valentine's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit it over there,'' Posada said. ``Find out if he can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Posada conceded he did not know what type of first
baseman he would be. Manager Joe Torre and the batting coach, Chris
Chambliss, a former first baseman, both added that they had never
seen Posada at the position. Imagine that? It was obviously curious
for Torre to allow Posada to make his major league debut at first
as the one-night replacement for the slumping Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing first?'' said Martinez, who lobbied Torre to
start against the left-hander Al Leiter and lost. Martinez, who
bats left-handed and who has a sore right shoulder after being hit
by John Rocker on Thursday night, quickly changed his tone of
surprise before saying: ``He will do fine. He's a good athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a good athlete does not automatically become a good first
baseman. Posada, who was drafted by the Yankees as a shortstop and
often fields grounders during batting practice, said he played
first for Santurce in the Puerto Rican winter league. It was the
first time Posada had made such a revelation. He had said he was
used as a designated hitter in about 20 games while resting his
knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop lying to the reporters,'' Derek Jeter shouted to Posada
after he was asked if he had seen his teammate at first while
visiting Puerto Rico. ``You never played first.''
</P>
<P>
   But Posada was at first Friday night, and Tim Raines, who has
spent most of his 18-year career as a leadoff hitter, batted
cleanup against the Mets for the first time in almost nine years.
So Torre used a right-handed-dominated lineup that had a
spring-training flair in a skirmish that means the world to fans in
the five boroughs and beyond and, of course, to George
Steinbrenner, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not your traditional cleanup hitter, but I'll be playing
that role tonight,'' said Raines, who had not batted fourth since
Aug. 29, 1989, with Montreal. ``It's not like I'm going to try and
become a slugger and hit home runs. But it will be nice to hit with
some runners in scoring position.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Raines cackled, which was something Posada was not doing.
While he initially took a carefree attitude to making his debut at
first in this of all contests, the 26-year-old could not hide his
anxiety. How would he react to bunts? Would he know where to be on
cutoffs from the outfield? What if he had to turn a 3-6-3 double
play? And, perhaps most important, would Posada have the proper
footwork around the base?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll find out how comfortable I'll be,'' Posada said. ``I know
I have to catch ground balls. We'll see. I'll be nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Posada was not alone. When Jeter was asked if Posada
could handle first, he simply said, ``I hope so. I'll let you know
after the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, who is a poor defensive player, could compound
Posada's potential difficulties. Valentine knows Irabu's strengths
and weaknesses from having managed him in Japan, and it would not
be surprising for him to instruct his players to push a few bunts
between the mound and first base to see if they cause chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to have the instincts,'' Posada said. ``I've
never played first. I won't be like Tino. It's not going to come
natural to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss downplayed the presence of a weak-fielding pitcher and
said: ``If you're a good athlete, and he is, you can do it. The
fact that somebody is a good or a bad fielder is not going to
affect the first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said he bypassed Martinez because the Yankees follow
Friday night's game with an afternoon game Saturday, and he did not
want the first baseman to irritate a nagging shoulder injury that
has bothered him since the Orioles' Armando Benitez plunked him on
May 21. The manager could have used the veteran Dale Sveum at
first, but he bats left-handed, and the Yankees loaded up on
right-handed hitters. That meant a nervous Posada was the
surprising answer to who was on first for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing,'' said Martinez, who is 16 for his last 91
(.176). ``There are three games here. Hopefully, I'll play tomorrow
and the next day. Physically, I'm fine. I can play. I think if I
had been swinging the bat better, I'd be playing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
