<HEADER>
A9770 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-26 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' NEW OWNERS LIED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To sum it all up:
</P>
<P>
   They lied.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgertown lounge, the ``Cheers''-like bar in Vero Beach,
Fla., the day the team's sale was approved by major-league owners,
the men from Fox assembled club employees and reassured them that
no sweeping changes lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In TV interviews, the men from Fox said they would allow the
people already running the team to continue doing it in their own
successful way.
</P>
<P>
   In radio interviews, the men from Fox said don't worry about the
subtle changes in hallowed Dodger Stadium, they had nothing but
respect for Los Angeles Dodgers traditions.
</P>
<P>
   They lied.
</P>
<P>
   They can put any spin they want on the five weeks that shook Los
Angeles, starting with the Mike Piazza trade and continuing with
the firings of Fred Claire, Bill Russell and most of the coaching
staff. They can say circumstances changed, that those promises no
longer applied. But that doesn't excuse them.
</P>
<P>
   They've made sweeping changes, replaced the men in charge of the
front office and dugout with rookies, and been thoroughly
insensitive to the traditionalist nature of Dodgers fans, all after
going out of their way to say they wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe it's not what they've done with the team _ each trade
and firing is defensible in its own right _ as much as the clumsy
way they've done it.
</P>
<P>
   Like firing general manager Claire and manager Russell, each
popular in what used to be thought of as the Dodgers family, only
hours after the death of Al Campanis, the grandfatherly former GM.
Yes, club president Bob Graziano had made up his mind about the
firings and Peter O'Malley taught him to act on decisions
immediately, but would waiting one day have hurt anything?
</P>
<P>
   Like trotting out softball-style ``Think Blue Week'' jerseys,
and debuting an eye-straining new crisscross design in the infield
grass, on the Wednesday night that 30 years of Dodgers coaching
experience was let go. It might surprise the Fox people, but such
little things as uniforms and mowing patterns really matter to
fans, and when they change at the same time as the rest of the
Dodgers world seems to be exploding, fans wonder if anything is
sacred.
</P>
<P>
   A fan roots for his favorite players. Then suppose they're
traded away. Now he roots for something he knows vaguely as The
Club _ meaning, really, the institutional memory borne by
fourth-decade employees like Claire and Russell. Then suppose
employees like that are fired. Now he roots for whatever is
symbolized by the crisp white of a uniform. Then suppose he can't
even count on that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Did they know they were lying? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't know the Dodgers would have virtually the same
record as the Pittsburgh Pirates heading into a late-June series.
They didn't know they'd have any reason to tell anybody they're
fired _ or, as Claire remembered Graziano's corporatespeak, ``Fred,
I can't recommend you continuing on a go-forward basis.''
</P>
<P>
   But if all Graziano and Fox superiors Chase Carey and Peter
Chernin, none of them with baseball backgrounds, are doing is
reacting to a bad half-season, it's fair to worry they'll be firing
and reassigning every time the team disappoints for 80 games, never
mind the role that injuries play.
</P>
<P>
   The sense now is the Dodgers are run by a new president,
Graziano, frantic to justify himself, and a new GM, Tom Lasorda,
and manager, Glenn Hoffman, hell-bent on earning permanent jobs,
and the effect will be a whirlwind.
</P>
<P>
   When the dust settles, will the Dodgers be any closer to a World
Series than they were April 1?
</P>
<P>
   What the new brass might fail to realize is how close that team
in spring training was to good enough, and, for that matter, how
close this one is.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had this kind of season in 1979. Two years later,
the only substantial changes being the emergence of Fernando
Valenzuela and Steve Howe from the farm system, they won the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   They had this kind of season in 1986 and '87. In '88, after
signing Kirk Gibson and making a lot of quiet roster changes, they
won the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers fans kind of liked that, the way patience paid off, the
redemption of last year's buffoons.
</P>
<P>
   A Russell-hating fan said to me this week: ``Russell was an
idiot. But he was our idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans' fears have come true _ sweeping changes, executed with
all the delicacy of a six-mile-wide comet.
</P>
<P>
   It's exactly what we were told wouldn't happen, back in the
Dodgertown lounge, the ``Cheers''-like bar in Vero Beach where, the
last time we were there, everybody knew your name.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
