<SLUG> BC-LITTLE-LEAGUE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS RECOVER BASEBALL TOURNAMENT DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GRINER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Burghardt and his son Josh dreamed of walking on hallowed
grass and hearing the crack of leather on wood in Cooperstown,
N.Y., legendary home of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But the Phoenix boy's chance to play alongside and against the
nation's best young ballplayers almost slipped away when his team
was allegedly swindled out of $13,000 raised it for the event.
</P>
<P>
   Josh's team, the Arizona Copperheads, was one of 33 teams across
the country that lost entrance fees raised by selling phone cards
before the tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   With help from several businesses and individuals, Josh and
Mike's dream came true Friday. A plane bearing 27 Copperheads and
three coaches left Sky Harbor International Airport en route to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Copperheads, composed of players from 9 to 12 years
old, will compete in the Cooperstown Dreams Park tournament during
the next two weeks. But their chance of getting there looked slim
in the days leading to their trip.
</P>
<P>
   The team coaches and parents financed the trip by selling
telephone calling cards for a Nevada-based company called
Timecards. According to tournament officials, one or more
executives with Timecards ran off with the money from Arizona and
32 other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised, overwhelmed, shocked,'' said Lou Presutti, a
director with the tournament who had worked successfully with
Timecards before. ``The kids' hard work, their dreams of coming to
Cooperstown and their anticipation of working hard at something was
definitely in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   To recover the money, Coach Craig Bartenhagen contacted Valley
television and radio stations on June 23 to get the word out.
</P>
<P>
   Donations quickly rolled in. One woman donated $500, asking in
return that a picture of the team hang next to Ted Williams in the
Baseball Hall of Fame. A Saratoga, N.Y., widow gave the last $1,000
of her husband's memorial fund to the team after hearing from a
daughter in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Armor-Deck, a home-improvement company based in Tempe,
contributed $1,000. Diamondback Charities auctioned off a Bank One
Ballpark suite for $1,500, which was donated to the team.
</P>
<P>
   The support overwhelmed Bartenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tugs a lot of strings of the heart,'' he said. ``There is
so much negative out there. Any time you turn on the news, there's
something bad happening. But there's actually a lot more good than
you would think.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Sunny, helped coordinate the donations as they
arrived. One of her favorites was a $3 money order.
</P>
<P>
   ``That money order was as important to that person as $1,000 was
to someone else,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office has not received a formal
complaint about the alleged embezzlement. The office will continue
its investigation when the Copperheads return from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Timecards, which recently changed its name to Future Stars of
America, according the Cooperstown Dreams Park administrators, did
not return phone calls Friday. &QL; 
 &UR; David Griner can be reached at 444-7937. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
