r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLBOARD-AZR &LR;      06-26 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBOARD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLBOARD SIGN SPURS FREE SPEECH QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RUBEN NAVARRETTE JR.  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got something to say? Lease a billboard. But hurt someone's
feelings, and you could get a crash course in broken contracts and
the limits of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Even though a California sign bemoaning illegal immigration has
been removed, the controversy rages on amid charges that free
speech has been trampled upon by billboard executives who put
profits and public relations before the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the physical confrontation that authorities have
feared may yet materialize Saturday as dozens of billboard
supporters intent on resurrecting it flock to the state line. They
likely will be met there by counterprotesters who find the sign
racist and offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The billboard, which was intended to be seen by thousands but
has now been viewed by millions, was located near the California
desert town of Blythe on Interstate 10. It read, ``Welcome to
California, the illegal immigration state. Don't let this happen to
your state.''
</P>
<P>
   That message, scripted by the Southern California-based
California Coalition for Immigration Reform, infuriated Mario
Obledo, a 66-year-old lawyer and veteran of the Hispanic civil
rights movement who threatened to deface the sign.
</P>
<P>
   Obledo's threat panicked the sign's owner, Martin Media of Paso
Robles, Calif., which removed the sign Tuesday and issued a refund
to the Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in free speech,'' said Connie Wauhob, the company's
general manager, from her offices in Fort Mojave. ``But when our
property was threatened, we had to draw the line.''
</P>
<P>
   While Wauhob would not confirm the amount of the agreement,
sources estimate it to have been close to $4,000 for a one-year
lease. The contract apparently contained a clause under which
either party could cancel it, as Martin did.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the billboard industry say companies often retain the
right to cancel agreements because of public reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we receive complaints from the public that a specific copy
is perceived as being in poor taste, we'll remove it,'' said Tom
Wisz, communications director for Phoenix-based Outdoor Systems,
Inc., the nation's largest outdoor media company.
</P>
<P>
   And according to a representative of the Washington-based
Outdoor Advertising Association of America, a good way to avoid
negative public reaction is to know your audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be able to judge the community and know what they
might find offensive,'' said Ruth Segal, executive vice president
for governmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Segal said that deciding what constitutes bad taste on a
billboard is a source of constant debate within an industry that
aims to catch the attention of passersby in ways that are, by
design, often provocative and controversial.
</P>
<P>
   And nowhere is that debate hotter than with the recently
intensified media battle between tobacco advertisers and
government-sponsored ef forts to discourage smoking, which are
becoming increasingly graphic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are high-impact messages,'' Segal said.
</P>
<P>
   While the tobacco ads are notoriously straightforward, other
billboard messages raise concerns because of their ambiguity.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in Duluth, Minn., a family recreation park
recently came up with what it considered a clever slogan for
challenging parents to play games with their children. The
billboard blared: ``Beat Your Kids!'' and then continued, in
smaller letters underneath, ``. . . or let them win at Castle
Golf.'' The sign was removed by representatives of the amusement
park after the mayor of Duluth complained that it was offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the California controversy could have been
avoided, it came along at an unfortunate time for Martin Media,
which is being purchased by Chancellor Media Corp., an owner of
radio stations, for an estimated $610 million. Even though the sale
was announced just one day before the billboard was removed, Wauhob
denied that the merger had any impact.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Coe confirmed that the Coalition intended to sue
Obledo, but not for interfering with the group's First Amendment
rights.
</P>
<P>
   That, legal scholars agree, is wise, given that First Amendment
protection extends to only acts by government. As a result, acts by
private citizens or companies to limit speech are rarely
actionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since government is not censoring anything in this case,
there's technically no constitutional problem with what's
happened,'' said Paul Bender, former dean of Arizona State
University's College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Coe said, the group intends to sue Obledo for
interfering with a contractual agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Obledo said Friday that he would ``welcome a lawsuit'' as a
forum to express his views.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Wauhob said that, despite the criticism it has
received, the company stands by its decision. It simply had, she
said, no idea just how heated the response would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it would be controversial,'' she said, ``but not this
controversial.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Ruben Navarrette Jr. can be reached at 444-4977 or at
ruben.navarrette &LR; pni.com
 &UR; via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-26-98 2359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
